INSERT INTO `des_notes` VALUES (1,2,'Dave Menconi','\"A good game presents players with interesting decisions.\" -- Sid M.\r\n\r\n1) Trade\r\n Abstract\r\n two players can choose to engage in a trade agreement. Both then pay \"goo\" every turn and gradually the trade relation increased in value\r\n2) Warfare\r\n ship to ship\r\n three kinds of ships\r\n BB wihch have guns; they have sort range, big damage and good accuracy\r\n MBs which have missiles -- they have medium range, high speed, limited accuracy and moderate damage; they also have a limited supply of missiles\r\n CVs which have \"fighters\" -- they have long range, anti-ship or anti-fighter capability (or both), excellent accuracy and moderate damage; players must choose what percentage to keep back for defence and what percentage to send on for attack\r\n Guns can also be used to bomb planets but they destroy infrastructure\r\n In a ship to ship fight, first the fighters engage the ships, then the missiles engage the ships, then the bb engage the ships\r\n the concept is that the two fleets are closing steadily; when they get close enough for the longest range fighters those fighters launch and begin closing the gap, then shorter range fighters and so on; when the fighters, based on speed and distance, arrive on target they do damage -- this may prevent some ships from firing or launching. Then missiles fire as they come within range and they do the same thing. Finally guns fire.\r\n Damage persists, is healed slowly and needs a base to completely heal\r\n If enemy ships are orbiting a planet that planet is interdicted, even if it\'s own, even if it has friendly ships also available.\r\n Planets may build planetary defenses, even if interdicted\r\n interdicted planet may not receive or offer goo\r\n troop transports can take a planet without damaging infrastructure\r\n3) shipbuilding\r\n Any planet can build light ships (scouts and light fighters) but bigger ships either can\'t be built or are impossibly costly to build without a space dock\r\n ships can\'t be built while a planet is interdicted\r\n4) Research\r\n Discrete and continuous (yeah, THAT\'S clerar)\r\n we\'d like to have research that gives us better technology that has diminishing returns AND we\'d like to have meta research (raw research) that causes paradigm shifts (like propellors to jet engines)\r\n5) Game Turn Structure\r\n Many orders take more than one turn\r\n Daily turns\r\n variable length commands\r\n6) Diplomacy  establish alliances\r\n trading relationships\r\n status -> hostile, neutral, friendly, allied\r\n each status has different benefits/obligations\r\n shooting at someone always take you straight to hostile\r\n hostile players can\'t have a trade relationship\r\n the status is non-symetric\r\n7) Economic model\r\n each colony has people\r\n people grow to the limit of the planet\r\n 10 people produce 1 unit of goo if they aren\'t manning a factor\r\n 1 industry needs at most one person and produces 2 units of goo\r\n higher technology allows few people to man an industry\r\n goo is autmatically shared among all non-interdicted planets\r\n goo allows you to build/create/fund things\r\n   building ships or buildings or industy\r\n   paying for spies\r\n   paying for trade relations\r\n   research\r\n8) Geometry of space\r\nflat 2d\r\nrandom distribution of systems\r\none planet per system\r\n metrics to prevent really bad maps\r\n9) exploration\r\n you know where the stars are (color, location, etc)\r\n but you don\'t know what kind of planet is on them\r\n10) structure of game\r\n A) how to win\r\n   popular vote\r\n   first player to get 2/3 of total vote wins\r\n   must wait until there is some minimum number of people\r\n B) when can one join?\r\n   Game start\r\n C) how many players\r\n   as many or as few as you have\r\n   number of planets is proportional to players\r\n   amount of space maintains a density of planets\r\n D) how to handle drop outs\r\n11) Randomness -- HOW much\r\n12) spying and coounter spying\r\n you spend goo\r\n it is possible to stop spies without discovering who sent them\r\n it is possible to learn who sent a spy\r\n maybe this depends on the ratio of the spy goo to the counter spy goo\r\n13)  movement\r\n every ship has a range\r\n every ship has a speed\r\n14) Commands\r\n move commands (go here)\r\n attack (defend)\r\n produce goo\r\n spies\r\n build\r\n research\r\n  ','2005-01-27','2005-01-27 22:59:58'),(3,3,'Dave Menconi','Design Application\r\n1/18/05\r\n\r\nFIRST PASS\r\n1/24/05\r\nTo sort of cut to the chase, I want to write two inital programs. \r\nThe first is the note taking program. It has a\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE design(\r\nDesignID INT AUTO_INCREMENT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,\r\nDate TIMESTAMP,\r\nDesignName TINYTEXT,\r\nDesigner TINYTEXT,\r\nDescription TEXT,\r\nDesignTS TIMESTAMP);\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE notes(\r\nNoteID INT AUTO_INCREMENT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,\r\nDesignNo INT,\r\nAuthor TINYTEXT,\r\nNote TEXT,\r\nNotesTS TIMESTAMP);\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE sections(\r\nSectionID INT AUTO_INCREMENT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,\r\nDesignNo INT,\r\nSectionTitle TINYTEXT,\r\nSectionText TEXT,\r\nSectionTS TIMESTAMP);\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE modules (\r\nModuleID INT AUTO_INCREMENT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,\r\nDesignNo INT,\r\nModuleName TINYTEXT,\r\nModuleText TEXT,\r\nModulesTS TIMESTAMP);\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE images(\r\nImageId INT AUTO_INCREMENT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,\r\nDesignNo INT,\r\nURL TINYTEXT,\r\nModuleNO INT DEFAULT 0,\r\nImagesTS TIMESTAMP);\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE defaultsections(\r\nDefaultSectionID INT AUTO_INCREMENT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,\r\nSectionTitle TINYTEXT,\r\nDefaultSectionsTS TIMESTAMP);\r\n\r\nINSERT INTO defaultsections \r\n(SectionTitle)\r\nVALUES \r\n(\'Introduction\'),\r\n(\'Definitions\'),\r\n(\'Database Design\'),\r\n(\'Technical Design Notes\'),\r\n(\'Issues\'),\r\n(\'Future Enhancements\');\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOverview\r\n1/18/05\r\nFirst I want a directory of all the designs I have. design/directory\r\nEach individual design should be a different application so that I can hide it or show it individually\r\nThere are two modes for design: initial and finished. Initial design is just a series of notes. They are processed in a certain way, time stamped and dated  and then displayed all on the same page. \r\nWe want to be able to add text and pictures. The first line of every paragraph (where \"paragraph\" is defined as a block of text with no blank lines in it) is the title (h3 or bold, whatever), the subtitle is the date and the rest of the lines are either paragrphs (if they are longer than 70 characters) or bullets (if they are shorter). Pictures, if uploaded, are put in the image directory, and added to the picture table associated with the design. They are displayed at the end of the text in a block. \r\nThe formal document is a formal design document which is another application so I can have a differet set of people see it.\r\nI want to have a group that can read and write notes (probably the same group) and a group who can read the final design and a group who can write/edit the final design.\r\nThe final design should be organized in sections. Off the top of my head, we should have Title, introduction, database table list, detailed table design, administration, data entry, reports, workflow analysis, audience, miscelaneous notes, module list, detailed module design. Each section should have a place for a graphic. You enter the list of tables and the list of modules first and then it provides space for each table and module.\r\nIt displays the information in a standard format but it will also generate a database creation code that you can just hand to mysql. \r\nWe\'d also like to have a program that can edit the format of the report -- change sections, change the way it\'s displayed and so forth -- so that it can evolve over time.\r\nSeems like we want to use the average length of the lines in a set of \"paragraphs\" -- we would normall call these \"lines\" to determine whether to do it as a list or as a pararaph. Or we could look at the number of periods on a line; zero or one suggests a list while two or more suggests a paragraph. Also, if there is only one line in a set that seems to be a list we should ignore it. \r\nA line of minus, underbars or equals should generate a <HR>. Unless the format of the entity is mandatory (like, it\'s a title or a subtitle) any word that\'s capatilized is bold. Any word that has an asterisk before and after it is bold (or italicized -- or both). Any word in quotes should, perhaps, be italicized. \r\nWHile it\'s cool to do all this formatting, I suspect that this block of text will look like shit no matter what we do. It\'s too rambly; I get like that sometimes.\r\na line that leads with a special character -- like a * or a - or a + -- should ALWAYS be a list. And we should leave in HTML -- if the user wants to throw that shit in then, by all means, let\'s respect it!\r\nWe need to write a program that formats this thing and see how it works. \r\nHow do you tell the difference between a main had with subheads and a main head with a block of text?\r\nTitles should all be title case.\r\nEmpty sections are simply left out of the formal document. \r\n\r\nINFORMAL DOCUMENT SECTIONS\r\n1/21/05\r\nInformal document database has a table that contains a list of all the designs,deign id date started, whether the formal deign is done, the designer and a description. It also has the informaal design table (\"design note table\") that contains a bunch of records with the design number, the date this \"thunk\" was created, a block of text and, maybe, who wrote it (might be different from the designer). \r\nThe page that displays and edits this simply has a form at the top and all the notes ever created below them in reverse chronological order (i.e. newest first). We MIGHT consider having an edit link next to each document and allow the user to edit any of the notes but I\'m not sure we want to do that. \r\nEach note should be formatted, I think. Maybe as noted above. Maybe we make the user add HTML. Or maybe we add a <P> to each CR, <li> to each + at the beginning of a line, and encase in <h3> a single word after a blank line or any line that is all caps. Any word that is all caps gets bolded and anything with * around it gets <i>. We do NOT remove tags, however. \r\nQUESTION: do we save all this stuff in a \"htmlized\" field or do we recalculate it each time? \r\n\r\nFORMAL DOCUMENT SECTIONS\r\n1/21/05\r\nContents\r\nDiagram List\r\nIntroduction\r\nModules List\r\nDetailed Module Design\r\nDefinitions\r\nDatabase Design\r\nDesign Diagrams\r\nTechnical Design Notes\r\nIssues\r\nFuture Enhancements\r\n\r\nThe Contents section allows the designer to add extra sections or delete sections that he doesn\'t need. We turn this into a table of contents that lists each section and has a link to the actual section in the HTML page. So, first off, there is a table of sections. There should be a way to reorder these sections, too. \r\nThe diagram list is a list of images that the user may upload or simply reference. It would be nice to put the diagrams in specific other sections instead of having them all in one place. Maybe the table should have the section number and, optionally, subsection number of the section (or module) that the image belongs in.\r\nThe Modules List also allows the user to add or delete modules from the design. So there is a table of modules.\r\nThe detailed module design is not one section but one section for every module in the module list. \r\nThe diagrams are either just thrown in toward the end or, if I cna figure it out, put in next to their sections. This can be tough since each module should have one. Perhaps it should be up to the user to insert the URL for each item. The diagram list allows him to maintain them and it shows him the HTML to insert one somewhere but he must put it there. Maybe we could allow him to flag an image to be \"imbedded\" meaning he will insert it somewhere or \"at end\" which means that the program will put it in a sort of a crowd after the database design but before the technical design notes. \r\nNeed a field that says what version of the design. If the design number is less than 1 then the formal design is marked \"draft\". If the design number is 1 or greater then the design is considered \"finished\".Oh, except instead of a decimal, use a major and minor revision number. If the design is a draft it does NOT get included in the design index but people can be directed to it for review purposed; they just can\'t link to it from the index.\r\n\r\nMAIN DESIGN PAGE\r\nMain page has a list of designs. Each has a title, an earliest data, a latest date a designer name and a brief description. \r\nAt the top of the page, above the designs, is a \"add a design\" form which includes the application number you must have. \r\nEach design has an \"edit notes\", an \"edit formal design\" and a show design. \r\nThere is another index page that lists all the complete designs and allow an authorized user to peruse them. Each finished formal design has an application number associated with it and only users authorized to see that application can see it. \r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(4,1,'Dave Menconi','Whatchamall DB Design\r\n1/18/05\r\n\r\n{ItemTable} \r\nItemID\r\nCategory\r\nItemName\r\nDescription\r\nPrice\r\nCount\r\nSpaceNo\r\nItemStatus\r\n\r\n\r\n{ImageTable}\r\nImageID\r\nItemnNo\r\nImageURL\r\n\r\n{SpaceTypeTable}\r\nSpaceTypeID\r\nSpaceTypeName\r\nSpaceTypeDesc\r\n\r\n{SpaceTable}\r\nSpaceID\r\nSpaceName\r\nSpaceTypeNo\r\nStartDate\r\nPaidUntil\r\nRentalRate\r\nSpaceStatus\r\nTenantNo\r\n\r\n{SpacePaymentMethodTable}\r\nPaymentID\r\nPaymentMethodNo\r\nSpaceNo\r\n\r\n\r\n{SpaceShippingMethodTable}\r\nShipingID\r\nShippingMethodNo\r\nSpaceNo\r\n\r\n{PaymentMethodTable}\r\nPaymentMethodID\r\nPaymentMethod\r\n\r\n{ShippingMethodTable}\r\nShipingMethodID\r\nShippingMethod\r\n\r\n{TenantContactTable}\r\nTenantID\r\nContactName\r\nAddress\r\nCity\r\nState\r\nZip\r\nPhone\r\nPaymentMethodNo\r\nUsername\r\nPassword\r\n\r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(5,1,'Dave Menconi','\r\n\r\nDefinitions\r\n1/18/05\r\nspace - a \"store\"\r\ntenant - a person who pays for a store\r\ncustomer - a person who buys from store\r\nSpaces can be category or gallery; the difference is essentially whether the product is produced or purchased\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nItems Table \r\nItemID\r\nCategory\r\nDescription\r\nImage\r\nPrice\r\nCount\r\n\r\nImage Table\r\nImageID\r\nImageURL\r\nItemNo\r\n\r\nSpace Type Table \r\nTypeID\r\nTypeName\r\nTypeDescription\r\n\r\n\r\nSpace Table\r\nSpaceID\r\nName\r\nTypeNo\r\nStartDate\r\nPaidUntil\r\nRentalRate\r\nStatus\r\nTenantNo\r\n\r\nSpace Payment Type Table\r\nPaymentID\r\nPaymentMethodNo\r\nSpaceNo\r\n\r\nSpace Shipping Type Table\r\nShipingID\r\nShippingType\r\nSpaceNo\r\n\r\nPayment Methods Table\r\nPaymentMethodID\r\nPaymentMethod\r\n\r\nShipping Methods Table\r\nShipingMethodID\r\nShippingType\r\n\r\nTenant Contact Table\r\nTenantID\r\nName\r\nAddress\r\nCity\r\nState\r\nZip\r\nPhone\r\nPaymentMethodNo\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(6,1,'Dave Menconi','\r\nList of changes to design document \r\n1/25/05\r\n1) All tenents have to select a classifaction for their stores based on a predetermined basis (like in the B&M mall: clothing, jewelry, electronics, etc.\r\n2) On the front page of the mall, there are two choices of display\r\nThe default is to display stores by class \r\nYou can switch to display product categories \r\nor display gallery types \r\nNote that you can look at all the stores or you can look at the categories of products in the catalog stores OR you can look at the types of subjecs in the Gallery stores. 3 cases.\r\n3) Search is a simple keyword search LIKE operator and % wildcards. Very simple: we take the search string, break it into a list of words, remove all the 1 or 2 letter words, then we create a select using each of these words on the product description (OR description LIKE %$word%...). This will get us a list of all the products that might be appropriate and we just show the first 25. The selection of which 25 to show is arbitrary. It would be nice to show the ones with the most hits first but that\'s hard. We should also apply the search to the stock numbers.\r\n4) Add to item database a special flag and a special price. Specials should be flaged with an icon and the price should be displayed crossed out and replace with the special price. \r\n5) I understand how we connect to the shoppig cart but we still need to know what we can send them and how we know it succeeded. \r\n6) Items will now have stock numbers which the tenant may (at his option) enter. This is distinct from the item number. A stock number is only unique if it is preceded by the store number (as in 1-256 for stock number 256 in store 1). We would certainly like to search on stock numbers.\r\n7) Add logging. Log visitors, if possible (_SERVER). Log every page shown (a URL of the page with all the paramters; take the POST parameters and add them to the GET parameters and then just build a URL as if they were all GET parameters.). URL come from, viewer IP, HTTP_-- USER_AGENT, [HTTP_REFERER], [REMOTE_ADDR]\r\n8) There should be a link for \"forgotten password\" on any login page. The procedure will be to ask for username. Send that user an email with a link that has a temporary password encoded in the url. user=foo&password=bar. Add a field for temporary passwords and expiry for them. Always check to see if the temp pw hasn\'t expired and allow them to log in. Recommend that the user reset their password. THIS IMPLIES, that the user can set their password in the first place.\r\n9) need a field for tenent\'s store logo\r\n10) Earl wants all images in the database, not in a directory somewhere. \r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(7,1,'Dave Menconi','Search engine\r\n1/25/05	 \r\n\r\nWhat do you want in a search engine?\r\nWe want to allow the user to enter a search string and to return the N items that MIGHT fit the MEANINGFUL words in that search string in order of which ones are BEST. If the user has misspelled a word, we want to suggest a correct spelling and let him search again.\r\nThat leaves a lot of undefined terms. Here are some definitions.\r\nN: somewhere between 10 and 50; I think 25 is a nice number\r\nMIGHT: I\'m talking about an OR search that uses synonyms where possible to broaden the search\r\nMEANINGFUL: we want to eliminate all the very common words (the prepositions, the articles and so forth)\r\nBEST: That\'s a hard one. A discussion follows.\r\nThere are two ways to calculate BEST. \r\nGoogle (and most other straight search engines) define best to mean \"items that most fit the keywords you entered\". They have many sophisticated algorithms to determine this but they are all models and at best they tend to get what you want close to the top. \r\nMany (e.g. Amazon, Ebay) define best to mean \"according to what most of our customers might want in this context\". Amazon uses popularity -- if you enter gibberish they will return a few hundred of their most popular items. Ebay uses ending times. \r\nI think, given that we really don\'t know what the customer wants, offering the 25 most popular items is probably pretty good, especially in the early days of Whatchamall when there are probably less than 25 hits for most reasonable searches. \r\nIn terms of implementation, I\'d like to create a list of words and their frequency counts (how many documents we see this in) every few days. There is an index table that tells which documents it is in and, for each document, how many times it was seen. This table has the word number, the document number and a frequency count (how many times the word occurs in one document). \r\nTo search for a single keyword you do a select on the word table, ignoring any words that are too common, and join the word table to the index table in such a way as to find all the documents that have that word in them. \r\nFor synonyms, we have another list of words and an index that relates them two by two. When we create the index, when we find a word we look it up in the synonym index and add all the synonym as well, with pointers to the same document. In other words, we find one word in the document but we add all of it\'s synonyms to the table as well, duplicating all the pointers to the document and the counts and everything. We add it WHILE we\'re looking through the document because it\'s possible that the synonyms themselves may be found in the documents and we want all the counts to be right. \r\nDave suggested that we might be able to use ISPELL in PHP to look up words. If ISPELL says it isn\'t spelled correctly then we get a list of suggested spellings and suggest the one with the most hits in the word list. \r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(8,7,'Dave Menconi','Davies list\r\nhounds like to create.free auction site like Craig\'s List. \r\nAuctions would be free. There would be very little bullshi,t. Initially there would be no auction enhancements (bold, featured, etc) and there would be no listing fees and not final fees. In fact, no fees of and kind. \r\nr-Mai/ask for a gift, completely voluntary and optional of some percentage of the transaction.like.tip you might give the doorman, if going through ad or made you Money... \r\nIvery transaction would have a Survey associated  with it. Some parts of the survey would be about the site and the experience and would be used to improve the site But there would be two questions that would relate to the Seller and buyer. \"please rate this by\", e r, bused Solely on this trans Bet/on.\" Then have 3-5 1-5 questions. Communic At/in Responsiveness. Satisfaction. Overall Rating. And \"please add any Comments abut this Seller/buyer based solely on this Defang Action. \"\r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(9,7,'Dave Menconi','Free Auction Site\r\nFields for an auction\r\n1) Title\r\n2) Description\r\n3) Category\r\n	baby & kid stuff\r\n	bicycles\r\n	books & magazines\r\n	cars & trucks\r\n	clothing & accessories\r\n	collectibles\r\n	computers & tech\r\n	electronics\r\n	furniture\r\n	household items\r\n	motorcycles/scooters\r\n	musical instruments\r\n	sporting goods\r\n	tickets\r\n4)Location of seller (optional)\r\n5) real email address\r\n6) reply to email address (may be annonimized)\r\n7) duration\r\n8) Sniping Delay\r\n9) start date\r\n10) End date\r\n11) starting bid\r\n12) maximum auction duration \r\n13) picture url\r\n14) bids\r\n15) buyer\r\n16) Paid? (Do *I* care?)\r\n17) Donation made? \r\n18) Buyer Survey Filled out?\r\n19) Seller Survey Filled out?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nQuestion 1\r\nAre people who use the auction site authenticated users (as with ebay) or just off the street? \r\nAnd, if they are just off the street, can they become users to have the system remember stuff for them. \r\nAnd, how do we authenticate bidders. \r\nDo we care?\r\n\r\nA person wants to put up an auction \r\n\r\n\r\nQuestion 2\r\nHow do we deal with dishonest sellers?\r\nHow do we deal with dishonest buyers?\r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(10,8,'Dave Menconi','Office Applications\r\n1/18/05\r\n1. Meeting Maker\r\n2. Collaborative Machine\r\n3. Minutes takers\r\n4. Membership manager\r\n5. Project Manager\r\nContract manager -- workgroup\r\nContact manager\r\nChat Room (low)\r\nBulletin board (low)\r\n\"Whatchadoin\"\r\n\"Whatchamadoin\"\r\nIBBM IttyBitty Business Machines\r\n','2005-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(11,2,'Dave Menconi','A lesson from celemp about order processing is that we should have the syntax of all the commands stored in a database and use that to parse them and generate errors. This means that a reasonable parsing algorithm and tell that something is amiss AND tell you what is is. \r\nFor example, if we stored (using a celemp command)\r\nBuild Mine Command:{#planet}B{#count}M{#resource-type}\r\nA parser can look at this and say to itslef, \"oh, I need a number followed by the letter B followed by a number followed by the letter M followed by a number!\"\r\nAnd if it couldn\'t find one of the numbers it expected it could tell the user\r\n\"Something went wrong with your Build Mine Command whose syntax should be {planet}B{count}M{resource-type}. Specifically, I didn\'t find the count. This command will be ignored.\"\r\nPlease note that I don\'t really like the infix notation of the CelEmp commands (although it may be easier on the players) and I CERTAINLY don\'t like the command names. \r\nIf we had syntax system (as I describe above) we could have several syntaxes for the same command that all parse stuff into the same buckets and pass them on in the same format.\r\nThus\r\nBuild Mine Command:{#planet}BUILD{#count}MINE{#resource-type}\r\nand\r\nBuild Mine Command:BUILD {#count} MINES ON{#planet} OF TYPE {#resource-type}\r\nWould all three generate an XML command like this\r\n<Command_name>Build Mine Command</Command_name>\r\n<count> {count}</count>\r\n<planet>{planet}</planet>\r\n<resource-type>{resource type}</resource-type>\r\n(Where the things in {} are the actual values.)\r\nIn this example the XML names are actually provide by the syntax string (except \"Command_name\" which is generic. The order processor at the other end won\'t even know what the format of the commands were; all it will know is what the xml gives it. \r\nI think we\'ll need to have an actual command number or single word command name in there somewhere so the processor is in on the secret. Maybe:\r\n(123)Build Mine Command:BUILD {#count} MINES ON{#planet} OF TYPE {#resource-type}\r\nWhere the number in parenthese is the command number (<command_number>...) and isn\'t shown to users while the words before the : is the name the users will be told. We could even translate these strings into human-readable syntax strings for the users to see in the manual/website!\r\nAlso, if we write this system once (with syntax strings, syntax checking, parsing to XML and an XML parser) we can give it to other people who want to write games and make the whole system much more robust. ','2005-01-29','2005-01-27 22:59:58'),(12,1,'Dave Menconi','Images\r\nThe mall requires tenants to uplaod a picture of each item and a store logo. \r\nUpload should be handled in such a way that it limits our exposure; no more than a few hundred thousand bytes in size and it must be read as a jpg. Write a function to do that.\r\nThen we pass the location of the file back to the calling routine and it applies policy. For item pictures we make two images, a thumbnail and a large picture. For the logo we make one image.\r\n \r\nFor the item pix we fit the image into a thumbnail bounding box (75x200) and into a big picture bounding box (500x750) and then save it into the image database. The index numbers of this are then added to the item database (must change the system a bit). Then we delete the image off the hard disk (for testing we\'re going to leave it there for a while, however). \r\n\r\nThe logo dimensions will depend. Either a square up in the corner or a 500 pix wide bar at the top depending on the web design.','2005-01-31','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(13,1,'Dave Menconi','PayPal\r\nThe is a form that we pass to paypal that includes two call back routines. When we get the call back that\'s when we log the transaction.\r\nI still don\'t know how the \"view cart\" works or how we know they\'ve actually paid the customer. The call back seems to be for successfully adding it to the card.','2005-01-31','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(14,2,'Dave Menconi','The game structure of Zspace will be in roughly three parts. Game management, turn parsing and turn processing. We will also want to create test computer players but that\'s not part of the game strictly speaking. \r\nGame management is a some mechanism by which we start a new game, set the game parameters, suspect or cancel a game, add or remove players and generally control the game. I envision this to be a set of tables controlled from a web page.\r\n\r\nTurn parsing is the front end of the turn entry system. There may be multiple inputs (mail, web, xml over http, direct input into a database, maybe others). All of them are pre-parsed and reformatted to be straight text commands (that is, the mail headers are removed, the xml stripped off or the web form processed to get to a block of text that is the commands). Then a parser does it\'s thing and generates errors, if necessary. These are sent back to the player via email and/or put on a page for the player to see on the web. If all goes well, it converts the parsed commands into xml and pushes these to the turn processor.\r\n\r\nThe turn processor will probably accept the xml formatted commands and store them until the next turn run. Then it will use an xml parser to conver that to a table and it will then run the turn, according to the rules of the game, based on the aggregate of the orders submitted. \r\nThe turn processor is also responsible for generating results. I think the result should be in xml format which is then stored somewhere. Various routines will then be invoked to send this out as a human-readable email, parse it at need into html for a \"turn results\" web page or allow a computer player to simply parse the xml into a table to do whatever it\'s going to do. \r\n\r\nNeedless to say, player will need to have some kind of preference file which the game will need to respect.','2005-01-31','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(15,2,'Dave Menconi','The part of the ZSpace game that I haven\'t quite figured out is what parts will need to be generic for all games and which parts will need to be specific to ZSpace. This is really as much a RedWall issue as it is a ZSpace issue. \r\nWe may need to write a complete design spec for ZSpace and then, with all the pieces laid out before us, figure out which pieces are ZSpace and which Redwall.\r\nClearly most of turn processing and all of  turn parsing belong to ZSpace but distributing the turn results could be handled by RedWall. Most of player management could be handled by RedWall or it can just validate the users for the game. It seems like the user preferences will be on a game by game basis so it might make more sense of the games handled it. ON the other hand, most of the preferences are the same across all games (mostly having to do with notification) so we\'ll like them to be standardized which suggests RedWall should handle it. \r\nRedWall must handle player registration and must also display what games are finished, pending or running. While the game will have to generate the contents of the game status page (which will probably have the public portion of the game  turn information for spectators to see), RedWall should control access to the pages. ','2005-01-31','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(16,1,'Dave Menconi','I\'m thinking that we should have separate files for the admin, tenant and user functions. Also I can\'t get past the notion that we should have subroutines for various functions: debug, login, mysql and maybe some Whatchamall specific but non-module specific subroutines. For example a upload function. ','2005-01-31','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(17,3,'Dave Menconi','SIMPLE TEXT CONVERSION\r\n\r\n1 Convert to html entities\r\n2 convert all /n/n to /n<p>\r\n4 explode on /n\r\n5 Any line that begins with + prepend with <li>; group lines into UL \r\n5 Any line that begins with a number prepend with a <li> (first line gets a <ol> before it, last line gets </ol> after it)\r\n6 look for * * around words and replace with <b></b>\r\n7 look for lines with all upper case and replace with capitalized <h3>\r\n8 Look for lines that consist entirely of ------ and replace with <hr>\r\n9 put a <br> at the end of any line without a <h*> or <p> or <hr> or <li> \r\n10 implode back to a single string, putting /n between lines\r\n11 when you actually display it put it in a table with 15% margin on left and right\r\n','2005-01-31','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(18,1,'Dave Menconi','SUBROUTINES WE NEED\r\nsearch routine: you pass it a list of keywords  and a list of fields & a link and it returns  an array with all the data that matches that data on that select. It takes all the words, throws away the bogus ones and puts %x% around them. And then it puts AND %x% in fielda and %x% in fieldb and %y% in fielda and %y% in fieldb. I guess. \r\n','2005-02-01','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(19,2,'Dave Menconi','Ok, I\'m going to make a specific research proposal here but I\'m not insistent. It just sort of popped into my head. \r\n\r\nLet\'s imagine we have a lot of specific research fields (such as \"range\" or \"speed\" or \"missile accuracy\") in a few research \"areas\". \r\n\r\nEach of the specific fields have a \"track\", with, perhaps, a few nifty discreet inventions thrown in. Typically, the track will go like this: 20% increase, 15% increase, 10% increase, 7% increase, 5%, 5% increase, 5% increase....  That is, it follows some curve of diminishing returns. Each of these increases is called by some name --  \"merculite missiles\" for example -- but it\'s the diminishing returns that matter. (values shown not to scale -- we need to work on that a bit)\r\n\r\nThe player may invest in each of the research areas or he may invest in just one. In each area, some subset of the possible fields will be available -- typically 50% -- chosen at random. The specific advance that will be available at any given moment will be the NEXT thing on the track -- it never skips a step. \r\n\r\nAs I say, we can throw some special items in like long range scanners or long range communications if we want. \r\n\r\nThis creates a discreet track which has many of the positive features of the MOO track but is more variable and doesn\'t have to be worked out in advance -- it\'s generated mathematically. \r\n\r\nIf we want, we can extend the track as I mentioned before by allowing a \"pure research track\" which takes a field that played out (all 5% increases) and creates a paradigm shift. But that isn\'t really necessary. We can slow down the diminishing returns somewhat.\r\n\r\nThe reason for the diminishing returns is so that a player won\'t invest ALL his research into just one field. If you had missiles that were 10 times as powerful as anyone else\'s you might be invincible on the battlefield. By making continued investment in one field less efficacious, we force players to diversify, preventing a \"silver bullet\" strategy from working. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, if the curve causes diminishing returns too early, the players will quickly learn that the ONLY reasonable strategy is to invest in one of EVERYTHING before investing in a second of ANYTHING! Once again, this creates a silver bullet strategy. \r\n\r\nLikewise, by not allowing players to invest in any field at any time we force players to diversify and to have different strategies. \r\n\r\nSome fields that I think would be useful are\r\n\r\nMovement Range\r\nMovement Speed\r\nAbility to refuel on ANY planet\r\nLong range sensors\r\nlong range communications\r\nMissiles\r\n * Faster\r\n * more powerful\r\n * longer range\r\n * more accurate\r\ndefenses\r\n * point missile defenses\r\n * point anti-fighter defenses\r\n * armor\r\n * shields\r\n * evasive maneuvers\r\n * repair\r\nguns\r\n * more powerful\r\n * longer range\r\n * more accurate\r\nfighters\r\n * better anti-ship\r\n * better anti-fighter\r\n * longer range\r\n * faster\r\nbetter ground troops\r\nplanetary defenses\r\nenvironmentalism\r\n * polution control\r\n * population growth\r\n * domed cities\r\nIndustry\r\n * automation\r\n * recycling (allows you to build with less resources)\r\n\r\nThat\'s all I thought of. \r\n\r\nDave\r\n\r\n','2005-02-02','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(20,4,'Dave Menconi','GAME/MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION\r\nThere are pages and pages of semi-formal design ideas posted (www.menconi.com/redwall) but the one thing that hasn\'t been clearly articulated is how the game communicates with the game site. \r\nMy new thinking is that there will be a set of database tables available to both the game and RedWall. Initially RedWall will put a record into the game status table saying that a game of Zspace (for example) is about to start. When it starts, a status of \"starting\" will be set by RedWall and then \"playing\" will be set by the game. Redwall will also put a list of players, the player information and so on into the player table (all with the game number from the status table). Thus the game will know who is in it. Finally, there will be a set of urls in the \"communication\" table that the game will set to tell the game site where user-readable status information can be found. There will be a variety of possible pages: \"general information\" about the game, \"current public information\" about the current state of the game and \"player specific\" pages that will require the players to log in to view. \r\nPeriodically, the game will check to see if there are any new games started and what players have been assigned to it. So if player Jones joins the game his name will be added to the list by the admin. If player Jones quits he is removed by the admin. If player Jones gets kicked out of the game, he is removed by the game. \r\nThis is a weak form of communication but the only things that need to be communicated is game status, players and where to find the web pages. \r\nI still need to work out who authenticates the players and how. If the pages are generated by php then I have a method but that seems unreasonably narrow. Maybe the game generates the html for each web page and puts the whole thing into a record in table. Then php created for redwall can authenticate a user and, if it\'s cool, show the player the player specific information. ','2005-02-02','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(21,2,'Rob Zdybel','\r\nPretty much what I\'ve been thinking but with a more mathematically derived\r\ncurve for returns. I like the idea of asymptotically approaching 2.0 from\r\nthe base of 1.0. You never reach 2.0 without some investment into basic\r\nresearch and ultimately a paradigm shift which puts you at that mark and\r\nallows your incremental improvements to start again at 2.0. This, I think,\r\nis something like what you were proposing at our first brainstorm. Instead\r\nof just a single basic research category, you have several fundamental\r\ncategories that you can research. You then have sub-categories within those.\r\nPropulsion for example would include range, speed and refueling capability -\r\nyou could then incrementally improve any one category or put money into\r\nbasic propulsion research which would allow a paradigm shift in one of the\r\nsub-categories. Or both.\r\n\r\nI\'ve added some comments to your statements below ..\r\n\r\n-----Original Message-----\r\nFrom: Dave Menconi <reply@menconi.com>\r\nTo: zdybel@earthlink.net <zdybel@earthlink.net>\r\nDate: Wednesday, February 02, 2005 3:16 PM\r\nSubject: Research\r\n\r\n\r\n>Ok, I\'m going to make a specific research proposal here but I\'m not\r\n>insistent. It just sort of popped into my head.\r\n>\r\n>Let\'s imagine we have a lot of specific research fields (such as \"range\" or\r\n>\"speed\" or \"missile accuracy\") in a few research \"areas\".\r\n\r\nexactly my thoughts\r\n>\r\n>Each of the specific fields have a \"track\", with, perhaps, a few nifty\r\n>discreet inventions thrown in. Typically, the track will go like this: 20%\r\n>increase, 15% increase, 10% increase, 7% increase, 5%, 5% increase, 5%\r\n>increase....  That is, it follows some curve of diminishing returns. Each\r\n>of these increases is called by some name --  \"merculite missiles\" for\r\n>example -- but it\'s the diminishing returns that matter. (values shown not\r\n>to scale -- we need to work on that a bit)\r\n\r\nyeah .. but no unique names except for paradigm shifts .. just increasing\r\n(asymptotically) capability\r\n\r\n>\r\n>The player may invest in each of the research areas or he may invest in\r\n>just one. In each area, some subset of the possible fields will be\r\n>available -- typically 50% -- chosen at random. The specific advance that\r\n>will be available at any given moment will be the NEXT thing on the track\r\n>-- it never skips a step.\r\n\r\nI was going to abandon that idea, but it might be nice to have a paradigm\r\nshift in Propulsion/Range uncover possible paradigm shifts in\r\nPropulsion/Speed for example\r\n\r\n>\r\n>As I say, we can throw some special items in like long range scanners or\r\n>long range communications if we want.\r\n>\r\n>This creates a discreet track which has many of the positive features of\r\n>the MOO track but is more variable and doesn\'t have to be worked out in\r\n>advance -- it\'s generated mathematically.\r\n>\r\n>If we want, we can extend the track as I mentioned before by allowing a\r\n>\"pure research track\" which takes a field that played out (all 5%\r\n>increases) and creates a paradigm shift. But that isn\'t really necessary.\r\n>We can slow down the diminishing returns somewhat.\r\n\r\nI\'m thinking basic research in each of the major categories - computers,\r\nweapons, propulsion, ecology, and industry - although the weapons category\r\ngets pretty fat and we may want to subdivide it into offense, defense and\r\nplanetary (including troops)\r\n>\r\n>The reason for the diminishing returns is so that a player won\'t invest ALL\r\n>his research into just one field. If you had missiles that were 10 times as\r\n>powerful as anyone else\'s you might be invincible on the battlefield. By\r\n>making continued investment in one field less efficacious, we force players\r\n>to diversify, preventing a \"silver bullet\" strategy from working.\r\n>\r\n>On the other hand, if the curve causes diminishing returns too early, the\r\n>players will quickly learn that the ONLY reasonable strategy is to invest\r\n>in one of EVERYTHING before investing in a second of ANYTHING! Once again,\r\n>this creates a silver bullet strategy.\r\n>\r\n>Likewise, by not allowing players to invest in any field at any time we\r\n>force players to diversify and to have different strategies.\r\n\r\nYeah, but it is tough to balance and we don\'t want there to be any obviously\r\noptimal path as you note.\r\n>\r\n>Some fields that I think would be useful are\r\n>\r\n>Movement Range\r\n>Movement Speed\r\n>Ability to refuel on ANY planet\r\n>Long range sensors\r\nIncreased information from sensor reads\r\n>long range communications\r\nability to re-direct fleets in flight\r\nattack computers\r\ndefense computers (ECM)\r\nminiaturization of computers allowing them to be placed on fighters and then\r\nmissiles\r\n>Missiles\r\n>  * Faster\r\n>  * more powerful\r\n>  * longer range\r\n>  * more accurate\r\nimproved immunity to ECM\r\n>defenses\r\n>  * point missile defenses\r\n>  * point anti-fighter defenses\r\n>  * armor\r\n>  * shields\r\n>  * evasive maneuvers\r\n>  * repair\r\nstealth technology and cloaking devices\r\n>guns\r\n>  * more powerful\r\n>  * longer range\r\n>  * more accurate\r\n>fighters\r\n>  * better anti-ship\r\n>  * better anti-fighter\r\n>  * longer range\r\n>  * faster\r\nIncreased survivability\r\n>better ground troops\r\nbetter offense (more punch per pound)\r\nbetter defense\r\n>planetary defenses\r\nshields\r\nmissile systems\r\nECM\r\n>environmentalism\r\n>  * polution control\r\n>  * population growth\r\n>  * domed cities\r\nterra-forming\r\ngaia-forming\r\nbiological weapons\r\nIncreased maximum population per planet\r\n>Industry\r\n>  * automation\r\n>  * recycling (allows you to build with less resources) ??do we use\r\nresources??\r\nreduced pollution output from factories (as opposed to cleaning up\r\nafterwards)\r\n>\r\n>That\'s all I thought of.\r\nThat seems like  a pretty exhaustive list .. we may want to consolidate some\r\nof it (reduced pollution and increased pollution control for example) or\r\nincrease the number of cross-possibilities (can\'t reduce your pollution\r\noutput? invest in ecology and improve your clean up ability) (can\'t get more\r\npowerful missiles? Increase their ECM and get more thru to the target). I\'m\r\nthinking I like the cross-possibility stuff right now ..\r\n\r\nMore to come .. RZ','2005-02-03','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(22,2,'Dave Menconi','I\'m pretty happy with the direction the research is going as well as the combat and the rest of it. I\'m positively excited about the turn structure. \r\n\r\nThe last thing you said to me on research was \r\n\"More to come .. RZ \"\r\n\r\nMy sense is that we have a good outline but need to define it a bit better. Also you made a few comments that I wasn\'t quite clear on. \r\n\r\n \r\n    >The player may invest in each of the research areas or he may invest in \r\n    >just one. In each area, some subset of the possible fields will be \r\n    >available -- typically 50% -- chosen at random. The specific advance that \r\n    >will be available at any given moment will be the NEXT thing on the track \r\n    >-- it never skips a step. \r\n     \r\n    I was going to abandon that idea, but it might be nice to have a paradigm \r\n    shift in Propulsion/Range uncover possible paradigm shifts in \r\n    Propulsion/Speed for example \r\n\r\nAs proposed, this scheme has no paradigm shifts and no area levels. Each individual field has a track and the next step on the track may be unavailable and you can invest in any one of the available fields in each of the areas.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure what idea you were going to abandon or how paradigm shifts enter into it. Basically I don\'t understand your comment here. \r\n\r\nMy proposal, I now realize, is flawed in that I don\'t specify a way in which things become available again. I think the solution to this is that every time you develop something in a particular area we create another random list of things that are available in that level. \r\n\r\nWe should probably weight the random list so that it\'s more likely that things lower on the track are available but if you\'re lucky (or unlucky) you might get two or three steps up on Propulsion before you do speed. \r\n\r\nThis all assumes that there are at least 3 fields in an area because if there is less than an area will have NO choices at all (that is, if there are only speed and range in propulsion we will either show you speed or range but not both and you only have one choice).\r\n\r\n\r\n    Pretty much what I\'ve been thinking but with a more mathematically derived \r\n    curve for returns. I like the idea of asymptotically approaching 2.0 from \r\n    the base of 1.0.\r\n\r\n2.0 from the base of one? Do you mean that you start at 1 unit of speed per turn and then you spend some money and it increases and more money and it increases and more and more money. Each investment increases the speed but by a decreasing amount. And no matter how much you spend you never quite get to 2.0. Is that what you mean? That\'s what I was thinking as well except that this implies tiny, tiny fractional improvements toward the end of the run and that\'s just silly so I made the lower limit 5%.  \r\n\r\nOne key question here, however: these investments are discreet, not continuous, right!? You must spend X to get Y improvements. X gradually increases and Y gradually decreases but at no point can you spend X/2 and get an improvement of Y/2, right? We\'re taking discreet points off a mathematically calculated asymptotic continuous curve. Right?\r\n\r\n    You never reach 2.0 without some investment into basic \r\n    research and ultimately a paradigm shift which puts you at that mark and \r\n    allows your incremental improvements to start again at 2.0. This, I think, \r\n    is something like what you were proposing at our first brainstorm. Instead \r\n    of just a single basic research category, you have several fundamental \r\n    categories that you can research. You then have sub-categories within those. \r\n    Propulsion for example would include range, speed and refueling capability - \r\n    you could then incrementally improve any one category or put money into \r\n    basic propulsion research which would allow a paradigm shift in one of the \r\n    sub-categories. Or both. \r\n\r\nOk, I\'m down with paradigm shifts. But how do they occur? Clearly you must invest in the \"propulsion basic (or pure) research field\". How do we decide how much research needs to go into that for effect and how do we know which thing gets shifted? \r\n\r\nAnd when the thing gets shifted does the old track disappear to be replaced by a new track!? Or can you now invest in internal combustion engines OR jet engines. \r\n\r\nOH and a really important question: when your technology goes up, does it automatically fix all your ships are are they stuck with the old technology until you upgrade them!? And can I build my ship with old technology (which will tend to be cheaper and, initially, not all that much worse). \r\n\r\nThe coolest, most flexible system would be one in which you could continue to do research in the old paradigm and continue to use it but you could also do research in the new paradigm and use it. Thus you could put OLD (but cheap) missiles on your new ship OR NEW (but expensive) missiles on it or BOTH or you could upgrade your existing ships or continue to have old missiles on them. \r\n\r\nWith missiles, as with fighters, we may want to require the player to actually PAY for the missiles. Which means that a cheaper but less effective missile will still be a good deal....\r\n\r\nThe problem with this view of the universe is that it get VERY complicated and detail oriented for the players. Some players like that but most do not and the detail oriented players will still play simple games....\r\n\r\n\r\nSO we want to simplify this. \r\nAll steps within a given paradigm of a given field get implemented automatically. So all ships have, at all times, the latest version of any given paradigm.\r\n\r\nFor paradigm shifts, you CANNOT continue to invest in obsolete paradigms of a technology. But you CAN continue to use it. But you CANNOT continue to build it onto ships. And you CAN upgrade. \r\n\r\nThat means that we have to keep track of every technological paradigm on every ship or planet and take it into account for calculations but we don\'t have to provide commands to build them all or do anything else except a single upgrade commands which ALWAYS UPGRADES TO THE BEST VERSION OF THE BEST PARADIGM. It also means that paradigm shifts need to be deployed which is kind of interesting (sort of like the air defenses of Germany at the end of the war -- mostly you\'re up against conventional fighters but you MIGHT have to face jets!).\r\n\r\n','2005-02-03','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(23,1,'Dave Menconi','SPECIALS\r\nEvery day we pick specials for the whole mall based on an the standard species mating algorithm for genetic algorithms where the thing we\'re selecting for is the percentage discount; we calculate this from the special price versus the normal price. \r\nThis means that absolutely ANY special in the store could be chosen but the probability of selecting any particular special is proportional to the ratio of the normal and special prices. Note that we\'re not using an actual genetic algorithm here, we\'re just choosing specials based on how good the special is. \r\nThe advantage of using a somewhat random selection althorithm is that nothing is ruled out and it becomes harder to game the system (of course this could be gamed by taking a $1 item, claiming its normal price is $100 and it\'s special price is $1 -- even so this trick doesn\'t GUARANTEE you get a slot and whether you get a slot or not the customers will catch on).\r\nWe could also take into account how recently or how often this store had a special in the front lobby. The fundamental goal of specials is to attact people from the front lobby into a varieity of stores so looking at how often a store gets it\'s name up there might be a better algorithm.','2005-02-04','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(24,4,'Dave Menconi','LOST PASSWORD\r\nWe need a lost password system. You click on the lost password link and the system sends you a password via your email. THis is a temporary password you can use to get in and edit your real password. You must use it within 2 days. ','2005-02-04','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(25,2,'Dave Menconi','Hi Dave, hope you had a great weekend!\r\n\r\nOK, lots of questions and even more suggestions in this email. I hardly know\r\nwhere to start. I think we are roughly on the same page regarding basic\r\nresearch and paradigm shifts - that is: each fundamental research group\r\n(there were five) would also support a \"basic research\" track as well as the\r\npotential for upgrading existing paradigms (yeah, either new or old -\r\nalthough the efficiency of new paradigms would probably be attractive enough\r\nand research points limited, so that most players would focus on the new\r\nparadigm). This supports the \"continuous and discrete\" research system that\r\nwe have been groping towards.\r\nThe 1.0 to 2.0 speed example was just an illustration of how a paradigm\r\nshift would work in practice with some numbers thrown in. Until a new\r\nparadigm was revealed, the player would have no idea where his basic\r\nresearch was leading him - regardless of how many sub-fields there were in\r\nthat research group. You might never get speed 2 or even speed 3 engines,\r\nbut eventually your basic research (and this would be a *lot* of basic\r\npropulsion research in this case) would reveal a speed 4 engine. (I just\r\nrealized that we should distinguish between interstellar \"jump\" speeds and\r\n\"combat\" speeds - providing an additional engine track effectively).\r\nThe cost of a paradigm shift would be arbitrarily determined/tuned by\r\nourselves and modified with randomality - hehe, if you were unlucky enough\r\nyou could spend forever and not get a paradigm shift (but you should have to\r\nbe very, very, very unlucky). All improvements in technology will be\r\nrandomly effected: Thus there will never be a one-to-one correspondence\r\nbetween money spent and improvement returned. Just a general trend that the\r\ncost of improving an existing paradigm gets larger and the improvements get\r\nsmaller as you approach the next paradigm level. (rather than let an\r\ninifinite amount of money be spent for vanishingly small incremental\r\nimprovements, we may want to allow spending at the far end of a paradigm\'s\r\nimprovement range to contribute toward basic research of that next paradigm)\r\n\r\nThen you kinda drift into an area that I have also been considering - how\r\ndoes new technology get to the fleet? This question also applies to the\r\nproblem of how do ships get built? In MOO, the player effectively piled up\r\n\"ship-stuff\" that could at whim be extruded as any number or type of ships.\r\nThis had the unfortunate result of encouraging players to build toward the\r\nlargest possible ship and then extruding either a couple of really big ships\r\nor a few hundred tiny ones when the moment to build came. Furthermore, until\r\nthe ships were actually extruded they had no fixed tech level. I think is\r\nnot-so-good. I think that a hull should be laid down with a specific,\r\nexisting technology and ship class defined. I furthermore think that\r\nupgrading individual ships in a class is too confusing - no upgrades on\r\nindividual ships should be allowed. If you want to you should be able to\r\nscrap individual ships and regain some fraction of the scrap metal towards\r\nnew construction. (this should also be true of ships under construction as\r\nwell). Then you could build a newer and better ship in its place.\r\nI would think there may be an exception to this general rule for expendables\r\nlike missiles and fighters, however. These would be auto-upgraded when\r\nlosses/uses were replaced. Assuming that there *are* such things as\r\nexpendables (the concept of expendable ammunition does lead one to the\r\npossibility of a class of refueling ships whose primary purpose is to carry\r\nweapons to restock the warships) and not just automatic replenishment\r\nbetween combats.\r\n\r\nI think that we are ready to start talking seriously about the ship design\r\nprocess. We have a pretty good list of technology available. Clearly the\r\nfirst step is to choose a hull size (determines the max carrying capacity)\r\nand a construction material from which to build (armor class). Then you\r\nlayer on as much stuff of whatever type you got that will fit on board. Not\r\nall hull sizes would be capable of carrying all types of things (carrying\r\nfighters would require a fairly large hull for example). I think you should\r\nbe able to define quite a large number of classes of ships (MOO allows only\r\nsix) and apply unique names to them. There would then be a defined cost to\r\nbuild a ship of this class at your friendly space dock. A space dock would\r\nbe capable of building only so many points per turn - although that might\r\namount to several new ships per turn (or many turns per ship, depending on\r\nwhat you\'re trying to build). I should start thinking about applying\r\nweights/bulk to some of the weapons we are already adding to the research\r\nsystem. It would be really cool if we could do an unique graphic\r\nrepresentation of each ship class - way cool, but an interesting (read ugly)\r\nprogramming problem (but so damn cool).\r\n\r\nWhich brings us naturally to the question of how the game is represented ...\r\nwhich I will have to think about a bit. Total text like Celemp is\r\nundoubtably the easiest and has the advantage of tapping into the player\'s\r\nimagination. But, let\'s face it - it pretty much sucks. We need to find a\r\nmore graphic approach and we need to apply it to most if not all areas of\r\ngameplay (i.e. research). For combat, I really would like to produce a\r\nnarrative of the battle; again, a simple one (read cheezy) would be pretty\r\neasy to code, but a good one might take a little work. For the strategic\r\nlevel we will want a 2D map (as already discussed). And all this graphic\r\ninterface needs to support a point-and-click, drag-and-drop controller\r\ninterface (all of which is, of course, underpinned by an XML messaging\r\nsystem which is what is passed to the back end to actually compute upon).\r\n\r\nWell, that\'s enough to chew on for tonite.\r\n\r\nLet me know your mind,\r\nRZ\r\n','2005-02-07','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(26,2,'Dave Menconi','By the way, I\'ve been thinking about the Game Site (which I call RedWall) and I\'ve come to the realization that it\'s hard to separate the site from the game. In fact, it seems like the game almost has to be written specifically for the site for it to work the way I want. But, since the first game IS being written for the site, this isn\'t really a problem. SO, what I want to do is make sure that we follow some rules when we write our game:\r\n\r\n1) The game itself can run however it wants in whatever language it wants (I like C but Java or PHP are also good; not fond of Perl but you can twist my arm)\r\n2) The game should use a MySQL database to keep track of everything\r\n3) The game should have several web pages, preferably written in PHP including\r\n  3.1) a promotion page that tells about the wonders of the game\r\n  3.2) a list of games that are starting with the ability for players to sign up\r\n  3.3) a list of games that are running with public information about the games (for players and spectators)\r\n  3.4) private pages for each player that show that players current and past status\r\n  3.5) data entry pages that allow users to enter their move \r\n4) The game should have a status database in some standard format that tells (at least) which players are playing, what turn it\'s on and whether the game is about the start, running, paused or ended. Oh, and what the date of the next deadline is. \r\n\r\nRedWall will provide two services for all games:\r\n1) A list of authenticated users (that is, when a player accesses your game, you will know his user name, email, etc)\r\n2) A set of forums or discussion boards for every topic including this game.\r\n\r\nI\'m figuring that 1-4 will be written for ZSpace initially but then generalize to make it as easy as possible to write fit a game in. Maybe some forms that allow the moderators to create a promotional game and some standards that, if adhered too, allow for some standard status pages to be generated. \r\n\r\nThe goal is for the second game to be much easier to write (even though it puts a small burden on ZSpace). It would be really COOL to be the de facto standard for game sites!','2005-02-08','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(27,2,'Dave Menconi','Research\r\nThere are 5 areas each with 4 technologies that can be invested in.\r\nThey are\r\nPropulsion\r\n   Speed\r\n   Range\r\n   Tactical Speed\r\n   Tacticla Range\r\nComputer\r\n   Accuracy\r\n   ECM\r\n   Scanners\r\n   Industry\r\nDefense\r\n   Shields\r\n   Armor\r\n   PDU\r\n   Point Defenses\r\nOffense\r\n   Guns\r\n   Missiles\r\n   Fighter Off\r\n   Figher Def\r\nPlanetology\r\n   Pollution\r\n   Ability to Colonize\r\n   Population Growth\r\n   Planet Maximum\r\n\r\nPlayers can invest in any of the 20 technologies. When you\'ve invested enough you jump one technology level which gives you some benefit in that technology. All technologies start aout at some number and vary from from that starting number to some maximum. The new value of the technology for technology level X is (<starting value> * (1-(1/N))^X). The value of N has to be related to the ratio of starting value to ending value or the technology will overshoot it\'s maximum.\r\n','2005-02-11','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(28,2,'Dave Menconi','Basic Research\r\nPlayers investin basic research in any of the 5 areas. Before the game starts the game selects some number of technologies in each level that it will let the players get breakthroughs in. There are only two constraints on this randomness: 1) there has to be SOMETHING in each paradigm level that the player can gain by investing and 2) each of the technologies must appear at least once in each 4 paradigm steps. When players invest in Basic Research, they accumulate basic research value. When the value goes beyond he \"level one\" value, the player is eligible for a breakthrough in one of the\r\n','2005-02-11','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(29,2,'Dave Menconi','Other Notes on Research\r\nHigher paradigms are much coslier\r\nInvestment varies w/out input\r\n\r\nBasic\r\nTakes >>$ to tip the bucket\r\nwhat you get is semi-random\r\nWatered down by all available p-shifts\r\nmax $ contribution capped??\r\n\r\nApplied\r\ncheaper\r\ninvestment grows\r\ndirected\r\n','2005-02-11','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(30,2,'Dave Menconi','Turn Sequence\r\n1. Spend (use whatever goo you have to produce according to your orders)\r\n research (universal)\r\n industry (per planet)\r\n ships (either built on space docks or on every planet)\r\n troops?\r\n pollution added and mitigated\r\n2. Combat\r\n3. Colonize\r\n4. Movement\r\n5. Colonize\r\n','2005-02-11','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(31,2,'Dave Menconi','Combat\r\nWhat we agee on\r\nThere are 3 kinds of weapons systems, fighters, missiles, guns\r\nThe combat system has the following algorithm:\r\nThe two fleets start out infinitely far away\r\nThey move to within the longest range weapon on any of the ships and those weapons launch.\r\nThe two fleets start moving closer according to their tactical speeds; the weapsons close the gap at their speed.\r\nAs each weapon arrives at the enemy fleet it takes effect and as each weapon comes within range it launches. So the order in which the weapons take affect depends on the tactical speed of the fleet, the ranges of the weapons and the speed of the weapons.\r\nShips that are damaged or destroyed before they launch or fire don\'t get to launch or fire.\r\nTHere are two major caveats to all this\r\n1) the speed of weapons must be more than 1/2 the speed of the fleets or the fleets will meet before the weapons system get there.\r\n2) These basic rules may be modified by orders from the player (or not).\r\n','2005-02-11','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(32,2,'Rob Zdybel','We had a pretty good brain-storming session last nite. I think we got\r\nresearch nailed down and made good progress on the combat system. I have\r\nbeen thinking about the \"combat posture\" thing and would like to suggest the\r\nfollowing system:\r\nEach player chooses the \"range\" that they want to fight at <avoid, fighters,\r\nmissiles, guns, point-blank> (this is think is useful because you always\r\nknow more about your own capability than the enemy\'s - so you pick the range\r\nthat you feel will favor you the most). Each player also chooses whether\r\nthey want to kill as many ships as possible or go for the big ones. We then\r\ncompare the two players requests. A retreat is always honored and the\r\nplayer(s) that choose it must move away from the system that turn.\r\nOtherwise, if the two players choose the same combat level we use that level\r\nand no deeper/closer. If (and this will probably be typical) one player\r\nchooses a more aggressive attack, the minimum range becomes the other\r\nplayer\'s choice and the final range is randomly chosen somewhere between\r\nthere and the more aggressive player\'s choice (inclusive). This random value\r\nmight be modified somewhat in favor of the attacker (the person who doesn\'t\r\nhave a planet to defend should have an easier time maneuvering away) if he\r\nhas chosen the less aggressive posture. Planetary defenses could be used by\r\nthe Defender in such combat (so there is an advantage to the defender\r\ntoo)(I\'m thinking planetary defenses could upgrade from gun-type, thru\r\nmissile-type and finally to fighter type?)\r\n\r\nI think that transports should be forced to run the gauntlet of surviving\r\ndefending ships and planetary defenses on the turn they arrive. This puts\r\npressure on the attacker to make sure he can eliminate enemy forces if he\r\nhas committed precious troops. On the other hand, in the case of neutral\r\nplanets, I think I agree with you that colony ships would NOT be allowed to\r\nland unless all opposition was eliminated. Does this seem crazy still?\r\nNaturally landing transports would be easy targets and would suffer badly\r\neven at the hands of a relatively small fleet.\r\n\r\nThe fight is then in the hands of the computer (your skippers) and you get a\r\ndetailed combat summary plus scans (detail dependent on deployed scanner\r\ntech) of the surviving enemy ships. None of this capture-a-hull stuff, ships\r\nthat die are vaporized.\r\n\r\nWe might add a \"skpper\'s choice\" in between going for the maximum number of\r\nkills and the largest ships - this would just allow the computer free rein\r\nto pick targets of opportunity.\r\n\r\nWould fighters be subject to point defenses of all ships they pass by or\r\njust those of the target ship? Likewise missiles? I\'m thinking one of the\r\nadvantages of more expensive fighter technology would be to allow them this\r\nprivilege. On the other hand, we could just peg it to evasion capability of\r\nthe fighter tech.\r\n\r\nI will try to start putting some of this stuff into psuedo-code. At least\r\nthe parts that we agree on ;-)','2005-02-11','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(33,2,'Dave Menconi','RECAP (to make sure I understand):\r\n\r\nThe players specify a range from \"retreat\" through \"avoid (but stick around)\", \"engage at my fighter range\", \"engage at my missile range\", \"engage at my gun range\" up to \"pedal to the metal, go for the whites of their eyes\". (Notice the slight change from \"missile range\" to \"MY missile range\"). \r\n\r\nAlso, each player gets to choose among \"shoot at little ships first\", \"shoot at big ships first\" or \"use your best judgement\". \r\n\r\n\"Defender\" is defined as a guy who owns the planet the battle is at. \"Attacker\" is anyone else so some battles may have two attackers. \r\n\r\nDefenders get to add their planetary defense to the battle but get some kind of disadvantage in avoiding combat. \r\n\r\nI like it but I\'m not sure I like the way it calculates a random value. What if we added this to the basic combat sequence (outlined in my note to you)? It would work like this: both fleets continue to advance until they\'ve launched the thing they wanted to do before disengaging and then they start to retreat. After a player has traveled some maximum distance from their starting point (we\'re assuming here that one fleet is chasing the other) they disengage even if they haven\'t come within the range of the weapon they specified. Defenders have a smaller maximum distance than attackers (which means that if the defender is trying to press combat on the attacker, they have to be significantly faster to do so).\r\n\r\nLet me use an example:\r\n\r\nLet\'s say that I have invested very heavily in fighters and not much else while you are a big missile guy. So you say \"engage to my missile range\" and I say \"engage to my fighter range\". Our two fleets close at flank speed until I can launch my fighters at which point I stop advancing. You keep advancing. When my fighters come back, I start retreating. You keep advancing. If you are faster than me, eventually you catch me and close to your missile range. If we ever come within my missile range I can fire but just as soon as you launch we will both disengage and I won\'t get to do anything else. \r\n\r\nIf you are chasing me and you hit your maximum distance from your starting point (which may be a fixed limit or may be partially dependant on your tactical range) you have to break off. \r\n\r\nA small random value can be introduced when determining the exact point at which each of us breaks off; that is, I might advance after I launch my fighters and only start to pull back after I recover them and you might keep advancing after you launch your missiles. This random value should be proportional to the size of the two fleets and inversely proportional to scanner and communication tech levels (the logic is that not all of your fleet gets the message to pull back from my fleet while there may be some confusion about when, exactly, a particular range is reached with respect to my fleet). \r\n\r\nBy the way, the definition of \"flank speed\" is the tactical speed of the slowest ship in a fleet and the definition of \"within range\" is within range of that type of weapon with the shortest range. \r\n\r\nThat makes the entire process largely deterministic. It does, unfortunately, give a sizeable advantage to the faster fleet (he will often get to engage more weapons when he wants to and avoid engagement when he doesn\'t). \r\n\r\nThe only part of this I don\'t like is that I would LIKE to make it hard to avoid combat while staying at the planet and this makes it too easy for the faster fleet to avoid at least some of the enemy ships.\r\n','2005-02-11','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(34,1,'Dave Menconi','http://www.menconi.com/designs/WhatchamallDesign.html\r\nhttp://www.menconi.com/designs/pageindex.html\r\n','2005-02-15','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(35,2,'Dave Menconi','','2005-02-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(39,1,'Dave Menconi','Now, this brings me to policies. I came up with an idea this morning that I\'d like to implement but I wanted to see what you thought of it. The system includes (in a mysql table, of course) a list of \"policies\". A policy has a name, a description and a value.\r\n\r\nFor example, it might be called \"max_upload_size\" with a description of \"The maximum size of an uploaded file\" and a value of 1000000 (1 million).\r\n\r\nThe code would get two huge arrays called $policy_values and $policy_desc and would pass them around. There would an admin function to add and edit these policies. (Just to make it more complex, the description wouldn\'t actually by stored in the policy file: it would be stored in the language file and the actual string that was put in the $policy_desc array would be in the current language -- why can\'t all those people just learn English!?).\r\n\r\nObviously, these would be passed to Smarty and would allow the web designer to put something on a web page like \"The maximum size of an uploaded file is 1000000 bytes.\" only knowing the NAME of the policy, not the description, language or value of the policy.\r\n\r\nThe admins could then set policies and change the descriptions of policies and have the information magically propagate through the system. Programmers would avoid putting \"magic numbers\" in their code. Web designers would have a wide range of useful information available that they could tell to users in appropriate ways.\r\n\r\nThis implies that all the data in the \"config.php\" file will be loaded into the policy table and read from these arrays. It also implies that there will be no local configuration -- an editor will not be necessary to set up Whatchamall -- just a web browser, you just install it and all the setup happens across the web.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure I\'m going to do this immediately because I want to try to get ahead here (the current estimate of when we\'ll be in alpha is 7 weeks and that\'s just too long).\r\n\r\n','2005-02-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(37,2,'Rob Zdybel','Research Psuedo-Coded\r\n\r\nFor (all research fields) Do SUM research allotment\r\nFor (all planets) Do SUM research credits\r\nFOR (all research fields) DO\r\n  credits_this_field = SUM_credits * (research_allotted/SUM_allotment)\r\n  bucket[i] += credits_this_field\r\n  IF (bucket[i].credits > bucket[i].min) THEN\r\n    P(advance) = (credits - min)/(ResearchDifficulty * bucket[i].min)\r\n    IF (advance) THEN\r\n      bucket[i].credits = 0;\r\n      IF (bucket[i].isAppliedResearch)\r\n      THEN\r\n        bucket[i].level += bucket[i].level / 2\r\n        Empty this bucket\r\n	 Adjust this technology on the available build list\r\n        make appropriate announcement to player\r\n      ELSE\r\n        Count technologies available in bucket[i].available tech list\r\n        Randomly choose one\r\n        Add this tech to the available build list\r\n        IF (this is a highest level technology) \r\n          THEN add all pre-existing technology on next level to available list\r\n        empty the basic research bucket\r\n        IF (tech level of \"new\" technology is > existing) THEN\r\n          empty the applied reserch bucket associated with this advance\r\n	  Set that applied research bucket to the new value\r\n          Adjust that bucket.min to reflect the new difficulty\r\n        Adjust the basic research bucket to reflect new min required\r\n			constant_array_of_mins[techlevelmax]\r\n        Make appropriate announcement to player','2005-02-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(38,2,'Rob Zdybel','Well .. this is my first try at this ..\r\nI accidentally added two empty notes\r\nLost all my indentation in my psuedo code\r\n	is that because I used spaces instead of tabs?\r\n		would multiple tabs work?\r\n				Is ther any way of setting the tab width?\r\n			was I excessively worried about line wrap or is it honored at all by this input box\r\nThis note will answer some of these questions .. and then you can delete it if you like\r\n','2005-02-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(40,14,'Dave Mencoi','First off, there are many, many more notes elsewhere. This is just a summary.\r\n\r\nOpenSky is played on a grid of squares 100 rows by 100 columns (10,000 squares). Each square is considered to be a city block. Initially, all the city blocks are worth the same amount (exceptions: freeways and rivers). Players will try to to buy city blocks and develop them.\r\n\r\nAt any given moment a plot of land has 3 components to it\'s value. First, the land itself is worth some amount of money -- initially $1000 (exception: rivers). Second, the players may improve the plot -- every $1 invested improves the value of the plot by $1. Third, plots get a neighborhood bonus from the plots in their arrea -- this bonus is the sum of the bonuses from all 9,999 other plots in the game which are proportional to the improvements and inversely proportional to the square of the distance (divided by some amount, like 10). This latter rule means that the person who wins will be the person who places his plots of land nearest other developed plots of land. \r\n\r\nAt the start of the game a river and/or a freeway may run through the middle of the area. Rivers cause the frontage sites to be worth more money; freeways cause all the frontage sites to have a greater effect (perhaps divided by the distance rather than the square of the distance). \r\n\r\nThe turn sequence is kind of odd. Imagine the game starts on a Monday. Monday morning, everyone gets their turn which tells them how much money they have, what real estate they have and so forth as well as what plots of land are on sale. From Monday morning until Wednesday night, anyone can bid on any plot of land that is for sale in a Ebay-style auction. From Wednesday night until Friday night you can only bid on plots that have already been bid on. At Friday at midnight the auctions close, the winners pay up, the sellers collect their earnings and a newsletter goes out telling everyone who won what. Until Sunday night you can submit a move that details which plots you want to invest in, pay any taxes, put up plots for sale and so forth. Monday morning, you are told your new status and we start over.\r\n\r\nI don\'t have an end game for this game yet. Maybe the first player to have a million in cash. \r\n\r\nThere are a few (but only a few) open questions. How many plots of land should go on sale? (Provisional answer: all unowned plots of land.) Can players bid on items which they can\'t pay for? (Provisional answer: the sum of your current high bids must be less than or equal than your total cash on hand, or you are not allowed to bid.) Follow-on question: do we let you count the current high bid of stuff you\'re selling? (Provisional answer: no). ','2005-03-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(41,15,'Dave Menconi','I\'ve long wanted to do a simple trading game. This game has levels. The first level is extremely simple. When you get a certain amount of money (or meet other criteria) you can sell all your stuff and buy passage through a particular gateway to the next level. You arrive at the next level with the starting conditions of that level (nothing more and nothing less, regardless of how much over the requirements you were on the previous level). \r\n\r\nThere is no winning and no losing in this game -- you just keep playing and buying into new levels until you get bored. \r\n\r\nA significant twist is that I\'ll define the interface in such a way that other game designers can create levels. So now you can move from my last level into a level that may or may not be similar. Essentially, the next \"level\" of the game could be anything! \r\n\r\nThis game is a turn based trading game with 4 levels. Every player has trading entities (a fleet, a caravan, a ship, or whatever), \"warehouses\" (places that he owns in which he can store goods and from which he can buy/sell/monitor the progress of markets at that location), an amount of money and goods stored various places. Money is universal but all other items are localized. \r\n\r\nEach location has from one to 6 buying and selling slots which buy or sell from among 100 different possible commodities. Each commodity has a base price (which varies from location to location) and a multiplier (which is unique to each commodity) and a fuzz number which is generated every turn for ever slot. The base price varies as commodities in a particular market are bought and sold (that is, it goes up every time an item is sold to and down every time something is bought from a market).  Multipliers exist to make some items more valuable and expensive than others; it also results in being able to make more money on those commodities if you can afford them. The system should also be skewed so that the more expensive things tend to be slightly less profitable (because getting 5% return on $100 is already 5 times as good as getting a 5% return on $20 and we\'d like your growth curve to look more like a lawn chair than a hockey stick). The fuzz is just a bit of random noise thrown in (just a few percentage points of the total price, no more) to make it less obvious what\'s going on. \r\n\r\nThe base price actually goes up in tiny steps. Let\'s say that each cargo of goods bought and sold will actually change the base price by 1 point. The transactions are actually broken into 100 steps: everyone gets to buy/sell .01 cargo at the current price, then it goes up/down .01 point for each person who did a transaction, then we do it again. That means that cargos will cost you more and make you less when you are buying or selling them while someone at the same port is buying or selling them at the same time. Oh well. \r\n\r\nIf no one buys a commodity the price of the commodity goes very slowly down. Likewise, if no one sells a commodity the price they\'re offering goes up very slowly. Provisionally, I\'m thinking they change one step every 3 turns of inactively (so 3 turns of inactivity is like one turn of activity) -- this means that a player who buys a commodity, sells it somewhere else and then comes back to buy again will be playing a slowly losing game. If the price goes down or goes up below/beyond some limit we retire that commodity.\r\n\r\nHere is where it gets kind of difficult. When a commodity goes away, and at the beginning of the game, we need to figure out which (and how many) commodities go where. The ideal would be to consider the global market and add demand and supply such that players will find it interesting. Maybe count the total supply (including stuff in warehouses and holds -- or maybe not) and add commodities such that we even it out (supply grows to meet demand but does demand grow to meet supply!?). Then we consider the multipliers people have been buying and add stuff that will bring the total supply and demand for that level and a bit higher up. But keep some cheap goods around for new players! \r\n\r\nThat is, roughly the basic game. ','2005-03-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(42,15,'Dave Menconi','Level one is a ancients game bases around the Mediterranian sea. There are up to 100 ports each one exactly one turn from every other one. Each one has a warehouse and from one to 6 buying and 1 to 6 selling slots (I can\'t decide). Every player has a warehouse and a ship. There are two exits (one at each end, clearly marked). Players start with $100 (except we call it \"gold pieces\"); players can leave when they reach $100,000. \r\n\r\nI\'m a bit vague on exactly how the buying and selling slots are allocated because I\'m just not sure what might be fun. I want to get the game running and then run some sims on it. ','2005-03-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(43,15,'Dave Menconi','Level 2 is set in the middle ages. The player has a caravan and a warehouse. The cities are set all over europe and norther africa and asia. There are 100 towns set in a carefully constructed network. Some are crossroads. Some are outliers. Some may not have much in them. I think, for simplicity sake, each town is one turn from it\'s connected town but some towns don\'t have much in the way of commodities -- that\'s better than having some edges in the network be multi-turn, I think. \r\n\r\nOnce again, 100 towns, 100 commodities. In addition to the map, we allow people to buy \"agents\" who will tell them about the current prices in towns. And we allow people to buy warehouses in distant towns. Maybe they can buy extra caravans. ','2005-03-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(44,15,'Dave Menconi','Level 3 is set in space. This is why the game is called \"Dark Galaxy\" in some instances. \r\n\r\nThe player has a spaceship. He also has a planet. The planet has a warehouse and the usual market slots. Actually, the only different between 2 and 3 is that we don\'t tell the players the map ahead of time. \r\n\r\nIt would be cool if the universe changed over time, with new connections growing and old connections fading away and isolated regions being removed and new regions being added. This would prevent old hands from giving newbies the map (or, for that matter having one themselves). \r\n\r\n','2005-03-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(45,15,'Dave Menconi','Level 4 is a space conquest game, pretty much pure and simple. Every planet has a \"resource\" number. You own a planet if you have a war ship at it or you were the last person to have a warship at it. Planets accumulate their resource. 100 resource points (RP) make a warship. 50 RP make a cargo ship. A cargo ship can carry 1 cargo or 10 rp. You can build a ship anywhere there are enough RP that you control. \r\n\r\nYou take a planet by being the only one with warships on it. When two or more players have warships on a planet they fight according to simple rules. Maybe Risk. The last one standing owns the planet; just that simple. \r\n\r\nOh, yeah, trading. :)\r\n\r\nWorks just like in the level 3 EXCEPT that you have to have the permission of the owner to trade on a planet. The owner gets 10 percent of every transaction on his planet; this is taken off in taxes. The trader gets full price. \r\n\r\n(ALTERNATIVE: the owner can set the taxes on every planet; the higher the taxes the slower the prices recover). \r\n\r\nWe need to do something about warlord: when you get 40% of the total planets in the game you are declared the WINNER and must leave the game. All you holdings, warships, cash, cargo, etc just goes way (alternative: it is given to your sons -- 2-6 computer players -- who squander it slowly). Likewise, when you get a certain amount of money you get to leave. \r\n\r\nWhat about people who have, say, 39% of the planets? They can make the game pretty un-fun for the other players potentially. If the map keeps changing they may find that to be a hell of a challenge. \r\n\r\nFood for thought. ','2005-03-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(46,16,'Dave Menconi','Every player gets to guess one number per turn. He can change his guess at any time. The game shows a list of all the current guesses to the nearest 10. At midnight it calculates the average of all the numbers and the person with the closest number to the average wins.','2005-03-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(47,16,'Dave Menconi','The game has a general display page which shows all the guesses. Closest 10 is divide by 10, take the integer and multiply by 10 (\"(int(current/10))*10\").\r\n\r\nThe game has a blurb which tells potential players about the game. If the viewer is a registered user it also has a signup link. If not it has a link to the site registration. Thas also has a link to all the current games.\r\n\r\nEach current game has a current status page which shows the standings of the game and a list of the players current guesses. Also who won yesterday, the guess that won and the total.\r\n','2005-03-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(48,4,'Dave Menconi','Redwall has a front page which has a list of the games in the site. Each game has a link to the blurb page and a link to the current situation in the game. Also a link to register adn a log-in link. \r\n\r\nRedwall also has a register page.','2005-03-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(49,16,'Dave Menconi','The game also has a user turn page which has the list of all the guesses the player has made and which he won. It has a form for entering the current guess as well as what the current guess already is. Maybe the stats on past turns. ','2005-03-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(50,16,'Dave Menconi','Game status page will allow you to log in. it also shows you the numbers your opponents have entered since you\'ve been playing. ','2005-03-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(51,2,'Dave Menconi','Rob,\r\n\r\nI\'ve gotten it to keep indents\r\n    like this\r\nAs well as really long lines that are actually too long for the page to display comfortably like this and like many of my other comments. I think it\'s good to go back and forth but I ask that you not give up on it just because I didn\'t get it right the first time. It took a while \r\nANDitalsworkswithreallylonglinesthathavenospacesinthembutgoonandonandonforeverwithonecontinuousline\r\n ','2005-04-05','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(52,18,'Dave Menconi','The key to this game is the model for running. Here is a proposed model. \r\n\r\nEach character at any moment has 4 possible states: resting, walking, running and sprinting. Each character has the following 9 attributes: speed of walking, running and sprinting, stamina, stamina recovery rate, and stamina cost for walking, running and sprinting. It may be that some of these attributes (but not speed or stamina) are fixed for all characters. \r\n\r\nStamina is the measure of a character\'s energy. No matter what he is doing, he recovers stamina at some rate. The cost for walking is typically lower than the recovery rate, the cost of running and sprinting is a great deal higher (presumably sprinting is WAY higher). Someone runs until he runs out of stamina and then is forced to walk or rest. \r\n\r\nIt would be nice if the speeds were maximum speeds and the cost for movement was tied to your actual speed. Maybe walking and sprinting costs are fixed (at a very low and very high rate) but you can run at any rate from just above walking to your maximum and the cost would be just above the recovery rate to the running cost. ','2005-04-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(53,18,'Dave Menconi','There needs to be a terrain model that tracks slope and terrain type (rough, hard, soft, etc) as well as line of site rules. \r\n\r\nPossible scenarios might include races -- both running around on a track and marathon-type races -- and chases. \r\n\r\nWolves vs. settlers would involve a pack of wolves chasing a group of humans. Humans who slow down enough for the wolves to catch them are attacked. Multiple wolves may be required to subdue a human and wolves who stop to work on the human are not able to chase the rest of the humans. But the wolves are fast enough to catch the humans quickly. The last human standing is the winner of the human side while the wolf that eats the most is the winner of the wolf side. Not sure if there is a way to get an overall winner. \r\n\r\nPrison Break is a race between guards and escaping prisoners. The guards have more stamina but the prisoners have a head start. The map would be important with several choices that the prisoners could make and site blocking terrain as well as short paths to freedom that are exposed and long paths that run through woods. Also we might allow the prisoners so many customization points which they can trade for time -- so they have fewer with a longer head start and more with a shorter head start. \r\n\r\nThe Hunt could be a bunch of humans trying to bring down some animals who are computer players. ','2005-04-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(54,19,'Dave Menconi','This will notify a user by email when a web site changes. There is a web page that  a user accesses to register the web site to watch. They enter a URL and frequency (probably never more often than once a day) as well as an email (or we just use their email on file). When we register, the program pulls down the page and does a checksum and stores that in the database. \r\n\r\nPeriodically, a program runs that looks in the database and pulls down the page and compares the new checksum with the old. If they differ, it send a notification.\r\n\r\nThe database simply has a table with the following fields: \r\nurl, email, frequency, checksum.\r\n\r\nSomewhere I have code that solves all the technical problems of this; it\'s just a matter of writing the app!','2005-04-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(55,19,'Dave Menconi','Ok, reality check: it ain\'t quite so easy! Almost every page has a chunk of stuff that changes from moment to moment. For this to work well, we have to map out the parts that change. \r\n\r\nSo we get a snapshot (baseline) and then we get another. We find the differences and record where they were and remove them from the baseline. Then we get another snapshot and remove the same sections. If the checksum matches the baseline then we can stop (or maybe we do this a few times just to make sure). \r\n\r\nNow we have a list of starts and lengths of things that need to be removed. We add that to another table. \r\n\r\nregistryno, start, end\r\n\r\nWe have to add a register ID to the first table. \r\n\r\nNow we do exactly the same thing but we remove the specified pieces before we do the checksum each time. ','2005-04-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(56,18,'Dave Menconi','Wolves vs Settlers\r\nThis game needs a set of special \"wolf rules\". The wolves are trying to eat the humans. One wolf can\'t eat a human but if one wolf attacks a human that human moves slower -- maybe half speed. If two wolves attack a human that human stops to defend himself. If three to five wolves attack a human that human is brought down -- he\'s going to get eaten! This takes a few turns (perhaps one turn to attack them and then one full turn doing nothing else -- perhaps required) but only the wolves who stay for the entire duration get credit. If the number of wolves drops below three, the human gets back up and the process has to start over. If more than 5 wolves attack the same human only the 5 highest prestige wolves succeed. \r\n\r\nWolves cannot talk to each other; they are anonymous. They are named wolf01 to wolf10. Wolf01 is the alpha male and wolf10 is, like, the youngest, weakest wolf. Wolf01 is the first player to sign up while wolf10 is the last wolf signed up. (Alternatively, the wolf players have the option of putting choice points on STRENGTH which is only useful for determining the pecking order and attacking wolves; ties are broken by highest sprinting speed then highest running speed.)\r\n\r\nHigh prestige wolves can attack low prestige whenever they want. Low prestige wolves can challenge high prestige wolves but cannot attack them. But after three challenges if the high prestige wolf doesn\'t fight he loses his place. If he DOES fight and loses he swaps places with the low prestige wolf. In any event both wolves waste a turn screwing around if they fight. \r\n\r\nHow are fights resolved? Strength plus stamina reserves. So jump them when they\'re tired. Feeding wolves are considered to be resting.\r\n\r\nSince the winner is the wolf that eats the most humans, one has to figure out how many human points you get when you share a human. Maybe each worlf gets a fraction (.2, .25 or .33) or maybe everyone gets 1. \r\n\r\nThere are as many wolves as humans. Humans have 1/3 the sprint speed and 1/2 the running speed and somewhat less stamina. Humans have some points they can play (key point of the game: do you want to be slow but with lots of stamina or fast  with no staying power? ). \r\n\r\nThe map is probably not critical but we want 2 or more reasonable ways to go. It might be interesting if the humans split up: every time the humans split up there is a chance that the wolves chasing them won\'t be enough to get them. On the other hand, humans will never outrun the wolves; they\'re only chance if to outrun the other humans.\r\n\r\nThere may be an ending that preserves life or the animals might always eat all the humans and the winner is the LAST human  to be eaten. \r\n\r\n','2005-04-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(57,20,'Dave Menconi','The goal of this project is to take data from the GPS and possibly other sources and use it to work out the speed of traffic at various times on various routes.\r\n\r\nFor starters, since we don\'t have the map data, we need to have a way to identify legs (\"leg\" is defined as a stretch of road with no turns). This means we have to be able to identify intersections. An intersection, I think, is a the point where two routes cross. Comparing two routes and identifying common points is a good start but not the whole story because what if the two routes are going down the same street? The routes have to be on different streets. So we\'re looking for two routes with only one point in common and that point is an intersection. \r\n\r\nOut of tens of thousands of points, how do we identify the common points? We want to impose a grid on it. One thought is to use a dynamic grid with only 10 points in a square. Perhaps a better thought is to simply make a uniform grid 1/2 the width of a road. That way, two points that are in the same grid and each part of a different perpendicular route, must define an intersection. \r\n\r\nPaths of routes between intersections are legs. The average speed of all the points along that leg is the speed of that leg. Now we figure out the legs contained in a route and we can figure out how fast we can travel it.\r\n\r\nWait, what if we downloaded actual routes? Do they have GPS coords as the turning points? Those are your intersections. We can then find points that go from one to the other and those are the data points we need for the speed...','2005-05-03','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(58,21,'Dave Menconi','Joe tends to do the following things\r\n\r\n\"Newsletter\" -- a set of timely notes to bring members and parents up to date. This would include the actual \"newsletters\" as well as things like the recap.\r\n\r\n\"Calendar\" -- a calendar month form of what\'s happening this month\r\n\r\n\"show itinerary\" -- a list of acts and times along with general information and directions to the venue\r\n\r\n\"band info\" -- information about the various bands\r\n\r\n\"fund raisers\" -- information about fund raisers\r\n\r\n\"weekly schedule\" -- schedule on a weekly basis','2005-05-16','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(59,22,'Dave Menconi','Amoeba War would be the perfect name for this except that it\'s been taken. Each player is a collection of Amoeba -- one celled organisms -- scattered through space. The Amoeba have begun to be self-aware and the player is their awareness directing their actions. \r\n\r\nThe game is based on Tim Conway\'s cellular autonoma, Life. The universe is a grid of squares which are either occupied by an amoeba or not. The universe, if left to itself, works just like Life: any square with less than 3 or more than 4 occupied squares surrounding it dies out (or is left empty) and any empty square with exactly 3 squares around it occupied gets a new amoeba. We add to thise rules a player phase before each Life phase (plus a setup phase at the beginning): the player has a certain number of moves and each move consists of taking an occupied square and moving its contents into an adjacent square. The number of moves a player has is based on how many of his occupied squares have more than one amoeba at the start of the turn: if 1 or less, he gets one move, otherwise he gets a number of moves equal to the number of squares. \r\n\r\nIdeally, victory comes when one has taken over the whole universe but this may not be possible as the universe is 100x100. ','2005-05-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(60,22,'Dave Menconi','A few other notes. Each player starts with a unique color amoeba. When an ameoba is born it is the color of the 2 ','2005-05-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(61,22,'Dave Menconi','A few other notes. Each player starts with a unique color amoeba. When an ameoba\r\nis born it is the color of the majority or it\'s grey. This could be important because the game may end when someone has, say 100 amoeba or when the player has some percentage of the total. \r\n\r\nFor setup, each player is assigned a 5x5 square. The allowed 5x5 squares are arranged in a checkerboard pattern, with the corners not allowed. The human players will only be on the edges but the computer players will be throughout (that is, in all the non-edge allowed squares). Computer players are not aware and do not move their pieces. I suppose they should be grey. Some of the \"human\" players may be played by more sophisticated computer players (like a player who arranges all his pieces in 2x2 squares and moves a corner onto one of the other 3). The player sets up 10 amoebae in his 5x5 square in any pattern he wants but he can only put one amoeba in any square. Then he gets his move (one move) and may move one amoeba into another square. (I should do some research about Life and see if 10 is enough to make a glider or a cannon -- setting up a cannon would be cool). \r\n\r\nA player is not told about the whole board but only his amoeba and two squares out from them. \r\n\r\nWe should build some simulators that the players can use. ','2005-05-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(62,23,'Dave Menconi','Need a \r\nGame Table\r\nGame ID\r\nGame Name\r\nNumber Players\r\nCoordinator Name\r\nLocation\r\nCoordinator Email\r\nDate\r\n\r\nPlayer Table \r\nGame Number\r\nPlayer Name\r\nPlayer Email\r\nDate\r\n\r\nAnyone can add a game and they are the moderator. Then Players can register for the game. When the requisite number of players have registered, the game is removed from the list and the email addresses are sent to the moderator.\r\n\r\nAfter 3 months any unfilled games are removed. \r\n\r\nThere is a page that lists open games (game name, number of players, number registered, location). At the bottom is a form to add a new game. If you click on a game it will allow you to register for it. If that registration fills the game, it will send a message to the moderator and remove it.\r\n\r\nAny action will cause the program to look at all the games and remove any that are older than 3 months. (If there is so little use that some linger beyond 3 months, what harm?)','2005-05-31','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(63,3,'Dave Menconi','We\'ve come a long way with this today. One major change is in how we\'re going to handle subsections. A subsection is just a section whose subsection field contains a non-zero number. Specifically, it contains the number of the section to which it\'s a subsection. ','2005-06-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(64,4,'Dave Menconi','The front page has a logo, then a list of links -- the site navigation stuff -- then it has a list of games with their logos. Each game has one or more of the following notations: \"Now Accepting Players\", \"Games Now Running\" and \"Coming Soon\". The last will always be by itself but the other two are independent of each other. The logo and each of the notations is a link. The logo and \"Coming Soon\" go to a description of the game with a link to the rules and the game sign up. Games Now Running goes to a page that shows the running games and their status and has links to player and non-player game information (i.e. public info and private info). Now Accepting Players takes you to the \"sign up for this game\" link.','2005-06-15','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(65,4,'Dave Menconi','FOR SITE\r\nFront Page\r\nRegistration Page\r\nLogin Page\r\nLogout Link\r\nLost Password Page\r\nDonation Page\r\n\r\n\r\nFOR EACH TYPE OF GAME\r\n   Game Description Page\r\n   Game Sign Up Page\r\n   Running Game List\r\n\r\nFOR EACH RUNNING GAME\r\n   Public Info Page\r\n   Player Login\r\n   Player Info Page\r\n   Player Orders Form\r\n','2005-06-15','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(66,4,'Dave Menconi','My new idea about running games works much more simply. RedWall maintains a list of running games and how often they run.\r\n\r\nRedWall has a process that runs through the running games list, finds the next one that runs and, when that one runs, calls that games \"process turn\" function and hands it a game number as the parameter.\r\n\r\nEach game has to have a process turn executable that the Redwall process can call. This executable knows how to find the state of the game and the turns and processes them.\r\n\r\nWhen games are started a flat tab delimited temporary file is created that has the player information in it (usernames and email addresses). The location of this file is passed to the \"start game\" executable provided by the game designer. This process converts the information from the flat file to the game\'s native format for storing information. \r\n\r\nWhen a turn comes in, Redwall collects the information, verifies that it came from a particular user and passes this information, in a file, to the \"input turn\" executable provided by the game designer. \r\n\r\nSO the game designer has to write 3 Unix programs in a language of his choice. \r\n\"process turn\" which takes the game number \r\n\"input turn\" which takes a file containing a user\'s turn information\r\n\"start game\" which takes a file containing all the starting information\r\n\r\nThe game must know it\'s own game type and each of it\'s game numbers. These together identify a specific game. RedWall provides a program that the game calls when the game is over. The game passes the game type and game number and results (must be in a standard format) and RedWall marks that game as closed, posts the results and so forth.','2005-06-15','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(67,4,'Dave Menconi','Ok, one thing I forgot is that a notation on a game type on the front page (or possibly on the game type description page) is \"Game Completed\" -- perhaps we only post this when a game has been completed recently (\"Game Completed Recently\").\r\n\r\nThis link takes you to a game page that has the results of the game. We need to have a standard format for this. How about, the first record defines the statistics the game is going to send and then subsequent records list the player username and his stats. The list is assumed to be in order from best to worst and it is not required (but desired) that it include all the players.\r\n\r\nFor example, the first line says\r\n\"Score,Cash,Ships,Planets,People\"\r\nAnd subsequent lines say\r\nDave,200000,10000,20,50,2000\r\nFred,180000, 9000,25,40,1600\r\nAnn, 150000,12000,13,25,1000\r\nAND SO FORTH\r\n\r\nIt would be nice if RedWall tracked all these stats for each player (first how many times in which game, second, how many times in which games, average score, average cash, average ships, average planets, average people). Note that RedWall has no idea what any of this stuff means, it just has to track it according to the data given, which is defined by the game. Not sure how to do that. ','2005-06-15','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(68,30,'DAM','An LBS Game: \r\nLOCATION LOTTO\r\nFirst, the player selects either longitude, latitude or radius.\r\nThen the player pushes go. If there are other players at the same longitude, latitude or radius within a certain period of time he gets a certain number of points. He can do longitude, latitude and radius from one position but then he\'s done that one and he can\'t do it again for this game (that is, for some period of time -- maybe a month). You get more points for longitude than for the others and more for latitude than for radius. At the end of the month the player with the highest points is listed, the player with the most locations tried from is listed and, perhaps the players with the highest score from each lat and long!','2005-06-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(69,30,'','An LBS Game:\r\nSNAKE\r\nAll the players playing are given 8 points, in order. The first is centered on them and the other 7 form the same shape and the same orientation. The goal of the game is either to move to all 7 points (you start on the 8th) in the shortest time or to move to most points in some period of time. \r\nA variation is to allow players to do the points out of order. ','2005-06-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(70,30,'DAM','An LBS Game: \r\nTREASURE HUNT\r\nA pattern of locations are laid out. This pattern is overlaid on the player. The player is told of the locations and some information as to their value and a rough pattern for them but not their actual locations. The player can pick one and get a range and direction. When the player gets close to a location he can attempt to \"dig it up\" through some process which I\'m not sure about -- but probably something more interesting and difficult than just clicking on a button. \r\n\r\nThe goal of the single player game is to see how many treasures you can pick up in a fixed amount of time or how long it takes to pick up a fixed number of treasures. \r\n\r\nFor multiple players playing simultaneously, the players are oganized into teams. We would like all the teams to be the same size to the degree possible and it\'s best if the players are NOT geographically close to each other; otherwise it doesn\'t matter how you arrange them. Each player has the same pattern overlaid on them. \r\n\r\nThe members of the team look to see which treasures seem to be the easiest/fastest to get to and propose to dig up the easiest by clicking on it. If two players click on the same treasure then one player can pick another treasure or both players can try for the same treasure. All the players can see which players are going for which treasures. And all the players can see which treasures they\'ve already gotten. Once anyone has gotten a treasure that treasure is no longer available to any other player. \r\n\r\nThe strategy behind this game is that some players on your team will be in a position to get some of the treasures while other players will not. It may be that one treasure is accross a freeway from me but it\'s just at the other side of an open park from you; likewise another is just up the street from me but it\'s on the other side of a building from you. By overlaying the exact same position over different kinds of terrain, each player has a unique relationship to each treasure. \r\n\r\n','2005-06-23','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(71,30,'DAM','Access Softek costs $125 an hour and has workers who are experienced. If you are only going to do projects for, on average, 9 months out of the year, AS will be cheaper. Also, they will be very profficient the first year while a home-grown team won\'t hit the ground until the second year. ','2005-06-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(72,30,'DAM','An LBS Game:\r\nCOLLECTION TAG\r\nThis is a multiplayer game. One player is designated \"it\". A grid is laid over all the players with their starting position in the center of the grid. Two players who are at the same grid position are said to be \"touching\". The screen shows where all the other players are in relation to the player and which people are \"it\".\r\n\r\nThe player who is \"it\" runs around trying to \"touch\" other players. When gets close enough (that is, close enough to the point on his grid that corresponds to the point on the other player\'s grid he\'s on) to be considered to have \"touched,\" the player touched joins the \"it\" team and now tries to tag other players. \r\n\r\nWhen all the players have joined the \"collection\" the game calculates statistics (for example, how many players each person captured and the order in which they were captured). If a new game is played, the last player caught who is in the new game is \"it\".\r\n\r\nThis game has many interesting aspects. The very best players will last the longest but will eventually join the collection because it gets harder and harder to avoid being caught as the number of people trying to catch you grows. \r\n\r\nThe game might be best played in a big field but it might also be interesting to play in an office building or on city streets. For the most part, the players in the most open areas will have the best chance but if several players are constrained then there can be interesting and amusing situations (where stepping 5 feet to the right puts me safely on the other side of a wall from you, for example). \r\n\r\nConsider the fact that, if several people are playing near each other they can bump into each other without \"tagging\" each other because they are in a completely different space from each other! So everyone in your office building could play this game and they would appear to be running randomly around even though they are actually chasing each other! \r\n\r\nYou could, to add interest, rotate the spaces of various players so that when you run North you appear to me to be running East to me. You can also make me run faster or slower on the grid to take into account, for example, the age of the players. These adaptations might make it possible, for example, to have a bunch of kids playing on large field in a way that might be more fun than just playing a normal game. Also, you could have a shorter or longer game by make the \"it\" people run faster or slower or by \"handicapping\" the players that did well in the last game. You could even do this automatically so the players who are moving slowly in the game are sped up while the players who are quick are slowed down.\r\n\r\nPeople being the way they are, there will probably have to be some limits to the area or one player will just run away and no one will be able to catch him. Players that step outside the boundaries of the grid join the collection. Also, one needs to keep in mind that all the different handicapping schemes can be \"gamed\" (that is, if fast players are slowed down then fast players will go abnormally slow to avoid the handicapping -- until they need speed when they will run their normal speed).','2005-07-06','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(73,31,'DAM','The basic idea is that there is a small set of inputs to a system of equations. The equations interact in many ways and then result in a small number of outputs. With such a system you could simulate, for example, the world economy and ecology. \r\n\r\nThe basic element of such a system is the cell. A cell has an id number and an equation and a value, which is always a floating point number. The equation uses other cells\' values to calculate this cell\'s value. The equation is basically an infix notation formula in string form that it parsed when we want to calculate the value of this cell. \r\n\r\nCells are calculated in a fixed order. Loops are possible and even acceptable (I think). ','2005-07-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(74,32,'DAM','Lord, it\'s simple. Just throw a page in here and no one will be able to look at it unless this application is one of that user\'s privs. \r\n\r\nWhen accessed, the program opens up all the files, gets the &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt; line from them (or the first &lt;h1&gt;&lt;/h1&gt; line if no title, or the first line of the body if neither or the first line of the file if none of them) and organizes these into a directory list. When you click on one, it displays the file. \r\n\r\nIt ignores index.html but considers .htm, .html and .txt fair game as well as files with no extender.\r\n\r\nIt opens up all these files and creates an array with: the first line, &lt;title&gt;, the line after &lt;body&gt;, &lt;h1&gt;. For efficiency, it can stop if it finds &lt;title&gt; or &lt;h1&gt;. Then it adds the line of this to the directory array (along with the filename) that is the \"best it can do\".\r\n\r\n\r\n','2005-07-17','2009-10-07 14:19:37'),(75,1,'Dave Menconi','Since \"Policies\" also (and most commonly from the user\'s point of view) refers to conditions of business and use, can we change this term to something more admin-oriented, such as \"settings\" or \"options\" or \"site parameters?\"','2005-07-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(76,23,'Dave Menconi','We\'re going to call this the \"Redwall Games Registry\".\r\n\r\n','2005-07-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(77,23,'Dave Menconi','1) register to be a moderator\r\n2) start new game (moderators only)\r\n3) Sign up for an existing game\r\n4) check on status (moderators only)','2005-07-23','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(78,23,'Dave Menconi','Tables\r\n1) List of coordinator\r\n2) list of players\r\n3) list of registered games\r\n\r\n1)  coordinator table\r\ncoordinator ID\r\nReal name\r\nemail address\r\npassword\r\nemail address\r\ntime stamp\r\n\r\n2) player table\r\nplayer id\r\nreal name\r\ngame no\r\nemail address\r\ntime stamp\r\n(note: this is not in 2nf so that when you delete the game you can delete the players)\r\n\r\n3) Game table\r\ngameid\r\ngame name\r\nnumber of players\r\ncoordinator no\r\ngame city\r\ndatestamp\r\n\r\n','2005-07-23','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(79,7,'Dave Menconi','Every user on the site has the option of creating three lists of users. The first, weakest list, is the list of people he has successfully concluded business with. The second, is the list of people on the site that he or she has communicated with other than for transactions. And the third is the list of people on the site whom you know personally. \r\n\r\nThese three lists, maintained for all the users, form a network. Closest to the user is the network of people he knows or are known by someone known to him. \r\n\r\nNext comes the people with whom he has communicated or who have communicated with someone in his network or with someone he has communicated with. \r\n\r\nThe last, largest, and least reliable group is the group of people the he or is first two networks have had a successful transaction with. \r\n\r\nUsers should be able to limit their transactions to only those people who are in one or more of these groups. They should also be able to query the network to ask \"is this person reliable\". \r\n\r\nWhen a transaction is complete, people are encouraged to rate the tranaction partner. So now the links in the network have weight (1-5) and people can say \"only count 5 links\". Only count people who are less than 5 away. \r\n\r\nAnyway, this gives you a much better sense of who you might be willing to transact with. ','2005-07-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(80,33,'DAM','All the php programs that I write have a variable $PARAMS that contains a combination of the $HTTP_POST_VARS and $HTTP_GET_VARS. This is the data that needs to be verified.\r\n\r\nSeems like a good start would be \r\n\r\n         foreach ($PARAMS as $key->$val)\r\n\r\nfollowed by \r\n\r\n        $val = CleanData($val) \r\n\r\nwhere CleanData is a routine that removes all non-printable chracters, javascript or anything else that might be harmful. \r\n\r\nand then a switch \r\n\r\n        switch($key){\r\n\r\nthat looks at each case and performs various tests to ensure that they meet the criteria for that particular field. \r\n\r\nIf the field is not one we know about we might consider removing it from the array (to prevent malicious people from shoving weird stuff into our array). One can go too far on this sort of cleanup but it seems to me that this is an array where the adage \"It pays to be paranoid\" applies.\r\n\r\nIf it all passes muster then we\'re golden. If not then we should make a list of fields that failed and why in an array. \r\n\r\nThen we need to call the appropriate display function, passing this array, and having it display the problems in an appropriate way.\r\n\r\nIn my code I have a display function and a parse function for each form and this is all controlled by the mode= parameter. So we know that if mode=parseregister there is a display function that displays that (probably Display_Register if I followed my naming conventions). So we have another switch statement that tells us which display routine to call. \r\n\r\nUltimately, I\'d like to construct a data-driven version of this but for now, my thought is to represent all the relationships in switch statements. ','2005-08-03','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(81,33,'DAM & TMT','When we detect weird stuff in the input, we should build an anomaly record that includes userid, host, IP, etc., whatever we can get, and store away for purposes of building a bad guy database.\r\n\r\nAs for verification...\r\nWe want to avoid putting up extraneous screens, hard on us and hard on the user.\r\n\r\nIf a data field fails validation, the original data entry screen should be refreshed with all valid fields filled-in with their data and an indication next to the bad field (display field name in different color, e.g.).  We could also put a link/button next to the field to display a help screen for that field, explaining what is valid data.\r\n\r\nI don\'t like the idea of a separate array for bad fields, maybe a structure for form fill-in data...\r\n  Field Label\r\n  Normal Color\r\n  Error Color\r\n  Sentinel Value\r\n  Current Value\r\n  Validation Function\r\n  Valid Data Flag\r\n  Required Field Flag\r\n  Help Function\r\n  Field Type\r\n  Field Size\r\n\r\nField Label is the text displayed on the form\r\nNormal Color is the color of the field label text, when not in error\r\nError Color is the color of the field label text, when in error\r\nSentinel Value is value field starts with, indicates no data entered\r\nCurrent Value starts with Sentinel Value, gets filled in by user on form\r\nValidation Function is self-explanatory\r\nValid Data Flag takes 3 values: Not Validated Yet, Invalid, Valid\r\nRequired Field Flag is self-explanatory\r\nHelp Function can be URL or display function, used when field in error\r\nField Type indicates type of data, string, numeric, radio button, etc.\r\nField Size indicates text entry box size\r\n\r\nEach field on a form has a record/structure like above.\r\n\r\nAfter submit button is pressed, all fields get validated, and if any fail validation, the form is re-displayed with valid data filled-in and invalid fields indicated with an error color and help button, but no data.  A new heading should be displayed that alerts the user there were errors in the entered data.\r\n\r\nUser doesn\'t have to enter good data twice and we don\'t have to display a bunch of extra screens that explain what went wrong, unless the user wants the help.  Experienced users will appreciate this approach.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure what you mean by the mode= parameter.  I had a form display function and a form submit function (probably same as your parse function).  To support frames I also had a third function that basically called the display function.  The next display function to call is usually dependent on error conditions, etc.\r\n\r\nUsually my parse function was split into the following three stages, in the order presented:\r\n  Validate input data\r\n  Do calculations / DB accesses and updates\r\n  Prepare for next display page\r\n\r\nErrors could be detected and handled through special pages in stages 1 & 2.  Once I got to stage 3, there should not be any possibility of error and the next form could be prepared/presented.\r\n','2005-08-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(82,33,'DAM','Yes, very good points. \r\n\r\nOn the array, I assume the key will be the field name? \r\n\r\nGee, if we add a field that identifies which form this field belongs to and put it all in a table in the database, we\'re within shouting distance of a data-driven generic form displayer/verifier. \r\n\r\nOn the Validation and help functions, does PHP have a way to turn the text name of a function into a function call? Or would we use a switch statement to do that?\r\n\r\nHelp function could be just a string that one displays in a generic page (that is, instead of having a function for every field, we have one function that displays the text that explains why the field failed). The link button could be a tiny bit of javascript (I don\'t like javascript as a rule) that pops up a little text window with the help text in it.\r\n\r\nI understood everything up to \"I\'m not sure what you mean by the mode= parameter.\" but I think that\'s ok. My code is written how it\'s written, it will be clear to you what I\'m talking about when you see it and then we can talk about how to make it better. \r\n\r\n','2005-08-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(83,34,'DAM','Create an app that, when linked to with the right params sends email to a designated user. It will only send email to specific users. \r\n\r\nThe question is, how do we ensure that spammer doesn\'t just call the link over and over!? \r\n\r\nCHAPKA!','2005-08-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(84,35,'DAM','What I envision is that the user enters in a list of single line statement which he wishes to order. The program presents two of them and asks which is more important. By assuming that if a<b and b<c then a<c (which may be true in mathematics but is a bit risky in opinions), the computer asks the minimum number of questions to rank the whole list. ','2005-08-17','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(85,35,'DAM','Another way to do that is \"by halves\". The user determines which things would be in the top half and which would be in the bottom half. Then you take each half and rank it and so on. \r\n\r\nNot sure about the user interface of ranking things by halves but maybe you could take the first thing and the thing in the middle and compare them and use them as the top of the two halves.\r\n\r\nWhat if we asked the user to select the thing he thinks is at the top and the thing he thinks is in the middle. \r\n\r\n','2005-08-17','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(86,36,'DAM','The basic idea here is to do a site that will assist gay people in finding thier life partner. The way this is accomplished is to have everyone on the site fill out a questiononaire and then to compare the results to all the other results to make a match. \r\n\r\nThe hard question is \" given a particular set of answers, which other set of answers represents the highest probability of being a good match\"? \r\n\r\nTo answer this question we need a statistically large collection of pairs of questionaires filled out by couples. We take the differences between their questionaires and then rate them based on their self-assessment of their relationship. So now we know that people with a good relationship have a high probability of a particular pattern. \r\n\r\nSo we match the person\'s questionaire with the one that has the highest statistical probability of making a good mate. \r\n\r\nWhere do we get the database? I\'m glad you asked that.\r\n\r\nWe create a site for gay couples in which we ask a whole bunch of questions of each of them, relate the two quesionaires and then give them some information about their relationship. The information about their relationship we pull out of our ass but we record the questionaires and use them as a basis for the relationship site. Also, we can use this data to say some things about their relationship, if we want. \r\n\r\nMy main idea for building the site is to have two parts to the main questionaire. The first part asks about you and your partner -- your name, your email address, how long you\'ve been together, your evaluation of your relationship and so on. This part also has the relationship number in it which is a unique number but not the index of this record. The respondant can either enter the relationship number of his significant other or get his own number (depending on whether he is entering this first followed by his sig other or if his sig other has already done it. \r\n\r\nThen there is the questionaire itself. I haven\'t quite worked this out but this consists of a list of questions each of which is numbered, and a list of answers each of which has the number of the question it\'s the answer to. This allows for the questionaire to change and for us to only compare identical questions. \r\n\r\nThere will also be a \"current questionaire\" that consists of a list of numbers which represent the questions we\'ll ask. \r\n\r\nThe questionaire editor will not let you change any questions but you can ADD questions and you can make checks next to the questions you want to be in the current questionaire. ','2005-08-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(87,37,'DAM','This starts as just a more sophisticated address book. As such, we\'ll start by listing the fields in the database. The actual application will start as nothing more than a program to select and edit such things. But we do want to be able to sort by various fields...\r\n\r\nname tinytext\r\nhometel tinytext\r\nrelationship tinytext\r\nprofession tinytext\r\nhomeaddr tinytext\r\ncompany tinytext\r\nofftel tinytext\r\ncelltel tinytext\r\nemail tinytext\r\nwrkaddr tinytext\r\nassistant  tinytext\r\nchildren  tinytext\r\nlastcall date\r\nrefferedby tinytext\r\nresults mediumtext\r\nfollowup mediumtext\r\nletter mediumtext\r\ncall mediumtext\r\nprefcomm enum (\'email\', \'cell\', \'home\',\'work\', \'mail\')\r\ninterests mediumtext\r\nowner int\r\ncomments mediumtext\r\n','2005-09-07','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(88,37,'DAM','Also\r\n\r\ncontactid int\r\nreferalno int\r\nowner int (an owner could be a contact with a referalno of 0 or = to the contactid)\r\n','2005-09-07','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(89,37,'DAM','All contacts should also have a \"last contact\" date which is very important plus a category and priority (which indicates immediacy). \r\n\r\nThe categories are thus\r\nA Active -- contact every 3 months\r\nB Background -- contact every 6 months\r\nC Complementary -- contact every 12 months\r\nD Dormant -- never contact\r\n\r\nThe priority is a number from 1 to 5 where 1 is the highest priority and 20 the lowest. This simply means that the program will have you contact the A1 people before the A2 people. The system will always work through all the A1s before handing you an A2 and will have you handle all the As before giving you a B. \r\n\r\nHowever, if you have NEVER contacted someone it considers this fact separately. A certain amount of time is set aside each week for contacting your current network and a certain amount of time is set aside for expanding your network and the two are considered independently.  ','2005-09-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(90,37,'DAM','Every week (may be adjusted), the system sends you an email (may be turned off), that tells you that you need to contact certain people. This is called a \"tickle\". You may also go to the web site and ask for the current tickle without it sending you an email. This is useful if you\'ve made new contacts or connected with old contacts since your last tickle but haven\'t updated the program. \r\n\r\nThe tickle is simply the N New contacts and O old contacts that have floated to the top. If you start to fall behind (that is, the number of contacts you are handling is less then the number of new contacts that are coming up) it will warn you about this and suggest you expand your slots to meet the load.','2005-09-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(91,37,'DAM','Preferences file (defaults in parens)\r\nDo I get email? (y)\r\nHow often?  (1 week)\r\nWhat times? (Sunday night midnight to 3 pm)\r\nHow many existing network contacts do I want to make (existing slots)? (3)\r\nHow many new network contacts do I want to make (new slots)? (1) \r\n\r\n','2005-09-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(92,37,'DAM','There is a user file that has basic user information including\r\nName\r\nemail address\r\npassword\r\nusername\r\nlast login\r\nnewcontacts handled in last month\r\nold contact handled in last month (look at log file, find people he changed the contact date on)\r\nnewcontacts needed in last month (total on list before culling for tickle)\r\nold contacts needed in last month (total on list before culling for tickle)\r\ntemppassword\r\ncontact time (a number between 1 and 60 which is the minutes beyond the hour that automated things happen for this guy).\r\ntimestamp\r\n','2005-09-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(93,37,'DAM','Files\r\nContact database\r\npreferences\r\nusers\r\nlogging\r\n\r\nApplications\r\nEdit a contact (edits one contact)\r\nSearch contact (searches list on certain specified fields)\r\nview/sort contacts (shows a list, possibly sorted, possibly result of search\r\nadd contacts\r\n\r\nFunctions\r\n\"I contacted this person on this date\"\r\n\"he gave me more contacts\" -- which should open a screen for you to enter them\r\n\"am I keeping up with my contacts or do I need to do more?\"\r\n\"Are my contacts categorized correctly (As should be providing me with the most new contacts)?\"\r\n','2005-09-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(94,37,'DAM','The report we want to support has the following elements\r\nContacts Made\r\nFollow Ups\r\nAppointments Scheduled\r\nAppointments Attended\r\nReferrals Received\r\nMeetings Attended\r\nResumes Mailed\r\nPhone Screens\r\nJob Interviews\r\nNegotiations\r\n\r\nNext weeks goals for all these things\r\nstrategic and tactical next steps (short notes from 1-10)\r\nAttitude  block of text\r\nproblems block of text\r\nlist of contacts made\r\nlist of follow ups done\r\nappointment scheduled\r\nappointments attentded\r\nreferals made (name, date, by whom)\r\nmeetings attended (date,group/purpose, cards)\r\nresumes mailed (company, date, position)\r\nphone screens (company, date, position)\r\njob interviews (company, date, position)\r\nnegotiations (company, date, position)','2005-09-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(95,38,'Ron Flynt','Roles Available: \r\n\r\nBuilder         \r\nCaptain         \r\nCraftsman         \r\nMayor         \r\nProspector 1         \r\nProspector 2         \r\nSettler         \r\nTrader         \r\n\r\nFields Available: \r\n\r\nQuarry (8), Corn, Sugar, Indigo, Tobacco, Coffee, Corn \r\n\r\nBuildings Available: \r\n\r\nBuilding        Cost        Building        Cost        Building        Cost        Building        Cost \r\nSmall Indigo Plant (4) 1 Indigo Plant (3) 3 Tobacco Storage (3) 5 Guild Hall (1) 10 \r\nSmall Sugar Mill (4) 2 Sugar Plant (3) 4 Coffee Roaster (3) 6 Residence (1) 10 \r\nSmall Market (2) 1 Hospice (2) 4 Factory (2) 7 Fortress (1) 10 \r\nHacienda (2) 2 Office (2) 5 University (2) 8 Custom House (1) 10 \r\nConstruction Hut (2) 2 Large Market (2) 5 Harbor (2) 8 City Hall (1) 10 \r\nSmall Warehouse (2) 3 Large Warehouse (2) 6 Wharf (2) 9 \r\n\r\nShips and Trading House: \r\nColonist Ship \r\n        5 colonists \r\n        \r\n\r\nShipping \r\nBoat 1 Boat 2 Boat 3 \r\nGood \r\nAmount 0/6 0/7 0/8 \r\n        \r\nTrading House \r\nGoods \r\n\r\nGoods Available: \r\n\r\n        Corn        Indigo        Sugar        Coffee        Tobacco \r\n        10/10        12/12        11/11        9/9        9/9 \r\n\r\nColonists and Experience Points Available: \r\n\r\n95 colonists        122 experience points \r\n\r\nNOTE: Fields and buildings are indicated as manned with a (M), a (U) indicates unmanned. \r\n\r\nPlayer 1:        4 Gold, 0 experience, 0 colonists\r\n\r\nBuildings: 0/12 \r\n\r\nNone \r\n\r\nFields: 1/12 \r\n\r\nIndigo (U) \r\n\r\nGoods:        None \r\n\r\nPlayer 2:        4 Gold, 0 experience, 0 colonists\r\n\r\nBuildings: 0/12 \r\n\r\nNone \r\n\r\nFields: 1/12 \r\n\r\nIndigo (U) \r\n\r\nGoods:        None \r\n\r\nPlayer 3:        4 Gold, 0 experience, 0 colonists\r\n\r\nBuildings: 0/12 \r\n\r\nNone \r\n\r\nFields: 1/12 \r\n\r\nIndigo (U) \r\n\r\nGoods:        None \r\n\r\nPlayer 4:        4 Gold, 0 experience, 0 colonists\r\n\r\nBuildings: 0/12 \r\n\r\nNone \r\n\r\nFields: 1/12 \r\n\r\nCorn (U) \r\n\r\nGoods:        None \r\n\r\nPlayer 5:        4 Gold, 0 experience, 0 colonists\r\n\r\nBuildings: 0/12 \r\n\r\nNone \r\n\r\nFields: 1/12 \r\n\r\nCorn (U) \r\n\r\nGoods:        None ','2005-09-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(96,38,'Dave Menconi','That looks great! I may actually prefer playing like this. \r\n\r\nHISTORY\r\nThe missing section is a \"history\" of what has recently happened. You show it as it would be on the first turn and it\'s obvious that this same form (with different values) would be used to show what the current static state of the game is. \r\n\r\nBut you also have to show the events. At a minimum, the very LAST event  -- but that means that you have to send an email to each player EVERY TIME AN EVENT OCCURS (i.e. one for Dave picking up a builder, one for Rob picking a building, one for Ron picking a building, and so on). It would be simpler (for you) to simply have a section here of all the events this round (since the governor changed) and then you only have to send people an email when they have a decision to make and that email will ALWAYS have all the relevant events. \r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could send everyone a message at the end of each ROLE that has all the events for that ROLE. This is in addition to the message that tells each person with a decision to make what the state of the world is (and what events have happened). \r\n\r\nFinally, you could send people emails ONLY when they have a decision to make and at that point send them all the events that happened since the last time they got an email. This is most efficient but *I* would probably lose track of which people have which information and then they would be confused. \r\n\r\nPersonally, I\'d just included ALL The events in this round and let the players sort out which information they\'ve already seen; I think they would find this more convenient and it would certainly be easier for me. \r\n\r\n\"EXPERIENCE POINTS\"?\r\nAre \"experience points\" what we usually call \"victory points\"? I gather that you have already determined that EP (VP?) pretty much needs to be open? Might as well since all I have to do is keep a pad by my computer where I write down every VP that\'s given out... \r\n\r\nAUTOMATION IDEAS\r\nAn interesting challenge will be to partially automate this process. Perhaps a database that has all this information and a web page that allows the moderator to edit the data with an entry for events. Like this: Rob picks builder. You go to the web site and remove \"builder\" from the list of roles and type into the \"event\" field \"Rob picked the builder role\". Then Rob buys a coffee roaster and you go to the web site and reduce the coffee buildings by one and type \"Rob buys a coffee building\" into the event field. Thus the system always has the current state of the game PLUS a list of \"events\" that it can send to people to explain how it GOT that way.\r\n\r\nThe program could then send email with this current state because you told it to -- another page with a list of players with check boxes next to them, a field for a message such as \"it\'s Rob\'s turn to pick a building\" and a button that says \"send\".\r\n\r\nOnce this \"moderator support\" system is working we can start automating certain tasks. We could, for example, change the text box where you enter events to a menu where you select an event -- you still have to change the state of the world but the system now knows what\'s going on in the game. From there we can automate when it sends emails and even change the state of the world based on events. \r\n\r\nI\'d want to grow this up step by step because it\'s pretty complicated and I suspect there will be some nasty \"edge cases\" that will require some experimenting. More than one test game will be required. \r\n','2005-09-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(97,38,'Ron Flynt','Experience Points changed to Victory Points don\'t know what I was thinking there. \r\n\r\nYou are right, there should be a current events area so I will add that too. We also should have a turn indicator that display the current turn number and the Govenor for the turn.\r\n\r\nYou are also correct that I decided to show victory points since any one could keep track of that anyway and I am forced to that is one of the winning conditions.\r\n\r\nI hadn\'t got to the point of thinking automation yet, I figured we try this first and then get there later.','2005-09-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(98,37,'DAM','<h3>EVENTS</h3>\r\nAppointment attended -- contacts, information, new status of contact\r\nmeeting attended -- new contacts, information gathered\r\ncontact followup -- Appointment scheduled, other information gathered, new status of contact\r\nresume mailed -- to whom, for what\r\nphone screen -- by whom, for what\r\njob interview -- by whom, for what\r\nnegotiations -- by whom for what\r\n','2005-09-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(99,37,'DAM','<h3>Appointment Attended</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who\r\n<li>Where\r\n<li>When\r\n<li>Source of referal (we should already know)\r\n<li>Date/time/duration\r\n<li>high points of conversation\r\n<li>List of contacts\r\n<li>New status of contact\r\n<ul>','2005-09-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(100,37,'DAM','<b>Meeting Attended</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>List of contacts\r\n<li>any new information gathered\r\n<li>New todo items generated\r\n</ul>','2005-09-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(101,37,'DAM','<b>contact followup</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Appointment scheduled\r\n<li>other information gathered\r\n<li>new status of contact\r\n</ul>','2005-09-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(102,37,'DAM','<b>resume mailed</b> \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>company\r\n<li>specific person\r\n<li>position\r\n<li>Date\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>phone screen</b> \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>company\r\n<li>specific person\r\n<li>position\r\n<li>Date\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>job interview</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>company\r\n<li>specific person\r\n<li>position\r\n<li>Date\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>negotiations</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>company\r\n<li>specific person\r\n<li>position\r\n<li>Date\r\n</ul>','2005-09-26','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(103,35,'DAM','Why not just have the user put a number from 1-n next to each item. n=2 it\'s by halves. n=3 it\'s by thirds. and so on. \r\n\r\nThen, if two or more things have the same number, we show just those items and do it again. This time, those items that are ranked 2 are given a value of \"12\" to distinguish them from the 2 items in the first pass. Thus, each pass gives you another digit until each item has a unique number. \r\n\r\nProbably best to present the items that are alike but have the smallest number of digits. \r\n\r\nWe may wish to allow the user to move an item from it\'s group to another -- or we may not. ','2005-09-30','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(104,37,'DAM','Other things that we need in this system\r\nCompany list & Networking organizations\r\nOrgID\r\nName\r\nDesc\r\nWeb\r\ntype\r\ntimestamp\r\n\r\nResumes sent & phone screens & job interviews & Negotiations\r\nEventID\r\nCompany\r\nPerson\r\nPosition\r\nDate/time\r\nType\r\ntimestamp\r\n\r\nNotes\r\nnoteid\r\nnote\r\ntype (event/org)\r\nsorceid\r\ndate\r\ntimestamp\r\n\r\nTodo list\r\n\r\nEvents\r\neventid\r\ntype (meeting, appointment)\r\nwho (org for meeting)\r\nwhere \r\ndate\r\ntime\r\nduration\r\nsource\r\nsummary\r\nother fields from sbform\r\n\r\nNOTE \r\npersons, todo, notes, companies and orgs must all have a field that contains (potentially) an eventid so that we can connect which things we learned from which events. \r\n\r\nThis is still a little chaotic but it\'s coming together a little. ','2005-10-03','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(105,38,'DAM','Now, about automation. \r\n\r\nThe first insight is that it won\'t be much more work to do this under RedWall - one has to write the user management software anyway so might as well meet the spec for RW. \r\n\r\nThe keys to the game is keeping track of the status and then processing events. I imagine events are harder (although status is pretty complicated) so let\'s start with that.\r\n\r\nEvents are essentially \"what we do at this moment\" for every moment in the game. If the game state changes, an event happens. Events are listed in a table in the DB and the current state of the game and all past states are indexed to an event (remember what I said about game status being a bit complicated).\r\n10/5/2005\r\n+ Pick a role -- current player gets to choose any role from among the existing roles, he is called the \"lead player\" for the duration of this role, then each player in turn is the \"phasing player\". For the meta-round of picking roles, the first player is the govenor and each player in turn is the \"choosing player\" \r\n+ Mayor -- Each player gets a certain number of new colonists and then each player gets to rearrange everything. Rearranging is done by having a list of everything the player owns and getting to distribute stuff over it. The player can put more stuff than he has on his holdings but the program will catch him and make him do it again.\r\n+ Builder -- You get a list of all the buildings currently available that you can afford with what each one cost you in gold. You get to click one-and-only-one. You can also pass. You aren\'t shown buildings you can\'t buy.\r\n+ Prospector -- Never any decisions about this -- the lead player (the guy with the role) just gets gold.\r\n+ Captain -- For each good that you have, that you can ship, we give you the choice of the ships you can put it on. \r\n+ Craftsman -- Every gets their stuff and then the lead player gets to pick his good from the intersection of the available goods and the goods he created\r\n+ Trader -- Each player gets a choice to sell the intersection between the goods has and the spaces left, keeping in mind the office.\r\n+ Settler -- player gets to pick from the available fields plus he may get to choose a quarry\r\n\r\nEach of these has to be modified by the possible buildings','2005-10-08','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(106,38,'DAM','I\'m thinking that there might be 3 different tables for keeping track of the status, plus a few \"definition tables\". \r\n\r\nThe definitions would be a descriptions fo the ships, a descriptions of the buildings and a description of the starting options for the various games (three, four and five players with various building sets). Now buildings and ships can be refered to by a single number and we can even now that building 5 in this game refers to a different kind of building than building 5 in another game.\r\n\r\nPlayer status has Gold, Goods, Extra Colonists, VP, Buildings and fields. I thinking that one player row will contain one column (field) for each of the 12 building slots, each of the 12 field slots and each of the 5 goods, plus a column for gold, extra colonists and vp. Each field slot has 13 possible values (empty, untended corn, sugar, indigo, tobacco or coffee and tended corn, sugar, indigo, tobacco or coffee) -- or we could do it correctly and have fields in a separate table (but I don\'t like this much). Each building slot has 47 possible values (empty plus all possible buildings, occupied or not). This system makes it a bit harder to figure out what is going on and violates some database rules but by adding a handful of \"control\" fields (player, game, event) we can simply add a new row (record) for each event and now we have a complete history of the player\'s status throughout the game! \r\n\r\nWe do the same general structure for the game status. Each good and building has a column with a count plus each ship, the colony ship, and each trading house section has a count of how many things are in it. Plus a column for each good available, a column for each type of field with a count for how many are available, a column for each type of field with a count of how many are in the box. Another column for each boat to indicate what type it is (empty or a good). A column for the number of VP left and column for the number of colonists left. Finally we need a game number and an event number as each event will generate a new record in this table. Oh and we need to track the amount of gold on each role -- and this is another event (pay the losers).\r\n\r\nFinally, there is the event table. Each row has all the possible things that can happen in one event; this is hard and I haven\'t figured it out. Certainly it needs an event number, game number and type field. Also a player field -- who is the phasing player at the minute of this event. Amount of gold on role. Prospector is easy. Captain is type of good, number of goods and boat number. Settler is a type of field, a possible second field and a free colonist. And so on. ','2005-10-08','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(107,39,'DAM','Why blog?\r\nBlogs are generally self involved. And this blog is no exception. But humans are odd in that they have a hidden connection to each other. If one thinks of one\'s \"self\" as including or involving others to any great degree then one\'s \"selfish\" blog might well contain information or insights of a generally useful and interesting nature. Indeed one would have to be very self involved, indeed, not to  be at least a little connected to those around one. And one\'s writing would reflect that connection. Even self involved people would presumably connect with other self-involved people... ','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(108,39,'DAM','Creationism\r\n\r\nHOw strange it must be to a scientist to see the creationist argument which really meets none of the criteria of science. And yet how hard it must be for a religious person in today\'s secular world to see almost no time devoted in the public school curriculum toward ethics or morals or any form of spirituality but lots of time devoted to science. \r\n\r\nThere is much to be said for both points of view and so much to discuss. But the way the discussion has been framed is in terms of \"Science vs Religion\". Both sides are very suspicious of the other -- scientists because they see creationism as disenguous and religious people because they see scientists a haughty and dismissive. \r\n\r\nBut we must find a way to frame the discussion in a better more useful way. As it\'s currently framed, either Science wins and we are doomed to an existence of physical mastery but with no higher sense than that we do things because we can, or Religion wins and we give up on all our technology and the worlds population is forced to drop from the current 9 Billion to something more sustainable with biblical-era farming techniques. \r\n\r\nOf course, the answer is obvious: no one wants to see either of the most extreme proponents of either side of this argument \"win\" the world. Even the most anti-religious people I\'ve met feel that there one must strive to be a \"good person\" and even the most rabid technophobe I\'ve ever talked to feels that some technology is necessary. \r\n\r\nThe problem, then, is that, for some odd reason, we strive to give up on our common ground and focus on our differences. ','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(109,39,'DAM','So, why write? I\'m wasting time, space on the hard drive and bandwidth. Exactly what do I think will be the benefit of all this effort? What will I gain? What will you gain? ^@^@^@    text_more^@^@^H^D<h5>Am I just trying to appear smart?</h5><P>\r\nThe most obvious reason to blog is to show off. \"See how clever I am? I had these clever thoughts today!\"  There was a point where I  suspected this motivation for myself and I very carefully did nothing. Demonstrating cleverness would not be a good reason to do anything.\r\n<P>First off, it would almost certainly demonstrate the opposite. People who are trying to appear clever are inherently afraid that they aren\'t clever and who knows better than they?\r\n<P>More importantly, it\'s a totally self-indulgent motivation.  And beside, the ideas don\'t come from me so it\'s certainly not *my* cleverness I would be demonstrating. <P> I\'m certain that I am not trying to demonstrate cleverness.\r\n<P> So, what <b>am</b> I doing?\r\n<h5>I get these ideas...</h5>\r\n<P>\r\nIdeas are constantly popping into my head. Essentially random ideas, at least in terms of what appears to be going on. If I just let them pile up my brain gets clogged and I get distracted and, well, disfunctional. I\'ve found that writing them down helps clear my head. I think thoughts and write them down. <P> But this is hardly worthwhile. Of what use is this? Ideas are a gift and to not use them is disrepectful of the giver.\r\n<h5>Are they worth a damn?</h5><P>\r\nIt\'s certainly true that the ideas were valuable when they were given to me.  But it\'s possible to distort such gifts. In any event, they are of no direct use to <b>me</b> which begs the question, \"To whom are they useful?\" (not to mention \"And for what?\"). How can I find out?\r\n<h5>Let\'s lay them out and see what people say.</h5><P>\r\nHow about I put them where other people can see them and comment on them? These perfect strangers will let me know very quickly if these ideas have any merit. Did I distort them or am I passing them on as I received them? And I\'ll find out what they are for.\r\n<P>A blog is perfect for this purpose. Besides, I know very little about  this medium and I\'m all about trying things to see what happens.\r\n@\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(110,39,'DAM','I remember an article in the ACM Communications (the journal of one of the leading professional software engineering organizations) in the mid-80s that pointed out the problems with electronic voting machines. As I recall it mainly dealt with the fact that voting machines were potentially corruptible.\r\n\r\nMuch has changed in these two decades but I think there is pretty good evidence that voting machines are still corruptible. Interestingly enough, we may have the technology (really, the techniques) to overcome this problem but we are not yet using it. More about this in a minute. First, let\'s go over the major problems with voting machines and then, perhaps, how to address those problems.\r\n\r\nEvery voting system is susceptible to fraud. Legal voters can be removed from the voting rolls, illigitimate voters can be added, ballot boxes can be stuffed, lost or added and corrupt officials can miscount the votes. In 200 years we have developed many strategies for dealing with these sorts of problems most of which have to do with the transparency of the system. People know how the system works and observers are available to verify that the system is being adhered to and that gives us some degree of confidence that our votes are being counted.\r\n\r\nThe extraordinary difference with electronic voting machines is that much of the voting process is completely hidden, not just from the individiual voter but from anyone. Believe it or not, it is difficult even for the engineers who wrote the code to be certain that the code they wrote is actually the code in the box at the moment they vote.\r\n\r\nThere are, broadly speaking, three categories of problems which are unique to electronic systems. <ul>\r\n<li>Corruptibility -- the possibility that someone involved in the creation of the system can corrupt the it\r\n<li>Hackibility -- the possibility that someone uninvolved with the system can corrupt it\r\n<li>Auditability -- the capability of the public to verify the results of the election after the fact\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nLets look at these one by one...\r\n\r\n<b> Corruptibility</b>\r\n\r\nIn normal software engineering environments the engineers rule the roost. Almost all of the testing and verification that happens starts from the premise that the engineers are doing their best to meet the specifications. Even in environments where this premise is correct subtle but far-reaching bugs are introduced that cause all manner of problems.\r\n\r\nIf one or more engineers wish to deliberately introduce bias into the system they would certainly be able to do so. Avoiding detection might be a challenge but this wouldn\'t be very hard unless there were processes and procedures in place specifically designed to preclude this.\r\n\r\nBased on what Diebold has said coupled with what people have been able to glean from memos and pieces of source code that have become available, Diebold does not seem to have any processes in place to prevent corruption. In fact there seems to be some cicumstantial evidence that their software development process does not meet \"best practices\" standards, much less the standards required for electronic voting.\r\n\r\n<b> Hackibility  </b>\r\n\r\nDuring WWII the \"best practice\" for cryptography was to use secret cyphers to encrypt your text and count on the security of the cypher to keep your messages secure. As it turned out, the Allies broke both the German and Japanese \"secret\" codes and could therefor predict the plans of their adversaries at various key points in the war.\r\n\r\nSince then experts in cryptography have avoided depending on secret information to protect messages from spies -- or, more recently, to protect systems from hackers -- because it just doesn\'t work. The industry best practice is to only use standard techniques that are well know -- the opposite of secret -- and have been proven to be effective against all manner of real-life tests.\r\n\r\nThe position of Diebold is that they dare not expose their code to review for security reasons. Anyone who understands the state of the art in security knows that this either a disingenuous or an incompetent position to hold. Either way, I have even less confidence in Diebold security than in Diebold software engineering processes.\r\n\r\nThe people who analyzed the Diebold code identified two major and obvious flaws in the voting machine\'s code. The first was that the machines use \"smart cards\" that are not protected by cryptography and could fairly easily be duplicated, thus allowing a hacker to vote multiple times and, possibly, end voting early on some machines. The second was that the machines transmitted the stored votes over either insecure phone lines or through insecure networks without any authentication or cryptography. This may make it vulnerable to various attacks.\r\n\r\n<b>Auditability </b>\r\n\r\nAt the end of the day, when all the votes are recorded and counted on our electronic machine, how do we know for sure that the numbers reported by the system have any relation at all to the actual votes cast? And if we suspect that they do not have a close relation, how would we find out?\r\n\r\nThe current systems do not print paper ballots so there is no way to recount the vote. In fact, the voting officials apparently do not <b>want</b> the machines to print ballots, probably because they don\'t want to have to count them (no one would want to be in the place of the Florida voting officials).\r\n\r\n<b> What Can Be Done?</b>\r\nThere is a software development methodology called \"open source\" which would be completely incorruptible. It essentially involves allowing anyone in the world, at any time, to look at the source code that is being developed and raise concerns about it. No one could slip even the most subtle \"bug\" into the code with thousands of programmers looking over their shoulder.\r\n\r\nIn addition, an independent auditor should be employed to verify that the software that is actually installed on the machines is identical that the software that was developed by the open source process.\r\n\r\nAuditibility is even easier to attain. If every machine printed out a ballot that had a list of names with clear marks next to the selected candidates, the voter would know instantly if the machine had recorded his vote correctly. Such a paper ballot could be constructed in such a way that it could be read accurately by a machine so that, in the case of an ellection irregularity, votes could be recounted. The combination of the voter being able to see what he voted for and the system saving a copy to count later would make the system extremely hard to break.\r\n\r\nPreventing hackability is still a major challenge but it should be possible to put private keys on all the smart cards, encrypt the data being sent back to the central counting locations and use other well understood security techniques to solve this problem.\r\n\r\n<b>Summary</b>\r\nIn short, if we really feel we need electronic voting machines, we should put in the effort required to make the safe and reliable.\r\n\r\n','2005-10-13','2008-10-23 16:32:37'),(389,18,'Old','Adenosine triphosphate atp\r\nIt is one of three energy-producing systems in the human body. The other two are anaerobic -- not using oxygen. They are ATP-CP and glycolysis. \r\n\r\nWhen you exercise beyond the limits of your ATP-CP and glucose systems, your body needs to start producing energy \"on the fly\" using oxygen. \r\n\r\nTo fuel any exercise beyond a few minutes, you are using oxygen to create ATP (adenosine triphosphate, the molecule that produces the energy in all living things, from bacteria on up). This process is actually going on all the time, which is why you need to breathe all the time. Your aerobic metabolism gives your body the basic energy it needs to function. \r\n\r\nThere is a difference between aerobic metabolism and aerobic exercise. Aerobic exercise is intended to expand your aerobic capacity. That is, we do aerobic exercise for the cardiovascular benefits that enable our lungs, heart, and blood vessels to do a better job converting oxygen into ATP. \r\n\r\nIf you\'re exercising so intensely that you need to stop after a few minutes to catch your breath, you\'re not doing aerobic exercise. That\'s using your anaerobic systems. \r\n\r\nIf you exercise with little or no intensity, like walking, you\'re using your aerobic system to produce energy, but you\'re not doing aerobic exercise. You\'re not expanding your aerobic capacity. \r\n\r\nTo get aerobic benefits, the exercise needs to be at a pace that you can maintain for at least 10 or 20 minutes and that feels \"comfortably hard.\" (Or you could do intervals, alternating anaerobic and aerobic exercise levels.) \r\n','2008-10-23','2008-10-24 06:05:23'),(111,39,'DAM','^@^@^@^Kallow_pings^@^@^@^A0^@^@^@^Bid^@^@^@^B39^@^@^@^Gblog_id^@^@^@^A7^@^@^@^Etitle^@^@^@^OVoting Machines^@^@^@^Lto_ping_urls^@^@^@^@heir software development process does not meet \"best practices\" standards, much less the standards required for electronic voting.\r\n\r\n<b> Hackibility  </b>\r\n\r\nDuring WWII the \"best practice\" for cryptography was to use secret cyphers to encrypt your text and count on the security of the cypher to keep your messages secure. As it turned out, the Allies broke both the German and Japanese \"secret\" codes and could therefor predict the plans of their adversaries at various key points in the war.\r\n\r\nSince then experts in cryptography have avoided depending on secret information to protect messages from spies -- or, more recently, to protect systems from hackers -- because it just doesn\'t work. The industry best practice is to only use standard techniques that are well know -- the opposite of secret -- and have been proven to be effective against all manner of real-life tests.\r\n\r\n^@^@^@^@^A^@^@^@^M^@^@^@^N^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^A^@^[^@^@^G Carlos^@^@^@^Lto_ping_urls^@^@^@^@xcerpt^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^Fstatus^@^@^@^A2^@^@^@^Nallow_comments^@^@^@^A1^@^@^@^Nconvert_breaks^@^@^@^K__default__^@^@^@^Kmodified_on^@^@^@^N20031105093839^@^@^@\r\ncreated_on^@^@^@^N20031105093839^@^@^@^Dtext^@^@^NÃTuesday, October 14\r\n\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(112,39,'DAM','^@^@^@^Kallow_pings^@^@^@^A0^@^@^@^Bid^@^@^@^B61^@^@^@^Gblog_id^@^@^@^A7^@^@^@^Etitle^@^@^@^\\Let Go of Your Quarter, Luke^@^@^@^Lto_ping_urls^@^@^@^@^N20031119234015^@^@^@\r\ncreated_on^@^@^@^N20031111054212^@^@^@^Dtext^@^@^B}One of the StarWars video games was, in part, a simulation of flying down the trenches in the Deathstar, flying over and under horizontal bars that blocked your way and avoiding the fire from gun turrets. The easiest way to avoid the gun turrets was to shoot them before they fired (or, at least, before they hit you).\r\n\r\nAt the start of this sequence the voice of Obi Wan would say to you \"Use the Force Luke!\" Those who had played the game many times knew that what he meant was that if you don\'t shoot out the gun turrets and avoid them by quick maneuvers but you still destroy the Deathstar, you would get an extra million points.\r\n...^@^@^@   text_more^@^@^LÂ°That\'s right A MILLION POINTS! Of course, if you get killed doing it this way then you lose your quarter and have to try again. I always admired this little bit of video gamesmanship because it essentially bets the player a million points against a quarter. I\'ll gladly give you a million points for a quarter any day and it\'s even better because most players couldn\'t do it (I don\'t think I ever managed it even though I could play for free)! I used to call this little trick \"Let Go of Your Quarter, Luke\".\r\n\r\nVideo games in general had to get a quarter out of you every 90 seconds to be profitable but it wasn\'t enough to simply take the quarter because it was important that the player want to put ANOTHER quarter into the machine. So the process had to be fun and, most importantly, the player had to feel that he was at fault whenever he lost. If it seemed like the game \"cheated\" or made him lose unfairly he wouldn\'t want to put in another quarter. Rather, the idea was to make the player feel that HE had done something wrong so he would try again!\r\n\r\nI was surprised to notice something very similar when I left the games industry to join Palm in the late nineties. A precursor to the Palm was the Newton. Many of the people who worked on the Newton also worked at Palm and so the Palm devices were a true decedent of the The Newton.\r\n\r\nThe Newton had true handwriting recognition but it wasn\'t very good. It could only recognize your handwriting most of the time -- say 90% of the time (I\'m not sure the exact amount). That sounds pretty good until you realize that it means that it makes an error about every other word (assuming it\'s getting 90% of the letters right). People criticized The Newton heavily for it\'s failings as a handwriting recognizer even as most of us geeks were amazed it could do it at all!\r\n\r\nPalm took a very different approach. They created Graffiti -- a special alphabet that has only a vague relationship to the real alphabet. So the claim for Palm was that if you write on a Palm with correct Graffiti it will recognize the characters -- a much weaker claim than that made by The Newton. Furthermore, I\'m not absolutely certain that the Palm could recognize Graffiti 100% of the time. It seems like I often do characters correctly but it gets them wrong.\r\n\r\nBut Graffiti was a huge success even as character recognition was pretty much a bust. And the reason is this: when you use Graffiti you have an expectation that it will only recognize the characters if you do them correctly. So when it fails, you assume you made a mistake and go back and do it again.  If you get it right you feel good about it. At no point do you blame the machine, even though it may well be at fault. Let Go of Your Stylus, Luke...\r\nIn this way, we can use human nature to make humans more forgiving of machine failings. The same thing happens when non-geeks approach a computer. Computers today are really hard to use (and yes, I mean even Macintoshes -- I don\'t have a biased bone in my body in this area). And yet beginning users -- who are most victimized by the poor user interfaces and confusing behavior of computers today -- are quick to blame themselves and work harder to learn the machines. Let Go of Your ^@^@^@^@^A^@^@^@^^^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^]^@^@^@^A^@Ã¦^O^@^GSERG^@^@^@   author_id^@^@^@^A1^@^@^@^Gexcerpt^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^Fstatus^@^@^@^A2^@^@^@^Nallow_comments^@^@^@^A0^@^@^@^Nconvert_breaks^@^@^@^K__default__^@^@^@^Kmodified_on^@^@^@^N20041108160145^@^@^@\r\ncreated_on^@^@^@^N20031111054212^@^@^@^Dtext^@^@^B}One of the StarWars video games was, in part, a simulation of flying down the trenches in the Deathstar, flying over and under horizontal bars that blocked your way and avoiding the fire from gun turrets. The easiest way to avoid the gun turrets was to shoot them before they fired (or, at least, before they hit you).\r\n\r\nAt the start of this sequence the voice of Obi Wan would say to you \"Use the Force Luke!\" Those who had played the game many times knew that what he meant was that if you don\'t shoot out the gun turrets and avoid them by quick maneuvers but you still destroy the Deathstar, you would get an extra million points.\r\n...^@^@^@   text_more^@^@^LÂ°That\'s right A MILLION POINTS! Of course, if you get killed doing it this way then you lose your quarter and have to try again. I always admired this little bit of video gamesmanship because it essentially bets the player a million points against a quarter. I\'ll gladly give you a million points for a quarter any day and it\'s even better because most players couldn\'t do it (I don\'t think I ever managed it even though I could play for free)! I used to call this little trick \"Let Go of Your Quarter, Luke\".\r\n\r\nVideo games in general had to get a quarter out of you every 90 seconds to be profitable but it wasn\'t enough to simply take the quarter because it was important that the player want to put ANOTHER quarter into the machine. So the process had to be fun and, most importantly, the player had to feel that he was at fault whenever he lost. If it seemed like the game \"cheated\" or made him lose unfairly he wouldn\'t want to put in another quarter. Rather, the idea was to make the player feel that HE had done something wrong so he would try again!\r\n\r\nI was surprised to notice something very similar when I left the games industry to join Palm in the late nineties. A precursor to the Palm was the Newton. Many of the people who worked on the Newton also worked at Palm and so the Palm devices were a true decedent of the The Newton.\r\n\r\nThe Newton had true handwriting recognition but it wasn\'t very good. It could only recognize your handwriting most of the time -- say 90% of the time (I\'m not sure the exact amount). That sounds pretty good until you realize that it means that it makes an error about every other word (assuming it\'s getting 90% of the letters right). People criticized The Newton heavily for it\'s failings as a handwriting recognizer even as most of us geeks were amazed it could do it at all!\r\n\r\nPalm took a very different approach. They created Graffiti -- a special alphabet that has only a vague relationship to the real alphabet. So the claim for Palm was that if you write on a Palm with correct Graffiti it will recognize the characters -- a much weaker claim than that made by The Newton. Furthermore, I\'m not absolutely certain that the Palm could recognize Graffiti 100% of the time. It seems like I often do characters correctly but it gets them wrong.\r\nIn this way, we can use human nature to make humans more forgiving of machine failings. The same thing happens when non-geeks approach a computer. Computers today are really hard to use (and yes, I mean even Macintoshes -- I don\'t have a biased bone in my body in this area). And yet beginning users -- who are most victimized by the poor user interfaces and confusing behavior of computers today -- are quick to blame themselves and work harder to learn the machines. Let Go of Your ^@^@^@^@^A^@^@^@^_^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^A^@Ã°^C^@^GSERG^@^@^@   author_id^@^@^@^A1^@^@^@^Gexcerpt^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^Fstatus^@^@^@^A1^@^@^@^Nallow_comments^@^@^@^A2^@^@^@^Nconvert_breaks^@^@^@^K__default__^@^@^@^Kmodified_on^@^@^@^N20050125073757^@^@^@\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(113,39,'DAM','created_on^@^@^@^N20031114093443^@^@^@^Dtext^@^@^BÃIt happened again yesterday: someone asked me \"do you believe in evolution?\" The questioner knows that I\'m religious and so the question he\'s really asking is \"how do you reconcile your belief in God with your belief in science?\" This question is worth spending some time on.\r\nWhat do we mean by the phrase, \"I believe in such and such\"? DOesn\'t it bring to mind the Cowardly Lion from the Wizard of Oz saying \"I DO believe in ghosts! I DO believe in ghosts\" or Peter Pan telling us \"clap your hands if you believe in TingerBell\"? Believing in something appears to have to do with not knowing the truth of the matter. You wouldn\'t say \"I believe in my shoes\" because you can see them.\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(114,39,'DAM','If you make fun of me for being Irish or Italian or a breeder it can be funny. But if you make fun of me for being Jewish or gay it won\'t be funny, not because Jewish people and gays aren\'t funny but because I\'m not one of them. It would be confusing, not funny.\r\nIf irony is involved then a mistruth emphasises the truth which means, once again, it\'s about truth.\r\nSometimes an over the top statement, not strictly true, underlines a deeper truth.\r\nIn short, we\'re not talking about literal truth here but pointing up a real truth using irony, exagerations, half truths and other devices.\r\nNot only must the center of humor be a truth but it won\'t be funny if the audience isn\'t in some way hiding from it. It has to be an uncomfortable truth.\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(115,40,'DAM','Dungeon Game 990425\r\n\r\nopen source\r\nsemi real time\r\nweb accessible\r\nemail accessible\r\np7 accessible\r\n\r\nBasic Idea\r\nA dungeon game in which the players give general orders to their characters. A turn is 20 minutes of real time and about 10-30 minutes of game time. The characters act on their own during the turn. If the player doesn\'t submit a turn the characters will continue to operate without new orders. This implies that characters need to be able to handle things without direct intervention from the player.\r\n\r\nThe danger this raises is that the player will feel out of control. This is the heart of the whole game design. All voluntary actions that the characters take must be deterministic, based on settings (lots of settings) that the player can change at will.  In general, the setttings you can make will be affected by the character attributes but the actions will not be directly affected by the attribtes. For example, you can set how quickly a character will run from danger.  But you can\'t set every character to fight to the death.  Really stupid characters, perhaps. Really strong characters. And, in some situations, really smart characters. (Or maybe we just have a \"brave\" attribute.)\r\n\r\nInasmuch as I would like this to be a OSS project I need to figure what parts need to be predefined. Also, I think this needs to be OOP project. C++ was my first thought but Java might be better.\r\n\r\n1) character attributes\r\n2) basic combat\r\n3) magic\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(116,39,'DAM','\r\nThere is a line, an interface if you will, between Truth and Reason. If you know Truth, if you experience it as a real thing, changing but immutible then you have no use for Reason. But then this line would not exist for you. If you know Reason, it\'s ebbs and flows, if you navigate it\'s moving and ever changing waters to reach your conclusions and decisions then you have no need of Truth. Again, this line would not exist for you. But if you have once experienced Truth and know of it\'s existence but in fear have run once again to the familiar and, you hope, controllable Reason you stand on the Edge of Truth.\r\n\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(117,39,'DAM','created_on^@^@^@^N20031114094837^@^@^@^Dtext^@^@^A\'It\'s my birthday! What are you going to get me? Well, that poses something of a problem since you don\'t know anything about me and so don\'t know what I might like. Perhaps a $20 bill would do the trick (ok, ok, you don\'t like me THAT much -- perhaps a $5 bill? would you believe, a $3 bill?)...\r\n^@^@^@  text_more^@^@^P/But money (or, as I like to call it, \"the universal gift certificate\") is so tacky. And besides, if you give me money, you are as much as admitting that you haven\'t given any thought to what I might like. I know: a gift card or certificate from some outfit like, for example, Barnes and Noble! You know (or strongly suspect) that I can read and it\'s less tacky than money. Whew, you survived another gift-giving opportunity with your social reputation intact!\r\n\r\nBut what do I really get for my gift card? I mean, what is the actual financial transaction that is going on here? You pay $20 for the gift certificate from some name-brand store and I get the equivelent of a $20 bill except nicer, right? Well, no.\r\n\r\nIn fact, the original $20 is more valuable than the gift certificate because I can spend it anywhere. It may be that I was going to spend the $20 on B&N anyway in which case it doesn\'t make much difference but what if I like Borders? They won\'t honor the B&N card and so I\'m now limited in my choices. This limitation has to reduce the value of the gift card to some degree. The minute you buy a gift card, it\'s already lost some value, at least as a financial transaction because $20 that could be used anywhere has now been converted to $20 that can only be used in one place. But B&N gave you a discount when you bought it, right? NO!? How odd. You\'d think they\'d be willing to pay you something to force your friends to use their birthday money at B&N rather than Borders...\r\n\r\nFurthermore, from a strictly financial point of view, B&N gets the use of your money from the time you buy the card until the time I actually use the card. While I admit this is probably not very much (if calculated extravagantly*, it might be 1/2% - 10 cents -- if I waited a month) it adds up to a great from B&N\'s point of view because they aren\'t just dealing with your $20 -- they might sell millions of dollars of these cards and so the use of that money may add up. The idea that people walk in and give them $20, taking away nothing of any real value except the right to buy $20 worth of stuff at a later time is really pretty cool from B&N\'s point of view -- it\'s like they were a bank that doesn\'t pay any interest to their depositors!\r\n\r\nBut it gets even worse. If you read the fine print on the back of the gift card you will discover that, while the card is worth $20 on the day you bought it, a year from now it will be worth less than $20. That\'s right, many gift cards start devaluing their cards after some period of time. In the case of B&N they deduct $1.50 from the card every month after it hasn\'t been used for a year. CompUSA deducts $2. I believe that most companies that sell gift cards have some form of devaluation over time. I believe this is because the cards represent a liability and they don\'t want to carry that liability on the books forever.\r\n\r\nWhen you buy a gift card you are not getting as much as you pay for. The gift limits where the recipient can spend the money, it gives the company the use of the money for free and the cards effectively expire after some period of time. In short, the cards aren\'t really worth their face value. For my part, I\'ll take the cash, any day.\r\n\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(118,39,'DAM','\r\n*A business like B&N may, at any given moment, have outstanding loans. These loans might be paid back at fairly high interest rates (higher than they can get by putting the money in the bank, for example). Every dollar they take in might be construed to reduce these loans by that amount. So one could CLAIM that every day they keep your $20 they are saved from havin^@^@^@^@^A^@^@^@$^@^@^@#^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^A^@Â¤^B^@^Gg to borrow that $20 for that day and are, therefor, making the interest rate on the loan they didn\'t have to take out. I\'ve assumed that such a loan might cost 6% interest per year so that would be 1/2% per month. It could be construed to be even more than that since, presumably, they are planning to use that loan to make even more money. In fact, this rational is absurd when applied to a single $20 transaction. But it might not be entirely unreasonable if applied to ALL the $20 gift cards sold this year... In any event, it\'s certainly worth SOMETHING to them.\r\n\r\n\r\n^@^@^@^Kallow_pings^@^@^@^A0^@^@^@^Bid^@^@^@^B67^@^@^@^Gblog_id^@^@^@^A7^@^@^@^Etitle^@^@^@^YWhy Gift Cards Are Stupid^@^@^@^Lto_ping_urls^@^@^@^@ght to what I might like. I know: a gift card or certificate from some outfit like, for example, Barnes and Noble! You know (or strongly suspect) that I can read and it\'s less tacky than money. Whew, you survived another gift-giving opportunity with your social reputation intact!\r\n\r\nBut what do I really get for my gift card? I mean, what is the actual financial transaction that is going on here? You pay $20 for the gift certificate from some name-brand store and I get the equivelent of a $20 bill except nicer, right? Well, no.\r\n\r\nIn fact, the original $20 is more valuable than the gift certificate because I can spend it anywhere. It may be that I was going to spend the $20 on B&N anyway in which case it doesn\'t make much difference but what if I like Borders? They won\'t honor the B&N card and so I\'m now limited in my choices. This limitation has to reduce the value of the gift card to some degree. The minute you buy a gift card, it\'s already lost some value, at least as a financial transaction because $20 that could be used anywhere has now been converted to $20 that can only be used in one place. But B&N gave you a discount when you bought it, right? NO!? How odd. You\'d think they\'d be willing to pay you something to force your friends to use their birthday money at B&N rather than Borders...\r\n\r\nFurthermore, from a strictly financial point of view, B&N gets the use of your money from the time you buy the card until the time I actually use the card. While I admit this is probably not very much (if calculated extravagantly*, it might be 1/2% - 10 cents -- if I waited a month) it adds up to a great from B&N\'s point of view because they aren\'t just dealing with your $20 -- they might sell millions of dollars of these cards and so the use of that money may add up. The idea that people walk in and give them $20, taking away nothing of any real value except the right to buy $20 worth of stuff at a later time is really pretty cool from B&N\'s point of view -- it\'s like they were a bank that doesn\'t pay any interest to their depositors!\r\n\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(119,39,'DAM','ÃŽThey should be talking about protecting man from himself.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental issues aren\'t merely important on moral or ethical grounds\r\nClear cutting, air polution, green-house gases, wasting energy, destroying bio-diversity,  fisheries destruction  and so on & so forth is a bad idea primarily because of damage to our own selfish, self-involved selves.\r\n\r\n1 million years from now (a flash in the pan from the Earth\'s perspective) little will show of our glorious civilization. Buried freeway overpasses and a little rubble from skyscrapers to be sure but nothing significant. Mother Earth is perfectly capable of shrugging off the effects of her miscreant children. A million years after we go extinct the air will be clean, new animals will evolve to fill all the niches and the land will heal. And Mother will not mourn for her children.\r\n\r\nBut I\'m a practical man. I\'m less concerned about 1 million years from now and much more concerned about how my children will fare.\r\n\r\n\r\n^@^@^@^Kallow_pings^@^@^@^A0^@^@^@^Bid^@^@^@^B74^@^@^@^Gblog_id^@^@^@^A7^@^@^@^Etitle^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^Lto_ping_urls^@^@^@^@at we all, by unspoken agreement, feel it should stay in. Not to worry; we have the power to keep it in it\'s channel and we are very good at it. Well, actually the universe we keep in it\'s channel isn\'t The Universe but it\'s every bit as good as the real thing and that\'s good enough for us.\r\n\r\n<P>Remember that miracles happen all the time. There are a few rules about them, however. You have to get out of the way or you won\'t see them. And, well, I think there\'s only one rule. As a practical matter, miracles are absolutely worthless as a practical matter. If you want a particular outcome the attainment of that outcome probably doesn\'t have much to do with the miraculous. But if you just stand aside, you might be very surprised.\r\n\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(120,39,'DAM','Gher chunk of meat. Isn\'t that interesting?\r\n\r\nThere\'s something else I\'ve noticed. Mostly when I look at other people I can easily believe that they are just animated meat. I could almost believe they were machines. But occasionally, I look in the eyes of a person and there is a spark the travels between us. I feel a definite connection, a kinship. I can\'t figure out how that happens if there isn\'t some third part connecting us...\r\n^@^@^@^Kallow_pings^@^@^@^A0^@^@^@^Bid^@^@^@^B70^@^@^@^Gblog_id^@^@^@^A7^@^@^@^Etitle^@^@^@^PIs There A God? ^@^@^@^Lto_ping_urls^@^@^@^@ knowing it (i.e. the question might then become, why am I so special that I accept that knowledge...).\r\n...^@^@^@   text_more^@^@^O You might ask, \"How do you know there is a God?\" I don\'t understand the question. To me it\'s like asking, \"How do you know that you exist?\" Oh, right, I forgot, many people don\'t really believe they exist; they think they are simply machines that are simulating existence.\r\n\r\nI think that it\'s a waste of time to try to prove the existence of God. He doesn\'t exist in the realm of proof, anyway.\r\n\r\n\"I don\'t believe in God.\" \"That\'s OK, He doesn\'t believe in you either\" <laughter>\r\n\r\nExcept that it should be: \"I don\'t believe in God.\" \"That\'s OK, He believes in you, anyway.\"\r\n\r\nI guess the only thing I would like to point out is that God must exist because all the rest of this stuff exists. (This is an extremely poor argument because, actually, the rest of this stuff doesn\'t actually exist. But that\'s another story.)\r\n\r\nYou may say, \"The rest of this stuff could exist through any number of processes. It doesn\'t prove anything.\" Oh, yeah? Name a process through which the universe would exist? If you\'re unwilling to call it \"God\" it\'s not my fault. (This argument, sullen and uncommunicative as it is, essentially suggests that the universe must exist in some larger context and that that context might as well be called \"God\" as anything else. Perhaps it\'s wrong; perhaps the physical universe is all there is. I know this to be incomplete; I can\'t prove it.)\r\n\r\nWhat about me? What sort of creature am I? I am a creature who exists in three parts. Two of these parts are the meat and the mind; that is, fingers that are typing these words and the entity that is coming up with them. The third part is, in part, the entity that connects the two. This third entity is God and connects me to all the rest of you meat-minds.\r\n\r\nYou may feel that there is no third entity; that the mind is simply a side effect of the meat. I know this to be incomplete; I can\'t prove it.\r\n\r\nAre you annoyed with me? I have made several statements but have made no compelling arguments to back them up. I will probably get hit with a lot of mail by people much smarter than me which will explain, either very slowing and patiently or with a great deal of, shall we say, vigor that I\'m totally full of shit. I know, however, that no one else has any better explanation.\r\n\r\nHold up your index finger. Wiggle it. Now, explain how that happens. Can you prove it?\r\n\r\nI assert that it happens because that third part of you wills it to happen. I can\'t prove it but I doubt anyone can prove me wrong. And, although this isn\'t a scientific explanation, there is no scientific explanation (by this I mean \"explanation that is testable in some way\") and all the other, non-scientific explanations are just as bad, as far as I can tell. It comes down to a matter of taste at this level -- I like Coke but you prefer Pepsi.\r\n\r\nOf course, it isn\'t a matter of taste, at all. I know there is a God and the rest of it follows from that.\r\n\r\nNow imagine, just for the sake of argument, just as a thought-experiment, that what I say is true. There is a God and I\'m composed of three parts. That means that you and I are so closely related that the difference is academic. Likewise the rest of the physical universe.\r\n\r\nWhy does *my* little finger wiggle when I want it to instead of yours? Habit; for some reason my conciousness is associated with this chunk of meat instead of that chunk so I tend to animate this one. This implies that I *could* animate some ot^','2005-10-13','