 this one. This implies that I *could* animate some ot^@^@^@^@^A^@^@^@)^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^A^@M^F^@^GSERG^@^@^@    author_id^@^@^@^A1^@^@^@^Gexcerpt^@^@^@^@^@^@^@^Fstatus^@^@^@^A2^@^@^@^Nallow_comments^@^@^@^A2^@^@^@^Nconvert_breaks^@^@^@^K__default__^@^@^@^Kmodified_o','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(122,39,'DAM','I just drove from Walnut Creek to the South Bay and I\'m upset.  Why am I upset? Looking back at my evening I became upset when my friend made clear to me that the majority of the country is against gay marriage. I knew that he was right and this is a very painful thought to me.\r\n...\r\n^@^@^@  text_more^@^@^D^EIt\'s not that I feel pain that loving couples who only differ from legally married couples in the gender of their spouses don\'t get the same legal benefits. This is certainly unfair and, frankly, outrageous but not particularly painful at a deeply emotional level. It makes me angry but it\'s not the pain I feel right now.\r\n\r\nAnd I\'m not crying over the fact that gay couples can\'t have their marriages recognized in the eyes of the state because the state is irrelevant to marriage. Marriage exists, if it exists at all, in the relationship and commitment of two people to each other and God. Gay couples can be truly married whether politicians (or judges) say so or not.\r\n\r\nI find it painful that everyone recognizes the importance of marriage to being human and yet some of us wish to withhold this from their fellow beings. That\'s a depth of hatred -- mindless violent hatred -- that I simply can\'t fathom. And I don\'t want to fathom it and that\'s what is causing me pain at the moment: the resistance to feeling the hatred.\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(123,39,'DAM','Every morning when you take your shower 10,000 people are there with you.\r\n\r\nBut don\'t worry. Your mother won\'t chastise you for it because they are only there in spirit.\r\n...^@^@^@   text_more^@^@^HÃ´They are mostly working men and women and technitions with high school educations or technical degrees. Hardly a PHD or even a masters among them. Few, if any, went to an Ivy League school or belonged to a prestigious fraternity.\r\n\r\nAnd yet, you can\'t take a shower without them.\r\n\r\nThey do a lot of things for you and yet you\'ve never seen them. Some of them maintain the gas lines. Some keep the water flowing. Some look after the power lines. Some report the problems, others fix them. Some maintain the roads and phones so that the problems can be reported and the fixers can get there. They have diverse jobs and they work all over your city, your county and even your state. Some even work in nearby states. All of them are necessary to your morning shower.\r\n\r\nAdmittedly, if some didn\'t show up for work (and, of course, some don\'t) others would cover for them. But if enough didn\'t show up, there would be no one to fix things when things went wrong. Water and power and gas and roads and phone lines aren\'t magic. They take constant supervision and effort to maintain. And that takes dedication, intelligence and skill.\r\n\r\nThe 10,000 people in your shower provide those things to you every day.\r\n\r\nMost likely many of them were educated in your county schools. Schools for which you pay taxes. And here\'s the point: do you pay enough taxes? Because few people think our schools are doing a good enough job. If the schools aren\'t doing a good enough job, someday, many years from now, you\'ll step in to the shower, turn on the water and get nothing. You\'ll try to call someone but the phones won\'t work. And, anyway, there will be no way to find the problem, no way to get to it, no way to fix it. We will have neglected to train the 10,000 vital people we need.\r\n\r\nThis is what your shool dollars are for: to create a body of people with dedication, intelligence and skill to keep your shower running. Not to mention the tens of thousands of people who provide the  hundreds of other vital services that you depend on every day The sewers. The mail. Trash pickup. Storm drains. Street cleaning. Traffic lights. The list goes on and on of services that are so reliable you don\'t even think of them.\r\n\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(124,39,'DAM','We settle for a lot less than we deserve and every time we settle for less we lessen our selves.\r\n\r\nHere\'s how they sell pickup trucks:\r\n\r\nEach of us feels some kind of connection to the universe in our hearts. Most of us can\'t figure out how to realize our relationship to the whole universe. So we\'d settle for a relationship with one other person.\r\n\r\nRelationships are really hard, however, so we\'d settle for a fling. A one night stand. Maybe just messing around a little. Something physical, at least.\r\n\r\nFor some reason persons of the opposite sex don\'t seem to be very interested. But that guy on television sure seems popular with the ladies and he has a truck  so we\'d settle for a pickup truck.\r\n','2005-10-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(125,41,'DAM','The idea behind this application is that we can make a list of companies that we THINK might be software firms and then many people can help research them. It\'s a colaborative search tool. ','2005-10-17','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(126,41,'DAM','Company Name\r\nCompany URL\r\nCompany type (Contracting, Search, Software, Hardware, Other)\r\nOtherTypeName //use this if company type is other, ignore otherwise\r\ncompany description\r\ncompany address\r\ncompany main phone number\r\nnotes\r\n','2005-10-17','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(127,38,'Ron Flynt','Notes on PBM Puerto Rico\r\n\r\nNotify governor of his turn.\r\nMove players chosen role to role taken and input player name in By box.\r\nAdd any bonus gold to players hand,  (in cases of builder and trader use this amount in calculations of gold spent or received.)\r\nExecute role taken.\r\nBuilder:  calculate cost of chosen building (include bonus from bonus area, bonus for being the builder, bonus for allowable quarries plus difference from players hand) and subtract amount required from player from his hand.  Add building to building area of player space, reduce number of chosen building in building available table and update number of buildings in player space. Add VP value of building to buildings VP in the player space and update total.  Contact other players in player order and execute as above.  Notify players when the twelfth building space is filled in any players player space (Game End).  (Note: If a player has an operating university, then the purchased building comes with a colonist making it a manned building.  Add one to number of colonists in the player space and subtract one from the available colonists.)\r\nCaptain:  Add 1 VP to players shipping VP and subtract 1 form VP available if the player is shipping goods.  Put # of goods on chosen ship, add # to players shipped VP, and subtract # VP from total available (If operating harbor add 1 VP to players shipped VP and subtract 1 VP from available VP) updated players total.  Contact other players in player order and execute as above.  Continue till all goods are shipped or remaining goods are not shippable i.e. no ship space available.  Remember to check for operating Wharf.  Conduct spoilage check 1 good per player unless operating warehouse.  Contact players with spoilage to get items to be saved.  Return goods from fully loaded ships to available goods an update amount of goods available.  Notify players when available VP has been exceeded (Game End).\r\nCraftsman:  In player order determine # of goods produced by player.  Update goods section of player space with name and number of goods and subtract goods produced from available goods. After all players have received goods craftsman receives one good of a type produced by the craftsman (his choice) if available, update available goods section for this choice.\r\nMayor:  Calculate # of colonist for each player starting with the mayor.  Mayor receives 1 additional taken from available colonists subtract one from the available colonist section and enter 0 into colonist ship.  Notify each player of # of colonist received and request where they are to be placed.  Update player spaces adding number of colonists to current amount and adjustment the placement of colonists.  (When large 2 space building is manned calculate the bonus for that building and add to bonus VP in player space and update total.  Count # of unmanned places in building area of all player spaces and place this amount on the colonist ship (Note minimum number is number of players in game) subtract number loaded on to colonist ship from colonists available.  Notify players when available colonists are not sufficient to load colonist ship (Game End).\r\nSettler:  Remove the chosen field from the fields available area.  Contact other players in player order for their choice removing each field from fields available space.  (Note:  A Quarry may only be taken by the player choosing the settler or by a player with an operating construction hut.  Also a player with an operating hacienda receives the next available field from the field pool.)  Remove any unused fields to unused pool and enter the required number of fields (# of players +1) into the fields available space from the field pool.  (Note: If a player has an operating hospice, then the chosen field comes with a colonist making it a manned field.  Add one to number of colonists in the player space and subtract one from the available colonists.)\r\nTrader:  Calculate amount of money earned for selling of good to Trading house (include bonus from bonus area, bonus for being the trader, bonus for any operating market plus amount for chosen good).  Add this amount to gold in player space.  Using player order contact players with sellable good and request if they wish to sell to the trading house.  (Note: no duplication of goods is allowed in the Trading house unless from the owner of an operating office.)  When the trading house has four good the trading round ends and the good are returned to the available goods area.\r\nProspectors 1 and 2:  Add one gold and any bonus to gold in players space.\r\nVerify VP total especially after large 2 space building are manned to assure bonus is calculated correctly.\r\nAfter the governor has executed his turn play passes to the next player in the player order.\r\nThe next player then chooses a role, move players chosen role to role taken and input player name in By box and execute role as above.  This is repeated until all players have chosen a role and role has been executed. \r\nAdd 1 gold bonus to roles not taken and reset roles available area to indicate all roles available.   Send email to all players detailing summary of just completed turn.  Add one to turn number and move governor to next player in player order and notify the governor that it his turn to pick a role.   Repeat till an end game position is reached.  Notify all players of final results, summarize last turn and show final VP calculations.\r\n','2005-11-02','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(128,38,'Ron Flynt','web page\r\neach player\r\nbuildngs\r\nsan juan\r\nfields\r\nvp\r\ncash\r\ngoods\r\nlast role\r\ngovenor?\r\nalso vp from building\r\nalso special building vp\r\n\r\ngame\r\ncolonists in spain\r\ncolonists on boat\r\nvp left\r\nbuildings\r\neach boat\r\ntrading house\r\nroles with money\r\namount of each good\r\nlist of available fields\r\n','2005-11-06','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(129,43,'DAM','This is a set of routines which is the obvious next step from the combination of wiki designer and the todo list. Once you\'ve created a complete list of tasks to do you then assign these tasks to people and then track the resulting project. \r\n\r\nClearly you have to have the tasks assigned to someone and, with that person\'s approval, you need to assign durations to all those tasks. Then you can calculate, for each project, how many man-hours it will take. If you enter in how many dollars for time and how much for overtime each person costs you can calculate how much the whole thing costs. \r\n\r\nSo much for planning. The key to this tool is execution. We want to be able to track how far we are on each task. What I\'d like to know is how many hours each person spent on each task, how complete each task is (either %complete or # hours to completion) and what each person spent the rest of their time. I\'d settle for simply having each task that is complete checked off. This is risky because the project software can\'t tell if a task is really hard or if it is being ignored but, if the tasks are short this will give you pretty good tracking. So the tracking software comes in two flavors. \r\n\r\nLIGHT\r\nSomething very like the todo list (each user sees a list of tasks he/she is signed up for and can check off the ones he/she has completed, PLUS he/she can add tasks to his/her list). This implies that the todo list should be segmentable by both project and user. And we need to think about who can and can\'t add tasks or projects to the list! In this method, all tasks are either 0% or 100% complete. \r\n\r\nHEAVY\r\nA time card that asks hours spent on each task as well as new percent complete (or hours to go). The information about the project is tracked from this. Engineers will hate this but it will give slightly better data for calculations. \r\n\r\nHEAVY VS LIGHT\r\nI\'m not sure the heavy method is worth it, frankly. Both methods will identify problems equally well (assuming data is entered every week, both will flag a problem on the day data is supposed to be entered) but the heavy method will give you more clues as to what the problem is. But you will then go to the developer in question and ask what is going on in both cases and, presumably, the developer will tell you. So the majore advantage of the heavy is that it\'s more precise -- but it\'s not necessarily more accurate. That is, it will take many weeks of data to be sure what is going on just because that\'s how long it takes for a project to \"shake out\" and so the fact that you\'ll be able to track a project to more decimal places with the heavy tracking doesn\'t really mean that you actually have more information. The real issue is that, with light tracking, a few developers taking an extra week can make your reports look alarming while, with heavy, these developers will be making progress through this.  Note that you could, in theory, mix methods with some developers using heavy and some using light. This might be useful in those cases where a developer is 90% done in the 2nd week, causing the system to throw an \"out of bounds\" exception even though he\'s well within operating parameters. You just enter the % done and it moves back into bounds. \r\n\r\nGENERAL\r\nWhichever way you use to track tasks, we make calculations at any given moment by considering all the tasks in a project, their durations and how much is left to do. The exact reports should be based on standard project management and something called \"earned value management\" which uses fairly simple metrics to answer the question \"are we out of bounds?\" and, if so, \"in what way?\"\r\n\r\nI\'d like to see reports on each developer such as a statistical comparison of projected times to actual times (compiled both across multiple projects and just this on) and how close is he at this moment to where he promised he would be. \r\n\r\n','2005-11-14','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(130,43,'DAM','Databases\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>PROJECT has pretty much what the design database has in it\r\n<li>TASK has \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>id<li>title <li>duration <li>assigned to <li>start date <li>desc <li>project <li>plus what\'s in the todo list table\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>TASKSTATUS <ul> <li>entryid<li>taskid <li>currentdate<li>hours worked this week<li>OT hours this week <li>hours to completion </ul>\r\n<li>Notes Contains notes about this project\r\n<li>formal design\r\n<li>comments <ul><li>commentid<li>designid<li>userid<li></ul>\r\n<li>Users add<ul><li>efficiency (ratio of projected duration to actual duration) <li>SD (standard deviation)</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n','2005-11-14','2008-03-21 17:06:12'),(131,43,'DAM','<h3>Earned Value Management</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Budgeted Cost for Work Scheduled (BCWS) - the budgets for all activities planned to be completed. Total projected project cost based on work breakdown and resource costs.\r\n    <li>Actual Cost of Work Performed (ACWP) - the real costs of the work charged against the completed activities. ACWP = work completed (by measurement)\r\n    <li>Budgeted Cost of Work Performed (BCWP) or Earned Value (EV) - the planned costs of the work allocated to the completed activities. This is the Earned Value. Earned Value = Percentage project complete X Project Budget\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>variances</h3>\r\nSchedule and cost variances can both be calculated in monetary terms from the data needed to produce the S-curves.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schedule variance is the difference between the Earned Value and the planned budget.\r\nSV = BCWP - BCWS\r\n\r\n<li>Cost Variance is the difference between the Earned Value and the actual costs of the works.\r\nCV = BCWP - ACWP\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Performance Indices</h3>\r\n\r\nSchedule Performance Index and Cost Performance Index give indications of the health of the project. Is the project on time, in budget or what?\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schedule Performance Index is a ratio of Earned Value and the planned value of completed works. A SPI < 1 is not good\r\nSPI = BCWP / BCWS\r\n\r\n<li>Cost Performance Index is a ratio of Earned Value and the actual costs of completed works. A CPI < 1 is not good\r\nCPI = BCWP / ACWP \r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Estimate At Completion</h3>\r\n\r\nThe EAC gives an idea of the final costs of a project. It takes into account the original budget (BAC), the Earned Value and the Cost Performance Index of the already completed works.\r\nEAC = ACWP + ((BAC - BCWP)/CPI)\r\n\r\n','2006-10-29','2008-03-21 16:59:14'),(132,43,'DAM','<h2>Function Spec</h2>\r\n<h3>Project Data Gatherer</h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Gathers, for every task, every week, hourse spent this week, hours projected to completion (or % complete at the option of the user). To calculate %complete, take the total hours spent plus the hours to completion and divide into total hours spent and then multiply by 100. \r\n<li>Entry has an \"entry Date\" which defaults to today but can be changed to any date past or future\r\n<li>Entry is for the week of the date entered. If multiple entries are made for that week then only the last entrie (based on the time stamp) is counted -- he who writes last, writes best.\r\n<li>Reports\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Project total hours (projected)\r\n<li>Percent Project Complete\r\n<li>Project end date (projected with current data)\r\n<li>Original start and end date\r\n<li>BCWS\r\n<li>ACWP\r\n<li>Earned Value (BCWP)\r\n<li>Schedule Variance\r\n<li>Cost Variance\r\n<li>SPI\r\n<li>CPI\r\n<li>EAC\r\n<li>A list of all completed tasks showing how much longer they took than estimated\r\n<li>A list of all developers, showing how far off their estimates were\r\n</ul>\r\n</ol>','2005-11-14','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(133,41,'DAM','<h2>Login Functions</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reg Page Allows user to enter basic informatation, tells you look for activation\r\n<li>Code that sends activation code to email \r\n<li>Change password page\r\n<li>Lost password enter user name and then send temporary password\r\n<li>Be sure to say where email is from \r\n<li>Expiration date on the temp password\r\n<li>Then we should immediately force a new password\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Mysql Routines</h2>\r\n<h3>Insert & Update Function </h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>calling function needs to know column name \r\n<li>routines try to log things to standard log tables; fails silently if they don\'t exist\r\n<li>Insert is an associative array with key->column names & value is the contents of the column\r\n<li>update is array with key->column names and value-> contents of column plus an array that specifies the where clauses \r\n<li>might want to pass Params and list of actual columns in the table to \r\n</ul>','2005-11-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(134,41,'DAM','<h2>Validation</h2>\r\nA foreach loop with a switch statement at the top of each parse function that runs through all the PARAM fields and, for those fields we care about, validates them. If all is well we parse it, otherwise we set a message string and call the display routine. \r\n\r\nAll the routines are stored in the validate.php which will ultimately be in the library. Eventually it will contain a generic validate function which will be controlled by a db table but that\'s for the future.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2005-11-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(135,33,'DAM & TMT','Validation\r\n\r\nA foreach loop with a switch statement at the top of each parse function that\r\nruns through all the PARAM fields and, for those fields we care about,\r\nvalidates them. If all is well we parse it, otherwise we set a message string\r\nand call the display routine. \r\n\r\nAll the routines are stored in the validate.php which will ultimately be in the\r\nlibrary. Eventually it will contain a generic validate function which will be\r\ncontrolled by a db table but that\'s for the future.','2005-11-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(136,43,'DAM','<h2>Combining WikiDesigner and ToDo List</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>create a new directory and put both sets of code there, changing the name of the todo list and combining config files\r\n<li>create a db with all the tables from both\r\n<li>change todo list so it will only add tasks associated with designs\r\n<li>add to the designer user documentation and requirement documents \r\n<li>add comments to everything \r\n<li>login stuff\r\n<li>add fields to todo list for owner, duration etc.\r\n<li>make the user interface nicer for entering tasks\r\n<li>add ability to parse tab tables\r\n</ul>','2005-11-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(137,42,'DAM','\r\n<li>create database with 10 fields\r\n<li>anyone can look but you have to be registered to add or edit\r\n<li>current company list code has to read it from this list, get the title from the master and use the correct fields\r\n<li>also need a list definition page\r\n<li>also need a list directory page\r\n\r\ncreate table listmaster (\r\nlistid int auto_increment primary key,\r\ntitle varchar(255) default \"untitled\",\r\ndescription varchar (255) default \"no description\",\r\nnamefield0 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield1 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield2 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield3 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield4 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield5 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield6 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield7 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield8 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nnamefield9 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nts timestamp\r\n\r\n);\r\n\r\ncreate table item(\r\nitem id int auto_increment primary key,\r\nlistno int default 0,\r\ntitle varchar(255) default \"untitled\",\r\ntype int default 0,\r\ndescription text,\r\nfield0 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield1 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield2 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield3 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield4 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield5 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield6 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield7 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield8 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nfield9 varchar(255) default NULL,\r\nts timestamp\r\n);\r\n\r\n\r\nAnothe table has a list of types\r\ncreate table type(\r\ntypeid int auto_increment primary key,\r\nlistno int default 0,\r\nname varchar(255) default  \"notype\",\r\nhide boolean,\r\ndescription varchar(255) default \"unspecified type\",\r\nts timestamp\r\n);','2005-11-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(138,31,'DAM','<i>Example</i>\r\n<b>Lunar Lander</b>\r\ninitial_height init 20\r\ninitial_velocity init 0\r\ninitial_fuel init 50\r\ninput_burn input 0\r\nconst_thrust contant +1\r\nconst_gravity constant -1\r\nacceleration interim const_thrust*input_burn + const_gravity \r\nvelocity =interim velocity + acceleration (init->initial_velocity)\r\nfuel =fuel-input_burn (init->init_acceleration)\r\nheight =height+velocity\r\nfinal_height =height (end height<=0)\r\nfinal_fuel =fuel (end fuel<=0)\r\n','2005-11-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(139,31,'DAM','How Program works\r\n5 Pages\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sim Directory</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> list of sims\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>link to add sim page (must be registered user)\r\n<li>names\r\n<li>descriptions\r\n<li>links to run page for each one\r\n<li>links to edit page for each one\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Add sim page</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Must be registered user\r\n<li>form to add all the data in a sim master record\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Edit Sim Page</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Allows you to edit the master information about sim\r\n<li>Link to edit sim cards\r\n<li>Link to sim list\r\n<li>link to run sim\r\n<li>link to delete sim (actually hides it)\r\n<li>Form with all the master sim table info \r\n<li>values are current sim table info\r\n<li>button for update\r\n<li>returns you to edit sim \r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Edit Cards Page</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>link to add card\r\n<li>link to run sim\r\n<li>list of cards\r\n<li>Name of each card in sim\r\n<li>link to edit card for each card\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Start Sim Page\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Shows basic sim information\r\n<li>Link to Sim Master Edit Page\r\n<li>Link to Sim Directory Page\r\n<li>It\'s mainly a form with all the initialization variables as form elements\r\n<li>Click on \"start sim\" \r\n<li>It saves all the initial values to the database\r\n<li>It updates all variables to their initial value\r\n<li>It goes to the \"Continue Sim\" page\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Continue Sim Page\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>Link to Sim Directory Page\r\n<li>Link to Edit Sim Page\r\n<li>Form with a list of input values\r\n<li>Also a list of final values\r\n<li>Possibly a list of final conditions\r\n<li>Field that defines how many iterations to step (defaults to 1)\r\n<li>Button steps it that many iterations\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Final Sim Page\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Link to Start Sim\r\n<li>Link to edit sim page\r\n<li>Link to Sim Directory\r\n<li>List of initial values\r\n<li>List of final values\r\n<li>Message about why it stopped (if possible)\r\n<li>Also make the final values whose end condition is met red\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>','2005-11-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(140,31,'DAM','<b>Miscelaneous notes about changes / additions to the current system</b>\r\n<li>When you hit start, all the initial values must be set in\r\n<li>On continue the following sequence happens\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Change input values\r\n<li>Update values of all the variables (by which I mean \"in order of seq field\")\r\n<li>check for end conditions; if end, display final screen\r\n<li>repeat until iteration count is satisfied\r\n<li>display continue screen\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>need a message for all end conditions; not sure where to put it, tho\r\n<li>need a step # in the master record\r\n<li>add the characters =,<,!,> to the list of legal characters\r\n<li>add input and final to the list of types\r\n<li>types now control where the variables are shown\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Initial type variables are shown in the start screen where they can be changed and at the end\r\n<li>Input type variables are shown on the continue screen where you can change them\r\n<li>Final type variables are shown during continue and at the end\r\n<li>Constants and intermediate variables are never shown. Constants should actually be values or an expression that is derived from other constants\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>change all single = to == early in the expression parsing; = is not to be allowed. the regular express to find all =s should be /={1,1}/ and preg_replace should do the trick\r\n<li>consider adding if, else and ; to the internal constant list; that should make expressions like \"if (a==b)1 else 2 ;\" possible which means that you can now have conditionals; under no circumstances should braces ({}) be allowed as that gives the user too much power. Note that the user can\'t assign any variable s or call any functions as function names will not be found in the variable list and evaluated to 0 so foo() will evaluate to 0() which will generate a nasty error\r\n<li>think about while, until, for and until; probably don\'t want any of that\r\n</ul>','2005-11-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(141,43,'DAM','Todo lists must be associated with special todo items called \"Milestones\". \r\n\r\nThe easiest way to do this in the database is to add a field to todo items \"Milestone number\" and if this is 0 then this item is a milestone. All other todo items must be associated with a milestone. \r\n\r\nFrom a UI perspective, you just get a list of all the milestones in the project and allow one to associate a todo item with one of the milestones. At any future date a todo item or milestone can be associate with a milestone in the edit process.  If a milestone is associated with a milestone it and all the todo items that pointed to it are now associated with the new milestone.\r\n\r\nThe implications of having todos associated with a milestone is that the predicted completion date of the milestone is calculated from the durations of the todos and it is not complete until all the todos are complete.\r\n\r\nAn ugly aspect of this system is that we have to calculate the todos of different actors separately. The easiest way to calculate the projected end date  for a milestone is to consider all the todos of one resource (aka \"actor\") and add up all their remaining time. Convert this into a calendar date (8 hrs/day, 40 hrs/ week added to today\'s date) and you have the projected date when that actor will be done. Now do that for all the actors. Take the latest one and that\'s when the milestone will be done. While we\'re at it we might as well allow one to see which resource is the \"critical path resource\" -- that is the one with the longest duration.\r\n\r\nOne other thing: we COULD have hierarchies of tasks. That is, tasks and subtasks  ad nauseum; I don\'t think I like that but we could do it.','2005-12-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(142,43,'DAM','There need to be two ways to look at tasks. First there is a list of all the tasks in a project and then there is the list of all the lists associated with a person. The list and the detail may well be identical; the difference is the filter. ','2005-12-15','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(143,43,'DAM','Milestones are defined in some systems by any task that has zero duration. That definition means that we can allow the interface to only include \"tasks\" and generate a milestone based on the duration. Or we can have a checkbox... ','2005-12-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(144,43,'DAM','But the key to milestones is not the milestones themselves but the tasks that make up the milestone...','2005-12-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(145,44,'Robert Holland','<H2>Robert Holland\'s Page Designs</h2>\r\n<img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/sbk/design/sbkdesign1.jpg\"><br>\r\n<img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/sbk/design/sbkdesign2.jpg\"><br>\r\n<img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/sbk/design/sbkdesign3.jpg\"><br>\r\n<img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/sbk/design/sbkdesign4.jpg\"><br>\r\n<img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/sbk/design/sbkdesign4a.jpg\"><br>\r\n<img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/sbk/design/sbkdesign5.jpg\"><br>\r\n','2006-01-02','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(146,44,'Dave Menconi','<h2>Dave Menconi\'s Mockups</h2>\r\nCheck out the <a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/sbk/\">Mockup</a>','2006-01-02','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(147,44,'Robert Holland','Dave, your mockup is a big step forward. I\'ll email you some content soon.','2006-01-04','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(148,43,'DAM','<h3>Assumptions</h3>\r\n<p>I\'m simplifying this system quite a bit when compared to standard project management systems. I thought it might be good to state them explicitely.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>One task, One engineer\r\n<li>Every task belongs to one and only one project\r\n<li>Every task is associated with a milestone\r\n<li>There is only one level of milestones -- this is a very flat work breakdown structure\r\n<li>by default, when a task is checked as done, the actual time taken is the time between the last task that was checked an this moment\r\n<li>every developer is doing one of the tasks in the system at any given moment\r\n</ul>','2006-01-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(149,43,'DAM','1) complete/test data collection routines\r\n2) create code to get \"total effort\" from collection of status records\r\n3) create code to get \"effort remaining\" from collection of status records\r\n4) add hierarchy to database (ability to related sub tasks to super tasks)\r\n5) add hierarchy to user interface (ability to add sub tasks to a super\r\ntask)\r\n6) create code to calculate total effort and effort remaining for\r\nsupertasks (and milestones, now that you mention it)\r\n7) incorporate hierarchy into various displays\r\n8) reporting screens including some or all of the following stats arranged\r\nin a reasonable way\r\n  Project total hours (projected)\r\n  Percent Project Complete\r\n  Project end date (projected with current data)\r\n  Original start and end date\r\n  Budgeted Cost for Work Scheduled\r\n  Actual Cost of Work Performed\r\n  Earned Value\r\n  Schedule Variance\r\n  Cost Variance\r\n  Schedule Performance Index\r\n  Cost Performance Index\r\n  Estimate At Completion\r\n  A list of all completed tasks showing how much longer they took than\r\n  estimated\r\n  A list of all developers, showing how far off their estimates were\r\n9) add input verification\r\n10) upgrade authorization system\r\n11) add logging\r\n12) move to secure server\r\n13) test with live data\r\n','2006-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(150,4,'DAM','This may well be a repeat of some of the other things I\'ve written but here is my new thinking about this.\r\n\r\nRedwall itself is a  LAMP web site that allows users to register, log in, sign up for games, submit turns, find out their status, talk on forums and so forth. \r\n\r\nBut the interesting thing is a standard for games. A game must have a program (in any language) that can be invoked in one of 4 ways. \r\n\r\nIn all cases, Redwall formats information it sends to the game in XML and the game must send back information in XML format. In both cases there may be big blocks of text or even binary data (text encoded I would think) embedded in the XML. These blocks are game-specific text or data which are sent to the player by RedWall without interpretation. \r\n\r\nI envision an XML schema which is pretty basic and simple and which has both required fields that every game must have (game number, turn number, etc) and some optional fields that games may ignore if they don\'t use those features.\r\n\r\n1) Start Game\r\nThis invocation is passed an xml file with a list of players: user name, user number, game number, player pseudonym, perhaps some game-specific parameters which are optional (which means they have perfectly valid defaults). The game program creates it\'s databases and so forth for that game. The game puts out to standard output an xml file that contains the status of the command (success or failure), the game number, the turn number, perhaps some other game information, and, for each player, a block of text which that player will understand to be his starting position (that is, the first turn). Redwall then logs the game specific data into a database, and sends the turn information to each player according to whatever method they have requested. \r\n\r\n2) Parse Orders\r\nWhen a player sends in orders for a turn, Redwall invokes the game and passes in the information for this turn/game/player (in xml) plus the text of the player\'s turn. The game returns an xml file that has the results of the parsing (success for not), the player/turn/game information and a block of text that has information about problems with the turn. Redwall will send this to the player. The game is responsible for storing the latest turn information for each player in whatever way it uses. RedWall will not send it again (unless the player sends another turn). \r\n\r\n3) Run Turn\r\nRedwall invokes the run turn command and passes an XML file with the game number (I think that\'s all that is required). The game runs and spews out an xml file with game status information, information for each player and, optionally, information for the public. Redwall doesn\'t interpret the information but displays the game specific text in the appropriate ways (showing the public info and sending the player infor to the correct players).  \r\nIf the game is over, this information is noted along with final standings and other information. The game should execute the \"game end\" code and clean up after itself as well as archive any information that should be saved for posterity. \r\n\r\n4) End Game\r\nIf, for some reason, RedWall needs to terminate a game, it sends the end game command and the game kills itself off and terminates, cleaning up all it\'s files, databases, cron tasks and so forth. The game will spew back the final status of the game, standings and so forth, if any. It is assumed that the game history is sent back as an xml file to be archived by RedWall; the game itself should keep nothing. \r\n\r\n\r\n','2006-06-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(151,4,'DAM','The major change in thinking on 6/13/06 from 6/15/05 (a whole year!) is that we want to use xml instead of flat files. And we added an end game command. \r\n\r\nXml tags\r\ngame \r\nturn\r\nplayer name\r\nplayer number (?)\r\nplayer pseudonym\r\ncommand (start, parse, run, end)\r\ncommand status (success, error)\r\ncommand error number\r\ncommand error message\r\nturn text\r\nplayer result text (must have a player parameter)\r\nturn error text\r\npublic text\r\ngame status (running, paused, complete, terminated)\r\nplayer stats -- not sure handle variable values with stats associated with them but seen the 6/15/05 final note for what I was thinking for a flat file. \r\n','2006-06-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(152,45,'DAM','First off, I need a database. It has to have ships, planets and player names as 3 different tables. All tables must have username, player name, player number(?), game, turn(?) and then the ship,planet or player name (which in the case of planets is a number). You may or may not put other stuff in there but those are the ones we need for this thing.\r\n\r\nThen we need to authenticate so we need an authentication table. I believe there is a standard format for that. \r\n\r\nFor the UI itself there are 3 sections: ships, planets and others. There is a top level page that has links to these three things and some help text. There is also a big help page that has lots of sublinks within it so we can have context sensitive help.\r\n\r\nThere are also 3 sub-sections. One to \"register\" (that is, add to the database) a ship, one for a planet and one for a player. These need links to the help system to explain what we\'re doing.\r\n\r\nThe planet section has all the commands that start with a planet number -- mostly building but I believe there are a few others. It has a drop down for all the registered planets, a drop down for all the possible command codes and a drop down for all the objects of the sentence. It would be good if we could have the selection of the verb change the possible objects but if we can\'t then just have a list of all the ships and resources we could possibly be talking about... (not very satisfying).\r\n\r\nAt the top of this page you can register ships and planets. \r\n\r\nThe ship page is simpler (I think). You just have all the ships, all the commands, and all the objects (which can really only be ships and resources and ship parts). This, again, could be better if we change the command when the verb is selected. \r\nThis has subsections for ships and planets.\r\n\r\nThe other section has commands for gifting ships and planets and for changing your status with respect to another player. \r\nIt has all 3 subsections. \r\n\r\n','2006-06-19','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(153,45,'DAM','We have to find out how to rewrite a page when a pulldown is selected. \"ONSELECT\"? That\'s the key to this whole thing. \r\n\r\nAlso, we need to go through all the commands and figure out all the possible subjects and objects. Not THAT complicated but there are always nasty exceptions. ','2006-06-19','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(154,43,'DAM','Here are the high priority tasks -- things I want next\r\nMy main goal is to get it usable for me (RJ can write his own):\r\n1) Multiple users -- test and fix any proglems\r\n2) Multiple projects -- test and fix any problems\r\n3) 5 types of users (just create the 5 types for now; no capabilities yet)\r\n   1) Worker (can see and edit his own stuff, create projects, add himself to any project, mark tasks done, etc)\r\n   2) Manager (has a defined set of workers; can add or remove his workers from any project; can look at an edit any information about any of his workers; can see reports about any of his workers)\r\n   3) Project manager (has a defined set of projects; can add or remove any workers from/to any of his projects, can edit any of his projects, can see reports about any of his projects)\r\n   4) Sr. Manager (can see everything, look at any reports, but edit nothing)\r\n   5) Admin (can see everything, edit everything, see every report, no exceptions)\r\n   Note that a single person can have several overlapping roles (ich). Managers are often project managers as well. \r\n4) Changes send email to owners (admin, manager, project manager)\r\n5) Ability to add, delete & edit projects (adding: anyone, delete and edit: admins and PMs; creating a project requires you to define a PM)\r\n6) ability to add, edit and delete tasks (only pm and admins)\r\n7) ability to add, edit and delete workers (only admins)\r\n8) Ability to edit people\'s privs and add new people (only admins)\r\n9) A few basic reports (\"How is my project doing?\" \"How hard is my worker working?\")','2006-06-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(155,46,'Summer','si c\'est bien sur','2006-07-19','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(156,47,'Dave','00 Store front\r\n10 documentation \r\n10 resource watch\r\n11 The 9 releases\r\n20 Confluence Pages\r\n20 checklists\r\n23 demo 2 work & Coord\r\n30 Co-manager\r\n30 advisor \r\n30 deleloper management & coordination\r\n30 sounding board\r\n40 weekly reports\r\n50 \" DECR\r\n50 \" Tests\r\n50 Distributed & Managed DEH\r\n50 GDC\r\n50 Gameshare\r\n50 OS distribution & management\r\n50 PS3 devkit effort for buzz\r\n50 Sent back CEBs\r\n50 international audio meeting\r\n90 \"brought a dependability & Grooming to our engineering effort\"\r\n99 build test rules\r\n','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(157,48,'dave','<h2>The Five</h2>\r\nThis is an \"ugly truth\" kind of place. I\'m sorry but I really believe that we are going to be, literally, in a world of hurt unless we start paying attention to what we\'re doing. There are 5 major areas that I believe can send our civiliation (by which I mean \"global society\" since I don\'t believe any portion of the world can maintain a technological society while a significant portion of the rest decends into war, famine, desease and general chaos). These five potential catastrophes are all related and need to be solved as a group. Solving one or two won\'t save us and I don\'t think it\'s actually possible to solve any of them separately.\r\nI want to make two things very clear from the outset. FIrst, this is not a doom and gloom, all is lost proposition. I think we can still save ourselves but we have to actually work at it. I see a lot of people ignoring it and I don\'t see anyone taking it really seriously.\r\nSecond, I am not an environmentalist per se. That is, I don\'t believe that we should put the earth before ourselves. However, as it turns out, we must rearrange our lifestyle so that the earth can sustain us or we simply won\'t survive. This aligns me with some ideas of environmentalists and sets me against others. For example, I agree that we need to do things sustainably but I would be against (for example) tearing down damns to recreate the natural wild rivers.\r\n\r\n<h3>Global Warming</h3>\r\nMore properly called \"global climate change\", this is observed and generally accepted warming of the earth. Most people agree that it\'s caused by the over use of fossil fuels. This means that it is either the potential cause or potential effect of every other one of the five except overpopulation.\r\nSomething that is not generally appreciated is that the global climate change doesn\'t necessarily mean that the mean temperature goes up everywhere in an orderly and predictable manner. Rather it means that there is a great deal more energy in the weather systems which means that the temperature, winds, rainfall and so forth are more variable and less predicable. This could result in a disruption of food growth if the \"bread basket\" areas of the earth became untenable as growing areas. It could also create a lack of water if rain fall was distributed differently. The main point, however, is that more variable weather will mean more variable crop yields -- it\'s hard to imagine that will be good for growing as much food as we need.\r\n\r\n<h3>Energy Shortages</h3>\r\nThis should come as no surprise to anyone. We\'ve known since the 50\'s that we were using up all the fossil fuels and we\'ve certainly known since the 70\'s that production doesn\'t always meet demand. What\'s becoming clear is that soon it may not be possible for production to meet demand. This has already caused wars and it will cause bigger and bigger wars as the demand becomes more acute.\r\n\r\n<h3>Overpopulation</h3>\r\nIn a sense, this is the root cause of all the others. As the population of the world grows it will need more of everything which will drive global warming, energy consumption, and require ever more food and water.\r\nBut this is an oversimplification. The truth is that every North American consumes so much more resources of every kind than any other citizen of the planet that any plan that doesn\'t involve Americans cutting back on their consumption radically is doomed.\r\n\r\n<h3>Starvation</h3>\r\nThere are several ways that starvation could happen. Climate change might rearrange places were food will grow in a way that prevents us from growing enough food. We could run out of energy and therefore not be able to sustain large scale agriculture and/or the transportation network. Or the population could simply grow beyond our ability to feed it -- there is only so much growth we can sustain, after all.\r\n\r\n<h3>Lack of Water</h3>\r\nCurrently some parts of America are using more water than they produces. They are borrowing water from other places. The people in those places, however, are growing and need more and more water themselves. Eventually something will have to give and those states that are importing water will find themselves with a shortage.\r\nPopulation growth has been the main thing that is driving this and there is no sign this will stop. But as the climate changes there will be an unknown effect on the distribution of water and that may cause a shift in where the water is. If it moves to places we can catch it then we\'ll be ok (that is, we\'ll run out later) but if not, we could run out fairly suddenly.\r\n\r\n<h3>So What?</h3>\r\nThe world is heading for 15 billion people, apparently. It is not really known if we can support that many or, indeed, how many we can support. Let\'s say it\'s 12 billion. It would be nice to think (although I admit, not very kind -- but I said this was a \"ugly truth\" kind of place) that those 3 billion excess people would simply lay down and die.\r\n\r\nFirst off, those doomed 3 billions will not take it lying down; they are going to try to get more resources to survive. There will be a series of border clashes which will eventually escalate into regional wars. Lots of people will die of famine, war and disease and that will take the pressure off for a time but then the war will flare up again. A war involving 3 billion people on one side is a pretty big war and it will very likely affect the rest of the world.\r\nThe effect of this extreme chaos will probably be that much resources will be consumed fighting, supplying armies and generally trying to protect oneself. The chaos will inevitably tax our resources so that we can no longer support 12 billion and more people will be threatened with starvation and more will go to war. The world will spiral down from a prosperous, fairly stable state to total chaos. You can\'t maintain a global economy in chaos so the world economy will become fragmented. Some fragments will be unsupportable so the chaos will spread. Some areas will be stable but, inevitably, they will be stable at a much lower level of technology (why inevitably?). Whatever this level is (what level WILL it be?), it will be the new \"dark ages\" and it will be the basis for the next civilization on earth many hundreds of years later.\r\n\r\nOf course, this scenario won\'t actually happen. Even if the Earth could support 12 billion people (which is unlikely), we would never get anywhere near 15 billion. Instead the wars would start while we still had plenty of food because of the inequality of distribution. They would get steadily worse until the chaos they caused completely prevented our reaching any kind of stable equilibrium. This dynamic makes it very hard to predict how much the earth can sustain. \r\n\r\n<h3>Why will we lose our technology?</h3>\r\nOur technology is based on a global manufacturing economy. If there is suddenly no fossil fuels, the transport web will fail because there won\'t be enough fuel to support it. That means that you can no longer acquire things that aren\'t produced nearby because the is no reasonable way to get them to you.\r\nIf everything you had access to was produced within, say, 500 miles of you, you\'re technology would be very much constrained. You need to have food production, energy production, manufacturing and so forth all fairly close by.  One could imagine a population heroically reproducing the 19th century with hard work but first they would have to cope with water and food without fossil fuels of any kind. By the time they dealt with those challenges much of the old technology would be lost -- not to memory but to practical use. Keep in mind that all this will happen, not in an orderly predictable fashion, but amidst war, famine, disease and other forms of chaos.\r\n\r\n<h3>What level of technology will be sustainable?</h3>\r\nIf we decided to cut back we could maintain our current technology. We would simply have to give up using too much of everything.\r\nBut if we\'re forced to cut back we\'re likely to lose the electrical grid. Once that goes down for, say, a decade, it will be very hard to bring it back up. Once we lose electricity most of our technology is shot. Of course some places will still have electricity and those places will be little islands of technology but most places will be struggling to farm enough food to feed themselves -- maintaining anything more will be tough.\r\nThink about it: no electricity from a grid and no fossil fuels. Where do you get energy? Burning wood? Horses? \r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>But what can we do?</h3>\r\nFor those of us in the US, the problem is really energy.  We could, if we were really committed, cut our energy usage in half in the next 20 years (by \"we\" I mean those of us in the US). I know that sounds outrageous but we could replace all our lights with LEDs, take mass transit whenever possible, drive tiny hybrid cars, and build energy efficient houses. We\'re filthy rich; we could do it all if we wanted to spend the money. We just need to decide that that is what we want to do!\r\nWe would also have to significantly increase our renewable energy sources.\r\n\r\nTheFIVE.org \r\nThe symbol for the 5 is a hand\r\n\r\nGlobal Warming\r\nLack of energy\r\nover population\r\nlack of drinkingwater\r\nlack of food\r\n\r\n<h3>The Case For The 5</h3>\r\nThese 5 things are not just a few of the things we should be concerned about. THhese 5 things are the first 5 things we must deal with before we can address all the other things that will hurt us if we don\'t address them.\r\nIt seems obvious that, if any of these things goes wrong -- we run out of energy without any way to replace it or our population becomes unsustainable -- people will die. If it goes a little wrong -- New York doesn\'t get food for a month, for example -- only thousands will die. IF it goes horribly wrong --  say food production is cut in half worldwide for an extended period of time -- millions or even billions could die.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, there are a LOT of things that can go badly wrong and almost anything going wrong makes it more likely that other things would then go wrong. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2006-10-17','2007-11-18 00:49:35'),(158,3,'DAM','Add a facility to edit individual notes. All that\'s really needed is a set of radio buttons on each note and a submit button at the bottom (or top) that says \"edit note\". When you check the button and hit edit a text box comes up (a big text box) with that note in it and you can edit it. Simple and yet adds a ton of functionality to this. ','2006-10-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(159,47,'Dave','10 resource watch\r\n20 checklists\r\n23 demo 2 work & Coord\r\n10 demo 1\r\n30 Co-manager\r\n30 advisor \r\n30 deleloper management & coordination\r\n30 sounding board\r\n40 weekly reports\r\n50 \" DECR\r\n50 \" Tests\r\n50 Distributed & Managed DEH\r\n50 GDC\r\n50 Gameshare\r\n50 OS distribution & management\r\n50 PS3 devkit effort for buzz\r\n50 Sent back CEBs\r\n50 international audio meeting\r\n90 \"brought a dependability & Grooming to our engineering effort\"\r\n99 build test rules','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(167,47,'Dave','Equipment\r\nOur group ran out of cables and needed new equipment to handle HD development. I made a list of stuff that we needed based on my work with the developers, identified the best vendors and ordered a whole bunch of cables and equipment. ','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(164,47,'Dave','Confluence Pages\r\nWe wanted to have pages on our intranet that had our promotional project information. The manager responsible for the projects wanted to keep and update the information as a word document. The intranet runs something called Confluence. In general, Confluence is much less capable than word in formatting.  \r\n\r\nSo I got a Word macro that particlaly converted from word to Confluence markup language. This resulted in some very odd pages so I wrote a perl script which would convert certain of the resulting Confluence Markup into better Confluence Markup. I also made some changes to the Word document so that the converter would be able to handle it better. For example, the Word document used indenting as it\'s main way of showing the organization of the text but Confluence doesn\'t really do indenting very well so I changed much of the text in the word document to bullets because Confluence could handle it much better. \r\nIn this way, I managed to create a system of pages in Confluence that presented the same information the Word document presented and made accurate, and aesthetic information available to the thousands of people who use our Intranet. \r\n','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(160,47,'Dave','documentation\r\nThe tools group had 9 projects whose code was complete but which did not yet have documentation. \r\n\r\nI coordinated the efforts of various technical writer contractors to get the documentation of the projects done.\r\n\r\nIn the event we managed to get acceptable documentation for all 9 projects. ','2006-10-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(161,47,'Dave','The 9 releases\r\n\r\nThere were 9 projects that were substantially finished. Each was a one or two\r\nperson project. There was no process so there was not test plan, no formal\r\ndocumentation, not process of any kind. I imposed some modest process including\r\ndocumentation (primarily users guide), test plan (written by developers) and a\r\nspecific release package that was defined to contain certain things. I left out\r\ntesting because we had no testers. I was hoping that the test plan would cause\r\npeople to think about problems.\r\nTHe results were that all 9 projects were released on time, all of them had\r\nadequate documentation and test plans. MOst had excellent documentation and\r\nvery good test plans and a few of them actually had tests that had been run. \r\nEven though I was in England all 9 were released on time. \r\nSeveral PS3 Launch teams have used the 9 libraries and very few problems have\r\nbeen found. \r\n','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(162,47,'Dave','Surfing Chaos\r\nThere is a problem at sony in that the manager of the platform team is managing about 4 times the number of people he should be. He\'s managing about 39 developers (most of the external and remote) while the typical range is 8 to 12. And he\'s doing this across 15 projects. My job was to make sure that things get done in a timely and orderly fashion. I have mostly accomplished this although using traditional project management didn\'t work very well. I used the process I used to use as a game developer which I called \"surfing the chaos\" which involves flexibly allocating resources to problems as they come up and not being too concerned if you can\'t accurately predict what will happen. This method is prone to quality issues and doesn\'t make for a very predictable system but you can get a lot done. IN the event, I also invented some light processes that seem to have addressed the quality issues.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(163,47,'Dave','Store front\r\nDeveloper support required internal developers to find equipment they wanted to\r\nbuy on a web site and, print out a form and send it back as a fax. This fax\r\nwould then be re-entered into the computer. What was needed was some way to\r\norder things on line. A storefront had been created for this purpose but\r\ndeveloper support had not adopted it. \r\nWe met with developer support and persuaded them to ','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(165,47,'Dave','I was working in a tools group that wrote low-level libraries (memory manager, file IO scheduler, MP3 decoder, etc) that were intended to be used on the Playstation platforms by Sony gameteams. The problem was that we were a young group and had very little project process in place. Heretofor all our releases had been pre-alpha releases with no clearly specified requirements. Since we had no test department, technical pubs department and very little history or tradition of conforming our work to a process a new process needed to be developed. This process needed to be tailored to the specific needs of the team and of the customers who would use the software and it could not overburden the developers. \r\n\r\nI developed a process that focused on 3 main areas: documentation that gave a concise overview of the software and how it might be used, test plans and a specification of how to construct a release so that our customers who used one would find others to be packaged consistently.\r\n\r\nIn the event we released 9 separate projects on the same day all with sufficient documentation and testing to be useable by the game teams immediately.','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(166,47,'Dave','New Process\r\nThe problem was that we have little process and we have virtually no resources to enforce process. We have 15 projects and 35 developers and no history of process. \r\n\r\nI adapted the processes I\'ve used in the past to make it lighter and more easily managed in this stituation. I divided a project into 4 stages: pre-project (including design and administrative activities), developement (including the bulk of the coding), developer (including the polishing, bug fixing and general clean-up of the code) and qa (including the documentation, packaging, testing and release activities). ','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(168,47,'Dave','Art Tool Chain\r\nWe had been using a product called Anark to do our user interface. Anark\'s run-time uses a fixed-function pipeline','2006-10-28','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(169,40,'DAM','Air Race\r\nA race game where the players have simple airplanes. The emphasis is on wackiness and interaction rather than the model of the aerodynamics. The players move around a track that consists of a series of hoops. There are power ups that you can collect that will allow you to go faster, shoot at other players put webbing accross the hoops and so forth. ','2006-10-29','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(170,43,'DAM','I did it the way I laid it out and I think I kind of got stuck. I don\'t find it useful for tracking simple todo lists and it looks like a hell of a lot of effort to get it to be useful for tracking actual projects. In particular, there is no where to put it that all the developers can see it. \r\n\r\nThe new idea is to combine them virtually. Both todo and designs will access each others\' databases but the actual code will be separate. \r\n\r\n\r\nWe need to fix the todo list so it gets it\'s \"product\" from the designs database. \r\nThen it needs to have durations, the name of the resource who is going to do it and a milestone associated with each todo item (task). Resources default to the author of the design and the default milestone is \"future\". \r\n\r\nAdd some links from the designs to the tasks and from the tasks to the designs. \r\n\r\nEventually, we should put the reports into designs. \r\n\r\nBefore I do any of this stuff I should look at the project management system again. ','2006-10-29','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(171,16,'DAM','Players one to ten are fake players with fake names and no one can log into them -- perhaps they have a random number as a password.\r\n\r\nIn the event that there are less than 10 guesses when a round ends these guys will add guesses. P=10-G\r\nif P<=0 we do nothing. If P>0 then we add P guesses using players 1 to P. (Where G is the number of guesses at the end of the round).\r\n\r\nWe want the exact ai that each player uses to be arbitrary. We will have 5 or 6 AIs and we\'ll pick one at random. \r\n\r\nOne AI is to calculate all the winning numbers for all the rounds and then do a best fit via linear regression and then add the average delta x and delta y to the last winner.\r\n\r\nANother idea is to take the line, figure out the delta of the last two points and find the point on the line that\'s closest to the sum of that delta and the last point.\r\n\r\nOr take the last two averages and take the delta X and delta Y and add it to the last one.\r\n\r\nTake the last value and add/subtract some small random value to it.\r\n\r\nJUst guess the last average.\r\n\r\nGuess the maximum.\r\n\r\nGuess the medium.\r\n\r\nGuess the min.\r\n\r\nGuess a random number in the range.\r\n\r\n\r\nDatabases\r\nUser \r\nusername\r\npassword\r\nuserid\r\nwins\r\n\r\nGame\r\nName of the game\r\nduration of the game\r\ngame ID\r\n\r\nRound\r\ngameno\r\nroundid (unique)\r\nroundno (unique to this game)\r\nend date\r\nend time\r\nover?\r\nwinnernamestring (could be multiple winners)\r\nwin left\r\nwin right\r\n\r\nGuess\r\ngame no\r\nround no\r\nguessid\r\ntime \r\ndate\r\nuserno\r\nleft guess\r\nright guess\r\n\r\nCODE\r\nuser account edit page where you can change your password and email\r\nregistration page name, password, password, email address (optional)\r\nUsers log in (loc_login)\r\nShow stats only they can see\r\nscreen with all the different games and at the bottom has all the guesses this player has made by date.\r\nEach game has a stats page and a game guess page. Stats include all your guesses and all the winning guess and the winner plus a list of winners and how many times they\'ve won\r\naverage left is average(leftguess) and average right is average(rightguess)\r\nTo calculate a winner you get the average left and average right and then you calculate the difference between the guess left and the averageleft for each player and those guesses with the lowest delta left are further considered. We subtract those guess rights from the averageright and the ones with the smallest of THAT are the winner(s).\r\n\r\nEvery round has an end date and time. \r\nGuess page says \r\nGUESS MY NUMBER\r\nTwelve hour Game (or whatever the name is)\r\nThis Round ends at: dd/mm/yy hh:mm\r\n\r\nLast Round Number: lll.rrrrrr\r\nLast Round Won by: Name[, Name[, Name...]] (lll.rrrrrr)\r\n\r\nYour Guess: [..........]\r\n{Enter Guess}\r\n\r\n<Game Statistics>\r\nHow To Play \r\nBasic rules of game plus a link to a more detailed description.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNOTES\r\nUsername must be unique\r\neach player can guess only once so we should either add a guess OR update a guess depending on whether one exists.\r\nEvery guess is a 3 digit left hand number (digits to the left of decimal) and 6 digit right hand number (digits to the right of decimal). To be precise, all the characters but the digits and the period are removed. Then we remove all periods but the first one. Then we take the digits to the left of the decimal and take the last 3 (or less) and the digits to the right and take the first 6 (adding zeros to pad to 6, if necessary). These two numbers are \"guess left\" and \"guess right\" respectively. Mathematically, a guess is a number between 0 and 999.999999 so the guessright is in \"millionths\". But practically, it\'s just the \"high order\" integer (left) and the \"low order\" integer; we don\'t ever divide by anything or combine them as a single number. \r\nThe goal number is the average of all the guesses which is averageleft and averageright.','2006-11-09','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(172,40,'DAM','HOw about a celular autonoma that\'s got probabilistic rules instead of certain rules. So, instead of 0 or 1 being death, 3 being birth and 4-8 being death, the rules have a table of probabilities like:\r\n0: 90% death\r\n1: 60% death\r\n2: 10% death\r\n3: 5% death, 80% birth\r\n4: 20% death\r\n5: 40% death\r\n6: 60% death\r\n7: 80% death\r\n8: 100% death\r\nOr some such. Thus a board with all cells occupied would sparse out and do something interesting! And other previously static things would slowly decay. ','2006-11-09','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(173,16,'DAM','Time to implement...\r\n\r\nI want a version of this game that is absolutely the minimum proof of concept.\r\n\r\n+ Any registered user can play\r\n+ Need to allow people to register (but activate by hand)\r\n+ Need a page that allows one to make a guess\r\n+ need a page that reports the state of the game to each player\r\n+ Need a program that runs the turn (called from crontab)\r\n+ As much as possible these should be proto-versions of redwall routines\r\n\r\n','2007-01-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(174,16,'DAM','select avg(leftguess) as avgleft,avg(rightguess) as avgright,avg(leftguess)+(avg(rightguess)/1000000) as sumofavg  from guess;\r\n\r\nrightguess must always be a 6 digit number or 0 (which is 6 0s). \r\n\r\n','2007-01-29','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(175,16,'DAM','There is now just a floating point (3.6) number for guess (the other way didn\'t actually work). Here are the selects to choose a winner.\r\nFirst, we get the average, plugging in the correct gameno and roundno\r\nselect avg(guess) from guess where gameno=1 and roundno=1;\r\n\r\nThen we plug the average into this select and it gives us the one user -- no ties (tie goes to whomever guessed it first). \r\n\r\nselect username,name,id,guessid,guess,abs(guess-565.3114669800) as guessdiff,guess.ts  from guess,user where userno=id and roundno=1 and gameno=1 order by guessdiff, guess.ts limit 1;\r\n\r\n','2007-02-01','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(176,16,'DAM','To update a guess, first check for an existing guess (plug in game, round and user values):\r\nselect * from guess where roundno=1 and gameno=1 and userno=16; OR\r\n select count(*) from guess where roundno=1 and gameno=1 and userno=16;\r\nif the count>0 then you update it (plug in guess, roundno, gameno and userno):\r\n\r\n update guess set guess=499.3818239 where roundno=1 and gameno=1 and userno=16;\r\n\r\nOtherwise insert the guess (plug in guess, roundno, gameno and userno) : \r\ninsert guess (gameno,roundno,userno,guess) values (1,1,24,367.286679508248);\r\n','2007-02-01','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(177,4,'DAM','I\'m thinking that redwall should be called \"turnstyle.org\". The idea for the front page that I have is that it\'s two columns. The header is across the top with some navigation stuff (including register and login) just below that.  \r\n\r\nThe left column is 600 pix wide with \"about turnstyle\", a link to the forum, a \"From the GM\" which is, essentiall, the site master\'s blog (that would be me) with a link to another forum below that. \r\n\r\nThe right column is 300 pix wide and it has a list of games on the site. Each game title is accompanied with 30 words of description and a link to the full marketing site for the game. Below that is a list of the game instances. Running games have a link to their public page; starting game have a link to the sign up page. \r\n\r\nThe marketing pages have a game name with a 600 pixel column of the game description on the left (with a link to the rules and to design notes from the author, if a available) and a list of the games (first the starting games, then the running games) on the right. The running games link to the public page, the staring games link to the signup page. (By the way, it\'s possible that you can sign up for running games; this would be on the public page, as well). \r\n\r\nHmm, you must be logged in to sign up. More thought is needed. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRef\r\nD:\\My Documents\\My Pictures\\2007-02-13\\Scan10014.JPG\r\nD:\\My Documents\\My Pictures\\2007-02-13\\Scan10015.JPG','2007-02-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(178,16,'DAM','WE need a \"hall of fame\" display\r\n select username,count(roundno) as wins ,roundno from guessround,rwuser where id=winner and gameno=1 group by username order by wins desc,roundno desc limit 10;\r\n\r\nTHis is the list of people who have played most\r\nselect username,count(roundno) as  plays from guessguess,rwuser where id=userno and gameno=1 group by username order by plays desc limit 10;','2007-02-21','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(179,16,'DAM','Email the password and username\r\n\r\ntest lowercase username against lower case username\r\n\r\nties: explain what we\'re doing\r\nchange ties to go to the LATEST person rather than the earliest; this for 2 reasons: first, it will encourage people to come back to the site, second it prevents the shills from winning as much.\r\n\r\nEmail me every round end with # of players, winner, winning guess and average\r\n\r\nAdd some stats about how many players are playing that only I can see.','2007-02-22','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(180,50,'DAM','On the subject of an application to schedule things, it seems pretty\r\nstraight-forward. Imagine you have a list of dates from each person\r\nthat DON\'T work for that person (never mind how you get them -- that\'s\r\na UI detail for now).\r\n\r\nIf you take the range of dates that are permissible (some day this\r\nyear or this month or whatever) and count how many \"noes\" you have for\r\neach day you can then make a list of the days with 0 noes and 1 noes\r\nand so on. The meeting should be scheduled on a day with 0 noes or, if\r\nthat\'s not possible, it either can\'t be scheduled or can be scheduled\r\non the day with the fewest noes to leave out the minimum number of\r\npeople.\r\n\r\nThere\'s a bunch of algorithmic details in there (how to get a list of\r\ndays from a date range, how to get the \"noes\" from a list of \"yeses\",\r\nhow to do the counting and so forth. But there\'s nothing there that\r\nyou can\'t do in PHP (or a Turing Machine for that matter).\r\n\r\nYou can then add lots of bells and whistles, if you want. You can\r\naccept input on days that people would prefer and days they would\r\nprefer not to have (but will do if necessary). You can have a \"master\"\r\nfor whom a \"no\" means that you can\'t have it even if it\'s the day with\r\nthe fewest noes. You can have an email that tells everyone what days\r\nare preventing a meeting and asking them to reconsider. And so forth.\r\n\r\nAs to the UI, the easiest way to do it is to have a list of dates with\r\na check box (or series of radio buttons for various preferences). The\r\nuser checks off all the dates they can make it, we put it in a\r\ndatabase and, when everyone has responded, the program runs (or when a\r\ncertain amount of time elapses).\r\n\r\nYou can do the same thing in the shape of a calendar if you would\r\nprefer but I\'m sure you can see that it\'s the same solution.\r\n\r\nObviously, you have to have some way to set parameters about the\r\nmeeting (does it have to be March or can be it March through July or\r\nwhatever) along with a description and other niceties.\r\n\r\nThis all begs the question that Dave alluded to as to whether you can\r\ntrust the answers. I submit that if you can\'t trust the answers then\r\nthere is no possible solution. I would allow people to schedule the\r\nthing and if they found the resulting date to be bad they would miss\r\nthe meeting.\r\n','2007-03-09','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(181,50,'DAM','As I understand it, we added 3 things to my original design\r\n1) An answer of not yes or no but \"maybe\". This, presumably, would be the answer you would give on a day that you really don\'t want to do the meeting but you will do the meeting if there is no other choice.\r\n\r\n2) The idea that there are 2 groups of people: the people who MUST be at the meeting and the people who CAN be at the meeting. \r\n\r\n3) The concept of a quorum which is that there is some group of people who must be represented in the meeting to some minimum degree in order for the meeting to be successful. For example there might be a membership who has to have at least (say) 20 people present in order for the meeting to be valid. \r\n\r\nIn addition we agreed that the meeting organizer would set the following things:\r\n- The data range in which the meeting would occur (\"when\").\r\n- The list of people in each category (must come, may come, quorum) as well as the number of the quorum (which would be zero if we\'re not using that aspect).\r\n- The location of the meeting.\r\n- The time of the meeting.\r\n- The purpose of the meeting (that is, a description). \r\n\r\n\r\n','2007-03-12','2007-04-21 23:43:07'),(182,51,'DAM','This lists all the games won since the end of 2006. I assume that you would use = and a specific date.\r\n\r\nselect eventdate,game,gamesname,playername,result from events,winlose,players,games where gameid=game and playerid=player and gameeventid=eventid and result=\'win\' and venue=1 and eventdate>\"2006-12-31\";\r\n','2007-03-12','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(183,51,'DAM','This lists the game dates for all the parties\r\nselect * from events where venue=1 group by eventdate order by eventdate;\r\n\r\n','2007-03-12','2007-07-15 07:29:44'),(184,51,'DAM','This is the list of players at this event\r\nselect eventdate,playername from events,winlose,players where playerid=player and gameeventid=eventid  and venue=1 and eventdate=\"2007-02-10\" group by player;\r\n','2007-03-12','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(185,51,'DAM','This is the list of quotes from that party, if any.\r\n\r\nselect * from partyquotes where quotedate=\"2007-03-10\";\r\n','2007-03-12','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(186,52,'DAM','base for games\r\n\r\nselect that will give you all the games played and who won:\r\nselect gamesname,playername,result,eventdate from winlose,events,games,players where gameid=game and playerid=player and eventid=gameeventid;\r\n\r\nselect eventdate,gamesname from events,games where gameid=game;\r\n\r\n\r\nAdd a page to edit games\r\nAdd a page to edit details of players\r\ndo a page that whos win/loss record for each player\r\nlist of all games with players (mark winners somehow)\r\nlist all the players with win/loss records\r\nlist all games with how often they\'ve been played\r\n\r\n\r\nselect that will give you all the games played and who won:\r\nselect gamesname,playername,result,eventdate from winlose,events,games,players\r\nwhere gameid=game and playerid=player and eventid=gameeventid;\r\n\r\nselect eventdate,gamesname from events,games where gameid=game;\r\n\r\nHave a page that edits games on the right and players on the left; call this\r\n\"detail.php\"\r\n\r\nHave a page that has a bar graph of the win/loss record for each player, in\r\norder by bigest loser,  a pie chart that shows all the losses and who had\r\nthem, another that shows all the wins and who had them and, at the bottom, a\r\nlist of all the games, who played and who won\r\n\r\n(I wish I could draw here)\r\n\r\nA  B\r\nA        B\r\nA        C\r\nA        C\r\nDDDDDD\r\nDDDDDD\r\nDDDDDD\r\nDDDDDD\r\n\r\nA is a vertical bar graph showing players and their win/loses.\r\nB is a pie chart showing losses\r\nC is a pie chart showing wins\r\nD is a text listing of every game, it\'s date and it\'s players, with the\r\nwinners marked.\r\n\r\na,b and c can be constructed from information in the following 3 selects:\r\n\r\n select count(*) from winlose where player=23 and result=\'lose\';\r\n\r\n\r\nGame Database\r\n Game number\r\n Game Name\r\n Game Description\r\n Game URL\r\n Max Players\r\n TimeStamp\r\n\r\ncreate table games (\r\ngameid int primary key auto_increment not null,\r\ngamesname varchar(30) not null,\r\ndescription text,\r\nurl tinytext,\r\nmaxplayers int,\r\ngametstamp timestamp);\r\n\r\nPlayer Database\r\n Player Number\r\n Player Name\r\n Player Email\r\n TimeStamp\r\n\r\ncreate table players (\r\nplayerid int primary key auto_increment not null,\r\nplayername varchar(30) not null,\r\nemail tinytext,\r\nplayertstamp timestamp);\r\n\r\n\r\nGame Event Database\r\n Game Event Number\r\n Event Date\r\n Game Number\r\n TimeStamp\r\n\r\ncreate table events (\r\neventid int primary key auto_increment not null,\r\neventdate date,\r\ngame int,\r\ntstamp timestamp);\r\n\r\nWinLose Database\r\n Game Event Number\r\n Player Number\r\n Result (win/lose/resign)\r\n TimeStamp\r\n\r\ncreate table winlose (\r\ngameeventid int  not null,\r\nplayer int not null,\r\nresult enum(\'win\',\'lose\',\'resign\'),\r\ntstamp timestamp);\r\n\r\n ----------\r\n Page\r\n\r\n Game Section\r\n  Game Name\r\n  Game Description\r\n  Game URL\r\n  Max Players\r\n\r\n\r\n Player Section\r\n  Player Name\r\n  Player Email\r\n\r\n Game Event Section\r\n  Event Date (default today)\r\n  Event Game (pulldown)\r\n  Player/result\r\n  Player/Result\r\n  Player/Result (*MaxPlayers)\r\n ==================\r\n insert players (playername,email) values\r\n (\'Dave Menconi\',\'davem@menconi.com\'),\r\n (\'Dorita Menconi\',\'dorita@menconi.com\'),\r\n (\'Janine Menconi\',\'janine@menconi.com\'),\r\n(\'Bill Beckerman\',\'BillBeckerman@earthlink.net\'),\r\n(\'Scott Nelson\',\'scott@spamwolf.com\'),\r\n(\'Mike Jones\',\'mfj@ieee.org\'),\r\n(\'Mike Janousek\',\'MikeJanousek@earthlink.com\'),\r\n(\'Ray Fischer\',\'RFischer@sonic.net\'),\r\n(\'Sabrina Nelson\',\'sabrina@alttv1.com\'),\r\n(\'TeeJe\',\'teeje@timebender.com\'),\r\n(\'Mike Edwards\',\'mike@he.net\'),\r\n(\'Kurt\',\'mailkurt@swimclub.com\'),\r\n(\'Ron Flynt\',\'Ron.Flynt@abbott.com\') ;\r\n\r\ninsert games (gamesname, maxplayers) values\r\n(\'Puerto Rico\',\'5\'),\r\n(\'Wiz War\',\'4\'),\r\n(\'Merchant of Venus\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Modern Art\',\'5\'),\r\n(\'Vinci\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Wizard Quest\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Chaos Marauders\',\'4\'),\r\n(\'Star Traders\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Quirks\',\'4\'),\r\n(\'Mississippi Queen\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Im The Boss\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Basari\',\'4\'),\r\n(\'Awful Green Things From Outer Space\',\'2\'),\r\n(\'Snits!\',\'4\'),\r\n(\'Munchkin\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Freight Train\',\'4\'),\r\n(\'Alhambra\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Acquire\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Condattiere\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Union Pacific\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Samakand\',\'5\'),\r\n(\'Risk\',\'6\'),\r\n(\'Fluxx\',\'10\'),\r\n(\'Democrazy\',\'10\'),\r\n(\'Bohnanza\',\'7\'),\r\n(\'Bang\',\'7\');\r\n','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(187,52,'DAM','select gamesname,eventid,eventdate, count(game) as count from events,games where game=gameid group by eventdate,gamesname order by gamesname;\r\n\r\nThis gives a list of games we such that each game appears not more than once per party. SO the number of times each game appears in this list is it\'s \"score\" such that it gets no extra points for being played more than once in a games party. Thus Zendo would get a score of 1 not 3 and fluxx gets only 6 instead of 14.\r\n\r\nGet a list of all the game we have. Then step through each of them and do this select with the addition of a \"where game=$thisgame\" with $thisgame being one game from the list. The num rows is the score for the game. Obviously, we\'ll want to limit the scope of the query.\r\n\r\nThe score of the game is the number of records.\r\nfuction gamescore(){\r\n    global $dbhost, $dbuser, $dbpass, $gamestable,$dbname;\r\n        $link = make_mysql_connect($dbhost, $dbuser, $dbpass, $dbname);\r\n\r\n        $gamescore = array();\r\n        $games = array();\r\n        $gameselect = \"select gameid,gamesname from games\";\r\n        $result = mysql_query($sql,$link) or die(mysql_error());\r\n    $num_rows = mysql_num_rows($result);\r\n        if ($num_rows>0){\r\n                while ($games[]=mysql_fetch_array($result,MYSQL_ASSOC)){;}\r\n            array_pop($games);\r\n        }\r\n        foreach ($games as $game){\r\n                $gameid=$game[\'gameid\'];\r\n                $gamename = $game[\'gamesname\'];\r\n                $scoreselect = \"select gamesname,eventid,eventdate, count(game) as count from events,games where game=gameid and game=\'\".$gameid.\"\' group by eventdate,gamesname order by gamesname\";\r\n                $result = mysql_query($sql,$link) or die(mysql_error());\r\n        $num_rows = mysql_num_rows($result);\r\n                $gamescore[$gamename] = $num_rows;\r\n        }\r\n        return $gamescore;\r\n}\r\n\r\n','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(188,52,'DAM','select gamesname,playername,result,eventdate,gameeventid,events.tstamp from winlose,events,players,games  where gameeventid=eventid and playerid=player and gameid=game;\r\n\r\nselect gamesname,playername,result,eventdate,gameeventid,events.tstamp from winlose,events,players,games  where gameeventid=eventid and playerid=player and gameid=game and eventdate>\'2005-02-12\';\r\n\r\nselect gamesname,playername,result,eventdate,gameeventid,events.tstamp from winlose,events,players,games  where gameeventid=eventid and playerid=player and gameid=game and eventdate>\'2005-02-12\' and result=\'win\';\r\nd','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(189,52,'DAM','// ----- Expense -----\r\n$PGExpense = new PowerGraphic;\r\n$PGExpense->title     = \'Expenses\';\r\n$PGExpense->axis_x    = \'Category\';\r\n$PGExpense->axis_y    = \'US$\';\r\n$PGExpense->graphic_1 = \"Year \" . $year;\r\n$PGExpense->graphic_2 = \"Year \" . $lastyear;\r\n$PGExpense->type      = $graphtype;\r\n$PGExpense->skin      = 1;\r\n$PGExpense->credits   = 0;\r\n$PGExpense->x[] = \'Total Compensation\';\r\n$PGExpense->y[] = $data[$year][\'TotalCompensation\'];\r\n$PGExpense->z[] = $data[$lastyear][\'TotalCompensation\'];\r\n$PGExpense->x[] = \'Total Building & Grounds\';\r\n$PGExpense->y[] = $data[$year][\'TotalBuildingAndGrounds\'];\r\n$PGExpense->z[] = $data[$lastyear][\'TotalBuildingAndGrounds\'];\r\n$PGExpense->x[] = \'Total Operations\';\r\n$PGExpense->y[] = $data[$year][\'TotalOperations\'];\r\n$PGExpense->z[] = $data[$lastyear][\'TotalOperations\'];\r\n$PGExpense->x[] = \'Total Travel\';\r\n$PGExpense->y[] = $data[$year][\'TotalTravel\'];\r\n$PGExpense->z[] = $data[$lastyear][\'TotalTravel\'];\r\n$PGExpense->x[] = \'Total Project Expense\';\r\n$PGExpense->y[] = $data[$year][\'TotalProjectExpense\'];\r\n$PGExpense->z[] = $data[$lastyear][\'TotalProjectExpense\'];\r\n$expensegraph = $PGExpense->create_query_string();\r\n\r\n//echo \'<img src=\"class.graphic.php?\' . $PGIncome->create_query_string() . \'\" bo\r\nrder=\"1\" alt=\"\" /> <br /><br />\';\r\n//$PGIncome->type=5;\r\n//echo \'<img src=\"class.graphic.php?\' . $PGIncome->create_query_string() . \'\" bo\r\nrder=\"1\" alt=\"\" /> <br /><br />\';\r\n//$PGIncome->type=6;\r\n//echo \'<img src=\"class.graphic.php?\' . $PGIncome->create_query_string() . \'\" bo\r\nrder=\"1\" alt=\"\" /> <br /><br />\';\r\n---------------------------------\r\n\r\n$PGTotals = new PowerGraphic;\r\n$PGTotals->title     = \'Totals\';\r\n$PGTotals->axis_x    = \'Year\';\r\n$PGTotals->axis_y    = \'US$\';\r\n$PGTotals->graphic_1 = \"Expenses\";\r\n$PGTotals->graphic_2 = \"Revenue\";\r\n$PGTotals->type      = 2;\r\n$PGTotals->skin      = 1;\r\n$PGTotals->credits   = 0;\r\n$PGTotals->x[] = $year;\r\n$PGTotals->y[] = $data[$year][\'TotalExpenses\'];\r\n$PGTotals->z[] = $data[$year][\'TotalRevenue\'];\r\n$PGTotals->x[] = $lastyear;\r\n$PGTotals->y[] = $data[$lastyear][\'TotalExpenses\'];\r\n$PGTotals->z[] = $data[$lastyear][\'TotalRevenue\'];\r\n$totalgraph = \"<img src=\\\"class.graphic.php?\" . $PGTotals->create_query_string()\r\n;\r\n$totalgraph .= \'\" border=\"0\" alt=\"\" /> \';\r\n','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(190,52,'DAM','select eventdate,gamesname from events,games where gameid=game;\r\n','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(191,52,'DAM','mysql> desc events;\r\n+-----------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n| Field     | Type          | Null | Key | Default | Extra          |\r\n+-----------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n| eventid   | int(11)       |      | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment |\r\n| eventdate | date          | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n| game      | int(11)       | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n| venue     | int(11)       | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n| tstamp    | timestamp(14) | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n+-----------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n5 rows in set (0.00 sec)\r\nmysql> desc winlose;\r\n+-------------+--------------------+------+-----+---------+-----+\r\n| Field       | Type               | Null | Key | Default |Extra|\r\n+-------------+--------------------+------+-----+---------+-----+\r\n| gameeventid | int(11)            |      |     | 0       |     |\r\n| player      | int(11)            |      |     | 0       |     |\r\n| result      | enum(\'win\',\'lose\', |      |     |         |     |\r\n|             |  \'resign\',\'last\')  | YES  |     | NULL    |     |\r\n| tstamp      | timestamp(14)      | YES  |     | NULL    |     |\r\n+-------------+--------------------+------+-----+---------+-----+\r\n4 rows in set (0.00 sec)\r\n\r\n','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(192,52,'DAM','This is the total games that have been played\r\nselect count(*) from events where eventdate<\'2007-12-31\' and eventdate>\'2007-1-1\';\r\nThis is the number of times each game was played\r\n select gameid,gamesname,count(gameid) as count from events,games where gameid=game and eventdate<\'2007-12-31\' and eventdate>\'2007-1-1\' group by game order by count;\r\n\r\n','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(193,52,'DAM','First, do this. This is the max number of plays for any game.\r\nselect count(gameid)+1 as count  from events,games where gameid=game and eventdate<\'2007-12-31\' and eventdate>\'2007-1-1\' group by game order by count desc limit 1;\r\n\r\nThen do this, substituting the first 10 (in both places) for the value from the first calc\r\n select gameid,gamesname,duration, 10-count(gameid) as davescale,duration*(10-count(gameid)) as jeffscale,count(gameid) as count from events,games where gameid=game and eventdate<\'2007-12-31\' and eventdate>\'2007-1-1\' group by game order by davescale;\r\n','2007-03-13','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(194,51,'DAM','I\'d like it to show\r\n- how many players\r\n- what games, who won each game\r\n- any quotes\r\n- how many games each player won (which, by coincidence, is their requested donation to the kitty)\r\n- Who the biggest loser at the party was\r\n- what the weights of all the games now are\r\n- what the top 5 games are\r\n- what the top 3 biggest losers are\r\n','2007-03-14','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(195,52,'DAM','I don\'t like any of the ideas I\'ve come up with for this. My current best thinking is to have a value, say from 1-9, assigned to each game. This is done each time we go to display the standings. The number is 10- the number of times the game has been played since the beginning of time or 1, whichever is greater. (Put another way, if the game has been played 9 or few times it\'s 10- times played, otherwise it\'s 1). \r\n\r\nThere are several problems with this. This means that every time we play a game it becomes much less valuable. 1-9 isn\'t a very broad base (the durations range from 5 to 120 minutes or more which is 24:1. Finally, we\'re talking about changing the database here! Ewe-ick!\r\n\r\nMaybe having it be 20 or 30 instead of 10 would be good. Also, what if we calculated it based on the beginning of the year. That way you\'re looking for a game that has never been played but that you can play a lot!\r\n\r\n','2007-03-14','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(196,50,'DAM','I\'d like to use acceptance categories of \"yes,\" \"no,\" and\r\n\"preferred.\" That way we\'re stating things positively as well as\r\nworking towards maximizing preferred dates.\r\n\r\n\"Preferred\" means that, if we have multiple days that work, do the one with the most \"preferred\" days in it. ','2007-03-17','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(197,50,'DAM','We need better date functions. Perhaps the ability to take dates from an arbitrary format (the code figures out what the format is based on whether it has -,/ or nothing) to the array and then the ability to go from the array to various forms. This is all very iffy because it\'s hard to tell what 5/6/07 means so we have to make SOME assumptions. Mainly we have to pick whether it\'s date/mo or mo/date. ICK.\r\n\r\nNext we have to write a routine that, given an array (or a string) with date ranges (either a single date or a date separated by dashes) we make a complete list of all the dates that are mentioned in the array. \r\n\r\nNow a routine that, given a date list will give us a date range from the very earliest date to the vary latest date. \r\n\r\nNext we write a date list inverter. Given a list of dates and a date range that encompasses them, give us the list of dates NOT on the list. \r\n\r\nThe heart of the system is routine that will take a list of dates and an array of list of dates (one list per person) and count how many times each date is found on all the lists. \r\n\r\n','2007-03-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(198,50,'DAM','Ok, first we have to create the meeting template. This is all the things that we discussed before but, most notably, the date range and the list of possible attendees. (put this in a database)\r\n\r\nNow we open up a page for all those attendees that allow them to accept or reject the dates. Each time they do this we add that date to a list. \r\n\r\nAt some point (not sure when) we run a routine that processes the meeting. First, it gets the meeting information. First it creates a list of dates for each person that they DON\'T want. Then it creates a list of ','2007-03-18','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(199,50,'DAM','I need an algorithm that, given a start and end date, will generate a list of all the dates in between. \r\nAccording to the php cookbook (pg61, section 3.10) you can use strtotime to add or suptract arbitrary date amounts. Using epoch time might be better for me. \r\n\r\nYou translate the start and end dates to epoch time and then you add 86400 seconds (seconds in a day) to it to get the next day and convert it back to a date. \r\n\r\nMay have trouble crossing the end of february boundary and/or the end of year boundary. Also, Daylight savings time will be a problem so we should translate this whole thing into UTC and back (or can we ignore it -- we only care about DAYs not hours -- if we look at noon of each day).\r\n\r\nWe can also figure out how many days will be on our list by using recipe 3.5 on page 52: finding the difference in two dates. It says to convert to epoch time and then subtract the last from the first (giving seconds) and then convert to days, hours, minutes and seconds using the code they provide (divide by 86400).\r\n','2007-03-23','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(200,50,'DAM','WE should use getdate() to get the time parts. If we want to write our own parser, we should use the array format that getdate returns. see table 3-1 on page 44 of PHP Cookbook.\r\n Reason: getdate conveniently converts from epoch to that array. \r\n\r\n3.2 converts from parts to epock 3.3 converts back (uses getdate()). \r\nDate can be used to convert.','2007-03-23','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(201,4,'DAM','Databases\r\nplayers\r\ngames\r\ninstances\r\ngm message\r\n\r\ngames \r\n  id int\r\n  name\r\n  short descr\r\n  market url (url for the marketing page for this game)\r\n  ts\r\n\r\ninstances\r\n  id \r\n  name\r\n  gameno\r\n  inveral_sec (interval in seconds between one turn and the next)\r\n  time_of_day (this is the time of day we want to run the turn)\r\n  paths to 3 executables (start, run, end)\r\n  ts  \r\n','2007-03-24','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(202,53,'DAM','date range -- period over which we\'re looking at the data\r\ninterval -- period in which we\'re counting, as in hits per HOUR\r\nstats -- hits and unique hits are the most interesting to collect\r\ndate ranges should probably be in weeks (monday through sunday)\r\n\r\nprobably also want to be able to look at specific weeks and/or averages over a week','2007-03-25','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(203,4,'DAM',' CREATE TABLE `tsgame` (\r\n`gameid` int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment,\r\n`gamename` tinytext,\r\n`shortdesc` tinytext,\r\nmarketurl tinytext,\r\n`ts` timestamp(14) NOT NULL,\r\nPRIMARY KEY  (`gameid`)\r\n    );\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE tsinstance (\r\n  instid int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment,\r\n  instgameno int not null,\r\n  instname tinytext,\r\n  interval_sec int default 86400,\r\n  timeofday time,\r\n  startpath tinytext,\r\n  parsepath tinytext,\r\n  runpath tinytext,\r\n  endpath tinytext,\r\n  ts timestamp(14) NOT NULL,\r\n  PRIMARY KEY  (instid)\r\n);','2007-03-25','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(204,50,'DAM','Different kinds of dates )and their names)\r\n3/27/07 m/d/y\r\n03/27/07 M/D/y\r\n03/27/2007 M/D/Y\r\n03-27-2007 M-D-Y\r\n03272007   MDY\r\n2007-03-27 Y-D-M\r\n20070327182340 YMDT\r\n27-Mar-07 D-Mon-y\r\n27-Mar-2007 D-Mon-Y\r\n27/03/2007 D/M/Y (europe?)\r\n03 27 07 (M D Y)\r\nThe idea is that I want a routine that will detect all of these and parse them, making assumptions as necessary but then you can override by handing the routine the name. No name=assumptions. \r\nThe problem is that many of them can\'t be differentiated. The killer id D/M/Y vs M/D/Y!\r\n\r\nStart by replacing. Replace / with -, replace space with -, replace comman with -, replace -- with -. Then check to see if there are any letters and, if so, replace the month names (3 char only) with the number. \r\n\r\nThen we remove. Remove everything but - and numbers. Just strip it out. \r\n\r\nNow comes the guesswork. Parse it out into three variables, s1, s2 and s3. Whichever one is 4 digits, make that the date and remove it, leaving s1 and s2. Now, s1 is the day and s2 is the month. If s3 is still there, it\'s the year. ','2007-03-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(205,54,'DAM','I\'d like to have 2 routines that parse things into tables. Both take arrays of assoc arrays and both take an assoc array that relates the keys in the other to headers. \r\n\r\nOne puts the whole mess in one giant table like company list or game list. This one is for a list of complicated things, like a game. Sorting paging and filtering are all necessary. This is a generalization of existing code. \r\n\r\nThe other creates multiple columns. This one is for simple lists like the mediation log. It takes a \"columns\" param which tells it how many columns.\r\n\r\nIt takes the count of the rows and divides by columns and rounds up (call this h). It creates a string and puts the <table> header into it, followed by the header for the far left <table>. THen it starts a loop 0-count on i. If i%h=0 and i!=0 then we close out the table we\'re on and start another table. At the bottom we close out the last table and the main table and we\'re done. ','2007-03-27','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(206,4,'DAM','The numbers game gets it\'s own page with links to instance pages. \r\n\r\nThe important issue here is where we draw the line between public views and players. In the case of the numbers game the only thing that\'s really private is the users guess and that the user\'s personal history. If we made those two sections conditional we could show the same page for public and private -- but is that in line with Turnstyle?\r\n\r\nGame instances:\r\npast (complete) present (running)  and future (starting) games \r\nWe show this with starting games at the top, present games in the middle and past games running off the edge. \r\nthere are potentially signup,  game (orders) pages and rail (non-player, public) pages\r\n\r\nfor past games there are rail pages that show the status of the game at the end (this might be special in that we\'ll show the winners)\r\n\r\n\r\ndefine things somewhere on the page (the meaning of \"game\" \"rail\" and \"signup\" -- maybe \"player\" \"public\" and \"signup\" or \"join\")\r\n\r\n','2007-04-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(207,4,'DAM','I\'m finding this hard to do. Let\'s try this:\r\nfor the numbers game (specifically) there are no starting games or signup pages or ending games. There are only running games. So let\'s focus on that. \r\n\r\nThe first thing is that you need to be signed up on turnstyle. If you have a turnstyle cookie, you are authenticated anywhere. In the numbers game you are also authorized anywhere.\r\n\r\nIf you are not signed up, you may also get to the \"stats\" page and the marketing page. \r\n\r\nSo we have one page everyone can get to (marketing) which I think is done now. Then, for each game, we have 2 more pages, one that everyone to get to and one that you must log in to get to. \r\n\r\nThe former is essentially written, although a lot of stuff needs to be teased out of it. \r\n\r\nThe latter needs to be changed structurely but it\'s basically working. Fundamentally, you have turn entry (with private turn information), a link to the marketing page, a link to the turnstyle games page. \r\n\r\n','2007-04-10','2007-04-11 00:59:56'),(218,15,'DAM','Game one has one a simple relationship among all the cities: it\'s one turn from any city to any other city.\r\n\r\nGame two has a bit more complexity: it is a variable number of turns. The map is fixed (it is the medieval world). \r\n\r\nGame three has a large number of planets and a small number of\r\nempty nodes (900 and 100 is my first thought but that\'s probably way\r\ntoo large). Each of these is considered a node in a graph and then we\r\ngenerate random edges until we have only one connected graph that\r\nincludes all the nodes. Empty nodes are useless by themselves but if\r\nthey have more than one edge they form connection points. One empty\r\nnode is selected to be the \"Old Ones\'Gateway\". \r\nIf you pay a large sum of money you get to go through to...\r\n\r\n...Game four is exactly like game 3 right up to the Old Ones\' Gateway which leads to game five. And so on...\r\n\r\n\r\nFor a real trip, let players buy weapons in game 4 and beyond.\r\nIf you \"own\" a world (have weapons on it) you can define who can trade\r\nand you can specify a tax on all trades. You can also determine who\r\njumps through the worm holes that are there. Obviously you have to be\r\nable to force an attack through a worm hole in either direction. Have\r\nto come up with some simple but interesting combat system. Probably\r\nbased on simple \"firepower points\". \r\nHow about this: you can move all the fp in one node to an\r\nadjacent node. If the node is occupied, and one of you has specified\r\nthe other as hostile, we count up the points. We flip a coin once each\r\nfor every one of the smaller groups points. Heads he loses a point;\r\ntails the other guy loses one. Then we take what\'s left of the smaller\r\nforce and the rest of the bigger force and fight them. If both sides\r\nstill have points, we start over. \r\nconsider adding some bonus for defending a worm hole. \r\n\r\n','2000-05-05','2007-04-11 15:16:22'),(219,15,'DAM','Game name : Traders of the Dark Galaxy                                       \r\n\r\n\r\nThe game will have 5 groups of commodities, each with 20 base\r\nprices. The same 20 prices will be repeated in each group. With 1-10\r\nplayers we\'ll have the first group (20 commodities), as you add another\r\n10 players, we add another group of 20 commodities until we hit 50\r\nplayers and 100 commodities. We always have as many cities as\r\ncommodities. This assumes that the number of commodities (and cities)\r\nis twice the number of players. \r\nThere also needs to be some way to remove cities and\r\ncommodities as players quit so that the game scales smoothly down even\r\nas it scales smoothly up. Perhaps we simply remove some commodities and\r\ncities when the number gets to a certain point. Or maybe we can come up\r\nwith a way that makes a commodity slot in a city not regenerate after\r\nit dies. \r\nThe price of a commodity is initially set to the base price\r\ntimes 2D6 (the multiplier) plus or minus a random number (the fuzz)\r\nbetween 0-1 -- add it to demand prices and subtract it from sale\r\nprices. Every turn, as the multiplier goes up and down, we add or\r\nsubtract a new fuzz number. This makes it harder to tell how the system\r\nworks, adds interest and makes the whole thing fractionally more\r\nprofitable.\r\n\r\nTrading Game 0\r\n\r\nlevel 1 2 cities per player, 1 com/city, all cities one turn apart, each city has 5 want, 5 offer\r\n\r\nlevel 2 3 cities per player, each citie is some distance from all others, based on map\r\n\r\nlevel 3, 800 planets with randomly connected\r\n\r\n','2000-05-30','2007-04-11 15:16:44'),(220,15,'DAM','Spies cost 1,10,100,1000,10000,100000. Each spy has associated\r\nwith it how many spies were bought. Each counterspy nullifies the spy\r\nwith the highest number associated with it. A successful spy tells you\r\nall the commodities in a city. A counterspy protects all the\r\ncommodities in the city.\r\n\r\nBase values of commodities are\r\n\r\n1 3 5 7 11 13 19 31 61 137 263 527 1001 1967 3095 8379 17457 39205 67350 97630\r\n\r\n\r\nWe could add a fudge factor to this to get the other ones but I\r\ndon\'t think the players will be able to see the base factor. This is\r\nessentially the powers of two except that 11 and 13 are inserted\r\nbetween 8 and 16 to give the players more low numbers. \r\n','2000-05-31','2007-04-11 15:17:03'),(216,15,'DAM','Using the formula p\'=p^1.03 seems to work pretty well. And\r\nalthough I like 2d6 better than 1d12, the two dice keep the average\r\npercentage return on investment down to 100% compared with the 1d12\'s\r\n~170%! This method doesn\'t seem to favor any particular price range\r\n(which is one of the goals, since there\'s no reason why rich people\r\nshould get THAT much richer).\r\n','1999-11-08','2007-04-11 15:15:49'),(217,15,'DAM','The game consists of cities and players and commodities. \r\n\r\n\r\n* Every player has: \r\n\r\n*  a name, \r\n*  a number, \r\n*  a password, \r\n*  an amount of money, \r\n*  a set of ships (nominally one)\r\n*  a set of warehouses (nominaly one)\r\n*  a set of spies\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n* Each ship has some cargoes (nominally one)\r\n* Each warehouse has some cargoes (nominally two)\r\n* Each spy has a city \r\n\r\n \r\n* Every city has:\r\n\r\n*  a set of warehouses (nominally one)\r\n*  a harbor with ships in it\r\n*  a commercial district which has commodities for sale and on demand \r\n*  a set of spies\r\n\r\n* Every commodity for sale has a type, a price and a quantity\r\n* Every commodity on demand has a type a price and a quantity\r\n* Every spy has an owner  and a price\r\n* Every ship has an owner\r\n\r\n\r\nThere is a special city, called \"in transit\" which is where we place\r\nships after they leave a city but before they get to the next one. This\r\nhas the ship number, the city left, the city moving toward, and the\r\ndestination turn.\r\n\r\nThere is also a map of the distance relationships among all the\r\ncities. For that matter, there is a list of how many on demand and for\r\nsale commodities every city has.\r\n\r\n(I should mention that spies cost 1,2,4,8,16,32,64,128... etc\r\nand can be placed anywhere. They have to be bought again. A spy will\r\ntell you all about the commodities and transactions in a particular\r\ncity. You can also use them as counter-spies but then they don\'t give\r\nyou any information. A counter spy will nullify the spy of an enemy\r\nthat is in the same town; the spy that is picked is the spy that is\r\nmost expensiv. The most expensive spy is least effective....)\r\n','2000-05-05','2007-04-11 15:17:17'),(215,15,'DAM','Let\'s say that there are always 100 cities and 100 commodities.\r\n\r\nEach city has 6 things it buys and 6 things it sells. Bought commodities are randomly selected. The sold commodities are randomly selected EXCEPT that a commodity that is already bought at that city is selected again (on average, this will happen once in 16 selections).\r\n\r\nEvery commodity has a multiplier associated with it. The multipliers might be the first 100 prime numbers (starting with 1) -- this is a pretty good distributions. In any case, there should be a lot of low multipliers compared to the higher multipliers, like in prime numbers.\r\n\r\nNow you roll 2 6 sided dice (the purpose of 2d6 instead 1d12 is that we want to make it less likely that we\'ll have things being bought for way less than they are being sold for). For the sell price, subtract 1. For the buy price, add one. That\'s the \"base value\". Now multiply the multiplier to the base value to get the actual price. Now pick a number from 1-3. This is the quantity available in the course of a turn for that buy or sell slot. When you\'ve done that for all 100 cities and all 1200 \"slots\" (6 buy slots plus 6 sell slots) you\'ve initialized the game.\r\n\r\nNow, to update this you need to have a storage bin called \"number of transactions\". Prices only change at the end of the turn (after everyone has bought or sold) based on the number of transactions. For slots that buy things, the price changes one step down for every transaction. The price changes one step up if there is no transaction. If the \"base value\" drops below 1 then we reinitialize this commodity according to the algorithm above, being careful not to match any of the commodities that are selling.\r\n\r\nFor selling the exact same algorithm applies but in reverse: prices step up for every transaction and down for no transaction. If the base value goes above some threshhold (12, say) then we reinitialize the commodity.\r\n\r\nAlternative: every commodity has a quantity of 1. If no one buys it goes up to 2. If no one buys again it goes to 3. One more turn of disinterest and it goes back to 1 but at a higher price. When someone buys the quantity goes down. When it reaches 0 it goes back to 3 but at a lower price. This reduces the volatility of the market.\r\n\r\nPerhaps we should start everythign at quantity 2.\r\n\r\nA few other points: all commodities are hidden from anyone who is not present. So you know what\'s going on where your ship and wherehouse are but not elsewhere. Then you have spies. Everyturn there are a random number of spies. Calculate this by rolling 4dN where n is the number of players. Every player specifies how many spies he wants (up to a limit of 3 or 4) and how much he\'s willing to pay (with some minimum). The player who offers the most, gets all his spies. We keep going down until we run out of spies. Players only pay for spies they actually get. Spies report on all the commodities at a city, as well as how much is in the warehouses and something about the ships there.\r\n\r\nEvery turn players may specify a bribe amount. You always pay the bribe amount. If you have a dispute with another player during the turn -- for example, if you offer the same amount for spies or if you and another player both try to buy a rare commodity -- the person who paid the higher bribe wins out. The player who lost out is informed of his loss and to whom he lost but not how much the bribe was.\r\n\r\nNow we \r\n','1999-10-10','2009-05-21 21:56:48'),(214,15,'DAM','Possible names: \"Buy Low, Sell High\", day trader, \r\n\r\n\r\nThis is a trading game set in ancient times around the\r\nmediteranian. There are a large number of cities around the med and\r\nthese are the focus of trading. \r\nThere are as many cities as there are players, no more and no\r\nless. Each player controls one city. In each city there is an auction.\r\nThe citizens of the city will bid on certain commodities if they come\r\nup for auction and the citizens of the city will put up a certain\r\namount of goods for auction. Each city is looking for different goods\r\nand is producing random things. Each city has one thing that it is\r\nknown for producing plus a few other things that it can produce which\r\nchange over time. Each city has some demands that also change over\r\ntime. There are as many products in the world as there are players. So\r\nwhen a player comes or goes the products that are produced and demanded\r\nmust be adjusted. \r\nOnly players that are at a city may participate in the trade\r\nat that city. The fact that a player \"controls\" a city means that the\r\nplayer is always, \"at\" the city, even when his trading fleet is\r\nsomewhere else. Furthermore, a player can warehose as much as he wants\r\nin \"his\" city for for free while in other cities he must rent space. \r\nThe auction system is interesting in that all auctions are\r\nreal-time auctions. That is, the auction is started when the turn is\r\nprocessed but it continues until some specified date (probably when the\r\nnext turn is processed. For example, if turns are processed on\r\nWednesday, all the auctions will start on Wednesday and end the\r\nfollowing Wednesday. Players who may participate (and someone can\r\nalways participate) will put in their bids during the week. There are\r\ntwo ways to do it: first, whoever has the highest bid when the auction\r\nends gets the goods or a \"going, going, gone\" auction in which the\r\nauction automaticly ends when the status of an item doesn\'t change for\r\n3 days (one day each for \"going\" \"going\" and \"gone\").\r\n\r\nA problem presents itself when we consider that almost all\r\nauctions will involve more than one item. Several choices are possible:\r\nwe can have the entire amount of a commodity be one block of stuff. Or\r\nwe can have each individual item be a separate auction. Or we can have\r\nthe auction be in blocks of some convenient number (10 or 100). Or we\r\ncan have a dutch auction in which the N highest bids get the N units of\r\nthe commoidity. \r\n\r\n','1999-09-04','2007-04-11 01:02:53'),(221,15,'DAM','All computer players know about the rules. They can always\r\ngenerate perfect orders. They can also generate slightly incorrect\r\norders. All computer players have perfect information about everything;\r\nthey have access to the game database. They also have their own\r\ndatabase in which they store relevant information.\r\n\r\nCP1 generates perfect orders but doesn\'t consider strategy.\r\nThis player sells a commodity if it can, buys a commodity if it can,\r\nhas a chance to transfer a commodity to it\'s warehouse, has a chance to\r\ndump a commodity (rare) and never quits. It never buys spies.\r\n\r\nCP2 is just like CP1 except that it has a n/100 chance to quit\r\n(where n is the number of turns it\'s been playing since the last time\r\nit quit) and a n/20 chance to join the game (where n is the number of\r\nturns it\'s been out of the game). \r\nCP3 has a strategy:\r\n\r\nB) else if we\'re at our goal city \r\n 1) set our goal to nil\r\n 2) if our hold is empty \r\n  2a) if we have a goal commodity and it\'s here; buy it\r\n  2b) else pick a commodity to buy\r\n 3) else if our hold is full\r\n  3a) sell our commodity if we can\r\n  3b) else find a city where we can sell it\r\n\r\n\r\nB) else If we don\'t have anything in our hold and are not at our goal city\r\n find the best commodity to buy and go there\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCP4 is a loser. it has a 50% chance to dump it\'s cargo, a 50%\r\nchance to leave the game, a 50% chance to come back It buys a cargo if\r\nit can otherwise it moves to a random location.\r\n\r\nAlgorithm to pick a commodity to buy:\r\n 1) Make a list of all the FS commodities\r\n 2) Remove from the list all the commodities that we can\'t afford, including those that we won\'t be able to afford next turn\r\n 3) Remove from the list all the commodities that don\'t have a matching OD\r\n 4) Remove from the list all the commodities who\'s multiplier is <=1\r\n 5) Remove from the list all commodities who\'s matching OD\'s multiplier is >=11\r\n 6) Take the most expensive commodity on the list & find it\'s city\r\n 7) return the commodity, it\'s expected price upon arrival and it\'s city\r\n\r\n\r\nAlgorithm to pick a city to sell in:\r\n 1) if we\'re in a city that ODs this commodity, sell!\r\n 2) make a list of all the OD commodities that match our goal commodity\r\n 3) remove any who\'s multiplier is >=12\r\n 4) take the most expensive OD and find it\'s city\r\n 5) return the city\r\n\r\n','2000-06-03','2007-04-11 15:17:44'),(222,15,'DAM','Although I think Scott is right about wanting to make the more\r\nexpensive shit less profitable, all the stuff below is too complex. How\r\nabout this: just add or sutract a small number from each comodity\'s\r\nmultiplier. Or, better yet, multiply or divide by a fixed percentage.\r\nSay 20% for the very most expensive, going down to 0% at the least\r\nexpensive (how about\r\n0,0,0,0,5,5,5,5,10,10,10,10,15,15,15,15,20,20,20,20). We always add\r\nthis amount to the FS price and subtract this from the OD price. So a\r\ncheap commodity with a base price of 10 and a multiplyer of 4 for the\r\nFS and 8 for the OD would be 40 and 80 giving a 100% profit. But an\r\nexpensive commodity with base of 1000 and the same multipliers would be\r\n4000+20%=4800 and 8000-20%=6400 for a total profit of only 33%.\r\n\r\nScott\'s comments 6/17/00\r\n\r\nScott Nelson suggested three main things. First, more player\r\ninteraction earlier in the game. Second, that spies should have a\r\nrandom chance to be killed by counterspies -- I added that to the\r\nrules. Finally, that rich players should find it increasingly hard to\r\nmake money. \r\nThis could be accomplished by each commodity, in addition to\r\nhaving a base price, also has a number that is added for or subtracted\r\nfrom the die roll multiplier. The idea is that you compress the range\r\n(you add to the sale price and subtract from the buy price). \r\nAnother way to do it is to vary the point at which a commodity\r\nis removed from the game. This would have the duel effect of\r\ncompressing the price for those commodities that have shorter life\r\nspans AND make them rarer. For example, we divide the 20 commodity\r\nprices into 4 groups of 5 each. The first group expires at 0 and 13 (as\r\nper the rules). The second at 1 and 12. The third at 2 and 11. The\r\nfinal group at 3 and 10. This means that, in this last group, you can\r\nnever make more than (9-4 = 5) times your cost while in the first case\r\nyou can make (12-1=11) times your cost. This implies that, although a\r\nwide range of profits are possible, it is more likely for big profits\r\nto be available to poor people than rich people. \r\nA 500% profit is still quite high, however. We should simulate this.\r\n\r\n\r\nAnother possibility is to change both the expire numbers AND the\r\ndice ranges: 1d12 for the first group, 2d6 for the second (possibly too\r\nmuch of a hit), 2d5 for the third and 3d3 for the forth. This could\r\nmean that the absolute prices for items in the low groups could\r\nactually be higher than the items in the high groups! Note, in case it\r\nisn\'t obvious, the effect of more dice. It tends to hold the profit\r\ndown because it tends to force both the OD and FS prices to the middle.\r\nA single die (1D20) will probably have better profits than 2 dice\r\n(2d10). This whole thing is very difficult to test in simulation\r\nbecause, while the range for 3d3 is still 7, you will experience very\r\nfew instances of that range. \r\nupdate 6/3/00\r\n\r\nCopyright 1999 Dave Menconi\r\n','2000-07-03','2007-04-11 15:17:32'),(223,15,'DAM','The formula would be \r\n\r\nODMult = multiplier * 1-(handicap/100) \r\n\r\nFSMult = multiplier * 1+(handicap/100)\r\n\r\n\r\nIf the handicap is 20 the first will give you 80% and the second\r\nwill give you 120%. That means that if you have a multiplier of OD=10\r\nand FS=4 you\'ll end up with OD=8 and FS=4.8. Instead of a 150% ROI (you\r\npay 4 and make 6 back) you have an ROI of 3.2/4.8 1.6/2.4 .8/1.2 .4/.6\r\n','2000-07-14','2007-04-11 15:17:59'),(224,15,'DAM','In the last levels you can expand the game very easily by simply\r\nsplitting the world. First you identify the \"narrowest\" point in the\r\nuniverse. That is, two collections of nodes that have few edges in\r\ncommon (how hard is this to do?). Then you split those two sets of\r\nnodes apart. To each of them you add a bunch more nodes and add edges\r\nuntil it looks right. Then you remove all the traders\' ships that were\r\ntrapped away from their bases and give those traders new ships and\r\n\"insurance money\" equal to the value of thier cargos. Then you start\r\nnew games around each of the two groups of systems.\r\n\r\nThere are two problems with this trick. First, I think it may\r\nbe very hard to do -- how do you find the right nodes (may be moot --\r\nif you simply start at a random node and do a breadth first search\r\nuntil you\'ve touched 1/2 the nodes in the world and then keep all the\r\nedges and nodes as one, breaking all the edges that you didn\'t touch\r\nand thereby splitting world, you would accomplish a \"good enough\"\r\nsplit). Second, it may be very disruptive for the players. Still, it is\r\na way to brighten a very dull game. \r\nPerhaps we should warn players that a large number of ships\r\n(say, 100 or 90) will cause instabilities in the connections between\r\ngalaxies. Then we do the split one or a few links at a time. The\r\nalgorithm would be that you choose a \"central node\" for one group. Then\r\nyou do a depth-first search and step on 1/2 the number of nodes that\r\nexist. Cut the next edge you encounter past the n/2th node. (This just\r\nisn\'t working out). \r\nWait, wait. Here\'s a stateful way to do it: you follow the\r\nalgorithm above -- you identify (but don\'t break) the edges you will\r\nbreak and identify (but don\'t add) the nodes and edges you will add to\r\neach of the two new universes. You store all this info somewhere that\r\nyou can get to it. Then, every turn, you remove 1/xth of the links you\r\nwant to break (reporting them to the players as \"the institute of\r\nnavigation and trade routes reports that some routes have been lost\")\r\nand add some nodes and their links (not reporting these at all). After\r\nx turns the separation is complete.\r\n\r\nThis whole idea will require a game structure that is very\r\ndifferent from the one I imagined. Originally, I thought we would have\r\n\"a game\" and then would start \"another\" game when the time was right.\r\nUnder this model, you have a set of maps which are independent of the\r\nnumber of games. This implies that when a player in the first few\r\nlevels goes through the \"Old One\'s\" gateway, he may end up anywhere.\r\nThis also allows for us to have weird links -- from one game\r\nhorizontally to another or even back down. And we can scale the game\r\nanyway we want. I think it\'s important to allow players who don\'t want\r\nto fight to go through a portal to a \"fight-less\" game. \r\nNow how about a stateless way to accomplish the same thing? We\r\nonce againh do a depth first search and we once again trash some number\r\nof links. We start from the very first node (\"first\" in some way that\r\nmakes it first every turn). We add all the nodes on the first turn (we\r\nhave to know how many turns we\'ve been doing this so we can know if\r\nthis is the first turn). Then we add some number of edges until we can\r\nget to all 100+ nodes from the central node. \r\nBAH, this is harder than I thought!\r\n\r\n\r\n','2000-08-22','2007-04-11 15:18:46'),(225,15,'DAM','The handicap should range between 0 and about 60%. For 20 steps,\r\nperhaps step it by 3s. At the early part of this, the growth is very\r\nhigh (as high as 500% per trade). But at the end, the profit is only\r\nabout 50%. At 50% growth it will take the player about 19 trades to get\r\n$100,000 (assuming he starts at $50). The fact that he has much, much\r\nhigher growth at the lower end will affect this somewhat but in those\r\nearly days he won\'t have enough money to really get ahead. Later, when\r\nhe has some serious cash, he doesn\'t have that growth rate.\r\n\r\n','2000-08-29','2007-04-11 15:15:17'),(226,15,'DAM','Once more, with feeling! :)                                            \r\n\r\nThe problem with all this is that it\'s VERY complicated. I need a game that\'s very simple but, unlike the Numbers Game, has player state, the necessity to sign up and, perhaps, an end game condition. (This latter may not be necessary but, if it is, we can simply say that when N players have more than X money the game ends that they represent the top N winners of the game.)\r\n\r\nI want to start out very simple and add complexity over time. I want to start with what I guess I would call \"Level 0\".\r\n\r\nThis game has 12 cities, all an equal distance from the others (1 turn). Each player has one ship which carries one commodity.  Each city buys 3 and sells 3 commodities. I think I like the idea of a base price and multiplier but the base prices are fixed. All commodities are for sale for 3 and bought for 6. The commodities are divided into 4 groups of 3 each: the cheap group has a multiplier of 1, next is 10, then 100 then 1000. The end condition is $100,000.\r\nWe may want to add a handicap for each commodity which is proportional to the price. \r\n\r\nThe only tough part of the game is to come up with an algorithm that distributes the commodities correctly across the cities.  How about:\r\n\r\n1) initialize a list of cities to have no commodities\r\n2) initialize a list of commodities a count of how many times we\'re buy and selling all set to 0\r\n3) loop through cities starting at the first and ending with the last\r\n4) loop through the 3 buy slots for that city (increment, test)\r\n5) Pick a commodity at random\r\n6) have we used this commodity before at this city? if so, goto 5\r\n7) is this commodity bought at 3 cities?  if so, goto 5\r\n8) Add this commodity to the list of buy commodities for this city\r\n9) tick off one more buy for this commodity\r\n10) goto 4\r\n11) loop through the 3 sell slots for that city (increment, test)\r\n12) Pick a commodity at random\r\n13) have we used this commodity before at this city? if so, goto 12\r\n14) is this commodity sold at 3 cities?  if so, goto 12\r\n15) Add this commodity to the list of sell commodities for this city\r\n16) tick off one more sell for this commodity\r\n17) goto 11\r\n18) goto 3\r\n\r\nwhen we fall through 18 we should be done...\r\n','2007-04-10','2007-04-11 15:14:53'),(229,15,'DAM','The game it self consists of this sequence:\r\n\r\nPlayer sells\r\nPlayer Buys\r\nPlayer moves\r\nComputer updates prices (which in this version, doesn\'t change)\r\n\r\nThis is because we want the player to be able to know for sure what the prices are when he buys and sells so we have it happen before he moves. Any other way to do it has to take into account the fact that the player won\'t know prices at the moment he writes his orders (because, for example, he\'s moving to somewhere he doesn\'t have information about).\r\n\r\nIn this version of the game, the prices don\'t change and we\'ll publish all the information about all 12 cities. BORING. But it\'s a valid first cut. \r\n\r\nThe game ends when a player reaches $30,000 (100,000 will take too long). \r\n\r\nThe orders consist of the following sections\r\n----------\r\nShips\r\nShip XXX sells nothing               (x)\r\nShip XXX sells NNN of commodity CCC for $$$ ()\r\nNOTE: you must sell something to have the room to buy anything.\r\nShip XXX buys Nothing                       (x)\r\nShip XXX buys NNN of commodity CCC for $$$  ()\r\nShip XXX buys NNN of commodity CCC for $$$  ()\r\nShip XXX buys NNN of commodity CCC for $$$  ()\r\nAGENTS\r\n - you have no agents - \r\n\r\nHOUSEKEEPING\r\nRename PPP\'s Ship XXX \"TTT\" as [    ]\r\n{SUBMIT}\r\n------------\r\nXXX is the ship name and is always fixed. NNN is the quantity of the commodity and is always 1. CCC is a commodity at the port of this ship. $$$ is the price. \r\nAgents are like warehouses in an earlier incarnation of the game. \r\n() is a checkbox: he may sell only one thing and buy only one thing. \r\nPPP is the player name, TTT is the name he\'s already called it. \r\n\r\nFor this version of this game, his options are limited but he might have multiple ships in some other game.\r\n\r\n','2007-04-12','2007-04-12 14:43:33'),(227,15,'DAM','After a great deal of experimentation, the proper way to initialize a set of cities is as follows:\r\n\r\n1) RANDOMLY ASSIGN COMMODITIES TO towns making sure only that there are the correct number of commodities and that no town has more than 3-3 slots\r\nNOTE: don\'t worry about duplicates at this point\r\nDUDE, you can fill each city with the same commodity and the algorithm works just as well! Pick the commodity at random\r\n2) Count how many duplicates are in each city\r\n2.5) if there are no duplicates got to 10\r\n3) pick the first city with duplicates (\"problem city\")\r\n4) find the first commodity in the city that\'s duplicated (\"problem commodity\")\r\n5) pick a city at random that\'s not our problem city\r\n6) Find the first commodity of the same type  in that city that our problem city  doesn\'t have (\"random commodity\")\r\n7) If there is no such commodity, goto 5\r\n8) swap the problem commodity with the random commodity\r\n8.5) increment counter, compare to some large limit and if we\'re past got 11\r\n9) goto 2\r\n10) we\'re done\r\nThis is actually not guaranteed to end but it\'s VERY VERY likely to end SO...\r\n11) this is an error; increment a counter and if the counter is over a limit goto 1 :)\r\n\r\nThe algorithm will complete faster if you pick a commodity in the random city that\'s duplicated. \r\n','2007-04-11','2007-04-11 15:07:55'),(230,40,'DAM','scott nelson suggested that we should have a version of the numbers game where the winner is the person who guesses the number FARTHEST from the other players \r\nYou could call the The UNIQUE Numbers Game or you call this \"Nelson\'s Numbers Game','2007-04-13','2007-04-13 19:26:00'),(231,4,'DAM','FOr the program to run games, we need a table that has the following fields (note: must be a separate table, you can\'t just add these fields to an existing table).\r\n\r\nID\r\ninstanceid\r\nday-of-week (enum mon-Sun, all, none) \r\ntime (time)\r\nstatus (running,stalled,?)\r\nevent (run, ?)\r\nts\r\n\r\nThis is a definition of when a game runs provide it runs at least once a week. If you want it to run more than once a week (every other day, for example) you can put multiple versions of this in there. You can\'t do \"odd\" days of the month or anything complicate -- it always runs on the same day(s) of the week. Likewise if you want to run a game multiple times a day, you have multiple records with the same day but different times. \r\n\r\nThis could be expanded to work less than once a week but I\'m not sure there is any call for that so we\'ll do it later (but that\'s what \"none\" means -- don\'t use the day of the week use some other value in the record. \r\n\r\nThere needs to be a web page that allows you to add and remove times to run the game. \r\n\r\nNow, the hard part is how to use this. \r\nWe need a select statement that will list all the events in the future. ','2007-04-14','2007-04-14 18:34:11'),(232,47,'old','I want to have an overview, something about managing 2 employees, something about releasing 9 \"products\", something about creating process, soemthing about doing a conference (?), ','2007-04-15','2007-04-15 19:59:13'),(233,4,'DAM','That whole thing about how to run games doesn\'t work because it\'s almost impossible to tell, when a job completes, when the next job will be. At least I couldn\'t figure it out, although it occurs to me that the crontab people know how to do it...\r\n\r\nSo that\'s the first solution: set the crontab to be what you want and don\'t control it from a database. These seems appealing but isn\'t my vision. \r\n\r\nBut I don\'t want to do that. So I want to narrow my solution. There are two cases that actually exist: weekly games and daily games. So right off, we need a switch between daily and weekly. Then we have a day and a time. Daily games ignore the day, weekly games play on that day. \r\n\r\nDaily games are easy, we figure out the date, add one day and pick a time (from the day that it was set to run, not from \"now\"). \r\n\r\nWeekly games are the same thing except that we add 7 days. \r\n\r\nImplement that and then we can work on more sophisticated algorithms.','2007-04-21','2007-04-21 18:21:59'),(234,45,'Old','<b>Ok, this isn\'t about the UI but about the database.</b>\r\nIt seem to me that the definition of a galashould not be stored in the database or, if it is, stored as a cloud of tables rather than attempting to do one table (in this definition its a structure containing structures). Essentially this is really a collection of variables about the game that occur once per game. Given that databases are about lists of records, it\'s not very good at this sort of thing.  One might almost create a table like this:\r\n\r\ncreate table galaxydefinition{\r\ngame int, // game number\r\nvarname tinytext, // variable name in text\r\nvarvalue tinytext};// string of variables value\r\n\r\nWhere the galaxy definition for each games consists of a bunch of arbitrary var names and var values that are looked up and interpreted when needed. In any event, it\'s kind of inconvenient, no matter how you do it. \r\n\r\nYou would, of course, keep the structure of structures exactly the way it is and read it in at the start. I\'m just considering how best to store it. \r\n\r\nThe only other problems are the arrays of values stored in the structures (mostly ore). One way to do it is to create a series of columns in the database like this:\r\n\r\n...\r\nmine6 int,\r\nmine7 int,\r\nmine8 int,\r\nmine9 int,\r\nore0 int,\r\nore1 int,\r\nore2 int,\r\nore3 int,\r\nore4 int,\r\nore5 int,\r\n...\r\nand so forth so that every record had the ore. This isn\'t TOO bad since you always have only 10 mines and 10 ore types in the records. \r\nBut a more flexible way is to  have a separate list like this\r\ncreate table resources{\r\ngame int,\r\nplanet int,\r\ntype enum (industry,ore,mine),\r\nsubtype int, \r\nquantity int);\r\n\r\nThen you do a select like this to get the data\r\nselect * from resources where game=1 and planet=4 ;\r\nand you get a list of all of planet 4\'s resources.\r\nOR to get a list of all the resources you can do this\r\nselect * from resources where game=1;\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat you CAN\'T get is an array of planets with an array inside each element. But you can build that up from the second list. \r\nJust step through and say\r\nif (type=0) //industry\r\n	planet[i].industry=record[\'quantity\']; //ok I have some syntax mixing here\r\nelse if (type=1) // ore\r\n	planet[i].ore[record[\'subtype\']=record[\'quantity\'];\r\nelse // mines\r\n	planet[i].mine[record[\'subtype\']=record[\'quantity\'];\r\n	\r\nIt\'s all quite tedious but simple enough to do. \r\n','2007-04-21','2007-04-21 21:16:17'),(235,50,'DAM','CREATE TABLE gsuser (\r\n  userid int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment primary key,\r\n  username tinytext,\r\n  userpass tinytext,\r\n  email tinytext,\r\n  name tinytext,\r\n  temppw tinytext,\r\n  tpwexpiry date default \'2000-01-01\',\r\n  type enum(\'inactive\',\'active\',\'admin\') default \'inactive\',\r\n  actword tinytext,\r\n  ts timestamp(14) NOT NULL\r\n  );\r\ninsert into gsuser (username) values (\"Alice\"),(\"Bob\"),(\"Charlie\"),(\"Don\"),(\"Ed\");\r\nupdate gsuser set userpass=\"p00psi\",email=\"fatzero@gmail.com\",name=username,type=\"active\";\r\n\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE gsnodate ( #\"nodate\" is a date people DON\'T want to have the meeting\r\n	nodateid int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment primary key,\r\n	meetinno int, \r\n	userno int,\r\n	nodate date,\r\n	ts timestamp(14) NOT NULL\r\n);\r\nadd a unique index meetingno,userno,nodate\r\nCREATE TABLE gsmeeting (\r\n	meetingid  int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment primary key,\r\n	startdate date, #the earliest day we can have the meeting\r\n	enddate date, #the latest day we can have the meeting\r\n	location tinytext, #where the meeting will be\r\n	time time, #what time we expect the meeting to be\r\n	desc text, #what\'s it all about?\r\n	quorum int default 0, # number of people who must be there to have the meeting\r\n	restricted bool, #can anyone in the user file come or is it restricted to some subset (specified in the people table)\r\n	ts timestamp(14) NOT NULL\r\n);\r\ncreate table gspeople ( #this is a list of people who must come or who may come to a meeting. \r\n	peopleid  int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment primary key,\r\n	meetingno int, #meeting number\r\n	userno int, #user number\r\n	type enum (\"may\",\"must\",\"quorum\"), # may=allowed, must=can\'t have meeting without, quorum=if they\'re coming they form part of the quorum\r\n#are may and quorum equivalent? Won\'t may=part of quorum and quorum=allowed?\r\n	ts timestamp(14) NOT NULL\r\n);\r\n	\r\n','2007-04-22','2007-04-22 16:31:26'),(236,50,'DAM','Here\'s how it works from my current perspective:\r\n1) Get the blockdates from the database. Probably a routine that just does it. Pass it the array from the table and the name of the field that has the date and it makes a list of epoch dates. Might be good to have epoch dates AND userno\'s but I\'m not sure.\r\n2) Get the interval from the meeting database. Convert to epoch dates in a array (\'start\', \'end\'). \r\n3) Pass the two arrays into the counting function. It turns the interval into an array then converts the values (dates) to keys (?). Then it runs through the block array and counts how many times each date comes up. \r\n4) At this point we can have an \"early out\" and check to see if we have any counts of zeros. If so we can skip down to where we consider preferences.\r\n5) Now we determine if there are any \"must have\" people who have blocked dates on this list. One way to do this is to get a list of blocked dates from musts and do the same count excercise. Remove all the elements with 0 counts and then use the remaining list to remove dates from the count list.\r\n6) Now we calculate how low a count consitutes a quorum by counting the total number of people who responded and subtracting the quorum number. \r\n7) Do we have any dates that have counts less than the quorum number? If no then the scheduling excercise has failed. If yes then we\'ve succeeded.\r\n8)If we\'ve succeeded than we need to apply preferences (again, make a list of prefered dates and count them). The date that works with the most preferences wins.\r\n\r\nThere are some real weird cases here. We assume that if a person hasn\'t put in any blocking dates that they find all dates to be acceptable but this isn\'t necessarily the case. Perhaps we should continue to collect data until everyone on the list has responded but what if someone can actually go to any date in the range -- how do we tell? \r\n\r\nWe could add a flag to the people list that indicates whether the person has responded and then have a \"I accept any date\" button on the date picker page. \r\n\r\nPersonally, I find it acceptable to take the dates from the people who respond and schedule the meeting. If the people who didn\'t respond can\'t make it then that kind of what they get for not responding. This could be a problem if one of them was crucial to the meeting. \r\n\r\nSetting up the meeting is kind of complicated. You have to allow the master to make a list of people who must come and a list of people who can come as well as the quorum number. This basical involves having the entire set of people in a big list with check boxes. Ick. But there really isn\'t a better way. They can be in multiple columns to take up less space if we want. Hopefully we\'re talking dozens, not hundreds...\r\n\r\nThen there is the report. In an idea universe we could just say \"Scheduling succeeded, the best day is xx/xx/xxxx!\" or \"Scheduling failed\" but people probably want more information, especially if scheduling failed. We probably want to make a list of people who blocked the 5 best dates so that the master can go apply pressure. And he probably wants to see the 5 best dates if it succeeds, too. \r\n\r\nAnd there is the issue of when scheduling is over. Perhaps there should be a cutoff date. Scheduling is still running as long as we haven\'t reached the cutoff date (or we could do an early out when everyone has responded).  If you look at the report BEFORE scheduling finishes you get to see who has and has not responded. If you look at the report AFTER scheduling finishes you get to see the dates that were picked. \r\n\r\nFinally there is the issue of email notifications. There are various policies that might be implemented to do notifications. Notify people about the meeting, remind them if they haven\'t done the sheduling, tell them that they\'re blocking, tell the master that we\'re done, tell everyone the date of the meeting. Most of these require a cron process to be running, which is a complication I would deal with for myself but maybe not for others. ','2007-04-22','2007-04-23 05:23:53'),(237,50,'DAM','man, do I feel silly\r\nselect distinct date,count(date) as count from gsblockdate where meetingno=1 group by date order by count;\r\n\r\nwill do a count and return almost the exact array that the count routine would (instead of date->count it\'s index->(\'date\'->date,\'count\'->count)\r\nOh and the zero dates are missing. To correct that, get the list of dates in the interval and then invert the block list against the interval list. Any dates in the resulting array have no blocks on them!','2007-04-24','2007-04-25 06:05:18'),(238,16,'DAM','For notification consider this\r\nNumbers Game game # 1, round 86:  7 guesses; average 382.9765690 ;winning guess  399.399; winner Isidila (52).\r\nThe <Name> Numbers Game has just run and you were asked to be notified. There were <guesses> guesses. The average guess was <average> and the winning guess of <wguess> was made by <username>. \r\nTo stop this notification from happening, change your account seetings at <account url>.','2007-04-27','2007-04-27 16:21:37'),(239,55,'DAM','INVOICE TABLE\r\ninvoiceid int primary key auto increment unique\r\nContractorName tinytext\r\nInvoiceNumber int\r\nBPAFno int\r\nDateSent date	\r\nDateRecd date\r\nProjectAmt date\r\nNotes varchar\r\nts timestamp\r\n\r\nbpaf table\r\nbpafid int\r\nbpafref tinytext\r\ncompany tinytext\r\nbpafdate date\r\nstart date\r\nend date\r\nvalue float(10.2)\r\nusable float(10.2)\r\nStatusno int\r\nprojectno int\r\n\r\nstatus table\r\nstatusid\r\nstatusname\r\n\r\nproject table\r\nprojectid\r\nprojectname','2007-05-07','2007-05-08 02:52:10'),(240,55,'DAM','The following is a list of the tables we need and the links that will be IN THAT TABLE.\r\nCompanies (just company information)\r\nprojects  (just project information) \r\ninvoices -> Companies, projects,  bpafs (an invoice may have many projects AND may be smeared across multiple bpafs so we need invoice<->project table and an invoice<->bpaf table)\r\nbpafs -> Companies, projects, (only one company but multiple projects so we need a bpaf<->project table)\r\nbudgets -> projects (the project, the year and amounts; 1-1 for any year)','2007-05-08','2007-05-08 14:42:55'),(241,55,'DAM','Budget\r\nProject\r\nStatus\r\nBpaf has a company no, status #, creates \r\ninvoice has an invoice #, company# ; adds line items for \r\ncompany\r\nline item (connect project to invoices)\r\nproject auth (connects bpaf to projects)\r\n','2007-05-08','2007-05-08 17:50:06'),(242,56,'DAM','Small Robot Navigation Indoors\r\n\r\nThe Problem\r\n\r\nSmall robots have severe limitations on their power consumption, computing power and sensor capabilities. Indoors GPS doesn\'t work and \"dead reckonning\" (calculating your location based on how far you\'ve gone in each direction) is generally not very accurate.\r\n\r\nA single autonomous robot, in an indoor environment has few options for navigation in the room. The best solutions I\'ve heard of involve video cameras and a lot of image processing (requiring lots of data processing) or infrastructure in the room (i.e. physical beacons that the robot can sense that tell it where it is).\r\n\r\nThe Situation\r\nMy solution applies to robots who are inside a structure that has walls with right angle corners and that is relatively flat. It can be adapted to structures with flat walls that meet at odd angles but round rooms and rooms that have variations in height greater than the height of the robot would be problematic. The basic algorithm can be adapted for arbitrarily complicated rooms -- a maze, say, or a ranch-style home -- but it will be most useful for fairly open rooms.  In short, the algorithm will work best in \"normal\" rooms that you would find in buildings. Caves, bombed out buildings, underwater environments and so on probably wouldn\'t be good places to put a robot equipted only with this system.\r\n\r\nThe Equipment\r\nThe robot needs to be able to \"look\" in 360 degrees, know which direction (reletive to, say, the front of the robot ) it\'s looking and be able to calculate the range from itself to the first obstruction. I envision a laser range finder mounted on the top of the robot that has a stepper motor that allows it to step around in a circle. A more complicated arrangement of multiple range finders that give partial coverage of the world would also work.\r\n\r\nA \"reference direction\" would also be very useful for many situations. A compass would work admirably but it only really needs to know that a particular direction is the same whereever it goes. This addition would allow the algorithms to be simpler and more robust and would allow the algorithms to work reliably in odd situations such as perfectly symetric rooms with lots of corners (say, a 10 sided room) or round rooms.\r\n\r\nThe Algorithm\r\nImagine a rectangular room in which the North-South axis was longer than the East-West axis. The room has nothing in it. We drop our robot into this room and teh robot sweeps it\'s laser in a circle accumulating ranges. Analysis of the data would reveal 4 points that are farther away than other points -- these are the corners of the room. By looking at the data in between these points we can verify that the room is rectangular and know which walls are longer. If there are holes in the walls (i.e. doors) these would be obvious, as well. Most importantly, every point in the room has a unique set of distances from the four corners so the robot always knows where it is as it moves through this room. The robot would select a set of reference points (probably the four corners in this case) and, as long as it could see at least one (preferably two) of these points it would be able to tell where it was.\r\n\r\nLet\'s say that the room has a shape that prevents it from seeing the whole room. The robot can create a map of the parts it can see, identify areas for which it has no information, and move in a direction that is mostly likely to provide maximum information. As long as it can see some reference points (say, two corners) it should be able to place itself on it\'s own map at all times. Thus, when it sees a new feature, it knows where it is and thus can place the new feature on the map. Ultimately it can fill out the map completely and navigate within this space.\r\n\r\nImagine that the room has 10 sides and is symetrical. Now it might be possible for the robot to get confused if it turns more than 18 degrees between scans of it\'s reference points. This would happen because it would get confused as to which corner was which. So if it found something in the room it would map it at the wrong location. The same thing might happen any time the only reference points the robot can see can be confused. This could happen if there was an odd geometry where, for example, a wall seen through a doorway looks like a corner but really isn\'t.\r\n\r\nThis problem could be solved by having a reference direction -- an electronic compass or gyroscope -- that could give it an absolute direction. This ensures that any odd geometries can be detected and corrected for and that the reference point it thinks it\'s using is the one that it\'s really looking at.\r\n\r\nA Few Oddities\r\nA room with a big hump in the middle could prevent the robot from seeing across the room. A round room has no corners so it would have no reference points (although a special case algorithm could be written to account for this).\r\n\r\nThe things that will really screw up our intrepid explorer, though, are clutter. Normal clutter (even clutter that moves) isn\'t a problem. We only really get into trouble with items that we can see that don\'t impede movement (such as a pingpong ball suspended from the ceiling at just the right height) and things that we can\'t see that DO impede movement. For example, a stack of heavy books. Or a coffee table or couch that the laser sees over but the robot can\'t move through.\r\n\r\nThe algorithm can be adapted to find and track other robots in the room. While it could get confused by robots close to the wall that don\'t move (thinkng that they are bumps in the wall -- which in effect, they are) it can be programmed to figure even these cases out when the robots move. Once it finds a robot (or any object) it can tell whether it\'s moving or not (by the fact that subsequent plots show it in different locations) and can avoid that object in it\'s movements.\r\n\r\nA Supporting Algorithm\r\nI have another algorithm that can be used by any mobile entity that knows where it is (such as a video game character). This entity can place \"virtual beacons\" on it\'s internal map and navigate by moving from beacon to beacon. The easiest way to place the beacons (and I think it can be shown to a reasonably  efficient placement) is to place a beacon every time a new feature comes into view while you can still see the previous beacon.\r\n\r\nSo you map the room and place a beacon. You move toward that gap over there (which you assume to be a door) and, when you get close enough to \"see\" into the adjoining room, but while you can still \"see\" the first beacon, you place another beacon. In the new room, but in sight of the old beacon, you place another one.\r\n\r\nOver time the world can be navigated by moving along a chain of beacons. These beacons can be formed, internally, into a graph and various graph algorithms can be performed on them (most usefully depth first searching or A* path finding algorithms).\r\n\r\nCurrent State of Play\r\nI have no code for the first algorithm but I do have code for the second. It would not be hard to demonstrate the first algorithm with a simulation of the robot mapping various shaped rooms but I don\'t have any time for fun stuff like that (much as I would love to do it).\r\n','2007-05-08','2007-05-08 21:29:37'),(243,55,'DAM','\r\nCREATE TABLE itprojectauth (\r\nprojectauthid int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment primary key ,\r\nbpafno int,\r\nprojectno int,\r\namount decimal (10,2),\r\npats timestamp(14) NOT NULL) ;\r\ncreate unique index bpafproj on itprojectauth (bpafno,projectno);\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE user (\r\nid int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment primary key ,\r\nusername tinytext,\r\nuserpass tinytext,\r\nemail tinytext,\r\nname tinytext,\r\ntemppw tinytext,\r\ntpwexpiry date default \'2000-01-01\',\r\ntype enum(\'inactive\',\'active\',\'admin\') default \'inactive\',\r\nactword tinytext,\r\nts timestamp(14) NOT NULL) ;\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE itlineitem (\r\nlineitemid int NOT NULL  primary key auto_increment,\r\nprojectno int,\r\ninvoiceno int,\r\namount decimal(10,2),\r\nlits timestamp);\r\ncreate unique index projinvo on itlineitem (projectno,invoiceno);\r\n\r\nCREATE TABLE itbudget(\r\nbudgetid int NOT NULL  primary key auto_increment,\r\nprojectno int,\r\nstartdate date,\r\ndurati