 contract is signed, commence spending.\');\r\n\r\ninsert into itcompany (companyid,companyname,companydesc,principal) values (1,\'Access Softek\', \'PS3 Developers\', \'Chris Doner\'),(2,\'GeekSpeak\',\'Techwriters\',\'Mike Boom\'),(3,\'Code Cobblers\',\'They don\\\'t do shoes!\',\'Scott Maxwell\'),(4,\'Mobileer\',\'PS3 and web\',\'Phil Burk\'),(5,\'Reactor Zero\',\'\',\'Matt Toschlog\');\r\n\r\ninsert into itproject (projectid,projectname) values \r\n(1,\'Ajax\'),\r\n(2,\'Anark\'),\r\n(3,\'Atomic\'),\r\n(4,\'Build and Test\'),\r\n(6,\'Doc-C-Matic\'),\r\n(7,\'DTE\'),\r\n(8,\'E&O Insurance\'),\r\n(9,\'Expenses\'),\r\n(10,\'FIOS\'),\r\n(11,\'Fonts\'),\r\n(14,\'Insurance\'),\r\n(15,\'Java\'),\r\n(16,\'Lua\'),\r\n(17,\'Memwatch\'),\r\n(18,\'Misc Tools\'),\r\n(19,\'MP3\'),\r\n(20,\'PAMF\'),\r\n(21,\'PerfStation\'),\r\n(22,\'PS3 Admin\'),\r\n(24,\'Techwriting\'),\r\n(25,\'THC\'),\r\n(26,\'Unknown\');\r\n\r\n\r\n','2007-05-11','2007-05-11 23:55:30'),(244,39,'Old','Fundamental to being human is the ability to see the world around you and know that what you are seeing is true. If you can\'t actually look and see and know then  you cannot honestly participate in any discussion that matters, even with regards to yourself. \r\n\r\nWhen we are young our parents and community tell us things which  we, by and large, believe. At some stage in our development we rebel against what we\'ve been told and believe the opposite. For a long time we have difficulty knowing what\'s true because we see what we were told to see or we see what we were told not to see.\r\n\r\nThis is the value of teachers; to help you see, not in relationship to what you\'ve been told but completely independent of what you\'ve been told. A true teacher never tells you anything but rather shows you things and allows you to see them. Some people can come to see clearly without a teacher but this is rare. In my (limited) experience, these people become teachers. \r\n\r\nMy favorite quote about this is \"You must be honest to live outside the law.\" (Bob Dylan) because it speaks to the need to actually admit what you\'re seeing with not outside influence. \r\n\r\nThis is, by the way, why traditional religion, slavery or any other form of physical or intellectual oppression is a tremendous disservice. Anything that gets in the way of seeing what\'s around you clearly is a hindrence to becoming a real human being. \r\n\r\nAs long as you don\'t know that what you are looking at is real you can only be considered insane. One\'s goal, then, is to become sane. To be able to see things as they are. \r\n\r\nOnce you become sane, you can participate in the great discussion that is life and that is the true heritage of being human. But to truly participate you need to continue in this honesty and say nothing that is not true for you. ','2007-05-24','2007-05-24 18:22:36'),(245,55,'DAM','\r\nI\'d like to propose a set of simplifying assumptions that will make the calculations MUCH easier to write but should still be completely accurate.  \r\n\r\n1) We have no money for any company from contracts that have expired. \r\n2) Only invoices that are submitted within the period a contract is active can be paid out of that contract.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure about this second one as some of our historical situations may have had invoices that came in BEFORE a contract was approved paid by that contract. But, going forward, this should always work. \r\n\r\nTo implement the \"calculation of the bucket\" (which is the critical calculation that must be performed and which could not be performed easily with a spreadsheet) I plan to take the following steps:\r\n\r\n1) Pick a date called \"thedate\" and a company \"thecompany\" (thedate is, by default, today but it could be any date past, present or future)\r\n2) Get a list of bpafs that meet ALL the following criteria: \r\n      - have been approved (regardless of WHEN they were approved)\r\n     - start before thedate\r\n     - end after thedate\r\n     - is associated with thecompany\r\n3) Get the total \"spendable\" value from all these bpafs -- this is The Raw Bucket (that is, the amount we had to spend before we spent any)\r\n4) Get the earliest date that any of these BPAFs started\r\n5) Get the latest date that any of these BPAFs ended\r\n6) Find all the invoices from thecompany that fall between the earliest start (4) and the latest end (5) \r\n7) Sum all the amounts of all those invoices. \r\n8) subtract the sum in 7 from The Raw Bucket calculated in 3. This yeilds Today\'s Bucket and is the amount we have to spend from thedate until latest end.\r\n\r\nI think there may be some cases where this figure will not be accurate. For example, if vendors send us invoices when we have no active contracts with them (remember \"active\" in this context means that the contract hasn\'t expired by date -- it doesn\'t speak to how much money is on the contract). I don\'t think this has happened. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, if 2 contracts overlap AND during that overlap some invoices come in, those invoices should be applied to the first contract but, if thedate is after the first contract expired then all of them would be applied to the 2nd contract thus resulting in a smaller Bucket. Not sure if that\'s a problem or not. \r\n\r\nOVERRIDES\r\nAn override says \"as of this date, we have X amount of money\". Overrides would be implement by simply ignoring all invoices and all contracts that were created before the override. We simply add a criterium to step 2 above: \"- are after the last override for this company\" and change 4 to be \"get the date that is the later of last override and the earliest date that any of these BPAFs started\" -- thus moving up the \'earliest date\' to be last override. \r\n\r\nADJUSTMENTS\r\nWe could also do adjustments (incremental changes to Today\'s Bucket) either by adding a fake invoice (positive or negative) or by having an adjustment file that does the same thing. \r\n\r\nShall I implement overrides and/or adjustments? \r\n\r\nPROJECTS\r\nThis system describes how to calculate The Company Bucket (which is the bucket that burned us last time). I can also do a similar calculation for The Project Bucket to determine how much money we have left for each project.  I don\'t know that it makes any difference since you can move money from one to another at will BUT it might be a useful tools for the managers to track how much they are speding relative to how much you allocated to them.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2007-06-13','2007-06-13 23:24:11'),(246,55,'DAM','select companyname,sum(spendable) as bucket, min(startdate) as firststart, max(enddate) as lastend from itbpaf,itcompany where statusno=9 and companyid=companyno and spendable>0 and startdate<curdate() and enddate>curdate() group by companyno;\r\n\r\n\r\nThis gets all the data you need from the bpaf file (although you could add \"and companyid=$thecompany\" to it to limit it down farther. I think this is one element of the company view right here.\r\n\r\nCompanyname, bucket, firststart, lastend.\r\n\r\nselect companyname,sum(amt) as spent from itinvoice,itcompany where contractorno=companyid and datesent>\'2006-08-20\' and datesent<\'2008-08-19\' and contractorno=4 group by contractorno ;\r\nThis gets all the data from the itinvoice table. Note that you must specify the firststart and the lastend as well as the contractorno.\r\nIt returns just th companyname (which you already know) and the spent amount\r\n\r\n\r\n','2007-06-13','2007-06-14 05:02:22'),(247,55,'DAM','IT Tracker\r\nNew Bucket Algorithm\r\n\r\nAdd a split amount and 2nd bpafref (the idea being that if the split amount is the amount that goes to the 1st bpaf and the rest goes to the 2nd bpaf\r\nWrite a routine for one company that...\r\n\r\nDoes a select to get all the bpafs for that company.\r\nChanges the bpafs to be indexed by bpafref\r\nDoes a select to get all the invoices\r\nFor each invoice...\r\n  if it has a valid bpafred # look up the bpaf that it\'s assign to\r\n  if the dates are right and there\'s enough space left in the bpaf, subtract it from that bpaf\r\n  if not then do the split \r\n  if there are issues, find which bpaf it fits in, adjust the invoices values, subtract it from the right bpaf and add it to a list to be updated\r\n\r\nAfter this process we should run through the bpafs and sum all the money from bpafs that are still current\r\n\r\nThis is the raw bucket','2007-07-04','2007-07-04 17:43:25'),(248,53,'DAM','Check for < and remove from virtually all input\r\non login names (and generally, I think) we need to remove / and .. from most code to prevent things like ../etc\r\n\r\nONLY constants can be passed to any PHP command that will read or write files or (lord help us) execs. If you need some kind of variable, use a switch statement. ONLY CONSTANTS!\r\n\r\nVariables that get inserted into SQL statements are very vulnerable. \"--\" and \";\" should be excluded and perhaps all the sql keywords?\r\n\r\nStop connecting to SQL databases as root!\r\n\r\nHash passwords and other fields where applicable; encrypt other sensitive data (does PHP have a real encryption algorithm?) using a key from the config file. Mcrypt and Mhash http://www.php.net/manual/en/ref.mcrypt.php http://www.php.net/manual/en/ref.mhash.php\r\n\r\nConsider connecting to the database over SSL...','2007-07-04','2007-07-04 19:08:00'),(249,53,'DAM','http://www.php.net/manual/en/ref.var.php\r\nhttp://www.php.net/manual/en/ref.ctype.php\r\nhttp://www.php.net/manual/en/ref.pcre.php\r\nmysql_escape_string():http://www.php.net/manual/en/function.mysql-escape-string.php','2007-07-04','2007-07-04 19:03:52'),(250,16,'DAM','List of one random test user\r\n select id,username,type,rand() as rand  from rwuser where type=\'test\' order by rand limit 1;\r\n\r\n\r\n','2007-07-15','2007-07-15 08:53:19'),(251,16,'DAM','Nelson\'s Numbers Game\r\nselect a1.userno,a2.userno,a1.testid, a2.testid, a1.x,a2.x, abs(a1.x-a2.x) as dist from test as a1,test as a2 where a1.userno!=a2.userno and a1.userno=7 order by dist,a1.x limit 1;\r\nThis gets the smallest distance from userno 7\'s value to any other point. By iterating through all the users this will give you the smallest value for each player. The largest of these is associated with the winner!','2007-07-18','2007-07-18 14:10:38'),(252,15,'DAM','Here\'s another wacky idea in a long line of wacky idea. \r\nMed trader is exactly as described but with the addition of caravans (I guess this would be a collapse of game 1 and game 2 into one game). The idea is that you can buy a caravan for significantly more than a ship but a ship only ever carries one cargo while adding a cargo to a caravan cost less than a ship. \r\n\r\nNow, Mediterranean cities still sell 4 things each but they only buy, say, 2. But interior cites buy 4 things but only sell 1 (how the hell does THAT economy work). So now we have med traders collecting stuff and caravan traders selling it deep in the interiors of Europe and Asia (and Africa?). We connect these two groups (beginners and intermediates if you will) through an auction. The med traders can put goods up for auction which the caravan traders can buy. The goods are stored in warehouses and the next time the caravan traders come through they can pick that stuff up and move it into the interior, making more money than they could collecting stuff from the cities directly. \r\n\r\nThe key to this is that a caravan (or a second ship) has to cost a lot more than the typical player can afford. Essentially, buying a caravan is equivalent to moving through the portal in the old scheme. And the money you can make in the interior has to be a LOT more than you can make on the med. But the stuff you buy in the interior is not worth as much -- the stuff for sale in the interior has to be different. Actually, the requirement is that most of the stuff available in the interior is only wanted on the med and most of the stuff they want in the interior can only be gotten on the med. You can muddy that up a bit but it has to be generally true. \r\n\r\nIt occurs to me that one can allow med traders to buy an ocean-going vessel that can leave the med and travel down to Africa and up to Europe. Problem is, this is just a distraction. In order to be interesting, these ships have to be less than a 1 cargo caravan but more than a med ship. The goods you sell in Africa have to be from the med (only) but the goods you buy in Africa can be salable in the med or in the interior. This adds people who will buy goods from the med and it adds goods that interior traders can buy (not sure the latter is a good thing). \r\n\r\nThe scheme is intended to have beginners and intermediate players in the same game. \r\n\r\nI suppose this is the 2nd stage. The 3rd stage would involve a train or road network (or both?) that would feed goods into a space port... \r\n','2007-09-23','2007-09-23 16:06:16'),(253,57,'DAM','http://www.eia.doe.gov/oiaf/analysispaper/pdf/tbl11.pdf\r\nFeb 2007\r\nmillion gallons per year\r\nYear	Gas	Ehanol	%\r\n2000	128662	1630	1.27\r\n2001	129312	1770	1.37\r\n2004	137022	3400\r\n2003	134089	2800\r\n2002	132782	2730\r\n2005	136949	3904\r\n\r\nyear	diesel	biodiesel\r\n2000	37238	-\r\n2001	38155	9\r\n2002	38881	11\r\n2003	40856	18	\r\n2004	42779	28\r\n2005	43180	91','2007-10-18','2007-10-18 07:34:52'),(254,57,'DAM','http://healthandenergy.com/ethanol.htm\r\nDavid Pimental 131,000 BTUs are needed to make one gallon of ethanol (from corn). One gallon of ethanol has an energy value of only 77,000 BTUS net energy loss of 54,000 BTUs\r\ncre of U.S. corn yields about 7,110 pounds of corn for processing into 328 gallons of ethanol; planting, growing and harvesting  requires about 140 gallons of fossil fuels and costs $347 per acre ; feedstock costs $1.05 per gallon of ethanol\r\n8 percent ethanol from the 92 percent water\r\nEthanol from corn costs about $1.74 per gallon to produce, compared with about 95 cents to produce a gallon of gasoline. \r\napproximately $1 billion a year in current federal and state subsidies (mainly to large corporations) for ethanol production \r\n10,000 miles a year on pure ethanol (not a gasoline-ethanol mix) would need about 852 gallons;take 11 acres to grow,;required to feed seven Americans\r\na total of about 97 percent of U.S. land area to run all american cars on ethanol','2007-10-18','2007-10-18 07:35:15'),(255,57,'DAM','http://www.eia.doe.gov/oiaf/analysispaper/biomass.html\r\nOverall, gasoline consumption is projected to increase by 32 percent on an energy basis, and by 34 percent on a volume basis, from 2007 to 2030.  (note: ethanol/gasoline blend requires more volume for the same energy)\r\nNational Renewable Energy Laboratory in 2002 estimated cellulosic ethanol plant with a capacity of 69.3 million gallons per year at $200 million \r\n Common blends of biodiesel are 2 percent, 5 percent, and 20 percent (B2, B5, and B20). Individual engine manufacturers determine which blends are warranted for use in their engines, but generally B5 blends are permissible and some manufacturers support B20 blends. Blends of biodiesel are distributed at stations throughout the United States. Some States have mandated levels of biodiesel use when in-State production reaches prescribed levels. \r\n\r\nhttp://www.eia.doe.gov/oiaf/analysispaper/pdf/tbl12.pdf\r\nenergy content of biofuels\r\nfuel	btu/gal(low heating value)	btu/gal (hi heating value	gals of gas\r\nconventional gas	115500		125071				1.0\r\nfuel ethanol (e100)	75000		84262				.67\r\ne85 (74%)		-		94872				.76\r\ndiesel			128500		138690				1.11\r\nbiodiesel(b100)		118296		128520				.95','2007-10-18','2007-10-18 07:46:40'),(256,57,'DAM','http://www.eia.doe.gov/oiaf/analysispaper/biomass.html\r\ncorn prices of about $2 per bushel and excluding capital costs, corn-based ethanol can be produced by the dry-milling process for approximately $1.00 to $1.06 per gallon (2005 dollars) or $11.90 to $12.60 per million BTu\r\n\r\nBiodiesel can be produced from soybean oil for $1.80 to $2.40 per gallon ($15.20 to $20.30 per million Btu) and from yellow grease for $0.90 to $1.10 per gallon ($7.60 to $9.30 per million Btu) [137, 138]. Feedstock costs for virgin soybean oil, which are dictated by commodity markets and vary between $0.20 and $0.30 per pound, constitute 70 to 78 percent of final production costs. Non-virgin feedstocks generally are cheaper, ranging from virtually no cost (for reclaimed restaurant trap grease) to 70 percent of the final production cost. For the production costs calculated above, virgin soybean oil was assumed to cost $0.26 per pound, and yellow grease was valued at 50 percent of the cost of an equivalent amount of soybean oil. ','2007-10-18','2007-10-18 07:49:59'),(257,57,'DAM','According to the most recent Agricultural Census (2002), the amount of cropland available in the lower 48 United States is 434 million acres [146], or 23 percent of the total land area [147]. The total amount of croplandâ€”defined as the sum of land used for crops, idle land, and pastureâ€”has been declining for the past 50 years and, increasingly, is becoming concentrated in the Midwest. The trend is expected to continue as population pressure leads to permanent conversion of some agricultural lands to other uses. It is unlikely that additional cropland will be added in the United States to accommodate increases in the demand for biofuels. Instead, the cultivation of biofuels will compete with other agricultural uses, such as pastureland and idle land, much of which is in the Conservation Reserve Program (CRP) [148]. ','2007-10-18','2007-10-18 07:51:54'),(258,57,'DAM','    * corn requires 29 percent more fossil energy than the fuel produced;\r\n    * switch grass requires 45 percent more fossil energy than the fuel produced; and\r\n    * wood biomass requires 57 percent more fossil energy than the fuel produced. \r\n\r\nhttp://www.coyoteblog.com/coyote_blog/2005/07/more_evidence_o.html\r\nIn terms of energy output compared with the energy input for biodiesel production, the study found that:\r\n\r\n    * soybean plants requires 27 percent more fossil energy than the fuel produced, and\r\n    * sunflower plants requires 118 percent more fossil energy than the fuel produced. ','2007-10-18','2007-10-18 07:54:20'),(259,48,'DAM','I\'m thinking that TheFive is the basis I want to use for a game about the global ecology. The game involves developing a model that relates a large number of factors and then letting the player tweak some of the variable. For example, if you tax the hell out of energy will it save the ecology or crash the global economy? \r\n\r\nThe key here is that I have to work out how each variable in the world affects all the others. This can be done by creating a set of equations. Of course, no one knows what those equations are. Right off the bat, I have to tell you that the resulting model has no chance of being \"right\". The idea is that the model is both reasonable and suggests something interesting. In other words, I\'m more interested in the game than in the model. You may believe that models represent reality. Be that as it may, games have a point of view. So the purpose of this game is to get people thinking about these issues and, perhaps, to inform them, albeit in a very biased way. Above all we need to be interesting. \r\n\r\n','2007-11-17','2007-11-18 00:47:26'),(260,48,'DAM','<h3>Population</h3>\r\nOn the face of it, population is the easiest to calculate. The total births less the total deaths in any given year and there you have the number. \r\n\r\nBirths are dependent on the growth rate (there is only one cause of a birth) which appears to be dependent on the wealth of the population in question. And now money is a factor! :)\r\n\r\nDeaths are a bit more complicated. The main causes are famine, disease, war, accidents and  old age. Famine is directly related to food supply. Old age is related to health care spending. Disease is very easily predicted as a projection of the past into the future based on the amount of money spent on heath care and, possibly, health research. War is unpredictable but I have a theory that if you look at average wealth in each of the continents and compare it to the average war-related deaths there would some correlation between wealth disparity and war-related deaths. At least, it\'s a place to start. \r\n\r\nAccidents vary widely from population to population. I think that the main cause of accidents is probably automobiles and you can probably predict the number of deaths by the number of automobiles and the number of automobiles by wealth. It\'s dangerous to be rich!\r\n','2007-11-17','2007-11-17 23:04:01'),(261,48,'DAM','<h3>Energy</h3>\r\nEnergy is basically total energy produced less energy used. Energy production is calculated, for each source, by considering how much total available energy there is from that source and how much investment has been put into that source. Energy use is calculated based on population per capita use. \r\n\r\nEvery kind of energy has a limit (solar panels: how much open space there is, nuclear: how much fissile materials, geothermal, hydro, tidal: how many suitable sites there are), an investment cost per megawatt of capacity (which isn\'t necessarily linear),  a cost per megawatt of production (which isn\'t necessarily linear) and some effect on the environment. Most effects will be to increase pollution (which will increase health problems) and to increase global warming. \r\n\r\nPer capita energy use is related to several factors. The population, the per capita wealth, the energy efficiency and the cost of energy are the main ones. How much energy a society \"needs\" is based on how much they can afford. I suspect that the amount of energy people want is related to the amount they can afford but if this is so then energy efficiency doesn\'t make any difference and it seems to keep growth down historically. So it seems like people have an amount of energy they WANT and then buy as close to that limit as they can afford. ','2007-11-17','2007-11-17 23:26:28'),(262,48,'DAM','<h3>Starvation</h3>\r\nHow much food can we grow? This is a very hard question. How much land do we have? How much topsoil does this land have? How much water? How much fertilizer? If a piece of land could be described in terms of how much food it can grow  \r\n\r\nOnce you know that, it\'s somewhat easier to figure out how much food people will eat -- unless they\'re North Americans. Essentially everyone will try to eat enough food to live. How much more food they will eat is an open question -- perhaps it can be related to how much money they have?','2007-11-17','2007-11-18 00:34:11'),(263,48,'DAM','<h3>Global Warming</h3>\r\nIf we simply gave each source of energy a CO2 footprint we should be able to just add up all the CO2 that they generate and that\'s the amount of CO2. Of course, today\'s CO2 affects us in the future and the affects we\'re feeling is really from a few decades back. \r\n\r\nThe question is, what, exactly, is the effect of this? I predict that global warming will reduce arable land, and reduce available water. It\'s hard to know the magnitude of these effects. On the positive side it might cause more sunlight and wind to fall on your solar panels and wind farms but that\'s not necessarily true. ','2007-11-17','2007-11-18 00:41:34'),(264,48,'DAM','<h3>Economics</h3>\r\nLike it or not, lots of things are tied to economics. We\'re going to have to simulate this, as well. ','2007-11-19','2007-11-19 17:10:01'),(265,58,'DAM','I deserve to be,\r\nI want to be,\r\nI can be,\r\nI will be,\r\nI am.','2007-12-22','2007-12-22 08:44:49'),(266,59,'DAM','This is a play whose purpose is to explore the debate between science and religion. The main characters are a married couple who have a young boy. They wish to send him to school and they are discussing what school to send him to. She wishes to send him to a scientific academy which will teach him technology, mathematics and science. He wishes to send him to a religious school which will teach him religion and art. Both schools teach the three Rs and are highly regarded generally. \r\n\r\nThe two obviously love each other but are each passionate about their own perspective. IF they make personal remarks it will always be in a loving way, with humor and respect (no cheap shots) and will always be received with chuckle or, at least, a wry smile. They each are well aware of their own foibles, failing and weaknesses as well as each others and they are quite comfortable with them, both privately and with each other. Essentially, this is a young couple with a young son who have been married 30 years and have explored all their personal issues and worked out their fears and aggressions. What\'s left is a deep abiding love and a willingness to work through issues and differences to come to what is best. In all probability, they wouldn\'t bother with this discussion except that each feels strongly about where to send the child.\r\n\r\nHe is religious, an emotional man, cares very deeply about his fellows and has some kind of soft profession -- teacher, nurse, social worker -- something in which he helps his fellow man and society. He believes in God, goes to church but is not constrained by doctrine or belief systems; rather he is caught up in the reverence of the sacred and the beauty of that which is greater than ourselves. \r\n\r\nShe is a rational clear thinker. She firmly believes that science, and especially the scientific method, will move us forward. We need to be rational and strong and stick to the facts and we can solve any problem. She has a technical job, scientist, engineer. (NOTE Maybe she is a doctor and he is a nurse; interesting?) She is not cold or emotionless -- she, after all, loves her husband and child -- but she has no use for \"irrational\" emotionalism. She tempers and controls her emotion with her intellect. \r\n\r\nThe play is structured like a debate. It would be nice to hide the stark structure in some plot but I\'m not that sophisticated yet. So, in my mind, the play takes place in 6 scenes. Each scene consists primarily of the two main characters talking together. They are\r\n1) Introduction -- we meet the characters become acquainted with their situation, personalities and dilemma; the stage is set.\r\n2) Argument for the pro -- one of them, lets say the man (religion), sets out his argument;  the case for religion is made. \r\n3) Rebuttal of the pro -- the woman now points out why she thinks the man\'s arguments are not persuasive\r\n4) Argument for the con -- the woman now sets out the argument for science.\r\n5) Rebuttal of the con -- the man now explains why he feels her argument is not conclusive for him.\r\n6) Resolution -- we have some kind of ending; I have no idea what. Maybe they decide to send the poor kid to a public school or maybe he gets hit by a bus which makes the issue moot.\r\n\r\nOne final note. I would love, LOVE, to have this be subtle. To have this be very dramatic and have all the arguments made in a non verbal way so that it doesn\'t come across as an hour of talking heads. I just don\'t know how to do that. \r\n\r\nOh, and, while I call it a play, I actually think of it as a short movie but only because I can conceive of how that might be done. \r\n','2007-12-28','2007-12-28 20:24:43'),(267,59,'DAM','<h3>ARGUMENTS FOR RELIGION</h3>\r\nNOTE: We\'re not talking about organized religion, we\'re talking about the argument for spirituality, emotionalism, humanity, the arts; in short everything in the right brain.\r\n1) Science is powerful but it has no guiding direction. Science without guiding morality brings us horrors. \r\n2) The human spirit wells up in the hearts of men with a longing that can be sated only with religion, art, music, poetry and other \"soft\" things; it cannot be sated with logic, fact or science.\r\n3) While it\'s possible that our emotional feeling that something exists that is greater than ourselves (whether you call it \"soul\" or \"spirit\" or \"god\") is simply delusion, it can\'t be proven that the physical is all there is. We are animate meat and that animation is mysterious even yet. \r\n','2007-12-28','2007-12-28 19:55:05'),(268,59,'DAM','<h3>ARGUMENTS FOR SCIENCE</h3>\r\n1) In many, many practical ways, religion and spirituality have gotten it wrong again and again. We owe our success as humans -- the very thing that allows us to have this conversation -- to the ability of reason to make our lives better and allow us to survive. \r\n2) There is no actual evidence for anything beyond the physical. Occam\'s Razor (you knew it had to come into it) requires that spirituality must not be real. Nothing goes bump in the night. \r\n3) All this \"soft\" artsy stuff is distracting and, ultimately, meaningless. We need to focus on what is real and valuable and get past this.  \r\n','2007-12-28','2007-12-28 19:54:47'),(269,59,'DAM','<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\nThe parents, after agonizing over the question for some time, conclude that they are arguing a false question. No one could teach their child Reason as well as his own mother who was so passionate and knowledgeable about it. And no one could teach their child Spirit as well as his own father for whom it was a natural state. So they each concluded that sending the child to a public school and then filling in it\'s deficiencies (as they perceive them) would be the best course. ','2007-12-28','2007-12-28 19:54:28'),(270,59,'DAM','<h3>Alternative Setting 1</h3>\r\nWhat if the little boy is a little girl. Every night her mother helps her untangle her hair and her father braids it for her. This is a sort of special time for each of them. Sometimes it\'s family time and sometimes it\'s just the parent and child.\r\n\r\nDuring these sessions the child (5 years old going on 20) and the parent discuss school. The mother talks to the little girl with passion about how lovely science is and the beauty of knowing things. And the father talks to the little girl about the spirit and how he looks forward to her learning of god and the wonders he brings. \r\n\r\nDuring each of these the child is an active participant, asking questions, listening with interest and expressing her interest. \r\n\r\nThis takes the place of the argument for the pro and the argument for the con but the two \"arguers\" aren\'t in the same room. \r\n\r\nThen the parents, perhaps, discuss the merits together. Maybe with her there but more likely after she has gone to bed. This takes the place of the rebuttals. They didn\'t need to be in the same room during the arguments; they each know exactly where the other stands.\r\n\r\nThen they sleep on it and the next morning work out the result. Perhaps the child points out the solution. Perhaps they are talking as they get themselves and their child ready for the day. They talk a bit and she listens quietly, absorbed in whatever she is doing. Then she says something like \"I wish you could be my teachers...\" It hangs in the air and then the parents exchange looks. They send her out of the room. One parent says, \"you know, maybe she\'s right: we could send her to a public school and teach her in the evenings and weekends. No one is better qualified than we are.\" The other parent silently looks thoughtful, not accepting the idea but giving it serious consideration. The piece should end with no specific resolution. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2007-12-28','2007-12-28 20:24:31'),(271,50,'DAM','','2007-12-30','2007-12-30 22:27:45'),(273,48,'DAM','The environment is a very complicated thing. By \"environment\" what I\'m really talking about is the world in which we try to live. I\'m sure with the discovery of global warming there are probably environmentalists who are congratulating themselves. \"We were right all along! And they didn\'t listen!\"\r\n\r\nBut they weren\'t right, not really. Sure, some of what they said we should do we should, in fact do. But other things were just wrong-headed. And all for the wrong reasons. We don\'t need to save the planet, we need to save ourselves. \r\n\r\nFor example, I saw an article in which environmentalists demanded that we take apart the great dams to return the rivers to their natural state. This would certainly save the planet but it would certainly harm efforts to prevent global climate change (because the dams would be replaced by some kind of power source that burns carbon). \r\n\r\nOf course, they had good ideas, too. Deforestation is a bad idea and environmentalists have always been against. Until recently, however, the call seemed to be to preserve the forests rather than to harvest them sustainably. The truth is that we\'re going to get wood from SOMEWHERE and if it\'s not sustainably from somewhere close to home than we\'ll destroy some rain forest somewhere -- it\'s inevitable. \r\n\r\nBut now we seem to be lining up behind the idea that we want to do thing sustainably. It\'s OK to use power but try to preserve it. It\'s OK to harvest forests but only sustainably. We need to protect the environment but the priority is on making it livable and sustainable, rather than to make it pristine and aesthetic. \r\n\r\nNot that I\'m against aesthetics but I\'m going to ask over an over again this question: how many people will have to die to allow you to preserve that aesthetic? Because the difference between a few less dams (and a few more carbon-emitting power plants) or a few more old-growth forests (and a few more denuded rain forests) could be, ultimately, the difference between a global temperature rise that will kill thousands and one that will kill millions. \r\n\r\nGiven this complexity and the effect of unintended consequences (and the extreme stakes), how can we possibly know what to do? We can\'t really. I\'m pretty sure that if the greatest minds in the world tried to design an environment that could sustain billions of people they would not agree on an opening statement for the symposium, much less come up with a plan. There are too many variables and uncertainties. \r\n\r\nBut we actually have a much harder problem than to determine what the perfect result ought to be: we have to figure out how to get there. \r\n\r\nOddly, we can say with some confidence what direction we need to go in right now, even if we don\'t know where we\'re going or how to get there. It\'s fairly obvious that we need to use less of pretty much everything, especially petroleum. And how to use less petroleum is fairly obvious: we as consumers should stop driving and we should immediately vote huge \"carbon taxes\" on pretty much everything. Such carbon taxes will make all kinds of alternatives practical  (simply by making petroleum artificially expensive now, instead of waiting until it becomes naturally expensive) while at the same time, funding government backed research and subsidies. The sooner we do this, the more we can mitigate the terrible cost of running out of oil suddenly without anything in place to replace it. \r\n\r\nThis will require tremendous sacrifices here in the developed world and will impose hardships on the developing world, as well. How big the relative hardships depend on the details of implementation but most it depends on whether you live in developed or developing country. Is it worse to have to give up luxuries to which you\'ve become accustomed or to never have those luxuries in the first place? And how many angels CAN dance on the head of a pin? \r\n\r\nMy friend suggests that the most important issues, the overriding thing that, if addressed could address all other problems, is energy. After considering this carefully, I have to disagree. I believe the key to everything is population. If we can\'t stabilize our population we can never get a handle on any other issue because we can continue to increase our population until we run out of something else (probably energy). If we CAN control out population then we can, presumably, gradually bring it to a sustainable level where we WOULD have enough energy (and water, and food, and everything else). \r\n\r\nBut, practically speaking, controlling our population is even harder than increasing our energy production. Who in the developed world would willingly accept a limit on their parenthood? And there are many millions in the world who believe it is there religious duty to have as many children as possible along with many more millions who could not be compelled to limit their progeny simply because there is no government stable enough in their part of the world to impose such a rule. \r\n\r\nThe problem of energy also seems intractable. Unless you believe that the world oil supply is actually infinite and that the problem is therefor one of production, we\'re going to run out of oil. And, because the growth curves are all exponential, we\'ll blow through what\'s left MUCH faster than we used up the same quantity before that. The threat is that we\'ll run out of oil before we have developed replacement energy sources, even though the price of oil will go  through the roof, making all kinds of energy more \"affordable\" (compared to oil). \r\n\r\nThe key issue about energy is investment. If we had an infinite amount of investment, we could build an infinite amount of solar panels (and hydrogen plants to generate power at night) and we\'d all be saved. But the cost of all those solar plants (assuming we could afford to have that much ground shielded from the sun) makes it impractical to do immediately. \r\n\r\nWe need two things: time and money! We can buy time but conservation and we can get money through taxation. It sounds too simple to be true but an immediate carbon tax would both generate a lot of money and force a lot of conservation. And the only reason why we haven\'t done it yet is that various people are still making too much money from the current structure to be willing to change it. And, of course, those of us who drive cars are afraid of what the taxes will do to our budgets.\r\n','2008-01-12','2008-01-12 19:52:27'),(272,50,'DAM','','2007-12-30','2007-12-30 22:27:37'),(274,4,'DAM','','2008-01-20','2008-03-04 06:27:35'),(275,62,'DAM','Things I care about wrt politics\r\neconomy\r\nwar\r\necology\r\n','2008-01-22','2008-01-23 03:31:56'),(276,51,'defer',' glimage                           \r\n glimagetype                       \r\n glpartyimage                      \r\n glpersonimage                     \r\nGlparty image is a list of images that are associated with a party. I don\'t have any of those currently but I should. \r\nglperson image is a list of images that are associated with a person. Don\'t have any of those, either.\r\n\r\nThe idea is that these two link tables contain a connection between an image in glimage and a person or party. The persons are connected by player # while the parties are connected by date. \r\n\r\nThe problem currently is that I don\'t know which party the pictures were taken at and that I have dozens of parties at which there were taken no pictures. ','2008-01-28','2008-01-28 22:01:50'),(277,63,'DAM','<h2>One Thing</h2>\r\nIn the beginning there was one thing. Call it \"god\", call it \"the singularity\", call it whatever you want. The key thing to understand is that, when there is only one thing it has no name for there is no one there to name it. \r\n\r\nWe must be very clear on this point: if there is only one thing it has no attributes or descriptions, no name, no thoughts. It just exists and not even that in any way that we can really comprehend. \r\n\r\nOne day the One Thing had a thought. Call it the \"word\" or the \"wisdom\" or whatever you want. At that moment there were only 3 things in existence and none of them were names. \r\n\r\nThis is my second big point. It is not possible for there to be only two things in existence. Yes, you can have a box and that box can have 2 things in it but what you mean by that is that there are 2 things, not counting the box and everything outside the box. So, what else is in the box? Why, nothing! And how can you tell the two things apart: is there something between them? Well, just the box and the empty space in the box and we said we\'d ignore that. If we don\'t ignore the space between the two things then how many things are in the box? Well, 3 but that doesn\'t make any sense -- I mean by unspoken agreement we always ignore the space between things!\r\n\r\nIf you have only two things in existence (if you could call that existence) then you must have a third thing. The fact that there is one thing and then another distinct thing requires that there be a separation between the two things. If there wasn\'t the separation there would be only one thing.\r\n\r\nAt the instant of the thought, we went from one thing to three things. Now it gets kind of interesting. \r\n\r\nWe have separation. On one side of the separation we have the thing that thought (the subject, if you will) and on the other side we have the thing that is being thought (the object, if you like). Both sides of the divide are really the same thing -- the divide itself is, indeed, the same thing. But at the instant of the Thinking of the Thought the three things took on different characters. \r\n\r\n','2008-02-24','2013-02-19 00:16:50'),(278,63,'DAM','<h2>Spiritual Book</h2>\r\n2/18/2013 I grabbed this from book parts and put it here where it belongs. Is this repeat stuff? \r\n<h2>Why Are You Here</h2>\r\n9/18\r\nWhy are you here? It\'s a good question. In a sense it\'s the only question. If you knew why you\'d know what you are, the nature of god and the circumstances under which you would leave. Why is the key that opens all the doors.\r\n\r\nBut neither science nor religion is very good at they \"why\" question. The best we seem to do is the what and how and then synthesize  the why from that. Or we just make it up, creating god, in effect, in our own image. \r\n\r\nI think the why is hard because it involves the reasons of the creator. The thing about the creator (which is especially true if you don\'t believe in a creator) is that he/she/it isn\'t a reasoning creature like us. Reasoning beings do things for reasons and hence, they change their mind when the reasons change and do something different. No being who could consturct this universe, with it\'s perfectly consistent laws, could be so flighty, so inconsistent, so reasonable. \r\n\r\nI think why is a hard question because there simply is no why. We\'re here in this particular why because this is how god is. Perhaps this is what was meant in the bible by man being created in god\'s image.\r\n\r\nIn the beginning the spiritual person is like a scientist. He makes observations, tries things and concludes stuff from what happens. It\'s a journey of discovery. We seek so that we may find answers about the universe and, sometimes, ourselfs. Sometimes it\'s a journey to find ourselves or even to fix ourselves, although not everyone takes that on. \r\n\r\nEventually one finds oneself and one discovers that one is not broken. \r\n\r\nOne begins to hear that quiet voice that seems to be speaking to you inside your head but which is really a distant echo of god\'s thought. Sometimes I describe it as the universe speaking to. Gradually one begins to trust it and then to depend on it  A family of racoons or a wood pecker or the name of your campsite take on special meaning. \r\n\r\nBefore you hear and see clearly you are seeking. But once you are firmly on the path there is no seeking. You are simply following directions. \r\n\r\nWhy? It\'s not out of necessity or curiosity or obligation. It\'s just how you\'re made. Your purpose is clear and you follow it \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Topics</h2>\r\nHere are some things I might want to write about\r\n\r\n<li>time, space, self: a trinity of illusions\r\n<li>what are we doing here?\r\n<li>who are you\r\n<li>be kind to yourself\r\n<li>your presonality; not you but awfully compelling\r\n<li>the third option\r\n<li>do you want to be better\r\n\r\n<h2>Who are you? </h2>\r\nIf you pick up this book it has to be because you want answers. You either don\'t think you know much about spirituality or you don\'t think you know enough. I\'m sure my publisher will not be pleased with me for telling you this but you already know everything you need to know about spirituality. Everything you need to know about life, the other people around you, who you are, what you need to do and how to do it is already available to you. Those of you who are still reading are waiting for me to explain what I mean by that. \r\n\r\nWho are you? \r\nAre you like the rocks and wind and the house that you live in? Or are you something different? \r\n\r\nAre you even like the grass and the trees? Those things are alive just as you are.\r\n\r\nWhat about the animals? I\'m here to tell you that dogs and cats (and birds and squirrels and even some flies I\'ve encountered) have attitudes and, in the case of dogs and cats, personalities. I knew a cat once that really hated me and made it\'s feeling very clear to me at every opportunity.\r\n\r\nAre you like the animals? \r\n\r\nI think we share many characteristics with all these things. Like the rocks we are made up of chemical compounds. Like the trees, we are alive. Like the squirrels we have attitudes and, like that little kitty cat, we have personalities (I didn\'t like the cat, either). \r\n\r\nBut we are also very different from all these things. I really didn\'t like that cat but I would never do anything to hurt it because I care for it\'s feelings. As far as we know, only we can take into consideration other people\'s feelings. People, among all the species on Earth, are the only ones who ponder their relationship to everyone and everything else, the only ones who consider their place in the universe. \r\n\r\nFor those of you who are thinking \"But what about dolphins or monkeys or whales; they seem like they might also be smart enough to consider their place in the universe\" I answer \"If so then they are people, too. Feel free to read this book to them.\" The point is not that you are better than all the other entities on the Earth. \r\n\r\nThe point is simplely that you are special in that you have a relationship with that wich is greater than yourself. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>The Eternal</h2>\r\n\r\nLike every other kind of life, we\'re born, we grow old, and we die. We experience the world as distinct from us and from each other. I\'m not you and he\'s not you and all those plants are separate. What\'s more we like to make up categories: plants vs animals vs inanimate objects. It\'s the way our brains work.\r\n\r\nIn short, we experience time and space and self. This is natural and, actually, pretty useful. This is how you find your car in the parking lot and find your house among all the other houses and manage to be on time for appointments. These preceptions come from our powerful minds. \r\n\r\nWe\'ve built elaborate systems that, for all practical purpose, master the world. For the most part, wild animals don\'t eat us, hunger doesn\'t wrack our bodies and violence doesn\'t stalk us. Well, except of course when it does. \r\n\r\nYou might well lament how many people are hungry and how much violence goes on but that\'s only because that\'s the natural state of animals. Being people, we\'ve used our wonderful minds and our tool-making hands to create a world in which those things are the sad exception instead of the universal rule. \r\n\r\nBut time, space, and self are actually a trinity of illusions. The universe is composed of only one thing, timeless, locationless and consisting of only one being. I, like many others, call this one thing, \"The Eternal.\" Sometimes I just use the term \"The Universe\", mainly because \"The Eternal\" is often used to describe a deity that is part of certain religions and I don\'t want to be confused for a member of a religion.\r\n\r\nOnce, there was no illusion. The one thing, the Eternal, sat silent, thoughtless, ecompassing everything, thinking nothing. It just was. Imagine what that might be like: there is only one thing so it can\'t be anywhere (because it\'s everywhere), there can be no time because nothing ever changes. \r\n\r\nInevitably, there was an awareness. I always think of this as \"happening\" but that\'s because I\'m caught up in the illusion of time. In reality, the awareness must always have existed simply because there was no time. \r\n\r\nThe existence of a thought brings into being a trinity. Clearly there is the thought and the thinker which makes two things. But there is a third thing, as well because, in order to have two things, there must be a separation between them. \r\n\r\nI say a \"thought\" but it was more like an awareness. The awareness might be thought of as the mind of the eternal while the eternal itself is pure spirit. The separation between the two might be thought of as the physical body. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhen you have dreams who is in your dreams? You might dream of a friend or a girl you met or a house or a car. But is that friend or girl or house or car in your dream? \r\n\r\nEverything in your dream was invented by you, the dreamer. You are all the parts played in your dream, all the things in your dream. You may not be aware of it but you are calling all the shots. \r\n\r\nTime is meaningless in a dream. Your dream may go on for hours or days or weeks inside your head but only takes a few minutes in real time. A few minutes of a night of sleep and whole worlds are created populated by people who have feelings and who love and do things. \r\n\r\nAnd it\'s all you. \r\n\r\nWe\'re the dream that was dreamt by the Eternal. The Eternal knows no time and now space but in the dream there is time and space. The Eternal is just One but in the dream there are many, many of us. We have feelings an emotions and we experience it all as reality. But it\'s just a dream. NOt our dream, mind you, but an illusion nevertheless. \r\n\r\nGiven that the is only one thing what does that make us? If good and bad, rich and poor, right and wrong are all just the one thing, the one dreamer who dreams us, then who are we and how do we relate? \r\n\r\nThere is only one thing and we\'re it, all of us, all the time. \r\n\r\nIf you truly believed that, it would change your life profoundly. Think about it for a bit. That guy trying to scam a few bucks from you, that salesman trying to sell you something you don\'t need, that person you\'re trying to persuade to give you something -- if they are all you\r\n\r\n<h2>The Game Designer</h2>\r\n6/9/10\r\nI often reflect that god must be a game designer. He certainly is like a game designer in many ways. \r\n\r\nFor example, he has created an environment that is not \"Real\" (at least not from the perspective of a timeless, spaceless entity)  and is utterly self consistent. \r\n\r\nAnd god must be very consistent or physics simply wouldn\'t work. \r\n\r\nI suppose part of why I think about this is that I was a  game developer for some time. But it\'s also because of Shroedenger\'s cat. \r\n\r\nBriefly, the cat is in a box and it\'s fate depended on a single sub atomic particle. If it did one thing, the cat died, if it did something else the cat lived. Now the cat is still in the box. You would think it would be either dead or alive now but according to Shroedenger the cat is both alive and dead until someone opens the box. \r\n\r\nThis is a very weird thing to understand but it\'s not uncommon in the world of Quantum Mechanics for an event to be dependent on someone seeing it. This is just a thought experiment -- no cat was actually killed (or even put in a box) but in many experiments what electrons and other tiny particles do depends on whether or not someone is watching. \r\n\r\nThis same things happens in video games. The monster doesn\'t actually spawn until the player shows up. In comptuer games this is done to save computer resources. All the resources are concentrated on the player. Perhaps god isn\'t interested in paying attention to tiny objects that no one can see. \r\n\r\nIn this place we call the universe, it weems to work the same way. Imagine that: the largest MMO ever creates, in 1:1 scale, played by everon who has ever lived!\r\n\r\nBut what\'s the point? \r\n\r\nHuman game developers do games for the amusement of other humans. Did god write his game for other god\'s? \r\n\r\nSort of. Ther is only one thing. Everything is an aspect of that one universal thing. In a way, we are the gods for whom the game was invented. In another way, it\'s really a solitaire game. \r\n\r\nBut what\'s the point (again with the points...)? How do you win?\r\n\r\nPerhaps, like most MMO RPGs, you don\'t win, you just play and play, getting better and better at playing. Are you getting better at playing? \r\n\r\n<h2>God Loves Us</h2>\r\nBeyond the edge of my conscious perception, I can feel the universe flicker. \r\n\r\nI think that god is re-recating each moment of time, instant by instant. Each instant he recreates the world almost like it was, including all the history and everything we remember. The only changes he allows are those that are caused by the interaction of everything with everything else -- the effects of time. \r\n\r\nHe must love us very much because we\'re all still here.  Think about it for a minute. If he didn\'t love you personally, would you still be here? Your existence proof of your creator\'s love for you. If god didn\'t love you he would have edited you out!\r\n\r\nI grant that if our perception and memory is so easily fooled we may all be replacements for characters he didn\'t lover. Maybe we just got here and our memories, like everything else, are just illusions. \r\n\r\nMaybe. But we\'re here now! So he loves you. He put you here special, just like this, and if god put you her, you must be really ok. Better than OK. Really good. \r\n\r\nIf you\'re basically OK, maybe you can relax a little. Don\'t be quite so hard on yourseld. Yes you probably have faults, you probably make mistakes, you probably aren\'t living up to your potential. But you are not inherently bad. If you were basically a sinner, god would have simply removed you a long time ago. \r\n\r\nYes you need to eat better, get more sleep, spend less time watching TV and more doing productive things. Work on stuff like that instead of beating yourself up about things you\'ve done and thinking about how it all must prove that your bad, blah blah blah.\r\n\r\nStop worrying about it and get ready for whatever is next. Become a better player not a regretful player. \r\n\r\n----\r\n<h2>THE BIG LIE</h2>\r\n\r\nI\'m a fraud. You\'ve been reading this book all thsi time and I\'ve been telling you all this stuff as it it\'s true. \r\n\r\nHere\'s a news flash: it\'s all true. \r\n\r\nBut, so is the opposite.\r\n\r\nAnd it\'s all false.\r\n\r\nAnd so is the opposite. \r\n\r\nEvery thing that is and isn\'t, can be or ever can\'t be is true somewhere somehow. \r\n\r\nNow I don\'t look so smart, do I!\r\n\r\nSo how do you know, how do you tell what\'s true and what isn\'t?\r\n\r\nWell, first off, what are you trying to do? Why do you care what\'s true and what isn\'t?\r\n\r\nIf you\'re just trying to be certain about something then it doesn\'t really matter what that something is. Pick the flavor of \"proof\" that you like and run with it. Good luck with that. \r\n\r\nbut if you\'re trying to be a better person then you want to believe in stuff that will help.\r\n\r\nBut how can you know in advance what will make you a better person. How can you know what to do, what to believe?\r\n\r\nI have some really bad news for you. You can know. You can\'t be fixed.\r\n\r\nAnd I have some good news: you can\'t be fixed because you aren\'t broken. \r\n\r\nIt\'s bad news because you aren\'t happy and you feel that if only you were broken you could be fixed and then be happy. But it\'s really good news too.\r\n\r\nYou cannot know what the right thing to do is unless the right thing is knowable by you.\r\n\r\nSure I can tell you some stuff. But what does that get you? Some one else will tell you some thing different. How do you pick, if you don\'t have the ability to tell the good stuff from the bad stuff, the right stuff from the wrong stuff? \r\n\r\nThe only possible hope you have to know what\'s right, what true, is to be able to tell on your own. And that would only be true if you aren\'t broken. \r\n\r\nSo either you\'re broken and can\'t ever be fixed (because, being broken, you can\'t figure out what to do to fix yourself) OR you\'re not broken. \r\n\r\nAssume you\'re OK. Now that you\'re already fixed, now that you\'re a part of god and know that you are loved, what looks right to you? Do you want to give that homeless buy a quarter or walk on by? Smile or frown? Be friendly or sullen. \r\n\r\nYou may think that you\'re getting my point: give the guy a quarter, smile and be friendly.\r\n\r\nbut that\'s not at all my point! I\'m saying do whatever the heck you feel is right in the moment. \r\n\r\nyou, you personally , are the standard of your own right behavior. Once you stop asking the question (you know what question: the one about whether you\'re OK) and just do what\'s in your heart you can\'t go wrong. \r\n\r\nExcept when you do. You\'ll know that, too. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-02-24','2013-02-19 00:38:50'),(279,63,'DAM','At this point I\'d like to stop and talk about belief and knowledge, preference and certainty.\r\n\r\nSo far what I\'ve described is what a friend of mine once dismissed as a an \"origin myth.\" He said that every culture had them, as if that meant that they weren\'t of any value. But I agree with him that they are not true in the normal sense of truth.\r\n\r\nAn origin myth is just a story that someone tells to explain his observations. He sees that the world is a certain way and he tells a story that explains how it got that way. I don\'t know why, exactly. Maybe the author needs to justify his observations or maybe explain them or maybe for some other reason. But whatever his motivation, I think origin myths are useful to explain the observations. It seems to me to be much clearer to explain how things are by saying how they got that way than to simply say how things are. \r\n\r\nIt\'s like they were saying \"Once upon a time there was a god. And he was angry with his fellow gods. So he engaged in a war with them. And that is what is going on in storms. \" As a modern listener to these myths you may think they\'re ridiculous but you no doubt find yourself thinking \"so he finds the storms to be violent and dangerous?\" -- you understand what the belief is and you can make good inferences about what the person\'s experience is. On the whole, it\'s a pretty useful thing. You know a lot about the story teller when you hear the story he tells. \r\n\r\nTo be specific, I do not know for a fact that the story I\'ve just told is true. I wasn\'t there, I have no evidence, either internal or external (more about that in a moment) about the story, the \"origin myth\" that I just told. But I like it. Of all the origin myths I\'ve heard, it seems to fit my observations best. \r\nSo I have no evidence that this is how the world came to be but I have evidence of how the world *is*. \r\n\r\nEvidence comes in two flavors which I will call internal and external. Internal evidence consists of experiences I have had that I cannot directly share with you. It may be possible for you to have a similar experience and, based on this commonality, to recognize what I\'m describing and believe that I experienced it. But I can\'t SHOW it to you. External evidence is evidence which I can hold under your nose to \"prove\" to you that what I say is true. \r\n\r\nYou would think that there is a huge difference. After all, if I have external evidence you HAVE to believe me, right? Well, no. The correct statement is that if I don\'t have external evidence, you will almost certainly NOT believe me. But there are people who believe that we are often visited by extra-terrestrial beings (and people who don\'t). Or who believe in Big Foot (or who don\'t). Or who believe that the earth is flat. Or that we never landed on the moon Or that the Holocaust never happened Or that the Theory of Evolution is wrong. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, there are people who fervently believe internal evidence. Jesus arose from the dead, God exists, George W. Bush is a genius or whatever. \r\nThe lines get pretty muddied here. \"How can you believe that?\" or \"How can you not believe this?\" are pretty common questions. \r\n\r\nI\'ve come to think that you can\'t really prove anything. You may know it to be true and you may be able to make a very persuasive argument for it but the listener, ultimately, gets to decide if you have \"proved\" your proposition. You have no direct control over that. Even among scientists who, presumably, all agree on the same standards of proof (that it be reproducible) don\'t seem to agree on almost anything. There are still scientists who don\'t accept that global warming is real, that evolution is the best explanation of natural history and I would not be surprised to discover that some scientists believe the world is flat. You may say, \"if a scientist doesn\'t believe the world is round, he\'s not a real scientist.\" But can you prove it?\r\n\r\nIt\'s in this context that I make a distinction between things I know to be true (because I have experienced some kind of internal evidence) and things that I think might be true (because they seem plausible based on the things I know). \r\n\r\nClearly, just because I know something to be true doesn\'t mean that you know it to be true or even think it might be true. I accept that I can\'t prove anything to you. \r\n\r\nBut if I can\'t talk about what I know because it\'s impossible to prove it then I essentially can\'t talk about anything. This book, then, is an attempt to cut the Gordian Knot and simply say what I know and let the chips fall where they may.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-02-28','2008-03-10 05:53:42'),(280,65,'DAM','First, here is the URL for Ari\'s Laboratory: \r\nhttp://www.arischindler.com/game/strategy/','2008-03-03','2008-03-03 22:01:36'),(281,65,'Ari','1) There are two key game models - Strategy and Adventure. Strategy\r\ncovers all games with area movement, where players fight for control of\r\nterritories, raising and deploying leaders, troops, and production\r\nfacilities. Adventure covers all games with area movement, where players\r\nroam between territories, collecting and recruiting leaders, troops, and\r\nequipment. For user interface reasons more than anything else, both\r\nmodels currently assume the fastest rate of strategic movement is one\r\nterritory per turn - so this works very well for armies on the march,\r\nspaceships jumping from system to system, and even short range aircraft\r\nthat are bound to nearby basing facilities, but doesn\'t really for\r\nscenarios where some aircraft or fleets are supposed to have global\r\nreach within a turn.\r\n\r\n2) A core design principal is that both game models will use the same\r\ndata models and unit attributes, such that, in theory, an Adventure game\r\ncould be layered inside a Strategy game with matching data. For\r\ninstance, there could be a Middle Earth Strategy game where players move\r\narmies around fighting over territory, with a Middle Earth Adventure\r\ngame layered inside - parties in the Adventure game would have to worry\r\nabout the titanic battles and shifts in territory happening around them,\r\nand could even participate in those battles should they end up in the\r\nright place at the right time. At some point, we may be able to fuse\r\nboth models entirely, but we aren\'t going to let that possibility divert\r\nus from launching them separately.\r\n\r\n3) The basic data types are Player, Universe (like Lord of the Rings\r\nversus Dune), Scenario (like Battle of Minas Tirith versus Battle of\r\nHelm\'s Deep), Game (each individual match of a given Scenario in\r\nprogress), Location (a specific area on the map), Route (a connection\r\nbetween Locations), Unit (like Sauron, the 1st Airborne, ICBM Factory,\r\nor British Parliament), Attack Type (like Particle Beam or Slashing\r\nWeapon), Defense Type (like Force Field or Elvish Armor), Mobility Type\r\n(like Legs or Treads), Terrain Type (like Stargate or Jungle or City).\r\n\r\n4) Each Location has a Name, Owner ID, and Terrain ID.\r\n\r\n5) Locations are connected via Routes. There can be multiple Routes\r\nbetween any two Locations. Each Route has a Name, Length, and Terrain\r\nID. I\'m leaning towards having a Width as well - consider the pass at\r\nThermopylae versus the steppes between Russia and Ukraine, or for that\r\nmatter, all the different types of tunnels in an underground war between\r\norcs and dwarves.\r\n\r\n6) Units have a Name, Owner ID, Attack Rating, Attack Type ID, Defense\r\nRating, Defense Type ID, Range, Mobility Rating, Mobility Type ID,\r\nDetection Rating, Detection Type ID, Stealth Rating, and Stealth Type ID.\r\n\r\n7) Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Attack Type IDs to\r\nDefense Type IDs to yield a base fatality rate, which is then multiplied\r\nby the attacker\'s Attack Rating and divided by the Defender\'s Defense\r\nRating to determine the chance of Destroying or Disrupting a target unit\r\nin an attack.\r\n\r\n8) Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Detection Type IDs to\r\nStealth Type IDs, to yield a base detection rate, which is then\r\nmultiplied by the detector\'s Detection Rating and divided by the\r\ntarget\'s Stealth Rating to determine the chance of Detecting the target\r\nunit.\r\n\r\n9) Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Mobility Type ID with\r\nTerrain Type ID to yield a base speed, which is then multiplied by the\r\nunit\'s Mobility Rating and divided by the Length of a Route to determine\r\nthe chance of that unit crossing that route in one turn. In combat, a\r\nsimilar computation is done to determine what kind of mobility each unit\r\nhas in that combat situation.\r\n\r\n10) Production is handled like a card game, rather than with production\r\npoints or the like. So each unit has list of preconditions for\r\ndeployment attached to it, like Locations it can be deployed in, Units\r\nthat must be in the same place to deploy it, Units that must be owned by\r\nthe deploying player or his enemy, etc. As part of each turn a number of\r\nUnits are drawn from the deck for each player, and added to their hand -\r\nthe number of Units drawn, the number that can be in hand, etc are\r\nparameters of each scenario and also tied to the Units in play according\r\nto rules that still need work. But the basic idea is that each player\r\ncan see what Units are on his horizon and the conditions for deploying\r\neach, and then fights to make those conditions happen. This basically\r\nfuses industrial production with politics and diplomacy into a single\r\nunified approach to bringing Units into the game, and adds some exciting\r\nuncertainty as well.','2008-03-03','2008-03-03 22:07:35'),(282,65,'DAM','There is also the information about players. In addition to having a real name and a login name, players should also be allowed to have a \"game name\" -- that is, a pseudonym that they can use for any given game. Players may have any number of pseudonyms but only one user name/account. In most cases, a player will only be allowed one position in a game (although I can think of some exceptions) and some players will try to get around this rule by having multiple accounts -- thus giving them an unshakable \"ally\" in the game. Since catching players doing this is such a pain in the ass, players who ARE caught are summarily kicked off without recourse (although they are always free to appeal the decision -- but the person to whom they appeal is the person who made the decision). \r\nIn database terms, all this requires two more tables (one for the user information and one for the pseudonym info). \r\nBecause players are human (more or less -- let us not quibble), they will try all kinds of bullshit. So that suggests another table for logging everything everyone does to allow us to figure out what nefarious things were perpetrated on us. \r\nBecause the game designers & programmers are human (again, let us no quibble) we need history tables on each game so that we can get back to the original data after some kind of catastrophic failure.  ','2008-03-03','2008-03-03 23:58:47'),(283,65,'DAM','Having spent about half my professional career screwing around with nasty internal data structures (things can get complicated when you are extremely constrained by computing power, memory AND time), I have long resolved to use standard databases to do all my games in future. \r\nSo far I have gained significant ability with MYSQL, which is the DB of choice for PHP which is my favorite language. There may be another data database that has some better feature set but it MUST be an SQL-based *relational* database. MS Access just isn\'t going to cut it!\r\nAs much as possible, all the work done on data is done by the database engine (which, we hope, is optimized for it), not in the program. Proper database use requires that all data be organized according to the \"normal forms\" which apparently looks to some people like unnecessary extra work but actually makes for a more efficient and maintainable database. \r\nAnother requirement that I will lay out here with respect to databases is to avoid calling stored functions from code. This will allow us to change databases at will since accessing and manipulating the databases is standardized across all SQL databases but calling stored functions IS NOT. (\"Once burnt, twice shy.\")','2008-03-03','2008-03-04 00:26:29'),(284,65,'DAM','Some random notes\r\n\r\n3: It seems to me that some of these are universal tables and some of these are associated with scenarios or games. For example, there is only one table with all the universes in it (by which I mean their ID and color information such as name, description and various associated images) but there almost certainly be one table of units for each game (that is, there won\'t be one huge table of units for all the games in the system). This is kind of a complicated issue and I need to tease apart a lot of considerations.\r\n\r\n5 Routes: I assume that routes are one directional? They almost have to be since there are some kinds of structures that are very interesting and require unidirectional routes. The more common bi-directional routes can be implemented by simply having two unidirectional routes. \r\n\r\nThere are some edge cases where this system becomes kind of ugly. Consider (as I have) a trading game set on the Mediterranean. There are 100 cities (I didn\'t say it was historically accurate) and any one can be moved to from any other one in a turn. This suggests a 100X100 routes = 10,000 routes. And, since every route is unidirectional and I want them to be bidirectional, I need 20,000 routes. This is in the range where I begin to think about computational efficiency. A simple special rule (\"any unit can move to any space in a turn\") eliminates all this data. \r\n\r\nI think widths are important but, obviously, they have to be considered in the combat resolution system which may make it very complicated.\r\n\r\nAlso, some system that makes it possible for some routes to be hidden under some circumstances would be good. Thermopylae has been invoked and, if I remember correctly, the outcome was ultimately decided by the Persians finding a different, lesser known, route. It makes for some interesting game play...\r\n\r\n6 Units should also have other \"flavor\" elements besides name. A description, various images and so forth. Because this game system is generic, adding as much flavor as possible is crucial to making each game appear unique to the user. \r\n\r\nTerrain is one of those things that might be universal but I can\'t really see much point. Probably better to have \"rough\" terrain in the Tolkein universe to be completely different from the \"rough\" terrain in the WWII universe. You will note that the actual effects on movement will be different in each universe, anyway; I\'m just saying there is no point in sharing names and descriptions. \r\n\r\n10:production -- this is a deep and complicated issue. It seems like a very wide set of effects can be achieved depending on the preconditions and the set of \"cards\" that are available to be drawn on any given turn. It\'s also possible that some obvious, simple effects cannot be achieved for a given implementation  of this. Can I do research? Can I pick what I want to produce? Can I have special production sites that allow for changing existing units? It\'s not clear to me that all these things can be done nor, if they can be done, what implementation details are required.\r\n','2008-03-03','2008-03-11 02:41:32'),(321,66,'DAM','','2008-03-03','2008-03-30 19:30:56'),(322,17,'DAM','The basic idea here is that each player has a certain amount of money and he uses this money to purchase one or more tanks or other systems. Then the players play the game within a scenario. \r\n\r\nMaybe a single game involves buying a bunch of stuff and then playing to the death or maybe you play a series of battles so you really want to be cautious. \r\n\r\nThe tank design will involve a variety of different types (ultra light through ultra heavy) with various things you can add on (a light chassis can\'t hold as much as a heavy chassis) such as guns, missiles, troop transport (?), radio gear, armor, etc, etc. You also get an HQ which you can trick out with things like mobility, armor, defending troops, sigint equipment, weapons, etc, etc. You can even buy (for a very high price) satellites and such like. \r\n\r\nYou can program your tanks to be somewhat autonomous (requires brain unit) or you can control them from the HQ. Tanks that are controlled from the HQ are potentially prone to jamming, sigint, signal homing missiles and so forth. Tanks that are autonomous are prone to extreme stupidity. \r\n\r\nThere are a lot of different games that can be played with the same stuff. \r\n','2008-04-12','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(323,49,NULL,NULL,'2008-04-02','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(324,60,NULL,NULL,'2008-04-02','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(325,61,NULL,NULL,'2008-04-02','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(326,64,NULL,NULL,'2008-04-02','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(327,67,NULL,NULL,'2008-04-02','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(328,68,NULL,NULL,'2008-04-02','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(329,69,NULL,NULL,'2008-04-02','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(330,61,'DAM','','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:46:24'),(331,61,'DAM','','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:46:32'),(332,61,'DAM','','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:46:40'),(333,61,'DAM','','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:46:53'),(334,61,'DAM',' ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:47:05'),(335,71,'DAM','  ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:47:32'),(336,71,'DAM','  ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:47:41'),(337,72,'','  ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:47:56'),(338,73,'',' ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:48:06'),(339,73,'','  ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:48:51'),(340,79,'',' ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 01:49:00'),(285,65,'DAM','\"road to rapid completion\"\r\nDesign\r\n	document the data models \r\n	document interfaces for editing  data models,\r\nPrototype \r\n	implement those interfaces\r\n	plug in test data sets for a couple of different universes. \r\n	build the interface for players to create accounts\r\n	build the interface for players to create games\r\n	build the interface for players to join games \r\n	build the interface for players to issue orders\r\nmake the games barely playable\r\n	plug in primitive production, \r\n	plug in primitive movement, \r\n	plug in primitive combat engines \r\ndo the full implementation of the combat engine such that all of these unit attributes really shine.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-03-03','2008-03-11 02:42:39'),(286,65,'DAM','Game models Table \r\nplayer table\r\nuniverse table\r\nscenario table\r\ngame table\r\nlocation table\r\n	name\r\n	owner\r\n	terrain\r\n	?\r\n	\r\nroute table\r\n	from location\r\n	to location\r\n	name\r\n	length\r\n	terrain \r\n	width\r\n	\r\nunit table\r\n	name\r\n	description\r\n	image\r\n	owner\r\n	attack rating\r\n	attack type\r\n	defense rating\r\n	defense type\r\n	range\r\n	mobility rating\r\n	mobility type\r\n	detection rating\r\n	detection type\r\n	stealth rating\r\n	stealth type\r\nattack type\r\ndefense type\r\nmobility type\r\nterrain type\r\nunit type table \r\nAttackDefense\r\n	Universe\r\n	AttackType\r\n	DefenseType\r\n	BaseAttrition\r\nDetectionStealth\r\n	Universe\r\n	DetectionType\r\n	StealthType\r\n	BaseDetection\r\nMobilityTerrain\r\n	Universe\r\n	MobilityType\r\n	TerrainType\r\n	BaseSpeed\r\n	\r\n','2008-03-03','2008-03-04 06:49:52'),(287,65,'DAM','Games can be run as turns or rounds. Turns means that each player gets a turn and then the next player gets a turn. Rounds means that all the players get to enter orders and, when all the players have done so, the round is \"run\" and a new round begins.\r\n\r\nGames can be run daily or weekly -- that should be pretty obvious.\r\n\r\nGame can be \"chained\" or \"unchained\". Unchained games will run at the allotted time regardless of who has entered or not entered their orders. Chained games will run either when the allotted time is up or earlier if a specific set of players have entered their orders (either a single player for games run as turns or all the player for games run as rounds). \r\n\r\nSo there are 8 possible game styles. Some of them may work better than others.\r\n\r\n1) Daily chained turns -- each player does his turn, with the next player able to do his turn only when the first finishes or at the end of the day\r\n\r\n2) Daily chained rounds -- all players enter orders when everyone finishes or at the end of the day, the round runs\r\n\r\n3) Daily unchained turns -- each player does his turn and they are considered complete at the end of day whether or not they have entered a turn\r\n\r\n4) Daily unchained rounds -- all players enter orders and the round is run at the end of the day, ready or not\r\n\r\n5) Weekly chained turns -- each player does a turn, with the next player able to do his turn only when the first finishes or at the end of the week  \r\n\r\n6) Weekly chained rounds -- all the players enter orders with the round run either when they are all complete or at the end of the week.\r\n\r\n7) Weekly unchained turns -- each player does his turn with the next player only able to do his turn at the end of the week.\r\n\r\n8) Weekly unchained rounds -- all players enter orders and the round is run at the end of the week\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-03-03','2008-03-11 02:43:07'),(288,65,'DAM','We need to have the standard site user management: sign up, activation, login, lost password, password change. \r\nUser\r\n username\r\n password\r\n real name\r\n gender (m,f,unspec)\r\n date of birth \r\n minor (t/f) if no data of birth, minor is assumed\r\n activation code\r\n type (inactive, active, banned, developer, admin)\r\n','2008-03-04','2008-03-04 15:57:11'),(289,65,'DAM','<h2>UNIVERSE</h2>\r\nOne must create a universe first, name it and so forth. Every universe must have attack types\r\nDefense types\r\nterrain types\r\nmobility types\r\ndetection types\r\nstealth types\r\nand tables that compare each of these types together. \r\nThere is also a collection of flavor information associated with a universe.','2008-03-04','2008-03-04 23:10:35'),(290,65,'DAM','<h2>SCENARIO</h2>\r\nOnce there is a universe, one may create a scenario in that universe. \r\nYou must specify (oy vey):\r\nA \"map\" (that is, a collection of locations and routes plus some kind of graphic representation of same)\r\nA unit set (a complete list of all the possible unit, their names, flavor text, flavor graphics, etc and their attributes)\r\nA unit order of battle (where and under what circumstances these units become available during the course of the scenario) This order of battle is used by the production system to allow units to come into being. \r\nNumber of players\r\nAI players? \r\nEnd conditions\r\nvictory conditions\r\nhigh score table information (that is, I finished first in the game; what do I get?)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-03-04','2008-03-04 23:26:27'),(291,65,'DAM','<h2>Game</h2>\r\nYou start a game by specifying a universe and scenario that you want to play. \r\nA unique instance (a copy) of the universe and scenario databases is created. A record for the game is created in the global \"Game\" database. It is in state \"starting\".\r\nPlayers may join; when the specified number of players are in place, the game starts. \r\n','2008-03-04','2008-03-04 23:24:25'),(292,65,'DAM','<h2>Running Games</h2>\r\nGames run between Midnight and 3 AM. Weekly games always run on Sunday night; daily games run every night. Chained games may run at any time if the conditions are met. The scheduler may insert a random delay to try to prevent multiple games from running at exactly the same minute.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-03-04','2008-03-04 23:31:16'),(293,65,'DAM','I\'m working on the way in which the game and site talk to each other.\r\nStarting and ending games is pretty easy along with running the turn\r\nand recording the winners and losers. The part I\'m thinking about\r\nright now is \"early end\" turns (where the round ends early because all\r\nthe players have entered their turn -- I call this kind of game a\r\n\"chained\" game because when your turn starts is tied to the end of my\r\nturn) and whether the site or the game displays results.','2008-03-04','2008-03-05 05:56:48'),(294,65,'DAM','<h2>The Site</h2>\r\nA distinction is made between the site that allows users to register, log in, sign up for games, submit turns, find out their status, maintain high score tables, talk on forums and so forth. The \"site\" will take care of users and \"game systems\" (<b>warning</b>: this term means something different than the word \"game\" in the universe:scenario:game paradigm; here it means any game system -- including the Ari Game Engine -- and is just used as a distinction from \"site\"). \r\n\r\nIn the site are \"games\"  (in any language) that can be invoked in one of 4 ways. \r\n\r\nIn all cases, the site formats information it sends to the game system in XML and the game system must send back information in XML format. In both cases there may be big blocks of text or even binary data (text encoded I would think) embedded in the XML. These blocks are game system-specific text or data which are sent to the player by the site without interpretation.   \r\nI envision an XML schema which is pretty basic and simple and which has both required fields that every game system must have (game number, turn number, etc) and some optional fields that game systems may ignore if they don\'t use those features.\r\n\r\n1) Start Game\r\nThis invocation is passed an xml file with a list of players: user name, user number, game number, player pseudonym, perhaps some game system-specific parameters which are optional (which means they have perfectly valid defaults). The game system program creates it\'s databases and so forth for that game. The game system puts out to standard output an xml file that contains the status of the command (success or failure), the game number, the turn number, perhaps some other game information, and, for each player, a block of text which that player will understand to be his starting position (that is, the first turn). The site then logs the game system specific data into a database, and sends the turn information to each player according to whatever method they have requested. \r\n\r\n2) Parse Orders\r\nWhen a player sends in orders for a turn, the site invokes the game system and passes in the information for this turn/game/player (in xml) plus the text of the player\'s turn. The game system returns an xml file that has the results of the parsing (success for not), the player/turn/game information and a block of text that has information about problems with the turn. the site will send this to the player. The game system is responsible for storing the latest turn information for each player in whatever way it uses. the site will not send it again (unless the player sends another turn). \r\n\r\n3) Run Turn\r\nthe site invokes the run turn command and passes an XML file with the game number (I think that\'s all that is required). The game system runs and spews out an xml file with game system status information, information for each player and, optionally, information for the public. \r\nThe site doesn\'t interpret the information but displays the game system specific text in the appropriate ways (showing the public info and sending the player infor to the correct players).  \r\nIf the game is over, this information is noted along with final standings and other information. The game should execute the \"game end\" code and clean up after itself as well as archive any information that should be saved for posterity. \r\n\r\n4) End Game\r\nIf, for some reason, the site needs to terminate a game, it sends the end game command and the game system kills itself off and terminates, cleaning up all it\'s files, databases, cron tasks and so forth. The game system will spew back the final status of the game system, standings and so forth, if any. It is assumed that the game history is sent back as an xml file to be archived by the site; the game system itself should keep nothing. \r\n\r\nThe site can be invoked by a game system -- a \"callback\" if you will -- in 2 ways:\r\n1) Turn Complete\r\nThe game system uses this to tell the site that a turn has been completed. This is necessary because some game systems may have very sophisticated turn entry systems that are not directly supported by the site and the site needs to know that it needs to \"start the clock\" on the next turn.\r\n\r\n2) Game Over\r\nThe game system will use this call to inform the site that the game has ended and to let the site know that it can stop timing turns and accepting email orders. The game system also uses this call to report high score information. \r\nFor example, the first line says\r\n\"Score,Cash,Ships,Planets,People\"\r\nAnd subsequent lines say\r\nDave,200000,10000,20,50,2000\r\nFred,180000, 9000,25,40,1600\r\nAnn, 150000,12000,13,25,1000\r\nAND SO FORTH\r\n\r\nIt would be nice if the site tracked all these stats for each player (first how many times in which game, second, how many times in which games, average score, average cash, average ships, average planets, average people). Note that the site has no idea what any of this stuff means, it just has to track it according to the data given, which is defined by the game system. Not sure how to do that. \r\n','2008-03-05','2008-03-05 16:15:04'),(295,65,'DAM','<h2> Production</h2>\r\nThe production system consists of 3 parts. \r\nFirst, there is a collection of units which might be produced by each player. To use a card analogy, this might be called a \"deck\".\r\nSecond, there is a pool of units which might be produced in the near future. To use a card analogy, this might be called a \"hand\".\r\nThird, there is a set of rules which determine, for each card in the deck, under which circumstances it might be deployed. \r\n\r\nAll three of these elements may be shared among the player and all three may be known or hidden to players to whom they do not apply. \r\n\r\nThe third element is of the largest interest because it\'s the most complicated and the difficult to pull off (not only in production but probably in the whole game).\r\n\r\nThis element requires two sub-elements. First, a way to describe a situation in the game and, second, a location where a unit might be deployed.\r\n\r\nThe second sub-element is somewhat easier to create but it should still be possible to define a location in very flexible terms. That is, it\'s not enough to say \"in Eqypt\" or \"in New York\" or \"in area 2345\". You have to also be able to say \"within x areas of area 2345\" or within x areas of this unit or this type of unit or even \"within x areas of a city which has these attributes\".\r\n\r\nThe first sub-element is even more complicated as it defines not just a location but a condition in the game. To be fully open-ended it needs to allow any condition or combinations of conditions that might exist in the game to be defined. \r\n\r\nThese requirements suggest nothing less than a scripting language. The scripting language does not need to DO anything but it does need to be able to evaluate boolean expressions involving pretty much every variable that makes up a game. \r\n\r\nIt\'s possible to write a custom scripting language, to define that scripting language in terms of it\'s syntax and semantics, to parse that scripting language (giving appropriate errors anywhere that there is an error), to convert that parsed information into the semantic information, to evaluate that information and come up with a list of legal areas on the one hand or a boolean value on the other. \r\n\r\nOf course it\'s possible to write a scripting language -- thousands of people have done it. A few of those thousands have actually survived. However, as both the victim and author of more than a few of those scripting languages, I am very much in favor of using something that already exists.\r\n\r\nIn this case, since the whole thing revolves around defining data that, after you parse it and evaluate it, you need to look up in the data, I think using the SQL syntax is probably the best thing to do. You limit it to just a few keyword and then you basically hand it to the SQL parser and return whatever error it returns. \r\n\r\nThis implies that we have a well defined and published database schema and that changing the schema means breaking existing games. But at some point you have to define the variables that any scripting language can access and changing those variables will break games in any case. \r\n\r\nThe basic syntax of SQL is variablename=\'constant\' as well as variablename=variablename. Wildcarding syntax looks like variablename like \'%constant%\' where % is the wildcard. Parentheses and the \"AND\" and \"OR\" keywords are supported. \r\n\r\nWe would have to make sure that all words not on a relatively short list are removed (we don\'t want people our game developers hacking our SQL databases).\r\n\r\nWe also may want to extend the syntax with keywords like \"exists\" and \"distance from\". \r\n\r\nThe key to this system is to construct a framework in which all the things that we want to examine are combined (from their various tables in the database) into one view and then allow the developer to ask specific questions about that view. \r\n\r\n','2008-03-07','2008-03-07 17:09:19'),(296,65,'DAM','<h2>The Rail</h2>\r\nThe players can look at their private information when they are logged in. But every game should have some public information that everyone can see by going to the \"Rail\" (poker term). This encourages non-players to get involved in the game. Maybe talk about it in the forums or study various strategies. Now players that may not get involved (because they never feel they know enough about the game) can learn enough to eventually play it and new players can actually know enough about the game to bring a reasonable amount of skill to play. \r\n','2008-03-07','2008-03-07 17:13:41'),(297,65,'DAM','<h2>Non Game Elements</h2>\r\n<li>Forums\r\n<li>High Score Tables\r\n<li>Rules Sections\r\n<li>Marketing Pages\r\n<li>Faction Pages','2008-03-07','2008-03-07 17:14:51'),(298,65,'DAM','<h2>Processing </h2>\r\nThe engine runs in stages. After each stage a plugin runs that may modify virtually any aspect of the stage. \r\n\r\nThe sequence is:\r\n<li>Archive -- saves game state so we can return to this point if necessary\r\n<li>Turn Processing -- make sure all units have at least default orders\r\n<li>Turn Plugin -- modifies or creates orders for any of the units (useful for AI)\r\n<li>Movement Processing -- all units move\r\n<li>Movement Plugin -- modifies movement for any unit\r\n<li>Combat Processing -- all units that meet the combat requirement\r\n<li>Combat Plugin -- modifies combat result for any unit\r\n<li>Production Processing -- Creates new units \r\n<li>Production Plugin -- modifies production \r\n<li>Results Generator -- creates \"turn results\" for each player\r\n<li>Results Plugin -- modifies results\r\n\r\n','2008-03-09','2008-03-11 02:42:12'),(299,63,'DAM','<h3>Proof Of God</h3>First off, I\'ve always known there is a God. I remember in second grade that I thought that the nuns were right that there was a God but completely wrong about the nature of God. \r\n\r\nIt\'s possible that I believed that there was a God in second grade because the nuns told me about Him in first grade and that my certainty that they were wrong in the particulars was just a childish rebellion. In the years since second grade, I\'ve thought of this many times.\r\n\r\nBut I don\'t believe it. Why do we believe what we believe? In my case it\'s because I\'ve had many experiences that confirmed my belief; I\'ve experienced God directly. Not in a way that I can prove to anyone but in a way that I feel very certain of. Internal evidence of a very persuasive sort.\r\n\r\nWhat is the nature of this God in which I believe so certainly? I\'m not as sure about that. I can tell that there is Something there but I can\'t access it directly. To perceive things that aren\'t here I have to be in a very relaxed, clear state. The experience is always pleasant and when it\'s over I always feel a sense of longing to go back. That\'s where we come from and this, this is somehow where we ended up. That\'s God\'s Reality and this is just the illusion we call reality.\r\n\r\nBut I don\'t believe that God is a benevolent entity that is looking out for me. More likely a He is a powerful Creator who is aware of Us but not of me as an individual. If he is, as I suspect, creating the world as it is instant by instant, he is an incredibly consistent God. And I personally think that an entity who creates me every instant is pretty benevolent, even if He doesn\'t send me birthday cards. \r\n\r\nObviously this God of mine (by \"mine\" I mean the God I posit, not my personal god) creates others besides me. In fact, he creates everything. You, too. \r\n\r\nSince He is our Source and since we come from Him we are all have His imprint. We\'re all part Him which means we\'re all connect to each other. \r\n\r\nMuch has been written about the horrible isolation that we feel as humans. But this is just the illusion of the thing we call (paradoxically) \"physical reality\". Here in space-time there is no way you (whom I\'ve probably never met) and I could possibly be connected (except by radio waves or other physical means that could be detected but never have been). So we must be completely isolated. \r\n\r\nThe joke that I sometime tell (although I\'m never sure if people really get it) is that the reason people buy trucks is because the are separated from their Creator. They feel this terrible longing to reconnect to that which is real but they can\'t figure out how to do that. So they want to connect to other people whom, deep inside, they feel are their brothers and sisters. But they don\'t know how to do that, either. So they figure they will settle for sex. But they can\'t seem to manage that either. So they buy a truck because the ad says that the chicks dig it. \r\n\r\nI actually spent six months trying to explain to anyone who would listen why this isn\'t true; how we are actually all connected at a fundamental level to each other. The result was that all my friends thought of me as a lovable (but annoying) nut. One friend suggested that I should read a book about science -- obviously he didn\'t think I understood about the Supremacy of the Physical (which is what science represents to many people). \r\n\r\nOk, so I can\'t convince anyone. But that doesn\'t mean it isn\'t true.  \r\n\r\nWhat has me convinced of this, quite apart from meditating and having experiences of the divine, is the look in the eyes of other people. Often they seem away, or distracted. \"Not Home\" in some sense. But other times they seem to actual be there. I can connect to them and I get a real sense of their presence.  Often a powerful sense and an extremely welcoming and pleasant sense. Perhaps it has a whiff of the divine about it. \r\n\r\nJust to recap, I make two assertion in this chapter. First, I assert that there is some kind of God. Second, I assert that we are all somehow connected to each other through that God. Everything else is what I suspect, or deduce or posit or maybe everything else is just wishful thinking. But those two things, I\'m certain of. I\'m not sure about Evolution or Creationism, Spirit Communication or why the sky is blue. But I\'m certain of those two things. Go figure.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-03-09','2013-02-19 00:19:32'),(300,63,'DAM','<ol>\r\n<li>We love each other\r\n<li>We can affect each other directly\r\n<li>Things go bump in the night\r\n<li>How does mud move, anyway?\r\n<li>Who am I?\r\n<li>WHo are you?\r\n<li>Again, how do you know?\r\n<li>WHen to be tolerant and when to just say \"that\'s just dumb!\"\r\n<li>THe power of meditation\r\n<li>THe power of prayer\r\n<li>My authority to say these things\r\n<li> Are we not gods?\r\n<li>The nature of consciousness.\r\n<li>How can I be so ignorant?\r\n<li>The 3 things -- body, mind, spirit; physical, mental, spiritual\r\n<li>Theology\r\n</oL>\r\n\r\n','2008-03-09','2008-03-10 06:01:03'),(301,63,'DAM','<h2>couple things to do:</h2>\r\n<li>Longest sentence is 55 words. Maybe break that up\r\n<li>use a lot of \"you\" -- see if we can take out at least 18 of those\r\n<li>move it to formal\r\n<li> see if you can find 10+ \"things\" or \"thing\" that you can remove -- too vague\r\n','2008-03-09','2008-03-10 06:00:11'),(341,70,'DAM','A turn based mafia game that would run on turnstyle. The server would moderate the night. The turn order would be a bit odd and the communication would have to be outside of the game. ','2008-04-09','2008-04-10 02:07:36'),(342,74,'davemenc',' ','2008-04-09','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(343,75,'davemenc','1) Order these from least ethical to most ethical\r\nA) You want a soda and a co-worker has a dollar on his desk and you take it.\r\nB) You are about to lose your house because you can\'t make the payments. You have an opportunity to steal enough money from your company, risk free. You take just enough to save your house. \r\nC) You need to groceries and you don\'t have car. Your roommate is asleep and you know where his car keys are so you borrow them. \r\nD) You\'ve been drinking but you need to work the next day so you drive home intoxicated.\r\nE) You consistently share music with people on line, not because you like them but because you get more music as a result. \r\n','2008-04-11','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(344,40,'defer','Tank Game\r\nEcologyGame  \r\nTrading Game\r\nNumbers Game \r\nAmoeba War\r\nOpen Sky \r\nThe Chase\r\nZSpace\r\n','2008-04-13','2008-04-13 07:05:20'),(345,76,'davemenc','<h3>Chapter one purposes</h3>\r\n\r\n<P>There are 4 things I want to get down in the first chapter.\r\n\r\n<br>1) Explain what the title -- and therefore the book -- means. This is a major theme but we really only want to foreshadow it here or why are we writing a book and not a short story?\r\n<br>2) Explain about his big leap of understanding about time travel and how he discovered it. Set the stage for his working for a corp.\r\n<br>3) Introduce his wife and describe his good relationship with her -- the one that he had before. She is his standin for the world. She is a metaphor for how he relates to God and the rest of mankind.\r\n<br>4) Demonstrate that the relationship with his wife has gone badly.\r\n\r\n<p>Chapter 2 we can go back and fill in some of the gaps. Answer some of the questions we\'ve created. Go over the background and the details of their life. Right up to the day after the play.\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Chapter 3 we can continue from where we left off after the play and how their life changes.\r\n<p>Chapter 4 is about Alan\'s first downfall and shit hitting the fan.\r\n<p>Chapter 5 is Alan\'s first recovery, the mechanics of how it works and what he accomplished. This isn\'t a recovery but just a solution to all his problems.\r\n<p>Chapter 6 is \"Alan through the loophole\"\r\n<p>Chapter 7 is Alan\'s second downfall in the past and the shit hitting the fan for the second time. This is all the problems coming up again in one form or another.\r\n<p>Chapter 8 is Alan\'s second recovery. This has to be a real recovery. Alan resolves his real issues.\r\n<p>Chapter 9 is Alan, using his new-found point of view, seeing the stars and working the universe to get home.\r\n<p>Chapter 10 is the home-coming and the resolution of the book.\r\n\r\n','2008-04-13','2008-04-13 23:37:51'),(346,76,'DAM','<h2>Starless Night </h2>\r\n<h3>Chapter 1</h3>\r\n\r\n<P>When Alan Morales was young his parents would go camping. Nothing fancy, just drive up to someplace remote -- usually the beach but sometimes the mountains -- and unpack the car and stay there. \r\n<P>They always brought a tent but he much prefered to stay outside. He would lie in his sleeping bag and stare up at the stars. So many stars! \r\n<P>\"What are the stars?\" he would often ask. \r\n<P>His father would always answer with the scientific explanation: gaseous balls of fire and so on. \r\n<P>He thought he liked his mother\'s answer better: \"The stars are God\'s eyes.\" Or sometimes she would say, \"The stars are our connection to God. \r\n<P>He knew this wasn\'t factual just as he knew Santa Claus wasn\'t coming -- but he continued to bake cookies for Santa Claus long after he knew Santa was just a story. He just liked the thought of the stars being more than gas.\r\n<P>Maybe thinking of them as an aspect of God was why he drew such comfort from them. He felt connected to something greater than myself. \r\n<P>Back in the suburbs, he would go outside in the dark and look up at the sky. There would be a few stars but nothing like there were when we were camping. \"Where did they go?\" he wondered.\r\n<P>He was probably in his teens before he learned the secret of the stars: they didn\'t go anywhere. When it was cloudy or there was a lot of light you couldn\'t see them but they were still there. But it was hard to draw comfort from stars -- whether God or gas -- that you couldn\'t see.\r\n\r\n<P>As happens to most children, he grew up. He studied at the University, got a job, met a woman, got married, had children. Apparently, his father\'s story about the stars had been the more compelling in the long run because he studied Astronomy and Astrophysics and got a job as a scientist. \r\n<P>At first, he got caught up with academia. For some, science is really quite compelling, especially pure science and, most especially, very pure sciences like astronomy. \r\n<P>Hundreds of years ago people like Kepler and Copernicus and Gallileo looked up at the stars and made some very shrewd obvservations. And other brilliant people built on their work and others on their work, century after century, each successive generation finding out information for which there could be no real use. \r\n<P>Who really cares exactly how far away a particular star is? But if you know it -- and we do, for many many stars -- you can sometimes use that information in clever ways to find out how far away other stars are. And use that information to find out other things. And so on. \r\n<P>But it seldom, if ever, has any real effect on us here on Earth. It\'s still compelling to be part of this giant, generation spanning conspiracy to know things. Not because we need to know them or because we can eat better for knowing them but just for the knowing. \r\n<P>Nothing he or his fellow scientists did ever had any applications in the \"real\" world. It was all just theoretical stuff that we did because that\'s what they did. Until one day, the theory had an amazing application. \r\n\r\n<P>He was working on the most esoteric of calculations. It had to do with the equations for black holes. As you might imagine, all this thinking took a lot of time. He was delving into an area of physics more complicated and arcane than the Cabala and more difficult to understand than women. He would go to work, run some numbers on his computer and lose all track of time. \r\n<P>One of the possible ways that the equations could go was that the black hole was an opening to a worm hole which would, presumably connect two black holes together. You could, in theory, enter one black hole and then be transported to the other black hole and exit it before light could move from the first hole to the other. This would, of course, violate the cosmic speed limit -- the speed of light. But you wouldn\'t get a cosmic speeding ticket because, technically, you went less than the speed of light through the worm hole. Because the worm hole didn\'t go through normal space, it was \"shorter\" than the distance between the two black holes and so you could traverse it faster. \r\n<P>Of course, you would be torn apart by the first black hole, would spend a significant part of eternity crossing it\'s event horizon and then have trouble escaping the event horizon of the second black hole and, even if you did, escape it only as very powerful radiation. So none of this was, in any way, useful. \r\n<P>Suddenly, He realized that you might be able to have the worm hole without the black hole. It never occurred to him, even then, that it might be useful to have a worm hole and, when he did the numbers, he was right. To have a worm hole the size of an atom and only a mile long you\'d have to use more energy than our sun had in it. But he kept thinking about it anyway. There seemed to be a hint of something in there; something surprising and shocking. Something perhaps even -- useful. \r\n\r\n<P>Naturaly, he was startled but not surprised when the phone rang. It was Doris, his wife, who was wondering where he was. Theater tickets were on the agenda, not an evening of musing. \r\n\r\n<P>His wife was unreasonably understanding. He hadn\'t always been a starry eyed dreamer. When they met he had been passionatly and romanticly in love and he had lavished attention on her. He had felt trully alive then but gradually the spark had died and now he felt a little like his whole life was covered in a blanket. Like the fog had rolled in and blotted out the stars. But she played the role of fog horn and always managed to clear the cobwebs away. \r\n\r\n<br>\"Thinking deep thoughts, dear?\" \r\n<br>\"Yes, I suppose I was.\"\r\n<br>\"Well, come home now and have some dinner and we\'ll go out together. It\'s Friday and we have theater tickets tonight.  You can pick up your thinking on Monday right were you left off.\" \r\n<br>\"Yes, dear, I\'ll leave right away.\"\r\n\r\n<br>As he drove home, his thought drifted over the past few years. We\'d met on campus -- his whole life revolved around campus -- and he was quite taken with her. \r\n+++\r\n<P>As Doris put down the phone she felt a twinge of anoyance. She remembered when he had been working on his PHD and they had been in love. For the longest time after they had married he had described her as his \"lovely bride.\" Then he\'d gotten his PHD and a job at the university and the awesome responsibility of being Married had set in. But still, they loved each other and their life together was joyful.\r\n<P>And then  Mattie had been born and that had even been more joyful, at least for her. And then Sammy came along. Maybe that was when the tension began. Still, he at least tried to help out, helpless and hopelessly distracted as he had been. \r\n<P>She wondered for a moment when the joy had gone and the tedium had settled in. Oh, the joy came back sometimes, to be sure. When they went camping, for example, they were all together and rest of the world receded comfortably into the background. \r\n<P>She didn\'t have time for this kind of musing; Mattie and Sammy needed to be gotten up and made ready for dinner, dinner needed to be gotten ready for everyone and she herself needed to get ready for her evening. \r\n\r\n<P>At length, the children were fed and gotten ready for the baby sitter and Doris and Alan ready for the play. As they drove off, Alan was strangely quiet but Doris was happy to fill in the gaps with chatter about the daily household events. Sammy was teething and Mattie was entering into some evil period -- tantrums and pouting seemed to be the norm these days. \r\n<P>The play was about the advent of computer games in the Silicon Valley written, apparently, especially for the San Jose Rep. Neither Alan nor Doris thought of themselves as part of the computer revolution that, they had heard, was going on all around them. He used computers for work and she had nothing to do with them. \r\n\r\n<P>Half way through the play Alan suddenly had an inspiration. Wormholes! Faster than light! The equations! He sat up suddenly and looked around nervously to see if anyone had been bothered by the light bulb that had just gone off over his head. No one seemed to care; they all appeared to be absorbed by the travails of the game designer on the stage. The rest of the evening was sheer torture; he needed to get back to his computer! But he couldn\'t just leave!\r\n\r\n<P>When the play was over, he dropped off Doris and headed back to campus. \r\n<br>\"You\'re going out!?\" asked Doris. \r\n<br>\"Yeah. Sorry, I just thought of something and I want to check it out. I\'ll try not to wake you when I come in. G\'night\". \r\n<br>She would have liked to say, \"That\'s OK, go ahead and wake me...\" but he was already gone.\r\n\r\n<P>The thing about wormholes, according to his calculations, was that they absorbed energy in proportion to their length. If the wormhole was infinitely short, it required no energy at all, which probably meant that there were wormholes popping in and out of existance all the time. If the worm hole was very short but still traversed some distance in real space it would not consume much energy. Best of all, there might be a useful application for such a wormhole.\r\n\r\n<P>Imagine you have a worm hole from here to a planet 4 lightyears from here. Let\'s say that there were people on this planet and they were receiving our television signals. Now imagine that it was the night after the presidential election and all the networks had declared the winner. The planet wouldn\'t know this information for another 4 years. But if we zip over there by way of our worm hole, we can get there in minutes and tell them. We have information for them that is 4 years in their future. In effect, we just came back in time 4 years.\r\n\r\n<P>Alan thought that was mighty interesting. He hadn\'t violated any laws and yet he had found a theoretical way to go back in time -- a sort of theoretical loophole. But, of course, going 4 light years would take more energy than the whole galaxy output. So forget the distance, just go back in time!\r\n\r\n<P>Alan suspected that if the two wormholes had just the right length and just the right spacial relationship to each other you get the loophole without too much energy cost. In other words, one could go back in time! He would need to use the computers to figure out exactly what configuration would provide the cheapest loophole. \r\n\r\n<P>Still, it wasn\'t at all practical: what could you do with a atom wide loophole? He started running computer calculations. By morning he had graduated to computer simulations. By afternoon he had worked out a way -- in theory -- to construct a loophole big enough for a man to travel through but energy efficient enough to be practical. If you could create the right conditions, a sort of hole would open up and whoever was standing there would fall through to the past. Controlling the conditions precisely would determine when in the past on would go but the amount of energy would not change significantly. And, in theory, the whole thing could be done using a car battery!\r\n\r\n<P>This time he was startled by the phone ringing. He had literally forgotten that anyone existed in the real world, so caught up was he with the world of black holes and wormholes and loopholes. \r\n\r\n<P>Doris was significantly less reasonable than usual. In fact she seemed quite upset. He only vaguely understood why. But he recognized that he needed a break and so he agreed to come home straight away.\r\n\r\n<P>Is it possible to be angry and frightened and sad and confused, all at the same time? If so, that\'s what Doris felt. It came out loud and kind of obnoxious but it was more complicated than just mad. She had gotten up and found Alan gone and convinced herself that he had come home and gone back to work. But it was Saturday. And his towel wasn\'t wet. And his clothes weren\'t in the laundry. She had argued the case back and forth all day and now it was too late to be working on Saturday (people who have the indecency to work on Saturday should have the decency to come home early). He should have been home hours ago, if he ever came home last night and, even if he didn\'t, he should have come home more hours ago. \r\n\r\n<P>As he drove home Alan felt not so much elated as focused. He was, for the first time in his career, on the trail of something truly useful. He was very concious of how much work it would take to actually make that come to light. He had long since forgotten about Doris and her upset.\r\n','2008-04-13','2008-04-13 23:41:00'),(347,76,'DAM','<h3>Questions</h3>\r\n1) How did Alan and Doris meet?\r\n2) What does Alan do in his spare time? \r\n3) What was A&D\'s first date?\r\n<br>4) First kiss?\r\n<br>5) Why did they name thier children as they did?\r\n<br>6) What was the scene like when they first discovered they were pregnant?\r\n<br>7) Was wast the first birth like? \r\n<br>8) What did Doris do before they were married?\r\n<br>9) What is their house like, how did they find it, how did they furnish it?\r\n<br>10) Do they go camping since the children came? \r\n<br>11) Talk about some of the camping trips before the children.\r\n<br>12) Who does Alan work with? Who is his boss? Who are his peers? Does he teach?\r\n<br>13) Who is going to hook him up in the private sector?\r\n','2008-04-13','2008-04-13 23:42:16'),(348,79,'davemenc',' ','2008-04-13','2008-04-14 00:33:03'),(349,80,'davemenc',' ','2008-04-13','2008-04-14 00:47:16'),(350,81,'davemenc',' ','2008-04-20','2008-04-20 20:17:22'),(351,81,'DAM','Sex On The Beach\r\n2 Shots	Vodka\r\n1 Shot	Peach Schnapps\r\n3 Shots	Cranberry Juice\r\n3 Shots	Orange Juice\r\nBuild the ingredients over ice.\r\n\r\n\r\nCosmopolitan\r\nPrint this recipe\r\nPrint this recipe\r\nCosmopolitan\r\nIngredients:\r\nAmount 	Ingredient (Click ingredient for more recipes)\r\n1.5 Shots	\r\nRussian Standard Vodka\r\n0.75 Shot	\r\nDe Kuyper Triple Sec\r\n2.5 Shots	Cranberry Juice\r\n1 Teaspoon	Caster Sugar\r\n0.5 Shot	Lime Juice\r\n Shake and strain into a chilled Martini glass.\r\nAdditional not\r\n\r\nSingapore Sling\r\nPrint this recipe\r\nPrint this recipe\r\nSingapore Sling\r\nIngredients:\r\nAmount 	Ingredient (Click ingredient for more recipes)\r\n1 Dash	Angostura Bitters\r\n2 Shots	\r\nHendricks Gin\r\n0.5 Shot	BÃ©nÃ©dictine Dom\r\n1 Shot	\r\nDe Kuyper Cherry Brandy\r\nTop up	Soda\r\n0.5 Shot	Lemon Juice\r\nLiquid 