in the Afternoon\r\nMimosa\r\nKir Royale\r\nMojito\r\n','2008-04-21','2008-04-21 21:47:12'),(354,82,'davemenc','The system is hugely slow with a 4 gig memory stick inserted. In particular the initial screen draw takes several seconds (!). I\'m sure that the system is looking  through the file system to find certain icons that it needs to draw the screen. First off, it could demand that they be put in places that it could find them more easily. Second, it could draw the screen and then, when it has a spare moment it could go look for the icons. Third, it could cache the icons in the main system memory so that it doesn\'t have to look for them every time.','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:37:35'),(355,83,'davemenc',' I bought the product because my cmoputer hard disk was going south. I used it to back up as much as I could before I replaced it. I lost a huge amount of stuff!\r\n\r\nThere several stages, I ended up getting a new computer. I connected your product to the new computer and installed the software from the the back up disk. That was nice, I liked that. But the license key (which for you guys is the serial number) wasn\'t backed up. What with having my hard disk fail and then replacing the hard disk and then having the whole computer fail, I had lost the packaging. And the backup system didn\'t save the license key for itself. It\'s like the people who made it never expected the computer system it was connected to to crash! Imagine that.\r\n\r\nSo I contacted customer service and explained the situation. No problem, just give us your phone number and we\'ll take care of it.I never heard from them again. \r\nSome weeks later the \"trial version\" (that\'s the \"trial version\" on the software I had already paid for, you understand) ran out. So now my choices are 1) pay for the software a second time or 2) not have my system backed up. \r\n\r\nSo I bought the software AGAIN. Ok, I\'m out $30. That sucks. \r\n\r\nAnd I point this out to your customer service representative. After several back and forth exchanges, it turns out that they have no record of the first exchange in which they promised to get me the license key for free. \r\n\r\nI really don\'t think I should have had to pay a second time. I don\'t think I should have had to ask twice. I think you should refund my money. ','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:08:22'),(356,83,'','','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:03:53'),(357,83,'','And while we\'re on the subject I have some other issues with your software. I\'ve been doing software for about 20 years. I think you have a very serious set of problems in your engineering department. \r\n\r\nThe customer service person I was communicating with the second time could help me with my problem; apparently couldn\'t even figure out what my problem was. But they did notice that my version of the software was old and very kindly pointed out where to get an update. But after that it was just a horror.\r\n\r\nFirst off,you have to uninstall the software before you can install the update. This is wrong because it\'s a horrible thing to do to your customers. The new software should do whatever it needs to do to disable the drivers and fix up the registry, disable and remove the old drivers and do whatever it needs to do as part of the new installation. It\'s sloppy and unprofessional to force the customers to do an uninstall. \r\n\r\nThen the uninstall shut down my computer without asking me! I\'m sorry, did your programmers think this was 1990? Totally unacceptable to shut a modern computer down on the user -- whose computer is this, anyway? I sure wish you\'d pay the price for it...\r\n\r\nOk, so the computer comes back up, and I reinstall the software. When it comes back up it doesn\'t have a license (naturally) and is back on the trial period and doesn\'t remember any of the backups. \r\n\r\nI\'m sorry to be so crude but this is all bullshit. The new software should install over the old software and when it\'s done I should have a working system that is licensed and doing backups. Forcing the customer to go through a multi-step install (with a forced reboot!) followed by forcing him to re-configure the software (again) is just wrong. At least at this point I\'ve been through it multiple times...\r\n','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:20:33'),(358,83,'','And one more level of issues. The basic user interface is horrible. Granted, it\'s made from standard user interface elements but inappropriately cobbled together. \r\n\r\nFirst it tells me what the steps are going to be. That\'s a good start. Then I click on the next button. Then I pick the destination. Then I have to click on a link that has me pick the source. But the drive I want to back up is on the \"disallow\" list (why? don\'t people back up their second drive?) and I\'m told to keep going and then click on advanced to fix it. So I go on, click on advanced, take it off the disallow list and then go back and fix the problem. In this lurching, arbitrary and confusing way, I eventually get the thing configured. It\'s not that I can\'t do it but why can\'t you make it easier? \r\n\r\nFirst off, if you are going to give me a list of steps, why not have THAT be the basic interface. At the top of every screen is the list of steps with the steps I\'ve completed greyed out (perhaps next to a \"back\" button) and the current step highlighted. Then in the bottom of the screen a set of controls to handle that step. (It\'s better to put the explanation at the top and the controls at the bottom than the other way around because people usually start at the top of the page or the screen and so they are more likely to find the instructions.)\r\n\r\nIf there is some reason why they can\'t do what they are trying to do, have a button that will take them straight to the place they can fix it. Or just have a dialog box that says \"would you like to allow this?\". \r\n\r\nThe use of a web-style link in the middle of a page is completely weird in the context of a non-web application. Apart from the dissonance it creates (really, it\'s important to give users a sense of connection to other applications they have used and not mix and match UI elements from different places), there is seldom a purpose in having a link to another page. If there is something that needs to get done, just put it in the space you had the link. Why make me click again. \r\n\r\nI guess the bottom line is, fire your UI designer and hire someone who knows what they are doing. ','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:33:06'),(359,82,'DAM','Garmin directs you off of a congested road onto the off-ramp and then back onto the onramp. In addition to being a dangerous thing to do and possibly illegal, it never works because the off- and on-ramps are congested too and usually have metering lights. That\'s just stupid','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:34:26'),(360,82,'DAM','The mp3 player has several problems. \r\n\r\nFirst off, when there is a 4 gig stick in the system the mp3 player takes several seconds (up to a minute) to fully start. \r\n\r\nNext when you select a playlist from a 4 gig stick it often (always?) crashes if the playlist is the first one alphabetically. The same playlist will work it it\'s further down the list. (By crash, I mean the screen goes dead and the unit goes into an off state). \r\n\r\nThe MP3 player has a serious problem with volume level. Granted most MP3s have a serious problem, but the system needs to be able to play MP3s at a level that is approximately the same as the navigation instructions. Granted there is a way to do this manually but as each MP3 plays this needs to be adjusted and it\'s several taps away.\r\n\r\nThe MP3 controls are horrible. If I want to move a few seconds up or back I need to hold my finger on a button for some period of time. If I tap it it skips to the next or to the beginning of this mp3. In some environments this might work but not on a touch screen. You should have a button that says \"skip forward 20 seconds\" or \"skip back 20 seconds\". If you want to be ambitiouse have another set that do a minute. \r\n\r\n','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:43:01'),(361,82,'','The passcode system is great and, since this one replaces the one that got stolen, I\'m totally in favor of it. But I have two objections to the way it\'s implemented. \r\n\r\nFirst off, does it have to take so long between starting up and asking for the passcode? \"Loading maps?\" Do you need the maps to ask me my passcode? You want to minimize the time the user is waiting for the system to enter something and, if necessary, replace it with time that the system is working on it\'s own. I don\'t like having to watch the system for as much as a 30 seconds(with a large memory stick; 20 seconds otherwise) just so I can put in the passcode.  It should ask for the passcode right off the bat and then move on. \r\n\r\nSecond, If I make a mistake in the password screen it goes to a screen that will only allow me to turn off the unit. Why doesn\'t that screen have a button on it that cycles the unit around so I can try again? Granted we want bad people to have to waste a lot of time trying to guess my passcode but you can make it a little better. If you really want to punish someone then make it take 20 seconds the first time he misses it and an extra 10 seconds every time after that. It takes me an extra minute to log in if I miss it currently so that would be a great improvement!','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:54:49'),(362,82,'','The current database doesn\'t have a lot of places of interest that have been in the same location for many years. And it has the wrong name for some things. ','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:55:41'),(363,82,'','The map database is flawed in many places with respect to whether I can turn right or not. It sometimes tries to send me across the street and around the block to turn left at places I can just turn left or insists that I should just turn left in places where I can\'t. \r\n\r\nNote that I\'m not talking about \"hard to turn left\" but places where you physically can\'t turn. \r\n','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 22:57:17'),(364,82,'','The system insists on giving me way points that are really just places that I shouldn\'t get off the freeway. Yes, I understand that I\'m supposed to stay on the freeway that I\'m on until it tells me explicitly to get off; how dumb would I have to be to accidentally go off an offramp at random and, if I\'m really that dumb, do you honestly think telling me NOT to get off will help? \r\n\r\nBy having a lot of waypoints like that, you distort the distance between real waypoints and cause me to be in the wrong lane or to think turns are coming too soon.\r\n','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 23:00:37'),(365,82,'','The GPS warns me way too late. If I know where I am I can get in the correct lane but it typically only gives me .2 miles to get over and often that isn\'t anywhere near enough. ','2008-04-24','2008-04-24 23:01:20'),(366,76,'DAM','A sequence in a book. Maybe this one...\r\n\r\n\r\nYou meet a blond girl in a bar  who is working as a waitress but wants to be an actress and considered herself to be in a class above you. She is certainly a member of a large set in SoCal.\r\n\r\nI thought of a kind of pickup scam that I might have tried on her if 1) she had been alone and 2) I was more of an asshole than I really am\r\n\r\nAfter the initial introductions.\r\nMe: Man, what a fucked day at work it\'s been. You\'d think that actresses who are working as waitresses would be willing to work on something less than an A movie! But we can\'t seem to find anyone!\r\nYou (not in on the scam): What the...\r\nMe (cutting you off): Yeah, you\'re right. I promised I wouldn\'t talk about work tonight. But, dude, it\'s been a week and we haven\'t found ANYBODY! Ok, ok, I\'ll stop.\r\nYou: Odd questioning looks.\r\nNow we just leave it. She either takes the bait or she doesn\'t.\r\n\r\nThe story I would push (revealing as little of it as possible, only if she insists, with sidelong glances at you as if I\'m afraid you\'ll hit me if I talk about work) is that we cast actresses for some fly-by-night movie company. Our boss has a kickback arrangement with some agency and we can only hire people from that agency. But none of them are suitable and we\'re going to lose our jobs (the project will get canceled, our boss will get fired, the company may go out of business) if we can\'t find someone to fill at least some of the roles soon. There is much pointless lamenting about how we have to go through this worthless agency and how we could probably find women on craiglist if we didn\'t have this constraint. They would be willing to get paid good money and get movie credits but not these bitches, etc, etc. Our boss is going to drive the company under just to make a buck but does he care? Etc, etc. Our company is obviously the sleaziest company on the planet. But we are casting agents and we can bestow jobs upon would-be actresses.\r\n\r\nAgain, I stop. We *can* bestow jobs but we don\'t want to! The following can only be revealed if she wheedles, begs, pleads and keeps pushing. If she\'s a workable mark and I\'ve done the stuff up to here correctly, she will.\r\n\r\nI can\'t possibly do an audition for the actress/waitress we\'re talking to. She couldn\'t possibly be interested. She doesn\'t know what she\'s getting into. I don\'t want to talk about it. It\'s just not possible. Etc.\r\n\r\nWell, I suppose Ari has a camera. We could film something and send it to our boss\'s boss, the head of the company and maybe, if he liked it, he would over ride our boss and that might work. Probably not. It would have to be a really GOOD audition tape. But you don\'t even know the genre, you probably couldn\'t handle it.\r\n\r\nAt this stage we reveal, as gradually as possible the kind of films we make. We don\'t actually say  what we do but we say things like, \"They\'re not exactly family films\" and \"they\'re not exactly Warner Brothers\" with many a wry smile at each other. The implication, of course, is that we cast porn films.\r\n\r\nBy now she has convinced herself that, no matter how bad our films are, she would be willing to take a chance on them since it\'s paid acting which is more than she\'s doing. By the time she figures out that it\'s porn, she\'s psychologically committed. We just have to keep saying \"no\" until she insists!\r\n\r\nIf she insists on coming back to your apartment then she can be pretty much talked into whatever we want. She knows it\'s something bad. Even if she\'s naive she\'s got to know it\'s naughty. I just ruthlessly push her into having sex with you.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, *this* is where I\'m a real asshole because you don\'t want to have sex with her and you\'re only going along because you thought I was interested in this slag and you were too polite to stop me. But now I turn the tables on you (dude, I\'m married, I *can\'t* have sex with *anyone*) and you either have to make a scene or have sex with her. In front of a camera. And I can tease you about it FOREVER!\r\n\r\nI suspect it would actually work. At least it would make a good sequence in a book... :)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-04-26','2008-04-26 07:14:49'),(367,84,'davemenc',' ','2008-04-27','2008-04-27 22:39:33'),(368,83,'DAM','William D. Watkins - Chief Executive Officer\r\nBrian Dexheimer - President, Consumer Solutions Division\r\nTodd Abbottâ€”Executive Vice President of Sales, Marketing and Customer Service\r\nBob Whitmore - Executive Vice President and Chief Technical Officer\r\nMike Wingert - Executive Vice President and General Manager for Seagate\'s Personal Compute Products\r\nPat Kingâ€”Senior Vice President and GM, Consumer Electronics\r\n- Executive Summary\r\n-- Who I am\r\n-- why I\'m writing\r\n-- what the problem is\r\n-- summary of grievances\r\n-- what I\'m going to do next\r\n-  \r\n','2008-04-30','2008-04-30 18:00:31'),(369,83,'DAM','<H3>Response if accused of threatening them.</h3>\r\nFirst off, this is not a threat. A threat is if I pull out a gun and say \"give me your wallet or I\'ll shoot you.\" Notice that I only have the gun so that I can get your wallet. My case differs in that it\'s a perfectly legitimate thing to do to \"go public\" about problems and try to get support for improving the software. I think it\'s going to be more effective to go to you directly and give you a chance to fix it but it\'s not \"fix it or I\'ll go public\" as it is, \"I was going to go public but I thought I\'d talk to you first\". \r\nSecond, the whole issue is academic. If you consider my plans threatening then so what? My position is perfectly reasonable from a customer\'s point of view and I think my fellow customers -- especially the potential customers -- will agree. ','2008-04-30','2008-05-01 05:13:36'),(370,84,'DAM','met a girl in a bar and she says, \"I\'m way out of your league\"\r\nI say, \"madam, you and I aren\'t even playing the same game. \"\r\nYou\'re playing at getting laid but I\'m just being a human being. Humans can get laid but no one who says \"I\'m way out of your league\" could possibly be human in that minute. \r\n\r\n','2008-05-07','2008-05-08 04:03:44'),(371,84,'DAM','I love California. But I really can\'t tell if other people, people from other states, who say they love California, are thuinking about it the same way. I suspect they love disneyland while I love the culture of the state, especially the high tech culture. Maybe I, for my part would find the high tech culture in, say Texas or Boston to be just as enjoyable. \r\n\r\nThis culture thing is a hard one to figure out. A lot of people work in offices but I sincerely doubt that they\'re experience is the same as mine. My computer is the entire deal for me. ','2008-05-07','2008-05-08 04:15:04'),(372,85,'davemenc',' ','2008-05-31','2008-05-31 18:18:39'),(373,48,'DAM','<h2>Keith\'s Comments</h2>\r\nSpend some time defining your thesis. I know this sounds a little high school, but youâ€™re arguing for something in this paper, and it would be easier to follow your ideas if you established and overarching argument at the beginning. My impression is that it would look something like this: \r\n<P>â€œOver the next hundred or so years, there is a substantial chance that global civilization as we have come to know it will cease to exist. It will be replaced by smaller societies which will resemble something closer to the dark ages. The challenges which threaten our current level of civilization can best be understood as a set of five interconnected issues which have resulted from our mismanagement of the wordâ€™s resources. Any of these issues could deal the fatal blow to our society if left unchecked. These issues are fundamental to all other problems in the world (violence, bigotry, xenophobia, intolerance) and must be addressed before any other problems can be solved. If left unchecked, any one of these big issues could get exponentially worse, and increase the dangers of the other big issues, creating a spiral effect leading to the end of civilization. As inhabitants of North America, and thus major contributors to these problems, we must take the initiative in addressing these issues. This will entail increasing our dedication to addressing these issues, and our willingness to accept the cost of solutions.â€ \r\n\r\nI may have missed some important point, or perhaps I misconstrued some of your arguments, but something like this is very important to help your reader get an idea of what youâ€™re working towards.   \r\n \r\nSpend more time defining what you mean by civilization. This is a very important idea. What are we saving? What do we stand the risk of losing? \r\nMany things lack sources. You state statistics, and ideas, and sometimes Iâ€™m not sure where they come from. I donâ€™t think you necessarily need to source everything, because this essay seems to be mostly the conclusions youâ€™ve come to based on the evidence youâ€™ve bumped into. If you leave it un-sourced, you may want to add something in the beginning which explains this decision. If instead, you have spent a significant amount of time researching for this paper, then you really need sources. This isnâ€™t even necessarily to give credit to others, but most importantly to give credit to yourself. To show the work youâ€™ve put into this paper, and to show that your statements are credible.  \r\n\r\nAlways explain how your arguments relate back to your thesis. You make many arguments and itâ€™s not always clear what youâ€™re working towards.  \r\nMaybe itâ€™s necessary to explain why these five things rather than some other theoretical group of five are useful tools for understanding the challenges to world civilization. For example, I could say that the world is faced with two huge problems: resource depletion, and climate change. Why are youâ€™re specific analytical tools the most useful? Why are you concerned about water depletion rather than deforestation, metal depletion? Why are the issues you chose the most fundamental.\r\n\r\nAlso, I could say that the world is faced with short sited political and economic systems which cannot address large global problems. This is the fundamental cause for all other problems. Why are your resource/environmental issues more appropriate ways of understanding the global challenges?\r\n\r\nAlso, all of your five issues relate to resource management. Why is youâ€™re article not entitled â€œThe One.â€ The one thing that we have control over in all of these changing systems is how we manage our resources. Youâ€™re five are the potential effects of resource mismanagement. Maybe you should recognize this in your introduction, that your paper is really all about resource management as a means of addressing the five most dire threats to the world.  \r\nYou use the word â€œthingsâ€ to describe your analytical tools. Find a better word. \r\nYou use the phrase â€œthe truth isâ€ as a rhetorical devise quite often. Try mixing it up with other introductory phrases. \r\n\r\nThis whole article is very much speculation. Many of your claims could take a thousand pages to really support. For example, your explanation for why we will lose our technology is based on your expectations of what will happen. Your expectations are reasonable based on the evidence you have, but you can bet that an â€œexpertâ€ on these subjects could come up with alternative theories. Itâ€™s just that youâ€™re making very big claims which require a lot of support. I donâ€™t necessarily see this as a huge problem given the real purpose of this essay (which I see as presenting the conclusions you have come to based on the evidence youâ€™ve been presented) but if you ever wanted to say, turn this into a book, you would need to work really hard at establishing a basis for many of your speculations. \r\n\r\nYouâ€™re claim that population is the factor which must be controlled more so than energy is a HUGE claim. You could dedicate an entire paper to that one claim. I know itâ€™s not really the point of your paper, but if youâ€™re going to say something that huge, spend more time on it.\r\n\r\nI very much got the impression that this paper is geared towards inhabitants of North America. You are trying to establish what we as North Americans can do, and why we should do it. I feel that you should establish this in your introduction. Also, it is totally appropriate to introduce your solutions in the introduction (higher taxes, more conservation, and of course more concern) so that the reader knows what youâ€™re working towards.  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-06-02','2008-06-03 06:09:49'),(374,84,'DAM','In a medieval village there is a quiet man. He has 2 suits of clothes (each week he washes one) he lives in someone\'s house, he does odd jobs around the town. Says little, keeps to himself. \r\n\r\none day a stranger comes. The reader knows the stranger is from the future. our quiet man takes him aside, gives him some clothes, helps him fit in. And, surprise, talks to him about prospects for returning to his own town. \r\n\r\nThe quiet man is time traveler who is marooned here. He would go back if there was a way but sees no way but he\'s happy to help the newcomer -- especially if that will keep the village peaceful and calm...','2008-06-09','2008-06-09 18:46:03'),(375,84,'DAM','<h2>Commencement</h2>\r\nGood afternoon to you all and congratulations!\r\n\r\nI am afraid I have some rather bad news for you, especially on such a happy occasion as this. \r\n\r\nWe are, all of us, fools. You too. But not just you, all of us. \r\n\r\nWe all put importance on things that aren\'t important and ignore things as trivial that are crucial. \r\n\r\nWe live with our foolishness ','2008-06-14','2008-06-14 17:35:04'),(376,40,'defer','I\'ve long thought about a game play element that I\'d like to pitch to you. I thought of it as the central theme of the game but it might be toned down to be just a single mission or some background element. \r\n\r\nThe basic idea is what I call an \"information economy\". The players in the game expend effort and, possibly, resources to collect information and then sell that information to people for whom the information is useful. They can also buy information and then package it up to sell it \"upstream\" for higher prices. To support this concept, I came up with the mechanism of \"triplets\": there are three pieces of information and the people who find this information useful will pay a lot for a complete set, thus allowing others to pay less for each of the pieces. \r\n\r\nThe actual information is less important but, obviously, it has to be *something* specific. One example would be for the triplet of information to describe an event and the pieces to be the time, place and type of event. The event itself could be a meeting, an attack, a transaction, etc. \r\n\r\nIn order to attain this information, the player needs to use survailance, breaking and entering \r\n\r\nIt would also be possible to generalize this structure to have any number of pieces of information and have the value of the information be on a sliding scale depending on how many pieces of information you sell as a set.\r\n\r\nAs part of a bigger game the information economy could either be a single mission (for example the player needs to get some money to do the next mission so you have a mission that involves collecting certain information and selling it) ','2008-06-14','2008-06-14 17:42:09'),(377,84,'DAM','<h2>Speech For The Commencement of Class of 2012 of the Time Traveler Institute</h2>\r\n\r\nClass of 2012, we welcome you to The Time Traveler Institute. As freshman you may be surprised that we have the commencement the first year you\'re here. But we find it saves a lot of time.\r\n\r\nThe program lists those students who will graduate; as you name is called, please accept your 2012 diploma in advance. Those not on the list, don\'t despair. Most of you will go on to do great things after leaving us. This applies especially to John Hernadez; it will be a tragedy and make us all sad when you commit suicide tomorrow. \r\n\r\nWe\'ll also like to offer condolences to the families of those who will die over the next 4 years; we\'re so sorry!\r\n\r\nTonight we\'ll have the video of our student speakers, recorded in 2012. \r\nAfter the second speaker there will be a fire alarm. This will not be a drill. Please leave the auditorium in a calm quick manner; no one will be hurt in the ensuing fire but that\'s because everyone leaves camly and quickly.\r\n\r\nThe third speaker and the rest of the commencement will completed next week at this auditorium. \r\n\r\nNow, without further ado we\'ll proceed to the first speaker. \r\n\r\nThank you\r\n\r\n','2008-06-15','2008-06-16 04:32:13'),(378,86,'davemenc','Idea: one person is tongue tied nervous\r\nidea: ','2008-06-29','2008-06-29 16:46:00'),(379,39,'Old','I assume, probably as does everyone else, that I have a unique perspective on the world. I see no reason to believe that we aren\'t all right. In the last few years, I\'ve come to understand some portion of the depth of that difference in perspective. \r\n\r\nI feel the need to touch on that most tedious of subjects: my beliefs. \r\n\r\nImagine that you knew that every human being was connected to you, not because someone told you or because you simply had faith, but because you directly experienced it every time you talked to another human being. Would that change your perspective on your fellow beings? \r\n\r\nImagine further that you knew, and had known since your earliest days, for as long as you could remember, that there was a God and that you could experience him directly at any time. What would that do to your world view?\r\n\r\nWell, these two statements apply to me. I have no idea if everyone can perceive these things and just won\'t admit it or is blocking it or if it\'s really just a thing given to some people. And, I\'ll be honest, I know no better than you do if I\'m insane. \r\n\r\nBut look at it from my perspective, please: *I* feel these things very deeply and if they are a sign of insanity there\'s really nothing I can do about it. So I accept my own perspective as real. \r\n\r\nAnd now it\'s your turn: you don\'t really know if you\'re insane either but you happily accept your perspective as real. Unless of course you really ARE insane in which case you should get off the computer and back into your padded cell. Now! I mean it!\r\n\r\nI know what I know and I completely accept both the reality of it and the fact that others won\'t necessarily accept it\'s reality. It leads to some mildly awkward situations. I mean, sure the reality is that we\'re all brothers. But we certainly seem in every rational, emotional, and physical way to be separate. \r\n\r\nWhen someone panhandles me, I know perfectly well that I\'ll be just as happy with the money in his pocket as in mine, ultimately. So I\'m happy to give it to him. But whoever I\'m with finds this to be really naive and dumb. Even the recipient feels that he\'s pulling one over on me. In a way, it\'s kind of cute -- they think I\'m the naive one! \r\n\r\nIt\'s not all just a feeling on my part. I have some specific experiences that are hard to explain (unless, of course, I question my own experiences in which case we\'re back to the insanity thing). It turns out that it\'s possible to create a situation in which someone else feels my intention or in which I feel someone else\'s intention. It\'s kind of like the Jedi suggestion except that recipient is under no compulsion -- they simply feel happy to go along with whatever is happening. I\'ve seen masters do amazing things with this but I\'m not that into it. But I know it\'s there; it\'s real. \r\n\r\nThe point of all this is not to convince you I\'m a nut. You\'ll come to understand that all too soon, I\'m sorry to say. The purpose is to give you the background on my perspective. If I don\'t tell you where I\'m coming from, you\'ll have no way of knowing. ','2008-07-21','2008-07-22 05:35:44'),(380,15,'DAM','In Dope Wars the whole deal is to find the good that has the largest variance in absolute amount (between buying in one place and selling in another) and trade in it. If you don\'t have enough money to fill your hold, you might want to buy buy something cheaper with a smaller variance. \r\n\r\nPercentage is largely irrelevant; the reason you want to buy this instead of that is because you can make more money per unit. Your profit is p=v*c where p is profit, v is variance and c is units of cargo which is the smaller of the total you can afford and the total you can carry. \r\n\r\nif M is money, B buy price,S is sell price and C is your total cargo capacity then c=min(int(M/B),C); v=S-B and p=min(int(M/B),C)*(S-B).\r\n\r\nSo what we want is a range of goods that have different values and variance proportional to the costs. \r\n\r\nWe also want a player to be able to buy more cargo capacity for a LOT of money. It shouldn\'t be linear, either. Maybe it\'s not buying another ship but buying a ship with 10 times then 100 times then 1000 times more capacity. ','2008-07-21','2008-07-22 05:48:22'),(381,39,'DAM','\"The Surge Is Working\" seems to be a phrase I hear a lot from conservative pundits these days. I have two issues with this phrase, one small and one huge. \r\n\r\nThe small issue is that we\'ve heard phrases before. \"Weapons Of Mass Destruction\" was popular for a while, and \"Links to Al-Qaeda\" followed by \"End Of Major Combat Operations\",  \"There\'s No Civil War\" and many, many others. And I\'ve also heard that the US Army is overestimating the progress that it\'s making in Iraq in terms of infrastructure. All of this has been designed to hide the simple fact that this war has been an absolute catastrophe. So here we are, again, claiming that, unlike all the failed policies that got us here, THIS policy saves us. Finally, the invasion of Iraq is working! Wow, that\'s a relief!\r\n\r\nWe\'ll I\'m sorry, but I don\'t believe you. I\'ve been told this so many times before and now you\'re telling me again that everything is good and I just don\'t believe you. It\'s like Lucy and the football. Every fall Lucy promises to hold the football for Charlie Brown and then pulls it away at the last second and every year he believes that THIS time she\'ll hold it. But you lost me the first time you pulled that football away from me!\r\n\r\nThat\'s the minor point: that I think the statement \"The Surge Is Working\" is an exaggeration or a careful selection of the facts or even an outright lie. \r\n\r\nThe major point is that, even if I believed you, the statement is meaningless. We went into this war with the intention (so we were told) of liberating the Iraqi people from a horrible dictator and giving them democracy. How are we doing on that? The country has descended into hell, there are warlords who control big chunks of the country, they can\'t keep infrastructure working much less build new infrastructure because it keeps getting destroyed, and there are people killed every week. \r\n\r\nOur goal was to restore order and even create a democracy in Iraq and people are claiming that the \"Surge is Working\" because fewer people are getting killed!? THIS is working? Really? \r\n\r\nBy and large people like William Crystal and David Brooks are smarter than me, better informed than me and every bit as honest as I am. But it seems that, sometimes, when you want something really, really bad, even the smartest, most informed and most integral are willing to claim anything as a victory rather than admit defeat. \r\n\r\nThe surge is working if and only if you are willing to redefine the word \"working\" so that it means \"not quite as large a debacle as it was before\". Nothing about this war is \"working\" in any other sense. ','2008-07-23','2008-07-23 18:23:29'),(382,39,'DAM','There seems to me to be much illogic in the current discussion of what to do about the housing crisis. \r\n\r\nThe first thing people do when discussing this subject is apportion blame (come to think of it, that seems to be the first step in every crisis, doesn\'t it?). Who are the victims here? The home owners','2008-07-25','2008-07-25 23:47:51'),(383,81,'Rongo!','<h2>The Drink Menu</h2>\r\n<li>Admiral Nelson 1 oz rum, 1 oz gin, 2 tsp triple sec, dash of lime juice.\r\n<li>Bacardi 1.5 oz rum, 1 oz limeade, dash of grenadine.\r\n<li>Bacardi Special 1 oz rum, 0.5 oz gin, 1 oz limeade, dash of grenadine.\r\n<li>Banana Daiquiri 1.5 oz rum, 1 oz limeade, 1 tsp sugar, 1/3 banana.\r\n<li>Batida de c^oco 1.5 oz cachaÂ»ca, 1 oz sweetened coconut cream, 1 oz condensed milk.\r\n<li>Batida de maracujÂ¶a 1.5 oz cachaÂ»ca, 3 oz passion fruit juice, 1 tsp condensed milk.\r\n<li>Black Hawk 1 oz bourbon, 1 oz gin, 1.5 oz lemonade.\r\n<li>Black Russian 0.75 oz KahlÂ¶ua, 1 oz vodka, ice.\r\n<li>Bloody Mary 1.5 oz vodka, 6 oz tomato juice, 