 <DD >start marching forward, in column </dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>Left Turn March</b> <DD >turn left  </dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>Right Turn March</b> <DD >turn right </dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>Halt</b> <DD > Stop</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>Double Time</b> <DD > march faster</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>Form Bars</b> <DD > Put together the bars</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>break down bars</b> <DD > take bars apart</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>Dismissed</b> <DD > Go off and play (but don\'t go far)</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt><b>Spin March</b> <DD > turn in place while walking</dfn></dt>\r\n</dl>\r\n<h2>Equipment list</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>6 shields\r\n<li>coolers\r\n<li>goldie\r\n<li>bucket of grog\r\n<li>misc. bar tools\r\n<li>Booze carrier (some kind of strap)\r\n<li>glasses carrier\r\n<ul>\r\n<h2> Roles</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>sergeant -- leads every aspect\r\n<li>Bartender (2) -- tends the bar\r\n<li>Shield bearer (6) -- carries the bar\r\n<li>Goldie Bearer (2-4)-- Carries Goldie\r\n<li>Cooler Carrier (2-4) -- Carries coolers\r\n<Li>Booze Carrier (?) -- carries booze\r\n<li> Drummer -- keeps beat\r\n<li>Other carrier -- carries something else\r\n<li>Marcher -- everyone is a marcher but some people are nothing else\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2> Sequence of Bar Construction</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li> sergeant stops march (halt)\r\n<li>sergeant calls for bar build (Form Bars) -- it will be build right in front of him -- and people get ready\r\n<li>sergeant calls for \"bases\" and 2 SPECIFIC shield bearers kneel at his feet\r\n<li>sergeant calls for \"bases\" again 2 more add their pieces\r\n<li>sergeant calls \"tops\" and get the tops of the bars -- specific people among the 3 marchers have mallets and do what needs to be done\r\n<li>sergeant calls for \"Coolers\" and the coolers are brought up\r\n<li> sergeant calls for booze and glasses and anything else that\'s needed\r\n<li>sergeant calls for bartenders\r\n<li>sergeant calls \"begin boozing\" to indicate the bar is open and steps out of the way\r\n<li> sergeant calls \"dismissed\" and everyone but the bartenders wanders off\r\n</ol>\r\n','2008-08-12','2008-08-12 19:42:49'),(385,87,'DAM','Need some pointers about how to march. \"lead with left\"\r\n','2008-08-12','2008-08-12 19:43:33'),(386,88,'davemenc',' ','2008-10-19','2008-10-20 06:02:35'),(387,88,'DAM','4 thngs\r\n1 stay in the lane\r\n2 keep around your speed limit\r\n3 stay a certain distance behind the car ahead of you n your lane\r\n4 don\'t collide wth any other cars\r\n\r\nThese are backwards n ompoprtance: dump 4 befor 1\r\n\r\nFor each car we need to know \r\n  x,y\r\n  x,y speed (or angle and speed)\r\n  index (index is the distance from the beginning of the road -- mile marker)\r\n  Lane\r\n\r\nThe world is defined as a collection of roadways (main roadway and on ramps) each of which consistss of a series of line segments and the widths of all the lanes. Each segment has a start and end index.\r\n\r\nIndexes are in whatever unit we\'re using (feet? meters?) and are counted by the lengths of all the line segments.\r\n\r\nThe \"track\" is defined by an XML document that defines each line seqment as an x1,y1, x2,y2 line segment in order. The indexes of all these is determined by counting the first one as 0 and then adding the length and that\'s the end of the first seqment and the beginning of the second. So then you do a binary search to see how far along we are.\r\n\r\nTo figure out the index of the projected location of a car we can simply add the distance it\'s expected to travel and assume it will be parallel to the edge. So you just take the current index and add to it the distance. This is going to have an error in it but I\'m not sure how to fix it yet. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2008-10-19','2008-10-20 06:11:16'),(388,88,'DAM','For each car\r\n calculate the location of all the cars as if they don\'t change their acceleration\r\n calculate the distance among all these predicted locations\r\n If our car gets too close to any other car, move away from the closest car\r\n If our car gets ','2008-10-19','2008-10-20 06:12:24'),(390,89,'davemenc','A \"book\" is made up of the following entities\r\nChapters\r\nSections\r\nSub-sections\r\nscenes\r\n\r\nThese are hiearchical in the sense that sections never span chapters, sub-section never span sections and all scenes are held within sub-sections. \r\n\r\nThere are two tools. One tool takes markers in a big chunk of text and breaks the text into sub-folders while, at the same time, constructing an outline. \r\n\r\nThe text must have special characters embeded at the beginning of the lines to tell it how to break up the text. Here they are (two forms):\r\n\r\nChapters ~~ or Chapter\r\nSections ** or Section\r\nSub-sections -- Or SSection\r\nscenes $$ or scene\r\n\r\nThe text after the markers doesn\'t matter to the program but the program preserves it and saves it into the outline. \r\n\r\nIt splits these into files that are called something generic like filexxxx or something (Maybe the name of the book should be in place of \"file\" so we can find them; this suggests a new code && which means \"title\" and we might as well add in a note //)\r\n\r\nSo this first tool chops up innocent text and generates lots of little files and a <title>outline.txt file which has the key to where all the individual files go.\r\n\r\nThe second tool eats the outline file and spits out the book. By default it will put all the cute little codes back into the book just where they belong. But it should also be able to suppress any of them optionally. \r\n\r\nIt simply ','2008-11-23','2008-11-23 17:32:42'),(391,84,'DAM','<h2>Starless Notes</h2>\r\nThe Line is a line because of the mountains. But why end points? Maybe it doesn\'t really have any end points but Alana was interested more in the edges. And the edges aren\'t straight but very convoluted; she theorizes, but hasn\'t confirmed that the edges have to do with the thickest parts of the mountains or some other attribute of the mountains themselves. \r\n\r\nThe reason the gradient works the way it does is because as the field strengths fall off it takes it out of the realm of the stasis field and puts it into a closer paths. The closest paths have slight shifts in the one or another dimension so that you can\'t really tell. So as you move it farther out it\'s still having almost the same effect -- which is to say that it\'s moving the truck into another dimension -- but you just can\'t tell because the dimension is just like this one. \r\n\r\nEvery now and then, though, instead of NOTHING happening, the eye or the film cameras catch a little flicker, as if the truck started to move into another dimension and then decided not to. What\'s really happening is that the truck is actually moving into another dimension but it\'s shifting in time ever so slightly so that all that happens is it flickers. \r\n\r\nThe power consumption would be very much the same as when it actually moves into another dimension and that means that it\'s anomolous anyway. What she needs is two atomic clocks...\r\n','2008-12-21','2008-12-22 09:21:22'),(392,84,'DAM','<h2>Starless Notes</h2>\r\n\r\nTwo young men got off their bicycles at the street and walked up the path to the front door. When they rang the bell nothing happened for some time but, just as they were about to turn away, the door opened and young man, about their age loooked out at them. \r\n\r\n\"I believe you are members of the Church of the Latter Day Saints? Am I right?\"\r\n\r\nThe two young men admitted that they were.\r\n\r\nThe young man in the open door came out on to the front step and closes the door behind him. It was a small step and so the two young mormon misionaries suddenly felt a bit crowded. They definitely felt liek their personal space was being invaded. If the goal was to intimidate, it was at least partially successful. One backed up to the edge while the other stepped down on to the concrete walkway. This made him shorter than the young man and so, if anything, it made him feel more intimidated. \r\n\r\nThe young man seemed delighted to see them but niether misionary thought it was a good kind of delight. They had been riding around for 4 hours already and they had taken a lot of abuse. It looked like they were in for some more. \r\n\r\n\"An organization\" the young man said, \"which engages in political discourse or supports political causes is a political organization. Religious organizations in America are not allowed to do that. And an organization which tries to take away the rights of minorities -- especially the rights of an identified and protected minority -- is an evil organization. For example, the Klu Klux Klan styles itself as a religion of sorts but it\'s actually an evil political organization.\r\n\r\n\"The Church of the Latter Day Saints was very involved in the last election, pushing for another bill that would prevent gay people from getting married, just as they did in the 2008 election. That makes the organization you belong to, although it styles itself a church, an evil political organization, no different, in principle, than the KKK. \r\n\r\n\"Thus,\" and here the young man\'s voice became much louder, \"a person less reasonable than myself would view you as skinheads and attack you on sight! Instead, I\'m going to tell you what I think of you -- which is very little -- and why and then ask you to leave.\"\r\n\r\n\"And, what the hell are you doing here anyway?\" he continued, warming to his subject. \"Do you honestly imagine that there is a person on this block, or in the whole state of California, that has not heard of your church? What, exactly, do you think you\'re doing here? Am I an aborigine, far from phones or televisions, who has never heard of Jesus!?\" By the time, the young man was shouting.\r\n\r\nBoth Mormons took a step back. The one on the step stumbled off and almost fell but the other one didn\'t catch him because he was already turning to flee back up the walkway. \r\n\r\n\"Please,\" the young man, thoroughly delighted with himself for having causes do much discomfiture, \"don\'t break your neck until you are off my property. I don\'t object to you hurting yourself so much but I would hate to have to pay the lawsuit! Now, go!\"\r\n\r\nThis last was quite unnecessary as the two missionaries were already getting on their bike. It certainly wasn\'t fair ','2008-12-22','2008-12-22 09:40:39'),(393,84,'DAM','<h2>Religion/Science Debate</h2>\r\nImagine there is an actual depate: \"Resolved: Religion has no place in society and should be completely replace by the Scientific Method.\" or some such.\r\n\r\nThe first possibility is to actually HAVE the debate. One person taking the pro, one the con and away we go. \r\n\r\nA more interesting possibility, especially if we do the first debate and then follow with this, is the idea that one person is talking pro and the other is not following the format at all. Every time the pro says something the Con partial agrees but points out that there are other possibilities. He tries, not to win, but to promote a third case -- the case that it\'s not an either/or proposition, not really.','2008-12-31','2008-12-31 19:32:50'),(394,61,'DAM','Why are there all these blank notes here? That makes me very nervous...\r\n\r\nOk, my though about this is that the point of view of the book could be completely from a project manager.','2008-12-31','2008-12-31 19:34:21'),(395,61,'DAM','Just to recap this idea, we have a fairly rich and successful american construction guy. He somehow gets kicked out of america or he retires or something. \r\n\r\nHe goes to the middle east, into Palestinian controlled territory and starts a construction company by buying an existing company. The existing company has some equipment (little equipment in western terms but most of the equipment in the area) but has been failing because no one wants to build anything in the middle of poverty and violence. \r\n\r\nHe convinces the proprietor, a relatively young Palestinian, to stay on. The young man wanted to be in construction and took over his father\'s business upon his father\'s death but couldn\'t make it work. So the main issue with his selling the business and continuing to work is the fact that his father\'s business will be owned by an American. He feels about this in about the same way we feel about the Chinese or Japanese buying up all our businesses, except he\'s far, far more passionate about it. Ultimately, what choice does he really have. \r\n\r\nAll this is told from the point of view of the project manager who is one of the very few people who come over from america.\r\n\r\nNow the new owner, let\'s call him \"Sam\", has connections. He has money and he starts by rebuilding businesses that can\'t really be abandoned. Grocerty stores, hostpitals, schools, shipping, etc. These are fundamentally sound businesses that are failing because their infrastructure has been destroyed or has decayed out of usefulness. \r\n\r\nSo he invests in the businesses. He doesn\'t build the stuff for free. Rather he invests in the businesses, uses those investments to attract other, local investments, and then uses this capitol to build the buildings. In the end, he owns pieces of various essential businesses and the government owes him money to pay back various short and medium term loans he\'s made.\r\n\r\nThis creates a situation in which people have to respect him for getting these things to work but they are also suspicious of him for the fact that he makes a profit on every deal and they resent him. Who is he to come in, profit in their misfortune and then, to add insult to injury, make their society a better place when they themselves could not. \r\n\r\nThe Israelis don\'t like him because he seems to be in bed with the local terrorist government. They hate that. \r\n\r\nThe government doesn\'t like him because, first off, all the emotional reasons above, and then, they owe him money. Rather than give him the money they\'d rather kick him out and use the money for something else. \r\n\r\nHe spends some time sleeping in a different place every night.\r\n\r\nEventually, his projects work and it can be shown that, if he\'s doing well personally, he\'s doing it by doing good so people are mollified. And he\'s careful to remain a SILENT partner in all the businesses so it\'s not like the American is TAKING OVER, he\'s just helping Palestinians to help themselves. \r\n\r\nThe Israelis ultimately accuse him of laundering money for the terrorists but a series of audits show that, almost miraculously, ever dollar invested went into legitimate businesses. There was some money that went into bribes but it\'s not substantial and even the Israelis know that this is how things work. Ultimately, the businesses he got working give people hope and reduce violence and so the Israelis back off. \r\n\r\nNice story? It\'s just the beginning. Now the guy starts a new round of businesses. Software. Manufacturing. Transport. Businesses that require infrastructure which he will build. He invests, he gets the locals to invest (they\'re making money now) and then he goes back to America and talks to his friends there and gets THEM to invest. \r\n\r\nThis freaks everyone out again! The Israelis have concerns about where these huge amounts of money are going. The government has concerns that he\'s bringing in more American control. But, this time, the people are with him because for them it\'s just jobs and hope. \r\n\r\nHe\'s now having some trouble with his right hand man, the guy who owned the company in the first place. There are a lot of construction projects and Sam is careful to pick and choose only those that he, personally, can profit from. Ultimately, amid sparks and upset, the young man starts his own company with money from local investors. This seems like a bad thing because now there is competition. It\'s much harder to get local investment and thus to attract foreign investment. But there are more projects starting and both companies manage to eke out an existance. \r\n\r\nThen the region begins to boom and Sam is a hero. Everyone loves him! Yay.\r\n\r\nThen comes a downturn. Now he\'s a smuck. His firm is on very firm financial footing and he\'s still managing to get some work so his firm is surviving. But his rival\'s firm is on hard times. It looks like the other company is going to fail which will be a boon for Sam\'s firm. At the 11th hour someone comes in and invests in the other firm, saving it. \r\n\r\nThe economy comes back a bit and we see a very different region than we saw before. The attentions of the locals is primarily on working and making money. There are still some hotheads but they don\'t have much support and the local police tend to keep them in check. This makes Israel happy (or at least not as angry) and so Israel is a source of wealth, as a happy trading partner. People doing to to Israel to work, they work locally and export the goods and services. This is more secure. For once the spiral is working in the right direction. Working businesses generate capital that gets invested to make more working businesses. Prosperity eases tensions which reduces violence which allows for prosperity. Good relations with Israel allow for trade which creates better relationships with Israel. Essentially, we pan across the landscape and see that the region is finally getting on it\'s feet. Even Sam\'s competing firm is doing well.\r\n\r\nThere are some, however, for whom this is a nightmare. Prosperity is bad so they try to destabilize the situation. They kidnap ISraeli soldiers or do some other bad things. But they people who do these things have always depended on a combination of fear and support to survive and the people simply aren\'t interested. The police receive tips about where these people are, there is a final showdown and the police let the soldiers go. Yay.\r\n\r\nIn the end Sam retires and sells his business to his rival for a very good price. THis surprises some people because they\'ve fought so long and hard. The project manager, who, at this point, knows all about both businesses, is taken into the confidence of the Palestinian owner. They had worked together before and, well, he\'s an american but he\'s not so bad (maybe he\'s a Palestinian American or maybe he black or something that would differentiate him in the eyes of the locals from Sam). As the pm goes through the new, expanded business he notices that there were investments made by Sam that the PM didn\'t know about at the time. And these same amounts of money show up in the Palestinian\'s company at about the same time. Apparently, the savior of the company was it\'s greatest rival. \r\n\r\nIt evolves that Sam was simply trying to build a viable economy and he needed someone to carry on after he was gone. \r\n\r\nThe end. \r\n\r\nThe point of the book is that people aren\'t inherently bad but that their fears make them bad. If you can assuage their fears they begin to look at how to live instead of how to take their enemies with them when they die. There is a certain tipping point and once that point is reached the force of the economy which dictated violence begins to cause peace.','2008-12-31','2008-12-31 20:12:47'),(396,90,'davemenc','Ian','2008-12-31','2008-12-31 21:00:06'),(397,90,'DAM','Ian looked under the bed but all he found was dust. He looked in his brother\'s dresser but there was nothing but clothes there. He slid the closet doors to his side of the closet. There on the floor of his brother\'s side of the closet was a suspicious lump under a small pile of clothes. \r\n\r\nIan moved the pile of clothes to reveal a box that a proclaimed that it contained 7 games in one. This was what his brother was going to give him for Christmas!\r\n\r\nQuickly he put the clothes back on the game, closed the closet and quickly walked away as if he hadn\'t just cheated and found where his christmas present was hidden.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n\"Did you look in my closet!?\" asked Ian\'s brother?\r\n\r\n\"No\" responded Ian. \r\n\r\n\"You did , too.\" \r\n\r\nAnd with that, Ian\'s brother grabbed Ian and threw him to the ground.  Ian, who was something of an expert, not to say, connoisseur of beatings, didn\'t find this one to be much of a beating. But it\'s still not much fun.\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-01-01','2009-01-02 04:45:09'),(398,90,'DAM','\"Ian, would you come into my office please\" said Harold Manning, the head of corporate recruiting for Cool Technical Associates over the telephone. \r\n \r\nHe had been watching Ian for some time and was disturbed that his employee was too much of a wimp to be successful in his department. Today was the day for Ian\'s \"come to Jesus\" meeting. \r\n\r\n\"Look, Ian, this is a dog-eat-dog world. You are simply too nice a person to be successful here. You need to toughen up and not be so willing to go along with what people tell you.\"\r\n\r\nHe was surprised by Ian\'s reaction: Ian laughed. Harold had a lot of experience managing people and a lot of experience with come to Jesus meetings and this is the last thing he expected. When you call them into your office and tell them that they are screwing up the bullies get aggressive and the wimps get sad. He\'d seen sullen and angry and denial and acceptance but never humor. Never any hint of humor.\r\n\r\nHe put on his tough guy act -- wimps always fold when confronted. \"What do you find so damn funny, Ian? Why do you laugh?\r\n\r\nIan laughed again and, while he was still smiling pulled a notebook from his back pocket. Reading from the notebook he said, \"In the time I\'ve been here, I\'ve been given 5 major assignments and I\'ve completed all of them, and you yourself have expressed deep satisfaction with the success of 3 of those assignments. Henry has been given 3 assignments but two of them were marked failures and the other I helped him with. Sue has taken on 4 companies but only one was satisfied. Fred did only two assignment and neither one was a stellar success. Jimmy finished 2 of his three and Wayne finished 3 of his four. They are actually pretty good workers which is why I helped them get their stuff done.\"\r\n\r\nIan\'s face changed from a smile to a look of genuine annoyance. \"Since I\'ve gotten here, your entire organization has been consumed with squabbling and back biting. You seem to reward undirected aggression even at the expense of actual performance. I noticed it almost immediately. I decided that, despite the weird atmosphere, it would be easy to succeed here. I worked hard on my assignments and, whenever I was challenged by my co-workers in any way, I backed down. I always ceded to them the best assignments, the good resources, and admitted that they were my superior in every way. Always in public, at least. In private, however, I had a discreet talk with each of them. Each of them were willing to give me considerations -- assignments, resources, leads, whatever -- in return for support against the other members of the team. By helping Harold make Fred look bad, I got a whole file of brand new leads. For helping Henry undermine Sue, Henry let me finish his assignment and rack up a bunch of placements.\"\r\n\r\nIan started to smile again. \"What\'s funny is that you are calling your best worker out on the carpet -- the one who is doing almost all the work -- because you believe he isn\'t going to succeed in this environment. That\'s actually hilarious!\"\r\n\r\nHarry\'s surprise turned to anger. This piss ant noob was trying to tell him how to run his business? He was full of shit! Harry knew that his team spent at least as much time trying to undercut each other as they did closing placements but they still got a huge amount done. That very aggression that caused them to attack each other was the thing that was needed to get the job done. Recruiting was war! You needed to attack the problem and kick ass to get placements and you couldn\'t just play games like Ian did. \r\n\r\n\"Ian, you\'re fired! Get your ass out of my office.\" \r\n\r\n\"Ok, boss. I\'m glad we had this conversation because I was going to give you two weeks notice today and now I can just leave. Thanks.\" And with that he tore a few pages from his notebook out and let them flutter to the desk, turned, and walked out of the office to say goodbye to his colleagues.\r\n\r\nHarry couldn\'t resist; he picked up the closest piece of paper. It had Sue\'s name on it and under that it had a list of her assignments over the last few months. Each one had a bunch of marks with a total number. It looked like the number of placements for each of the companies. It was absurdly low. Sue was a hard worker, an abrasive, aggressive go-getter. No one could cold call a company like she could! Surely she had gotten more placements than this.\r\n\r\nHe looked at the other pieces of paper and found similar stories. Some had done better and some even worse but no one had really nailed their assignments, according to these numbers. And he knew they must be wrong because there was no way that we had done so poorly on the Application Network job or on the Integrate Science contract. Those companies had been very satisfied. \r\n\r\nOnly when he had looked at the last piece of paper, the one with Ian\'s name on it, did he begin to doubt his version of reality. This showed large numbers for both AN and IS -- had Ian been carrying everyone else for this past months? Surely not.\r\n\r\nHarry turned on his computer and called up the commissions. Sure enough, Ian had gotten the lion\'s share of all the commissions for the last several months. What the hell was up with that? The weak link was carrying the strong links. \r\n\r\nHarry sat and thought about what Ian had said and tried to fit it into what he himself had observed. It began to all fit together. Ian always backed down in public but he always seemed to be working some kind of deal whenever Harry encountered him outside of meeting. \r\n\r\nIt had seemed like Ian was simply a waste of space -- someone who just didn\'t fit in --  but now Harry realized that he had been undermining the whole operation since he got there. Back in the good old days there had been less back biting and more work getting done. Now that Ian was gone, the team would be even stronger.\r\n\r\nHarry left the office to make sure that Ian was gone and to call a meeting which would bring on a new and more prosperous period for everyone. \r\n\r\nIt was as if he didn\'t e notice that the placement numbers for the past few months had been hirer than ever before. As if he didn\'t know that the good old days had not been all that good.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-01-19','2009-01-20 01:38:53'),(399,84,'DAM','<h2>Miscelleneous Dinner</h2>\r\nAn awards dinner. 8 people around a table, arbitrarily self-selected. A man (bob) is sitting by himself and the woman (alice) next to him is the wife of a man (charlie) who wrote a book that is getting an award, was up for an award or was published by someone who is putting on the awards -- he is there because of his book. We know nothing of bob.\r\n\r\nBob turns to alice and says in a voice loud enough to be heard around the table \"Now that your husband has published his excrable and pointless book I suppose your life has become completely meaningless, depending as it does on whatver meaning your husband can find for his.\" (Or some other such thing, attacking the husband through the wife and implying that both of them are useless). He turns to charlie and says \"what, no comment?\"\r\n\r\nCharlie responds that it is a statement sufficiently interesting to warrant comment. He notes that it was sexist and that the women around the table were more offended than the men indicating that our society still has significant sexist tendencies. The actual comments aren\'t very interesting but the tone suggests that bob has some kind of issues. It\'s as if bob had, in the middle of a light and well prepared repast, thrown up all over the table. The obvious response is to try to clean up the mess but the interesting question is, what did the sick person eat that caused them to throw up? So, sir, what is your issue that compells you to try to pick a fight with such passionate comments.\r\n\r\nBob gets up and leaves. Maybe we learn later what is thing is, and maybe we don\'t. \r\n\r\ncharlie turns to the table and asks if any one knows what it was that bob was trying to say? \r\n\r\nMaybe he\'s just a bully. \r\n\r\nNot a bad hypothesis but bullies are shooting for an effect and don\'t generally have so much passion. Of course the passion, like the fossiles, may have been planted but one would want some other supporting evidence. \r\nThe man ','2009-01-22','2009-01-22 18:12:57'),(400,88,'DAM','','2009-01-22','2009-01-23 17:07:56'),(402,84,'DAM','<h1>Business Meeting</h1>\r\nThe boss has called all the workers into a room -- maybe 8 -- and is telling them about the challenges ahead, the goals, giving them a pep talk or just letting his ego run wild. He can do that, he\'s the boss. \r\n\r\nEveryone has come in and sat down, many have coffee, some have notebooks and several have put their cellphones on the table in front of them. \r\n\r\nAt some point one of the worker, murmuring \"excuse me\" gets up and leaves. The boss seems mildly annoyed but this meeting has been going on for a while and the boss doesn\'t happen to be talking at that moment so he says nothing. \r\n\r\nA few minutes later the phone of the person left behind starts to play some obnoxious ring tone. Stanford and Sons would be good except that it\'s too true. Acid rock, perhaps or some other TV jingle. Maybe a commercial. \r\n\r\nEveryone has stopped talking and are looking at each other. The boss walks around to the side of the table with the cell phone, picks it up  and walks to the door. Opening the door, he throws it, with significant force. We hear it hit a wall and bounce. \r\n\r\nHe turns to the person who had been speaking and says, with a smile, \"You were saying?\" The meeting goes on.\r\n\r\nOne might, if one wishes, describe the scene when the person who left gets back and finds his cell phone in the hallway but I would prefer to leave that to the imagination. ','2009-01-23','2009-01-23 17:14:05'),(401,39,'DAM','<h2>Occam\'s Razor</h2>\r\nOccam\'s Razor should not be used to shave the barber. That is, it might be\r\nuseful to direct your attention more closely to something but it should not be\r\nused as the only indicator of truth. Many many wrong things have been\r\npropogated because they were the simplest explanation. Simplicity, by itself is\r\nnot an indicator of truth. \r\n','2009-01-23','2009-01-23 17:02:30'),(403,84,'DAM','<h2>Easter</h2>\r\nIan is in high school. He is living at home, the last child out. He is not living as an only child but as a solidary child. His parents are at least as focused on his absent sibs as on him but he\'s the one who washes the dishes, mowes the lawn, etc. \r\n\r\nEaster comes and everyone comes home. In a way, he is a host of the activities in terms of preparations and certainly by implication since he LIVES here and they are VISITING. \r\n\r\nBut in the event, he finds himself shockingly back in the role of youngest child. \r\n\r\nThis is a way to point up his relationship to his family and to show that it\'s not worth spending a lot of time on it. \r\n\r\n','2009-01-23','2009-01-23 17:17:12'),(404,84,'DAM','I guy sends the US secretory of war a letter in which he predicts 4 events.  The letter is postmarked August, 1939 from Elk City, KS. It was signed with an unusual (but not bizzare) name. Like \"Kenneth Kurtz\" or \"Jonathon Fredricks\" -- not \"John Smith\". The letter was marked \"personal and confidential\".\r\nThe events are\r\n1) Invasion of poland, September 1, 1939.\r\n2) Poland defeated by October 1, 1939\r\n3) Invasion of France, May 10, 1940. \r\n4) Surrender of France, June 25, 1940.\r\n\r\nThe secretary of war Harry Hines Woodring actually gets the letter and reads it. But he finds it ridiculous. It\'s possible that Poland will be invaded but certainly not in few weeks. And the other 3 dates are just absurd. Poland would make a better showing and France\'\'s army is greatest in the world -- it\'s unlikely Germany would even try them and, even if they did, theres no way they would win and certainly no way they\'d win quickly. And what\'s this BS about the invasion of france happening months after the fall of poland? Surely  Germany would be invaded by france much sooner than that.\r\n\r\nAfter the invasion of Poland happens the SecWar is mildly surprised  -- the date is exactly right -- but figures its a lucky guess. But when Poland falls in a month -- again on the exact date predicted -- even an asshat like the secwar knows something is up. He asks the FBI to find this guy. \r\n\r\nNot much chance of that happening. \r\nThe guy is a time traveler and left the timeline the day after he sent the letter. He appears at the front door of the war department asking to see the secwar a week later. \r\n\r\nThe secwar has him arrested. The secwar believes that we should stay out of the war and definitely doesn\'t want someone telling people that there will be a war in France in a few months. And he wants to find out how this guy knows so much. The secwar is an isolationist.\r\n\r\nWhat the secwar doesn\'t know is that the man sent a similar letter to the President with a 5th event on it:\r\n\r\n5) Your humble writer will be arrested by the Secretary of War at the War Department, October 8, 1939\r\n\r\nRosevelt showed up at the War Department just in time to take custody. \r\n\r\nIt develops that this event -- the SecWar knowing about the letter but not telling the president that he had it -- causes SecWar to be fired some months later but the public grounds are a disagreement about the war.\r\n\r\nHe leaves office June 20, 1940, five days before the fall of france. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-02-01','2009-02-02 06:34:25'),(405,90,'DAM','2: Ian.2 	Ian walking to school (8w, ian\'s older brother, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:50:27'),(406,90,'DAM','2: Ian.4 	Ian on the playground (4w, Ian, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:50:34'),(407,90,'DAM','2: Ian.5 	Bully (0w, Bully, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:50:38'),(408,90,'DAM','2: Ian.6 	Ian\'s enemies (0w, Ian, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:50:43'),(409,90,'DAM','2: Ian.7 	Ian\'s pal\'s (0w, Ian, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:50:48'),(410,90,'DAM','2: Ian.8 	Ian coming home from school (331w, Omnicient, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:50:55'),(411,90,'DAM','2: Ian.12 	Ian\'s girlfriend (0w, Omnicient, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:51:36'),(412,90,'DAM','2: Ian.10 	Clarissa\'s Christmas Present (0w, Omnicient, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:51:06'),(413,90,'DAM','2: Ian.11 	summer school (0w, Omnicient, Outline) ','2009-02-10','2009-02-11 04:51:11'),(414,90,'DAM','<h3>Ian At the Church Meeting</h3>\r\nAfter some searching around, Ian found the address. He was somewhat confused at first because he expected a church meeting to be held in a church and this was obviously a residence. \r\n\r\nHe almost didn\'t go in. He felt timid and unsure but he marshalled his courage and walked up to the door. Was this the right place? The right time? Would they remember who he was? Did they really allow guests? \r\n\r\nHis stomach felt tied into knots; he felt like he needed to go to the bathroom. But he lifted his arm and pushed the button. \r\n\r\nNothing for it, he had pushed the button and he woul look like a total loser if he left now. \r\n\r\nAn eternity ensued. The house remained quiet and dark. He had just about convinced himself that he was on the wrong night or at the wrong house or, just maybe, on the wrong planet, when he heard voices coming up the walk. \r\n\r\nA man and a woman turned the corner from the the driveway, saw him and instantly lit up with smiles. \r\n\r\n\"Well hello there!\" greeted the woman. \"Are you here for the meeting?\" \r\n\r\n\"Yes.\" muttered Ian, completely overwhelmed. \r\n\r\n\"Great. Welcome. Reverend Alice is setting up in the back and probably can\'t hear you. We always just go in.\" \r\n\r\nSomehow their friendliness did not make Ian feel any more at ease. Paradoxically, it had quite the opposite effect. Where before he felt like someone who might be in the wrong place, their forced friendliness seemed to him to confirm that he was in the wrong place. It was as if the very sincerity of their greetings proved his worst fear: that he was intruding and had not business here at all. \r\n\r\nIan joined a small group in a cosy living room with a couch, a few stuffed chairs and four or five folding chairs scattered around. A young, dark haired woman wearing a green shirt and a minister\'s collar saw him and smiled a welcome. She had intense, penetrating eyes that seemed to see right through him, giving him the instant sense that she knew he didn\'t belong. \r\n\r\nShe set down the books she had been setting out on the chairs and came over. \r\n\r\n\"Hello, I\'m Reverend ALICE. You must be Ian?\" \r\n\r\n\"Um, yes.\" said Ian, with so little certainty that it sounded like he didn\'t know his own name. \r\n\r\n\"Good. BOB told me you\'d be coming. We don\'t get many visitors but it would be just my luck to have two on the same night. BOB won\'t be here tonight, I\'m afraid, but we\'ll take good care of you. We\'re just about ready to start so why don\'t you take a seat.\"\r\n\r\nWhen everyone had settled themselves on the various pieces of furniture, Ian looked around. The participants of this meeting were in a rough circle. Each was clutching a folded piece of regular paper which was printed as a little four page booklet. To his immediate right was a fleshy, white haired older man. To his left was the couch with the woman who had greeted him on the front steps and her companion. Directly across from him was Reverend ALICE and, on either side of her, were two college aged guys. Sunk complacently into an easy chair between the white haired man and  one of these guys a very large woman rounded out the group. \r\n\r\nSeven in all, counted Ian. Eight, if you counted him, but only seven if you counted people who know what was going on. Ian felt a little better, having compiled this statistical information. \r\n\r\nHe glanced down at the booklet in his hands. On the cover was a cross below which it said \"Unification of Christianity Church Spiritual Study Guide\". He opened up the \"booklet\" and on the left side -- the half page -- it had a header that read \"The Five Principles\" followed by 5 paragraphs. On the other side it had a header that said \"The Five Actions\" which also had five paragraphs. \r\n\r\nHe turned the page and found that the back was blank except for the words \"copyright 2010, Reverend ALICE\". He looked up and found everyone looking at him. He could feel his face flushing as if he had been caught doing something wrong. Looking around he got the feeling that, perhaps, they were just waiting for him to be ready but he still felt incredibly self conscious. \r\n\r\n\"Before we begin,\" asked REverend ALICE, \"do you have any questions, Ian?\"\r\n\r\n\"Um, no. Ah, thank you.\" More than anything in world, Ian wished they would stop looking at him. \r\n\r\n\"OK. First before we begin, let us take the first two of the Five Actions: Prayer and Meditation. Let us all hold hands. \"\r\n\r\nThe white haired man to the right reached out for Ian\'s hand. Ian had to awkwardly set the booklet down before he could hold hands with him. The woman to his left took his other hand. The man\'s hand was a bit damp but the woman\'s hand was cool and dry. Ian relaxed a tiny bit. \r\n\r\nEveryone bowed their head and, after a slight pause to check to make sure the hand-clasped connection was complete, Reverend ALICE intoned, \"Almighty saviour, please bless this meeting and bring peace and understanding to it\'s participants. Let us spend a moment in silent prayer.\" \r\n\r\nNot knowing what else to do, Ian watched Reverend ALICE. He could see that everyone closed their eyes and bowed their heads. His sense of being out of place came back strongly. He didn\'t want to close his eyes so he simply watched. After about a minute, Reverend Alice opened her eyes. Seeing him looking at her she smiled what she probably thought was an encouraging smile. Then she looked around the room. Ian followed her gaze; a few people were looking up but most still sat with heads bowed. \r\n\r\nWhen there were only one or two people with heads bowed, Reverend ALICE intoned, \"Amen\" and everyone raised their heads and looked at her. \r\n\r\n\"First off, let\'s welcome our guest. This is Ian. Ian {Reverend ALICE introduces him to the other 6 people in the room}\"\r\n\r\nIan actually feels a little less nervous now that he knows their names but he suspects this is just because he\'s now trying to remember their names and this takes his mind off his sense of being out of place. He wonders briefly if he\'ll ever have a place and if he would recognize it if he found it. Maybe Richard is right: I\'m just a misfit.\r\n\r\nBy the time he comes out of his reverie, Alice has said something he didn\'t catch and everyone is picking up their booklets. Ian picks up his booklet and dutifully opens it. \r\n\r\nUnder the principles he sees\r\n- original sin\r\n- acceptance of the Savior\r\n- purity of heart\r\n- connection of everyone through prayer to Savior\r\n- we must not just be good we must act in our goodness\r\n\r\nOn the other side, the list is\r\n- prayer\r\n- meditation\r\n- tithing\r\n- kindness\r\n- good works\r\n\r\n\"The first principle of our faith is that we all have original sin. Called by a lot of names, all this really means is that we can\'t ever be good on our own. Which brings us directly to the second principle: we can only be good by accepting the Savior. All good comes through Jesus Christ and so without him we can\'t be good. Does anyone want to add anything? \"\r\n\r\nALAN suggested, \"It seems to me that we not oly can\'t be good but we, of necesity, must be bad without the Savior.\" \r\n\r\n\"Yes, that\'s very good, ALAN. The next principle is that, once Jesus has cleansed you of original sin you must keep yourself clear of that sin by purity of heart. Does anyone have any experience they would like to share?\"\r\n\r\nThe meeting continues around the room. Everyone but Ian eventually finds some experience to share that is relevant to one of the principles or actions listed in the booklet. Ian is struck by how willing they are to agree with everything that\'s said and how anxious they all seem to twist the events of their life around to match the principles and actions listed in the little booklet. \r\n\r\nFor example, to illustrate \"Purity of Heart\" CHUCK described an elaborate situation at work involving his boss, who apparently is a beautiful woman, and a coworker who, it seems is having an affair with her. To Ian, this sounded more like gossip than a religious discussion. The others appeared to have some doubts about CHUCK\'s story as well because, when he finished they all just stared blankly at him. As if to clarify, CHUCK added, \"But, of course, I would never do anything like that.\" Everyone smiled and nodded, finally getting the point. Yes, this was a good example of purity of heart, indeed. \r\n\r\nIan looked over at Reverend Alice to see if she, too was buying this story as a valid example. She was certainly smiling as much as anyone but he thought he saw some doubt in her eyes. Perhaps, Ian thought,  she felt that she should accept any participation as valid and then work on the strength of the participation over time. \r\n\r\nAfter more than two hours, they worked through the Five Principles and Five Actions and came to the end of the evening. Coffee and cookies were brought in and Ian was asked what he thought. He tried to sound as sincere as he could when he said \"oh, very nice\" and \"very interesting indeed\" and \"thank you very much for including me\" but he fled as soon as he politely could. \r\n\r\nOn the drive home, Ian thought about what his Five Principles would be. He frankly didn\'t think much of their Five Principles but it seemed a good excercise to know what one\'s principles were.\r\n\r\nFirst off, thought Ian, I know there is a God. And I know that God is good. And a good God wouldn\'t make man inherently flawed so this original sin stuff was bogus. \r\n\r\nIn fact, Ian didn\'t buy this sin stuff in general. He felt a strong, fundamental connection to all the people he met and he believed that nothing he did in support of that connection could possibly be wrong.  \r\n\r\nOf course, he wasn\'t too sure what \"in support of\" really meant. And he had friends who love to construct what he thought of as \"scenarios\". \"What if there was a crippled girl who was in your way to save a boy on railroad tracks -- if you knew you would hurt her would you knock her over to save the boy?\" Or \"What if the bad guys were going to kill your girlfriend unless you beat up someone they didn\'t like?\" Ultimately, who could know? He thought that deliberately hurting someone was wrong no matter what excuse you used for it. But he didn\'t know if that would really hold true with lives on the line. \r\n\r\nRight or wrong, those were his first two principles: God exists and is good and we are all connected. And if you support that connection, everything else will take care of itself. \r\n\r\nIan felt a sense of hopelessness overwhelm him. There had never been, there could  never be, a religion that held these beliefs. Religions were all about things you must never do. He would never find a religion that held principles anything like his. He would be an outcast all his life, just like his brother said.\r\n\r\nIan reached home in a state of near despair. He went to bed but only his physical exhaustion allowed him to sleep.\r\n','2009-02-10','2009-03-29 00:44:43'),(415,90,'DAM','<h3>Ian\'s Brother Dies </h3>\r\nIan sat bolt upright. He could hear his mother crying very loudly, something that he has never heard before. His father was home and trying to comfort her. His sister was shouting \"Do something. For god\'s sake, he won\'t wake up!\"\r\n\r\nHis first thought was \"something is wrong\" but he immediately realized how inadequate that was. When a little boy dug up an anthill and the ants scurried back and forth trying to make sense of the calamity, Ian was sure they had a similar experience to what was going on in his house. Something had turned his family upside down. \r\n\r\nAll of a sudden he knew. It didn\'t make any sense but he could hear all the voices of his family but one and that, added to \"he won\'t wake up\" must mean that there was something wrong with Richard. He foolishly looked at his brothers bed as if he would see him lying there. It was still made just as it had been when he had come in the night before. His brother had been watching TV in the living room but had torn himself away long enough to tell him, \"hey freak, don\'t mess with my stuff!\" as he walked through the room. He had barely noticed, so distressed had he been after the religious.\r\n\r\nHe pulled on his pants and rushed  out into the house. His brother was lying on the couch, fully clothed. His mother was bending over him with her arms around him crying hysterically. His father, who usually would be either at work or asleep, was holding his mother, trying to pull her away from the supine form on the couch. \r\n\r\nHis father glanced up and Ian knew in that instant -- knew that his brother was dead and knew that his father knew. His mother obviously knew but his sister was still trying to get someone to do something to save her brother. Ian went over to her, took her hands and looked into her face. \"He\'s gone. There\'s nothing we can do.\" \r\n\r\nShe collapse into his arms and wept against his shoulder. Surely this was the most bizarre thing that had ever happened to him -- this young woman who had never shown him the slightest mercy pouring out her grief on his shoulder -- and yet it was right. Somehow this felt like how it should be. Perhaps it was that family members should comfort each other -- not in his family, certainly, but in families in general. But more than that, he felt it was his role to comfort people in need. It was what he was for, who he was. Just to feel the grief was enough.  \r\n\r\nAll this he thought of in just the few moments that he held her. Then his father pulled his mother from his dead brother and his sister ran to their father for comfort. \r\n\r\nHe went to call 911 -- surely the police would want to know about a dead body.\r\n\r\nThere were hours of tedium to follow. Waiting for the police, for the coroner, for the mortuary. Friends came with food and comfort. And then days of tedious preparations. A casket, a funeral, a service, a wake. For some reason, Ian had stopped thinking.  His endless analysis of himself and everything around him had simply been suspended. Even the stark information that his brother had had an undiagnosed brain tumor that had been affecting his personality for years did not rouse him to think. It didn\'t even cross his conscious mind to think how much this explained or even how much damage this did to his, Ian\'s, world view. His brother was gone and no other thoughts made any sense or even had any place in his brain. Thought was canceled due to lack of interest. \r\n\r\nFinally, when the body was gone, and put in a casket, and put in the ground, when the services had been held and the wake over and the friends gone. When even the food was gone and even his mother had stopped crying. Finally, Ian felt an overwhelming sense of grief. He lay down on his bed and cried and cried. As if he had lost his best friend. As if he had lost everything he owned. As if he had lost himself. \r\n\r\nWhen he woke up the next morning he was baffled. It was as if he had been thinking about something important when he went to sleep and now he couldn\'t remember what it was. Oh, yeah, Richard is dead! Hmm, how odd. And everything he ever said about me was because of a brain tumor, very interesting. My entire world view is based on sheer thin air, fascinating. \r\n\r\nIan thought to himself, \"I must be numb and that\'s why I don\'t feel anything.\" Then he realized he was thinking again. He HAD been numb but that he was back now. And all his feelings of being disconnected from the world, of being a misfit, of being incompetent and unsure all came flooding back.\r\n\r\nAnd like a thunderclap, like Saul struck blind on the road to Damascus, Ian suddenly realized that he knew nothing. His whole life he had blamed his brother for everything. And now his brother was dead. Dead! He didn\'t really know what that meant, where his brother was but, for sure, his brother was no longer around to tell Ian who he was. Maybe Ian was still incompetent, unsure, and a misfit but it wasn\'t because of Richard any longer. He was going to have to find himself for himself. \r\n\r\nAnd, for a moment, Ian was completely overwhelmed by the scope of the task. \r\n','2009-02-10','2009-03-29 01:22:54'),(416,90,'DAM','<h3>Ian at the Shrine of the Dead </h3>\r\n\r\nA few month after his brother\'s death, Ian\'s sister heard about the Dia de los Muertos -- the Day of the Dead. She got it into her head that they should go to the festival held by the local Hispanic community to honor her brother. She had always been good at persuading their parent to do practically anything she wanted and since her brother died and she became the oldest it had been even easier. So they were all going to go \"to honor their dead\". \r\n\r\nIan was pretty sure that she just wanted to go because she thought it would be cool or fun or something. He didn\'t believe for a minute that her motives were pure, but it didn\'t really matter why she wanted to do it -- they were doing it. \r\n\r\nThe day of the festival came around and they all packed into the car and drove across town. They paid a small fee at then wandered around. It was essentially a street fair with a sort of skull theme. Ian, who had never really heard of this before, felt that it was kind of interesting the way certain themes were repeated over and over. \r\n\r\nNaturally everyone knew what was going on but Ian and, for a second, he started thinking about what a misfit he was. But then he caught himself and realized this was completely different. This was a new thing to experience and he could be as much a part of it as he wanted to be. For the most part he was over wanted to belong so desperately but sometime he fell into the old ways of thinking like a cart got stuck in the deep ruts in a dirt road. \r\n\r\nHis sister wanted to get something to eat and there were booths with all manner of food and sweets so his parents and sister went off in that direction. He wasn\'t hungry and he was growing a interested in what this \"Day of the Dead\" think was so he went deeper into the festival. \r\n\r\nHe came across a shrine adorned with skulls and effigies of beautiful  skeletons. There were little shelves where people had placed pictures of their loved ones and candles. The area was filled with people crying and comforting each other. For a moment, Ian was reminded of his grief for his brother; all that emotion came rushing back at him. He didn\'t flinch from it and the feeling left him as soon as he fully experienced it. \r\n\r\nIan closed his eyes and he could feel the pain and suffering of the people around him. He allowed their pain to flow over and through him. He felt it without flinching from it, experiencing it completely and the feeling would pass to be replaced by more grief. \r\n\r\nHe stayed like that for several minutes and, gradually, almost imperceptibly, the pain subsided. After a half an hour he thought the pain was lessened. Or was he just used to it? He had no objective messure but he looked around and he felt sure that the people at the shrine were in less distress than they had been. \r\n\r\n','2009-02-10','2009-03-29 01:51:11'),(417,86,'DAM','Greetings listeners! Welcome to the first episode of the Dave and Dave show! \r\n\r\nI\'m sorry to give you bad news right off the bat but I regret to tell you that Dave has died. \r\n\r\nHe was walking from his car one day, recording some new ideas for this radio show on a tape recorder and a man jumped out. We know exactly what happened next because his recorder caught the whole thing. \r\n\r\n<static and hiss as from a poor recording device>\r\nMan: Hey, you\'re the sumbitch that screwed my wife, ain\'t you?\r\nDavid: well, I\'m not sure. Who is your wife?\r\nMan: What, you seduce a lot of women, you fat pig? I doubt that...\r\nDavid: I don\'t mean to brag but I do all right\r\nMan: you posted that ad on that computer thingy...\r\nDavid: You mean \"Craigslist\"?\r\nMan: whatever it\'s called -- inviting someone to come over to you B&B. My wife came over and you had sex with her!\r\nDavid: Well what did she expect from Bagels and a Blowjob? And, technically speaking, it wasn\'t actually sex. \r\nMan: Oh, so NOW you remember? \r\nDavid: Well I can see why you would be upset. I mean you must not be much in the bedroom if your wife puts out for a bagel... \r\nMan: Why you asshole! I\'m going to kill you...\r\n\r\n(Tape cuts off)\r\n\r\nDAVE: Well, I think we should leave the other gruesome details to your imagination.\r\n\r\nDAVE: We\'re all very regretful here at the Dave and Dave show. But out of respect and acknowledgment we\'ve -- well, I mean, \"I\'ve\"; I\'ll have to get used to being all alone in this -- decided to keep the original name instead of cutting the poor bastard out of the title. \r\n\r\nDAVE: Well the first thing we\'ve -- I mean \"I\'ve\" -- decided to do is to have a call in bulletin board. This is a very popular practice in some rural parts of the country. People sell items and announce lost cats and so forth, kind of like a craigslist without computers. We\'re calling this the radio bulletin board. \r\n\r\nDAVE: hello, who is this?\r\n\r\nVOICE: This is Adam from Greensborough.\r\nDAVE:Ok, Adam, do you have an announcement you\'d like to place on the radio bulletin board?\r\nVOICE:Sure. I\'d like to announce that I\'m available for any women out there.\r\nDAVE:<with some trepidation and reluctance> Um, available for what?\r\nVOICE: Well I suppose for anything they\'d like but I was really thinking of a quick blow job. \r\nDAVE: <appalled> Hey, this isn\'t that kind of show!\r\nVOICE: But you said it was like craigslist and I...<CLICK>\r\n\r\nDAVE: Well, that\'s a bit too much like craigslist, I\'m afraid. Well, gee, let\'s try this one more time.\r\n\r\n\r\nDAVE: Hello, who is this?\r\nDAVID: <in his normal voice> Hi, I\'m calling to announce a special offer at a local B&B.\r\nDAVE: Wait a second. I know that voice. Is this Dave? \r\nDAVID: Yes but I just want everyone to know that women who come to my B&B will get 1/2 off. It\'s a great offer. \r\nDAVE: Where are you? I thought you were dead!\r\nDAVID: No such luck. I\'m still here.\r\n\r\n','2009-02-16','2009-02-20 15:53:41'),(418,91,'davemenc',' ','2009-02-27','2009-02-27 18:20:04'),(419,91,'DAM','Alice walks into the office of a railroad executive (Bob) and throws a package on the desk. It looks like something Amazon.com had shipped via ups. This meeting took weeks for Alice to set up, talking to friends who knew friends who had connections with railroads. She started with her conservationist friends -- \"tree huggers\" and managed to connect to some people at the railroad who are interested in promoting the green aspects of railroads. \r\n\r\nAlice pitches this idea that, instead of shipping consumer packages across country via trucks, as UPS does, you use trains. You aggregate in special facilities in cities, pack the stuff into shipping containers, and move it along rail lines to another city where it gets unpacked. Consumers can either come pick it up at a central facility or pay an extra fee to have it delivered to their home. \r\n\r\nThe basic concept is that railroad shipping is WAY cheaper than truck shipping so Amazon can ship consumers their packages for MUCH less than UPS currently charges them. Since shipping cost is a fundamental driver -- well, limiter, actually -- of sales, reducing shipping costs significantly would help amazon out a lot and, therefor, amazon would support this effort. \r\n\r\nMeantime, the railroads would benefit, consumers would benefit, the process would be lots greener our children would benefit. \r\n\r\nAlice has an elaborate and convincing model of how all this works and what she wants from the railroad exec is a bit of moral support. Open some doors, make kind noises in the right ears, give her some figures she can plug into her model. But she stopps short of actually asking for money or any kind of commitment.\r\n\r\nThis whole conversation is really a discussion that Alice is having with charlie who is an investor. She is explaining to him how this whole thing got started. She doesn\'t oversell the railroad\'s involvement but she does make it clear that the railroad would back the plan as it would make them millions and maybe get them back involved. She make sure to point out to charlie how railroad stock, now in the toilet, would shoot up, making a killing for their shareholders -- a kind of \"everyone wins\" sort of argument. Probably something about bailout money being used to renovate railroad tracks might come in here.\r\n\r\nShe shows charlie her whole model. She has a LOT of detailed in formation about packages shipped from one place to another -- numbers, weights, months, places they come from, places they go to , by type of user, etc, etc. Charlie is curious how she might have gotten all this information. \r\n\r\nShe explains that some of it was leaked to her by amazon executives (a whole nother scene with amazon execs, maybe) but that most of it was gotten from a cracker who broke into the UPS site. \r\n\r\nThe model shows clearly that you could both make more money and pass significant savings on to consumers with this plan. It also shows that you have to build about a dozen distribution centers in a dozen cities to even get started and that you would have to plow profits back into more centers for a long time. But, in the end, you would have a thriving business that would, basicly, eat UPS\'s lunch. \r\n\r\nShe pitches the is idea to many people and begins to get some traction.Along the way, we learn that the plan is quite viable, that the feds don\'t like the idea of her hacking into UPS or stealing data from Amanzon and that, in fact, she really didn\'t do that. The feds continue to investigate Alice but they don\'t have anything on her. We also learn that she was a conservationist but that she thinks the conservationist movement is irrelevant in the face of global warming, caring so deeply about wild rivers and beautiful trees, defending deserts from solar power companies but allowing coal plant to increase their hold on the power production. she is pretty hard on them\r\n\r\nJust as her plan seems to be getting some traction, UPS squashes it by cutting their own deal with the railroads and beginning to ship stuff via rail instead of trucks. They already have the distribution centers and so can start immediately while Alice is just about to start building her centers. The whole plan collapses under it\'s own weight and the investors get ready to sue her when they realize that, surprise of surprises, the contracts are all written in such a way that they can gracefully walk away in the circumstance and she doesn\'t try to stop them.\r\n\r\nIn the end we discover, possibly fromt he feds -- who don\'t have a case, by the way -- that the whole thing was a scam. What really happened in that initial meeting with the railroad was that she pitched the idea of proposing and pushing this whole plan just so that UPS would start shipping more stuff via rail. UPS had been reluctant because they already were making money and they didn\'t want to invest in the centers that would be required. So the railroad was paying her to promote this scheme. ','2009-02-27','2009-02-27 18:44:04'),(420,81,'Rongo!','The first idea I have is to create a genetic algorithm that has the actual ingredients as genes and to use the classic \"crossover\" method to generate new drinks from existing drinks. But I don\'t see how that helps with the cards, and, anyway, most of the drinks generated would taste like ass. And the fitness function has to have a human so a few people would get REALLY drunk. Still, it might make a pretty cool party: the computer generates drinks an the participants each get a drink and rate it. Designed properly, with enough people, the drinks at the end of the evening might not be too bad.\r\n\r\nOk, but about those cards. We have various sets of attributes (the sweet/savory/spicy attributes, the alcoholic components, the non alcoholic components, the type of glass -- every possible way to classify a drink) which, you will notice are all actually lists of attributes (it can be sweet AND spicy, have rum AND tequila, etc). The obvious \"closeness\" from one drink to another is the number of these attributes that two drinks have in common. If you wanted to get it a little more complicated (although I\'m not sure it\'s better) you could weight some of the attributes -- the flavor rating (sweet/spicy, etc) is 2, the ingredients are 1 and the glass and garnish are .5. Of course, you could argue it the opposite way -- two drinks are close if the LOOK like each other so color, glass and garnish are 2, kind of booz is 1 and actual flavor is .5. (Personally, I like the idea of having the hidden essence of the drink drive this so I like the idea of two spicy drinks that look completely different being similar.)\r\n\r\nOk, so that\'s a distance rating. I can\'t really see past your suggestion that each card has the closest drinks listed on it and, when you mate them a drink is chosen from their offspring. I want to think about that a little more, however. It should be chosen at random and in such a way that some drinks are far more likely to come up than others, rather than have the patron pick, I think. This could be accomplished by having a number next to each of the 7 drinks which represents the number you roll to get that drink. That results in two drinks and you either let the patron pick between those two or dice them off. \r\n\r\nIf I were writing a program for this I would \"intersect\" the two drinks and find the drink that is closest to that intersection. One way to do it would be to combine the two lists of attributes and come find the drink with the most in common with that list. This would tend to get you elaborate drinks. Or maybe take a random subset (maybe a crossover) of the two lists and use that to find the closest drinks. I think I would prefer to have a method that works the same every time -- maybe the attributes are ordered and we always take the first n attributes that are present. (I would order the flavor attributes first, the ingredient attributes second and the color and glass attributes last so that only on the simplest drinks have the color and glass attributes come into the equation).\r\n\r\n<B>To simply state my goal, I want to take two drinks and find a third drink that, while seemingly completely different, somehow seems similar to the two \"parent\" drinks in some way. Preferably in some way that\'s subtle and hard to define. So if the two original drinks are in highball glasses and then new drink is in a highball glass, that\'s a bit obvious. But if one of the starting drinks is sweet with rum and the other is savory with whiskey, having a savory rum drink would be kickass. </b>\r\n\r\nObviously, I\'m not sure how to accomplish this with cards alone. \r\n\r\nNow, if I could have a BOOK with a list of drink A and drink B giving drink C, I could use a computer to generate that book. You have drink A and B, you look them up in the book and find drink C and that\'s the drink you get. Or you look them up and get a list of possible drink Cs and you roll to find which one you get. \r\n\r\nThe card thing would work if we had multiple decks. I need to think about this more. \r\n\r\nThis is kind of a random collection of stuff. \r\n\r\nOn Mon, Mar 9, 2009 at 8:10 PM, Lucifer <lucifer@goldencafe.org> wrote:\r\n>  Ooooh - here\'s one that is 100% up your alley:\r\n>\r\n>  To adapt the bar ever so slightly to the theme this year, and thereby\r\n> secure our newfound portal placement and hopefully a mad stack of early\r\n> arrival passes, I think we should add an \"evolutionary\" element to our drink\r\n> cards. The most robust approach that comes to mind is that we create a\r\n> system where any two drink cards can be \"mated\" to generate one or more\r\n> offspring drink cards. One approach I can imagine is that we compute the\r\n> \"distance\" between drink cards, and list the 7 closest \"neighbor drinks\" on\r\n> each card - perhaps mating the two cards can then generate any of the\r\n> \"neighbor drinks\" listed on either card or somesuch? Something to chew on,\r\n> especially because listing the 7 closest drinks is a pretty badass feature\r\n> of the drink cards in their own right.\r\n>\r\n>  Thoughts?\r\n>\r\n>  Lucifer\r\n>\r\n>\r\n\r\n','2009-03-10','2009-03-10 18:03:51'),(421,92,'davemenc',' ','2009-03-14','2009-03-14 07:14:12'),(422,92,'DAM','Michael li-ming wong; michael.wong@ropesgray.com; white collar lawyer\r\nmichal malyszko; michal.malyszko@ubkbc.pl; business consulting\r\nmichael sliwinski; michael@nozbe.com; nozbe .com\r\nthad a. davis; thad.davis@ropesgray.com; lawyer -- sister in law\'s resume\r\nandrew filev; anderw@tam.wrike.comwrike; cool interactive movies\r\nbennett phillips; bennett@nighthouse.com;ninth house; interactive videos ','2009-03-14','2009-03-14 07:28:20'),(423,86,'DAM','Dave: I brought a guitar today <strums a random chord>.\r\nDavid: I didn\'t know you played.\r\nDave: Oh, I don\'t play. \r\nDavid: Well, why do you own a guitar? \r\nDave: Well, it\'s not *MY* guitar. It\'s my son\'s. \r\nDavid: <sigh> Ok, so why do you have a guitar with you?\r\nDave: to keep it from being lonely. \r\nDavid: This is actually a hopeless conversation. \r\n\r\n(*It seems that, before I can get to anything new and interesting, I\'m going to have to go through the style of every comedy team I\'ve ever seen. This is classic smothers brothers or Abbot and Costello -- dummy and straigt man -- only not as good. This isn\'t actually going to work for us. First, those guys were geniuses and we have to be better if we want to play in their pool. Second, it\'s all just derivative. I wouldn\'t want to do it even if we WERE better.*)\r\n','2009-03-14','2009-03-14 19:09:47'),(424,86,'DAM','Dave: My wife sent me to get some trash bags this morning. In that particular store the trash bags were on the same aisle as the mops and brooms and was called \"the closet needs\" aisle. I kept looking for the horse tranquilizers. The latex outfits. Maybe some handcuffs. \r\nDavid: And what about the trash bags?\r\nDave: Well when I got past the vibrating broom handles, there was a section with trash bags. They all had names like Brawny and Hefty. Big, strong names. \r\nDavid: what about \"glad\"? \r\nDave: No I wasn\'t glad to seem them. \r\nDavid: No, I mean glad brand trash bags. \r\nDave: \"Is that a glad trashbag or are you just happy to seem me.\"\r\nI just think they should have some other kinds of trash bags. Why aren\'t any of them called \"Petite\"\r\nDavid: \"young miss?\"\r\nDave: yeah, dainty trash bags. Don\'t you think there\'s a market for Dainty trash bags? Make them pink and you only store dainty things in them. No coffee grounds or banana peels for these bags. They\'re for left over orange zest or flower petal garnishes or napkins that spent the whole meal in a woman\'s lap. \r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-03-14','2009-03-14 19:22:08'),(425,86,'DAM','I tend to make \"David\" the straight man and \"Dave\" the funny one but I don\'t mean anything by it. I think the real flaw is the very concept of straight man. We need to riff off each other. ','2009-03-14','2009-03-14 19:23:10'),(426,86,'DAM','<b>Stand up</b>\r\n{looking at a patron} {very aggressively} What are YOU looking at? I\'m watching you! \r\n{To audience}Sorry, but that guy has been staring at all the performers. \r\n{To patron}{maybe use two fingers pointing to eyes and pointing to him}\r\n','2009-03-15','2009-03-15 15:59:11'),(427,86,'DAM','Community Announcements\r\n+ the meeting of the procrastinator\'s club has been postponed\r\n+ the of the antisocial club will never be scheduled\r\n+ The meeting of the apathy club has been cancelled because no one signed up.\r\n+ The meeting of the attention deficit disorder club is, um, oh, look at that...\r\n','2009-03-17','2009-03-18 01:02:43'),(428,86,'DAM','Dave: I\'ve been getting a lot of email lately. I used to really hate it but then I got a blackberry. \r\nDavid: Oh, you like reading email on your blackberry?\r\nDave: No but if you set it on vibrate in put it in your pocket just right a lot of email feels really good...','2009-03-17','2009-03-18 01:04:34'),(429,86,'DAM','Dave: I\'m a bit of an entrepreneur, you know. \r\nDavid: When I was in college all the cool kids pretended they were in a band. Now I suppose all the cool kids pretend they\'re entrepreneurs.\r\nDave: No, really, I invent things.\r\nDavid: I\'m almost afraid to ask but, OK, what have you invented?.\r\nDave: A little door that sits in a toilet stall so you can slide it open and talk to the guy in the next stall. \r\nDavid: Wait, isn\'t that called a glory hole? \r\n\r\n','2009-03-17','2009-03-18 15:26:41'),(430,81,'Rongo!','Ari\r\n\r\ni think the cards need to be mated by book','2009-03-18','2009-03-19 00:50:40'),(431,81,'Rongo!','\"Ari\r\n\r\ni think the cards need to be mated by book\"\r\n\r\nOk, so we have a big pile of attributes, we take the two drinks and make an even bigger pile of attributes. Then we use some, as yet unspecified, algorithm to generate one and only one drink. We capture the combinations of all the possible drinks in a book and that\'s the \"Golden Cafe Field Guide To Cocktail Mating\".\r\n\r\nThe devil is in the details, of course. I think you\'d get pretty close to what we want if you simply made a pool of attributes (the union of all the attributes of the parent drinks) and found the drink that had the most attributes in common with those. \r\n\r\nI think we\'ve already done all the data work here (we have a list of drinks, each drink has attributes) and when I get out from under the crazy work I happen to have right now, I will try my hand at an algorithm that generates drinks. \r\n\r\nSince the end product is a book (not a program), we can fudge the results. \r\n\r\nDave','2009-03-18','2009-03-19 01:10:11'),(432,40,'defer','<h3>Foot Race Game</h3>\r\nI suspect I\'ve documented this somewhere. <b>Yeah, like in <i>The Chase</i></b>I need a search function!\r\n\r\nOk, the idea is that we have a really good model of fatigue. People can run, walk, stop, sit, and go prone. Each person runs and walks a particular speed, uses up energy at a particular speed and regains energy at a particular speed. Also, he has a particular observation ability and a certain capability to change state (prone to standing, sitting to standing, standing to walking, standing to running, etc). \r\n\r\nIn sprinting you use anaerobic energy but while you\'re walking you use aerobic energy. So sprinting uses up a small store of energy very rapidly while walking uses up an amount of energy roughly equal to the amount that can be replenished. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, your whole system\'s energy gets depleted after a prolonged period of walking, requiring rest. \r\n\r\nFinally, after a very long time (say, most of a day) you get hungry, thirsty and in need of sleep which further degrades your ability to continue. \r\n\r\nTo summarize:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Energy\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>Short term energy\r\n    <ul>\r\n    <li>Small reservoir (short reservoir attribute)\r\n    <li>Lost extremely quickly while sprinting (sprint short cost attribute)\r\n    <li>lost fairly quickly while running (run short cost attribute)\r\n    <li>lost slowly while walking (walk short cost attribute)\r\n    <li>regained slowly wile walking (walk short generation attribute)\r\n    <li>regained more quickly while standing, sitting or lying down (rest short generation attribute)\r\n    <li>when short term energy goes negative/zero player must stop until he has a positive reserve \r\n    </ul>\r\n  <li>Long term energy\r\n    <ul>\r\n    <li> large supply (long reservoir attribute)\r\n    <li> used moderately quickly while running or sprinting (run long cost attribute)\r\n    <li> used slowly while walking (walk long cost attribute)\r\n    <li> use even slower while standing (stand long cost attribute)\r\n    <li>regained slowly while sitting (sit long  generation attribute)\r\n    <li>regained quickly while lying down (prone long generation attribute)\r\n    <li>when long term energy goes to zero, player collapses\r\n    <li>when long term energy goes negative, player collapses and becomes unconscious, regen at prone rate\r\n    </ul>\r\n<li>Speed\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>Sprinting (sprint speed attribute)\r\n  <li>Running (run speed attribute)\r\n  <li>Walking (walk speed attribute)\r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>Observation\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>Observation only affects what you can see\r\n  <li>base observation (observation attribute)\r\n  <li>Range standing\r\n  <li>range sitting\r\n  <li>range prone\r\n  <li>prone, sitting, standing and moving players have different observation modifiers\r\n  <li>distance modifies what you can see\r\n  <li>there may be blocking terrain which prevents you from seeing something  \r\n  <li>moving observers can\'t see as well as stationary observers\r\n  <li>there may be terrain that partially prevents you from seeing something\r\n  <li> observation is a scale of zero to five\r\n      <ul>\r\n      <li>0: can\'t see thing at all, not reported\r\n      <li>1: think you see something, reported as \"possibly motion in this area\"; possibly false 1s are reported\r\n      <li>2: you see something but you don\'t know what it is\r\n      <li>3: you see something, can tell what it is\r\n      <li>4: see it clearly\r\n      <li>5: absolute clarity\r\n      </ul>\r\n    <li>every observation level but 5 reduces ranged combat score\r\n    <li>0 prevents combat\r\n    <li>1 reduces even close combat\r\n    <li> 2-5 have no effect on close combat\r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>short range combat\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>you can\'t attack what you can\'t see\r\n  <li>standing (sprinting, running, walking) (base combat attribute) -- modified by both kinds of energy (long combat modifier, short combat modifier)\r\n  <li>sitting (sitting combat modifier)\r\n  <li>prone (prone combat modifier)\r\n  <li>changing state (e.g. prone to sitting, sitting to standing) (changing combat modifier)\r\n  <li>may attack while moving but must move with defender\r\n  <li>moving defender has combat value reduced (moving defense modifier) \r\n  <li>stationary defender may attack back\r\n  <li>if attacker has more combat than defender, defender loses long term energy proportional to diff (damage factor)\r\n  <li>if attacker has less combat than defender, attack is fended off\r\n  <li>weapons may give attack or defense additions to combat\r\n  <li>when long term energy goes negative \r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>ranged combat\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>every weapon has a range (weapon range modifier) it has no effect beyond that\r\n  <li>every player has a weapon accuracy matrix -- for each weapon he may get bonuses for skill\r\n  <li>weapons have a base chance to hit\r\n  <li>weapons get a to hit bonus for 1/4 range and 1/2 range\r\n  <li>chance to hit is modified by how well the target is observed \r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>camouflage\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>animals and humans may have a blending score that reduces (or increases) others\' ability to see them\r\n  <li>blending may be negative (prisoners bright orange jumper)\r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>Questions\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>should long term energy effect short term energy regen?\r\n  </ul>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-03-27','2009-09-29 21:21:08'),(433,93,'davemenc','<h3>Database</h3>\r\nThe people database will contain all the fields from the current lists (first name, last name, etc, ad nauseum) plus a few status fields. This is the basic list of people. It represents everyone the system knows about now or any time in past. These aren\'t attendees, they\'re just people. \r\n\r\nWe\'ll need a few other people fields: username, password, (collect from everyone? probably not), admin, viewer. Each of these people might be authorized to look at the database of people the database of attendees and/or edit them. \r\n\r\nThe attendees database will contain references to the people. In addition to the index to the people database there will be \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>conference (probably a year)\r\n<li>Speaker\r\n<li>registered/waitinglist\r\n<li>Authorized/unauthorized\r\n<li>Hotel room\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nThe content database is probably something we want to save for another day.','2009-03-28','2009-03-28 16:21:09'),(434,93,'DAM','The basic registration page should look about like the old one. Each field will have an example or a definition. \r\n\r\nAll the data will be collected on one page. At the bottom of the page will be a \"register\" button with no other links on the page. \r\n\r\nThe data collected will be validated. If validation fails on any field it will generate an error message like {fieldname} value not valid; must contain {field definition} where \"fieldname\" is the actual name on the page and \"field definition\" is a clear explanation of what will work in that field. \r\n\r\nThis page must be thoroughly tested and problems entered into a jira database. \r\n\r\n','2009-03-28','2009-03-28 16:28:09'),(435,93,'DAM','In addition to the registration page we also need a bulk registration page (where tab delimited file is pasted into a big text box and bulk added to the database), a registrant edit page (selectable by errors and missing data), a people edit page (likewise selectable) and a registrant report page. ','2009-03-28','2009-03-28 16:30:56'),(436,93,'DAM','As alluded to earlier, a future issue might be to track content.','2009-03-28','2009-03-28 16:31:43'),(437,84,'DAM','THey  had just finished the set and she was setting aside her big djembe drum when she saw him approaching. She wasn\'t really very interested in the fans -- she was just there to play -- but she was always polite to the customers because that was part of the gig. She was even polite when they flirted at her because, mostly, they thought it was a compliment. She wasn\'t the least interested in men but, again, they were customers and she got paid to do this. She saw it as part of being a professional. \r\n\r\nThe man came right up to her smiling so she smiled back politely. Not a very genuine smile but she didn\'t really think about it. \r\n\r\n\"That was very good. I\'m very proud of you.\" \r\n\r\n\"Thanks. Um, \'proud\'?\"\r\n\r\n\"Yeah, proud of you. For playing so well. Don\'t be like that; don\'t pretend that you don\'t know who I am. You know me. And I know you. And we both know that we should be proud of how well you played. It might well have been one of your best performances.\"\r\n\r\nShe was taken aback. She had been proud of that performance, herself. It wasn\'t going to win her an award or anything -- not in this little joint in this tiny town -- but that didn\'t matter. Good was good and she had done her best this time. \r\n\r\nBut what was this about knowing him? She didn\'t know him, she\'d never seen him before. And she told him so: \"I\'m sorry but I don\'t believe we\'ve ever met.\"\r\n\r\n\"Well, no, not actually been in the same room. But we know each other. We\'re as intimate as lovers, as close as a brother and sister who grew up together, as similar as too peas in a pod. We\'re so close that I might as well be you. I know that was your best performance ever because I can feel you feeling it. And you\'re proud just as I\'m proud. Congratulations. \"\r\n\r\nThis is very confusing. What is he talking about? Intimate as lovers? She\'d never heard this line in a pass before. She didn\'t know him. \"No, I\'m sorry, I don\'t know you.\"\r\n\r\n\"Now, stop that. You know me and you know you do. I can see it in your eyes, feel it in your heart. You love me just like you love yourself. I felt it in your every beat, in every movement of your hands. We\'ve known each other since before we were born. And we\'ll always know each other. There\'s no point denying it. Our relationship is as true as your existence; in fact your existence depends on our relationshop. Without me, you simply aren\'t so you might as well admit it. \"\r\n\r\n\"No, I don\'t know you from any one else,\" she began.\r\n\r\n\"Yes, yes, you have the same relationship with everyone else. You know it and I know it but they don\'t know it so why bring up the painful truth of it? It\'s just you and I that know it for now so until they\'re ready to admit it, let\'s leave them out of it, shall we? \"\r\n\r\nThe crazy pattern began to emerge from his speach. Suddenly he didn\'t seem predatory or crazy. She understood what he meant and he was absolutely right. She smiled -- a genuine smile this time -- and nodded. \r\n\r\nThey simple looked at each other for a few moments. Then he smiled and moved back into the audience. She looked after him for a moment and then went to find the other members of her band, happy in the knowledge that someone else knew what she had known all along. \r\n','2009-03-28','2009-03-29 05:23:49'),(438,90,'DAM','<h3>Alana And Ian</h3>\r\nIan asked his friends in the club, in a quiet voice, who the beautiful woman was and learned that she was a graduate physics student who, although new to UCPA, already had a reputation for being incredibly smart (which, at first class university, is saying a LOT). \r\n\r\nAfter the club meeting, Ian went up to Alana and introduced himself. It was proof of his successful development of genuine confidence since his brother had died that he wasn\'t the least bit nervous talking to a smart, beautiful woman. \r\n\r\nIan invited Alana out for a cup of coffee. Perhaps because Alana was at a new school and didn\'t know many people or perhaps because she found friendly, confident, good looking Ian charming, Alana agreed. \r\n\r\nWhen the two of them were comfortably seated in the coffee shop with the beverage of their choice (black coffee for Alana and herbal tea for Ian) Ian started the conversation by asking, \"So, Alana, what are you studying here at UCPA?\" Ian already knew, or thought he knew the answer this this question but he found that it\'s much easier to start a conversation by asking people about themselves than by telling them what you thought you knew. \r\n\r\n\"I\'ve recently transferred here from the East Bay. I have an MS in Physics and I\'m working on my doctorate. I don\'t really know anyone here. I find it hard to meet new people. Actually, you\'re almost the first friendly face I\'ve met.\" She stopped speaking abruptly as if she had said too much. She concentrated her attention on her coffee. \r\n\r\n\"That\'s odd,\" suggested Ian, \"I\'ve found everyone here to be very friendly. But, then, I\'ve been here for years. Maybe it\'s harder for a newcomer.\" Ian realized that he was staring at Alana and redirected his attention toward his tea.\r\n\r\n\"Well,\" Alana admitted, \"I haven\'t exactly been polite to my hosts.\" She hesitated for a moment and then blurted out, \"The facts are the facts and I just can\'t be polite to people who who are wrong!\" \r\n\r\nAfter a long pause Ian said quietly, \"I\'ve always found that people are more important than facts.\"\r\n\r\n\"Without facts people wouldn\'t have anything. Every thing we have we owe to Science!\"\r\n\r\nAfter a few hours of sometimes heated discussion, both Ian and Alana noticed, with some surprise, that it was getting dark outside. Each of them had carried on their half of the conversation with evident enjoyment and had simply lost track of the time. \r\n\r\n\"Alana,\" Ian asked, \"Could I interest you in some falafel?\" \r\n\r\nAlana was surprised by this sudden turn from their philosophical discussion to the practical issue of food. \"Falafel? Isn\'t that some kind of vegitarian food?\"\r\n\r\n\"Oh, wow,\" exclaimed an excited Ian, \"are you in for a treat! There is a great little falafel joint around the corner. Let me buy you dinner before we call it a night.\"\r\n\r\nTrue to his word, Ian led Alana around the corner and into a tiny shop with student-painted, brightly colored murals all over the walls. He ordered a few falafels and some drinks. Alana seemed to find the meal to be everything Ian had predicted. \r\n\r\nAfter the meal, Ian and Alana bid each other good night. Over the next few months they spent a lot of time in each other\'s company, eating falafels (or food from some other shop on the fringe of the campus), talking aobut politics, current events, and even history and physics. \r\n\r\n\r\nThey didn\'t agree on much but they respected each other and, more than anything else, they both enjoyed the opportunity to share their views with another passionate point of view. Both had learned that most people are uncomfortable with strongly held opinions and so they prized their time together. And, as time went on, they became friends.\r\n\r\n','2009-04-12','2009-04-13 05:52:09'),(439,84,'DAM','<h3>Idea: Post Global Warming Nuclear Carrier </h3>\r\nThe idea is that, after society has collapsed due to global warming, there are still some pockets of civiliazation. One of them is around the American fleet. THere is a nuclear carrier that\'s still cruising around. There are pirates and they have issues. They need various kinds of fuel for their tenders and support ships and, most important their airplanes. They have killer aircraft but they don\'t have much fuel. They have a regular city; they can make their own water, move around easily, maybe have access to some satelites, They need food, fuel, and lots of other supplies. \r\nThey have wild adventures. Not sure what the ultimate goal is. ','2009-04-19','2009-04-20 06:30:17'),(440,90,'DAM','I think that the day that the bully beats ian up, before he goes home, she confronts him and gives him a split lip. She basically attacks his friend just outside of school and, when he comes to try to make her stop (he has anger management issues) she hits him in the mouth. He and his friend get away and he\'s fine with it. \r\n\r\nThen, after he walks home, he sees his brother. His brother has heard about the encounter and knows that their mother is going to blame him and so gives Ian a real beating.','2009-05-08','2009-05-08 15:11:13'),(441,90,'DAM','What if Ian gets a job at Alana\'s company. He\'s in HR and he doesn\'t really have any duties but he ends up managing Alanas group. The would inevitably be problems with the young college kids and Alana wouldn\'t be likely to see the issues much less resolve them. \r\nAt first being close to the woman he loves is wonderful for Ian but it\'s like always seeing her but never being close. It\'s worse than staying home in some ways. \r\n\r\n','2009-05-16','2009-05-16 17:37:00'),(442,15,'DAM','The turn sequence should be trade, adjust prices, move.\r\nThe prices should adjust very slowly like a change every 10 trades and the change should only happen when the turn is over, not while people are trading. \r\n\r\nThe ships carry one thing, move anywhere in one turn, and you only get one. \r\nA caravan carries one thing, but takes multiple turns to go between cities but you get multiple.\r\na truck carries one thing and takes only one turn to get anywhere on the continent but it can\'t leave it\'s area. you can have multiple\r\nA modern cargo carrier can go to any port in the world but it might take multiple turns. \r\nan airplane can go anywhere in the world in one turn \r\n','2009-05-19','2009-05-20 06:49:03'),(443,4,'DAM','To build a new system I need 3 subsystems. \r\n\r\nFirst a login site. This should be a site-wide authentication and should include provisions for editing users and giving them access to various stuff. It should not have styles, it should allow me to set all that up. \r\n\r\nSecond I need a list manager which is a set of routines that allow me to specify virtual table (i.e. the result of a select) and then displays that table as bit html table. You can filter on certain defined fields and sort on columns as well as, perhaps, click on any row to get the information that isn\'t shown in the table. All this is definable.\r\n\r\nThird I need a form that will add or update an arbitrary table. Something heavily protected but web based that allows me to edit the values in a table. Part of this is that I need a way to say that this number in the table is really an index into that table over there so that we can have pulldowns.','2009-05-21','2009-05-21 16:32:57'),(444,15,'DAM','city \r\n  cityid\r\n  name \r\n  (cities need not have warehouses or other facilities; in that case it\'s more like a waypoint)\r\nCommodity\r\n  commodityid\r\n  name \r\n  baseprice\r\nMarkets\r\n  marketid\r\n  cityno\r\n  commodityno\r\n  quantity (default 1)\r\n  markettype enum(forsale, ondemand)\r\n  price\r\n  transaction count (after some transactions the price goes up)\r\nwarehouse\r\n  warehouseid\r\n  cityno\r\n  owner (playerno)\r\n  content (commodity #)\r\n  quantity (default 1)\r\nroute\r\n  routeid\r\n  fromcity\r\n  tocity\r\n  turns (default 1)\r\n  type enum (bi-directions, uni-directional)\r\nplayer\r\n  playerid\r\n  userno (actually usernumber from authenticaion table)\r\n  nickname\r\n   (is there any reason not to have the player number=userno?)\r\n   note that nicknames in games are not the same as the global user name\r\n  Money\r\nships\r\n  shipid\r\n  ownermp\r\n  capacity (default 1)\r\n  cityno\r\ncargoes\r\n  cargoid\r\n  commodityno\r\n  shipno\r\nstorage \r\n  storageid\r\n  commodityno\r\n  warehouseno\r\nspies\r\n  spyid\r\n  playerno\r\n  cost\r\n  assignment (city#)\r\n  spytype enum(spy, counterspy)','2009-05-21','2009-05-22 04:56:02'),(445,94,'davemenc',' ','2009-05-29','2009-05-29 23:29:17'),(446,60,'DAM','Outline\r\nA company called Serendipity, Inc, puts in a bid with a municipality to buy a pair of public housing high-rises. The site includes a park and some abandoned buildings which are filled with heroin addicts. The community is outraged. There are protests, marches, picketing, pamphlets, editorials and angry blogs. Everyone seems to be against this plan. But the city needs the money and the people in power respect money. And Serendipity, Inc has money. Tens of billions at least. \r\n\r\nWhen they actually closed the deal all the tenants and most of the rest of the community thought they were going to do something bad -- evict everyone and tear the whole thing down, for example.  So when they announce that they are going to move some tenants out of certain apartments, everyone assumes the worst. \r\n\r\nThey notify certain tenants that they want them to move and offer them alternate living space in some condos Serendipity bought on the edge of the site. Nothing fancy but somewhat better than public housing. And it\'s not really noticed by the press but the people asked to move certainly know that their apartments in the public building are the worst. Some are only too happy to leave but some are suspicious and are afraid that they won\'t be allowed to come back once they leave. Besides, their homes are what they\'re used to. Most of the people who don\'t want to leave are left in peace and alternates are selected -- it\'s like SI is trying to fill up the condos for some reason. But some people are pretty much forced to leave -- the law says that a landlord and move some on provided the landlord offers an alternative equivalent space. It turns out the the people who are forced to move into the condos are all in a single floor of one of the buildings -- a floor that is know to have serious health, safety and, perhaps, structural problems. \r\n\r\nThe company scours the buildings asking everyone if they have any experience in construction. A construction crew comes in and starts rebuilding all the vacated apartment, fixing the walls, new carpet, fixed plumbing, paint, whatever the apartments need. The construction company, Marblehead Construction, used to be predominantly white but now it\'s \"salt and pepper\". For some reason a lot of people in the buildings were hired to work on the buildings. Turns out Marblehead is a wholly owned subsidiary of Serendipity and they bulked up the workforce with locals. \r\n\r\nThere is more outrage about some presumed conspiracy or another but the complaints make even less sense when the people in the condos were moved back into their previous homes. Some of the apartments had been empty so there were more places to put people and so this time more people were moved out of their apartments. \r\n\r\nThe Marblehead Construction company just kept growing. In addition to fixing up apartments and \r\n\r\nbuilt more housing\r\nan elementary school\r\nbank\r\ngrocery store\r\ncommercial spaces\r\nhigh school \r\nbought more land to build a university\r\nkicked out the drug dealers and, eventually, the drug users\r\n\r\n','2009-06-01','2009-06-02 05:17:04'),(447,90,'DAM','<h2>Unique Dialogue</h2>\r\nEach person has to have his/her own personality and express it in his/her own voice. How would this person say it with different personalities? \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Personalities\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>persister\r\n<ul><li>emphatic<li>disagreeable<li>fault finding\r\n<li>emoter\r\n<li>introvert\r\n<li>workaholic\r\n<li>promoter\r\n<li>rebel\r\n<li>Persister\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Accents\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>regionalisms\r\n<li>slang\r\n<li>articles\r\n<li>southern/british accent?\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Other \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>metaphors\r\n<li>random thoughts\r\n<li>obscenities\r\n<li>Speech impediment\r\n<li>Repeated words and sounds (ah, um, you know)\r\n<li>precise speaking\r\n<li>Using big words\r\n<li>never using big words\r\n<li>jargon\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-06-08','2009-06-19 05:17:18'),(448,90,'DAM','<h2>The Vacation</h2>\r\nThe vacation doesn\'t make much sense. What if Ian needs to gather some information about stories of \"magic\" in the early history of the west? Instead of a vacation it\'s a working trip for him. The ghost stories need to be carefully followed up. The whole thing makes more sense, provided we can sell the idea that his thesis is furthered by information about the gold country. \r\n\r\nPerhaps he\'s doing research about the modern era.\r\n\r\nMy latest thinking is that his paper has pissed off his advisor so his advisor has sent him on wild goose chase into the gold country. He drags Alana along. He only needs to visit a few libraries but he makes it into a mini-vacation and takes a week. It doesn\'t take anywhere near a month. \r\n\r\nThis assumes that Alana has completed enough of her thesis that she can leave. As far as I can tell, that means all of it. It would be cool to get Mann to sender her away but until the thesis is done Mann can\'t close the deal. Perhaps when the thesis is DONE but not REVIEWED Mann will want Alana away because she wants to delay the world hearing about it as long as possible. I like the idea that Mann, who before denigrated Alana for wasting time with her \"boyfriend\" because it was in her best interest to do so, now takes the exact opposite position becuase, again, it\'s in her best interest to do so. \r\n','2009-06-08','2009-06-19 05:21:26'),(449,95,'davemenc',' ','2009-06-10','2009-06-10 16:24:07'),(450,95,'DAM','</pre>\r\n<h2> SPEECH 7: Research</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\nStart with \"black gold;;;Texas Tea;;; we\'re talking about OIL!\"\r\n<br>cutting back will get us so much\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>saves lots of money\r\n<li>separates us from middle east, terrorism and a general attack on the poor\r\n<LI>saves the environment especially green house gases\r\n</ul>\r\n<br>\r\nEnd with facts about US usage.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>25% of total consumption\r\n<li>21 million barrels a day of \r\n<Li>70% of petroleum to transportation\r\n<LI>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Black Giant \r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>date 1930  October 5,\r\n  <li>Size 140,000 acres, 5 counties, 45 miles, five miles (8 km) across\r\n  <li>who found and where, Columbus Marion (Dad) Joiner, 3,536 feet , \r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>Saudi Arabia\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>deal we made -- california oil company, California Arabian Standard Oil Company, Chevron\r\n  <li>why -- oil pressure down\r\n  <li>When 1933\r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>Oil first found\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>When northwestern Pennsylvania in 1859\r\n  <li>where\r\n  <li>By whom \"Colonel\" Edwin Drake\r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>Hidden pennies\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>make a list \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>military intervention\r\n<li>poverty?\r\n<li>environmental impact\r\n<li>Tax breaks (the golden gimick: 50% of oil profits forgiven in \'30s)\r\n</ul>\r\n  <li>How much, roughly\r\n  <li> what would oil cost without that\r\n  </ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Final Speech (approximately)</h3>\r\n<pre>\r\n<b>Black Gold</b>\r\n<b>Texas Tea</b>\r\nWe\'re talking about Oil. \r\nAnd here in the US we use a LOT of it. I\'d like to talk ab it about why that is.\r\nIn 1859, in Titus PA, a man by the name of Colonel Drake drilled the first oil well. He wasn\'t a real colonel, he was something of a con man but whether he meant to or not, he managed it.\r\nIn 1859 there wasn\'t a huge demand for oil but by 1930 the entire economy depended on it. Car and factories, ships and power stations all depended on oil.\r\nAnd everyone was looking for it. \r\nA man by the name of Dad Joiner was selling shares in his oil field. He bought up some mineral rights in texas and he sold shares. His first well was a bust and he made a profit. His second well was a bust and he made a profit. On his third try he hit oil and he went to jail. The problem was he was selling more than 100% of each of his projects so when it succeeded he couldn\'t pay up.\r\nSeems like everyone famous in oil was either a con man or a criminal. \r\nBut what we are interested in about Dad Joiner\'s well is that it turned out to the be biggest oil well in all of the continental US. 45 miles long by 5 miles wide. They called it the black giant and it had a lot of oil. \r\nImmediately everyone started drilling in it and by 1932 the pressure began to drop and they weren\'t getting as much oil out of the well as they knew was there. They didn\'t know then what they later learned: you can pump mud back into a well to keep the pressure up.\r\nThe US government, concerned that they couldn\'t run an economy without oil, cut a deal with Saudi Arabia. We would protect them and they would sell us cheap oil. \r\nAnd this set the tone for the next 70 years. Instead of reducing demand to be in line with supply, we would increase supply. \r\nAnd it put is in the middle east.\r\nWe put the shah in power and then helped saddam hussein when he was ousted. We fought Saddam in Kuwait and then we invaded Iraq, all because we needed the oil and so we had to be involved in the middle east. \r\n\r\nWhen you spend $3.50 at the pump that\'s just the start. You also pay taxes to fight wars in the Middle East and to keep the shipping lanes safe. And various people get subsidies of various kinds that you pay for. Tax breaks for people to buy larger vehicles, for example. \r\n\r\nAnd there are non-monetary hidden costs. People in poor countries with oil were promised the moon but ended up with giant gas flares that light up the night and make a lot of noise and leave soot on everything in their villages. They have enormous health effects. But when the people complain they are ruthlessly put down by the government -- and the oil companies. \r\n\r\nCloser to home, oil consumption causes pollution which has it\'s own health costs. And global warming -- we don\'t even know what effect that will have long term. \r\n\r\nPerhaps we should start reducing our consumption? What would it take? Well, last years oil price spike was caused by demand coming close to production. If we could reduce our demand by just a bit -- say 10% -- we could prevent that from happening again. What would it take to get a 10% reduction in oil demand? Well, 70% of our oil goes to transportation so if we could get a 20% reduction in our gasoline consumption that would be a 14% reduction in the total oil use.\r\nAnd what would that take. 20% sounds like a lot, right. \r\nIf everyone could stay home one day a week, that would do it. Or get more efficient cars; the average is 17mpg so 20mpg is 20%, or 20mpg to 24mpg. \r\n\r\nThe time has come to change our thinking about oil from trying to find production to meet demand to reducing our demand. It\'s not the hard to start. \r\nThank you.\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-06-10','2009-06-17 14:57:58'),(451,84,'DAM','<h3>Idea: A women lies about something  </h3>\r\nThe name of this story is \"The Lie\".  The woman has some truth that she lies about to her boyfriend. She doesn\'t want to tell him. She commits to it totally. She \"creates in her soul\" a little place for the lie to live. THen she marries the guy and has children with him and has a life. She keeps to the lie; she\'s committed. Then the truth comes to light, the lie is exposed and everyone has to re-examine all the truths they thought they knew.\r\n\r\nFor example, let\'s imagine that the woman has a child and puts it up for adoption. She meets her boyfriend and she doesn\'t tell him. They start to get serious and he tells her something of his past. He had lovers before, a fiance, a child, sex with an elephant, something. Probably not that serious, less serious than her. But he tells her and it costs him a lot. THis is the key scene: he looks at her with expectation and she says, positively, that she has lived  a boring, uneventful life. \r\n\r\nYears later the child finds her and comes back into her life. Her husband learns not only that she had a child but that she lied to him. Her son has to cope with the fact that he has a brother that he never knew anything about. He\'s less concerned about his mother\'s lie but he goes back and forth between delight that he has a sib and fear that he\'s no longer the center. ','2009-06-15','2009-06-16 04:35:21'),(452,95,'DAM','<h2>SPEECH 2: Organize</h2>\r\n<P>2/2/09\r\nmy father\r\nI want to talk about my father. He died in the 90s at the age of 72.  I was sad when he died and I missed him for years after which really surprised me. \r\nBy the end of the speech you\'ll know why. \r\n\r\nPre-me\r\n	born - pre war\r\n	drill instructor in SD\r\n	war imo jima\r\nme & him\r\n	youngest dreamer clumsy\r\n	childhood boot camp\r\n	views on programmers\r\n	Left home\r\n	lacked confidence\r\n	blamed him\r\nEnd of life\r\n	over the years, I got to know him as a person\r\n	toward the end of his life he had health problems \r\n	he used to say Dave, don\'t ever grow old. <pause>\r\n	One day he stopped growing hold <pause>\r\n	\r\nMy mother found him on the lawn. I discovered  I was very sad at his death and I couldn\'t understand why I had these feelings since he\'d been so hard on me. But I realized that, for good or ill, he\'d shaped my life. In a way, he had become a part of me. 	\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-06-17','2009-06-17 18:34:45'),(453,84,'DAM','<h3>Idea: Two Minute Wrong Number</h3>\r\nLet\'s say that Alice had a cell phone number that was, for example 666-6666. She was delighted by this number for a lot of reasons but one of her favorite reasons was that she would get calls fairly frequently from babies or very young children because they would get the phone from their parents and poke the keys. Her number was more likely to connect than most people\'s numbers so she would get calls. \r\n\r\nShe would talk to the babies and try to get them to \"talk\" back until the parent caught the kid and hung up the phone. Sometimes she would have long conversations with babies cooing or 3 year olds talking to her. \r\n\r\nSomeone is murdered. The police discover that Alice had talked to the victim for more than a minute which indicates to them that Alice and the victim have some kind of relationship. \r\n\r\nBut when they talk to Alice she denies knowing the victim. They don\'t believe her and they present their evidence. they are elaborately unimpressed by her explanation. \r\n\r\nWith just one other tidbit of circumstantial evidence Alice would be in deep trouble. This could be a red herring or it could be an interesting main story line: Alice needs to solve the murder. \r\n\r\nNow turn it around: Alice is murdered. The police are trying to figure out why all these random people called her. They need to figure out which phone calls are significant. \r\n\r\nI don\'t want to forget that Dorita has a number that people call all the time by accident. If you dial 888-xxx-xxxx instead of 1-888-xxx-xxxx you get her (the last 3 digits don\'t matter). And 1-888-xxx-xxxx is the local hospital. \r\n\r\n','2009-06-23','2009-07-20 21:33:49'),(454,54,'defer','<h3>RESTful Interface</h3>\r\n\r\nI think I can convert all my existing crappy interface (\".php?mode=foo&record=bar\") into a more restful interface by using the trick in CAKE with the RewriteRule in the .htaccess file. \r\nTo allow an interface like this: &lt;app&gt;/&lt;mode&gt;/&lt;item&gt;/&lt;order&gt; or \r\n&lt;app&gt;/mode&gt;/&lt;sort&gt;/&lt;item&gt; \r\nlook for webroot/(..*)/(.*)/(.*)/(.*) and convert it to \r\n(1)?mode=(2)&sort=(3)&item=(4) or\r\n(1)?mode=(2)&sort=(4)&item=(3)\r\nThis would have to be customized slightly for some applications. \r\n','2009-06-23','2009-06-24 01:21:31'),(455,95,'DAM','<h2>Speech 8: Persuade</h2>\r\n6/24/09\r\nIt\'s a real challenge for me to do a persuasive speech because I\'m such a moderate. Not A or Z but somewhere in the middle -- M, say.\r\nEveryone agrees that global climate change is real but there\'s wide spread disagreement on what to do about it. \r\nThe conservatives would have it that we can\'t afford to do anything that might hurt the economy. I heard Senator Murkowski from Alaska give a speech in which she suggested that congress just needs to realize that market forces will make energy clean without intervention and everything will be fine. \r\nI disagree. If we don\'t radically change our CO2 footprint -- which, by the way, is still going up AND accelerating -- the direst predictions of the scientists will become reality. \r\nTo give one example of the dire consequences of inaction, consider food. \r\n- increased heat reduces the snowpack which reduces the water available in the spring\r\n- chaotic weather also makes it hard to farm\r\n- higher temperature reduces the areas in which you can farm -- pushes it away from the equator\r\nThis all adds up to poor farming\r\nBut it does not reduce population growth.\r\nGlobal climate change, if unchecked, may lead to severe famine!\r\n\r\nEssentially, the argument is that we can\'t afford to fix our profligate use of CO2 because the rich are making too much money, even if it means that our children\'s children won\'t be able to feed themselves! This is not a rational or reasonable position. \r\n\r\nOn the other extreme are the conservationists. I have a lot more in common with them, I think, but they still go too far. \r\n\r\nThey want to save the planet, regardless of hte cost to humanity. Take for example nuclear power. Conservationists don\'t like nuclear power because there is no way to store the waste for thousands of year while it stops being radioactive. But if you believe in the predictions of the scientists, we have a clear choice:  widespread starvation in this century or possible radiation leaks in a few hundred years. Personally, I would choose to put off the demise of my civilization by as  long as possible so I would go for the nuclear power plants.\r\n\r\nConservationists are well known for wishing to save the planet. I don\'t think the planet is in any danger. Long after we have destroyed the atmosphere and killed ourselves off, the planet will still be here and will be teaming with life. It just won\'t be OUR life. \r\n\r\nWe don\'t need to save the planet, we need to save ourselves!\r\n\r\noutline\r\n- Challenge\r\n -- normally you want to take a or z\r\n -- i want to take L which is harder\r\n- global climate change not in question\r\n- we don\'t agree what to do\r\n- pro business\r\n -- do nothing\r\n -- hurt economy \r\n -- hurt business\r\n -- senator murkowski\r\n  --- do nothing\r\n  --- market forces will fix everything\r\n- must take action\r\n -- co2 is not just increasing, it\'s rate of increase is increasing\r\n -- Consquences: food\r\n  --- increased heat reduces the snowpack which reduces the water available in the spring\r\n  --- chaotic weather also makes it hard to farm\r\n  --- higher temperature reduces the areas in which you can farm -- pushes it away from the equator\r\n  --- adds up to poor farming\r\n  --- but the population will still grow \r\n  --- probably widespread famine\r\n -- profits vs lives\r\n- Conservationists\r\n -- more in common but I still disagree\r\n -- they want to save the planet at the cost of humans\r\n -- nuclear power\r\n --- obviously no co2\r\n --- radioactive waste\r\n --- I would choose a 1000 year problem over a 100 one\r\n- one group wants to save profits\r\n- one group wants to save the planet\r\n- I say we don\'t need to save the planet, we need to save ourselves\r\n\r\n','2009-06-24','2009-06-30 03:29:45'),(456,39,'DAM','<h2>Shermer</h2>\r\nMr. Shermer, most of what I have read by you seems to me to be correct.  In theory, a skeptic has no bias. You don\'t allow your secret wish for there to be aliens (even if there was such a wish, which there probably isn\'t) to make you more easily persuaded by the evidence. No, if one cannot lay an alien at your feet, you will not accept the existence of aliens, period.\r\n\r\nBut I, frankly, suspect you of a bias. I think that, in the absence of any evidence about something you seem to assume that there must be a physical explanation. \r\n\r\nFor example, you mentioned in a recent Scientific American article the competing theories of how the universe came into existence before the big bang. Science not only doesn\'t know but the current thinking is that Science *cannot* know. And yet you dismiss the possibility of God saying \"let there be light!\" in favor of some other physically based theory. That\'s just a bias \r\n\r\n','2009-06-24','2009-06-24 18:06:41'),(457,90,'DAM','alana tells a friend that Ian drives her crazy because she has to remind him constantly about where things go, belong, should be put away, used and generally everything. \r\n\r\nIan tells a different friend that she drives him crazy because she has all these bizarre rules \r\n\r\nSomehow they resolve all this and become straonger','2009-06-28','2009-06-29 00:59:27'),(458,90,'DAM','meeting with ian\'s advisor\r\nadvisor\r\n - good research\r\n - bright future\r\n - hate to see you throw it away\r\nIan\r\n - I thought it was a clever cut on a subject that\'s been done to death\r\n\r\n\r\n\"Ian, we apreciate your sense of humor but this is serious!\r\n\r\nI\'m not making a joke here. I tseems to bme that the evidences supports this as a reasonable hypothesis. \r\n\"A reasonably hypothesis!?\" Shouted Bob. \"Look, you might as well not publish anything as publish this! If you publish this you won\'t get your masters and even if you do you no one will hire you. \"\r\n\r\n\"But it meets all the standards and guidelines. The research is solid and, frankly, it\'s no more ridiculous than most of the others I\'ve seen! Why are you on my case?\"\r\n\r\nThere was a long silence. When he broke it Bob sounded much calmer. \"Look, Ian, here\'s what I\'m going to do. I\'m going to send you on a field trip for me. While you are gone I want you to think about this. It won\'t be hard to use what you\'ve written to support a conclusion that makes sense. Just a little bit of tweaking and you\'ll be done.\"\r\n\r\n\"But Bob, all I have to do is submit my work to review and I\'m done.\"\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-06-28','2009-07-02 02:41:50'),(459,84,'DAM','<h3> Idea: Camera Hat </h3>\r\nThere is a guy, Bob,  who has a camera attached to his hat. He is constantly connected to the internet and is streaming, real time, images from his hat. \r\n\r\nBob\'s in a bad part of town and a guy mugs him. As Bob is pulling out his wallet he tells the mugger that this is probably a bad idea because they are under video surveillance and that the police are probably on their way, called by the people who watch the video. \r\n\r\nThe mugger doubts this and Bob points to his hat. The mugger knocks his hat off and Bob smiles as he hands over his wallet, pointing out that the mugger\'s face has already been seen. \r\n\r\nThe mugger gets angry and put the gun to Bob\'s head. But Bob points out, as calmly as he can, that this won\'t help. After all, if he\'s found dead that mugger will be the primary suspect and, really pretty much a lock for the murder!\r\n\r\nThe mugger hesitates and, just then, sirens are heard. The mugger bugs out. The comes come and a serious amount of hassle ensues for Bob but, as several commentators point out, he\'s still alive.\r\n\r\nPeople hear about the story and a lot of people want to get video hats of their own and for their loved ones both to protect themselves from muggers and to prove or disprove that their loved ones are where they are supposed to be at any given moment. The theme song of this \"video hat movement\" becomes \"you\'re so vain\" for oh so many reasons. \r\n\r\nA few months later Bob goes off the grid.  His hat records the same scene at the same location for hours. It looks like the hat was set on the table and just left there. Viewers go through several attempts to resolve this (calling the police, calling the restaurant, etc) but it takes several hours before it can be determined that the hat isn\'t where it\'s supposed to be. It is eventually found in a storage room in the restroom of the restaurant. It has been transmitting an accurate location but a false image for hours. It\'s rigged with a cheesy picture which seems to have fooled everyone. \r\n\r\nSo where is Bob. A few days later his body is found in a dumpster. At first the Hat Movement people claim that this proves the bad shit that can happen when you give up your hat -- a cautionary tail. \r\n\r\nBut it turns out that he was dead at least a few days before his hat showed up. \r\n\r\nSo how was he killed? \r\n\r\nBob was attacked. It seemed that he tripped and recovered but what really happened was that he was attacked from behind by two hidden assailants and his hat was taken from him. One of his assailants, who looked like Bob, continued on. He didn\'t stick to Bob\'s agenda but, then, Bob seldom did. He went to the restaurant his hat was found in and got the picture and then the picture rig was attached to the hat and the final get away affected. \r\n\r\nThere is all kinds of crazy shit that can go on here but it\'s basically just your standard murder mystery with this weird hat-thing going on. \r\n','2009-07-05','2009-07-20 21:34:15'),(460,84,'DAM','<h3>Idea: Email from African Lawyer who is Legitimate</h3>\r\nImagine a lawyer (Andy) who works in a law office in some third world nation. Periodically, a client dies and the law office has to handle the will. This particular lawyer has been set the task of dealing with a will that gives money to various people in europe and america. Being a small law firm, they can\'t really afford to call all these people, much less fly someone out to europe. So Andy has to send email to all these people. For example, his email might look like this: \r\nI am Albert Jamal,Attorney at law.A deceased client of mine that shares\r\nthe same last name as yours died as a result of a heart-related condition\r\nin March 12th 2007. His heart condition was due to the death of all the\r\nmembers of his family in the tsunami disaster on the 26th December2004 in\r\nSumatra Indonesia. \r\n\r\nI find this very amusing.\r\n\r\n','2009-07-20','2009-07-20 21:34:54'),(461,96,'davemenc',' ','2009-07-20','2009-07-20 21:35:34'),(462,96,'DAM','The name of this story is \"The Lie\". The woman has some truth that she lies about to her boyfriend. She doesn\'t want to tell him. She commits to it totally. She \"creates in her soul\" a little place for the lie to live. THen she marries the guy and has children with him and has a life. She keeps to the lie; she\'s committed. Then the truth comes to light, the lie is exposed and everyone has to re-examine all the truths they thought they knew.\r\n\r\nFor example, let\'s imagine that the woman has a child and puts it up for adoption. She meets her boyfriend and she doesn\'t tell him. They start to get serious and he tells her something of his past. He had lovers before, a fiance, a child, sex with an elephant, something. Probably not that serious, less serious than her. But he tells her and it costs him a lot. THis is the key scene: he looks at her with expectation and she says, positively, that she has lived a boring, uneventful life. \r\n\r\nYears later the child finds her and comes back into her life. Her husband learns not only that she had a child but that she lied to him. Her son has to cope with the fact that he has a brother that he never knew anything about. He\'s less concerned about his mother\'s lie but he goes back and forth between delight that he has a sib and fear that he\'s no longer the cente ','2009-07-20','2009-07-20 21:38:46'),(463,97,'davemenc',' <h2>Drink Clusters: Problem</h2>\r\nI want to have custer of drinks. The clusters should be about 50 drinks and should be, in some concept, \"closest\". Conceptually, we shouldhn\'t have dirnks in the cluster that are too far from each other. \r\n\r\nThe purpose of this is to have drinks that can be mated without having too many drinks on a page. \r\n\r\nI\'m thinking each cluster will have an icon and drinks associated with an icon can be mated. It may be that a drink ahs more than one icon and thus belongs to more than on cluster and so can be mated with more than one cluster. \r\n\r\nSo, clusters overlap. \r\n\r\nNow, we have a good way to measure drink closeness. If you do the standard distance between drinks you get an N dimensional distance between drinks. I plan to use this mathematical trick.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-08-04','2009-08-04 22:22:45'),(464,97,'DAM ','<h2>Drink Clusters: Graph Theory</h2>\r\nRJ suggested an algorithm in which you pick a distance and find all the pairs  drinks that are at least that close to each other. A cluster is formed by all the drinks that are all at least that clsoe to each other. \r\n\r\nThis is, I believe, a graph theory problem. If we construct a graph that consists of all the drinks as nodes and all the distances as edges (only one edge between nodes) and then pick a distance, we can easily find all the drinks that might be in clusters by removing all the drinks that aren\'t at least that distance. \r\n\r\nThen we can find all the drinks in a given cluster by finding all the drinks that completely cross connect. A  cluster is a set of drinks that all cross connect. \r\n<h3> algorithm</h3>\r\nThe algorithm for this would be something like...\r\n\r\nPick a distance. Make a list of all the drinks and distances. Create a graph of all these drinks. Remove all the edges that are greater than the distance. Now we use this new graph to cluster drinks.\r\n\r\nTake a drink and add it to a cluster list. Pick a drink that\'s adjacent to this drink and add it to the list. Now pick a drink that\'s adjacent to this second drink and see if it\'s adjacent to every drink on the cluster link. If so then you keep going, if not you have to back up.\r\n\r\nThis is a depth first search but with the caveat that you can\'t take a step unless the new node is connected to all previous nodes, and, of course, you\'re not looking for short routes but completely interconnected sets of nodes. \r\n\r\nWhen you\'ve tried the entire set of interconnected nodes from your starting nodes, you mark that node as complete and pick a new, unused node. \r\n\r\nYou have to put something in there that prevents you from finding sub-sets of existing clusters but still allow you to find valid clusters that intersect existing clusters. \r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Picking a distance</h3> \r\nIf you consider each drink and it\'s relationship to every other drink you would get a list of distances. The smallest of these is the distance between this drink and it\'s closest neighbor. Do this for all the drinks. Now find the largest value for the distance from a drink and it\'s closest neighbor. This number is the smallest cluster distance that will included all the drinks in at least one cluster; smaller than this and some drinks will be left out. ','2009-08-04','2009-08-04 18:43:42'),(465,97,'DAM ','<h2>Drink Clusters: Geometry </h2>\r\nThe goal here is to create a collection of circles that contain all the points. Two thing you need for a circle: a center point and a radius. We pre-define the radius and so now the problem is picking a set of points. \r\n\r\n<h3>Bottom Line</h3>\r\nI\'ve chewed on this for several hours and you have two choices. \r\n\r\nFirst, there are good algorithms for dividing a space into boxes and then subdividing those boxes (or increasing those boxes) until you have the number of boxes you want with the amount of stuff in each. The problem is that this is in N-space which makes the calculations fairly complicated.\r\n\r\nTo avoid dealing with N dimensions you can deal with distances. That means you pick points and get distances the points to all the drinks. If you use drinks for the points you don\'t have to do a lot of extra work and it\'s probably a pretty good approximation to a good point. But there are a lot of different combinations of points and distances yielding very different answers. \r\n\r\nYou can brute force through, trying every combination of up to 10 drinks for every possible distance. If you have a good metric for what you\'re looking for you\'ll finish, eventually, with a good set of clusters of drinks. \r\n\r\nSurely there is a more elegant solution that that!\r\n\r\n<h3>A Specific Algorithm</h3>\r\nLet\'s look at this in 2d first. I don\'t think there are any issues between Nspace and 2space that aren\'t just more comparisons. \r\n\r\nYou have a list of groups. Each group consists of a list of rectangles. \r\n\r\nYou need a minimum and maximum size for your groups. Let\'s say our minimum is 45 and our maximum is 55 and let\'s say that we have 150 points. \r\n\r\nStart with one group with one rectangle that contains everything. \r\nPut the group in a priority queue. The queue is ordered from largest to smallest and it ALWAYS pulls off the largest.\r\n<b>Start</b>\r\nIs the queue empty? Go to Empty (below)\r\nPull the first thing off the queue.\r\nCase 1: It\'s too small. Make a list of groups that are adjacent, order from largest to smallest. Find the first group that, when combined with our current group, will not go over the size limit. If possible combine them. \r\n\r\nCase 2: It\'s too large. Subdivide the group in to 4 equal sized groups. Put the 4 new groups back on the queue.  Go to Start.\r\n\r\nCase 3: it\'s the right size. Take it off the queue; it\'s done. Go to Start\r\n\r\n<b>Empty</b>\r\nRun through the groups. If they\'re all the right size, we\'re done.\r\nIf they aren\'t then check to see if we accomplished anything on the last pass. If so then add all the non-finished groups to the queue and goto Start.\r\nIf we didn\'t accomplish anything, then take all the groups apart, divide all the rectangles into 4 new rectangles and add them all to the queue. Goto Start\r\n\r\nThis is not guaranteed to finish but the worst case is that each point is in it\'s own rectangle and the rectangles expand to encompass the right numbers of points and it finishes. \r\n\r\n\r\n','2009-08-04','2009-08-06 16:54:15'),(466,97,'DAM ','<h2>Graph Theory: A Good Algorithm</h2>\r\nStart as before with a graph of all the drinks and a distance. Remove, as before, all the edges that are longer than the distance. \r\n\r\nMake a list of all the drinks. Add it to a list. Create a queue of drinks connected to this first drink. This queue represents all drinks within the distance to the first drink. For each of the drinks in this queue, look at each drinks in the list and make sure they are connected to it. If all the drinks in the list are connected to a drink, you can add the drink to the list. \r\n\r\n','2009-08-04','2009-08-04 22:30:57'),(467,97,'DAM ','<h2>Lucifer\'s Algorithm</h2>\r\nHere\'s the simplest algorithm I can think of for automatic speciation - it would be trivial in Lisp or Prolog, and a bit more cumbersome in any of the C dialects.\r\n\r\n1) Build a list of all drink pairs sorted by their distance - feel free to exclude all pairs beyond a certain huge distance if you need to conserve memory or somesuch.\r\n\r\n2) Create an empty list of species - each species will have a numeric identifier and a list of drinks it contains.\r\n\r\n3) Moving from closest pair furthest pair, find the species that each drink belongs to:\r\n\r\n 3a) If neither belongs to a species already, create a new species and put them both in it.\r\n\r\n 3b) If either but not both belong to a species already, add the straggler to the species the other one belongs to.\r\n\r\n 3c) If both belong to species, and if the total number of drinks between the two species is less than 20, move the drinks in the second species into the first species, and then delete the second species.\r\n\r\n Its a calculated shot in the dark, that may just work - if not, I\'ll articulate a more cumbersome approach where each set has a \"center of gravity\" that allows us to determine when it should accrete with other sets.\r\n\r\n\r\nforeach ($drinklist as $drink1) {\r\n$drinkspecies[$drink1] = -1;\r\n foreach($drinklist as $drink2){\r\n  $drinkdistance[$drink1][$drink2] = distance($drink1,$drink2);\r\n }\r\n}\r\nasort($drinkdistance);\r\n','2009-08-05','2009-08-06 15:04:02'),(468,97,'DAM ','<h2>Refinement of Lucifer\'s Algorithm</h2>\r\nLucifer\'s algorithm uses the CD to combine groups. If two drinks are closer than the CD, they will always be in the same group (which he calls a species). \r\n\r\nA refinement would be to count how many drinks are closer than the CD and only lump them together when you have more than a certain number of these drinks.\r\n\r\nA way to visualize what\'s happening here is to think of two drinks as being close together but belonging to two distinct clusters of drinks. \r\n\r\nPicture two clouds of points that are quite distinct but come closest where two points, one on the edge of each cloud, come closest. When the algorithm finds these two points, it combines the two clouds into one group.\r\n\r\nYou could even think about a string of points leading from one cloud to the other. Even if the two clouds are quite distinct and far apart, a single \"trail\" of points would cause the two clouds to be combined.\r\n\r\nBut if you required there to be more than one point that was close enough, then the two groups would have to be much more connected. If having one string of points is unlikely, having two would be really surprising and having several would be impossible. \r\n\r\nOf course, we don\'t know that the clouds are separate. It\'s possible that our \"clouds\" is really just one cloud and we are just happen to have formed two clouds out of it because we haven\'t yet considered the points they have in common. \r\n\r\nBut both these cases would be handled with this refinement. ','2009-08-05','2009-08-06 15:16:54'),(469,97,'DAM ','<h2> Equivalent Algorithm To Lucifer\'s</h2>\r\nOrganize the distances by drink (that is, for each drink, have a list of distances from that drink to every other drink). \r\n\r\n<b>Start</b>\r\nPick a drink that hasn\'t been assigned to group a and add it to a queue. \r\nCreate a \"current group\" (CG)\r\n\r\n<b>Process Queue</b>\r\nTake a drink from the queue and add it to the CG. Find all the drinks that are no more than the critical distance (CD) from that drink and add them to the queue.\r\n\r\nIf the queue is not empty go to <b>Process Queue</b>\r\n\r\nIf there are drinks that have not been assigned to a group, go to <b>Start</b>.\r\n\r\nI believe this to be the same as Lucifer\'s original algorithm.\r\n','2009-08-06','2009-08-06 15:03:17'),(470,97,'DAM ','<h2>Tweak to Groupings</h2>\r\nWhen you form a group, throw everything out of the group that\'s farther out from the rest by more than twice the Critical Distance (CD).\r\n\r\nThe problem is, figuring out which drinks that meet this criteria to throw out. ','2009-08-06','2009-08-06 15:07:38'),(471,97,'DAM ','<h2> Lucifer\'s New Tweak</h2>\r\n1) Same as initially defined, except that you MUST exclude all pairings above some threshold distance.\r\n\r\n2.5) Create an empty list of species pairs - each pair will include the identifiers of the two species being paired, along with an integer indicating how many of their members are in contact. Note that these pairings are bidirectional, so if there is a pair (1 3) then there will NOT be a separate pair (3 1).\r\n\r\n3c) If both belong to species, find or create a species pair and increment its integer value by 1. Then compare the integer value to the number of drinks in each species - if the integer is greater than either drink count, and if the total number of drinks in both species is 50 or less, then accrete the smaller species into the larger one.\r\n','2009-08-06','2009-08-06 15:33:28'),(472,97,'DAM ','>  BTW, an alternate approach given our specific application is to build the\r\n> species pairs during the loop but NOT combine any groups - you then sort the\r\n> species pairs from highest percentage of overlap to lowest, and grind down\r\n> the list combining species until each is 50 or less drinks and no other\r\n> combinations can be made.\r\n>\r\n','2009-08-06','2009-08-06 15:51:07'),(473,90,'DAM','I would like Ian to show his learning. Ian is presented as, basically, perfect. He DOES have absolutely no fear and no lack of confidence in his own ability, he really isn\'t a very practical guy. \r\n\r\nMaybe when he works with people who screw him over he becomes disillusioned. ','2009-08-07','2009-08-07 15:32:48'),(474,90,'DAM','All day Sunday, the day after the dance, Alana was walking on air. She was still thinking about the night before, the dance, the kiss. If anyone had asked, she probably would have said that it was a one time thing, that she would never be in Andy\'s arms again. But no one asked and, for Alana, she was still in Andy\'s arms, forever. \r\n\r\n\"alana, there\'s a phone ccall for you,\" called her mother.\r\n\r\nAndy was on the phone. \"Alana, I had to call you. It was wonderful last night! I can\'t stop thinking about you!\" \r\n\r\n\"I can\'t stop thinking about you, either,\" admitted Alana.\r\n\r\nAlana and Andy talked for an hour and would have gone on talking for longer but Alana\'s mother stopped them. \"Alana, get off the phone. You\'ve been on there for an hour.\"\r\n\r\n\"I\'m sorry, Andy, my stupid mother wants me to get off the phone so I have to go. I\'ll see you tomorrow at school.\"\r\n\r\nThe next day Andy and Alana met before their home rooms. \r\n\"Andy, I\'m really sorry I had to hang up on you last night. My stupid mother just doesn\'t understand. \"\r\n\'Well I understand. Your parents still think you are a little girl but I know you aren\'t.\" \r\nAndy put his arms around Alana and pull her close. Alana put her head on his chest, she felt safe and loved. The bell rang and they had to rush to class. They didn\'t share any classes together but after school they met behind the gym to cuddle and kiss and exchange endearments. \r\n\r\nThis formed the pattern for the week. They would talk on the phone until Alana\'s \"stupid\" mother would make them stop, meet before class and then after school. \r\n\r\nGradually their meetings became less cuddly and more sexual. ALana thrilled to Andy\'s touch on her breasts and when his leg moved between her legs she wouldn\'t  pull away. It all felt so wonderful and she loved Andy -- and she knew he love her -- so much that it never occurred to her that their meetings had a progression to them, from holding to cuddling to kissing, to caressing. Alana didn\'t see this as wrong or inappropriate; she was thrilled by the attention and, really, it all felt so good. She just thought this was what boyfriends and girlfriends did. \r\n\r\nHer first doubt came when, late in the week, Andy slipped his hand between her thighs. Andy had been kissing her and rubbing her breasts and moving his leg between hers for a while in this session and seemed a bit more aggressive than usual and Alana was aroused. But this seemed to step over a line. For the first time, Alana pulled back. \r\n\r\nAndy whispered in her ear a continuous stream of reassuring words \"it\'s OK, baby, I love you, it will feel good, you\'ll love it, I want this for you, let me do this for you...\". Andy didn\'t stop but pushed forward and, constrained by his \r\nembrace and the wall behind her and his leg still partially between her own, there wasn\'t much Alana could do to stop it. \r\n\r\nAnd it did feel good after a few seconds. And then it felt very good and then time stopped and Alana relaxed into it. Afterward Alana didn\'t want to let Andy go. He had to carefully extricate himself from her, kiss her on the forehead and reminder her that they had to go and that he would call her. \r\n\r\nAlana felt changed. She knew that she would do anything for Andy simply because he made her feel this way. She loved him, she was his and this is how it was meant to be. \r\n\r\nThat night, Andy dropped a bombshell on her: there was a party Saturday night. If she could get out of the house, he would pick her up and they could be together and dance at the house of Andy\'s friend. \r\n\r\nAlana was deeply in love but even she would probably would have had some second thoughts about being alone with Andy in, say, the bedroom of a strange house. But she thought of it as a recreation of the dance at which they met. It seemed so perfect, so romantic. She wanted to go. And, of course, Andy, her Andy, wanted her to go.\r\n\r\nBut there was a problem, of course. She could hardly tell her mother that she was going to a party with her new boyfriend that her parent didn\'t even really know about yet (somehow she had neglected to tell them). \r\n\r\nShe would have to come up with a plan. This meant lying to them which, while not really the first time, was a rare occurrence. ','2009-09-14','2009-09-15 15:25:58'),(475,90,'DAM','Saturday morning, over breakfast, Alana asked if it was OK if she went over to here friend Amber\'s house that night. Oh, and could she get a ride over there. She mentioned that she and Amber had a project that they needed to work on. Amber would be expecting her at 6:30 and they would be working on their project for hours. She said that Amber\'s parents had agreed to take her home. \r\n\r\nShe had told Amber that she would be coming over but only for a short time.  She would wait until her parents drove a way, say goodbye to Amber and run around the corner to the park where she had arranged with Lance to pick her up before 7. \r\n\r\nAt the end of the evening Lance could drop her off around the corner from her house and she would walk in, freshly back from Amber\'s house and no one would be the wiser.\r\n\r\nShe was very pleased with her plan and confident that it would work like a charm. But then her mothers said, \"OK but be back by 10 PM\". \r\n\r\nLance would surely think that only a kid would need to be back by 10 but Alana could hardly tell her mother that. \"I don\'t think that will give us enough time to finish the project. I\'ll just be at Amber\'s. Can\'t I stay a little longer? Say, 11?\"\r\n\r\n\"If you need more time you should start earlier. Be home by 10.\" \r\n\r\nAlana glanced at her father but he was avoiding her gaze, the coward. She tried again, with little hope. \"I can\'t go earlier because Amber has something going on before that. We need to get this done by Monday\". \r\n\r\n\"Well you can work on it tomorrow.\"\r\n\r\nAlana suddenly saw a glimmer of hope! \"But tomorrow is Sunday and Amber visits her grandmother Sunday afternoons.\" \r\n\r\n\"Well then, arrange to finish your work in the morning.\" Mrs. Perez was getting somewhat vexed by all the arguing. \r\n\r\n\"Ahem.\" Mr. Perez cleared his throat. \"Dear,\" he said diffidently, \"Alana can\'t go in the morning because she will be in church with me.\"\r\n\r\nMrs. Perez looked exasperated but she saw, only too late, that she had been out maneuvered. She looked at Alana for a long moment, as if wondering if Alana had planned that out. Final she said, \"Very well, 11 PM. Don\'t be late.\" And that ended the matter. \r\n','2009-09-17','2009-09-18 04:17:39'),(476,90,'DAM','At 6:40 Alana stepped out of the car in front of Amber\'s house, a little later than Alana had wanted but not bad considering that it was her father who brought her. He had read his book until 6:25, as the clock slowly moved around in it\'s dial, and then insisted that Alana get a coat and took forever to find his keys and his own jacket and so on. Alana\'s mother would have had her there 5 minutes early but she was still on her time line. \r\n\r\nShe leaned back in and kissed her father goodbye. As she closed the door she could feel her excitement rising in her. Soon she would be with Lance. She almost skipped to the front door and rang the bell. Amber seemed to take forever to come to the door and Alana\'s father waited patiently in the car as she waited impatiently at the door. \"Why can\'t he just drive away!\" she thought furiously, mindful of the seconds ticking by. But, when the door opened, she was careful to turn to him, give him a big smile and wave in the hopes that this would cause him to drive away more quickly.\r\n\r\nShe gave Amber the book that was her excuse for coming over and Amber seemed a bit confused. \"Did your father just drive away? I thought you just came to drop off the book. We\'re about to have dinner.\"\r\n\r\nAlana zipped up her book bag again, looked at Amber and merely said, \"goodbye\". It was hard to ignore all those valid questions but she had decided that she didn\'t want to confide in Amber and if she wasn\'t going to tell her everything the less she knew the better. \r\n\r\nAlana walked out the door and down the street with a baffled Amber looking after her. \r\n\r\nAlana was happy. She bouncing with joy that her plan had worked but most of all that she was about to see Lance. And not just see him, as she had seen him before and after school every day this week but be with him for several hours. She longed to feel his touch, thrill to his caress.  She couldn\'t believe how he made her feel. Surely no one else in whole universe could make her feel the way Lance did and no one in the history of the world had felt like she did when Lance was touching her. \r\n\r\nThere was Lance\'s car on the street in front of the tiny park. She ran over and got in the passenger seat. He grabbed her up in his arms and pulled her to him and kissed her with a long passionate kiss that foretold many more like it in the evening ahead.\r\n\r\nAt length, Lance put the car in gear and took off, driving thrillingly fast for his young passenger. But he could have driven off a cliff and Alana wouldn\'t have complained as long as they went off it together. Alana\'s father had read Romeo and Juliet with her (each of them reading out loud the various parts) but only now did she really understand how Juliet had felt. What a wonderful feeling to be in love and to care about nothing else!\r\n','2009-09-17','2009-09-18 04:17:07'),(477,90,'DAM','A novel is considered a novel when it\'s 60k or longer. That\'s less than 200 pages. \r\n\r\n200k+ is an \"epic\" novel\r\n\r\n multiply the pages by 250 to get your WC\r\nor divide word count by 250 to get pages','2009-09-18','2009-09-18 07:41:47'),(478,96,'DAM','You told me that you see it as OK to lie provided you totally commit to the lie and \"create a space in your soul for it.\" I would say that you are making the lie, in some sense, a reality at which point, of course, it ceases to be a lie and BECOMES reality.\r\n\r\nThe book idea is based on this concept. Imagine a person who had a thing happen. A personal thing that was extremely hard but private and only really affected that person. The person puts it behind them by ceasing to acknowledge that it ever happened. They create a space in their soul, put the truth there and then the reality is that it never happened.\r\n\r\nYears later they\'ve been so successful that this truth has completely ceased to be for them. It\'s gone. For them, the lie is the literal truth. No one around them has any idea even tho they are extremely close to many people who would say they know that person to their very soul.\r\n\r\nAnd then a physical manifestation of the original truth appears. Something undeniable. And now our principal character, as well as everyone with whom the character has a relationship has to cope with this inversion of the reality.\r\n\r\nTo put it in concrete terms, imagine that a woman gets pregnant in high school. The event is hushed up, she goes to visit her aunt for a few months and puts the baby up for adoption. It\'s incredibly painful for a wide range of reasons but it\'s over. She\'ll never see her baby again so why dwell on it? She locks away the event so thoroughly that, for her, it never happens.\r\n\r\nShe marries a wonderful man and has two wonderful children. They are all very close and this closeness is based on never keeping secrets, never telling lies. Everyone knows her down to her very soul.\r\n\r\nThen (and you must have seen this coming) her kid, now 18, contacts her. Shows up. Confronts her family.\r\n\r\nThe part that I think is interesting here is that she is still the very same person that they knew before. But, because they thought they knew everything about her and now they discover they didn\'t, it changes the way they look at her. Trust is broken.\r\n\r\nI would write it in such a way that the reader really gets her point of view -- she didn\'t lie, she didn\'t hide anything, this event was literally not true for her any more. But also get her family\'s point of view. What a wonderful place to put the reader!\r\n\r\nI\'m thinking that this might be the book I write in November, although I might not be ready to knock out such a expository book in a month. I mean, essentially, the book only has a few plot points; all the rest is getting inside the characters heads and poking around.','2009-09-19','2009-09-19 17:10:38'),(479,96,'DAM','This book has deep psychological underpinnings which might not be obvious at first blush. You might say \"but she lied\" but the fact is that we all have memories that we change or suppress. Her\'s is an extreme case but it\'s nothing we haven\'t all done. ','2009-09-19','2009-09-19 17:12:11'),(480,84,'DAM','<h3>Story: Formerly Beautiful Woman</h3>\r\nI was in a hotel at a conference. I was waiting in the bar for some people to meet me for dinner. There was a man and a woman who came in and we had some drinks and talked. She was a middle aged woman, somewhat petite, a little pretty but not beautiful and the years had not been overly kind to her (she wasn\'t old looking but she showed her age).\r\n\r\nAt one point in the conversation she said something like \"when you look like this\" and made and expansive wave of her hands that took in her body from head to toe. I don\'t know what she was talking about specifically but what she obviously meant was \"when you are an incredibly beautiful woman like I am, the world is different for you\" -- maybe she meant people help you more or that it\'s easier to get things done.\r\n\r\nThe only explanation I have for a rather ordinary middle-age woman saying that is that she used to be incredibly beautiful and her beauty was a huge comfort for her and even an advantage. Things came easy for a beautiful woman like her.\r\n\r\nI found this very poignant because things were not going to be so easy for her in the future.\r\n\r\nBut I found tremendous comfort in the man she was with. He had a light in his eyes that glowed only for her. As long as he loved her, it was obvious to me that he would protect her from the cruel world that throws away roses once they begin to fade. He would keep her safe from harm. Come to think of it, he was probably the reason she thought she was still beautiful -- she didn\'t see herself reflected in mirrors, she saw herself reflected in his eyes.\r\n\r\nFor my part, my heart goes out to the well liked and the beautiful and the haughty -- the people I spent my youth wishing I was like  (and liked by) -- for beautify fades and popularity fades and likewise haughtiness. In the end those people will face a harsh period where they have to work out how to relate to a world that no longer loves them.\r\n','2009-09-19','2009-09-19 17:22:05'),(481,84,'DAM','<h3>Story: Formerly Beautiful Woman</h3>\r\nI was in a hotel at a conference. I was waiting in the bar for some people to meet me for dinner. There was a man and a woman who came in and we had some drinks and talked. She was a middle aged woman, somewhat petite, a little pretty but not beautiful and the years had not been overly kind to her (she wasn\'t old looking but she showed her age).\r\n\r\nAt one point in the conversation she said something like \"when you look like this\" and made and expansive wave of her hands that took in her body from head to toe. I don\'t know what she was talking about specifically but what she obviously meant was \"when you are an incredibly beautiful woman like I am, the world is different for you\" -- maybe she meant people help you more or that it\'s easier to get things done.\r\n\r\nThe only explanation I have for a rather ordinary middle-age woman saying that is that she used to be incredibly beautiful and her beauty was a huge comfort for her and even an advantage. Things came easy for a beautiful woman like her.\r\n\r\nI found this very poignant because things were not going to be so easy for her in the future.\r\n\r\nBut I found tremendous comfort in the man she was with. He had a light in his eyes that glowed only for her. As long as he loved her, it was obvious to me that he would protect her from the cruel world that throws away roses once they begin to fade. He would keep her safe from harm. Come to think of it, he was probably the reason she thought she was still beautiful -- she didn\'t see herself reflected in mirrors, she saw herself reflected in his eyes.\r\n\r\nFor my part, my heart goes out to the well liked and the beautiful and the haughty -- the people I spent my youth wishing I was like  (and liked by) -- for beautify fades and popularity fades and likewise haughtiness. In the end those people will face a harsh period where they have to work out how to relate to a world that no longer loves them.\r\n','2009-09-19','2009-09-19 17:29:53'),(482,90,'DAM','At church Alana was very disturbed. Wasn\'t sex a sin? She hadn\'t gone to confession yet; should she not take communion. But if she didn\'t her father would wonder what was going on. In the end she took communion but she felt extremely guilty. She actually felt dirty and couldn\'t wait to get home and take s shower. \r\n\r\nSunday afternoon Alana was shocked that Lance didn\'t call her. He had never given her his number but she managed to find it in the phone book and called. She was told that he wasn\'t in and left a message. He never called her back. Alana spent the entire afternoon wondering what might have happened. He didn\'t love her any more. He had been arrested. He had been killed. He had to clean the garage. She had hours to come up with every possible -- or impossible scenario. \r\n\r\nShe had trouble sleeping because her mind was whirring. But she got up early because she desperately wanted to get to school and see Lance. ','2009-09-20','2009-09-20 21:32:13'),(483,98,'davemenc','<h3> The Basics</h3>\r\nOk, flock off. There, now I\'ve said it and we can move on.\r\n\r\nI wrote down some notes. For the first time, I think I know HOW to do it. But who\'s got the time...\r\n\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe goal is to generate graphics that look like the way a flock of birds wheels and slides around in the sky. \r\n\r\n<h3> Basic Mechanics</h3>\r\nThe top of a bird should be dark and the bottom light (could be brown, blue, black or it could be much more complicated or even unique to each bird). When birds fly up they expose more of their top to us (assuming we\'re behind them), when they fly down the expose more of their bottom to us. When they turn to the left they bank to the left; to the right they bank left. \r\n\r\nMy big insight is that all of these things can be calculated based on acceleration. Up and down can be calculated from rectangular coordinates but left and right is relative to your line of flight so you have to go to polar and get the angle. \r\n\r\nUltimately, I\'d like the wings to flap naturally -- and while we\'re wishing, let\'s wish for a bird model -- but we could just have two triangles that are attached at the base and simply define the angle every pulse. Up, down, up, down. But initially I\'ll just use two triangles that have a fixed relationship -- 45 degrees or something like that.\r\n\r\n<h3>Algorithm</h3>\r\nThe basic algorithm is to apply acceleration to each bird based on three considerations: \r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Collision avoidance\r\n<li>Out of frame avoidance\r\n<li>Flocking\r\n</ol>\r\nMy thought is to do these three things in reverse order, giving 20% of some maximum acceleration to flocking, 40% to out of frame avoidance (that is, there is a bounding box and all birds try to stay within it) and whatever is left (at least 40%) to collision avoidance. This means that collision avoidance overrides the other two calculations and is therefore effectively of higher priority.\r\n\r\n<h3> Collisions</h3>\r\nCollisions are calculated based on bounding boxes. abs(x1-x2-S)<0 and abs(y1-y2-S)<0 and abs(z1-z2-S)<0 means a collision where x1 is predicted position (current position plus velocity) and S is the size of the bounding box. \r\n\r\nCollisions are handled by taking one of the colliding birds (arbitrarily) and calculating a vector directly away from the other and adding that value to the velocity. \r\n\r\nI was thinking of stepping through the birds, checking collision for current bird against all other birds and if I find one just change the velocity of current bird. Then on to the next bird. This isn\'t very sophisticated and may result in a collision but it\'s simple and will probably work most of the time. The main failure case is that the last few birds in the collection, in avoiding a collision, fly into another bird. \r\n\r\nThe proper way to do it is to keep adjusting and readjusting birds until there are no collisions. This might take a while...\r\n\r\n<h3>Frame</h3>\r\nWith just collision avoidance and flocking there is no good reason why the birds would just fly away, never to be seen again. So we put a bounding box around the flock. The tighter the bounding box the more the birds will have to wheel and turn to stay in it. Of course if it\'s too tight the birds won\'t all fit and there will be more collisions. It should be sized so the birds fit in it, so it\'s centered on the screen and so it\'s up off the ground. \r\n\r\nI was thinking that you test a bird\'s apparent position (add velocity and position) and compare it to the bounding box. See the collision stuff... Then you use the same code to move it back away from the part of the box it\'s in. Figuring out the direction and speed you want to move it might be a tad hard.\r\n\r\n<h3>Flocking</h3> \r\nCalculate the center of the flock and then head every bird toward that center. Since this is only allocated a small amount of acceleration and it\'s done first, it can be simple since collisions will be overridden.\r\n\r\n<h3>Other Issues</h3>\r\nThe main other issue that I see is velocity. No bird can be stopped in air and doing so would look stupid. So you have to make sure every bird has a minimum velocity, even if it hits something. \r\n\r\nLikewise, birds can only fly so fast. So no bird should be allowed to fly faster than a certain speed. \r\n\r\nThus, after we adjust all the velocities but before we apply them we should adjust them to within the proper range. \r\n\r\n<h3>Instrumentation </h3> \r\nInitially I don\'t really want to draw anything. So I want to code this all up and then collect data. This might included...\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>average center\r\n<li>average distance from center\r\n<li>average distance from each other\r\n<li>max distance\r\n<li>count of collisions\r\n<li>max speed\r\n<li>min speed\r\n<li>average speed\r\n<ul>','2009-09-23','2009-09-25 02:12:55'),(484,98,'DAM','<h3>Some random notes</h3>\r\ncal center of flock\r\n	for each bird \r\n		get a vector to center of flck\r\n		scale vector\r\n		apply to velocity\r\n	for each bird\r\n		calc next position\r\n		check for inside frame\r\n		if not calc vector to frame\r\n			scale vector\r\n			apply to velocity\r\n	for each bird\r\n		detect colleision\r\n		if collision\r\n			calc vector away\r\n			scale vector\r\n			apply velocity\r\n			recal bounding box\r\n	for each bird\r\n		apply final velocity\r\n		check for collisions\r\n		check for out of frame\r\n		coalculate flock\r\n	collect stats\r\n	\r\n	---------------------\r\nvector is\r\nRx-Px, Ry-Py, Rz-Pz \r\nwhere Pxyz is the position after velocity and Rxyz is the reference location \r\nThis assumes we\'re going toward the R. \r\nMake them all negative if we\'re going away. \r\n','2009-09-24','2009-09-25 02:20:27'),(485,99,'davemenc','We were kind of talking about the sex industry, and the interesting dynamics that come into play amongst its workers, patrons, and the business in general?','2009-09-28','2009-09-28 21:38:13'),(486,100,'davemenc',' What about BM? I think it would be cool to write about a girl or boy that stumbles upon BM and is introduced to a whole new world that embodies open mindedness, vulnerability, and love.  But through his or her journeys sees the other side of BM, too: sex, drugs, and rock n roll.  And, it is his or her choice to see how to relate and use his or her experiences at BM to the default world.  This one may be hard to capture, but you could gather a lot of evidence from GC\'ers opinions to support what BM is to your main character, and use the GC\'ers personal experiences to give you ideas to write about.','2009-09-28','2009-09-28 21:37:31'),(487,99,'','strippers have a sort of fantasy life about their customers. They find the men who come in kind of attractive and the men certainly find them attractive and this is flattering. They give attention to the customers and get a payoff of interest and, what do you know, money. \r\n\r\nMeantime, the men fantasize about the women. The attention and the affection that the women show them gets translated into some kind of actual sexual attraction or even love. Thus they come back again and again to bask in the fantasy that the girls love them and care about them and even want to have sex with them. And of course they have even deeper more private fantasies that the girls actually are having sex with them. \r\n\r\nThese two sets of fantasies build on each other. Both parties get a lot of pay offs in the short term. But, ultimately both parties can really get hurt. ','2009-09-28','2009-09-28 21:41:58'),(488,18,'Old','\r\nOk, the idea is that we have a really good model of fatigue. People can run, walk, stop, sit, and go prone. Each person runs and walks a particular speed, uses up energy at a particular speed and regains energy at a particular speed. Also, he has a particular observation ability and a certain capability to change state (prone to standing, sitting to standing, standing to walking, standing to running, etc). \r\n\r\nIn sprinting you use anaerobic energy but while you\'re walking you use aerobic energy. So sprinting uses up a small store of energy very rapidly while walking uses up an amount of energy roughly equal to the amount that can be replenished. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, your whole system\'s energy gets depleted after a prolonged period of walking, requiring rest. \r\n\r\nFinally, after a very long time (say, most of a day) you get hungry, thirsty and in need of sleep which further degrades your ability to continue. \r\n\r\nTo summarize:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Energy\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>Short term energy\r\n    <ul>\r\n    <li>Small reservoir (short reservoir attribute)\r\n    <li>Lost extremely quickly while sprinting (sprint short cost attribute)\r\n    <li>lost fairly quickly while running (run short cost attribute)\r\n    <li>lost slowly while walking (walk short cost attribute)\r\n    <li>regained slowly wile walking (walk short generation attribute)\r\n    <li>regained more quickly while standing, sitting or lying down (rest short generation attribute)\r\n    <li>when short term energy goes negative/zero player must stop until he has a positive reserve \r\n    </ul>\r\n  <li>Long term energy\r\n    <ul>\r\n    <li> large supply (long reservoir attribute)\r\n    <li> used moderately quickly while running or sprinting (run long cost attribute)\r\n    <li> used slowly while walking (walk long cost attribute)\r\n    <li> use even slower while standing (stand long cost attribute)\r\n    <li>regained slowly while sitting (sit long  generation attribute)\r\n    <li>regained quickly while lying down (prone long generation attribute)\r\n    <li>when long term energy goes to zero, player collapses\r\n    <li>when long term energy goes negative, player collapses and becomes unconscious, regen at prone rate\r\n    </ul>\r\n<li>Speed\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>Sprinting (sprint speed attribute)\r\n  <li>Running (run speed attribute)\r\n  <li>Walking (walk speed attribute)\r\n  </ul>\r\n<li>Observation\r\n  <ul>\r\n  <li>Observation only affects what you can see\r\n  <li>base observation (observation attribute)\r\n  <li>Range standing\r\n  <li>range sitting\r\n  <li>range prone\r\n  <li>prone, sitting, standing and moving players have different observation modifiers\r\n  <li>distance modifies what you can see\r\n  <li>there may be blocking terrain which prevents you from seeing something  \r\n  <li>moving observers can\'t see as well as stationary observers\r\n  <li>there may be terrain that partially prevents you from seeing something\r\n  <li> observation is a scale of zero to five\r\n      <ul>\r\n      <li>0: can\'t see thing at all, not reported\r\n      <li>1: think 