eaks pretty well in Portuguese. There sexual relationship falls off somewhat but their personal relationship increases. \r\n\r\nIN the end, he moves to Rio and marries her. She continues to do her business and to provide or accept his relationships with ohter woman. ','2009-12-27','2009-12-27 18:43:55'),(577,104,'davemenc','<h2>Chapter outlines</h2>\r\n1) Woman is mad at her lover. Lover cheater on her and she knows it because she saw a text message. She is laying in wait. She is on a hill in SF or Oakland or any place else. Her lover comes by in her car and the woman flag her down. Lover is surprised but not concerned or scared. She rolls down the window and asks what\'s going on. The woman says \"look\" and looks down at something in her hand. When the lover in the car leans out, the woman hits her in the forhead as hard as she can. Then she puts heavy object (a trophy? a bowling pin?something she stole from a roommate no doubt) under the back tire. The car is at the top of a hill facing down. She reaches into the car and unhooks the seatbelt and then puts the car in gear and unsets the break. Finally, she removes the heavy object from the back wheel. Then she moves away at a good pace as the car plummets down the hill. She wipes off the object and puts it back in her roommate\'s room. \r\n\r\n2) The police find the car at the bottom of the hill. They assume it\'s an accident. The woman\'s lesbian significant other comes and identifies the body and it\'s all tears and upset. (But we know that she\'s the killer.) The cops are very sympathetic. Then the autopsy report comes back and says that the big bruise on the woman\'s forehead isn\'t from the steering wheel. They deduce that the car rolled down the hill and find blood at the top on the ground; they deduce something like the actual scenario. The police begin to look seriously at the SO. It\'s all very suspicious.\r\n\r\n3) The murderer is worried that the police figured out it was murder so quickly but relieved that they are looking at the SO. \r\n\r\n4) The police discover that the SO was somewhere else -- with lots of witnesses -- at the time of the death. Her alibi is iron clad. They cast about. One detective looks at her work and talks to various people at the bank -- several of whom are women and look likely. Another looks through the things found on the body and discovers a text message from a lover. They converge on the lover\'s house which is the victim\'s house and the SO\'s house. There were 6 women living in the house (now only 5) and they go right to the woman with the text message they take her into custody but can\'t prove anything so they have to let her go. Then they dump the phone and discover that all 4 of the women in the house were having affairs with the victim. So they get a search warrant -- a dicey thing -- and search the house. They find a blunt object with scratches on it which they think might have been used to block the wheel. They find a bloody rag in the trash. They start to look at the owner of the blunt object.\r\n\r\n5) The murder is extremely worried that they\'ve stopped looking at the SO but somewhat relieved that they are looking at the blunt object owner. \r\n\r\n6) The blunt object has blood on it and is the right shape but has no fingerprints. The owner is the leading suspect but it doesn\'t really constitute proof because it could be anyone in the house. None of them have alibis. All of them have motive and opportunity. It\'s well known that the victim travels that way. \r\nOne of the detectives realizes that the owner of the blunt object is right handed. Detective realizes that murderer had to hit the victim with her left hand. They do tests and what-not and the murderer is DEFINITELY left handed. So the owner is not the murder.\r\n\r\n7) the murderer is extremely distressed to hear about the left/right thing. She is left handed (of course) and her roommate is right handed so she\'s not really scared. She resolves to hide her handed-ness while she thinks of how to escape. \r\n\r\n8) The cops notice that one of the women in the house, although she APPEARS to be right handed, is really much stronger with her left hand. She\'s faking it! AHA, here is our killer! They start looking really hard at her and interrogate  her. But her story is that she was raise by her grandmother who worked hard and long and brutally to get her to use her right hand even though she was left handed. Apparently her gma had been tortured by nuns and thought it was the right thing to do. The police flat out don\'t believe her. They\'re convinced that this is all a lie. But they really don\'t have much hard evidence.\r\n\r\n9)The murderer has bought some time by pretending to be right handed. While the police interrogate her roommate she is frantically trying to figure out how to get away. She takes out all her cash and rents a sleezy room in a crappy hotel in a bad neighborhood. She figures she\'ll be almost untraceable here. But she has to find a way out of the city! But how?\r\n\r\n10) While they are interrogating the roommate the woman points out that the other woman is really left handed. The cops had looked and noticed her doing things with her right hand so if this is true they are back to two suspects again. They go to find her to ask her about this. She\'s gone. Now the man hunt begins. They let the other roommate go and start casting about. They trace the cellphone back to her room, they put a watch on her credit cards and on her other accounts. But they can\'t find her in any of her usual haunts. The case has hit a dead end. \r\n\r\n11) The murderer is in a desperate way. She is living in a real shit box of a room, she\'s being hit up by people who think she\'s a hooker, she\'s eating at a mc donald\'s (she doesn\'t dare move around or spend much money) and she\'s really frightened by her surroundings. She\'s GOT to get out of here. But she only has a few $100 or so. She takes a cab to the bus station and she buys a ticked to Calexico with cash, in the hope that she\'ll be able to loose herself in Mexico.\r\nIt\'s a brutal trip and she\'s exhausted when she gets to calexico. She gets off the bus and is immediately arrested by a sherif who holds her for the sf cops to get. \r\n\r\n\r\n12)The cops were watching the bus, train, airports and ship terminals and spotted her ticket purchase. They were looking for someone who got on a bus and went to a border town, especially calexico. If she had gone to any other city first (say LA) they wouldn\'t have been able to check. As it was, the were notified about the calexico ticket and they interviewed the ticket seller within a few hours and notified the sherrif in calexico. \r\n\r\nAfter the ups and downs of the investigation and the long trip, she admits everything when they final catch her.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2010-03-03','2010-03-04 06:07:40'),(578,104,'DAM','','2010-03-03','2010-03-04 05:31:15'),(579,84,'DAM','The pot of water was at a full boil but ravioli\'s or wan-tons or whatever they were wouldn\'t get off the spoon. Maybe the wrappers were the wrong type or maybe Alice should have put flour on them to keep them from sticking before she wrapped Betty\'s shrimp stuffing in them. For whatever reason every time Betty tried to lower the spoon into the water and drop the wontons into the water, the spoon would come back with the wonton stubbornly sticking to the spoon. \"Damnit, I can\'t get it off the spoon!\"\r\n\r\nChad came over to help out. He started picking the little triangular packets up one by one and gingerly dropping them into the water. Soon most of the wantons were in the water. \"How many will fit in here.\" \"I dunno,\" responded Chad, peering into the boiling pan. \"I think all of them will fit.\" \"Ok, when they float to the surface, they\'re done.\" \"OK, I\'ll watch them\". \r\n\r\nOne by one the transparent dough-wrapped packets came to the surface. Chad removed the first few but they stuck together. That didn\'t seem right to him; cooked pasta didn\'t stick. So he just went with his instinct and put them back in. But not for too long because over cooked raviolis would break apart. So he just watched and removed them when they looked good.\r\n\r\n\"Do you follow recipes?\" Dave asked of Chad. \"Well, yes, actually I do.\" \"I think it\'s much better if you just play it by ear. Just do what seems right.\" \"WEll, I would agree but you have to have experience to do that. I hardly ever cook so I just don\'t have the feel for it that you need. Now, my wife, she can start out with a recipe, be missing 3 major ingredients, make substitutions from leftovers and have it be better than the original.\" Dave smiled. \"Yeah, that\'s mastery. You do have to know what you\'re doing. But the recipe will never be as good as going with the flow.\" \"Plus, my wife is a chemist.\" \"Yeah, a chemist would know how the food cooks. That\'s cool.\" \r\n\r\nBy this time there was a pile of raviolis and a bowl of sauce in front of them so they paused to dish the little packets onto their plates, cover them with sauce and add cashews. \"Man, that\'s really good!\" \"Yeah and they hardly stick at all.\" They both laughed.\r\n','2010-03-04','2010-03-04 15:41:33'),(497,101,'ALM&DAM','This is the right address, right?\r\n\r\nThinking of you\r\n\r\nDave\r\n- Show quoted text -\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n---------- Forwarded message ----------\r\nFrom: auto-confirm@amazon.com <auto-confirm@amazon.com>\r\nDate: Fri, Sep 11, 2009 at 3:01 PM\r\nSubject: Your Order with Amazon.com\r\nTo: \"dave@menconi.com\" <dave@menconi.com>\r\n\r\n\r\nThanks for ordering from Amazon.com! Your purchase information appears below.\r\n\r\nWant to manage your order online?\r\nIf you need to check the status of your order or make changes, please\r\nvisit our home page at Amazon.com and click on Your Account at the top\r\nof any page.\r\n***********************************************************\r\nBILLING AND SHIPPING INFORMATION\r\n*******