eks at a time. So knocking out a few hundred words in an email is\r\neasy.\r\n\r\nThird, I get excited and when I\'m excited I have more energy than the\r\nsun. And, well, I\'m excited by our friendship and so I turn a lot of\r\nenergy toward it.\r\n\r\nSo, you mustn\'t think that you need to keep up. I love to hear from\r\nyou (and, being the sensitive soul I am, I will notice if I don\'t) but\r\nI don\'t take it personally when people don\'t respond to my long,\r\nrambling, run-on messages, that just seem to go on and on and on and\r\non without any end in sight.\r\n\r\nI love to write you but would not want you to feel obligated by the\r\nburden of responding to every single little thing I write.\r\n\r\nLove you and looking forward to seeing you next week!\r\n\r\nDave\r\n\r\nPS and you know how some people just like to hear their own voice?\r\nWell I\'m not particularly fond of my spoken voice but I REALLY love to\r\nread my own writing. Believe it or not, I sometimes just go back over\r\nmy emails to you again and again. Of course, I find myself reading and\r\nre-reading the emails FROM you as well but that\'s kind of\r\nunderstandable -- I mean, I don\'t know what your emails say until I\r\nread them, but with mine I know what they say before I even write\r\nthem...\r\nReply\r\n		\r\nForward\r\n		\r\n		\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\namber morrison\r\n to dave\r\n	\r\nshow details Sep 18\r\n	\r\nNo worries dear.  I can picture you doing that, and I don\'t mind one bit!\r\n\r\nI love our chats, your rambles, your inquisitive nature, and your amor expressed through our e-mails.  I don\'t work as fast as you.  But, reading your emails, and seeing that I\'ve got mail before I read them excites me, too.  I am very happy for our friendship, and admire the person that you are. \r\n\r\nLove,\r\nAmber   ','2009-10-02','2009-10-02 21:18:45');
