er because we love each other. Sometimes that love is an intimate thing and we help each other in very personal, intimate ways (buy food for each other) and sometimes that love is a distant love and we help each other by stuffing a dollar into a cup as we walk by.\r\n\r\nGranted, all those men paid money to see you dance but that\'s different. That wasn\'t helping you, that was a transaction. The clerk at the store doesn\'t give you stuff because she likes you and you don\'t give her money because you like her -- it\'s commerce.\r\n\r\nPlease tell me you don\'t confused commerce with love; it would break my heart!\r\n\r\nAnd this is why I don\'t go to strip clubs any more (oh, yes, I used to). The woman dancing while she looks in my eyes feels like love but it\'s just commerce. It\'s way too easy to get confused and way too painful a mistake to make. Remind me to tell you sometime how they sell trucks in America.\r\n\r\nThere is always the possibility that I misread your text and that you didn\'t mean to imply that there was a \"quid pro quo\" (latin meaning \"this for that\") in those situations. But what I think is that you don\'t THINK there was but that you are AFRAID there might have been. And the fear came across (and you could give me no greater compliment than to show me your fears).\r\n\r\nForget it. If I tried to buy you a camera for a kiss you\'d turn me down flat. I suspect this might be related to why you didn\'t want me to give you a camera -- because gifts sometimes have strings or hidden obligations attached. Or maybe you have your pride and want to prove to yourself that you can make it on your own. (Yes, I read and re-read your answer about the gift but you basically said you hate accepting gifts, not WHY you hate it. )\r\n\r\nBy the way, your aversion to gifts might be perfectly appropriate. If you don\'t want to accept gifts that have strings attached then the trick is figuring out which gifts have strings -- and that\'s kind of hard. \"When in doubt, don\'t\" might not be a horrible rule.\r\n\r\nIf you don\'t want to accept gifts because you want to do it all on your own then I can understand that. I would remind you that none of us can do it on our own and all of us are powerful beings who don\'t need to prove anything so it\'s a dangerous position to take. But sometimes we have to make a stand to prove to ourselves that we really ARE worthy.  This the position I\'ve been in at Burning Man for the last few year but my friends have largely gotten me over it.\r\n\r\nAnd all this is a long winded way of saying that I was troubled by the way you wrote about your boyfriend and your parents. I\'m sure you know that there is love in those relationships but if I say nothing might cause you to think that *I* think agree with the way you wrote it. I can\'t have that; I would never believe it for a second. (Well, OK, I would believe it if you looked me in the eye and told me that\'s the kind of person you are; one has to believe the reality in front of one self.)\r\n\r\nOk, I should get off my ass get some stuff done today.\r\n\r\n\r\nLove\r\n\r\nDave\r\n\r\n\r\namber morrison wrote:\r\n\r\n    - Show quoted text -\r\n    < I will suggest \"improving\" is highly over rated>\r\n\r\n    LOL\r\n\r\n    <Then we stop trying to fix ourselves and realize we\'re not broken. >\r\n\r\n    Wow.\r\n\r\n    < Come to think of it, he was probably the reason she thought she was still beautiful -- she didn\'t see herself reflected in mirrors, she saw herself reflected in his eyes. >\r\n\r\n    OMG.  Any, yes.  I found it incredibly interesting.  You know my beautiful Angelina Jolie look a like cousin says it all the time, which is an extremely harsh reality for her and me to face.  She says, \"one day all this, my looks, will fade.\"  And in her extremely intelligent head I know she is thinking, \"so I better get a man fast or do something with my life.\" She kind of had a nervous break down after she admitted the looks thing to me about three months ago.  Wow, that is so true Dave.\r\n\r\n    Sometimes I think about being the ugly duckling of the bunch (my sister, cousin, and close friends), and am grateful for it.  Because it forced me to be stronger, study harder, play less hard, and not rely on my looks to get the things I wanted as openly as the other girls.  But, I did use my sexyness from an early age to get older boys.  One, I had for three years.  He took care of me, gave me lunch money for school, paid for my SAT test (not my SAT II, which is why I couldn\'t go to a UC school), and my first car so that I could get to college.  I wasn\'t necessarily promiscuous when I learned about the things I could get for being, well, sexy; but, I was \"smart.\"  I didn\'t have money, I wanted better things: better food, clothes, lifestyle.  So I got it.  He even persuaded me or asked me to think about my future, career, life.  He helped get into college.  So, I guess I can relate to that women you met in the hotel with her husband.  And I guess I can relate to others who use their looks to get what they want to some degree.  Aside, my mom did it in the Philippines (how she got my dad, reason I am born; and, reason we are in US and not in the PI, which many other military men did.  Left them there.)  \r\n    Aww.  Got to get ready for work!\r\n\r\n    Love,\r\n    Amber  \r\n    --- On *Fri, 9/18/09, dave@menconi.com /<davemenc@gmail.com>/* wrote:\r\n\r\n\r\n       From: dave@menconi.com <davemenc@gmail.com>\r\n       Subject: Re: Tired\r\n       To: \"amber morrison\" <amberlynnmorrison@yahoo.com>\r\n       Date: Friday, September 18, 2009, 4:59 PM\r\n\r\n       DULL!? No way! I live for conversations like this and, mostly, I\r\n       starve for lack of them. I love you all the more for sharing it\r\n       with me!\r\n\r\n       First off, I find you extremely attractive physically. Put more\r\n       crudely, you have a sexy body (back to sleep Little Head, we\'re\r\n       not going there). 