s them.\r\n\r\n       For me that period was adolescence (well, and maybe some of the 30\r\n       years of \"improvement\") but now that I\'m 50 I feel on top of the\r\n       world with some much in my life.\r\n\r\n       And now that I\'ve gotten here, I\'m not sure it relates to you at\r\n       all. But I found it interesting to write... :)\r\n\r\n       Love you. Counting the days.\r\n\r\n       Dave\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n       On Fri, Sep 18, 2009 at 12:14 PM, amber morrison\r\n       <amberlynnmorrison@yahoo.com\r\n    - Show quoted text -\r\n       </mc/compose?to=amberlynnmorrison@yahoo.com>> wrote:\r\n\r\n           Yeah, a bit.  To be frank, I have always resented my body.\r\n            Not until I was about 18 or 19 did I start switching my\r\n           schema around to a more loving, my body is my temple kind of\r\n           thing.  I think that women, most women that I know who are\r\n           quite beautiful physically, tend to pick at themselves more\r\n           than most men think.  They are not thin enough, not big busted\r\n           enough, ass is too flat, turkey jiggle arms, and the list can\r\n           go on an on.  \r\n           I was always the chunky girl next door, so I picked up on the\r\n           tom boy thing fast so that I could hide my body.  I l-o-v-e-d\r\n           pizza.  I actually used to have a problem with getting bloody\r\n           noses, caused from overexcitement, when my dad or any other\r\n           family member would say, \"pizza hut.\"  I was a cute kid.  I\r\n           have never been skinny and I don\'t think I ever will.  I am\r\n           fond of hatha yoga, Bikram especially, and am a vegetarian on\r\n           most days.  Meaning that I occasionally eat fish, love salmon.\r\n            So, I\'m a pescatarian to be correct.\r\n           And, the scale is most enemy.  I hate, loathe it, and kind of\r\n           crave it in a masochistic kind of way.  Our bodies are funny\r\n           things pe