s him because he\'s\r\nwestern and the israelis hate him because he\'s helping the\r\npalestinians. The US thinks he\'s supporting terrorism. The locals are\r\njealous and think they\'re getting ripped off. The twisty ending is\r\nthat his right hand man quits and starts another construction company\r\nin competion. It thrives for a while and then it runs into trouble but\r\na mysterious third party saves it and this new business begins to\r\nseriously undermine our protagonist\'s business. Eventually, he dies\r\n(he\'s old) and he leaves everything to the guy who is compeition who,\r\nit would seem, had become his rival. The person telling the story\r\ndiscovers that our hero was the mystermious force: he had wanted the\r\nyoung man to take over construction in the region all along but the\r\nhero knew that he couldn\'t just give it to the kid so he created a\r\ncompetition and forced the kid to fight for it.\r\n\r\nSenedipity is about a mysterious consortium that buys two huge public\r\nhousing projects in an eastern city. Everyone is afraid that they are\r\ngoing to get turned out in the street but the consortium, called\r\n\"Serendipity, Inc\" starts renovating the buildings. It creates jobs\r\nfor the tenants and then day care and then schools. It set up good,\r\nsafe high schools and then builds a nearby college. This all spans a\r\nperiod of decades.  In the college they start having very strange\r\ncurriculum in the areas of technology and physics. The prestigious\r\nprofessors begin to leave because they think the college is getting to\r\nstrange but Serendipity just replaces them with graduates from the\r\ncollege itself -- it\'s been bootstrapping this whole time to have the\r\npeople from these housing projects form a kind of self sustaining\r\ncommunity within a community. Now the college starts doing research\r\ninto very essoteric physics, not constrained by any preconceived\r\nnotions or any external rules because they are all funded by\r\nSerendipity and staffed by people who have been raised by Serendipity\r\nall their lives in an environment carefully constructed by\r\nSerendipity. Kind of creepy, no? Turns out the whole point is to\r\ncreate some amazing physics breakthroughs (anti gravity, time travel,\r\nteleportation -- impossible stuff) that Serendipity owns. Out of that\r\ncrazy process they created a whole intellectual culture unlike the\r\nexstabilished academic culture and were able to do impossible things\r\nwith it.\r\n\r\nA woman goes to the railroad company with a proposal. Shortly after\r\nthat she is seen going around to investors with a pitch. The idea is\r\nthat she is going to create a shipping company -- like UPS -- that\r\nships to consumers but that doesn\'t use trucks almost at all. The idea\r\nis that everything is loaded onto trains. She has secured an exclusive\r\ndeal with the railroads and has a bunch of data about UPS shipping and\r\nAmazon sales (it\'s implied that she hacked into those companies to get\r\nthe information) that shows how profitable the whole thing would be\r\nbased on the actual packages that are currently moving in the country.\r\nThe investors are impressed and UPS is scared. They talk to the FBI\r\nand accuse the woman of hacking their servers. Meantime they secretly\r\ngo to the railroads and undercut her deal with a deal of their own.\r\nThe woman\'s deal collapse around her ears; she has been screwed by big\r\ncorporate scull duggery!  Every investor gets back every penny, it\r\nturns out she just made up all the data so the FBI leaves her alone\r\nand she quietly fades away. The deal with UPS and the railroads goes\r\nthrough and millions of tons of carbon doesn\'t go into the atmosphere\r\nthat HAD been going into the atmosphere. We as readers learn that the\r\nproposal she made to the railroad is that they would pay her a hefty\r\nfee to get this whole scam set up sot hat UPS would set up contracts\r\nwith the railroads.UPS would never had gone in that direction without\r\nher but the whole deal is a very sound one AND the direction the\r\ncountry has to go.\r\n\r\nThe Lie: imagine that a woman gets pregnant in high school. The event\r\nis hushed up, she goes to visit her aunt for a few months and puts the\r\nbaby up for adoption. It\'s incredibly painful for a wide range of\r\nreasons but it\'s over. She\'ll never see her baby again so why dwell on\r\nit? She locks away the event so thoroughly that, for her, it never\r\nhappens. She marries a wonderful man and has two wonderful children.\r\nThey are all very close and this closeness is based on never keeping\r\nsecrets, never telling lies. Everyone knows her down to her very soul.\r\nThen (and you must have seen this coming) her kid, now 18, contacts\r\nher. Shows up. Confronts her family. The part that I think is\r\ninteresting here is that she is still the very same person that they\r\nknew before. But, because they thought they knew everything about her\r\nand now they discover they didn\'t, it changes the way they look at\r\nher. Trust is broken. I would write it in such a way that the reader\r\nreally gets her point of view -- she didn\'t lie, she didn\'t hide\r\nanything, this event was literally not true for her any more. But also\r\nget her family\'s point of view. What a wonderful place to put the\r\nreader!\r\n\r\nI could also write about burning man or strippers but I don\'t have any\r\nplot worked out on those. Give me a day or so... :-)\r\n\r\nDo you like any of these stories? I know they are very complicated and\r\ninvolved but a novel is a very complicated and involved thing.\r\n\r\nSo now I have 6 different story ideas. Ideas are easy; writing books\r\nis hard! :-)\r\n\r\nLove you and miss you already (even tho I talked to you just a few hours ago).\r\n\r\nDave\r\n- Show quoted text -\r\n\r\n\r\nOn Mon, Sep 28, 2009 at 12:36 PM, amber morrison\r\n<amberlynnmorrison@yahoo.com> wrote:\r\n> oohhh.  What are you thinking the next book should be?  We we