 Let yourself cry. Be sad. Things are ending\r\nthat you were very attached to and you need to mourn that. Be gentle,\r\nfeel the pain and allow it to move through you. Ultimately resisting\r\nonly traps it inside where it will do more damage. I know this and I\r\nwould not have you in more pain or sadness than absolutely necessary.\r\nThere\'s no need to wallow in it or to recreate it so you can feel more\r\nof it but if you feel bad, you ARE allowed to cry. And you ARE allowed\r\nto call me and tell me how bad you feel. You need to know that.\r\n\r\nBut also know that new things are beginning! Do you know the Easter\r\nStory? This is what it\'s really about: every sad ending has a happy\r\nbeginning associated with it (or as I\'ve heard it said \"every death\r\nhas it\'s easter\"). Your sister may have rebuffed you but there is now\r\na communication channel open. Your old boss fired you and I understand\r\nall the things that means but it opens the door for new and better\r\nrelationships in the future.\r\n\r\nMy heart breaks for you but I know you\'ll be OK in the end. You ARE\r\nstrong, not because of the shell or because you can say \"I\'m fine\"\r\nwhen you heart is sitting in pieces on the table in front of you. You\r\nare INHERENTLY strong. You don\'t have to do anything to BECOME strong\r\nand you sure as fuck don\'t need to prove it to anyone (especially\r\nyourself). You will be fine (actually you\'re mighty fine already but\r\nthat\'s a whole different conversation) and you will be happy again.\r\nAnd you are loved -- by me and by other people, most of whom I can\'t\r\nname.\r\n\r\nLove you and missing you\r\n\r\nThanks for the call!\r\n\r\nLove\r\n\r\nDave\r\n\r\nOh, yeah, I ordered your birthday present. What DAY is your birthday?\r\nExactly? You\'ll get the present in about a week. Hope you like it!\r\nReply\r\n		\r\nForward\r\n		\r\n		\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\namber morrison\r\n to dave\r\n	\r\nshow details Sep 29 (3 days ago)\r\n	\r\nThank you so much.  I am taking your advice, have been from the start.  And, I\'ve seen a major improvement in my outlook and happiness since our chats have started.  You have provided me with more support than I would have ever dreamed of.  You are a dear friend and companion.  I am seeing more clearly now because of you, and constantly remind myself or think about how you and everyone else is a reflection of me.  Oh, how beautiful are the stars at night.  Even if I can\'t see them, I know they are there.  Thank You Dave.\r\n\r\nLoving you each second of the day,\r\nAmber   \r\n\r\nFrom: \"dave@menconi.com\" <davemenc@gmail.com>\r\nTo: amber morrison <amberlynnmorrison@yahoo.com>\r\nSent: Monday, September 28, 2009 4:10:31 PM\r\nSubject: Thanks So Much For the Skype Call\r\n- Show quoted text -\r\n\r\nLovely Amber who lights up my life,\r\n\r\nThank you so much for the Skype call. It was wonderful to hear from\r\nyou and even better to see you. My eyes drank deep and it was lovely!\r\n\r\nI really liked the fact that I could see your face and have some idea\r\nabout what you were feeling (\"I\'m fine\"). I really can feel your pain\r\nno matter where you are but, honestly, I don\'t necessarily know that\r\nit\'s *your* pain I\'m feeling unless I can see you or hear your voice!\r\n\r\nPlease, please share your pain with me. It\'s literally what I\'m made\r\nfor. And I truly believe you will feel better.\r\n\r\nBut knowing that I love you and want all the best for you will also\r\nmake you feel better, I\'m sure.\r\n\r\nListen, my love, I know you are going through a hard time right now.\r\nPlease don\'t be tough. Let yourself cry. Be sad. Things are ending\r\nthat you were very attached to and you need to mourn that. Be gentle,\r\nfeel the pain and allow it to move through you. Ultimately resisting\r\nonly traps it inside where it will do more damage. I know this and I\r\nwould not have you in more pain or sadness than absolutely necessary.\r\nThere\'s no need to wallow in it or to recreate it so you can feel more\r\nof it but if you feel bad, you ARE allowed to cry. And you ARE allowed\r\nto call me and tell me how bad you feel. You need to know that.\r\n\r\nBut also know that new things are beginning! Do you know the Easter\r\nStory? This is what it\'s really about: every sad ending has a happy\r\nbeginning associated with it (or as I\'ve heard it said \"every death\r\nhas it\'s easter\"). Your sister may have rebuffed you but there is now\r\na communication channel open. Your old boss fired you and I understand\r\nall the things that means but it opens the door for new and better\r\nrelationships in the future.\r\n\r\nMy heart breaks for you but I know you\'ll be OK in the end. You ARE\r\nstrong, not because of the shell or because you can say \"I\'m fine\"\r\nwhen you heart is sitting in pieces on the table in front of you. You\r\nare INHERENTLY strong. You don\'t have to do anything to BECOME strong\r\nand you sure as fuck don\'t need to prove it to anyone (especially\r\nyourself). You will be fine (actually you\'re mighty fine already but\r\nthat\'s a whole different conversation) and you will be happy again.\r\nAnd you are loved -- by me and by other people, most of whom I can\'t\r\nname.\r\n\r\nLove you and missing you\r\n\r\nThanks for the call!\r\n\r\nLove\r\n\r\nDave\r\n\r\nOh, yeah, I ordered your birthday present. What DAY is your birthday?\r\nExactly? You\'ll get the present in about a week. Hope you like it!\r\n','2009-10-02','2009-10-02 22:06:36'),(522,101,'ALM&DAM','Writing This Year\r\n				\r\n	[Gmail]/friends		X	\r\n				\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\ndave@menconi.com\r\n to amber\r\n	\r\nshow details Sep 29 (3 days ago)\r\n	\r\nAmber,\r\n\r\nI gather you didn\'t understand what I was saying last night about the\r\ntrap and the bait and all that.\r\n\r\nIn one of my emails, I \"casually\" mentioned that I was going to write\r\nanother novel and that I had a bunch of stories to choose from. I did\r\nthis as a playful little gambit. I expected that you would say, \"Oh,\r\nreally? Tell me about the stories!\" and that would start a discussion.\r\nOf course it was also possible that you would ignore the \"bait\" and\r\nnot spring the \"trap\". In any event it seemed like a kind of fun way\r\nto bring up the subject; more fun than \"hey, let me tell you about...\"\r\nor \"let me ask you opinion\". Besides, maybe you didn\'t want to hear\r\nabout it or give an opinion (yes, I know you love me but you are not\r\nrequired to be interested in EVERYTHING; you\'re allowed to be bored by\r\nsome of this stuff).\r\n\r\nAnyway, that\'s what I did.\r\n\r\nAnd you exceeded my wildest expectations. Instead of just saying, \"oh,\r\nreally, tell me about it\" you said, \"Here are the ideas I came up that\r\nI think would be fun.\" Not just passively hearing the stories but\r\nactively participating in their creation! Not just taking the bait (by\r\nasking) but actually taking the trap, too and driving the conversation\r\nto some degree.\r\n\r\nI really loved that! Let\'s face it, I\'m pretty damn smart (yes, I\'ve\r\ncome to grips with it; I\'m often not the smartest guy in the room, but\r\nI\'m way above average and, even among the geniuses that I work with, I\r\nusually have something useful to contribute) but there you are staying\r\nright up with me! Probably doesn\'t seem much to you because you know\r\nhow smart you are but I\'m always delighted by the evidence that you\'re\r\nat LEAST as smart as I am! I love you so much for that.\r\n\r\nSo that\'s what I was commenting on. Does that sound arrogant? I\r\nhonestly don\'t think it is; it would only be arrogant if I actually\r\nwasn\'t very smart. The vast majority of the world isn\'t very smart and\r\nthey think smart people are kind of tedious and boring. So one has to\r\nkind of \"slow down\" for them to have a reasonable conversation. Just a\r\nfact of life.\r\n\r\nJust as someone with your emotional/spiritual acumen is rare, so is\r\nsomeone with your intellectual power. And beautiful to boot! The\r\ntrifecta! I do love you so!\r\n\r\nChanging the subject slightly, the book I think I want to write this\r\nyear is Serendipity, Inc. It\'s a straight up story about a company\r\nthat appears at every point to be doing one thing (and exactly what\r\nthey appear to be doing changes over time, that\'s a big part of the\r\nbook) but they are really doing something completely different. Most\r\nof the book will be speculation and reaction to every stage of the\r\nplan that the company works through; no one will be able to figure it\r\nout, it will all seem random because no one thinks in terms of 70\r\nyears. I think I\'ll tell it from the eyes of a young man born in the\r\nbuilding just after it\'s bought. Or maybe he\'s 10; I\'m not sure.\r\n\r\nThis story has the advantage that it\'s BIG. I know a LOT of stuff that\r\nhappens and so if I just write what I know about it in enough detail\r\nthat will be the 50K words.\r\n\r\nThe other way to go is to take on a story I don\'t know anything about.\r\nStrippers, for example. And just get stuck with it and see what\r\nhappens.\r\n\r\nSerendipity, Inc is about plot; strippers would be about characters.\r\nI\'d just throw a bunch of women in a strip club and see what happens.\r\nI\'d need you to spend some time explaining to me how strip clubs work.\r\nWho the players are (owner, manager, women, door people, \'tenders,\r\ncustomers) as well as some personality types you tend to see. It\'s all\r\nabout the people but it has to have a credible framework.\r\n\r\nStrippers is risky and scary which is why I want to do it.\r\n\r\nI miss you.\r\n\r\nLove\r\n\r\nDave\r\nReply\r\n		\r\nForward\r\n		\r\n		\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\namber morrison\r\n to dave\r\n	\r\nshow details Sep 29 (3 days ago)\r\n	\r\nNo, Dave.  It\'s not arrogant, it\'s confident.  :)\r\n\r\nI would love to see how the Serendipity plays out.  Physics is a topic that I wouldn\'t be able to teach, but, it is very interesting to learn.  I know I love a good plot in a novel.\r\n\r\nThe stripper thing: we should skype sometime on that one because then you could ask a question, and I could answer.  But, I could tell you the personality types are usually girls who know they are attractive, but have some kind of low self esteem, unless they are on cocaine.  They kind of get by based on their looks.  In other cases they are hustlers and know what they can offer a man; thus, are very confident.\r\n\r\nMiss u too,\r\nAmber ','2009-10-02','2009-10-02 22:07:25'),(523,101,'ALM&DAM','Another Story Idea\r\n				\r\n	[Gmail]/friends		X	\r\n				\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\nDave Menconi\r\n to Amber\r\n	\r\nshow details Sep 28 (4 days ago)\r\n	\r\nAmber,\r\n\r\nHow about this for a plot.\r\n\r\nWe\'re at burning man (not someone but US) in the golden cafe. Everyone is there. We get a few days into building the camp, pretty much a straight up description of what happened in 2009.\r\n\r\nOn Monday, something really bad happens. Say, the chill space comes apart. With people sleeping in it.We kind of assume that there was some stupid mistake made in putting it up. Someone trots out the \"burning man not safe\" saying or the \"safety third\" and we start putting it back together. But then someone notices that some parts were cut (I have to think about it carefully to see how you could get it to come down).\r\n\r\nThere is a kitchen fire. And it smells of gasoline.\r\n\r\nSome of the premium booze tastes like lighter fluid. Because it has lighter fluid in it.\r\n\r\nThe refrigerators go off in the middle of the night and we find them unplugged.\r\n\r\nThe evaps leak -- because someone poked holes in them with a piece of rebar.\r\n\r\nAll this vandalism and sabotage threatens to ruin our experience -- or even get someone serious hurt -- and we have to figure out who is doing it and make them stop.\r\n\r\nI have no idea right now why someone would do that. What would be their motivation? What are they trying to do?\r\n\r\nBut it should be someone in our camp, simply because it\'s a tradition for this kind of \"whodunit\" mystery.\r\n\r\nMaybe it\'s first person with me as the narrator and you are the protagonist who figures it all out.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, through it all we can be doing all manner of fun things; perhaps things we did or things we would have liked to do.\r\n\r\nWhat do you think?\r\n\r\nDave\r\n\r\n\r\nReply\r\n		\r\nForward\r\n		\r\n		\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\namber morrison\r\n to me\r\n	\r\nshow details Sep 29 (3 days ago)\r\n	\r\nWriting about all the things we did at BM would be awesome.  Of course, most of it would be exaggerated.  However, the idea about someone doing that to the camp just doesn\'t seem plausible.  Maybe if it was a set of coincidences then I could imagine it.  But, now I see what you mean: writing about BM is soo hard because we hold it so dear to our hearts.  I am thinking, who would do that? And it definitely hits home.\r\n\r\nI don\'t know.  Maybe the construction idea.  Or, what about talking about BM in a nonchalant kind of way.  Day one, this person did that, we set up this, and person A was so funny because kind of thing.  Day two, we all went out and found this over there and this person did this.  Day three......So that, reader is more a participant than just the reader.  And kind of can see what we all see.  The key here would be to not outspokenly say this is what BM is, just make them feel it.  You are really good at explaining how others feel in the things of I\'ve read, imagine the possibilities and roles you could portray just from our camp. This may be useless, but the idea just thrills me.\r\n\r\nLove,\r\nAmber \r\n\r\nFrom: Dave Menconi <davemenc@gmail.com>\r\nTo: Amber Morrison <amberlynnmorrison@yahoo.com>\r\nSent: Monday, September 28, 2009 8:17:08 PM\r\nSubject: Another Story Idea\r\n- Show quoted text -\r\n\r\nAmber,\r\n\r\nHow about this for a plot.\r\n\r\nWe\'re at burning man (not someone but US) in the golden cafe. Everyone is there. We get a few days into building the camp, pretty much a straight up description of what happened in 2009.\r\n\r\nOn Monday, something really bad happens. Say, the chill space comes apart. With people sleeping in it.We kind of assume that there was some stupid mistake made in putting it up. Someone trots out the \"burning man not safe\" saying or the \"safety third\" and we start putting it back together. But then someone notices that some parts were cut (I have to think about it carefully to see how you could get it to come down).\r\n\r\nThere is a kitchen fire. And it smells of gasoline.\r\n\r\nSome of the premium booze tastes like lighter fluid. Because it has lighter fluid in it.\r\n\r\nThe refrigerators go off in the middle of the night and we find them unplugged.\r\n\r\nThe evaps leak -- because someone poked holes in them with a piece of rebar.\r\n\r\nAll this vandalism and sabotage threatens to ruin our experience -- or even get someone serious hurt -- and we have to figure out who is doing it and make them stop.\r\n\r\nI have no idea right now why someone would do that. What would be their motivation? What are they trying to do?\r\n\r\nBut it should be someone in our camp, simply because it\'s a tradition for this kind of \"whodunit\" mystery.\r\n\r\nMaybe it\'s first person with me as the narrator and you are the protagonist who figures it all out.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, through it all we can be doing all manner of fun things; perhaps things we did or things we would have liked to do.\r\n\r\nWhat do you think?\r\n\r\nDave\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nReply\r\n		\r\nForward\r\n		\r\n		\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\ndave@menconi.com\r\n to amber\r\n	\r\nshow details Sep 29 (3 days ago)\r\n	\r\n<the idea just thrills me.>\r\nWell, I live to thrill you!\r\n\r\nBut my instinct says that, without some kind of overarching plot or\r\nunifying set of events it would actually be boring! I know, hard to\r\nbelieve that burning man could