t and neither one was a stellar\r\nsuccess. Jimmy finished 2 of his three and Wayne finished 3 of his four. They\r\nare actually pretty good workers which is why I helped them get their stuff\r\ndone.\"\r\n\r\nIan\'s face changed from a smile to a look of genuine annoyance. \"Since I\'ve\r\ngotten here, your entire organization has been consumed with squabbling and\r\nback biting. You seem to reward undirected aggression even at the expense of\r\nactual performance. I noticed it almost immediately. I decided that, despite\r\nthe weird atmosphere, it would be easy to succeed here. I worked hard on my\r\nassignments and, whenever I was challenged by my co-workers in any way, I\r\nbacked down. I always ceded to them the best assignments, the good resources,\r\nand admitted that they were my superior in every way. Always in public, at\r\nleast. In private, however, I had a discreet talk with each of them. Each of\r\nthem were willing to give me considerations -- assignments, resources, leads,\r\nwhatever -- in return for support against the other members of the team. By\r\nhelping Harold make Fred look bad, I got a whole file of brand new leads. For\r\nhelping Henry undermine Sue, Henry let me finish his assignment and rack up a\r\nbunch of placements.\"\r\n\r\nIan started to smile again. \"What\'s funny is that you are calling your best\r\nworker out on the carpet -- the one who is doing almost all the work -- because\r\nyou believe he isn\'t going to succeed in this environment. That\'s actually\r\nhilarious!\"\r\n\r\nHarry\'s surprise turned to anger. This piss ant noob was trying to tell him how\r\nto run his business? He was full of shit! Harry knew that his team spent at\r\nleast as much time trying to undercut each other as they did closing placements\r\nbut they still got a huge amount done. That very aggression that caused them to\r\nattack each other was the thing that was needed to get the job done. Recruiting\r\nwas war! You needed to attack the problem and kick ass to get placements and you\r\ncouldn\'t just play games like Ian did.\r\n\r\n\"Ian, you\'re fired! Get your ass out of my office.\"\r\n\r\n\"Ok, boss. I\'m glad we had this conversation because I was going to give you\r\ntwo weeks notice today and now I can just leave. Thanks.\" And with that he tore\r\na few pages from his notebook out and let them flutter to the desk, turned, and\r\nwalked out of the office to say goodbye to his colleagues.\r\n\r\nHarry couldn\'t resist; he picked up the closest piece of paper. It had Sue\'s\r\nname on it and under that it had a list of her assignments over the last few\r\nmonths. Each one had a bunch of marks with a total number. It looked like the\r\nnumber of placements for each of the companies. It was absurdly low. Sue was a\r\nhard worker, an abrasive, aggressive go-getter. No one could cold call a\r\ncompany like she could! Surely she had gotten more placements than this.\r\n\r\nHe looked at the other pieces of paper and found similar stories. Some had done\r\nbetter and some even worse but no one had really nailed their assignments,\r\naccording to these numbers. And he knew they must be wrong because there was no\r\nway that we had done so poorly on the Application Network job or on the\r\nIntegrate Science contract. Those companies had been very satisfied.\r\n\r\nOnly when he had looked at the last piece of paper, the one with Ian\'s name on\r\nit, did he begin to doubt his version of reality. This showed large numbers for\r\nboth AN and IS -- had Ian been carrying everyone else for this past months?\r\nSurely not.\r\n\r\nHarry turned on his computer and called up the commissions. Sure enough, Ian\r\nhad gotten the lion\'s share of all the commissions for the last several months.\r\nWhat the hell was up with that? The weak link was carrying the strong links.\r\n\r\nHarry sat and thought about what Ian had said and tried to fit it into what he\r\nhimself had observed. It began to all fit together. Ian always backed down in\r\npublic but he always seemed to be working some kind of deal whenever Harry\r\nencountered him outside of meeting.\r\n\r\nIt had seemed like Ian was simply a waste of space -- someone who just didn\'t\r\nfit in --  but now Harry realized that he had been undermining the whole\r\noperation since he got there. Back in the good old days there had been less\r\nback biting and more work getting done. Now that Ian was gone, the team would\r\nbe even stronger.\r\n\r\nHarry left the office to make sure that Ian was gone and to call a meeting\r\nwhich would bring on a new and more prosperous period for everyone.\r\n\r\nIt was as if he didn\'t e notice that the placement numbers for the past few\r\nmonths had been hirer than ever before. As if he didn\'t know that the good old\r\ndays had not been all that good.\r\n\r\nReply\r\n		\r\nForward\r\n		\r\n		\r\n \r\nReply\r\n \r\n|\r\nDave Menconi\r\n to amber\r\n	\r\nshow details 11:13 PM (15 hours ago)\r\n	\r\nThe current plan is to rewrite the scene and take most of it, which is just descriptions of events, and rewrite it as the actual  events. So instead of 8 months of work all being recapped in that office, we\'ll see at least some of  the interactions with his coworkers. Then we\'ll have the scene in the office but I\'ll make it much less triumphant for Ian. It will be a defeat for him and the boss will be much more satisfied.\r\n\r\nIt\'s really fascinating how you can take an event and express it a lot of ways.\r\n\r\nAmber: You are wonderful. I love you.\r\nDave: You are too and I love you too.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAmber looked deeply into Dave\'s eyes. \"You are wonderful,\" she breathed. Time stood still. \"I love you.\"\r\nThe light shown from Dave\'s eyes. \"You are too.\" He kissed her, a long slow kiss that built to a crescendo of passion. At length, Dave pulled back and regarded Amber with a loving passionate gaze. \"I love you too.\"\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nConcerned that he didn\'t really believe it, Amber tol