e...She asked him if he would like to go upstairs for 200 hundred more so that they could get more privacy....\r\n','2009-11-03','2009-11-03 23:04:42'),(560,99,'','Bunny stood naked and in front of the mirror and look at herself critically. She wasn\'t pleased with what she saw. She knew that the men at the club liked her, clapped for her, tipped her well and even paid to have private time with her. They were very nice to her and paid her many compliments. But she knew that they didn\'t really know. She knew that she was chubby. She liked her breasts but she constantly battled the fat in her thighs and ass and, especially, her tummy. She just could never really control her weight. And whenever she tried too hard, the weight seemed to come off her tits first. \r\n\r\nHer face was another sore point, in her opinion. She constantly tried to create the kind of smooth complexion that the other girls had but she just couldn\'t seem to manage it. \r\n\r\nShe stood 5\' 10, 120 lbs with bright blue eyes, brown hair flowing down to the middle of her back and long legs for her height. 29-22-28 with C cups and breasts that were all natural.','2009-11-04','2009-11-04 19:44:27'),(561,99,'','Pops and Bunny have a relationship. They cuddle and are quite fond of each other. But they don\'t have sex. They talk about everything and pops is quite fond of bunny. He is incredibly lonely and she is very nurturing and giving. He can\'t figure out what she gets out of being with a 50+ man who is missing some crucial parts. ','2009-11-04','2009-11-04 19:45:51'),(562,99,'','<h3>Characters\' Names</h3>\r\nAndy\r\nBob\r\nCharlie\r\nDave\r\nEarl\r\nFranky\r\nGeorge\r\nharold\r\nJake\r\nLance\r\nManny\r\nNick\r\nOliver\r\nPete\r\nRon\r\n','2009-11-15','2009-11-16 00:24:03'),(563,39,'DAM','Not sure this is a blog article or just a letter to the professor who teaches the lecture series about greek philosophy.\r\n\r\nI know you read a lot. It\'s practically your profession. In fact it\'s probably the part of your profession that you don\'t like as much; you\'d rather be writing. So I\'ll try to keep this brief and, more importantly, interesting. \r\n\r\nI want to thank you for your introduction to Greek Philosophy. \r\n\r\nI liked the being vs becoming part. I can see the river and the water and understand how it can be there and yet always be changing. No problem for me in agreeing that things can be the way they are and the way they appear to be at the same time. I\'m familiar with these concepts. \r\n\r\nAnd when you get to relativism I\'m right there. Not a big fan of the Sophists, they appear to be con-artists and players to me. But I am definitely a relativist. Socrates? Kind of a jerk. Loves to be right and is good at \"proving it\". No wonder they killed the old fool. I would love to write a 1000 words on the personalities of the Sophists and Socrates and how their personalities relate to the personalities of people we see around us. \r\n\r\nWell, it looks like I\'m going to escape my first philosophy class without having to actually examine any of my core beliefs. So long and thanks for all the fish!\r\n\r\nBut, wait, what is that niggling doubt? Don\'t *I* want to be right about things, too? Not so much. NO, no, not like \"I\'m right so you must be wrong\" that\'s not me but what about \"I\'m right so this house won\'t fall down\". Right when it makes a difference to be right? Isn\'t that important? \r\n\r\nSocrates asks questions like \"What is Justice\" and then he parses the supposed yes or no questions and demonstrates that the answerer, who was so confident a moment ago, doesn\'t actually know what he\'s talking about. I find it hard to read. Hard to accept that \"What is Justice\" is a valid question. But if I can\'t accept the challenge to answer a simple question like that, then do I actually know ANYTHING? \r\n\r\nI\'m at Burning Man, a 7 day festival in the desert. I\'ve been building the camp for 5 days and it\'s been sweaty, hard work. I need a shower. But here you only have what you bring and I didn\'t bring a shower. My friends in the \"Black Rock City Canoe Club\" say I can use their \"shower\" which consists of an aluminum canoe sitting just off the street and a pump sprayer. I take off my clothes and get into the canoe (the canoe catches the water so it doesn\'t contaminate the desert -- \"leave no trace\" is a form of absolutism I embrace). I\'m washing my naked self when two young women walk by. Thy are wearing the standard outfit for young women: boots with fur and bikini bottoms; in a wind storm they\'ll put on masks and goggles. Neither I nor they think that almost naked women walking down the street and passing a naked man taking a shower in a canoe is at all odd. Almost anywhere else in the world we would be arrested and charged with something; here it\'s pretty normal.\r\n\r\nThat is an example of relativism in my experience. Hard to apply the rules that exist at your university to that situation. Even if we just don\'t go to the festival we still have to accept that the rules are different there. Absolutism only works if you ignore stuff that doesn\'t fit your ideal.\r\n\r\nAnd yet, even at Burning Man absolute rules apply. If you don\'t drink enough water, you WILL die. If you don\'t stake things done the desert winds will blow it over. A generator caught fire because we tried to start it when it was leaking fuel. \r\n\r\nEven in the life of a Relativist there are still absolutes. At any given moment there is a best things to do at this moment, or, at least, there are better or worse things to do. And what Socrates is trying to do is to figure out what those things might be. Ultimately he\'s trying to figure out HOW to figure those things out. \r\n\r\nAnd THAT\'S what I want to thank you for. Not for Socrates who, obviously, was there long before you came on the scene (and will be there down through the ages long after we\'re both dead) but for presenting Socrates in a way that is accessible to me. Because I may not embrace his philosophy but it\'s important that I understand what his philosophy is. ','2009-11-22','2009-11-22 22:16:59'),(564,84,'DAM','Book IDEA: the economics of spiritualism\r\n\r\nWhat if you could measure the effect of spiritualism? If you measure how often important ideas occur to multiple people at once you can see how enlightened society is at that moment. ','2009-11-22','2009-11-22 22:22:57'),(565,84,'DAM','Lunchtime at Boston Market. I like to get there early and get my food so I can watch the lunch rush. I always get a table where I can see the people waiting for their food. Lunch and a show, if you see what I mean. \r\n\r\nThese two corporate types came in to get a big order. They brought a cart and loaded it with food. They were waiting for more food so I had a good chance to look at them.\r\n\r\nThe woman was young and pretty with blond hair. Nicely dressed. Probably an admin. The guy was a tad overweight, middle aged, wearing jeans and a dress shirt -- corporate uniform for  management -- with a goatee and his hair split down the middle.\r\n\r\nThe woman seemed annoyed that she had to pick up food. The guy was joking with the woman and he was cheering her up, drawing her out of her funk. He seemed comfortable in his own skin. Can\'t imagine he was thrilled to be getting food for the office, certainly wasn\'t his job. It was probably hers. But he was cheering her up. \r\n\r\nSee what I mean? Always something interesting going on. \r\n\r\nA motorcycle guy walked in. He wasn\'t wearing leathers but he had a bald head and a big spade beard like the motorcycle guys wear. He looked pretty tough and maybe not like he was in a good mood. \r\n\r\nAs he stood in line the corporate guy was looking at him with some interest. Maybe he knows him, I\'m thinking. \r\n\r\nThe motorcycle guy has a lot of nervous energy and is looking around. He notices the corporate guy looking at him. \r\n\r\n\"What? Are you looking at me?\" he asks aggressively. \r\n\r\n\"Sorry. I was just admiring your beard.\"\r\n\r\nThe motorcycle guy moves in close. \"What, you don\'t like my beard? \"\r\n\r\nThe corporate guy doesn\'t flinch. \"Actually, I think it\'s kind of cool. I was just trying to figure out how you got that affect. You let it grow out along the jaw. It\'s interesting how you do that.\" He doesn\'t seem to notice that the other guy is annoyed and getting more annoyed. \r\n\r\nThe motorcycle guy gets right in his face. \"I don\'t give a crap about beards. You watch yourself.\" \r\n\r\nThis is the point where the corporate guy should loose his smile and back away quickly. Everyone in the place is watching and they all expect it. Everyone is holding their breath to see what the guy is going to do. Time is frozen. \r\n\r\nHe smiles a big grin. He says very quietly but with a joking tone, \"Got some anger management issues there, big guy?\"\r\n\r\nOnly me and the motorcycle guy can hear it but everyone can see it\'s not the right response. Not the right facial expression, not the right body language. Everyone\'s eyes go wide.  They  mentally lean in closer. The only motion in the place is the manager heading for the phone but it will all be over before he dials.\r\n\r\nThe motorcycle\'s face begins to contort into anger. But the corporate guy smoothly continues.\r\n\r\n\"It\'s OK, I\'m not laughing at you. I\'m laughing with you. I understand. Everyone here is on your side, you know. Some of them don\'t even know it but it\'s true. The people around you are always on your side, brother. How could they not? There\'s only one side and we\'re all on it.\"\r\n\r\nHis face has gone from grinning to sincere intensity but he\'s still speaking very quietly, just to the motorcycle guy. No one else can hear except me. The motorcycle guy has gone from angry to baffled. What nonsense is this guy spouting? \r\n\r\n\"Look, I know very well you could kill me right now and not have a problem with it. But why? What do you get you of it? I\'m not against you. I\'m with you.\" A slight pause. \"Hey, I\'ll let you in on a little secret. Well, it\'s not really a secret, but people don\'t seem to notice. \r\n\r\n\"God loves you. I can prove it, too. Time proves it. I mean there isn\'t really time. It\'s just an illusion. Each instant is just here forever. But we think there\'s time because God destroys every instant and recreates the whole world exactly the way it was but we remember the last instant.\"\r\n\r\nThe motorcycle guy is still baffled but now he\'s curious. \r\n\r\n\"We remember the past so we think it\'s real and we project in to the future so it all seems like it flows but there\'s only ever this instant. Just this point in time.\" He looks at the guy triumphantly but motorcycle guy just looks more confused than ever. \"Don\'t you see? God created this instant. He created you in it. He made you just the way you are, big beard, anger issues, everything. He LOVES you! He must or why create you? He loves you JUST THE WAY YOU ARE! He could choose to leave you out of the instant or change you but he chooses you exactly this way. And if God loves you, well that is good enough for me! I love you too. We\'re on the same side.\" He looks carefully at the motorcycle guy. \r\n\r\n\"So you can kill me if you want. Just remember that God has a choice and he chooses you every instant. You have a choice too. What are you gonna do, brother?\" I could see the tear well up in the corporate guys eyes as he looked the motorcycle guy. \r\n\r\nThe motorcycle guy looks at him for a long instant, many emotions flowing over his face. Bafflement, doubt, then maybe a hint of wonder. Wonder that God loves him, rough and ready motorcycle guy with anger management issues? Or wonder that you would find such crazy people in a Boston Market? I couldn\'t say. After a bit the motorcycle guy turned and, shaking his head, walked up to give his order. Everyone moved out of his way, even though it wasn\'t his turn. Relief washed over the place. No one understood what happened but they\'re relieved that it wasn\'t bad. \r\n\r\nThe corporate guy turned back to the counter and loaded more of his order onto the little cart. \r\n\r\nLike I say, you never know what might happen during lunch rush. ','2009-11-26','2009-11-27 18:44:36'),(566,84,'DAM','Sitting in the airport is no fun. Waiting. Just waiting. A flight arrives and then boards. Very tedius. \"Southwest calling all passengers for Flight 203 for Sacramento. Gate 3. Sacramento. Gate 3.\" \r\n\r\nAnd still I sit here. Maybe I should go to Sacramento. \r\n\r\nThere\'s no one at gate three now because they\'ve all boarded. A man runs up with a guitar on his back and looks at gate 3. He looks at the flight information at gate 3\'s kiosk, looks at his boarding pass and back. Obviously he\'s trying to figure out if he\'s at the right gate -- he knew he was late but he thought there would be a bunch of people. Maybe he\'s at the wrong gate! Seconds tick by. \r\n\r\nMeantime, the crew is getting ready to leave. Have they closed the doors? Can he still get on?\r\n\r\nFinally he moves forward. He doesn\'t come back out so he either made his flight or is sitting on the tarmac crying about the fact that he didn\'t make it to Sacramento. I\'ve been to Sacramento and I think it\'s far more likely that he\'s sitting on an airplane crying that he IS going to Sacramento. \r\n\r\n\"Ashlynn\" the woman calls. She leaps out of her chair to retrieve her wayward child. The child is toddling all over the terminal, always under the watchful eye of her mother. Screaming happily and running this way and that. Her mother lets her wander around but not go too far. \r\n\r\nRight now her mother is with her as she meets a slightly older girl. They stand ten feet apart and stare and stare at each other. Ashley is delighted but the other girl appears to be only mildly interested. Perhaps she isn\'t as outgoing as Ashley. \r\n\r\nAll the other passengers in the waiting room smile indulgently at her as she runs around. They don\'t seem to mind the noise she generates. Perhaps they welcome the distraction. Maybe they wish they could run around introducing themselves to the other children.\r\n\r\nThere\'s a woman across from me who  looks to be in her late 20s and pretty. Well made up. A good looking woman. But what\'s interesting to me about her is her eyes. She looks very sad. She looks like she\'s just lost her best friend or broken up with a boy friend. I could easily believe that she\'s getting on a plane just like in the old song \"Leaving on a jet plane; don\'t know when I\'ll be back again; Oh honey, I hate to go. \"\r\n\r\nI wish I could cross the aisle and sit down next to her. Strike up a conversation. Ask her if she\'s OK. But I really can\'t. Well, maybe I can but I\'m a little worried that she will react badly.  Beautiful women have a tendency to be worried that any approach is an attempt to pick them up and I\'m worried that she will be  guarded. She may even find me creepy. \r\n\r\nBesides, I\'m not sure what she needs right now is confrontation. Here she is sitting in an airport, trying desperately not to cry. Trying to appear just like all the other passengers. Trying not to be sad. If someone walks up and says \"are you OK\" it violates the social contract that says \"I\'ll ignore your stuff if you ignore mine.\" It allows us all to stay isolated from each other, which, for some reason, we seem to like to do. I hate the social contract but I am very sensitive to it in the way that only an outsider who is trying to appear \"normal\" can be. \r\n\r\nSo I content myself, if that\'s the word with such a huge emotional hole in the room, with sending her positive thoughts. Believe it or not, what she really needs is someone who understands -- not understand what\'s wrong but just understands that she\'s upset. It would be better if she KNEW that someone else understands but that would involve all kinds of trust issues. So the best I can do is just know and be happy for her. ','2009-12-04','2009-12-04 22:35:43'),(567,84,'DAM','The airport. She\'s finally made it to the airport. The screaming kids, the stupid music, the crowds. She\'s on time for her flight and so she can just sit down and read her email and maybe forget. Forget what a mess her life has become. \r\n\r\nIt all began to go downhill when her boyfriend moved to San Diego for his new job. It was a problem because she loved him but she had a job of her own. She understood but she couldn\'t leave. So they were trying to do the whole long distance thing. \r\n\r\nThen she discovered that she was pregnant. She wasn\'t ready for this, even if her boyfriend was in town but in this situation she simply couldn\'t see any good way out. She flew down to SD to talk to him about it. She expected that the meeting would be difficult because neither of them wanted this. \r\n\r\nThe met at a restaurant. They spent longer than usual on small talk, the weather, how her flight was, how people they both knew were doing. She was getting up the nerve to tell him. Apparently he got up his nerve faster. \r\n\r\n\"Honey, I\'ve got something to tell you. I know this will be hard but I just need to be honest. This long distance thing just isn\'t working for me. I think we give it a rest; stop seeing each other for a while and see what happens. \" \r\n\r\nNo doubt he thought that leaving the possibility that they would get back together might soften the blow but, on top of not knowing what was going to happen with the baby and relationship it was just another uncertainty on a pile of uncertainties. \r\n\r\nObviously she didn\'t want to tell him about the pregnancy NOW, after he\'s broken up with her. She tried to be strong. She tried to pretend she isn\'t pregnant. How would she act, how would she react? She manages to make it through dinner without crying. She even hugs him before she leaves. \r\n\r\nNow she sees that she was a fool. Who would have dinner with a boyfriend right after he breaks up with you? The normal thing to do would have been to run from the restaurant and never see him again. Her attempt to act normal backfired horribly.\r\n\r\nOf course, what he thinks of her is the least of her worries. What is she going to do? How is she going to cope with this double blow? For now, she just has to sit here and not cry. She\'ll get on the plane and go home and then -- what? Can\'t worry about that now. Just don\'t cry...\r\n\r\n\"Do you want to talk about it?\" The voice next to her startles her and she jumps a bit. \r\n\r\n\"What?\" she says, mostly to hide her surprise.\r\n\r\n\"I couldn\'t help but notice that you seem to be sad. Would you like to tell someone about it? Or is knowing that someone cares enough?\"\r\n\r\nShe didn\'t know what to say. \"What? Who are you?\"  She got control of her thoughts. \"Look, I appreciate your concern but I\'m fine, really.\" \r\n\r\nHe looked at her and smiled. \"Yes, you\'re OK now. I\'m glad.\" And he walked away, just like that. \r\n\r\nOf course, nothing had changed. She was still pregnant and the father had still broken up with her, leaving her to do what needed to be done all by herself. And she still didn\'t know what that was. \r\n\r\nBut somehow it didn\'t seem all that impossible any more. She WAS OK, now. Who WAS that guy? She looked around for him but she couldn\'t see him. \r\n\r\nShe did notice a little toddler running around under the watchful eye of her mother, screaming with delight and trying to meet everyone and get into everything. \r\n\r\nHmm, maybe she knew what needed to be done, after all. \r\n','2009-12-04','2009-12-05 15:58:45'),(568,40,'DAM','<h1>Collectors Game</h1>\r\n<h2>Basic Idea</h2>\r\n<P>The basic idea of the game is that you have a bunch of objects and you try to collect them and then turn them in as sets to make money. \r\n\r\nThe objects have a color and a size and a \"form\" (like a rocking horse or a chair). An object is worth one but two objects that match in one attribute is worth more. The formula is <set size>^(1+<number of attributes that match>), that is, 2 objects that match in one attribute are worth 4, in 2 attributes 8 and in 3 attributes 16. 3 objects are, respectively, worth 9, 27 and 81. And so on. \r\n\r\nI\'m thinking that there are 5 forms, 5 colors, 5 sizes for a \"deck\" of 125 objects. \r\n\r\nThe main mechanism of the game is an auction that everyone participates in. The players are given some money and and objects (say $20 and 5 objects) \r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Modeling</h2>\r\nIt occurs to me that I could model this game with cards. The idea would be that you have cards that have each color, size and form of object and then you put your cards up for auction. \r\n\r\nEach card would have something that tells what it is (text at first, graphics later) plus 2 rows of numbers from 0-9. Each turn we lay out some cards that the \"system\" is putting on auction. Then players can put cards on auction, too. Each player has colored beads and he puts his colored beads on the card to show his bid for that card. There is no real order but we might make each person do one bid on each card. \r\n\r\nAlternatively, each person has colored markers with values. Or colored markers and money. You indicate your bid by putting money on it and putting your marker on the money. \r\n\r\nAny sets that are played the \"game\" automatically bids the value for that set. \r\n\r\n<h2>Auction Database</h2>\r\n<Venue \r\n  venuid\r\n  venuname\r\nauction\r\n  \r\n\r\n','2009-12-10','2009-12-10 15:33:36'),(569,84,'DAM','Saturday we had our usual games party. All the regulars were there and there were some new people. Alan, for example, brought a woman he knows named Betty. She brought a bottle of wine which was something of a problem because, as a rule, we don\'t allow alcohol at our games party. Drunkenness doesn\'t really add anything to the experience and, anyway, you never know who is going to show up so it is wise to be careful. \r\n\r\nThe party went very wellk but it lasted past midnight and we were all exhausted. WE barely made it to be bed and then it seemed we needed to get up for church on Sunday. The sermon, as sermons are wont to do, ran late. By the time the congregation trooped out to lunch, it was already one PM. Of course eating with a big group always takes longer so we didn\'t get home until almost three. \r\n\r\nAt 4 we had to go to a Christmas party that involved bringing gifts that are put under the tree which are then pick out at random. People steal each other gifts and the unwrapping and the stealing continues until everyone has a gift and then everyone goes home. We hadn\'t had a chance to get the two gifts we needed and there was that bottle of wine so we put it in a gift bag and left. On the way we picked up some food to share and a gift card at a grocery store and we were all set. \r\n\r\nThis party was put on by a Carl who doesn\'t come to our games party or, as far as we are aware, know anyone who does. Two entirely separate groups, one on Saturday, one on Sunday. \r\n\r\nWhen we got there we put our gifts under the tree and bustled about putting our food out. When we finally settled down to see who was there we discovered that Betty was there! She apparently knows Deborah (whom we don\'t know) who knows Carl from the bank he frequents. What a small world. \r\n\r\nWe tell the story to various people while we are there: \"Isn\'t it odd! Betty was at our party yesterday  and here she is at Carl\'s party today!\" Everything thinks it\'s pretty funny.\r\n\r\nEveryone picks a number and then, in order, picks a gift from under the tree or steals a gift that has already been unwrapped. There are many amusing moments as a cherished gift gets stolen or a hated gift is passed over once again. Finally, someone picks up the bottle of wine. WE have no idea of our danger. \r\n\r\nWhen the bottle is unwrapped the wine is displayed for all to see. Of course, there is no tag on the gift so no one knows who brought it but we are pleased as \"our\" bottle of wine is showed off with some tiumph; apparently it\'s a fine bottle of wine!\r\n\r\nThen our pleasure is destroyed at a stroke as Betty points to the wine and says \"That looks just like the bottle of wine I bought yesterday. Isn\'t that an odd coincidence!\" Then a light dawn on her face and she looks over at us. Her tones of wonder change to accusation as she says, \"I gave that bottle of wine to you at your party yesterday!\" \r\n\r\nNow everybody is looking at us. We\'ve been caught regifting which, while not exactly a social crime, is somewhat embarrassing. And it seems that Betty is very offended by it. \r\n\r\n\"Oh,\" I stammer, \"yes, we liked the bottle you gave us so much we got another one to bring to this party.\" I\'m hoping that this somewhat obvious lie will allow everyone to save face and save the party. \r\n\r\n\"How odd,\" says Betty coldly, \"I bought mine in the wine country north of San Francisco. We\'d just come from there when we arrived at your party. They told us it was available in stores yet.\" She paused dramatically, \"Did you go up to the wine country today?\" ','2009-12-20','2009-12-21 00:53:44'),(570,93,'DAM','','2009-12-23','2009-12-27 19:46:07'),(573,96,'DAM','One day her husband insists on telling her some dark secret from his past. He\'s divorced, he has a hairlip, maybe he started dating her before he broke up with his previous girlfriend.Something he\'s afraid she\'ll dump him for and maybe it\'s pretty bad. But she loves him and she believes he won\'t do it again (sleeping with another woman would be good but that\'s a bit too much -- maybe with some mitigating circumstances or maybe he didn\'t actually sleep with her, but would have except for some intervening event). Anyway, it hurts but she forgives him.\r\n\r\nHe gives some speech about how important it is that they be honest and how he hopes she will be honest with him. \r\n\r\nHis example perhaps should show her that she needs to tell him about the pregnancy but what he did was sleezy and indicates a poor character while what she did was simply an accident that she handled as best she could. Her thoughts are \"OF COURSE he should tell me about that, it happened right under my nose and it was a major betrayal. My little secret is over, it happened before we met and I did\'t do anything wrong, I didn\'t betray him, I don\'t need to be forgiven. It\'s not the same.\"\r\n\r\nBut from then on, he constantly harps on the theme of \"we have not secrets, we tell each other everything, we know everything about each other\". It\'s not quite that he keeps bringing it up non-sequiter but circumstances keep coming up where the issue of honesty arrise and he always goes there. A friend asks advice about his girlfriend in an issue where the friend could maybe not fully disclose events but our guy says \"no, you should tell her everything; look at us we have no secrets and we are very happy together\". Or their kid gets caught lying and he tell the kid \"no, you should never lie. Your mother and I have no secrets and...\" Or some politician gets caught and there\'s a big scandal about the coverup: \"I just can\'t understand how someone could betray our trust like that; I thought he was a good guy. I\'m sure glad I don\'t have anyone around me...\"\r\n\r\nDon\'t go too far. The point is not that this is an important thing to him but merely (\"merely\") that he believes they are completely honest with each other. \r\n\r\nShe never lied about anything to him, she just left out one event in her life. And yet to him it will be a huge betrayal and we need to make it clear why. ','2009-12-28','2009-12-28 09:40:13'),(574,95,'DAM','WHY I LOVE REBAR\r\n\r\nThis is a piece of rebar. It\'s used for reinforcing concrete. Why, you might ask, would Dave Menconi, software engineering manager and all around bon vivant, care about rebar? Do I have a secret life in construction? \r\n\r\nIn a manner of speaking, I suppose I do. This is a story about burning man, a festival in which we build a city in the desert in an environment so harsh that we practically risk our lives to go. \r\n\r\nThe first day usually looks something like this.  <empty>\r\n\r\nThis is a view from the air a few days later. <BRC> this is a city of 40,000 people, mostly assembled in 3 days, which has to brave high winds for 7 days and then be removedc and packed up in such a way that it leaves no trace. Setting concrete would be too slow \r\n\r\n','2010-01-03','2010-01-03 17:20:35'),(575,97,'DAM ','<h2>K-Clusters</h2>\r\nIn this algorithm you pick some points at random and then cluster objects in to groups based on which point they are near. Then you take the average location of each group and re-cluster using those locations. Keep doing this until \"some criteria\" is met, presumably until everything is stable. \r\n\r\n<h3>Problems</h3>\r\nThe main problem with this is that you will get different groupings with the same data and this is a big problem because you can\'t tune other parameters. \r\n\r\nAlso, the number of groups are based on the number of points you pick initially and this might not be optimal. \r\n\r\n<h3>My Algorithm</h3>\r\nTo find the initial cluster centers, look at each object. If there are no cluster centers, the location of the object forms the first. Otherwise, if the location of the object is closer to an existing cluster center than X, ignore it. Otherwise, make a new cluster. \r\n\r\nThis is basically the same way we create the initial drinks under \r\n\r\nNow you have the list of the starting clusters. Add each object to it\'s closest cluster point. Then find new cluster points based on the averages of the cluster points, just as in the original.\r\n\r\nWhen you have your final groups, count how many groups. If it\'s greater than the terminal number (5 is a good number), eliminate groups and do the whole thing again. \r\n\r\nThe groups you eliminate are the smallest groups. COunt how many objects are in each group and then remove all those groups with the smallest count. The remaining group centers are the new group centers and you recalculate the whole thing again (including the test for how many groups and so forth). \r\n\r\n','2010-01-27','2010-01-28 20:29:43'),(576,84,'DAM','The party was an odd one. A dinner party in which the attendees were asked not to say whether they were coming or what they were bringing. \r\nThis was OK with Alan. He understood. He\'d known Betty for some years and he admired her spirituality. He even admired her lack of logic. And he was sure that there would be an interesting mix of people present. People who who were spiritual, he hoped. He had met some fabulous people at Betty\'s house in the past and it had a fabulous view of San Francisco, sitting, as it did, on Potrero Hill. \r\n\r\nAnd this time was not exception. It was after dinner that Carol had come over to talk to him. Alan found Carol interesting because she was a body person. Alan himself was a mind person. That is, he addressed his surrounding though the use of his intellect. He thought it would be good to rub elbows with people with different perspectives and Carol would be the ideal person. Alan had a hard time with his body; it always seemed to want to give out just when he was getting going. Sleep, food, bathroom breaks, it was always demanding something. \r\n\r\nWhen he was younger he had not given in. but as he got older -- not just more mature emotionally but older physically with all the aches and pains that brings -- he had come to realize that he needed to make sure that the needs of his body were met. He needed to be more in touch. \r\n\r\nAlan  knew that a body person like Carol would not think much of his mind-oriented approach. Just because he was becoming more open to other points of view didn\'t mean that other were more open to his. \r\n\r\nSo he was not surprised when she said, \"You need to think less.\" This was the standard formulation of the dismissal of intellect. \"That may be true but thinking has it\'s uses.\"\r\n\"Like what?\" \r\n\r\n\"THis is a deep and serious question so let me answer at length, OK?\"\r\n\r\nCarol nodded. \r\n\r\nI was born in Santa Rosa, a few miles to the North of here. My father was born right here in San Francisco and I spent several days each year here visiting relatives. I am a second generation native Californian and San Francisco is important to me. \r\n\r\nI suspect that when you see an image of the Golden Gate bridge you think of it as marketing, as some sort of tourist device to make get excited about coming to San Francisco. But for me it\'s an icon, like an ahnk or a cross. When I see the Bridge my breath catches and I\'m reminded of everything I love about California and the heart of NorCal, San Francisco. To me it\'s a gateway both over the water and through the water. It represents connection and attachment. \r\n\r\nWhen you stand on the porch of this house, you can\'t actually see the bridge. You can only see a single upright, painted it\'s bright red. When I see that, my mind\'s eye can construct the whole bridge. It\'s as if I\'m seeing the whole bridge. But it\'s more than that. It\'s as if I\'m seeing all the things the bridge means to me, heart, home, family, belonging, being part of something greater than yourself. \r\n\r\nAnd it can go the other way, too. When I see a rose I see the inherent beauty of the physical rose, the pretty shape, the color, the delicate texture, just like anyone else. But I also see lots of things that are hidden. The internal reproductive organs and the  I can see all the parts of the rose, take it apart in my mind and lay the pieces out and marvel at the ordered way they go together. For me there are several layers of beauty there. \r\n\r\nAnd it goes both ways. I can think about how the bridge is built even as I see what it means and see the rose in the context of other flowers and it\'s relationship to the animals it supports and the way it evolved. \r\n\r\nJust knowing all this stuff is useless, less than useless as it can distract. But allowing it to inspire awe and inform my spiritual and emotional experience is incredibly valuable. \r\n\r\nAnd I\'m not the only one in the room who does this. You all do the same thing. When you see a rose you remember the roses you gave your mother and the smell of your corsage at your first formal dance. You are aware of the structure of the rose and it\'s relationship to you and your life, just as I am aware of this body I inhabit. \r\n\r\nThe only difference is that I have spent a lot of effort to become really good at the mental part while neglecting the physical. And, perhaps, you have put more effort into the physical than the intellectual. \r\n\r\n\r\n','2010-02-28','2010-03-01 04:26:22'),(571,90,'DAM','The day before the deadline, Alana got to work about 1 PM. One of the guards in the lobby opened the door for her, as usual. And, as usual, YYY wasn\'t back from lunch yet. Alana didn\'t mind because YYY got her anything she needed; what if she took long lunches? \r\n\r\nNext to the door to the lab there was a coat rack with lab coats. Alana took hers, as usual and clipped her badge to the pocket. Then she walked over to the door and swiped her card, as usual. \r\n\r\nBut this time the door didn\'t open. She swiped it several times but it still didn\'t open. She actually checked her cellphone to see the date: yes it was the day before the deadline. She shouldn\'t be locked out, it must be a mistake. \r\n\r\nShe called the head of security on YYY\'s phone. \"I\'m sorry, Dr. Perez, but Mr. ZZZ asked us to lock you out of the building. You shouldn\'t even be here. I\'m sending someone over to escort you out.\" And then he hung up the phone. \r\n\r\nAlana was stunned. Apparently Mr. ZZZ had jumped the gun by a day. \r\n\r\nIf Alana had been more experienced in the 