ging, I could get a job as an actress easily but acting jobs are hard to find. So I got a job as a waitress which, eventually, turned into a bartending job. Have the actors and actresses in this town are bartending \"until they hit it big\". I think they only gave me the job in the first place as \"eye candy\" in the place, making me wear \"the uniform\" -- slacks and a man\'s shirt and tie but insisting that I wear tighter pants and shirt so that my \"assets\" would show through. \r\n\r\nAt least Mr. Fox didn\'t want to know about my assets. He asked questions about my computer skills and my experience in an office. It didn\'t seem to matter that I wore the outfit from work (didn\'t have time to change and, anyway, I don\'t have much of a wardrobe). It all worked out -- I got the job. And it seems like there are flexible hours so I can work it in with the bartending job. I just hope there are enough hours...\r\n\r\n<h3>Dorthy</h3> \r\nI don\'t know why everyone says that economy is so bad. I never have trouble getting a job. You just show up in a short, tight skirt and a sexy blouse, smile like a fool when you meet the boss -- it makes \'em all tingly -- and then cross and uncross your legs a few times during the interview. It doesn\'t matter what I say or how much experience I have, I always get the job. And Foxy Fox was the same as always. He went for it. Of course, it\'s only a part time gig but I\'ll keep looking. It\'ll be easy.\r\n\r\n<h3>Ethel</h3>\r\nEvery year it seems to get harder to be a personal assistant. Two years ago I was assistant to a VP. Then I had to settle for a job with a director. Now, this guy is just a manager (SENIOR manager, he says). Someone with my experience, you\'d think I\'d be working for a CEO by now! \r\nI sometimes wonder if it\'s just an age thing. Maybe the senior management want top surround themselves with pretty young girls and the junior guys have to settle for older women like me. That\'s a pretty sexist thought. \r\nAnyway, I need the money so here I am. Only part time but maybe I can push it toward a full time gig.\r\n\r\n<h3>Frank</h3>\r\nI sure hope this is worth it. I went through dozens of resumes to find someone for this admin job. Well, several someones, actually. I hope having 5 women all working for advancement will be worth the effort. I think it will. After all, by giving each of them only 1/5 of the salary they usually get, each will want to work very hard to please. \r\nIt was a little hard to see this to HR; of course I pitched it in terms of flexible hours and the difficulty of getting any one person to work 50 hours a week. I hope they don\'t go and interview the girls themselves; they almost never talk to contractors so I\'m probably OK.\r\n\r\n','2010-03-11','2010-03-11 16:37:37'),(582,90,'DAM','How does Alana get the mountain man out of the hospital? We don\'t want him awake.\r\n\r\nFirst principals\r\nBy the time he gets into bed, he\'s fine. When the current nurse goes off shift (midnight?)the guy has been all patched up and has a few hours sleep. He still has a bunch of drugs in his system so he\'s groggy.\r\n\r\nShe removes the drip in his hand, and then dresses him in some kind of clothes that look like street clothes. Then she slaps him awake and gets him to groggily get into a wheel chair. She wheels him out.\r\n\r\nWhat about the nurse? What about security? how does she avoid getting caught? Where does she get the wheel chair (ok, she steals that at the hospital). \r\n\r\nNow she loads him into the truck (once again slapping him awake) and drives. He doesn\'t see anything. \r\n\r\nThen she has a really bad night with him, as previously documented. Then, when he wakes up, he\'s much weaker and she takes more time to explain everything to him.\r\n\r\nWhen you need to go, and someone helps you to a seat with a hole in it, very little explanation needs to be made. \r\n\r\nHe is ambulatory but just barely and only because to stop moving will normally mean death to mountain man. so he\'s used to this.\r\n\r\nMaybe add some dreams or reminisces about past situations he\'s found himself in. \r\n\r\n','2010-03-21','2010-03-21 23:20:15'),(583,84,'DAM','I have two feet but only one shoe\r\ntwo shoes but only one foot have you','2010-04-06','2010-04-06 15:19:28'),(584,84,'DAM','<h3>Talk About Me</h3>\r\nI wasn\'t always the confident person you see before you. \r\n\r\nI was a catholic boy and was in the tender care of nuns when I was young. I have a dim memory of having my hand hit with a ruler: \"Hold out your hand!\" SMACK! OW!\r\n\r\nThe nuns were an odd bunch, always into discipline and using extreme means to keep the kids in line. We lived in awe and fear of the nuns. I remember seeing two 8th grade boys, close to 6 feet tall, towering over little Sister Evelyn who was maybe 5 feet tall. They were cowering even as they towered. She was wagging her finger at them and they were hanging their heads and looking sorry and contrite. \r\n\r\nI knew there was a god but it didn\'t seem very likely it was the god the nuns taught me about. They\'re god put me here on earth to test me and if I failed would punish me. This sounded a lot more like a nun than a god, to be honest. Always testing and punishing. \r\n\r\nBy the 8th grade I was pretty much an outcast. I was one of the smart kids. I did my best in school and tried to follow all the rules and always did poorly in sports and all the other kids seemed to hate me, but I had no idea why. \r\n\r\nThere were other outcasts, bad boys mostly, but we didn\'t spend any time together. I didn\'t like them and they didn\'t like me. \r\n\r\nIn the 8th grade Catholic kids go through Confirmation which is sort of like a bar-mitzvah, if that means anything to you, except that you don\'t come of age. But it is the time when you affirm you faith for yourself. \r\n\r\nI declined this honor and simply refused. This was allowed and I was kind of surprised that no one took me aside and tried to convince me I should go through with it. The week before the actual confirmation ceremony they had a practice session at school. Of course they didn\'t let me watch -- the nuns were probably making one of their tiresome little points -- so I found myself sitting outside the church on a little bench. And someone else was there as well. Who else didn\'t get confirmed? Well, it was Jim Evans,  the baddest of the bad boy outcasts. I looked over at him and thought, \"Holy crap, how did I find myself on a bench with HIM!?\" And I could see in his face that he was thinking EXACTLY the same thing. \r\n\r\nYears later my mother told me that she was convinced that the only reason I had failed to get confirmed was because I was influenced by Jim Evans. As if!\r\n\r\nBut I desperately wanted to belong. They kids at school wouldn\'t let me belong to anything. I could have become a Catholic but that was the nuns let me in and, Catholic or not, the kids still wouldn\'t have accepted me. \r\n\r\nEventually I found a little church that I hung out with. I was a seeker, trying to improve myself, get fixed and become enlightened. I didn\'t know what that meant but it sounded good. I guess I thought that if you were enlightened all the other enlightened people would accept you.\r\n\r\nThe church was run by a guy named Bob-- Archreverend Bob to you smucks -- and he really knew his spiritual stuff.  It seemed I could never quite get the answers right and I was really desperate belong so I tried so hard. \r\n\r\nOf course that was part of the problem. You can\'t struggle your way to enlightenment, whatever the heck enlightenment might be. Even I know that much. \r\n\r\nThen the church, and it\'s head, began to dabble in computer stuff. By this time I had been working as a professional software engineer for more than a decade. Naturally, I wanted to help. But I soon discovered that, like everything else in the church, I didn\'t have the right answers in this, either. \r\n\r\nHang on, if I\'m an world class expert in software development, working in the Silicon Valley for god\'s sake, how can I not have the right answers. I began to suspect that, just as the nuns presented god in their own image, Bob was kind of presenting the truth that he liked best. \r\n\r\nI finally got it. Yep, I realized that \r\n\r\n','2010-04-07','2010-04-07 23:39:24'),(585,84,'DAM','an arcane brotherhood takes over the government through the use of magic. In addition to defeating the military they put a bag of powder in front of every person\'s house known to have above average intelligence. The group traditionally known as \"the intellectuals\". \r\n\r\nAlan has a bag of powder in his possession that\'s actually good and in it is a stone of positive energy. Recognizing that the bag of powder in front of his house (it looks like oregano) is going to cause a plague in his houshold that will kill his wife and children (not to mention Alan himself), he put the stone in the bag, confident that it will counteract the plague, even though he has no way to know this. \r\n\r\nThe resulting explosion stuns him and destroys both the bag of plague and the positive energy stone and now can\'t find his bag of good powder (don\'t know if that comes into it or not). \r\n\r\nAfter the revolution succeeds, a representative (Bob) of the new governing cabal visits Alan. They wanted him dead like all the other top people in society so that they could have his land and have him out of hte way. \r\n\r\nAlan points out that he is not a threat to them, that he\'s a loyal citizen of the new regime and that they can afford to leave him alone now that they have absolute power. Perhaps he teases Bob gently \"I for one, welcome my new overlords. Congratulation on you richly deserved rise to power. What kind of government will you put in place? Some for me of representative democracy, perhaps?\" \r\n\r\nBob issues dire threats against Alan but goes back to his colleagues to consult with them about what should be done. \r\n\r\nEventually they decide to make Alan the head of the secular government. They have him write a constitution -- anything he likes as long as it preserves all their power, land and wealth while preventing them from having to pay taxes, or do anything for society. The constitution he writes creates, essentially, a 2 part society. The cabal is completely protected from everything -- no laws apply to them, they don\'t have to give up anything or do anything. All other citizens are subject to the normal rules that society has -- laws, taxes, drafts, etc. Although the government he puts in place is a republic, Alan himself is a virtual dictator. All other governmental bodies essentially are his assistants. He is subject to a vote but can choose to ignore it at his sole discretion. Most of the government is elected but he appoints the key elements -- the prime minister, the president, the supreme court, etc -- and can veto their laws with no override. \r\n\r\nThis may seem like a betrayal at first but remember that every single person of any skill or power or standing in terms of governance has been killed. He has trouble finding people to appoint. \r\n\r\nHis goal, then, is to rebuild the body politic, in his lifetime, to the point where it can wrest power from the cabal in the succeeding generation. ','2010-04-25','2010-04-25 17:01:51'),(586,84,'DAM','','2010-04-28','2013-02-19 00:25:42'),(587,95,'DAM','<h2>SCIENCE</h2>\r\n(for kids)\r\nHi, my name is Dave Menconi. Your teacher has asked me to tell you about science. \r\n\r\nWhat a huge subject this is! Where does one begin? It\'s like she asked me to alk about the whole universe or generally about cars or maybe about sports. I mean, Where does one begin?\r\n{thoughtful pause}\r\nWell, maybe sports wouldn\'t be too bad. I mean, at any given moment there\'s usually only one main one going on. Like right now it\'s baseball season. And most people are only interested in a few of the many teams. A\'s fans? Giants? \r\n\r\nIs there anyone here who has NEVER been to a baseball game? Anyone who has no idea how baseball is played? \r\n\r\nImagine someone like that going to a baseball game for the first time. Wouldn\'t they be bewildered? Some guy throws a ball at a guy with a bat and the guy with the bat either hits it with the bat, swings at it but doesn\'t hit it or does absolutely nothing. In each case, different things happen for no apparent reason. He might hit it but not move or he might hit it and run like his life depended on it. \r\n\r\nAfter a while, through several batters and several innings (we know they\'re called innings but he wouldn\'t) some patterns might emerge. \r\n\r\nEventually it will become clear that going past all the bases and coming back home is the point of the game. ANd that hitting the ball is often the best way to do that. The first time you see a home run it will be pretty clear that this is a good thing for the batter and that he wants to do that more and that the pitcher is trying to prevent it. \r\n\r\nBut there will still be a lot of questions. How would you ever figure out about balls and strikes. Sometimes the batter refuses to swing and gets a strike and sometimes he refuses to swing and gets a ball. A insightful observer might guess that the difference between a ball and strike might have something to do with where the ball went. One might guess that and then watch more carefully and confirm it through observation. \r\n\r\nBut I digress. As I say, I\'m not here to talk about how to figure out baseball but about science which is a method for figuring out the universe. Baseball was invented in {insert history info here} and it\'s inventor was happy to tell anyone who would listen how to play. But the universe came into being {insert history info here} and however that happened, no one left a manual lying around. \r\n\r\nBut now that you mention is, science works pretty much the same way I\'ve been describing in our baseball game. Our clueless fan was doing exactly what scientists do. First he watched until he noticed some patterns. Then he made guesses (in science they don\'t use that word -- they call them hypotheses -- but they\'re really guesses) about might be going on. Finally, he watched some more to see whether he was right or wrong. \r\n\r\nIn baseball all this might happen on a sunny afternoon. But in Science it can take hundreds of years. \r\n\r\nWhen Isaac Newton published his great work The Calculus in which he described how the heavens moved and invented a new form of mathematics to describe it, he said he had been standing on the backs of giants. He meant that he could never have done his work if other people hadn\'t been observing the stars for hundreds of years and come up with very accurage measurements of how they move. \r\n\r\nThose guys didn\'t understand what was going on, mind you, they just made the observations.\r\n\r\nGalileo was an exception. Everyone knew that the moon and the planets moved around in the sky night after night in front of a fixed field of stars that just spun around the earth. Everyone knew that these heavenly bodies were fixed to spheres that spun around the earth. But Galileo didn\'t buy that; he suggested that the earth and the planets revolved around the sun. He got into a lot of trouble for that. \r\n\r\nNewton used what Galileo said to figure out the rules that governed the planets. He figured out that gravity held everything together and kept all the planets from just flying apart. He figured out that the fact they were spinning kept them from all falling into one big lump.\r\n\r\nLike a ball on a string. As long as you spin it, it keeps flying around you. The string is gravity and the motions is just like the motion of the planets. \r\n\r\nThe way galileo and newton figured this out was to look at all the evidence and notice a few patterns. In the case of galileo it was that the planets didn\'t move in nice neat circles around the earth -- at some point every year they moved backwards for a few nights. We know now that this is because the earth catches up with them every year and passes them. But then it was just weird; why would the perfect spheres run backwards? \r\n\r\nGalileo figured it out. And then, knowing that everything revolved around the sun, Newton figured out how gravity works. This is harder than figuring out how baseball is played just by watching. Consider-- no score board, no crowd cheering to give you hints. Not even an umpire to call the plays. \r\n\r\nBut better than that, more amazing, Newton boiled it all down to three little laws. Man, he was good!\r\n\r\nYou are probably wondering why you care. You want to hear about things that are relevant to your lives. But hey, your in High School: nothing is relevant to your life except, well, maybe the rules to baseball.  Baseball is entertaining and inspiring and has all kinds of drama and excitement. But if you didn\'t understand the rules you wouldn\'t understand any of it. \r\n\r\nScience, believe it or not, is the same way. Entertaining and inspiring with all kinds of drama and excitement. I admit it move kind of slow (but then so does baseball sometimes) but then there\'s hundreds of years of excitment to look at.\r\n\r\nI see you rolling your eyes at me. Entertainment? Drama? No way, right? But that\'s just because you don\'t know the rules of the game; you haven\'t been following the season. \r\n\r\nRight now there is a huge mystery going on in science. It\'s the weirdest thing. Back in the {date of hubble\'s discovery} a guy named Hubble (may have heard of the telescope named ofter him) discovered that the universe is expanding. That is, everything is moving away from us. That\'s kind of weird. But scientists took it in stride. They figured that, if everythign in the universe was moving away from everything else, it has to be slowing down because of gravity. Everything pulls everything else toward it with gravity so, given this pull, the expansion has to be slowing down. But the slowing down itself is slowing down because as the universe expands gravity grows weaker. So will it move out slower and slower forever or will it evententually stop moving and then start to collapse. I think most people were rooting for the collapse -- what they called the big crunch which would then give rise to another big bang which is how they think the univers got startd. Bang, crunch, bang, crunch. Very symetrical.\r\n\r\nSo all the scientists are checking this out, doing measurements trying to figure itou. The answers they\'re getting after 30 years or so don\'t make any sense so the game goes into extra innings. Finally, they have an answer after 40 years or so: the universe is moving away faster and faster.\r\n\r\nOk, gravity could make it slow down but what could make it speed up. Well, that\'s the clincher: nothing. The Scientists -- all of them -- are absolutely stumped. Clueless. \r\n\r\nAnd they are STILL clueless! That\'s right the greatest minds in the world can\'t tell a ball from a strike when it come to universe expansion. They\'re inventing something called \"dark energy\" that\'s supposed to pop into existence in the middle of nowhere and make things go faster. Who knows, maybe their right. Maybe one of you will figure out what thisstuff is. \r\n\r\nOh, yes, there\'s plenty of time to get in on the game! It\'s been going on for hundreds of years and it will keep going when you all have your PHd.\r\n\r\nAnd science has something that baseball doesn\'t: politics. yep, scientists discovered that all that carbon we\'re pumping into the atmostpher is causing the earth to warm. And now lots of politicians are saying Na-ah! Is not! Kind of gooffy but also kind of important. After all, if you have children and global warming is as bad as the scientists say, they could be in a lot of trouble. But the politicians say, nah, it would cost to much to fix; we should ignore it. \r\n\r\nAnd Science\'s heroic cousin is technology. People get them confused. Science works out the rules of how radio waves work -- figured that out in the 1930s. And then technology uses that information to make TVs and microwaves, and GPSs and cell phones and all manner of cool stuff. Without technology you\'d have to watch TV in the dark! And without science, you\'d have no technolgy.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBut someday \r\n\r\n','2010-05-05','2010-05-06 06:04:35'),(588,95,'DAM','The teacher walks into the class and says\r\n\"Good morning. My name is Dave Menconi but you will not call me that. What you will call me depends on how you feel in the moment. If you like what I just said or feel good about me at that moment you will call me \'snuggle bunny\' as in \'snugglebunny, I agree\' or \'snugglebunny, I understand what you want.\' If you don\'t like what I just said or are unhappy at the moment you will address me by the honorific, \"numbnuts\" as in \'numbnuts, that\'s a dumb idea\' or \'numbnuts, I don\'t want to do that\'. If you feel neutral or don\'t have an opinion you can address me as \"hey you\" for example \'hey you, the answer is 5\' or \"hey you, may I go to the bathroom\' (the answer is \'no\', by the way). Finally, if you are completely confused you can call me \"what the\". For example, \'what the, that doesn\'t make any sense.\'\r\n\r\nhe now proceed to drill them on this process to make sure they will all use the right name in each situation. Anyone who starts a sentence without one of those four names is told \"your sentence is badly formed; would you please try again\" in a neutral voice. \r\n\r\nThe teacher now hands 6 pieces of paper to 6 randomly chosen students (to be a jerk he might ask for volunteers and then give it to 6 random people). He tells the students to read the paper and follow the instructions on the paper in the upcoming exercise but not to share it with others. Then he tells everyone that the pieces of paper will make the exercise more interesting for everyone.\r\nThe teacher now announces that he is in charge. The Snugglebunny Government has taken over and, as a benevolent dictatorship, has decided that only people who have their name on the piece of paper in the possession of Snugglebunny can sit in chairs in this room. Since none of you have your names in the possession of Snugglebunny you can\'t sit in the chairs. However, since I am a reasonable man, I will give you some time. \r\n\r\n\"Everyone take out a blank piece of paper and write your name on it and pass it to the front.\"\r\n\r\nCompliance is totally unenforced and anyone who complains that someone has done it wrong it stopped from complaining. \r\n\r\nNote that at every step the teacher asks for questions and/or comments and goads them into saying something so that the students have opportunities to call him names. \r\n\r\nWhen the papers come up he calls for volunteer bureaucrats. \"Now, all kidding aside, you want to watch carefully for the next few minutes. Careful observation will teach you more than you will learn the rest of the day and I mean teach you thinks you can use right now in your lives. Pay attention.\"\r\n\r\nNow he organizes the 3 helpers to sort the papers into 3 piles -- a-i, j-r, s-z -- according to the first name of each child. Then he has them compare the names to lists of students (again, a-i, j-r, s-z) and mark off who has an has not submitted names. \r\n\r\nThe names of people who did NOT turn in papers (at least one of the 6 people with special instructions will be told not to do so) will be announced and those students will be evicted from their seats. \r\n\r\nBefore the students are allowed to sit down, the teacher gathers their thoughts on the exercise. \r\n\r\nHe asks the people standing how they feel about it. What do they think? Good rule? Makes sense? \r\n\r\nThen he asks the sitting students the same questions. \r\n\r\nAnd the students who did the sorting. Was it hard? Easy? fun Boring? \r\n\r\nNow about watching the sorting, what did people learn?\r\n\r\nThe goal is to get people to see how arbitrary it all is, what a nuisance it is to keep track of compliance and enforce it and what a drag and a waste it is. Also, as a bonus, students working together can do complicated tasks like sort papers very rapidly but it would take much longer for one person to to it. But it takes organization and communication. more on this later.\r\n\r\nHe has the kids sit down. \r\n\r\n\r\nNow, what we experienced this morning was an example of a governmental regulation in action. This was, in fact, the most benign regulation imaginable. I didn\'t make you pay any money or reconfigure your desk or demonstrate that your desk was neat or that you didn\'t have a cell phone any of the other 100 things I might require of you. \r\n\r\nAnd yet look at what a nuisance it was. All regulations are going cause disruption, expenses, annoyances, costs for enforcement and ultimately will put people out of business and/or make it hard for them to get work done. This is true of all regulations, no question.\r\n\r\nAnd yet, perhaps there are regulations that are beneficial. What do you think? can you think of regulations whose benefits might outweigh the cost?\r\n\r\nNow we get into it. We make 3 lists: good, bad, not sure\r\n\r\nWhen the conversation about good and necessary vs bad and unnecessary regulations winds down, we have another conversation about the sorting. People working together can get more stuff done than people working separately. Think of some examples in the world -- buildings bridges, the school, the building, sure, but the way it runs.  But how do you get people to work together? What about communication? How to get them to communicate effectively? Woudl they do that normally? \r\n\r\nNow we talk about authority. \"Do I have any authority? I kicked kids out of their seats because they didn\'t comply with arbitrary instructions. can I do that? \"\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAnd yet I did, didn\'t I. \r\n\r\nAnd talk about the titles. It\'s silly and yet I got them to do it. (not sure whther they will all use the neutral one or mix it up -- either way, it will be something for them to look at) \r\n\r\nI have granted authority. Talk about this and how it works. I can\'t do a damn thing to any of them and yet I can report them to their teacher, to their principal, call their parents, call the police. This is granted authority.\r\n\r\nBut I also have assumed authority. To some extent, they do what I say because I simply insist and they go along. \r\n\r\nWhy? What value does authority have? Why did the principal give me granted authority? How does it benefit me? How does it benefit them. \r\n\r\nHere\'s the kicker: authority, regulations, bureaucracy, makes civilization work. We all want to be rebellious and flaunt authority, we all want to be free, we all bad-talk bureaucracy but without these things there would be chaos. \r\n\r\nGet them to talk about the two sides of this coin: try to get them to see that one side is the nuisance and cost and silliness of arbitrary rules while the other side is the ability of people to work together and avoid hurting each other. \r\n','2010-05-20','2010-05-21 00:49:50'),(589,95,'DAM','Let\'s go to another star. The closest start is four light years away. Any guesses how far away that might be? \r\n\r\n4 light years. That means the distance that light travels in 4 years. Light is fast. Light is really fast. \r\n\r\nThink about this: when you make a phone call all the way around the world the delay is practicaly undetectable. \r\n\r\nLight is very fast. \r\n\r\nwe\'re going to have to do some serious math so let\'s ','2010-05-20','2010-05-21 05:47:45'),(590,105,'davemenc','Soft, pleasant music plays. \r\n\r\nThe wedding party assembles around the officiant at the alter. The groom, the groomsmen, the bridesmaids. \r\n\r\nAfter some inevitable wait, the weeding march plays and the bride, escorted traditionally by her father, comes down the aisle. \r\n\r\nAfter a brief pause the officiant speaks. \r\n\r\nWelcome, everyone, to the wedding of Jeff and Samantha. \r\n\r\nToday, we will all agree, is their day. But, in a very real, practical sense, it\'s not for them. \r\n\r\nIt\'s for you.\r\n\r\nConsider this: Marriage is a path. A couple has either entered the long and winding path or they haven\'t. The government can record the fact of it, religion can sanctify it and the officiant can celebrate it. But, ultimately, the couple is either married or they are not. They are either on the path or not. \r\n\r\nThese two, are married. I saw this from the first time I met them. Quite simply they are already, right now, connected in that beautiful way that we call marriage. They are already walking on that path.  \r\n\r\nI expect you might be surprised to hear me say this. After all, what am I doing up here if they are already married?\r\n\r\nOur purpose today is for Jeff and Samantha to acknowledge the fact that they are married to the community of people who mean the most to them. \r\n\r\nAnd to give all of you, the members of that community, an opportunity to formally acknowledge their existing state of marriage. For marriage is a journey of growth and discovery and one cannot grow or discover in isolation. One grows within one\'s community.\r\n\r\nThis is the sense in which today is about you. \r\n\r\nWould the family of the bride please stand & repeat after me\r\n- We welcome Jeff into our family as a new son, brother, nephew, cousin. We support him in his marriage to Samantha in the hope that he will become all that he can be.\r\n\r\nPlease sit down\r\n\r\nWould the family of the groom please stand & repeat after me. \r\n- We welcome Samantha into our family as a new daughter, sister, niece, cousin. We support her in her marriage to Jeff in the hope that she will become all that she can be.\r\n\r\nPlease sit down. \r\n\r\nWould the friends of Jeff and Samantha please stand up -- those of you who are crashing the wedding can remain seated -- and repeat after me. \r\n\r\nWe welcome Jeff and Samantha into our community as friends. We support them in their marriage with the hope that they will become all that they can be. \r\n\r\nPlease sit down.\r\n\r\nFrom time to time you will be in a position to act or not act in a manner that will impact this marriage. I charge you all to remember these vows you have taken and always act in a way that supports Jeff and Samantha in their marriage. \r\n\r\nJeff\'s Vows\r\nI, Jeff Miller, take you, Samantha Schwartz, to be my wife, I will cherish our union and love you more each day than I did the day before. I will trust you,  respect you and support you in the hope that you will become all you can be. \r\n\r\nSamantha\'s Vows\r\nI, Samantha Schwartz, take you Jeff Miller, to be my husband, I will cherish our union and love you more each day than I did the day before. I will trust you, respect you and support you in the hope that you will become all you can be. \r\n\r\nThe Ring is an important symbol of marriage. The perfect circle is a fundamental shape that symbolizes the endless renewal of life. It also evokes capture or protection. Yet one must choose to enter the circle to be captured within it. Two circles together form the symbol of the infinite which represents the infinity of possibilities. \r\n\r\nJeff and Samantha exchange rings and say,\r\n\"With this ring I thee wed.\"\r\n\r\nRemember that you have committed to this marriage in front of your family and your friends. When difficult times come, you can call upon the people here for you are not just married to each other but married within the context of a community who love you. \r\n\r\nPlease kiss your spouse. \r\n\r\nMusic Plays and we go off to party. I rather like \"the Wedding Song\" for a recessional but that\'s a matter of taste. \r\n\r\nA few other notes. \r\n\r\nIt should be obvious that I wrote some vows for you as place holders. I don\'t object to any part of this being changed. It\'s your day; we\'ll do it your way. \r\n\r\nI believe that, at some point, we need to sign the certificate and for that we need witnesses. We need to find out the requirements for that county. \r\n\r\nAt my wedding we had a few classical musicians from the local college play some chamber music for the 40 minutes it took everyone to sit down and to bring up the bride. It\'s fairly cheap, pretty good and helps out someone who needs it. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2010-09-16','2010-09-17 03:34:08'),(591,105,'DAM',' Wedding rings are an outward and visible sign of an inward spiritual grace, signifying to all the uniting of this man and this woman in marriage.\r\n\r\npaul on love','2010-09-16','2010-09-17 02:48:11'),(592,105,'DAM','1) WEdding party and, most especially, the bride make their entrance. \r\n2)Do we want a wedding reading? \r\n3) My little bit\r\n4) rings\r\n5) Vows: how about: I, (Bride/Groom), take you (Groom/Bride), to be my (wife/husband), I will cherish our union and love you more each day than I did the day before. I will trust you and respect you in the hope that you will become all you can be. \r\n\r\n5) Kiss\r\n6) and out\r\nNo parting shot','2010-09-16','2010-09-17 03:03:37'),(593,84,'DAM','<h2>Trip To Europe Impressions</h2>\r\nThe clouds skitter across the grund like little animals frollicking in a pastoral scene\r\nThen they grow dark and angry, pouring forth the cold cruel drenching rain on all god has created. \r\nBut even this serves to nourish and renew the denizens of the pastoral scene. \r\n\r\n9/20/10\r\nI\"m on a plane heading toward Amsterdam. I close my eyes for a second.\r\nWhen I open them I don\'t know where I am...\r\n\r\nI\'m walking down a street. I\'m not sure where I am. I look for street\r\nsigns but there are no sign posts. I look for signs on buildings but I\r\ncan\'t read them.\r\n\r\nI\'m by a river. Maybe I was by a river before but I\'m not sure. What\r\ndirection am I traveling? I look at the sky but it\'s all gray. Maybe\r\nit will rain.\r\n\r\nI walk faster but I\'m almost struck by a bike. He rings his bell and I\r\njump out of the way just in time.\r\n\r\nThere is a line of people at a shop waiting for something. When I get\r\nto the front of the line the woman says \"4\" and I look in my wallet\r\nand  see only play money. I give her a 5 anyway and she gives me a\r\nchocolate coin as change.\r\n\r\nThen she hands me a cone. \"Ice Cream!\" I think but it\'s full of french\r\nfries with a brown peanut sauce on top and a little wooden fork to eat\r\nit with.\r\n\r\nI keep walking and walking. I find a map in my pocket but it makes no\r\nsense. There are rivers everywhere in great loops. It looks like a\r\nchild\'s drawing. It means nothing to me.\r\n\r\nI notice a shop window that has a girl looking back at me. She is in a\r\nbathing suit but it\'s too cold for swimming. She gives me a seductive\r\nsmile and motions me closer. I hurry on.\r\n\r\nI found a coffee shop and, thinking that I could relax in a coffee\r\nshop, I went in. But it was dark and seedy and everyone was smoking\r\nweed and laughing darkly. I fled to find a pub that was bright and\r\nclean and friendly. They even gave me a cup of coffee.\r\n\r\nI wander around, crossing rivers and taking streets at random. The\r\nbuildings all seem very old, older than me, older than my family,\r\nolder than America.\r\n\r\nI hear a very load mechanical sound which startles me into opening my\r\neyes. The pilot has just put the fasten seat belt sign on and we\'re\r\nlanding in Amsterdam. I wonder what it\'s like?\r\n----\r\nWe leave Amsterdam late. Weve had a great meeting but we\'re all exhausted \\. We get onto our plane. The minute I hit the seat I\'m asleep. \r\n\r\nI\'m in a box that rolling back and forth.  Everytime it rolls my knees bump into the other people. Our luggage is on our laps and on the floor. Outside we can see an industrial landscape roll by. We screech to a halt and pay the driver. \r\n\r\nI\'m in a bright white room with electronics packed into the front, none of which seems to work. A voice drones on and on about some technical subject. I doze...\r\n\r\nI\'m playing a new game. Some sort of generic character is jumping from place to place. Meantime my colleagues are talking about state machines that have to do with controlling a character that is jumping from plance to place.\r\n','2010-09-22','2010-09-26 10:29:54'),(594,84,'DAM','\r\n<h2>3 waiters</h2>\r\nWears his glasses on his nose, very smart kEeps things running. Grey\r\nshortish hair.\r\nRoind bald head with round glasses.\r\nYoung, good looking, atheletic.','2010-09-27','2010-09-27 16:22:44'),(595,105,'DAM','<h3>Advice</h3>\r\nI\'ve been asked to give some advice to the newly married couple. I am reluctant to give advice but, since the request came from the couple, what can I do? \r\n\r\nAbout a year ago, my wife and I hit our 25 wedding anniversary. I found it something I wanted to brag about at first but everyone I mentioned it to asked me \"what\'s your secret\"? \r\n\r\n\"What\'s my secret!?\" To be lucky enough to have an amazing wife?  In the face of a relationship that\'s lasted literally half my life, sound bites like \"never go to bed angry\" simply don\'t seem to cut it. \r\n\r\nBut then I realized that the person isn\'t saying, \"I want to be married 25 years\". They\'re thinking, \"if you\'ve been married 25 years, your relationship must work and I want a relationship that works, too\". \r\n\r\nWhen you look at it that way, when you take the time element out of it, it becomes pretty simple. Not, \"what have I been doing for 25 years\" or even \"what have I been doing for the past year\" but \"what am I going to do now?\"\r\n\r\nEvery moment, each of us has millions of choices. Right now you have choices. <pause> OK, I see that none of you chose to get up and leave. You could have, you know. \r\n\r\nPhilosophers through the ages, all the way back to the Greeks, have said that we want to make choices that will make us happy. But if you want your relationship to work you must make choices that will make your partner happy. Oddly, if you generally make choices that make your partner happier, you will be happier. And if you\'re partner also makes choices to make your happy you will be happier still. \r\n\r\nYou know that feeling when you give a back rub to someone and they are really digging it and you really feel great that you can do something for someone else? A real sense of skill and accomplishment goes into a good back rub. \r\n\r\nNow imagine that that person is giving you a back rub, too. So they are getting and giving a great back rub and you are getting and giving a great back rub, too. \r\n\r\nOf course life involves more than just back rubs. Sometimes you\'ll make choices that don\'t involve your partner. Crying babies, car accidents, financial disasters and many other things all intervene. \r\n\r\nBut, my advice, since you asked, is to make as many choices as you can that will make your partner happy. \r\n\r\n','2010-10-11','2010-10-11 17:16:16'),(596,4,'DAM','<h2>State Machines</h2>\r\nIt suddenly occurred to me that a state machine would be the perfect addition to this system. I outlined the basic structure of one game in my notes.\r\n\r\nThe structure of the state machine is very simple. There is a file that contains the state for the game/instance/player combination you want. This file contains the names of all state machines and the names of the states they are currently in. \r\n\r\nThe easiest way to do this is to have it be a PHP file that contains an array of key=>value (machine->state) pairs. You just include the file and there you are.\r\n\r\nEvery state has 4 functions associated with it. Start, Run, End, Guard. The names of these functions are constructed: SM_<machine name>_<state name>_<start|run|end|guard>. They do not have to exist for the system to run correctly (but it obviously won\'t do anything without them). \r\n\r\nThere is a \"state machine\" function (SM_main_run) and you call this to handle all the machines. It includes the array, loops through and, for every machine, it figures out the state. It calls the Run function and then the guard function and if the guard function returns a state name it then changes the state to that one, calls the end for the old state, calls the start for the new one and goes on to the next one. \r\n\r\nThe actual state machine is implemented in these functions. I\'m planning on writing them by hand but you could do it any \r\n\r\nThen it or something else, \r\n\r\n','2010-10-14','2010-10-14 23:51:29'),(597,4,'DAM','<h2>Auctions</h2>\r\nThe routines needed for auctions include\r\nstart (it starts an auction -- this must return the index)\r\ncheck suction end (it checks to see which auctions should be marked \"inactive\")\r\ncancel (it blows away an auction with no result\r\nclose -- it closes an auction early with results\r\nshow all (game gets a list of all relevant auctions)\r\nshow one -- give it the index and get auction and all bids\r\nshow unprocessed -- gives a list of all the unprocessed auctions \r\n\r\n---\r\nprocess in order \r\n -- all auctions that have no buyer\r\n -- all acutions involving the computer player on either side\r\n -- ','2010-10-25','2010-10-25 19:33:31'),(598,96,'DAM','Ambur suggests that the story be told non-linearly. \r\n\r\nThere is an adopted child who grows up in a loving family. \r\n\r\nThere is a woman who has a boy friend. She loves him and is attached to him. \r\n\r\nThe boy finds out he\'s adopted and it eats at him. \r\n\r\nAbsolute honesty is crucial to the man. He tells his girlfriend everything but she is a private person and is reluctant. \r\n\r\nThe boy begins to hate his parents because they aren\'t HIS parents. Every request is dispised and even their very love reminds him that his real parents hate him. \r\n\r\nThe man and the woman have a difficult heart-to-heart in which she \"tells him everything\" but she knows that she is lying. She has a deep, old secret that she isn\'t telling.\r\n\r\nThe Boy turns 18 and leaves home to find his real mother. \r\n\r\nThe man, now satified that the woman is telling him everything, marries her. The have a child and are very happy. \r\n\r\nThe boy ','2010-10-30','2010-10-31 06:57:02'),(599,106,'davemenc',' First off, the overwhelming feedback that I got for this class is that no one wants to here about the basics. But, of course, no advanced class can start without a firm grounding in the basics. \r\n\r\nFortunately for you, what I call basics and what you call basics are not the same. I assume that what you mean by \"basics\" have to do with how to send email using your particular kind of client. I\'m not going to discuss that. In fact, I\'m going to assume you know how to use your client. In fact, if you can\'t figure out how to do anything I\'m going to tell you in your particular client then I\'m going to recommend that you find a different client. \r\n\r\nMy examples will all be done using Gmail just because it\'s easy to get to from here. \r\n\r\nNow, first basic thing that you need to know is what email is. Email is a protocol that allows one computer to send a message to another comptuer on your behalf. ','2010-11-21','2010-11-21 20:52:14'),(600,106,'DAM','<h2>Outline</h2>\r\nTo Vs CC\r\nAppropriate use of the BCC\r\nThe Headers Are your friends\r\nemail\'s path from your desktop to mine\r\nSpam\r\nViruses\r\n','2010-11-21','2010-11-21 23:16:10'),(601,4,'DAM','<h2>Auction Rules</h2>\r\nThere are a cloud of rules that need to be associated with auctions. \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>You should be able to have short auctions. \r\n<li>To bid you must put up the money immediately. The money is in escrow and you get it back when someone outbids you.\r\n<li>Because the money is in escrow we don\'t need to worry about defaults\r\n</ul>\r\nThe idea is that the player can put money on multiple items in a week, purchase some of those items and then resell them. \r\n','2010-11-26','2010-11-26 15:38:43'),(602,106,'DAM','<h2>Anatomy of an Email Address</h2>\r\nLet\'s look at a few common email addresses. \r\n<li>davemenc@google.com\r\n<li>dave@menconi.com\r\n<li>dave_menconi@playstation.sony.com\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>davemenc@google.com</h3>\r\nThis first one is a very standard email address. Before the @ sign we have a username. Every email must have a username before the @ sign. It can contain some special characters such as a period, and underbar and even a dash. It cannot have any spaces or slashes in it. \r\n\r\nAfter the @ sign is what\'s commonly called the domain name but here I will called it the gateway name. This string uniquely identifies a gateway into mail system. You might think of this as a \"server name\" but this particular gateway leads into a complicated cloud of servers -- probably hundreds or even thousands -- all working together to handle millions of emails. That\'s why I canll it a gateway -- you don\'t know or care what\'s on the other side of the gateway, just that whatever it is will handle your email. It\'s like there\'s a little window in a wall. You go to that window and you hand the man there a letter and he says \"OK\" and you know that he\'ll do the right thing. But you don\'t know how. \r\n\r\n<h3>dave@menconi.com</h3>\r\nHere again, another email address. I happen to know that this email address leads to a single directory on a server with hundreds of similar directories. The \"domain name\" \"Menconi.com\" is just like \"google.com\" but instead of leading to a facility with thousands of computers it leads to a single computer that\'s shared by hundreds of people. \r\n\r\nIn almost all cases the gateway will turn the email -- which was just a collection of bits going over a wire -- into at least one and possibly many files. The most important file is a simple text file that you could open and read in even the simplest text editor. We\'ll take this apart shortly. There might also be other parts to the email, for example, a picture. We\'ll talk about that a bit more. \r\n\r\n<h3>dave_menconi@playstation.sony.com</h3>\r\n\r\n','2010-11-28','2010-11-28 19:40:26'),(603,99,'','Some girls wear boots up to their crotch. Some wear shear pants that cover their legs and crotches but not very well. Some where shorts over their panties or bathing suites. Spangly bras.\r\n\r\nSome do some serious dancing. Some count on the fact that they have awesome bodies and just wiggle their tits and asses. Some, as noted, do pole work and some do not (pole work varies but you really shouldn\'t both if you can\'t hold your self on the pole -- that\'s basically openers). Some have booties and some \"stripper shoes\" and I saw a girl do pole work with booties, although she wasn\'t very good. \r\n\r\nThe club I visited had all the girl on stage (in this case, multiple stages) for a few minutes just to show the customers what they could expect. They didn\'t do anything (two girls practiced poll moves). \r\n\r\nThe club was remarkably chummy. Everyone seemed to like everyone. It was nice. \r\n\r\nSome girls did little moves with their asses, wiggling just one cheek. A few tapped their pussies. One poked her asshole through her panties -- making a point, I guess. One licked her fingers. Several grabbed their own tits and a few pushed open their panties in various ways. \r\n\r\nThis was the Brass Rail so they couldn\'t strip down but they still managed to take things off. \r\n\r\nI guess the key note is that some were real dancers and some just wiggled their asses (assets).\r\n','2010-12-23','2010-12-23 21:27:22'),(604,99,'','The sound system at the brass rail is pretty straight forward. They had a few boxes and a laptop. Thinking about it, one of the boxes has to be an amp. There was a mix board. Probably a preamp. That\'s what a simple sound system should be. \r\n\r\nThe laptop makes a lot more sense. It should run DJ software that allows you to fade in a fade out. ','2010-12-23','2010-12-23 21:49:01'),(605,107,'davemenc','A man is sent to a hotel room in a foreign country. He doesn\'t speak the language, he doesn\'t know anyone there. His job is to wait until he\'s contacted. It\'s a mysterious spy-thing. \r\n\r\nBut we tell the story from a chamber maid\'s perspective. She knows he never leaves, she knows he uses escort services. She comes in and cleans while he\'s there. She discreet and appropriate but he starts nodding to her as if she\'s and old friend and she can tell he lonely.\r\n\r\nShe makes up a romantic fantasy about him. \r\n\r\nThen, one day, when she comes in, with music quietly playing on her cart (as she always has), he playfully takes her hand and dances to the music, just for a moment. \r\n\r\nsomehow she gets the courage to show up after her shift with her boom box playing and they dance for a long time. (Better: he convinces her to come back, catches her heading home and gets her to come in and dance with him.) \r\n\r\nThen he orders her dinner and try, piteously, to communicate (neither knows more than a smattering of the other\'s language). He indicates she should come back. \r\n\r\nHe\'s like a secret lover that she has and she struggles over whether to come come back. She shouldn\'t but she does but she should stop.\r\n\r\nShe comes back many times and they both struggle mightily to learn the others language. They each get to a point where they can understand quickly but she has trouble pronouncing. \r\n\r\nHe gets sloppy and let\'s her overhear his communications with his base and so we gradually learn that he\'s a spy and that things aren\'t going well. \r\n\r\nShe misses there \"date\" sometimes because of family things and, when she shows up, he stricken. it breaks her heart that she\'s his only friend. \r\n\r\nThey fall in love (natch) and they have sex and then they begin sleeping together. \r\n\r\nMaybe he orders a prostitute during the day when he thinks she\'s not a round. Maybe during her period. She is devastated but thinks of him and forgives him. \r\n\r\nShe gives him everything, invests everything in him even though she knows that she is only a kind of extended one night stand. He seems to love her but she knows from the overheard conversations, that he\'s just on a mission. \r\n\r\nShe hears from conversations in the middle of the night that he\'s in danger but that he insists that he stay on for a few more days. She imagines that he\'s braving it for her.\r\n\r\nShe\'s scared for him.\r\n\r\nThere are 3 ways this can end. She fantasizes, somewhat desperately, that he will stay for his love of her and they will live happily ever after. Her best friend (the only other character in the book) points out, somewhat kindly, that this is impossible. How will she explain this to her mother and father? What will Auntie think? And grandma? It\'s impossible. \r\n\r\nThe way she really expects it to happen is that a car will come, he\'ll pack up all his stuff and fly away. This seems imminent. She dreads it and believes fervently that the only reason he is still hear is because he loves her. Love will conquer all. \r\n\r\nThe way it happens is that she goes in to clean his room and finds him on the floor shot. The room is trashed to the point where she almost can\'t find him. He\'s been tortured. Maybe he\'s actually still alive. \r\n\r\nIt would be good to have something that indicates, at the last, that she wasn\'t important to him, just to be the cherry on the top of her banana split.\r\n\r\nMaybe they grab her. Maybe he slipped something into her boom box so that he wouldn\'t be at risk. Under torture he told them where it was, gave her up without a backwards glance. \r\n\r\nMaybe we play back the entire interrogation and he refers to her in off-handed ways. \"That slut, she doesn\'t know anything. She\'s just pussy to while away the nights. Something to do...\" and so forth. \r\n\r\nWhat is the aftermath? She kills herself? She marries that moron that was picked out for her? She makes love to her best friend? where does she go with this? ','2010-12-27','2010-12-27 18:53:02'),(606,107,'DAM','Keith suggested that it be a female spy with a young male lover. THis is solely because he thinks it would be easier to write from the young male perspective but it has kind of a nice twist to it. ','2010-12-27','2010-12-27 20:15:02'),(607,84,'DAM','<h2>The Pumpkin Festival</h2>\r\nI don\'t know that this is a book. Maybe a short story, maybe a piece of a book.\r\n\r\nThere is a writer. He wants to get his name out there. He\'s published a book but the publisher is pushing the book. He\'s happy to do that but he wants to become famous so he hires his own publicist. \r\n\r\nShe sends him to do a speech at a pumpkin festival. The festivities end at midnight and there are several speakers and they\'re running late. \r\n\r\nThe organizer says to our speaker that he\'s going to have to cut him from the program because of so on and so on. You can keep the honorarium, we\'ll pay for the trip but we just don\'t have time.\r\n\r\nOur speaker responds with, \"hey, I\'m not here to speak, I\'m here to enhance the experience of the attendees. How can I help you do that? Do you need an MC? Do you need someone to serve pumpkin soup, find people in the crowd. You must need someone to help you cuz there\'s just you and a few volunteers who keep flaking out.\"\r\n\r\n\"Well, I was going to MC but, honestly, I don\'t really want to.\" \r\n\r\n\"Great, give me your notes, show me to the green room and don\'t give it another thought. I\'m all over it!\"\r\n\r\nHe goes to the other speakers, tells them he\'s been hired to MC (which they immediately don\'t buy cuz he\'s on the program). Some are suspicious others don\'t care. \r\n\r\nHe tells them that time is tight, the whole thing ends at Midnight because of county ordenacnes and they aren\'t going to make it unless they cut back. So cut out that 4th instance you were going to talk about and cut it back to just the A material. OK. \r\n\r\n\"Fuck you. I\'m going to talk as long as I want and there\'s nothing you can do about it.\" says the first speaker. He tries reason \"but that screws over the last speaker.. I\'ll have to cut him short\" The guy doesn\'t care.\r\n\r\nSo now he has 5 minutes to come up with a way to control these unruly assholes.\r\n\r\nHis speech involved some dumb comments about pumpkins. but he brought an air horn to spice it up. So he incorporates the air horn. He warms up the audience cheering something like:\r\n\r\nGood evening. I\'m John Smith, your Emcee for the evening. I was supposed to give a speech tonight but we\'re running late and we haven\'t the time. You\'ll never hear it. See, it\'s right here but you can\'t hear it. Do you want to hear it? Give a shout if you do... No, more enthusiam. That\'s what we need tonight, some enthusiasm!\r\nWhen I call these people out you need to cheer. Let\'s practice that. Hooray!\r\n\r\nOk, times, tight like I said. So I need you to help me enforce a time limit or you\'ll never hear the last guy\'s speech either. \r\n\r\nWHen you here this, it\'s the 2 minute warning. When you hear it agin we\'re out of time so start counting down 20, 19, 18, 17... When you get to 0, shout the guy off the stage!\r\n\r\n','2010-12-27','2010-12-27 20:31:08'),(608,108,'davemenc','The game is constructed of Tiers of Niches. Each niche is a role that a player can take on. He can only be in one niche but he can sell to the highest bidder at any time and that person takes on all his stuff and then he can move on to a another niche. Niches are constantly coming into being (and, possibly disappearing but only after they\'ve been abandoned) and new tiers are appearing as well. \r\n\r\nFor example, at the start of the game the available niches are\r\n- building spaceships with existing tech\r\n- developing new tech\r\n- running a surface to orbit shuttle service\r\n- running a orbital services (mainly docking and sleeping facilities)\r\n\r\nThe first person in the game can buy a space ship from the government and start doing surface to orbit. The government, businesses and tourists are his customers (which all comes down to \"the game\"). \r\n\r\nThe second person can\'t get a spaceship but he can get the plans for a space ship so he starts building space ships. He gets to design the ship from existing tech. He would happily pay for new tech. He sells his ships to the government (who vaporizes them) and to other players (who use them to run shuttle services).\r\n\r\nThe third person starts developing new tech. He gets to make choices about what tech seems promising. He always makes money but he can also hit it really rich if something pans out. His customers are the government and the other players who want his tech early or exclusively. The gorvernment will generally give out the tech after it\'s old for a smaller fee. \r\n\r\nThe fourth person runs a space station. He gets to buy one from the government. Tourists and people working in orbit are his customers. \r\n\r\nNew players can fill those niches. A person who wants to build a space station needs to buy the parts from a ship manufacturer, needs to buy transport from a shuttle service and probably needs to buy space on an existing station for his workers. Thus he drives the economy but begins to make money soon after he starts which he can either horde or invest in his business.\r\n\r\nSoon the government announces that it wants a detailed survey of the moon. Through the power of the infrastructure that exists, a ship is made available to a new player who starts mapping the moon from orbit. The government pays him for the data. \r\n\r\nIt turns out the the moon is covered with very valuable resources. Oxygen, water, metals, diamonds, you name it, it\'s on the moon. (OK, not true, but something has to drive the next step in the story). So people build a base there, right in the middle of an area thought to be high in something good.\r\n\r\nThis creates a new niche: prospectors. For a nominal fee you can start prospecting on the moon. Lots of little strikes and a few huge strikes drive the development of the moon. More bases, processing plants, rail lines are all needed. And are all niches that players can occupy.\r\n\r\nWhen the moon is full of people doing industry, we start in on Mars. When Mars is well along to being ripped up, we do the asteroid or the moons of the big planets.\r\n\r\nAt any time, a niche can be abandoned or sold and if human players don\'t fill it, the computer players will. \r\n\r\nThe big sell of the game, the grand vision is that the game -- the players -- tell a story. They start small, build up their enterprises and then get into the next thing. I expect that there will be certain players who are always on the forefront of story, going to the moon first, going to mars first, etc. There will be very successful players who will stay in one niche, churning out money. But most players will come into the game, play as prospectors for a while and leave. This is OK because if it happens enough this will be the Oregon Trail of their generation.\r\n\r\nThere are some difficulties with this design. First off, it has a lot of elements and, at least until we go to mars, they all have a unique relationship one to another. And we\'ll want to be able to add technologies and niches and events as the game goes on to reflect current events in the real world. So it will require on going development. All this is probably not out of line with existing MMOs.\r\n\r\nA bigger potential problem is that the game doesn\'t work well unless a lot of the niches are filled. This will need to be solved by having many players in the game be computer players. The computer players are always putting their niches up for auction, however and they ony take over niches when we feel that we need more.\r\n\r\nA bigger problem is that it might be possible for there to be too many people in a niche. If too many players are in a niche it reduces the profitability for all of them and makes it hard for them to get out. But maybe it\'s a popular niche so people keep coming in. We can limit the number of people who can join the niche AND we can incentivise some of the people in that niche (the richest) to move to another niche through the use of events.\"You\'ve been offered the opportunity to buy a new business for only 1/2 it\'s usual price.\" Eventually the niche thins out.\r\n\r\n \r\n','2011-01-05','2011-01-08 00:18:04'),(609,108,'DAM','<h2>Space Exploration Game</h2>\r\n<h3>Elevator Pitch</h3>\r\nThis is a massively multiplayer game that allows players to explore the inner solar system and beyond. As the game progresses the available technology improves and the \r\n\r\n','2011-01-10','2011-01-10 20:59:43'),(610,109,'davemenc','Probably have this written down somewhere else but here we go again.\r\nTo do the Game of life you need 3 arrays. One is a 2 dim one byte array called Board, and the other 2 are 2 byte arrays (change and check) that contain x/y pairs in the Board array. \r\nThe Board is the size of the board plus 2 in each dimension while the other two are the size of the total squares on the board.\r\n\r\nEach square on the board is bit packed so you ROL to get the value and then it\'s either 0 or 0xFF where 0 is empty and FF is full. The high order bit is used to remember what we\'ve looked at. \r\n\r\nThe game starts with an empty board and a change list full of the initial squares to be populated. The empty board has it\'s edges filled with 0x80 -- this indicates that there is nothing there but that it\'s already been added to the check list. These will never be checked or changed. \r\n\r\nThe loop starts. \r\nFirst we take the list of changes and loop through them. For each one we check the high bit. If it\'s not set we change the position on the board (xor with 7F), then  add this coord to the check list and set the high bit. Now we generate the list of 8 coordinates around the change and for each one we check the high bit; if it\'s not set we set it and add that coord to the check list. \r\n\r\nAt this point we should have one and only one instance of every coordinate which needs to be checked for changes to make the next generation. \r\n\r\nWe can now draw this generation right here in the middle of the loop. \r\n\r\nNow we clear the change list and step through the check list. For each item on the check list we use the rules of the game to decide if this cell changes state and then we reset the high bit for this coord. \r\n\r\nProbably applying the rules of the game involves counting the number of full squares in the 8 adjacent squares and then handing this number and the current state (1 or 0) to a function which figures it out. We\'re only interested in whether it changes or not, not in it\'s final state. \r\n\r\nIf it changes we add it to the change list and move on. \r\n\r\nWhen we\'ve done all the checks we reset the check list.\r\n\r\nHere we reach the bottom of the loop. We have a list of changes which will be applied at the top of the list. \r\n\r\nOne important note: if you set the edges of the board to 80 at the start, they can never change. This saves you from having to do \"if x>0 and x<MaxX-1\" and \"if y>o and y<MaxY-1\" code every time you evaluate a coordinate. Provide only that you loop from 1 to MaxX-2 every time you loop through to display it (thus never displaying the edges), you never have to check for or change the edges. You DO have to check a bit before every application of changes but this is a small price to pay (for several reasons it\'s much smaller than the testing of the coordinates against two values). \r\n\r\nImplementation\r\nThe simplest way to do this is to implement the check and change arrays as stacks. I was thinking a simple array with an index. The index is always the position you would add (push) or one higher than the position you would remove (pop). So you just push, push, push as you build the list and pop, pop, pop as you step through it. And the list always resets itself and rebuilds itself for free. \r\n\r\nWhy This Is Good\r\nThe whole system uses 50% more memory than the obvious implementation. It should be something like 2x faster to calculate. Here\'s why: in a typical game of life, only about 1/10th of the squares change in any given generation. Most of the board is empty and most of the rest are static. So you only have to check around those squares that changed. It\'s possible that you\'ll have to check 90 of the board (if 1/10 of the squares change and you have to check 9 squares for each of the changes, there isn\'t much win here) but it\'s far more likely that most of the changed squares will be near each other. Since we only have to check a square once, no matter how many changed squares it\'s near, this cuts WAY down on the checks. \r\n\r\nSo, for a typical 10x10 board, there are 100 squares and we have to access each square 9 times for a total of 900 accesses. I expect that most of our time will be taken up just reading the values of the squares. \r\n\r\nIf the figure of 1/10 is accurate then we only have to look at 10 squares. If they are all independent of each other then that would be 810 accesses which isn\'t much of a savings. But typically about half of those will be duplicates (that is, two or more changes affect the same square) so we hope for about 400 accesses which is about 1/2 the number.\r\n\r\nThere ARE two critical numbers here: the number of changes and the number of checks. Key, of course, are the number of checks. We can count these generating by generation and see what happens as part of the analysis of the efficiency of the algorithm. ','2011-01-11','2011-01-11 22:47:56'),(611,106,'DAM','How to be more effective\r\n- all lower case e. e. cummings\r\n- all caps\r\n- Leet and twitter \"codes\"\r\n- One question\r\n- two line paragraphs\r\n- question is last\r\n- short emails\r\n- use smileys\r\n- clear sentences \r\n- short sentences\r\n- reading emails\r\n- responding in line\r\n- threading emails\r\n- TO: vs CC:\r\n- Use of BCC\r\n- sending to large lists\r\n- the art of the joke email\r\n- Safety in email\r\n- using abbreviations\r\n- be careful to answer the question\r\n- failure to send\r\n- send to the right person\r\n- subject line\r\n- subject line and threading\r\n- managing your history\r\n- abuse@xxx\r\n- sending out spam\r\n- getting spam\r\n- the magic \"--\" in email\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-01-12','2011-01-28 00:52:32'),(612,84,'DAM','<h2>Five\'ll Get You Ten</h2>\r\na game company decides to put $10 in some of their games as a promotional device. The games are supposed to be randomized but the people who ship out games don\'t get the memo; they always send out the first games off the line to their biggest customer and down the line. The games at the big customer have all the $10 bills.\r\n\r\nThe game is a complete flop and none sell. So the big customer puts them all on remainder for $5. So, effectively, there are 100 or 1000 games in a store that cost $5 and all have $10 in them. \r\n','2011-02-09','2011-02-09 16:05:23'),(613,110,'davemenc','First off, we need to design the database(s).\r\n\r\nThere needs to be a camp database. Every person will belong to one or more camps (many to many? -- have to allow for that). Each camp will have a description and, hell, I don\'t know, maybe some other information. Amount of dues?\r\n\r\nThere needs to be a people database. This should contain contact information and a picture along with a password and username and security level.\r\n\r\nThere needs to be a \"signup\" database. What has this person agreed to pay for, what services do they expect. In theory, this could be directly connected to the people but my instinct tells me not. \r\n\r\nI think we might want a \"plans\" database. When are you arriving? Who are you going with, how big a vehicle are you bringing, when are you leaving, etc, etc, etc. Again, in theory, this could be attached to the people database but I think not. \r\n\r\nIt might be interesting to have a friends database -- a many to many relationship among people. \r\n','2011-03-18','2011-03-18 16:19:46'),(614,99,'','Brandy -- run in, brandy has a short temper -- she was with her husband who, incidentally, beats her\r\nBunny -- Allure hates bunny with a passion and so one natually assumes that the feeling is mutual -- bunny was withwest\r\nErica -- lots of friction -- at home across town\r\nFitz -- red herrying -- it would be too much work for fitz\r\nHunni -- Young\'s favorite -- at first scoffs but admits she was with a man, give him the address then changes story to have been with young\r\nLenny -- She comes on to him and he gets very upset -- lenny was helping his uncle \r\nMack -- with his girlfriend\r\nMichael Young -- knows too much about what he\'s doing and wants a cut -- claims to be with hunni\r\nNick -- it was Allure that Nick fell in love with and Allure he wanted to shoot --\r\nPete -- it was allure he was trying to get it on with -- \r\nPops -- enemy of Young and Allure; friend to Erica and Bunny -- \r\nRichard -- brother, inheritance, sides with his parents -- \r\nVikki Allure came on to her husband, wil -- with her husband (did they do it together) \r\nVince -- got attached and then dumped -- \r\nWest -- trying to drag west back into the dark side -- with bunny (did they do it together) \r\nWil -- Allure made him look bad in front of his wife --  with his wife (did they do it together) \r\nYuumy -- friends with bunny & Erica\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOK, the obvious people should be the guy who tried to shoot allure before, Brandy, and the woman who got banned from the club because of allure.\r\n\r\nI like Will & Vikki, too. \r\n\r\nDetermine that everyone else has an alibi immeditely to get them out of the way. \r\n\r\nAdd some clues in the past for the people you want. ','2011-03-19','2011-03-26 16:49:45'),(615,111,'davemenc','In U.S. law, prior restraint is a form of censorship in which one is prevented, in advance, from communicating certain material, rather than made answerable afterwards. \r\n\r\nThis book is about an artist who is being stopped from producing his work because the academics in his community don\'t think he has the right to do art based on what he knows. He\'s not educated, he hasn\'t sacrificed enough, he doesn\'t take it seriously enough. He has a fucking paying job for christ sake!\r\n\r\nMeantime, the academics are being attacked by the right because they\'re liberals. Funding is being cut. ','2011-03-21','2011-03-22 05:01:26'),(616,110,'DAM','PERSON\r\nReal Name\r\nPlaya Name\r\nEmail (use \"&\" for \"@\" and it may fool some spammers)\r\nPhone #\r\nDeadly Food Allergy\r\nEmergency Contact name\r\nEmergency Contact Phone #\r\nFirst Year at Burning Man?\r\nFirst Year at Golden Cafe?\r\nHome City\r\nHow Many Burns?\r\nPicture URL\r\n\r\n\r\nPLANS\r\nArrival Day & Time\r\nDeparture Day & Time\r\nCamp Within Village\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSupplies\r\nTent Size\r\nVehicle Type and Size\r\nHow many fire extinguishers?\r\nHow much flammable liquid other than booze? (In gallons, if more than one gallon.)\r\n','2011-03-22','2011-03-22 15:42:15'),(617,99,'davemenc','<h2>MURDER MYSTERY OUTLINE</h2>\r\nFirst, Pops knows it\'s Michael Young. He confronts young on one of his visits and Young tells him to fuck off. But he adds, just as Huni comes into view, that he was with Huni that night so it couldn\'t have been him. After he leaves Huni comes to the bar with one of the other pretty girls. He asks her about Young and she corroborates his alibi. DAMN. it can\'t be young.\r\n\r\n*** We need to establish two facts: 1) that Huni has a husband, 2) that Huni\'s husband is unique among husbands in that he maintains contacts among the strippers. ****\r\n\r\n*** We need to establish that Mac is on vacation***\r\n\r\n*** we need to tweak Brandy\'s assertions in the wake so she sounds guilty ***\r\n\r\nHe talks to brandy and she tells him to fuck off (getting to be a pattern). \"If i killed that bitch, I\'d be proud!\" or \"Yeah, I killed that bitch, and I\'m proud of it.\"  Prime suspect. \r\nFor some reason (need to work that out -- maybe she\'s sick but agreed to do something) he calls her contact number and gets her husband. \"HER HUSBAND!?\" Yeah. He\'s a complete dominating bastard and beats her. So Pops takes a flyer and ask. \"Hell yeah she was with me; you think I let that bitch out of my sight?\"\r\n\r\nBy this point he\'s gotten a hold of Allure\'s posse member to ask her for leads. She tells him to fuck off because she HATES that skank. She hopes he never finds her killer. That bitch got me kicked out and it\'s been hard. But he offers to get her back in the club if she\'ll dish. So she comes in and they have a long convo. IMPORTANT: this convo is only about ALLURE. Allure has been seeing this Toutaling guy because of Young. SOme kind of business deal with Young. He\'s investing in Young\'s clubs so Young wants to keep him happy. She has a good alibi for the night.\r\n\r\nWest sees the posse girl and asks him about it. He explains. She tells him that she heard about this deal from Allure and that Allure had figured it out and was going to get Young to cut her in on the deal. She thought that Allure was going put the bite on Young that night. Why didn\'t you tell me this before? \"I don\'t knkow but her answer better be good!\" Maybe has to do with his personally relationship with him and bunny.\r\n\r\n\r\nNow he asks Lenny about Toutaling and Lenny is surprisingly forthcoming. Toutaling is a mobster who loans money. He\'s been loaning money to Young. He\'s got some wacky deal where he\'s going to get his claws into Young\'s partner\'s clubs as long as they don\'t see it coming. \r\n\r\nNow he gets a call from Huni\'s husband who has heard from various sources that Huni was sleeping with Young. He calls to deny it. Huni was with him, she doesn\'t sleep around