re not here on vacation...\"\r\n\r\nHe looked so stricket at hsi fau pau that she had to smile. \"no, I\'m on businees. I\'m in sales. What do you do?\"\r\n\r\nHe paused as if he wasn\'t sure what he did. I guess you say i\'m ceo of a tine ','2011-05-22','2011-05-23 03:28:08'),(627,15,'DAM','The way it will work is this:\r\n1) Generate a new game by running the create game program; \r\n2) At any time players can sign up and be added to the game\r\n3) at the start and at turn run (like at midnight for a daily game), a function is run that applies all the moves by all the players (none at the start), adjusts all their commodities (money an goods) and then generates the prices for the next turn. \r\n4) When people log in we display their status from the current situation, including the current prices\r\n5) when people do their move we have a program that generates a \"move\" from their form. This has to have what? Buy, sell, move. Maybe each thing they own can have a buy sell move and then the player might be able to do some things. So there are ship orders and player orders. Players might be able to bribe ports, send spies, buy new ships or warehouses. \r\n','2011-06-24','2011-06-24 19:02:27'),(628,63,'DAM','When we were in our late 20s my wife and I decided to have children. We had always assumed that we would have children some day but we decided to wait until we had a stable life and not rush into children. \r\n\r\nHow arrogant I was! I blithely assumed that I would be able to have children and raise them and have them come out OK without any actual evidence. In fact, if my own parents were any guide, I would drive my poor children crazy and force them to spend years overcoming whatever crazy ideas I put into their heads!\r\n\r\nIn the event I got incredibly lucky and my children turned out to be people I admire a great deal but I can\'t see how I had much to do with it. Perhaps my wife did it or maybe there are hidden forces. \r\n\r\nIn any event, children are incredibly difficult to raise properly and there is no guide whatsoever to tell you how to do it (or, more accurately, there are dozens of guides, all of them different and most of them mutually exclusive). \r\n\r\nConsider this: you are a painter (houses, not fine art) and someone comes to you and asks you to create a monumental sculpture. You say \"Sure, I\'ve always wanted to create sculpture\" and you commit your years of your life and tens of thousands of dollars to creating this sculpture. Not \"learning to create a sculpture,\" mind you, but just jumping in and starting work. \r\n\r\nWhat would you expect the outcome to be? I think it\'s safe to say that a person who has never done a sculpture of any sort before will fail if they try to create a huge one from scratch without any more preparation than simply buying the materials. \r\n\r\nAnd yet, every parent I know approached child rearing with just this sort of a \"can-do\" attitude. And I was no exception. I believed it was the right thing to do and that we would succeed. God help me. \r\n\r\n','2011-06-28','2011-06-28 21:50:57'),(629,63,'DAM','Be Do have Use\r\n\r\nI keep meeting people who are very, very strong in one aspect of their life but weak in others. They always seem to be hard luck cases. For example I met a woman who is really smart, always studying things and very focused on material success but deeply and truly unhappy. \r\n\r\nAnother person studies yoga and is very comfortable in her body and is beginning to understand spirituality but is always complaining about \"people who think too much\". Things go well for a while but ','2011-07-26','2011-07-26 23:10:27'),(630,63,'DAM','<h2>Origin Myth Again</h2>\r\nOnce, long ago, before men, before the universe, before there was time, even, there was something. \r\n\r\nThere was only one thing, ever existing, never changing. It had no thoughts, not time, no appendages. It was one thing. \r\n\r\nIt may have sat there for all eternity or for an instant for there was no time to mark it\'s duration.\r\n\r\nIt may have been infinitesimally small or may have been larger than all the universes ever conceived. There was no knowing because there was nothing to compare it to.\r\n\r\nAnd there was no one to do the comparing. \r\n\r\nIt sat, without thought, without time, without space.\r\n\r\n~~~\r\n\r\nIt had a thought. \r\n\r\nI think the thought was something like \"I am\" but that might be too complicated. Perhaps it was more like \"huh\"  like a thought you might have sitting on a warm summer evening when you first notice the stars have come out.\r\n\r\nSuddenly there were three things. Time and space and size and shape and thought suddenly existed! \r\n\r\nIt turns out that you can\'t ever have only two things. You can have one or three. But in order to have 2 you must have separation between the one thing and the other thing and that separation is a third thing.\r\n\r\nWhen the First Thought came into existence it brought many other things with it. Not as consequences, not as \"this therefor that.\" They simple were.\r\n\r\nThere had always been Spirit, for that is what we now call the One Thing. The Spirit never dies, never changes always is. \r\n\r\nThe thought itself was Mind and was the One Thought that embodies all thought. \r\n\r\nThe space between the Mind and the Spirit was the Body which is the One Body that encompasses all physicality.\r\n\r\nIt may be that the creation of this one thought is the event scientists call \"the Big Bang\" and was the creation of our universe. Or it may be that there were many other creative thoughts between that first thought and our universe. There is no way to know.\r\n\r\nEach creative thought created soemthing in the image of the first 3 things. Creation is fractal which means that each thing is a whole thing that is made up of myriads of things that are just like the whole thing and is part of something that also looks like the whole thing.\r\n\r\nThe universe has a mind which is like and part of the The Mind. It has a physical existence which is like and part of The Body. It has a spirit that is like and part of The Spirit. \r\n\r\nThe world has a mind which is like and part of the The Mind. It has a physical existence which is like and part of The Body. It has a spirit that is like and part of The Spirit. \r\n\r\n\r\nMost importantly you have a mind which is like and part of the The Mind. You have a physical existence which is like and part of The Body. It has a spirit that is like and part of The Spirit. \r\n\r\nEach of us is made in the image of that First Thing. Our mind is connected to The Mind and our body is part of The Body and our spirit is part of The Spirit. \r\n\r\nAnd because we are all part of something infinitely greater than ourselves we are all connect to each other in ways that we sense but have trouble seeing clearly.\r\n\r\nWe are each unique, as different as the proverbial snowflakes. But we are all made of the same thing . There is still just the One Thing and our differentness is an illusion. \r\n\r\nSum\r\nEsse\r\nFui\r\nFuturus\r\n\r\nI Am\r\nTo Be\r\nI Will Be\r\nI Will Have Been\r\n','2011-08-11','2013-02-19 00:21:07'),(631,63,'DAM','<h3>Letter to ambur L, 12/31/2010</h3>\r\n\r\nDear Ambur,\r\n\r\nI should mention right up front that this is my last letter to you. \r\n\r\nHoly Fuck, youâ€™re in for it now. This is the letter you wonâ€™t get around to reading for 6 months (if ever). I suppose this is where my true colors are revealed. I do not believe that you are very much interested in the description of the human being through use of schematic diagrams. I, however, love this kind of thing! So who am I writing for? \r\n\r\nThe church I used to belong to had a lamentable tendency to redefine words. \r\n\r\nTake â€œreligion.â€ Most people would say â€œreligion means an organization dedicated to some specific set of beliefs or, more generally, the collection of all such organizations. For example â€œI hate religion.â€ \r\n\r\nThey redefined â€œreligionâ€ to mean â€œThe relationship between God and Mankindâ€ in which â€œrelationshipâ€ is the juxtaposition between and among things (that is, you always have a relationship to everything), â€œGodâ€ is everything that is outside of the physical universe and â€œMankindâ€ is all of us taken together. Now the sentence â€œI hate religionâ€ doesnâ€™t even mean anything unless I redefine â€œhateâ€ to mean â€œdeeply ponderâ€. \r\n\r\nI donâ€™t say that their definition isnâ€™t a better, more useful definition. But now I say â€œI think â€˜religionâ€™ is an important thing,â€ and someone like Pete says, â€œI hate â€˜religion,â€™ â€œ and it sounds like weâ€™re disagreeing. But, really, weâ€™re not even talking about the same thing, even though weâ€™re using the same fucking words! \r\n\r\nOf course, in Peteâ€™s case, he wouldnâ€™t even accept the validity of my definition, since he probably doesnâ€™t believe in an entity called â€œGodâ€, much less agree with my sentiment about our relationship with that entity. Unless, of course, I redefined the word â€œGodâ€ to mean something different than most people mean (which the church did). In any event all this is just going to piss Pete off. \r\n\r\nThis trick of redefining words for your own personal use is pretty isolating. When people ask â€œwhat religion do you belong toâ€ I couldnâ€™t even begin to answer. Not only do we have no beliefs in common but, for christâ€™s sake, we donâ€™t even have a common language with which to discuss those beliefs. Itâ€™s like that old comedy sketch â€œWhoâ€™s on First?â€\r\n\r\nBut one thing it does give you is a clarity of thought among those people who know the new definitions. Take â€œchoiceâ€ and â€œdecision.â€ For most people, these two words mean pretty much the same thing. A word nerd would say that â€œdecisionâ€ connotes a bit more logic and judgement while â€œchoiceâ€ connotes a bit more preference. But these nuances will be lost on most normal people. \r\n\r\nBut I was taught (and I have come to believe from my own experience) that there are two very different ways to come to a course of action. \r\n\r\nOne involves making judgments, making rules that are intended to apply forever and generally where the process tends toward to a final result that we donâ€™t have to revisit. This process involves opposition: this is the right way because of these factors while that is the wrong way. We will always do it this way and never do it that way. This way was denoted â€œdecisionâ€ and once you make a decision itâ€™s hard to back it out again. All of us are filled with decisions that we made decades ago which cause us to act one way or another today (or weâ€™ve spent ENORMOUS amounts of time overcoming those decisions). \r\n\r\nThe other involves simply picking. There is no  rhyme or reason for this, we just pick something. This was denoted â€œchoiceâ€ and itâ€™s lighter and much more flexible. When I choose I can choose again and the second time I can do the same thing or something different. I can pick chocolate today and vanilla tomorrow. \r\n\r\nWhen you make a decision, you are kind of stuck with it. If you decided to go with vanilla the first time because chocolate stains then you can hardly pick chocolate the second time because it still stains. If you just chose it without any reasons you can choose chocolate the next time, or not. Decisions, in this sense, lock you in, while choices free you. \r\n\r\nChoices seem to be much better in this sense but they arenâ€™t really. You make decisions in a state of mind where you want to be right. You make choices in a state of mind where you donâ€™t care whatâ€™s right. In the first state you are certain there is a right and wrong and you are determined to be right. They called this state â€œenemy.â€ In the second state you doubt that there even is a right or wrong so they called that state â€œdoubtâ€. \r\n\r\nI guess now that Iâ€™ve come this far I should tell you the rest of it. \r\n\r\nThe Scientologists came up with something they called the Tone Scale (http://www.scientologyhandbook.org/SH4_1.HTM). EST had something called the Integrity Tone Scale which they donâ€™t seem to admit was related (http://www.karl-belser.com/SevenSteps/IntegrityTone.html). \r\n\r\nThe founder of my former church came up with something he called the States of Understand Love (or SOUL -- he really liked acronyms and he was very clever) which was based on the EST ITS. \r\n\r\nHe created his own terms for everything because he wanted them to spell something out. He wanted it to spell the terms be, do, have, and use, the first three representing the soul, mind and body and the last representing our relationship to God. Each state in his list started with a letter from his list. SO Betrayal comes first and then Enemy, then Doubt, then Obligation then Harmony. \r\n\r\nI canâ€™t remember most of the others because, frankly, I never got up that high. \r\n\r\nThe fact is that most people wander around in Betrayal (betraying themselves and everyone around them) and sometimes coming clean enough to get pissed off at how everyone else is betraying them. This takes them to Enemy. Then they do something bad (like hurting someoneâ€™s feelings or killing them) and they have to face their results. This makes them Doubt. Usually this is so uncomfortable that they slide down to Betrayal again. Eventually, if you work at it, you get into the habit of refusing to make decisions about stuff and you end up perpetually in Doubt. That sucks real bad but if you stay there long enough you make some nice clean choices. When you face up to those results you find yourself in obligation. \r\n\r\nMy teachers did mention that any time you come into a new situation (which we all must do) you move into betrayal all over again. \r\n\r\nInterestingly, the site I linked to is yet a fourth version of the tone scale. In this fourth model, itâ€™s a loop and as you move â€œup the scaleâ€ you always find yourself back. \r\n\r\nAs I say, I love this kind of stuff. I hope youâ€™ve gotten something out of it, too.\r\n\r\nHappy New Year! \r\n\r\nLove\r\n\r\nDave\r\n','2011-08-19','2013-02-19 00:20:12'),(632,40,'DAM','<h1>Espionage Game</h1>\r\nThis is a card game in which players collect cards to complete missions. The missions are constructed by randomly selected mission cards. A player requests a mission and specifies how many cards are in the mission. Each card has an \"element\"of the mission and the more elements the more complicated the mission and, hence the harder to complete. And the more points it is worth. \r\n\r\nElements may include layers of security, the specific tasks such as assisintation, sabotalge, rewiring a generator, cutting into a wall, finding a document, getting into a party, recruiting, etc.\r\n\r\nEach player draws \"capability\" cards which match the elements. The most important cards are the \"stealth\" cards which allow you to circumvent \"security\" cards. \r\n\r\nThe game play is that a player asks for a mission and specifies how many cards. The mission is drawn and he either takes the mission or \"assembles a team\" of players willing to take the mission. Each of the members of the team may play capability cards (one per turn) to work through the elements of the mission. \r\n\r\nFor example, a mission may have several security cards, a \"crash a party\", a \"fake identity\" and an \"assassinate target card\". The player chooses 3 other players to be on his team. They have the \"stealth\" cards to overcome the security cards (they EACH need a stealth card for every secruity cards -- there must be SOME disadvantage to having so many people on a team). Someone on the team has a \"crash party\" card and someone has a \"assassination\" card but no one has a fake ID card. So they can crash the party but they must sit there drawing cards turn after turn until they draw an ID card. Each turn they much play some number of stealth cards until they complete the mission. \r\n\r\nWhen they finally play all the cards they need the mission is complete and they tally the points. Each \"element\" card has a score and they divide the total of that score among themselves.\r\n\r\nOther players may attempt the same mission and, if they succeed they get ALL the points and the other team gets nothing. \r\n\r\nThis is based on a dream in which I had find which drawer in a chest of drawers was in front of a specific section of wall, remove the correct (locked) drawer, get through the wall (the wall didn\'t exist in the dream) and turn off a switch. Then put everything back the way it was and escape.\r\n\r\nAs I woke up I invented my own scenario in which I was to disrupt a party by putting liter fluid in the punch and getting the generator to fail when I turned off the power. ','2011-09-11','2011-09-11 16:35:37'),(633,63,'DAM','Magic can be considered the manipulation of the world through your mind. Many other definitions exist but, for the moment, let\'s consider this definition.\r\n\r\nI am not a magician but I have noticed that I sometimes manipulate the world around me, usually by accident. For example, I had an MP3 player. I was constantly complaining that it didn\'t work very well, the user interface sucked and the features weren\'t very good. It stopped working one day. Yep, you could say, \"well, what do you expect from a crappy MP3 player\". But I\'ve noticed that when things around me consistently annoy me, they tend to get lost or broken. Put another way (which is the correct way to say it), <i>if I allow myself to become annoyed about something and hold that annoyance for long enough,</i> that annoyance affects the world around me. \r\n\r\nThis unconscious manipulation of the physical universe is pretty inconvenient. I will often give myself a cold or cause my car to be broken into. These negative results are cause by the fact that I am not paying attention to the effects I\'m having on the world. \r\n\r\nI see most of the people I\'ve met putting more or less random thoughts into the space around them. Of course all kinds of random things happen which they term \"bad luck\". Things don\'t work out or they get flat out screwed by the world over and over again. \r\n\r\nIt is possible to control this. It is, at least in theory, possible to control this so well that you can make things happen in the world. To actually manifest real results. But I don\'t think that\'s where we should start. \r\n\r\nLet\'s start much simpler. Let\'s start with paying attention. Don\'t try to change anything. Just watch yourself. Are you upset about things often? Are you annoyed by stuff some times? What\'s your attitude toward the people around you.','2011-09-21','2011-09-22 00:13:12'),(634,63,'DAM','NEED 100 Topics\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>interactions with random people can bring you insights\r\n<li>meditation reasons\r\n<li>meditation methods\r\n<li>guided meditation\r\n<li>massage\r\n<li>relationship wbetween the subconceious and the soul\r\n<li>the case for god\r\n<li>Rant about materialism\r\n<li>Shermer\r\n<li>integrity tone scale\r\n<li>The power of suggestion\r\n<li>Random thoughts\r\n<li>silencing your mind\r\n<li>We love each other\r\n<li>We can affect each other directly\r\n<li>Clear your mind -- thoughts about thoughts\r\n<li>Things go bump in the night\r\n<li>How does mud move, anyway?\r\n<li>Who am I?\r\n<li>WHo are you?\r\n<li>Again, how do you know?\r\n<li>WHen to be tolerant and when to just say \"that\'s just dumb!\"\r\n<li>THe power of meditation\r\n<li>THe power of prayer\r\n<li>My authority to say these things\r\n<li>Are we not gods?\r\n<li>The nature of consciousness.\r\n<li>How can I be so ignorant?\r\n<li>The 3 things -- body, mind, spirit; physical, mental, spiritual\r\n<li>Theology\r\n<li>Socrate\'s hidden message\r\n<li>A head without thoughts?\r\n<li>where is your center of thought\r\n<li>How your brain works\r\n<li>the seat of conciousness\r\n<li>dawkins\r\n<li>science: more questions\r\n<li>your body\r\n<li>your mind\r\n<li>your spirit\r\n<li>body vs spirit\r\n<li>mind vs spirit\r\n<li>body vs mind\r\n<li>love under will\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n','2011-10-03','2012-01-21 20:02:16'),(635,63,'DAM','<h3>Socrates</h3>\r\nBriefly, the message from socrates is that EVERYONE is dumber than they think. (um, that would INCLUDE Socrates. you, too. And me.\r\n\r\nLet\'s go over this in more detail. Socrates was a philosopher. He never wrote anything down so most of what he did and believed we know from his student Plato. But what we think he did was that he spent a lot of time in the public market place (which, in Athens, was a market place of ideas as well as things), talking to various people about what they knew. He asked questions (now known as the \"Socratic Method\"). Typically he gave people choices. \"Who should know more about horses, you who recite poetry aloud, or a person who works with horses?\" Generally he would push people into a corner in which they admitted that they didn\'t really know as much as they thought they did. This, of course, made them feel foolish and did not make them love him very much. \r\n\r\nTo me, he comes across as a know-it-all who is trying to prove how smart he is and is generally being a jerk to everyone around him. IN the end they killed him for it (technically he was accused of corrupting the youth and heresy but I\'m pretty sure they killed him because he was getting under their skin and maybe because the son\'s of the influential people were asking embarrassing questions). \r\n\r\nWhy he did this was open to debate. He said he did it to prove that he was not the wisest man in the world (which he claimed the Oracle at Delphi said he was) and to be the horse fly that stung the body politic to wake it up. But the context of these comments were, to my mind, places where he might have said things he didn\'t believe. \r\n\r\nIn any event, I think his purpose in doing this was to demonstrate that no one was as smart as they claimed. I think he was trying to get everyone to question their beliefs. \r\n\r\nIf I\'m right, his whole purpose, the purpose he followed for much of the end of his life, was to make the point that we don\'t know much and certainly not as much as we think. \r\n\r\nThis is an extremely important thing to realize. Most of what you know is wrong, in fact, and the fact that you believe you\'re correct makes you doubly wrong. \r\n\r\nThere\'s a lot of other lines of evidence that suggests the same thing. For example, modern scientists have been studying why we believe what we believe and have been finding evidence in study after study that shows that we have horrible biases. We tend to find evidence for what we already believe in, we tend to put faith in our emotions over our reason, we are more likely to believe what we\'re told than what we see. In study after study evidence accumulates that we don\'t think as well as we think we think. \r\n\r\nWhat are we to do with this information? Should we think about it? Take it to heart and question everything?\r\n\r\nThe problem is that we will simply follow an inward spiral. It\'s clear that we\'re not as smart as we think we are but it\'s also clear that if we question every thought we\'ll have to question that questioning and, since we have no way to resolve any of this, we\'ll just sit in the dark wondering if we know anything. \r\n\r\nThe only way out is to assume that our perceptions and beliefs are basically sound but to not take them very seriously. HOld your thoughts lightly. ','2011-10-07','2011-11-13 21:07:32'),(636,63,'DAM','<h2>Rules Are Made To Be Broken</h2>\r\nThe good thing about rules is that they force us to look at what we believe. Take the law against marijuana. Let us imagine that you like to smoke a bowl occasionally. You must weigh your desire to get high against the fact that it\'s against the law. To what degree do you value conformance? To what degree will the law be enforced, by which I mean how likely is it that you will be caught and what are the consequences of that? To what degree are you willing to modify your behavior to reduce the risks? \r\n\r\nMeantime, the people who put the rules in place are making a similar calculation. How important is it that people not smoke marijuana? How much money and trouble do we want to expend to prevent people from doing that? \r\n\r\nThis is kind of a conversation between the people who make the laws and the people who might break the laws. They may never talk to each other but the conversation goes on, each on it\'s own side, and each effects the other through enforcement. \r\n\r\nWhen they were arresting civil rights activists in the south, the activists came up with a novel strategy: don\'t make bail. Instead of arresting people for supposed crimes, forcing them to pay a fine (in the form of bail) and then releasing them, the authorities suddenly found themselves in possession of a bunch of rowdy civil rights activists. There was a limit to how many they could hold at any one time, and the activists would break the rules of the jail (singing was a favorite tactic) which forced the jailers to address trivial issues. The government couldn\'t let them go and it couldn\'t do much worse to them than put them in jail without violating it\'s own rules. \r\n\r\nThe point of this is not in the practical sense of \"if you don\'t like a law, go ahead and break it.\" In general, I would be an advocate of following all the laws and rules of a society or situation simply because it helps to go with the flow in most situation. But from a spiritual perspective, rules fullfill a specific role. They are NOT anything inherent to the universe, even the ones that we right down and SAY come from the Almighty.\r\n\r\nI should here make a distinction between laws that are written down and laws that just are. The \"laws of physics\" are a written down version of the way the phsysical universe works. You can violate those laws to the degree that they do not actually describe how the universe actually works. But, as far as I know, you cannot\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Rules Are only Made In Enemy!</h2> \r\n','2011-11-13','2011-11-15 16:27:18'),(637,112,'davemenc',' ','2011-12-31','2011-12-31 18:35:21'),(638,112,'DAM','The first thing I remember is playing in the back yard with my borthers and systerm. We had a sand box that my father made (lterally a board box, filled with sand. He used to subscribe to popular mechanics and this had thise little wordless cartoons tht showed a man building things. It wouldn\'t surprise me if the sand box was such a project. \r\n\r\nI remember that we used to like to fill it with water and make channels and rivers out of it. Damns and roads and so forth. Of course, we\'d come in all bedraggled and muddy. \r\n\r\nThe lot our house was on was farily large and covered with grass. In front there was a row of fruitless mulberrry trees that were enourmous and in the back there were dwarf fruit trees. a plum, an apricot, a peach tree, a cherry tree. Near the sandbox was a giant willow tree. and on the side yard was a gnarled fig tree.I also remember a swing set which probably had a slide attached. I remember it used to rock back and forth when we swung really high until my father -- always the handyman -- cemented the legs into the ground. \r\n\r\nAll around the perimeter of the land were hedges. In the back and on the side, they were huge, more than 3 feet thick and taller than I was (taller than I was at any age -- by the time I reached my full height they towered 8 feet tall). In the front they were modest. Our front door had a concrete walk that ran bolt straigh to the sidewalk in front of our house. Flanking either side of it just as it came to the small concrete front porch and right in front of the eves, were two Italian cypresses. On the street end were two buches flanked the walk making it seem more regal and manastorial than it really was. After all it was just a long, low ranch style home, one story high with a front door, a back door and a door into the garage. \r\n\r\nWhen I was young I was perpetually desperate to be involved in whatever my older brothers and sisters were doing. I understand that this was true of my #3 brother who was desperate to be involved in the activities of #1 & #2 brothers. They were all much older than me and had concerns that were as remote from my young considerations as a dog\'s considerations were from an ants. I spent most of my time with my older sister -- the younger of 2 sisters both of whom were younger than my three brothers -- who was only 3 years my senior. My dear system may have destperately wanted to hang with our older sibs as well but she was stuck tiwh me, \r\n\r\nShe did her best to get what amusements she could out of me, dressing me up in wacky womens clothing and teasing me relentlessly until I cried. I can still hear her saying \"I was going to give you this but now I\'m not\". Of course she was never going to give me anything but she like to torment me. And when was was two and she was 5 or I was three and shee was six or I was 8 and she was 11 she always had the upper hand.k \r\n\r\nI have a dim recomllection that my brothers and systers took some of my stuffed animals and hung them and buried the. It\'s concevable that this was aome really bizarre dream I had when I was very young (although where would a young person get such an idea) or even a memory that formed later. It was such a long time ago, how can I know? But I remember remembering this when I was very young so I think that, rathing than it\'s being an early sign of mental illness on my part it was something my siblings really did. i would guess that someone who was much older (a teenager, I would think) ran accorss some story of executions and it formed a temporary morbid attraction for them which they chose to play out with my stuffed animal. I, of course, being desperate for attention, was more than happy to go along with them, although I remember later being very upset at the loss of the stuff animal. I Think it was a bear. In any event, what I remember was that they hanged the bear from the swingset and then buried it somewhere in the back yard. THe hanging would not rally have hurt it but when the burial naturally got it all durty and wet which made it unfit for further use. I can only imagine what my parents thought of all this. \r\n\r\nI had friends in the neighborhood, although I\'m not sure we were very close. We went to different schools but if we wanted to play with someone outside of school it was going to have to be us unless our parents would drive us somewhere -- oh the joys of suburban living. \r\n\r\nWe lived on the edge of a court (Gregory Court, perhaps) and we often played games in the court which, having no through traffic, was relatviely sfe. I remember looking up at the sky in those day of youre and seeing the milky way very clearly whcih you can hardly do now anywhere in the Greater Sacramento Area now. We played kick ball and hide and seek and had our disputes one person against everyone else. I\'m sure I was on either side of that at various poings. \r\n\r\nMy friend TOm was the most interesting among us. His father would get all kinds of surplus gear and his family lived on a double lot (that is, there was another empty lot behind his main lot). This second lat hid behind a fences and it was full of random stuff, nail-filled boards, weeds, old parts of various machines. And Duchess the German Sheppard dog. What a delightful place to play. Sometimes TOm would have big sppols of wire which he would bring out into the court and we would take turns rolling around. If you stook on it and walked backwards you could get it to move forward. You had almost no control but you could get it to move. \r\n\r\nWe spent a lot of time climbing on to the fences in the neighborhood and walking along them. We became verycapable in this regard as we got older. A sizx foot fense was not any kind of an impediment but, rather, a roadway for us to move round on, rather like a roman road which was used for both transport and defence. \r\n\r\nTom built a fort in his back yord, out of playwood and 2x4s. Perhaps his father helped him -- I wasn\'t involbed in the building of it. As I remember it, it had electricity and loads of army surplus gear that was covered in swithces.Probably some kind of uncommunications stuff but now  we were the crew of lost in space or undersea explorers. We would play at this from the day that school got out in June until we had to go back in september. Tom provided the expertise and the equimpment to create the sets but I think it was my fertile imagination that provided the scenarios. \r\n\r\n','2011-12-31','2011-12-31 18:35:43'),(639,112,'DAM','The best part about the house we lived in in Carmichael was the tree. Not the fruitless mulberry trees in the front -- they were useless. BUt the fruit trees in the back and the fig tree on the side and even the willow tree were brilliant. ','2012-01-01','2012-01-01 18:37:19'),(640,63,'DAM','<h2>Fear</h2>\r\nIn the book Dune, fear is described as \"the little death that brings total annialation\". I think of fear as an obstacle to be overcome. If you do not overcome it fear will kill your dreams, kill your hope and make life impossible to live. \r\n\r\nI want to be clear on this: fear protects you. You can be happy, you can be safe, you can live a long and comfortable life by always heeding your fears. But it will not be the life you were meant to live, not the life you could have lived if you overcame your fears.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do when dealing with fears is to know they are there and what they are about. Quite often we imagine that we are going about our live long day without fear but what we\'re really doing is avoiding fear so thoroughly that we aren\'t even aware that we afraid of some things. \r\n\r\nI find that even thinking about doing something I\'m afraid of makes my stomach twist in knots. I try, every day, to think about doing all manner of bizarre things that I would probably not actually want to do. Quit my job, divorce my wife, take up with that pretty blonde, give all my money to charity, volunteer with a church -- I just keep thinking up stuff that I could do. When I hit something that upsets me or makes me nervous I say to myself \"ah ha! there it is, I\'m afraid of that.\" Sometimes it\'s hard to know, because I\'m feeling emotional without knowing why. But if I keep picking at it, thinking about the emotion, looking at what makes it feel better or worse, eventually I can figure out what made me upset. \r\n\r\nThere are three ways to overcome fear. I don\'t count in this those things I never think about doing because I\'ll be afraid of them -- that\'s not overcoming fear that simply avoiding it. I\'m only counting things where I know I have a fear and I face it squarely and the fear is gone. \r\n\r\nThe first and most common is repetition.l I was afraid of driving once but now I drive 40 miles a day. I SHOULD be afraid. I am very likely to die in a car accident simply because it really is dangerous and I\'m doing it every day. But long acquaintance with the fear makes it mute.\r\n\r\nThe second is mastery. Once I\'ve done something well and succeeded at it I need no longer fear it. The fear is proved to be groundless. The nervousness subsides and I find myself in a postive loop -- the more I do well the less fear I feel so the more I can do well.\r\n\r\nThe third way is by far the jmost important. It\'s when I know I have a fear, I know it\'s real, I have very good reasons to fear but I do the thing anyway. This is the key because, of course, I can\'t do the other two things until I do this one. \r\n\r\nThe only way I know to overcome fear is to want the thing you get for moving forward more than you don\'t want the thing that you are afraid of. It\'s like an equation: [desire for good outcome] - [fear for bad outcome] = [energy to move forward]\r\n\r\nIt\'s important here that I understand very well exactly what I\'m afraid of and what, exactly, I\'m hoping to gain. \r\n\r\nI know I would be afraid to jump off a bridge with a bungie cord around my waist. Could I do it? Sure. But I won\'t and the reason is that there is no pay off. What I\'m afraid of is that I will be killed in the fall and I know that is extremely unlikely (although possible). But my payoff would be that I get the thrill, the excitement, the exhilaration of free fall and I don\'t really like free fall. I don\'t find it pleasant and I don\'t really want to do it. So I won\'t. But if you would like to offer me $1000 (or something else good) then that would tip the equation the other way.\r\n\r\nI used to be terribly afraid of public speaking. Why? I was afraid that I would look like a fool, that people wouldn\'t like what I had to say and that they would think less of me. I wanted to get my thoughts out but I was afraid of the negative consequences. I overcame my fear of speaking simply because I stopped caring what other people think of me. (I know this sounds unlikely and even, perhaps, a bit cold, but it\'s true.) \r\n\r\nIn this case, the upside hasn\'t changed but the negative consequence went away. Pretty much, for 2 cents I\'d recite the Gettysburg Address stark naked. (So why don\'t I? Well, it would be annoying to a lot of the people around me. Their annoyance is a negative consequence for me, not because I care what they think but because they are me and I don\'t want to be annoyed. But there\'s no fear operating here. If I was convinced that it would be a net benefit -- a profit of at least 2 cents -- I wouldn\'t hesitate.)\r\n\r\nI\'ve been talking about this in stark, almost mathematical terms. But that\'s not how fear works. Fear is an emotion, one might almost say fear is THE emotion, and so it\'s harder than I make it sound to buck it. \r\n\r\nRecently, I have found that I have a major fear in my life. I am on a spiritual path that I am afraid will take me away from my cozy comfortable existence. I like my 9-5 job and my cozy suburban home and living with my wife, having the kids visit on holidays. It\'s nice. And I\'m afraid that my path will lead me away. \r\n\r\nMore than that I\'m afraid that, since I have no teacher or adviser, I will convince my self that I don\'t need to leave my cozy existence when, indeed, I do. I\'m afraid and I\'m afraid of that fear. \r\n\r\nON the other side, I have learned that the universe protects me from my more egregious mistakes and nurtures me in my fears, reassures me and keeps me moving forward. What I need more than anything is faith that I will be supported in life and will be able to keep moving forward. \r\n\r\nIn the end, there is only one way to overcome fears. Work out what they are and, one by one, do the thing that we fear. If we can do it once, we can do it again and then the fear has no power over us.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-01-03','2012-09-23 18:10:00'),(641,63,'DAM','<h2>Golden Rule</h2>\r\nWe usually consider it a good thing to do unto others as we would have them do unto us. It\'s the golden rule, right? But, in point of fact, other people are not us and they don\'t necessarily care about the same things we do. \r\n\r\nI don\'t mean to attack the Things You Learned in Kindergarten but this is a next step. We start out being completely selfish. Then we develop empathy which is the ability to imagine that other people feel the way we do and so would be affected by things the same way we are. Then we spend a LONG time, decades at least and perhaps our entire lives, trying to figure out what, exactly we want and, by implication, what the people around us might want. \r\n\r\nThe fact is, we don\'t know what other people want. Talking to your sock puppet model of the people around you will not help you understand them better. \r\n\r\nThe next level of relationship, then, is to talk to the people around us, ask them what they want and really listen. The problem that often comes up here is that we ask and we hear them say either what we expected or what we imagine we would want. And so, in the end, we give them what WE want rather than what THEY want. \r\n\r\nIn order to get past this we need to do what\'s sometimes called active listening. This is listening to the other person and really trying to get what they\'re saying, asking them, \"reading back\" what they told you, as you understnad it. \"You want, WHAT? I never would have guessed.\" And THEN, when we feel we truly understand, then we try to be of service. Or not. As you will.\r\n\r\nThere is another level to this as well which involves understanding other people directly by feeling what they feel and by seeing from their point of view. I have not mastered this, yet. Indeed I am only just convinced that it\'s possible. But I am thoroughly convinced that it is necessary.\r\n','2012-01-21','2013-02-19 00:16:25'),(642,42,'DAM','The basic entity on the site is the SET. This consistes of two tables. \r\n\r\nThere is a directory of sets which consist of the set description, the key description, the value description, the owner, the set number and whether this is public and, perhaps, a few other attributes. This is kind of the master table of sets.\r\n\r\nThe second table is the list of the elements in the sets. Each element has an id, a key, value, a set number and a type. The type describes what kind of value this is. It can be a word (that is a short string), text (that is, an arbitrary large amount of text). an image, a set (that is, a set can contain a set), or some other kind of object. \r\n\r\nEach of these objects, which are elements of sets, have their own unique table but it\'s simple. It has an id, the object (the actual image or a url to an image, the actual text, the string, or whatever other kind of thing is is) and an optional description of the object. Each table is a unique kind of thing that can be in a set.\r\n\r\nNow any kind of thing can be created using these combinations of sets of sets. ','2012-01-23','2012-01-24 06:45:07'),(643,42,'DAM','The idea is that any arbitrary kind of thing can be constructed out of a list of more basic things. \r\n\r\nSo you want a picture gallery? It\'s a set of elements each consisting of a set of 2 objects, a picture and a caption.\r\n\r\nIf each set in the list has a generic type then you can create layouts. Now you define the type you want it to be and the way you want it layed out and you can represent anything and allow it to be displayed appropriately. And then you create a layout for editing it and you think you\'re editing a photo gallery but you\'re editing a list of lists!','2012-01-23','2012-01-24 06:48:35'),(644,63,'DAM','<h2>Questions</h2>\r\nWe have questions. There are tons of things we don\'t know and we are taught from a young age to ask questions. \"the only stupid question is the question that is not asked\" and so forth.\r\n\r\nBut not all questions are created equal.\r\n\r\nFirst off, notice that the \"question words\" -- who, what, here, when, how, why -- all have wind sounds associated with them. This suggests that questions are associated with the element of air which is associated with thinking and thought. \r\n\r\nSo questions are appropriate when you want to think about something or when you are thinking about something and you want information about what you are thinking about. \r\n\r\nSome people think all the time, to the point where they actually can\'t imagine what it means to not think. They may believe that they are not thinking at all.\r\n\r\nOthers may think very seldom and may, in turn, believe that they are thinking all the time. \r\n\r\nThe difficulty is that I can\'t know what your experience is and vice versa so we all pretty much assume that everyone else is having our experience. \r\n\r\nIf, in fact, you happen to be a person who thinks all the time, you may wish to set aside some time for stillness in which you choose not to think. Likewise if you happen to be a person who never thinks very much you might want to set aside some time for thought. \r\n\r\nQuestions, as I\'ve already suggested, are thought provoking things. It is generally good to ask questions about things that you want to think about and to not ask questions about things that you want to access without thoughts. \r\n\r\nFor example, if you want to know how a steam engine works, questions will get you well on the road to that understanding. If, on the other hand, you wish to contemplate the Infinite, questions will not be helpful because the Infinite cannot be comprehended by your thoughts. \r\n\r\nQuestions, then, put us in a thinking state and can be useful or harmful depending on what we\'re trying to accomplish.\r\n\r\nAll questions are not created equal, however. The who, what, when questions evoke a concrete answer. A person place or thing is the answer to who, what, where. The part of speech associated with those answers is the noun and that generally brings us to specific object, person or location. \r\n\r\nObviously, I can construct a question using who, what, where that will elicit a non-concrete answer (Who is the Creator of the Universe? Where do we go when we die? And so forth). But these questions are unanswerable. It certainly is fun to ask questions that have no answer such as \"Can God make a rock that He can\'t pick up?\" but their only actual use is to shut down your thought process. \r\n\r\nThe question \"when\" is like who, what, where in that it elicits a specific time but, of course, time is an abstract concept. You can\'t hold a time in your hand the way you can a rock. Other than that, when is pretty much like who, what and where. \r\n\r\n\"How?\" is a question that elicits a process. The answer will always be a series of steps.\r\n\r\nWhy is a very special question because it elicits a motivation. Sometimes people ask why questions when they really mean \"how\". For example \"why does the sun rise\" probably means \"how does the sun rise\" or \"what processes are involved with the sun rising?\" rather than \"what is the sun\'s motivation for rising\". \r\n\r\nThe question \"why is he dead?\" is a good example of a why question that has deep roots. The answer might be \"because he bled to death\" or \"because a bullet entered his body and cut an artery\" or \"because the expanding gasses of the burning gunpowder propelled the bullet into his body\"  or \"because someone fired a gun at him\" or \"because John hated him\". At each stage I can ask \"why did that happen\" and dig one step closer to the motivation.\r\n\r\nIn this sense, why and how are similar. Both invite a discussion of a chain of events. But how is really about the chain itself while why is more about the first action.\r\n\r\nYou can keep going back and back and back until you get to \"why did God create the universe?\" I do not wish to invalidate the question; indeed, I would love to know the answer. But if the answer is knowable, I doubt that the knowledge of that answer starts with a question.','2012-02-03','2012-02-03 22:15:33'),(645,63,'DAM','<h2>Observations</h2>\r\nIt is possible to find things out without asking questions. \r\n\r\nIf I want to know why God created the Universe I can find this out by keeping the question in mind and paying attention to everything around me. \r\n\r\nIf one awaits long enough, eventually, the Truth will be revealed. \r\n\r\nThis is not quite like mediation in the traditional sense but it is an application of what you might learn from practicing mediation. It requires holding something in mind without actually thinking about it for a long time. \r\n\r\n','2012-02-03','2012-02-03 22:21:13'),(646,63,'DAM','<h2>Awaiting</h2>\r\nA man stands by the side of the road. Since the sign says \"bus stop\" we assume he\'s waiting for a bus. He seems anxious, he might be looking down the road for his bus or checking his watch. The man next to him is unconcerned, he\'s just reading a paper. He\'s not even here, he\'s just doing something else. \r\n\r\nThis is waiting. It\'s an activity. It involves ignoring who and where you are and either focusing on what is about to happen -- whatever you are waiting for -- or checking out and doing something else.\r\n\r\nI often notice people at a light. They are reving their engine, anxious to go. They seem impatient for the light to turn green. When the light finally turns green, they usually aren\'t paying attention. Sometimes the guy behind (all too often, me) needs to give a short honk to get their attention.\r\n\r\nThis is one of the aspect of waiting: one cannot keep ones attention on something that is not happening. We typically go internal and \"drown out\" what\'s going around us with some internal musings. This is because we don\'t like what\'s going on around us -- the bus isn\'t coming so we\'re going to check out.\r\n\r\nBest case, you can use that time that the bus isn\'t here -- that \"dead\" time -- to read the paper.\r\n\r\nThis is all in stark contrast to \"awaiting.\" Awaiting is not an activity, it\'s a state. To be fair, I can\'t see much point in \"awaiting\" a bus or even a light. \r\n\r\nBut there are many things that we want in life that will come in good time but whose timing we do not control. A \"relationship\" for example. Some waiting for a relationship is actually pretty unpleasant. They tend to have a series of hopeful but disappointing encounters with various people. When they aren\'t dating someone they are anxiously looking and then they grab at whatever \"opportunity\" arises and are all excited and then they crash and burn and \"give up\" for a while. During that period the right person wouldn\'t be noticed if he or she was wearing a sign while during the anxious period anyone looks like Mr./Mrs. Right.\r\n\r\nOne who is awaiting a relationship would be pleasant to be around. They are engaged in their environment. They are with the people they are with and when they are alone they are with themselves. They live in the Now, not in the illusory \"Then\". But they are always available and aware of the thing they want. They are looking for it ALL THE TIME but they are never focused exclusevly on it.\r\n\r\nThis is the key to awaiting. A person who is focused on that hasn\'t happened gets more of that -- the thing not happening. THe person who focusses on what IS happening get more stuff happening. THat make more stuff available and gives them more choices. \r\n\r\nBe aways aware of what you want but focus on what you have. \r\n\r\nThis can result in a person evaluating every person and saying \"nope, not right, nope, not right.\" But that\'s not what I mean. If you really engage with the person in front of you, you will find them delightful. Or annoying. Or frustrating. Or something. You will find them to be WHAT THEY ARE, at least what they are in relationship to you. That\'s engagement, that\'s attention. Keep that up and eventually someone will come along and you\'ll find that you\'re having fun with them. Eventually, it will occur to you that you\'re in a relationship. \r\n\r\nLife is what happens while your making other plans. Awaiting is the way you make the life that happens align with your dreams. Be who you are, focus on what presents itself. But always keep your dreams in mend.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-02-03','2012-03-03 18:06:16'),(647,113,'davemenc',' ','2012-02-12','2012-02-12 18:54:55'),(648,113,'DAM','I Why Infusions? \r\n\r\nII Basic Infusion Techniques\r\n A. Alcohol Selection\r\n B. Alcohol Preparation\r\n C. Containers\r\n D. Material Preperation\r\n E. Proportions\r\n F. Durations\r\n G. Removing the Material\r\n H. Filtering\r\n I. Bottling\r\n J. Safety\r\n K. Artistry\r\n\r\nIII Candy Infusions\r\n A. Skittles\r\n B. Jolly Ranchers\r\n C. Werthers Caramel\r\n D. Cooked\r\n E. Chocolate Malt Balls\r\n F. Reeces Peanut Butter Cups\r\n G. Chocolate Candy\r\n H. burned dark sugar\r\n I. butter finger \r\n J. homemade caramel\r\n K. malted balls\r\n L. snickers\r\n\r\nIV Fruit Infusions\r\n A. Lemon\r\n B. Melon\r\n C. Peach\r\n D. Pomegranate\r\n E. Apple\r\n F. C antelope\r\n G. cherry\r\n H. granny smith apples\r\n I. Pomegranate\r\n J. Strawberry\r\n\r\nV Herbs & Spices\r\n A. Mint\r\n B. Cinnamon\r\n C. Basil\r\n D. Dill\r\n E. Lavender\r\n F. Mint\r\n G. Nutmeg\r\n H. Oregano\r\n I. Rosemary\r\n J. Sage\r\n K. Vanilla\r\n\r\nVI Vegetables\r\n A. Ginger\r\n B. Beets\r\n C. Carrots\r\n D. Jicama\r\n E. Beets\r\n F. Carrot\r\n G. Cucumber\r\n H. Habanero\r\n I. Tomato\r\n\r\nVII Other\r\n A. Bacon\r\n B. Coffee\r\n C. Tea\r\n \r\nVII Experiments\r\n\r\nVIII Drink Recipes\r\n\r\n','2012-02-12','2012-02-22 05:22:19'),(649,63,'DAM','\r\n<h2>Pleasure and Pain</h2>\r\nI\'ve noticed something very odd. When we have a complicated experience that mixes \r\npleasure and pain, we tend to forget how painful it was and remember the good parts. \r\n\r\nIt seems to be completely unconscious. I don\'t have to remind myself that there was also pleasure, I simply forget the pain.\r\n\r\nFor example, let\'s say I decide to build a deck in my back yard. I figure I can knock it out in a weekend so I start digging the holes for the foundation. Hours later and I\'m tired and appalled by how little I\'ve accomplished. The whole project takes many more days than expected, many problems crop up and maybe even a trip to the emergency room. \r\n\r\nEventually, after many trials and tribulations, I get the whole thing down. \"Never again,\" I mutter as I turn my back on the whole mess. \r\n\r\nBut other people like it and soon our social life revolves around the deck. Over the next year it proves to be a great addition to our home. \r\n\r\nSo when my friend asks me if I can help him put in a deck, I say \"sure!\" with enthusiasm. \"Decks are great!\" I think to myself. \r\n\r\nWhat the heck happened? Why don\'t I remember that I had a TERRIBLE time with my deck and that I swore I would NEVER do that again? \r\n\r\nThe same lesson plays out over and over, whether the effort is physical or emotional, whether the pain spills blood or tears. \r\n\r\nI think this is some kind of compensation mechanism. If we only avoided pain we would soon just shut down. Everything mankind does involves pain. But somehow if we derive long term advantage from it, we\'re willing to overlook the pain and do more of it. \r\n\r\nThus hovels turn into houses, sex turns into relationships, houses turn into villages and relationships turn into families, generation after generation. ','2012-02-15','2012-03-03 17:45:42'),(650,113,'DAM','Jicama\r\ncherry\r\ncucumber\r\nLemon\r\nstrawberry\r\nskittles\r\nmalted balls\r\nlavender\r\noregano\r\nrosemary\r\ntea\r\nhome made carmel\r\nbacon\r\nhomemade caramel\r\nburned dark sugar\r\noregano\r\nthyme\r\nsage\r\ndill\r\nmint\r\nhabanero\r\ncantelope\r\njolly rancher\r\nwerther\r\nginger\r\nponegranite\r\nvanilla\r\nbutter finger \r\nsnickers\r\nbeets\r\npeach\r\ntomato\r\ngranny smith apples\r\ncarrot\r\nbasil\r\n\r\nTODO\r\ncoffee\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-02-20','2012-02-22 05:04:01'),(651,113,'DAM','<h2>Why Infusions?</h2>\r\n<P>I always say that all my taste is in my mouth. ','2012-02-21','2012-02-22 05:34:18'),(652,113,'DAM','Chapter 1 Why Infusions\r\n\r\nI like flavors. I think I would say that all my taste is in my mouth. Cooking food creates fantastic flavors but it\'s complicated. The application of heat and the mixtures of flavors creates intricate flavor combinations. \r\n\r\nInfusions are simple and clean flavors. I can created a single flavor, all by itself. Then I can mix the flavors in various ways.\r\n\r\nThe best way to extract a flavor is with alcohol because it dissolves a much wider range of chemicals than water or oils or, pretty much, any other kind of liquid. Many of those chemicals are the flavor elements of the food. \r\n\r\nThere is also a long tradition of creating and mixing alcoholic beverages. THis is an area full of lore and history and it\'s generally appreciated by people. Being able to share a special alcholoic beverage is a real contribution to most parties. And being able to mix a special cocktail whose ingrediants were custom made from raw materials, is a unique skill. \r\n\r\n','2012-02-25','2012-02-26 05:21:16'),(653,63,'DAM','<h2>Our Little Boxes</h2>\r\nWe live in little boxes. We wander around in our boxes and never touch the edges. We believe that we are free but there is a hidden part of us directing us, encouraging us, sometimes screaming at us in fear, not to go near the edges. \r\n\r\nInitially our boxes are very small. We imprint the little things our parents do without having any idea why they do them. Overtime we have experiences we like or don\'t like and then we fear the things we were doing when we had the \"bad\" experiences and habitually do the things that we feel led to the \"good\" experiences. \r\n\r\nThese habits become reinforced in some instances as we have other experiences. We develop of network of \"good\" and \"bad\" actions that are a combination of things our parents showed us, things they told us, and things we tried that seemed to work or not work.\r\n\r\nConsequently, we live in the middle of a box that is outlined by our fears. We don\'t ever go near the edge and we relaly like to stay in the middle because we believe that\'s what will make us happy. \r\n\r\nA better metaphor than \"box\" might be if we imagine that we live on a spire. We are deathly afraid to get too close to the edges to the point where we pretend that there are no edges, lest we be tempted to go look over the edge. This is too scary.\r\n\r\nIt can hardly be imagined the depth and complexity of our efforts to avoid the edge. IT\'s not just that we\'re afraid to go near the edge. We\'re afraid to acknowledge that there IS an edge. We\'re afraid to do anything that might suggest that there could be an edge. We live in a very confined space which we delight in pretending is the entire universe. To even get near the edge of the box seems absurd.\r\n\r\nCharles P. Thorp. taught that the instructions for getting outside the box are written on the outside of the box. Which is certainly how it seems when you are inside the box. In my view, the box is irrelevant. There is no edge, there is no box, there are no walls. \r\n\r\nI\'ve heard that an elephant is trained not to wander off by staking one leg of the elephant when it\'s small. The elephant wanders around in a small space but, being young and not very coordinated, whenever it goes too small the rope pulls it\'s leg and it falls down. This is unpleasant so the baby elephant learns not to go too far. When the elephant gets large it never tests this lesson. If it did, it would simply pull out the stake and move on. But they don\'t even bother to stake full grown elephants because the elephants never test the rope.\r\n\r\nYou must be willing to test the rope. We all start out avoiding fear and unpleasantness and gravitating toward  pleasure. This seems like obvious common sense. But if we would grow, we must learn to test our fear. Like your tongue poking at a sore tooth, we must poke at our fears, find out what, exactly we are afraid of and then confront that fear. Over and over again, we must find and confront our fears. \r\n\r\nA word of caution is required here. It is possible to turn your world upside down and to habitually move toward our fears. The problem with this is that it\'s potentially unconscious. You do not want to go from unconsciously avoiding fears to unconsciously gravitating toward them. And we should always remember that fears, like pain, have a purpose in our life. They warn of something that can actually hurt us, physically or emotionally. As we explore our fears we should do so thoughtfully and consciously. \r\n\r\nI should make it clear that I\'m not talking about the kind of thrill seeking that causes people to jump out of airplanes, although I suspect that might have a use in this area. If one were terrified of heights to an unreasoning degree it might well help to overcome that fear but physical feats that confront the fear of heights. \r\n\r\nBut this would only be useful if one then used this new found victory over fear to confront other, internal fears. If one can jump out of airplanes but is still afraid of emotional commitment one is still in a box. This is the fundamental point: the box is not physical and cannot by overcome by physical actions. The fear is physical and is designed (perhaps by evolution) to protect us from physical threats but it\'s being misused by our lowest mind to constrain us in non-physical ways. \r\n\r\n','2012-03-01','2012-03-03 17:33:51'),(654,63,'DAM','<h2>The Man In Me</h2>\r\nI have been talking to myself. There is a part of me that does not speak but has a very real and vibrant consciousness of his (?) own. The conversation works best if I\'m half asleep and drifting in and out of consciousness. When I\'m awake, I get my say, then when I drift off to sleep, my friend gets to express himself. \r\n\r\nI find great joy in the ability to talk to him in this way. He has always been there for me, guiding me, helping me. I think about what I want to know, I go to sleep and in the morning I know. That\'s my little man. \r\n\r\nI depend on him, I work with him, he is my partner in all things. I love him. \r\n\r\n\r\nAll the meditation techniques, the tarot cards, all the tricks to get in touch with one\'s inner self are directed at talking to this person. And I just had a 20 minute conversation with him in the most pleasant way imaginable! Awesome!\r\n','2012-03-03','2012-03-03 16:38:39'),(655,63,'DAM','<h1>Experiences</h2>\r\nOk, your brain, or at least MY brain can distinguish between the most amazing differences but you have to give it a VERY wide variety of inputs. That means that you need to have the WIDEST possible range of experiences to make anything work. \r\n','2012-03-12','2013-02-19 00:18:01'),(656,40,'DAM','<h2>Tank Game</h2>\r\nThis is a turn based game. There is a board with interesting terrain. The board contains places of power, cities, or ail fields, or whatever. If you possess these you have a steady stream of points. With points you buy offensive and defensive units. \r\n\r\nNow each side buys tanks and robots (infantry) ','2012-03-19','2012-03-20 05:53:01'),(657,63,'DAM','<h2>My <i>Other</i> Selves</h2>\r\n\r\nFor the past 30 years and more, I\'ve found it very effective to go to\r\nbed with a challenge in mind. Maybe I\'m trying to come up with a game\r\nalgorithm or figure out what to do about my car or whatever. When I\r\nwake up, the answer comes to me, often in the shower. I am quite sure\r\nthat there is a part of me that works on these problems while I sleep\r\nand gives me the answers in my dreams. Sometimes I get them in a\r\ndream, sometimes I only get them when I have a few minutes to think\r\nabout the problem again (and the first time for every day is typically\r\nin the shower), sometimes I am awakened in the middle of the night and\r\nI run to record whatever the brilliant idea is.\r\n\r\nI\'m reading a book about magick  by a witch (Amber K, interestingly\r\nenough). I like it, even though I kind of get the feeling it\'s written\r\nfor a teenage girl. One thing the author says is that we have 3 parts\r\nto our psyche: the conscious self (\"me\"), the \"Younger Self\" (I assume\r\nthis is the part that gives me insights in my dreams) who likes\r\npleasure and is associated with our animal totems, our connection to\r\nthe earth and our dreams, and the \"Higher Self\".  (The HS communicates\r\nthough YS and is not, as far as I know, relevant to this discussion).\r\n\r\nI don\'t know from \"Higher Self\" but I feel that the \"Younger Self\" is\r\nthat part of me that has been guiding and supporting me all these many\r\ndecades. This is a big deal to me and I find that I am profoundly\r\ngrateful.\r\n\r\nSince I read that I\'ve been spending a few minutes as I go to sleep\r\nfeeling that love and gratitude. Sometimes when I\'m partially asleep\r\nin the morning or evening I\'ve felt that I\'ve had a conversation with\r\nmy Younger Self, although, by and large, I don\'t remember the exact\r\ndialog.  It has been very pleasant and exciting.\r\n\r\n4 times I remember that it has given me specific messages in my\r\ndreams. The first was when I decided I would call it \"Davie\" and I got\r\nthe clear message in a dream \"Don\'t call me by my name.\" This could\r\nmean several things but I take it to mean \"don\'t call me \'Davie.\'\" So\r\nnow I think of him as \"Younger Self\" or \"Yes\". He hasn\'t complained\r\nabout that but I suspect he has a more specific name.\r\n\r\n2 other times there was a clear message which seemed pretty cool but\r\nwhich, in my dream, I promptly avoided remembering by thinking about\r\nsomething else.\r\n\r\nLast night I wrote down the message on the wall with a blue ballpoint\r\npen. Then I immediately decided that the woman in the other room (my\r\nwife? my mother? certainly some kind of authority) would be annoyed so\r\nI got some rags and erased it. I couldn\'t really remove it but the\r\nvery act of being concerned about it meant that I forgot what the\r\nmessage was.\r\n\r\nIt is clear to me that some part of me is actively and aggressively\r\nBLOCKING the messages from my Younger Self.\r\n\r\nThat suggests that there is yet ANOTHER Self involved. I have the\r\nfeeling that it\'s trying to protect me from this new information. The\r\nYounger Self does not talk directly to me because that would be\r\ndangerous in some way so this Other Self is protecting me from that. I\r\nbelieve that the \"danger\" is not real. Maybe if I lived in a jungle.\r\nOr maybe some of the things YS has to say will be profoundly\r\ndisturbing. Or maybe YS just wants me to eat more sugary foods and\r\nspend more time fucking and Other self is concerned about that (in\r\nwhich case YS is Freud\'s ID and OS is Freuds Superego).\r\n\r\nOne way to look at this is to consider that, after 30 years of the\r\nYounger Self trying to get in touch with me, I\'m finally beginning to\r\nactually get the messages directly. I can\'t actually remember the\r\nmessages but it\'s still a huge step.\r\n\r\nBut I would like to be able to receive the messages and carry them\r\ninto a waking state. I\'m not looking for lucid dreaming or anything\r\nlike that, I just want to get Other Self from suppressing the\r\nmessages.\r\n\r\nIt may be that the key to this is to convince Other Self that it\'s OK\r\nby somehow assuaging it\'s fears. \"It\'s OK, I\'m in no danger, I\'ll stay\r\nout of the jungle, I\'ll avoid any weird behavior, I\'m OK.\"\r\n\r\nI may have this all muddled. And I\'m pretty sure that, in time, I will\r\ncome to understand this better.\r\n\r\nBut if you have any insight, for example experiences that suggest I\'ve\r\ngot this all wrong (or somewhat right), I\'d sure like to hear about\r\nit.\r\n-------\r\nI think we do this completely differently. I have all kinds of insights that I don\'t have conscious access to (don\'t allow myself to see, haven\'t figured out how to see, don\'t know what I\'m looking at, don\'t even know there\'s a question to which that might be the answer, whatever). The way I gain access is by exploring the problem space as thoroughly as I possibly can. I roll around in the question and then the answer presents itself. \r\n\r\nI know perfectly well that anything you or anyone else tells me, anything I read in a book, anything from the internet or anything I think up on my own is, at best, information. No amount of information will ever answer my question (not any real question). But information allows me to see which thing I don\'t know that I know is the thing I seek. \r\n\r\nPerhaps there\'s a better way to do it. Perhaps the answer comes before the question. Perhaps over the next 20 years I will learn that; I\'m not opposed. But I have developed THIS process over the LAST 20 years and it\'s, well, it\'s what I have to work with. \r\n\r\nIronically, this particular inquiry is in the hope that I will gain more direct access to the answers and not have to look everywhere to find my glasses only to find that I was wearing them the whole time. \r\n\r\nIt reminds me of what my teacher used to say: \"the instructions on how to get out of the box are on the outside of the box.\" That\'s not actually true as there really is no box but the point is that it\'s a useless thing to tell someone. I can\'t see how it could possibly help -- even now when I long ago broke that box down for kindling.  \r\n\r\nProbably pretty frustrating for you to watch and for that, I\'m sorry. But, well, there it is. \r\n','2012-03-25','2012-04-01 14:54:36'),(658,63,'DAM','<h2>Know Thyself</h2>\r\nThe single most important thing to know is yourself. Each of us has our own unique way of meeting the world. We each have things that make us happy or sad. Most importantly, each of us has a different way to organize our work and to approach a problem. \r\n\r\nFor example, I ted to approach problems very logically, perhaps it would be fair to say that I over think things.And yet I tend to get things done in a flighty way, flitting like a humminb bird from one task to another as the spirit moves me. \r\n\r\nAfter understanding how you work -- which can be done in the solitude of your own mind -- the next most important thing is to understand how the people around you work. To figure out your methods in relationship to others. \r\n\r\nThis is important because -- one assumes -- you will be working with other people. They will want to understand why you are approaching the problem the wy you are and they will, m ost importantly, want to know that you will succeed. This will require that you understand and accept their way of approaching problems so that you can explain your way in their terms. \r\n\r\nThis is actually all very difficult and complicated. Each of us has a collection of assumptions. We assume that the way we do things is the right way to do thing. This, by and large, is good because if we don\'t think we\'re doing it \"right\" we\'ll spend all our time trying to \"fix\" ourselves. But when we come in contact with others, they probably have different ways of doing things which they believe are the \"right\" ways. \r\n\r\nFirst we have to be tolerant of the processes other people use. When we think to ourselves, \"what the heck is he doing\" we then need to say \"that\'s OK, whatever it is, it probably works for him\". \r\n\r\nOnce we get to a point where we can accept that other people\'s processes are OK, then we need to spend effort coming to understand what they are doing and why. This will involve some careful, respectful communication but mostly it involves careful observation. Listen a lot. Only ask questions when you have built your relationship to the point where they trust you enough to tell you what\'s going on.','2012-04-01','2012-04-01 14:53:58'),(659,114,'davemenc',' I have been going to Burning Man for a few years. For the first year I was very concerned with survival. But then I got involved in complex theme camp and I became interested in building things. It is pretty amazing to get there a few days early, see the desert empty and naked and then see it fill up with, well, buildings. Temporary buildings, to be sure, but buildings. \r\n\r\nThere are lots and lots of discussion about how to survive Burning Man but I want to talk about what\'s next after that. How do you LIVE at Burning Man? \r\n\r\nWelcome to the Beyond Survival Blog. Here I plan to talk about all manner of subjects that most people never think about like how to use rebar and what makes a good structure. ','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 15:05:33'),(660,114,'DAM','<h2>Bungie Balls</h2>\r\nI admit that \"bungie balls\" sound like a disease like \"playa foot\" but they\'re actually a very useful little item. It\'s a stretchable loop attached to a little ball. You wrap the loop around something and then snap it over the ball and it holds it securely.\r\n\r\nTypically bungie balls are used to hold tarps onto poles so that they will stay on a structure. But, just as importantly, they ensure that the structure keeps together by putting tension on the tarps. We\'ll probably talk a little more about structures later.\r\n\r\nThe elasticity of the bungie ball is crucial for it to work (because otherwise it would just be \"rope\") but it\'s also important because it means that anything tied together with bungies has some give. If the wind picks up the bungies stretch and the tarp can move a little out of the way until the wind dies down. This give makes a structure put together with bungie cords a little safer in the wind than it would be with rope even though (actually because) it\'s a little less secure. It would be much better if a bungie ball broke than that the structure was blown down.\r\n\r\nBungie balls come in several sizes but it doesn\'t really matter what size you get. If a bungie ball is too long you can wrap it around the pole multiple times until it\'s tight. If it\'s too small you can simply add another one and chain them together. \r\n\r\nI\'ve found that the best way to use bungie balls is to take a bunch of them and loop them over one wrist. Then you pull them off one by one and push the loop through a grommet hole on your tarp, around the pole and then over the ball. \r\n\r\nWhen taking them down, you simply remove it and put it on your wrist. \r\n\r\nYou can use a single bungie ball to hook two or more tarps to a pole or to multiple poles or use it to secure a bundle of poles. We often use one to secure a stack of tarps together by looping one through a grommet of several tarps. \r\n\r\nOver time, the bungie part will become frayed or will lose it\'s elasticity. Since you usually use dozens on any given structure, it\'s no big deal if one breaks but be careful that they don\'t all go bad at once. \r\n\r\nIn short, I keep a few extra bungies in my gear (in addition to the ones there for a specific project) just in case I need to secure something.  \r\n','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 21:35:27'),(661,114,'DAM','<h2>Tarp Clips</h2>\r\nMost tarps have grommets around the edge that allow you to secure the tarp to a frame or a structure. Typically they are every 6 inches and typically they use up about 6\" of material (so a 10x10 tarp is really only 9.5x9.5). \r\n\r\nBut sometimes the tarp doesn\'t have grommets or you need to secure something other than a tarp or you just need more secure points. Tarp clips to the rescue. They come in two basic types.\r\n\r\nOne type has a set of jaws that clamp onto the edge of the tarp. This is a pretty common use case -- they basically replace or augment grommets that are along the edge. These can be pretty easy to use although some of them require some strength to lock into place or remove. Sometimes, if the tarp is thin and the forces are large, the edge can tear our. \r\n\r\nThe other type has two parts that sit on opposite sides of the tarp. One part pushes the tarp through the other part and then, through some method, locks into it. These have the advantage the they can be put anywhere on the tarp, not just on the edge. The disadvantage is that you pretty much have to have one hand on either side of the tarp (easy if the tarp is in a pile, not so easy if it\'s already attached to a structure). \r\n\r\nEither kind will work for most applications but I slightly favor the ones that can lock in the middle of a tarp. After all, I can put those either in the middle or on an edge but the edge ones only go on the edge. \r\n\r\nThe most important things about securing a tarp, whether with grommets or with clips is to ensure that you have enough anchor points. The more anchor points the less stress is on each individual points. So if it looks like it\'s about to tear out, add some tarp clips and maybe save the tarp. \r\n\r\nWhile I\'m on the subject, you can also add grommets to tarps. You buy a grommet kit and then follow the instructions. The advantage is that, properly done, it\'s as good as an original kit and it\'s a lot cheaper per grommet than tarp clips. The disadvantage is that it takes longer to put in each grommet and it requires a permanent hole in the tarp (which may or may not be what you want). \r\n','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 21:57:11'),(662,114,'DAM','<h2>Securing Things</h2>\r\nWind is a powerful force, especially on a vertical tarp held in place by, say, vertical poles. Say you have a standard Costco carport (which I usually just call \"a costco\" because it\'s SO common at Burning Man). It\'s area is 10\' by 20\' and it\'s perfectly vertical. Assuming the wind comes at it directly (that is, not at an angle), a 20 MPH wind puts about 800 pounds of force on the structure, while a 30 MPH wind puts 1800 pounds of force on it. A costco is really strong so it probably won\'t collapse under that  pressure* but if it\'s not held to the ground it will move.\r\n\r\nConsider the forces. The wind is trying to push it along the ground but the leeward legs (the legs away from the wind that will be in \"front\" of the motion) are going to get caught on the ground and \"dig in\" so the structure will very quickly try to rotate around those legs, even if they aren\'t secured. That means that the top will move forward and down and the bottom will move up and the costco will be on it\'s side. Then, of course, the wind will catch in the huge cavity of the structure and blow it along the ground until it gets caught on something and bent to pieces. \r\n\r\nWhat we need, then, is something that can keep the legs on the ground. Something that resists not just lateral motion along the ground but upward motion as well. This latter is particularly important because wind can sometimes enter a structure and, having nowhere else to go, lift the structure straight up. \r\n\r\nTo secure a structure we want something that will go deep in the ground and resist pulling up. Just a few inches isn\'t enough, it needs to be at least a foot long. Most people feel that 18\" is a good length. \r\n\r\nI like rebar for this. I use 2-3 foot pieces, hammer them into the ground and leave 6-8 inches sticking up to connect to the structure. I use 1/4\" for small structure and 3/8\" for heavier things.  You can also use fence posts, metal stakes or anything else. Just make sure it won\'t pull out and won\'t bend or break. Plus, you\'ll need to get it out eventually, so you don\'t want it to be too hard to pull up. And, of course, you need one for every leg of your structure so you don\'t want to spend too much.\r\n\r\nThen we need to secure the legs of our structure to that thing. The typical costco comes with little feet with 3 holes. If you put 3 8\" nails in the 3 holes it will only be secure until the first real wind storm and then you\'ll be in trouble. Leave the little feet at home. \r\n\r\nI\'ve seen people put the conduit or other pipes (like the poles of a costco) over the tops of the stakes. Don\'t do that; it won\'t hold the structure down. If you have every had to hold down a structure in a wind storm as it tried to rise off the stakes it was set on you would not use that technique.\r\n\r\nI like the \"Zee method\" (named for Bryan Zee who taught me how to do this): you put a stake (as I say, I like rebar) next to ever leg and then tape the leg to the rebar with duct tape. When you want to pull it up, just cut off the duct tape pull down the structure and then remove the rebar. \r\nFor extra security, you can add guy lines. You hammer a stake into the ground and tie a rope to it. Then you tie the other end of the rope to your structure. Ideally the stake will be at an angle so the force of the wind won\'t pull it out. And, of course, the rope should be strong. Be aware, also, that metal rods sticking up can be dangerous; more about that anon.\r\n\r\nOne final thought on putting up a structure. As you put your structure up there will come a time when it will be sufficiently large and covered with tarps as to present a tempting target to the wind but insufficiently attached to the ground. Try to minimize this period of time as much as possible and try to have some people around who are ready to grab the structure if it starts to blow away.\r\n\r\n\r\n* The next time someone talks about 70 MPH winds at Burning Man consider that the force on a costco would be about 10,000 pounds. I don\'t believe that a 2\" tube can take 5 tons of force and most structures are made of 1\" conduit so it\'s unlikely that a wind storm that left anything standing was 70 MPH. ','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 22:29:51'),(663,114,'DAM','<h2>I Love Rebar</h2>\r\nYes, I do. Let\'s start with straight rebar.\r\n\r\nStraight rebar can be used to secure anything. You hammer it in straight to secure vertical poles and then tape them to it or at an angle to do guy wires. \r\n\r\nIf you leave any part of the rebar exposed you should get something to top it. They make orange, mushroom shaped caps that you can buy at any hardware store but they want scandalous amounts of money for them. You can also top them with tennis balls (but I don\'t play tennis so I\'d have to buy new ones) or plastic bottles but these aren\'t very safe (imagine tripping and landing with your chest against a piece of rebar encased in a soda bottle -- it would still be a fearsome wound). If you get some plastic Ts for PVC piping you can top with those and it\'s almost (but not quite) as good as the mushrooms. Also be sure to light any rebar that sticking up at night and mark any guy lines you put up.\r\n\r\nIt would be even better if you could contrive to not have any rebar sticking up. That\'s why I tend not to put guy wires on things if I can avoid it. But if you can\'t avoid it, consider using hook or T or candy cane rebar. \r\n\r\nHook and T rebar is made by welding something to the top (either a cross piece or a hook). This means that you can hammer the rebar all the way into the ground with nothing sticking out. \r\n\r\nCandy cane rebar (in the shape of a candy cane) can be made with a 1/4\" pipe. You put it over about 3\" of the rebar, lay the rebar on the ground, put your foot on it and carefully lift the pipe up. Gradually curve the rebar around until it\'s bent double. Make as tight a curve as you can since it will be hard to hammer in if it\'s not pretty tight. \r\n\r\nWhen it comes time to pull the rebar out, you can use a pair of vice grips. You clamp the vice grips onto the rebar and twist back and forth until it\'s loose and then pull straight up. Twist and pull, twist and pull. If it\'s really stuck, pour a little water in to the hole. \r\n\r\nOr you can get a stake puller. It costs a bit but you can pull a dozen pieces up in the time it would take you to twist and pull one with vice grips.\r\n\r\nThe rebar you hammered all the way into the ground is a bit tougher. You have to dig it out a bit and then use a piece of rebar or a crowbar to get enough of the rebar out that you can twist it or pull it with the puller. \r\n\r\nWhatever kind of rebar you use and however you get it out, be sure to get it ALL out. There nothing worse than leaveing some rebar behind!','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 22:46:37'),(664,114,'DAM','<h2>Structures</h2>\r\nThere are several different kinds of structures appropriate to burning man. The key to all of them is that they provide shade and, often, some protection from the wind. \r\n\r\nTypically you usually have to pick between how clean your space is and how cool it is because a space can either be cooled by air moving through it (which will carry dust) or ','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 22:49:58'),(665,114,'DAM','Costcos\r\nyurts\r\ndomes\r\nwood framing\r\nscaffolding\r\n\r\nair conditioning\r\nevaporation\r\nwater management\r\nshowering\r\nmeals\r\n\r\n','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 22:51:22'),(666,114,'DAM','http://www.frameconnector.com/','2012-09-11','2012-09-11 22:56:37'),(667,63,'DAM','<h2>The Physical</h2>\r\nBy now, the reader will understand that I do not believe that the physical world is all there is. Nevertheless, the physical is not to be ignored. I would go so far as to say that everything here on earth begins with the physical. If you meet someone who claims that they have transcended the physical, try to shake his hand. If you can feel him, he\'s still here. QED.\r\n\r\nHowever spiritual you are, however otherworldly, however in touch with The Spirit you might be, one little contact with a speeding bus, one tiny fall from the 4th floor, one week without food or water and you will be wholly here in physical world. Or perhaps transitioned to a different plane. \r\n\r\nI don\'t mean to claim that there is no one who has mastered the physical world. I am suggesting that mastery of the physical world generally does not involve ignoring it but rather embracing it. \r\n','2012-09-19','2012-09-20 20:48:52'),(668,63,'DAM','<h2>Personality</h2>\r\nI had a teacher who taught that personality was an element of the ego and that, while we couldn\'t avoid ego (and still be alive) we could --\r\n\r\nI don\'t know much about ego but I\'ve spent years studying personality and I\'m afraid I strongly disagree. Our personalities are nothing more (and nothing less) than our collected preferences. You prefer to be around a lot of people, I prefer to be alone. I prefer to have my opinions acknowledged as being sound, you prefer to be constantly reconsidering your opinions. \r\n\r\nThe introvert can hang with a crowd and the opinionated can spend an evening reexamining his every belief. It\'s just that they will each hate the experience. And it costs them in willpower, which, it turns out, is a finite resource. \r\n\r\nIt\'s like you love carrots but hate Brussels sprouts. You can certainly order Brussels sprouts; there\'s nothing stopping you. But if you have them in a meal it won\'t be a good meal. On the other hand, if you order carrots, you\'ll be happy. If, for some strange reason, you could only order Brussels sprouts, you would actually begin to dread meals. \r\n\r\nThat\'s what our personalities are like: you are the way you are because you like it that way. You could be a different way, but it makes you feel bad and it tires you out and makes you dread situations where you have to do that. \r\n\r\nWe all compensate for these feelings. Usually we avoid the situations we hate but if we can\'t do that (sometimes you just have to be in a crowd) we find ways to compensate. For example, instead of interacting with the whole crowd, we\'ll find one person to interact with and focus on that person. \r\n\r\nOur whole lives revolve around these little compensations. Most choice are made, mostly unconsciously, out of avoiding rubbing up against our personalities. Most upsets come from our fears that we\'ll have to do something our personality doesn\'t like. \r\n\r\nThe truth is, why would you want to go through life doing stuff you hate? Why not just go along with the program and \"be yourself\" which usually means \"do what your personality dictates.\"\r\n\r\nBut there is a catch here. If you don\'t know what your personality wants from you or if you think this is just \"who you are\" then you\'ll constantly find yourself doing thing, avoiding things, and getting upset for no apparent reason. This creates all manner of drama and random behavior that everyone finds so unpleasant. \r\n\r\nIf you would leave drama and fear behind you must come to understand what your personality dictates for you. There is a lot of literature out there that categories and defines various personalities. Some of it works well for me and some of it doesn\'t seem to work at all. If you read some of this literature you might gain some insights. \r\n\r\nBut before you look at that, try this: look for choices and pay attention to which way you choose. Do you know why? Image yourself choosing in the opposite way. What would happen? Would you like it? In your mind imagine how you would feel. Is there upset? Fear? If you have no reaction or you can\'t think how you would feel, try it. Be an explorer in your life, be curious, find out your own secrets. You will gradually discover what makes you tick.\r\n\r\nArmed with this knowledge, you can now make real, integrated choices. Yes, I\'ll hate going into that crowd, but if Jin, the love of my life, wants me to, maybe I\'ll give it a try. Or maybe if Jin keeps insisting I do things that are hard and uncomfortable for me, I\'m better off with a different friend. \r\n\r\nI want to make it clear that I don\'t believe you necessarily can or should \"learn to like\" things that you don\'t currently like. It\'s true that over time our personalities (and our tastes) change so it\'s not bad to try old things again (especially if you\'re young) but this isn\'t a moral issue. There is no \"one size fits all\", no one way that\'s right for everyone in life. \r\n\r\nFinding out who you are is imperative. You can never be a real person if you don\'t know that. But setting out to change yourself is a fool\'s errand. If it doesn\'t end in catastrophe (and you\'ll be lucky if it doesn\'t) it will certainly end in failure. \r\n\r\nIf I am skeptical about attempts to change oneself I am absolutely against any attempt to change anyone else. The lover who gets into a relationship thinking they will \"fix\" their partner is engaging in destructive and, yes, I\'ll go there, evil behavior. Why? Because they\'re model for \"correct\" behavior is based solely on their own personality. To drive someone away from their own personality is just plain mean, especially if they\'re too stupid to see what a trap it is.','2012-09-23','2012-09-23 17:40:46'),(669,14,'DAM','You can own a plot of land. And you can own each improvement on the plot of land. An improvement may be thought of as a \"floor\". Each floor costs a bit more and is worth a bit more. So the first floor costs, say, $100. The 2nd floor costs 1.5 as much as the first and so on. Floors can be bought and sold just like plots. They are distinct so a plot can be bought or sold without affecting any of the floors. \r\n\r\nThere are 2 different kinds of improvements: residential and commercial. To determine how much you pay you consider the total floors (not value) of commercial and the total floors of residential. The one with more is worth less while the one with less is worth more. This could be linear but it may be more fun if it isn\'t, thus providing a huge incentive to be the owner of the lesser one AND a huge incentive to build more of the lesser one. If MORE is the total floors of the one that has more (max(resfloor,comfloors)) and LESS is the total floors of the one that has less (min(resfloor,comfloors)) than the value for the lesser one is multiplied by LESS^2/MORE^2 and the value of the greater one is MORE^2/LESS^2. This is the IMPROVEMENT TYPE MULTIPLIER.\r\n\r\nThe owner of a plot of land may set one of 4 states for his plot which affects who may build on his plot: 1) No building; 2) Residential building only; 3) Commercial building only; 4) any building. I\'m not sure anyone would do anything but \"any building\" but he should have the right. \r\n\r\nThe key to the whole game is how much each floor pays off. The base value of an improvement (floor) is how much was paid to create it originally. The \"base value\" of a plot of land is calculated as the total of all the base values of all the floors. The \"total value\" of a plot of land is the base value of the plot of land plus the LESSER of  the base value of every other plot of land divided by the square of the distance divided by 10 and the base value of the plot (that is, the added value of all the other plots of land can never be more than the value of the plot of land).  The \"ratio value\" of a floor (improvement) should be calculated as: the base value of the floor divided by the base value of the plot.\r\n\r\nEvery turn each floor generates FLOOR_INCOME = the TOTAL_VALUE_OF_PLOT times the RATIO_VALUE_OF_FLOOR times the IMPROVEMENT TYPE MULTIPLIER divided by 10. The plot itself generates PLOT_INCOME = TOTAL_INCOME (the sum of all the floor incomes) divided by 10. \r\n\r\nNote that an empty plot of land generates no income at all.\r\n\r\nOn any turn, a player may do any or all of the following as many times as he can afford:\r\nBid on any plot of land owned by the bank\r\nBid to add an improvement to any plot (minimum bid is the greater of the cost for that floor # and the current bid+1)\r\nAdd a floor he owns to the auction\r\nAdd a plot he owns to the auction\r\nBid on a floor already in the auction\r\nBid on a plot of land that is in the auction already\r\n','2013-01-06','2013-01-06 22:36:26'),(670,63,'DAM','<h2>Context</h2>\r\nCommunication depends on context. Everything we say or do or think or perceive \r\nhas meaning only because there is a context behind it. If you don\'t know the context you can\'t decode the meaning. Of course, you have SOME context so you will assign SOME meaning to whatever you see or think or hear. \r\n\r\nThe key point is that without that context the thing has no inherent meaning. In a sense the context IS the meaning. And if I tell you something and your context is radically different from mine, you will hear something completely different from what I meant. \r\n\r\n\"Context\" is a very broad word and it\'s hard to nail it down to narrowly and still have the broad statement be true. ','2013-02-01','2013-02-01 18:26:05'),(671,115,'davemenc','We open on a young man driving. He regrets going out that night. he regrets ordering the fish; should have had the hamburger. He regrets not hitting on the waitress. We goin into some detail about his evening. It is quite clear he\'s a moron. \r\n\r\nHis mother regrets that he didn\'t make something of his life. She should have insisted that he go to college. She should have saved more for his college fund. She should have hassled him in highschool to get better grades. Maybe it\'s not her fault; maybe it\'s his biological parent. She regrets that line of thought almost immediately...\r\n\r\nHis biological mother regrets giving him up. it\'s a theme in her life. She gave him up because he was an accident but then her boyfriend left her and she had to drop out of school anyway and then she had nothing -- except, of course, her reqret.\r\n\r\nHis current father regrets he married his wife. He regrets that they couldn\'t have children of their own, he regrets they adopted this kid he reqets not holding out for a different, younger, better kid with a better pedigree. He has no regrets about thinking this way. He only reqrets he didn\'t \"wise up\" sooner.\r\n\r\nHis fear of future regrets drives him into the arms of a younger prettier girlfriend. He and she both want to avoid regretting that they took the chance. The family breaks up quickly and they are washed up on each other\'s beaches. She regrets breaking up his family and feels that now she has to see it through. He regrets straying from his marriage but he\'s afraid that if he dumps her he\'ll have nothing. \r\n\r\nThe book is not about Regret, it\'s about fear. Fear of regret. Regret is this weird mental mirage that causes you to look back at things that can\'t be changed and wish you didn\'t take the course that looked at least as good as the other course at the time. Fear of regret is a sort of pre-second guess. The mental gymnasitcs of trying to guess what mental mirages you might have for any given choice, most of which aren\'t actually avaiable to you, creates a kind of mental hall of mirrors in which you hopelessly wander. But we present it as a series of regrets; we pound this theme home until even the reviewers (my wouldn\'t that be nice: my dream is to have a work panned) think the book is about regret. \r\n\r\nNow we turn back to the moronic boy, the ne\'er do well whose life everyone regrets. He does what all the romance movies tell him to do and presses his suite on a woman who has already rejected him because -- you guessed it -- he\'s afraid he\'ll regret it for the rest of his life if he doesn\'t. we might even have a character tell him that in oh, so many words. \r\n\r\nOk, I guess that\'s the introduction. I have no idea what the actual book is. ','2013-02-18','2013-02-19 00:04:39'),(672,84,'DAM','<h2>BLESS THE WORKER</h2>\r\nGod bless the workers for they keep the old world turning\r\ngod bless the factory worker for he keeps the butter churning\r\nGod bless the plumber for he keeps the water flowing\r\nGod bless the lineman for he keeps the motors going\r\ngod bless the road man for keeps the wheels turning\r\ngod bless the teacher for she keeps the children learning\r\nI just twiddle bits\r\nI just make computers hum\r\n\r\nI would starve without my rum\r\nGod bless the phone man for he keeps the words from slowing\r\nso I say, thanks for the workers for they keep the old world turning\r\n','2013-02-18','2013-02-19 00:12:10'),(673,63,'DAM','<h2>Regret</h2>\r\nRegret is this weird mental mirage that causes you to look back at things that can\'t be changed and wish you didn\'t take the course that looked at least as good as the other course at the time. Fear of regret is a sort of pre-second guess. The mental gymnastics of trying to guess what mental mirages you might have for any given choice, most of which aren\'t actually avaiable to you, creates a kind of mental hall of mirrors in which you hopelessly wander.','2013-02-18','2013-02-19 00:35:30'),(674,40,'DAM','<h1>The Tenth Gate</h1>\r\nThere are 100 worlds. Number them from 1-100. 1-10 is group 1, 11-20 is 2. Each world has 9 gates. Each gate is connected to another world in the same group. \r\nThere is a 10th gate that is connected to a different group.','2013-03-12','2013-03-12 15:41:48'),(675,63,'DAM','<h2>Wet Fish</h2>\r\nIf you could talk to a fish in aquarium about his \"culture\" and condition you would find out that he is completely unaware that he is wet. He cannot conceive of every being anything but wet and this lack of a contrasting alternative leaves him without any context in which to view himself. He just IS, neither wet nor dry in his conceptualization of himself. \r\n\r\nEvery culture has this problem to a greater or lesser degree. They cannot conceive of being anything other than what they are so they largely unaware of what they actual are. \r\n\r\nGlobal communication being what it is, every society is at least AWARE of some alternatives and so they typically vilify and denigrate the alternatives which is the next best thing to not knowing about them at all. \r\n\r\nThis fundamental belief that we are the best possible thing that we can be and everyone else is evil or stupid is what makes it so hard to change. For a hundred years people in the our country KNEW that white males were the pinnacle of society. We white males are STILL trying to recover from the idea that we need to treat women and minorities as equals. And when the gay rights movement came along we suddenly had to struggle with two new startling concepts. First that we weren\'t \"white males\" but \"white heterosexual males\" -- a fact that had always been true but, just like the wet fish, we had never considered the necessity of giving it name; we were just \"normal\". And second that we had to accept these supposedly abnormal people as equal participants in the society! \r\n\r\nThe truth is very simple: when we really accept who we are, there is no real difference. That dark-skinned lesbian is just as much me as that white guy is. Ironically, this leads people who would pretend to enlightenment to talk about being \"color blind\" which is just an excuse the ignore the problems we created through centuries of overt racism. Unfortunately it\'s not enough to \"go forth and sin no more\" -- you must fix the things you broke, first. \r\n\r\nThis concept of wet fish is even more useful when applied to our individual selves. It may be that you will be happier, healthier, and wealthier if you could go through life believing that however you currently are is the only way you could possibly be. Unfortunately, you were born knowing, deep in your heart, that you are much more than your physical self. This eventually leads, no matter how isolated you  try to be, to the realization that you can be something different than you are. And once you know this, once you realize that you are wet, you become curious and want to be dry. And once you discover that you can be different in any part of your life you become curious to be different in other parts. And soon you come to wonder if there is ANY part of your life that is fixed.\r\n\r\nAfter all, how do you KNOW that you have explored every possibility? The very essence of \"wet fish\" is that there are some things about you that you haven\'t ever thought COULD be different. How do you find them? How do you know they even exist? \r\n\r\nLogically you can\'t. Fortunately, the universe isn\'t actually governed by logic (even though, logically, it must be). \r\n\r\nThe universe is governed by the Spirit. \r\n\r\n','2013-03-18','2013-03-18 22:40:16'),(676,63,'DAM','<h2>Go forth and sin no more</h2>\r\n(From \"wet fish\")\r\nUnfortunately it\'s not enough to \"go forth and sin no\r\nmore\" -- you must fix the things you broke, first. \r\n','2013-03-18','2013-03-18 22:30:33'),(677,63,'DAM','<h2>The Opposite of Entitled is Grateful</h2>\r\nYou either believe you deserve everything you have and more and are annoyed when you are not give all that you deserve or you are grateful for what you have and feel no rancor for getting less or not getting more. If everything is a gift then you just appreciate the gift and don\'t expect more but if it\'s your birthday and mom always gives you a good present then if she doesn\'t give it to you today you are put out about it. \r\nThe opposite of \"entitled\" is \"grateful\". If one feels gratitude for what one is given, as if it\'s a precious gift, then it doesn\'t matter whether one has a little less or a little more. But if one feels as if one is entitled to what one has, one is annoyed and put out if one gets a little less and, in fact, feels that one should get more. \r\n\r\nI don\'t think one can feel gratitude and entitlement at the same time. \r\n\r\nThis is the real tragedy of the Radically Entitled: they don\'t feel the appropriate wonder and gratitude at their experiences. \r\n\r\nI also think that one\'s sense of gratitude engenders one desire to be generous and entitlement engenders the opposite (stinginess). \r\n','2013-05-27','2013-05-28 01:19:25'),(678,63,'DAM','<h2>All True</h2>\r\nI\'m going to tell you something that is true but that you will disagree with. It\'s OK that you disagree, it\'s to be expected. But what I\'m going to tell you is true, nevertheless, not withstanding the fact that no one will believe me.\r\n\r\nI\'ve said elsewhere that there is only One Thing. When you look at the world and see all it\'s diversity and multiplicity it just means that that One Thing has many, many faces.\r\n\r\nA quarter has two sides (and an edge, plus an interior, if you want to be pedantic) and yet it\'s still only one quarter. You can prefer the face over the back, if you like but the back is still an important part of the quarter. \r\n\r\nIn this way, the One Thing has all these different components which form it but it is not many things, it is only One Thing.\r\n\r\nPeople have different beliefs. I met a Christian woman who said that she has belong to several different Christian churches. They all believe in different things and trick is, she told me, to figure out which one was true and to belong to that one. She obviously felt she had found the one true faith and, no doubt, had committed to it.\r\n\r\nBut all those churches have people just like her who feel that they have found the one true faith and are committed those churches. Perhaps someone tried her current church and switched to one of her former churches and concluded that it was the one true faith. \r\n\r\nThey can\'t both be right. One must be wrong. Right?\r\n\r\nAnd yet there is only One Thing. Both women (even the hypothetical one) are part of the One Thing. It would not be complete without either one of them. \r\n\r\nAnd all the churches are part of the one thing. \r\n\r\nIf there is only One Thing then how can some parts of it be more or less than other parts? Just as the face of a quarter is no more a part of the quarter than the back, the one woman is no more a part of the quarter than the other.\r\n\r\nThe part of this that people get stuck on (as in, tell me I\'m full of shit)is when you consider ALL the different ideas people have had down through the ages. The murderers. The rapists. The racists. The slavers. Every manner of perverse and pernicious belief and behavior. And yet, it\'s all true. \r\n\r\nIn fact every thing that has ever been conceived is true (but not every thing that \r\n','2013-06-07','2013-06-07 18:40:19'),(679,63,'DAM','<h2>Mind Body Problem</h2>\r\nReally, there is no mind-body problem, if we believe that we actually are a spirit. \r\n\r\nIt\'s like an orchestra and a symphony. An observer who can only see the instruments and hear the symphony might believe that there is orchestra-symphony problem in that all these separate instruments can\'t possibly spontaneously create that symphony. \r\n\r\nBut if you can see the conductor there is no problem. The conductor (and the composer, let\'s not forget the composer who isn\'t on the scene but has left his mark in a rather heavy-handed way) is the unifying influence that turns a bunch of instruments into a symphony. ','2013-07-08','2013-07-08 13:37:48'),(680,63,'DAM','<h2>An Unselfish Act Is In Your Own Best Interest</h2>\r\nwhen we are upset we typically have some kind of issue that we are upset about. Like a loose tooth, we keep going back to the issue and jiggling it to see if it still bugs us. Yep, still loose!\r\n\r\nThe more we poke at our issues the more they upset us and the more they upset us the more we poke at them. It\'s a vicious circle and we just go deeper and deeper. \r\n\r\nBut if we could get out of our head and focus on something else, we would break the cycle. \r\n\r\nIt turns out that we need only focus on something outside yourself. It can be anything, a rock, a tree, the sky, the weather. But we often fall back into ourselves. The rock starts out as a distinct thing but pretty soon we start thinking about how we feel about the rock and then it isn\'t so effective at getting us out of our head.\r\n\r\nFocusing on other people is better because they do things and interact with us and distract us better than a rock. But we can still fall back on thinking about other people in terms of ourselves. If only there was a way that we could stay focused on the other person in their terms!\r\n\r\nA wise man once said that you should do a good deed, a selfless act, and that it would make you a better person. I used to think this was kind of trite. But then I came to realize that doing something solely FOR another is an extremely powerful way to get out of our own head. ','2013-07-08','2013-07-09 05:14:25'),(681,63,'DAM','<h2>Fear</h2>\r\nFear is always bringing the future into the Now. No one, I will assert, is ever afraid of the past, they are afraid of how the past will affect the future; will my past be found out, will I be punished for it, etc. And no matter what horrific thing is going on at this moment, you don\'t fear IT, you fear what will happen NEXT. \r\n\r\nIf fear is a bad thing, and I think it is, it\'s badness derives from taking your attention away from the Now. And that\'s the antidote for it: keep your attention firmly on NOW. ','2013-09-24','2013-09-24 15:37:00'),(682,63,'DAM','<h2>Conflict</h2>\r\nThis is a little outside this subject matter but it will probably fit in by some logic.\r\n\r\nThere are two kinds of conflict. First there is one person who does or doesn\'t, will or won\'t, has or hasn\'t DONE something and another who is mad at him for it. THen there is politics or the OPINION about things. \r\n\r\nInner conflict is, as far as I know, all about whether YOU yourself want to do or not do something. It\'s hard to imagine a person who is conflicted about their own opinions (unless someone outside has been arguing one way or the other). ','2013-09-24','2013-09-24 15:40:20'),(683,63,'DAM','<h2>Gratitude</h2>\r\nThe Power of Gratitude In Your Life\r\nHow to be happy in your relationships with the people and things around you.\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\nThe central idea of this essay is that we tend to focus on what we don\'t have instead of focussing on what we do have and that this focus causes us to continue to not have. \r\n\r\nThis is not a new idea. I heard about this decades ago and it wasn\'t new then. What might be new, or at least what I hope will you will find usefully stated here, is the idea that you can refocus your attention through gratitude. \r\n\r\nBefore we delve into this, I\'d like to define some terms.\r\n\r\nThe big thing that needs to be addressed, the elephant in the room, is the issue of \"need.\" What do I actually need? \r\n\r\nI might reasonably say that I need air. And, indeed, I will have a hard time living without air. Likewise, there are all manner of things, such as money and food, that I will run out of shortly and, eventually, die from the lack of.\r\n\r\nBut that\'s eventually. What do I need *NOW*? By \"now\" I mean \"in this moment\". Normal people will allow their thoughts to stray to the past, to think, perhaps, about what was needed historically in situations like this, or to the future to consider what might be needed soon. But none of that is relevant. \r\n\r\nI suggest that if we limit ourselves to this moment, we will find, you and I, that we don\'t really NEED anything. I know this because you are reading this passage. If you needed air you would be unconscious and hardly in position to read. You might actually be hungry or thirsty but I\'m going to guess that these desires have not gotten to the life threatening level yet and might be better categorized as \"wants\" than actual needs.\r\n\r\nI am not a big fan of the word \"need\" because I think it\'s misleading but I wanted to address it because it\'s the common way most people think about what they lack. I prefer the word \"lack\" to describe the things in our life that we feel are missing. \r\n\r\nBy \"lack\" I mean that collection of things that we don\'t have that we want to have. It\'s important to understand that lack is related to \"want\" not \"need\". If I don\'t get what I need, I die; if I don\'t get what I want, I am unhappy. \r\n\r\nGenerally, there might be a lot of things that are lacking in our lives. Maybe a job. Money, too, but, while everyone could use more money, not everyone feels that they lack money. But I will bet that high on the list is a relationship with another person. \r\n\r\nOne way to think of this is that my relationship with the things and people around me are poor. Certainly this would be true of people (if this is one of my lacks) but it also applies, in an odd way, to money and jobs and any other material things.\r\n\r\nmore about relationships? \r\n\r\nSo far, we don\'t really need to invoke the supernatural to explain any of this. For now, if it works we can attribute it to the \"Placebo Effect\" or to the intervention of our Guardian Angel or the hand of God and it still works. \r\n\r\nThe point of all this is that we lack some things in our lives, we would like to have some things we don\'t have, we  feel that some things are missing. And it will be helpful to think about this lack as a lack of a certain kind of relationship. Maybe I have a job but I don\'t like it or maybe I am in a long term relationship but don\'t feel fulfilled. \r\n\r\nWhen we think about the relationship between us and the things around us, there is one thing that will be instantly clear: the things with which we have a crappy relationship are the things we find lacking. I know, I know, we find them lacking and that IS our relationship. If we have no significant other, of course our relationship with our non-existent significant other is poor (but, interestingly, not non-existent) and we\'re sad about it! That\'s why it\'s a lack!\r\n\r\nHere\'s the thing, though: is it the lack of the thing that makes us unhappy or our poor relationship that makes us unhappy? \r\n\r\nI am not an athletic person. I have always been big and clumsy and maybe a bit overweight. People picked me last for sports because when they picked me I always let my team down. I was, and am, BAD. But I don\'t have a bad relationship with my sports ability. I\'m perfectly happy with my lack of skill at, say, baseball. I don\'t HAVE the ability, I LACK the skill but my relationship is just fine so I\'m happy.\r\n\r\nSo here is the heart of the issue, put bluntly and writ large: if we were happy with our lack of, say, a spouse, we would be fine with it. If we could somehow move from being unhappy about our relationship status to being perfectly happy, our life would radically change. Our situation wouldn\'t change, we would still be without a spouse, just like before, but we would now be happy with that. I would say our RELATIONSHIP with our non-existent spouse would have changed. \r\n\r\nI\'ll even go one step further. If our relationship with our spouse improved to the point where we were happy with it (that is, happy with the lack of a spouse), and we were done with worrying about it or trying to change it, we might find ourselves in the position, by sheer accident, of having a spouse. \r\n\r\nIt\'s like when I loved my bike, broken pedal and all, and found myself in front of a bike shop where I could fix the pedal. If we have no problem with our world, anything is possible.\r\n\r\nBe warned: trying to be grateful for the lack of something just so we can get that something is a little like a 12 year old praying for a baseball mitt. And it\'s exactly like a drug addict quitting just so the drugs will feel better when he relapses. It\'s pointless and even unhealthy.\r\n\r\nLife IS a game. But it\'s not a game show. We\'re not playing for STUFF. We\'re playing for the sheer fun of playing. To learn to play better, read onâ€¦\r\n\r\nGRATITUDE\r\nHopefully, I\'ve made it clear that the goal is to give up wanting stuff we don\'t have. But what is probably still unclear is how to do that. \r\n\r\nWanting to give up what we want is actually pretty hard. We want what we want and why shouldn\'t we? But once we realize that WE are in charge and can want whatever we want to want (!), it\'s actually pretty easy to choose what we want. It can take a long time (sometimes a VERY long time) to decide to change what we want but once we decide, it\'s pretty easy.\r\n\r\nThe secret is gratitude. The key thing we need to do is to stop focusing on the lack. That focus, that attention is what is creating the bad relationship in the first place. All we need to do is to focus on something else. Develop the skill of gratitude. Think about all the things that we DO have. \r\n\r\nWhen I speak of gratitude, I am not speaking of an emotion that swells in one\'s chest as one gazes at one\'s newborn. I am speaking of a feeling that one cultivates by thinking certain thought, by channeling one\'s attention, and, most importantly, by constant practice. \r\n\r\nTo begin, I placed my attention on something I was happy with. I thought about how much I appreciated the fact of it\'s existence. I set aside other thoughts and ideas and concentrated all my thoughts on that one thing. I found other things that I felt gratitude for and practiced thinking about them. \r\n\r\nNow, whenever I found myself thinking about things I didn\'t have or thing I didn\'t like, I made it a habit to go back to thinking about how much I appreciated the other things. I filled my mind with gratitude and appreciation.\r\n\r\nOver time I became good at feeling gratitude and began to feel gratitude for things that normally would make me feel uncomfortable. Like waiting in line; I can now appreciate a good wait. Or driving in traffic; I now have a lovely long commute every day. I am not a patient person but whenever I feel impatience, I think about how grateful I am to be alive so I can be bored.\r\n\r\nFor this to work at all, it takes practice. It is possible to decide to be happy all the time if one wants to. It\'s just a matter of practice -- and knowing how powerful and useful the ability can be.\r\n\r\nHOW IT WORKS\r\nThis is where I get a bit metaphysical. What I\'m supposed to do here is explain  what God is like and why He likes things in exactly this way. But instead I\'m going to present 3 different stories which are all equivalent and you can pick the one you like best. \r\n\r\nGod Loves Us\r\nGod loves us and and wants us to be happy. He listens to our prayers and responds when appropriate. He is best pleased when we show gratitude for all he has given us. \r\n\r\nWhen we pray with gratitude for our lives and all that fill them in our hearts he rewards us with more. \r\n\r\nBut when we beseech Him with whiny demands for more, it pleases Him not and He simply turns his attention to other quarters.\r\n\r\nThe Universe Loves Us\r\nThe Universe, the Source of all that is and isn\'t, loves us in the sense that it holds us in it\'s metaphorical hands, cradles us, and makes real, in some sense, our every whim. Some of our desires manifest in dreams, some in thoughts, and, in some very rare cases, when the desires are very clear and held for a long time, in the physical reality. \r\n\r\nThe Universe has a very different view of the world than we do.  It can\'t tell whether our attention is directed with such intensity at what we want or at what we don\'t want. Indeed, it doesn\'t make such distinctions; it just \"follows our gaze\" and gives us what we\'re looking at.\r\n\r\nWhen we spend a lot of time annoyed with our lot, the Universe see that as a request and, loving us, it fulfills it.\r\n\r\nOur Minds Love Us\r\nOK, our minds don\'t love us. Awash in chemicals and electrical impulses, my merely reacts in a mechanical way to inputs from my various senses.  We, each of us, are all fooled thereby into thinking we have will (even \"free will\") by emergent behaviors of our billions of neurons.\r\n\r\nWhen we have certain thoughts they engender certain feelings (that is, certain combinations of chemicals and electrical impulses). Thoughts that focus on the negatives in our lives keep our minds awash with negative emotions which distracts us from the positive things in our lives. Cultivating feelings of gratitude distracts us from these negative emotions and allows us to dwell on the good things. We are happier as a result.\r\n\r\nWHY?\r\nBut why, one might ask, does this work? Why does God like us when we are grateful,why does the universe reward us, why do we feel happy.\r\n\r\nI have no idea. For me, why questions always come back to \"because it is the will of god\" (or if one is a materialist, \"because that\'s just how random chance caused this existence to turn out\").\r\n\r\nSorry, that\'s the best I can do.\r\n','2013-09-24','2013-09-24 15:41:52');
