INSERT INTO `des_sections` VALUES (1,2,'Introduction',NULL,0,1,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(2,2,'Definitions',NULL,0,2,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(3,2,'Database Design',NULL,0,3,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(4,2,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,4,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(5,2,'Issues',NULL,0,5,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(6,2,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,6,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(7,10,'Introduction',NULL,0,7,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(8,10,'Definitions',NULL,0,8,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(9,10,'Database Design',NULL,0,9,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(10,10,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(11,10,'Issues',NULL,0,11,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(12,10,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,12,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(13,11,'Introduction',NULL,0,13,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(14,11,'Definitions',NULL,0,14,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(15,11,'Database Design',NULL,0,15,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(16,11,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,16,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(17,11,'Issues',NULL,0,17,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(18,11,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,18,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(19,12,'Introduction',NULL,0,19,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(20,12,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(21,12,'Database Design',NULL,0,21,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(22,12,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,22,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(23,12,'Issues',NULL,0,23,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(24,12,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,24,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(25,1,'Introduction','<P>Whatchamall is an online mall. Individuals and companies who want to sell \r\nthings on the internet will buy space in the mall, paying a modest monthly \r\nfee, and receiving a simple interface that allows them to manage their \r\ninventory, manage their payment methods, and shipping choices and generally \r\nprovide those services that allow a tenant to easily sell items on the \r\ninternet. The only limits will be that a customer can only sell 100 \r\ndifferent products (note that he can have an unlimited total inventory) in \r\n100 categories plus there will be some limits to image sizes, lengths of \r\ndescriptions and other raw bandwidth issues.\r\n\r\n<P>There will be two types of spaces: galleries and catalogs. The difference \r\nis mostly style and concept but galleries will generally consist of items \r\nthat are either one of a kind or are manufactured at need by  the tenant. \r\nTechnically, there will be no inventory in a gallery. In terms of marketing \r\nand presentation, galleries will be less about selling stuff and more about \r\npresenting great works; more like a museum than a store. \r\n\r\n<P>If a customer enters the Mall through the front door -- that is through \r\nthe Whatchamall URL rather than through a space\'s URL --  he will be \r\npresented with a list of stores organized by categories, a set of specials \r\ntaken from thorough out the spaces in the mall and a search engine that \r\nsearches the whole site. Or he can switch to a view of all the item \r\ncategories in all the catalog spaces in the whole mall or all the topics in \r\nall the galleries in the whole mall.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Upon entry to a space, a customer will see a list of categories (that is, \r\ndepartments in the store) and a set of special deals that the store is \r\ncurrently offering. There will also be a search function.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>In each category, tenants will have a list of items. Every item in the \r\nlist will have a price, a thumbnail picture, and a count (gallery items may \r\nnot have counts associated with them) as well as a link to a detail page \r\nthat has a full-size picture and a complete description. Both the list and \r\nthe detail page will have a \"buy it\" link.\r\n\r\n<P>Customers (i.e. buyers) buy things by clicking on the \"buy it\" link \r\nassociated with each item. The link will take the customer to the PayPal \r\nshopping cart.  Whatchamall does not contain a shopping cart because we plan \r\nto use PayPal\'s cart.\r\n\r\n<P>There will also be pages that allow tenants to register, edit their \r\naccounts, and add, edit and delete items and categories. Other pages will be \r\nprovided for administering the Mall itself.\r\n\r\n',0,20,0,'2005-07-14 00:08:33'),(26,1,'Definitions','<ul>\r\n<li>Space -- a store\r\n<li>Tenant -- the operator of a space\r\n<li>Customer -- a person who buys things from the tenant\r\n<li>Catalog Space -- a store that sells normal retail stuff\r\n<li>Gallery Space -- a store that sells one of a kind items\r\n<li>Item -- something for sale in a catalog space\r\n<li>Subject -- something for sale in a gallery space\r\n<li>Category -- a division within a catalog space\r\n<li>Topic -- a division within a gallery space\r\n<li>Administrator (AKA Admin) --  manages Whatchamall\r\n\r\n</ul>',0,40,0,'2005-07-13 19:41:19'),(27,1,'Database Design','<P>By convention, each table has a unique primary key which automatically \r\nincrements from 1. This is called by the name of the table with \"ID\" \r\nappended to it. When and entry of this type is referenced from another table \r\nwe use the name of the table with \"No\" appended to it. The goal here is to \r\nhave each column name be globally unique so that we don\'t have to prepend \r\ntable names before the column names (e.g. \"WHERE Item.Space=Space.ID\" vs. \r\n\"WHERE SpaceNo=SpaceID\"; we\'re doing the latter).\r\n\r\n\r\n',0,100,0,'2005-07-13 23:55:01'),(241,1,'ThemeBackgrounds Table','<pre>\r\n ThemeBackgroundID int(11) \r\n ImageNo int(11) \r\n ThemeNo int(11) \r\n</pre>',27,170,0,'2005-07-14 05:15:59'),(28,1,'Technical Design Notes','<P>All pages will be implemented in Smarty, a template program. Most program \r\nfiles will contain a cluster of functionality -- possibly several modules -- \r\nand will keep their functionality separate by use of URL parameters and a \r\nbig switch statement.  The users will be authenticated through the use of a \r\nusername and password in the tenant contact database but the admins will be \r\nauthenticated through the standard, site wide authentication system.\r\n\r\n<P>Languages will be handled by having all text that appears on a screen \r\nstored in a table. To add another language one creates a new language entry \r\nin the Languages table and then creates a new phrase in that language for \r\nevery phrase in the Phrases table. This means that we\'ll load a huge array \r\nof phrases at the start (or any time the user changes languages) and \r\neverything in the templates will be references to this array. The problem \r\nwith this is that, while you can pass a single string to smarty, you can\'t \r\npass an array and then de-reference single elements (you can loop through \r\nit, sure, but not a single element). This implies that we\'ll have to figure \r\nout which phrases will appear in each template and pass them singly to the \r\ntemplate!\r\n<P>Search is a simple keyword search LIKE operator and % wildcards. Very \r\nsimple: we take the search string, break it into a list of words, remove all \r\nthe 1 or 2 letter words, then we create a select using each of these words \r\non the product description (OR description LIKE %$word%...). This will get \r\nus a list of all the products that might be appropriate and we just show the \r\nfirst 25. The selection of which 25 to show is arbitrary. It would be nice \r\nto show the ones with the most hits first but that\'s hard. We should also \r\napply the search to the stock numbers.\r\n<P>The logging should happen at the top of every php file and should report \r\nthe URL for that page as well as the indicated fields from the $_SERVER \r\narray. The transaction logging will be harder: we need to put a php file \r\nwith a routine that logs the transaction information and then redirects to \r\nPayPal. This could look suspicious. Might be better to log stuff when it \r\ncomes back from PayPal (i.e. when we deduct the inventory count).\r\n<p>I\'d like to split this system up into two files. The first (index.php) \r\nhandles everything for customers and has no security at all.  The second is \r\nthe site management code and is protected by the site authentication system. \r\nThe third is the space management system which the tenants use and is \r\nprotected by an internal password. By splitting this up into 3 sections, \r\nI\'m hoping to give customers, tenants and admins each their own entrance for \r\nconvenience and security.',0,140,0,'2005-07-13 21:00:29'),(29,1,'Issues','',0,160,0,'2005-07-14 00:00:57'),(30,1,'Future Enhancements','<ul>\r\n<li>Shopping cart which would allow for other payment methods.\r\n<li>Upload or email files that contain items for bulk adding of items.\r\n<li>Inventory system (tracking the need for reorder and reorder status, etc.).\r\n<li>Tenant and customer forums to gather feedback allow for cooperation among tenants.\r\n<li>More sophisticated search engine.\r\n<LI>More interesting and useful reports.\r\n<li>Logging of transactions (which isn\'t done now because transactions are currently a private transaction among paypal, the customer and the tenant)\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n',0,180,0,'2005-07-14 21:58:34'),(31,3,'Introduction',NULL,0,31,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(32,3,'Definitions',NULL,0,32,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(33,3,'Database Design',NULL,0,33,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(34,3,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,34,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(35,3,'Issues',NULL,0,35,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(36,3,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,36,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(37,4,'Introduction','<P>RedWall is a multiplayer online game site, primarily for the play of the email style of games. It is intended to be a \"one stop\" location for multiplayer online games. \r\n<P>RedWall provides a variety of resources to simplify the process of developing games. Primarily, RedWall allows users to to register and sign up for games. It also provides a convenient framework to hang web-based game-related information such as game descriptions, game rules, game status and other related information. \r\n\r\n<P>RedWall will also have a \"standards based\" approach to game design. That is, there will be defined ways that the game site can communicate to individual games so that the game engines can be managed from a central location. These defined ways will only work if the game is designed according to the standard but RedWall will also include tools (\"adapters\") that will allow common game designs to be hooked into the standards with a minimum of rework.',0,10,0,'2005-06-27 00:09:16'),(38,4,'Definitions','<li>Player -- a player of a given game\r\n<li>User -- a user of the RedWall site\r\n<li>Registered User -- someone who has registered on the site and is allowed to sign up for games\r\n<li>Unregistered User -- someone who can browse the site but is not allow to sign up\r\n<li>Game Type -- the implementation of a specific game design\r\n<li>Game -- a running game, that is, the instantiation of a particular game type\r\n<li>Player -- a member of a particular game\r\n<li>Bounce -- an email that did not get to it\'s recipient \r\n\r\n',0,60,0,'2005-06-27 03:50:17'),(39,4,'Database Design','<P>By convention, each table has a unique primary key which automatically increments from 1. This is called by the name of the table with \"id\" appended to it. When and entry of this type is referenced from another table we use the name of the table with \"No\" appended to it. The goal here is to have each column name be globally unique so that we don\'t have to prepend table names before the column names. \r\n<P>Also by convention all database tables are named in the singular and in all lower case. \"user,\" \"game\" and \"player\" rather than \"Users\", \"Games\" and \"Players\". Likewise the fields in the tables are all named in the lowercase. \r\n<P>Almost every table has, as it\'s last field, a timestamp. The naming convention for this is the name of the table followed by \"ts\", all in lowercase.  This field always has the last change to the record. \r\n\r\n\r\n<P>\r\ncreate table gametype -- this is a list of the types of games that we have<BR>\r\n gametypeid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n gametypename tinytext,<BR>\r\n gametypeurl tinytext,<BR>\r\n gamets timestamp,<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\ncreate table user -- list of people who are registered on the site<BR>\r\n userid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n username tinytext,<BR>\r\n realname tinytext,<BR>\r\n emailaddress tinytext,<BR>\r\n password tinytext,<BR>\r\n age int,<BR>\r\n signupdate date,<BR>\r\n usertype enum (player,tester,admin),<BR>\r\n temppassword tinytext,<BR>\r\n temppwexpire datetime,<BR>\r\n userts timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\n\r\ncreate table game -- actual games, an instance of the game type<BR>\r\n gameid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n gametypeno int,<BR>\r\n status enum (starting,running,paused,finished),<BR>\r\n turninterval int, <br>\r\n gamets timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table player -- link table between users and games<BR>\r\n playerid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n userno int,<BR>\r\n gameno int,<BR>\r\n playerts timestamp,<BR>\r\n gameplayernum int<BR>\r\n playerts timestamp,<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\ncreate table policy -- site policies<BR>\r\n policyid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n policyname tinytext ,<BR>\r\n policydesc tinytext ,<BR>\r\n policyvalue tinytext ,<BR>\r\n adminname tinytext ,<BR>\r\n policyts timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table language -- languages that are supported<BR>\r\n languageid int auto_increment <BR>\r\n languagename tinytext <BR>\r\n<BR>\r\ncreate table phrase -- phrases that are used on the site<BR>\r\n phraseid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n phrasename tinytext,<BR>\r\n phrase tinytext,<BR>\r\n languageno int,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table sitelog -- logs page <BR>\r\n sitelogid int auto_increment primary, <BR>\r\n referer tinytext,<BR>\r\n remote_addr tinytext,<BR>\r\n http_user_agent tinytext,<BR>\r\n username tinytext,<BR>\r\n request_uri tinytext,<BR>\r\n params text,<BR>\r\n logts timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table dblog -- logs changes to the database itself<BR>\r\n dblogid int auto_increment primary, <BR>\r\n sqlcommand tinytext,<BR>\r\n dblogts timestamp,<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n\r\ncreate table emaillog -- logs emails sent<br>\r\n emaillogid int auto_increment primary, <BR>\r\n userno int,<br>\r\n emailadr tinytext,<br>\r\n status enum (success,failure),<br>\r\n emaillogts timestamp,<br>\r\n<br>\r\n ',0,70,0,'2005-06-27 03:52:38'),(40,4,'Technical Design Notes','',0,80,0,'2005-06-27 00:59:35'),(41,4,'Issues','',0,90,0,'2005-06-27 03:53:20'),(42,4,'Future Enhancements','',0,100,0,'2005-06-27 00:59:35'),(43,7,'Introduction',NULL,0,43,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(44,7,'Definitions',NULL,0,44,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(45,7,'Database Design',NULL,0,45,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(46,7,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,46,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(47,7,'Issues',NULL,0,47,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(48,7,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,48,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(49,8,'Introduction',NULL,0,49,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(50,8,'Definitions',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(51,8,'Database Design',NULL,0,51,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(52,8,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,52,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(53,8,'Issues',NULL,0,53,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(54,8,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,54,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(55,13,'Introduction','<P>Whatchamall is an online mall. Individuals and companies who want to sell \r\nthings on the internet will buy space in the mall, paying a modest monthly \r\nfee, and receiving a simple interface that allows them to manage their \r\ninventory, manage their payment methods, and shipping choices and generally \r\nprovide those services that allow a tenant to easily sell items on the \r\ninternet. The only limits will be that a customer can only sell 100 \r\ndifferent products (note that he can have an unlimited total inventory) in \r\n100 categories plus there will be some limits to image sizes, lengths of \r\ndescriptions and other raw bandwidth issues.\r\n\r\n<P>There will be two types of spaces: galleries and catalogs. The difference \r\nis mostly style and concept but galleries will generally consist of items \r\nthat are either one of a kind or are manufactured at need by  the tenant. \r\nTechnically, there will be no inventory in a gallery. In terms of marketing \r\nand presentation, galleries will be less about selling stuff and more about \r\npresenting great works; more like a museum than a store. \r\n\r\n<P>If a customer enters the Mall through the front door -- that is through \r\nthe Whatchamall URL rather than through a space\'s URL --  he will be \r\npresented with a list of stores organized by categories, a set of specials \r\ntaken from thorough out the spaces in the mall and a search engine that \r\nsearches the whole site. Or he can switch to a view of all the item \r\ncategories in all the catalog spaces in the whole mall or all the topics in \r\nall the galleries in the whole mall.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Upon entry to a space, a customer will see a list of categories (that is, \r\ndepartments in the store) and a set of special deals that the store is \r\ncurrently offering. There will also be a search function.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>In each category, tenants will have a list of items. Every item in the \r\nlist will have a price, a thumbnail picture, and a count (gallery items may \r\nnot have counts associated with them) as well as a link to a detail page \r\nthat has a full-size picture and a complete description. Both the list and \r\nthe detail page will have a \"buy it\" link.\r\n\r\n<P>Customers (i.e. buyers) buy things by clicking on the \"buy it\" link \r\nassociated with each item. The link will take the customer to the PayPal \r\nshopping cart.  Whatchamall does not contain a shopping cart because we plan \r\nto use PayPal\'s cart.\r\n\r\n<P>There will also be pages that allow tenants to register, edit their \r\naccounts, and add, edit and delete items and categories. Other pages will be \r\nprovided for administering the Mall itself.\r\n\r\n',0,10,0,'2005-06-15 17:16:12'),(56,13,'Definitions','<P>Whatchamall is an online mall. Individuals and companies who want to sell \r\nthings on the internet will buy space in the mall, paying a modest monthly \r\nfee, and receiving a simple interface that allows them to manage their \r\ninventory, manage their payment methods, and shipping choices and generally \r\nprovide those services that allow a tenant to easily sell items on the \r\ninternet. The only limits will be that a customer can only sell 100 \r\ndifferent products (note that he can have an unlimited total inventory) in \r\n100 categories plus there will be some limits to image sizes, lengths of \r\ndescriptions and other raw bandwidth issues.\r\n\r\n<P>There will be two types of spaces: galleries and catalogs. The difference \r\nis mostly style and concept but galleries will generally consist of items \r\nthat are either one of a kind or are manufactured at need by  the tenant. \r\nTechnically, there will be no inventory in a gallery. In terms of marketing \r\nand presentation, galleries will be less about selling stuff and more about \r\npresenting great works; more like a museum than a store. \r\n\r\n<P>If a customer enters the Mall through the front door -- that is through \r\nthe Whatchamall URL rather than through a space\'s URL --  he will be \r\npresented with a list of stores organized by categories, a set of specials \r\ntaken from thorough out the spaces in the mall and a search engine that \r\nsearches the whole site. Or he can switch to a view of all the item \r\ncategories in all the catalog spaces in the whole mall or all the topics in \r\nall the galleries in the whole mall.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Upon entry to a space, a customer will see a list of categories (that is, \r\ndepartments in the store) and a set of special deals that the store is \r\ncurrently offering. There will also be a search function.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>In each category, tenants will have a list of items. Every item in 