15 17:18:56'),(60,13,'Future Enhancements','<P>Whatchamall is an online mall. Individuals and companies who want to sell \r\nthings on the internet will buy space in the mall, paying a modest monthly \r\nfee, and receiving a simple interface that allows them to manage their \r\ninventory, manage their payment methods, and shipping choices and generally \r\nprovide those services that allow a tenant to easily sell items on the \r\ninternet. The only limits will be that a customer can only sell 100 \r\ndifferent products (note that he can have an unlimited total inventory) in \r\n100 categories plus there will be some limits to image sizes, lengths of \r\ndescriptions and other raw bandwidth issues.\r\n\r\n<P>There will be two types of spaces: galleries and catalogs. The difference \r\nis mostly style and concept but galleries will generally consist of items \r\nthat are either one of a kind or are manufactured at need by  the tenant. \r\nTechnically, there will be no inventory in a gallery. In terms of marketing \r\nand presentation, galleries will be less about selling stuff and more about \r\npresenting great works; more like a museum than a store. \r\n\r\n<P>If a customer enters the Mall through the front door -- that is through \r\nthe Whatchamall URL rather than through a space\'s URL --  he will be \r\npresented with a list of stores organized by categories, a set of specials \r\ntaken from thorough out the spaces in the mall and a search engine that \r\nsearches the whole site. Or he can switch to a view of all the item \r\ncategories in all the catalog spaces in the whole mall or all the topics in \r\nall the galleries in the whole mall.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Upon entry to a space, a customer will see a list of categories (that is, \r\ndepartments in the store) and a set of special deals that the store is \r\ncurrently offering. There will also be a search function.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>In each category, tenants will have a list of items. Every item in the \r\nlist will have a price, a thumbnail picture, and a count (gallery items may \r\nnot have counts associated with them) as well as a link to a detail page \r\nthat has a full-size picture and a complete description. Both the list and \r\nthe detail page will have a \"buy it\" link.\r\n\r\n<P>Customers (i.e. buyers) buy things by clicking on the \"buy it\" link \r\nassociated with each item. The link will take the customer to the PayPal \r\nshopping cart.  Whatchamall does not contain a shopping cart because we plan \r\nto use PayPal\'s cart.\r\n\r\n<P>There will also be pages that allow tenants to register, edit their \r\naccounts, and add, edit and delete items and categories. Other pages will be \r\nprovided for administering the Mall itself.\r\n\r\n',0,60,0,'2005-06-15 17:16:12'),(61,14,'Introduction',NULL,0,61,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(62,14,'Definitions',NULL,0,62,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(63,14,'Database Design',NULL,0,63,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(64,14,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,64,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(65,14,'Issues',NULL,0,65,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(66,14,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,66,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(67,15,'Introduction','<P>This is a trading game set in ancient times around the\r\nMediterranean. There are a large number of cities around the med and\r\nthese are the focus of trading. \r\n<P>There are always 50 cities and 100 commodities. Each city has 6 things it buys and 6 things it sells. All commodities are hidden from anyone who is not present. So you know what\'s going on where your ship is but not anywhere else elsewhere.\r\n<P>It\'s always true that every city is one turn away from every other city.\r\n<P>The goal of the game is to make money by buying commodities in one city and selling them in another. \r\n<P>There is a special city, called \"the gateway\", that leads to a more advanced game. Passage through the gateway costs all your resources (ships, commodities, money, etc) and puts you into the next game with whatever the starting resources for that game are. There is a minimum amount of money required to go through the gateway. Initially this game will not have a second level but it will have a gateway with an requirement of an infinite amount of money (so no one can go through it). \r\n\r\n',0,10,0,'2009-05-21 22:16:08'),(68,15,'Definitions','<dl>\r\n<dt>City<dd>A location in the game, usually with multiple markets.</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt>Commodity<dd>A single good that can be bought sold or carried around in a ship.</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt>Ship<dd>A Commodity carrying device that always in a location and owned by one and only one player. </dfn></dt>\r\n\r\n<dt>Markets<dd>A place to buy or sell a commodity. There are likely several at each city.</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt>Multiplier<dd></dfn></dt>\r\n<dt>Base Value<dd></dfn></dt>\r\n<dt>Gateway<dd>A city that allows you to move from </dfn></dt>\r\n<dt>Forsale<dd>A market that sells a commodity is said to be a \"forsale\" market</dfn></dt>\r\n<dt>Ondemand<dd>A market that buys a commodity is said to be an \"ondemand\" market </dfn></dt>\r\n</dl>',0,20,0,'2009-05-22 23:29:50'),(69,15,'Database Design','<pre>\r\ndrop table if exists trd_city ;\r\ncreate table trd_city (\r\n  cityid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  name tinytext,\r\n  cityTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);#  (cities need not have warehouses or other facilities; in that case it\'s more like a waypoint)\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_commodity;\r\ncreate table trd_commodity (\r\n  commodityid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  name tinytext,\r\n  baseprice int,\r\n  commodityTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_market;\r\ncreate table trd_market (\r\n  marketid int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  cityno int default 0,\r\n  commodityno int default 0,\r\n  quantity int default 1,\r\n  markettype enum(\'forsale\', \'ondemand\'),\r\n  price int default 0,\r\n  transactions int default 5,# (after some transactions the price goes up)\r\n  active int default 0, # did a transaction occur this turn?\r\n  marketTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_warehouse;\r\ncreate table trd_warehouse (\r\n  warehouseid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  cityno int default 0,#\r\n  owner int default 0,# (playerno)\r\n  content int default 0,# (commodity #)\r\n  quantity  int default 1,#\r\n  warehouseTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_route;\r\ncreate table trd_route (\r\n  routeid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  fromcity int default 0,#\r\n  tocity int default 0,#\r\n  turns  int default 1,#\r\n  type enum (\'bi-directions\', \'uni-directional\'),\r\n  routeTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_player;\r\ncreate table trd_player (\r\n  playerid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  userno int default 0,# (actually usernumber from authenticaion table)\r\n  nickname int default 0,# (is there any reason not to have the player number=userno?)\r\n   #note that nicknames in games are not the same as the global user name\r\n  money int default 0,#\r\n  playerTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_ship;\r\ncreate table trd_ship (\r\n  shipid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  ownerno int default 0,#\r\n  capacity  int default 1,#\r\n  cityno int default 0,#\r\n  shipTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_cargo;\r\ncreate table trd_cargo(\r\n  cargoid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  commodityno int default 0,#\r\n  shipno int default 0,#\r\n  cargoTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists trd_storage;\r\ncreate table trd_storage (\r\n  storageid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  commodityno int default 0,#\r\n  warehouseno int default 0,#\r\n  storageTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\ndrop table if exists  trd_spy;\r\ncreate table trd_spy (\r\n  spyid  int not null auto_increment primary key,\r\n  playerno int default 0,#\r\n  cost int default 0,#\r\n  assignment  int default 0,#(city#)\r\n  spytype enum(\'spy\', \'counterspy\'), \r\n  spyTS timestamp(14) NOT NULL \r\n);\r\n\r\n</pre>',0,70,0,'2009-05-22 23:25:13'),(70,15,'User Interface','',0,50,0,'2009-05-22 20:52:35'),(71,15,'Game Mechanics','<h3> Multipliers</h3>\r\n<P>Every commodity has a multiplier associated with it. The multipliers might be the first 100 prime numbers (starting with 1) -- this is a pretty good distributions. In any case, there should be a lot of low multipliers compared to the higher multipliers, like in prime numbers. \r\n<P>The commodities associated with low multipliers are \"cheap\" commodities; those with high multipliers are \"expensive\" commodities. Poor players fill their cargo holds with cheap commodities because that\'s all they can afford. Rich players want to buy the more expensive commodities because a small swing in an expensive commodity is a lot more money in absolute terms. Poor players have an advantage over rich players because there are more cheap commodities so it\'s more likely they\'ll be able to buy something cheaper than they sell it. \r\n<P>The multiplier for a particular commodity never changes. It is the thing that makes a particular commodity uniquely that commodity (outside it\'s name which has no game mechanical effect).\r\n\r\n<h3>Base Value</h3>\r\n<P>The base values for all markets change over time based on how much commodity is bought and sold in that market. The base value is a number between 1 and 13. If it ever gets to 14 or to 0 it means that the commodity has either run out in the market or the market has flooded. The market will then be re-initialized. \r\n\r\n<h3>Initializing Markets</h3>\r\n<P>To initialize (re-initialized) a market, pick a commodity at random. Ensure that this commodity is not being bought or sold in the same location -- there should never be two markets in the same location with the same commodity.  \r\n\r\n<P>Generate two integers between 1 and 6 inclusive. For the sell price, subtract 1 from this number. For the buy price, add one. This makes it more likely that the initial buy prices will be lower than the initial sell prices. This value is the initial \"base value\". \r\n\r\n<h3> Changing The Base Value<h3>\r\n\r\n<P>Base values (and, therefore, prices) only change at the end of the turn (after everyone has bought or sold). Every time a commodity is bought or sold the \"transactions\" count for that market is incremented. Every turn that no commodity is bought or sold the transaction count is reduced by 1. \r\n<P>When the transaction count reaches -1 the transaction count is set to 10 and the base value is changed. Forsale markets have their base values reduced by one. Ondemand markets have their base values increased by one. \r\n<P>When the transaction count reaches 11 the transaction count is set to 0 and the base value cahnged. Forsale markets have their base values increased by one. Ondemand marksts have their base values decreased by one. \r\n<P>If the base value reaches 0 or 14 the market is re-initialized.  \r\n\r\n<h3>Price</h3>\r\n<P>The price is an integer that is calculated by adding a random number between 0 and 1 to the base price and then multipying this sum by the multiplier. \r\n\r\n<h3>Buying and Selling</h3>\r\n<P>When the player buys a commodity he loses the price from his money and gains the commodity. When he sells a commodity he loses the commodity and games that amount of money. ',0,40,0,'2009-05-22 23:43:14'),(72,15,'Future Enhancements','',0,80,0,'2009-05-22 20:52:35'),(73,16,'Introduction',NULL,0,73,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(74,16,'Definitions',NULL,0,74,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(75,16,'Database Design',NULL,0,75,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(76,16,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,76,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(77,16,'Issues',NULL,0,77,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(78,16,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,78,0,'2005-06-15 05:57:12'),(79,17,'Introduction',NULL,0,79,0,