 edit and delete items and categories. Other pages will be \r\nprovided for administering the Mall itself.\r\n\r\n',129,0,0,'2005-06-15 17:16:12'),(178,4,'User Database','The user table has the user informaiton in it. Access to this must be restricted. The fields of this table are in the <a href=\"http://67.113.154.163/designs/index.php?mode=displayformal&designno=4#Database%20Design\">Database Design section.</a>',169,10,0,'2005-06-27 00:53:21'),(179,4,'User Module','The user module manages the user database. It allows all other routines unrestricted access to the user information except that it never gives out the user password. Instead, it authenticates the user by taking a username and password and returning true or false. \r\n\r\n    <LI> add user\r\n    <LI> get user info (gets everything except password)\r\n    <LI> does user exist? (returns boolean)\r\n    <LI> is this user/password valid? (returns boolean) ',169,20,0,'2005-06-27 00:57:12'),(141,24,'Introduction',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:29:15'),(142,24,'Definitions',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:29:15'),(143,24,'Database Design',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:29:15'),(144,24,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:29:15'),(145,24,'Issues',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:29:15'),(146,24,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:29:15'),(147,26,'Introduction',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:30:37'),(148,26,'Definitions',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:30:37'),(149,26,'Database Design',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:30:37'),(150,26,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:30:37'),(151,26,'Issues',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:30:37'),(152,26,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,NULL,0,'2005-06-15 17:30:37'),(154,13,'What is this section\'s seq',NULL,0,90,0,'2005-06-15 17:43:24'),(155,13,'What is this subsections\'s seq',NULL,56,10,0,'2005-06-15 17:44:32'),(156,13,'Another subsection',NULL,59,50,0,'2005-06-15 17:45:00'),(157,27,'Introduction','',0,10,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(158,27,'Definitions','',0,20,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(159,27,'Database Design','',0,30,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(160,27,'Technical Design Notes','',0,40,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(161,27,'Issues','',0,50,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(162,27,'Future Enhancements','',0,60,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(163,27,'New Section','',0,70,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(164,27,'New Section','',0,80,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(165,27,'New Section','',0,90,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(166,27,'New Subsection','',165,10,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(167,27,'Newer Subsection','',165,50,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(168,27,'Newest Subsection','',165,30,0,'2005-06-15 18:05:38'),(169,4,'Player Management','Everyone who plays a game must be a registered user but it is free to register. Users may pick their own username and password and must give a valid email address. The player may opt to have information sent to his email address or may choose to visit the web site instead. \r\n\r\n<P>In order to play a game the player must both register as a user on the site and use his username to register for a game. The following is a detailed discussion of the components needed to meet these needs.\r\n',0,20,0,'2005-06-27 00:59:35'),(170,4,'Game Management','<P>We will need a system that does game management. This system will keep track of:\r\n\r\n    <LI> Which games are accepting new players\r\n    <LI> Which games are currently running\r\n    <LI> How often the runnning games are accepting input (?)\r\n    <LI> Whether you need pay to play in the games\r\n    <LI> Which games are complete \r\n<P>The game specific page will list all this information for each game type.\r\n<P>The game management system will also need to allow games to start, manage turn input, manage the running of the turns and ending a game. It will also manage score tables customized to each game. \r\n\r\n<!-- <img src=\"http://67.113.154.163/redwall/rawdbdiag.jpg\">-->',0,30,0,'2005-06-27 03:33:21'),(171,28,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-06-15 18:20:47'),(172,28,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-06-15 18:20:47'),(173,28,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-06-15 18:20:47'),(174,28,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-06-15 18:20:47'),(175,28,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-06-15 18:20:47'),(176,28,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-06-15 18:20:47'),(205,4,'Main Page','<P> There will be a main page for the whole system. The front page has a logo, then a list of links -- the site navigation stuff --\r\nthen it has a list of games with their logos. Each game has one or more of the\r\nfollowing notations: \"Now Accepting Players\", \"Games Now Running\" and \"Coming\r\nSoon\". The last will always be by itself but the other two are independent of\r\neach other. The logo and each of the notations is a link. The logo and \"Coming\r\nSoon\" go to a description of the game with a link to the rules and the game\r\nsign up. Games Now Running goes to a page that shows the running games and\r\ntheir status and has links to player and non-player game information (i.e.\r\npublic info and private info). Now Accepting Players takes you to the \"sign up\r\nfor this game\" link.\r\n<P>\r\nSite Navigation includes\r\n<li>Home (this main page)\r\n<li>Registration Page\r\n<li>Login Page\r\n<li>Logout Link\r\n<li>Lost Password Page\r\n<li>Donation Page\r\n<P>',0,15,0,'2005-06-27 01:00:10'),(181,4,'New User Registration','To register we have a simple form in which the user enters a bunch of information which is then used to create a new user entry in the database. The only validation that we do is to make sure the user name is unique and that the password and validation password match. The other fields in the database are initialized, as well.\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\r\n<LI> username\r\n<LI> real name    \r\n<LI> password\r\n    <LI> verify password\r\n<LI> email address\r\n    <LI> age \r\n</ul>\r\n<P>This information is processed & verified and then added to the database. The username must be unique, the password and verify password must match, the email address must be formatted correctly, the age must be numeric. We add to this the date of registration and the usertype (which always starts out as player). ',169,40,0,'2005-06-27 01:04:04'),(182,4,'Lost Password','<P>The user enters a username and we generate and send a temporary password to his email address. The temporary password and the expiry are stored in the user table. The login routine must respect both the temp password and the expiry. The temporary password is never actually removed, it just expires. ',169,50,0,'2005-06-27 03:06:27'),(183,4,'Account Management','The Account management page allows the user to examine and change his/her information. The page is protected by a cookie containing the user. Elements should include (italic items can be changed):\r\n\r\n    <LI> <i>Real Name</i>\r\n    <LI> Username\r\n    <LI> <i>Password</i>    \r\n    <LI> <i>Verify Password</i>\r\n    <LI> <i>Email Address</i>\r\n    <LI> List of Games Registered\r\n    <LI> Report of bounces in the last month \r\n<P>\r\nThe player should not be able to change his/her username here (or, possibly anywhere). Also the player should not be able to change his/her age.  ',169,60,0,'2005-06-27 03:15:11'),(184,4,'User Analysis Utility',' We need a program that will examine the user table to determine which, if any,  users should be deleted. This is a web page that shows a lists of people that fit the following attributes:\r\n\r\n  <Ul>\r\n<li> New Users (starting date no more than one month in the past)\r\n    <li> Inactive Users (users who are not in any games)\r\n    <li> Long time Inactive users (users who have not sent in a turn for 2 months or more)\r\n    <li> Bad Email users (users who\'s last bounce is more recent than their last turn)\r\n</ul>',169,70,0,'2005-06-27 03:15:11'),(206,1,'Case Studies','<P>There are 3 users who may use this system. The first is the customer who comes to buy something. The second is the tenant who wishes to manage his space. The third is the mall manager. Although we want all users to have a good user experience, I\'ve listed the users in order of importance: if the customers find this a compelling experience the tenants and the admin will ultimately be happy. ',0,50,0,'2005-07-13 19:41:41'),(207,1,'Customers','<P>We will consider three customers, Alice, Bob and Charlie. We will suppose \r\nthat all three are interested in finding the perfect toe cosy but may be \r\ntempted by other things and are willing to browse around to some degree. I \r\nbelieve typical customers take as short a route as they can to their goal \r\nbut will happily buy other items if they see it <B>AND</B> they get what \r\nthey are looking for.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Alice enters \"toe cosy\" into Google and finds a category page in the Mall \r\nwith a toe cosy on it. It also has many other things and she has to root \r\naround a bit to find it, especially if the category is a big one. She \r\nprobably finds this experience somewhat trying in direct proportion to the \r\nnarrowness of her focus on toe cosies and to the size and diversity of the \r\ncategory. Remember that Alice has many other links to choose from on Google.\r\n\r\n<P>Bob heard about Whatchamall and came to check out the toe cosies there. \r\nHe has three options. He can browse around for a toe cosy store among the \r\nstores in the mall (presumably only looking at the stores in the \"clothing\" \r\ncategory), he can use the search engine or he can switch the view to look at \r\nthe item categories. \r\n<P>If there are not too many stores and they are all clearly marked on the\r\nscreen he will probably browse the stores first. He will probably jump into \r\nsome stores that MIGHT have toe cosies and then come back if nothing \r\ninterests him (or, conceivably, buy things while he\'s there).\r\n<P>If he switches to the item category view, he will, presumably, see some \r\ncategories that look promising -- hopefully a LOT more promising than the \r\ngeneric \"clothing\". If there are a LOT of categories he might not see the \r\ngood ones. This will be a challenge because the relevant item categories may \r\nnot start with a predictable letter and so there may be no simple way to \r\ndivide them up. \r\n\r\n<P>Assuming he doesn\'t find what he came for browsing around, he may use the \r\nsearch engine. The search engine should give him a page with a list of items \r\nthat have something to do with toe cosies. He can then jump directly to the \r\ndetail page of an item or even buy it from search results page. Notice that \r\nhis experience is much different from Alice\'s.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Charlie heard about a toe cosy store and has a link directly to the head \r\nof the store. Like Bob, Charlie can now browse or search but, unlike Bob, \r\nCharlie is much more likely (whether searching or browsing) to find a close \r\nmatch to what he is looking at (assuming, of course, that the store he went \r\nto is really a toe cosy store). If he doesn\'t find what he wants he can use \r\nthe search engine right there to search the whole mall.',206,10,0,'2005-07-13 19:44:16'),(208,1,'Tenants','<P>Dave is a tenant in the Mall. He has a toe cosy store called <I>The Cosy \r\nToe</I>. To set up his store he divides his inventory of 100 items into 6 \r\ncategories of roughly 20 items each. This causes some difficultly because he \r\nhas a <B>lot</B> of socks and some other miscellaneous items that don\'t fit \r\ntogether very well (for example, \"Basalt Cosy Toe Stones,\" \"Toe and Finger \r\nCushion Strips,\"  toe clippers and bunion cream). Nevertheless, he makes the \r\nhard choices and arranges his products among the categories. Now he has to \r\nupload 100 pictures and write 100 descriptions into little square boxes on \r\nthe screen. It\'s a nuisance. Then he has to enter inventory and pricing for \r\n100 items.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Once Dave has set up the Mall he\'s fairly happy with the way it works for \r\nthe customers (although he\'d like to differentiate himself from his fellow \r\ntenants a bit more). However, he has to maintain his inventory separately \r\nfrom the Mall because the Mall only handles inventory and sales and doesn\'t \r\nkeep track of when he needs to reorder or which items are on back order or \r\nany of the hundred other details that a retailer needs to track.\r\n<P>It does tell him what his customers are looking at so he has information \r\nbeyond raw sales to tell him what\'s hot and what\'s not and what would sell \r\nbetter if the price were lower. Since the Mall doesn\'t do much advertising \r\nhe needs to advertise and uses the reports to analyze the effectiveness of \r\nhis advertising expenses. Best of all, the Mall has low overhead.\r\n\r\n',206,20,0,'2005-07-13 19:44:16'),(209,1,'Mall Management','<P>Earl is the manager of the Mall. Most of what he does is \"customer service\" \r\nwith the tenants: explaining how it works, tracking down and reporting bugs, \r\nreporting desirable enhancements (and nagging the programmers about them) \r\nand generally checking to make sure everything is running smoothly. In the \r\nabsence of problems, there is little for him to do.',206,30,0,'2005-07-13 19:44:16'),(187,4,'Designing A Game','<P>The game designer has to write 3 Unix programs in a language of his choice.\r\n\r\n<li>\"process turn\" which takes the game number \r\n<li>\"input turn\" which takes a file containing a user\'s turn information\r\n<li>\"start game\" which takes a file containing all the starting information\r\n\r\n<P>The game must know it\'s own game type and each of it\'s game numbers. These\r\ntogether identify a specific game. RedWall provides a program that the game\r\ncalls when the game is over. The game passes the game type and game number and\r\nresults (must be in a standard format) and RedWall marks that game as closed,\r\nposts the results and so forth.',0,40,0,'2005-06-27 03:56:54'),(188,4,'Starting A Game','When games are started a flat tab delimited temporary file is created that has\r\nthe player information in it (usernames and email addresses). The location of\r\nthis file is passed to the \"start game\" executable provided by the game\r\ndesigner. This process converts the information from the flat file to the\r\ngame\'s native format for storing information. \r\n',170,10,0,'2005-06-16 06:22:01'),(189,4,'Inputing A Turn','<P>When a turn comes in, Redwall collects the information, verifies that it came\r\nfrom a particular user and passes this information, in a file, to the \"input\r\nturn\" executable provided by the game designer. \r\n<P>We also record that we received email from this player for \"active player\" management.',170,20,0,'2005-06-27 03:40:23'),(190,4,'Running A Turn','<P>RedWall maintains a list\r\nof running games and how often they run.\r\n\r\n<P>RedWall has a process that runs through the running games list, finds the next one that runs and, when that one runs, calls that games \"process turn\" function and hands it a game number as the parameter.\r\n<P>The processor must take the turn and process it. It must\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n   <li> log the player input in the history file\r\n   <li> process the turn\r\n   <li> generate results\r\n   <li> update the game state\r\n   <li> distribute the game information; players can get\r\n<ul>\r\n          <li> notification (via email) that the game web page has been updated\r\n          <li> the turn report via email\r\n          <li> both \r\n</ul>\r\n</ol>\r\n<P>\r\nThis list describes a system in which human players can get results and play the game. There are a few other things that we might like to have.\r\n<P>\r\nFirst, it would be good for the players to have a more sophisticated view of their turn. For this we need some kind of long term database of activities. From this database we can, based on the details of the game, create trend reports that the player may find fun or useful.\r\n<P>\r\nSecond, it may be advantageous to have computer players in a game. These can be used to flesh out the players (so we have 20 players instead of just 10, for example) or to balance the game (so that resources get evenly distributed). Computer players can\'t easily read all the information in a text turn report. So there needs to be some kind of machine readable report that has the events of the turn. Of course, computer players can open up the game state file and see even the information that they shouldn\'t see (i.e. \"cheat\") but important information (such as which events failed) might be hidden to them.\r\n<P>\r\n\r\n<P>Each game has to have a process turn executable that the Redwall process can\r\ncall. This executable knows how to find the state of the game and the turns and\r\nprocesses them. Exactly how this is done may vary from turn to turn; all that is required is that an executable exist that can get the information from RedWall and run the turn. \r\n\r\n<P>When games are started a flat tab delimited temporary file is created that has\r\nthe player information in it (usernames and email addresses). The location of\r\nthis file is passed to the \"start game\" executable provided by the game\r\ndesigner. This process converts the information from the flat file to the\r\ngame\'s native format for storing information. ',170,30,0,'2005-06-27 03:47:45'),(191,4,'Ending a Game','<P>When a game ends, the game calls a RedWall routine with the path to a file that contains the results of the game. \r\n<P>The first record defines the\r\nstatistics the game is going to send and then subsequent records list the\r\nplayer username and his stats. The list is assumed to be in order from best to\r\nworst and it is not required (but desired) that it include all the players.\r\n<P>\r\nFor example, the first line says\r\n\"Score,Cash,Ships,Planets,People\"\r\nAnd subsequent lines say\r\nDave,200000,10000,20,50,2000\r\nFred,180000, 9000,25,40,1600\r\nAnn, 150000,12000,13,25,1000\r\nAND SO FORTH\r\n<P>\r\nIt would be nice if RedWall tracked all these stats for each player (first how\r\nmany times in which game, second, how many times in which games, average score,\r\naverage cash, average ships, average planets, average people). Note that\r\nRedWall has no idea what any of this stuff means, it just has to track it\r\naccording to the data given, which is defined by the game.',170,40,0,'2005-06-27 03:55:47'),(192,29,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-06-17 02:10:04'),(193,29,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-06-17 02:10:04'),(194,29,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-06-17 02:10:04'),(195,29,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-06-17 02:10:04'),(196,29,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-06-17 02:10:04'),(197,29,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-06-17 02:10:04'),(198,30,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-06-23 04:24:23'),(199,30,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-06-23 04:24:23'),(200,30,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-06-23 04:24:23'),(201,30,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-06-23 04:24:23'),(202,30,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-06-23 04:24:23'),(203,30,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-06-23 04:24:23'),(210,1,'WhatchaMall Modules','<P>The WM program consists of three main programs: the customer program (which is in index.php), the tenant program (which is in tenant.php) and the admin program (which is in admin.php). There are also a number of other files that contain various subroutines in support of one or more of these main programs. \r\n<P>These three programs are divided in this way primarily because of security: the customer program needs no security, the tenant program verifies that the user is a valid tenant at the start and then verifies that the tenant is allowed to do specific things throughout the functions and the admin program verifies at the start that the user is a valid admin (all admin functions can be performed by any admin). \r\n<P>The indivudual modules are accessed through the use of a mode= phrase in the url (or hidden variables in the case of post data). The user is largely unaware of this mechanism but all control is passed from one module to another (and, in case of forms, within the module from the form display to the form processing) through this mechanism.',0,65,0,'2005-07-13 22:18:27'),(249,1,'Search Engine','<P>The search engine is simply a text field with a \"search\" button next to it. It will do a very simple search for all the individual words (longer than 2 characters) that aren\'t on a list of words to ignore. It will look through the name and description of items, the name and description of store categories and the names of stores. \r\n<P>This passes the following variable to the template:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>biglogotag -- a tag containing the WhatchaMall logo\r\n<li>items -- a list of the items found (all item fields)\r\n<li>stores -- a list of stores found (all space fields)\r\n<li>spacecategory -- a list of store categories found (all store category fields)\r\n</ul>\r\n<P>The template is contained in search.tpl.',245,20,0,'2005-07-13 23:03:46'),(252,1,'Store Item Summary','This module displays a summary of all the items in this category. Each item has a thumbnail and a name and a price. It also has a link to a detail page and a link to buy the item. If the item is on special the normal price is shown with a line through it, a special price is shown in another color and an icon is placed next to the item name (perhaps the word \"Special\" with a yellow explosion around it like \"new!\" on the MencBigSale site).\r\n<P>The variables that are passed to the template are: \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>    maxtnwidth -- maximum thumbnail width\r\n<li>    maxlogwidth -- maximum logo width\r\n<li>    background -- background name\r\n<li>    biglogo -- name of store logo\r\n<li>    items -- list of active items with their categories (ItemID,ItemName,Description,Price,Count,ItemStatus,SpecialFlag,SpecialPrice,RFID,UPC,CategoryName,CategoryDesc)\r\n<li>    message -- a message from the program to the user\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<P>The template is contained in either catsummary.tpl or galsummary.tpl depending  on whether this is a catalog or gallery store. ',245,50,0,'2005-07-13 23:24:13'),(270,1,'Theme','Theme management allows the admin to create new themes as well as to edit existing themes and upload the theme thumbnails that the tenants will use to select a theme. The page also allows the admin to upload backgrounds and to related background to themes; only those theme/background combinations that are allowed by this sytem can be chosen by the tenants. ',247,70,0,'2005-07-14 21:58:34'),(250,1,'Store Category List','<P>This is a list of stores in the mall in a particular category. The categoryno= variable in the url determines the category number. \r\n<P>It passes the following variables to the template:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>spaces - a list of the active spaces in this category(all the space fields)\r\n<li>message - a message from the program to the user\r\n</ul>\r\n<P>The template is contained in storelist.tpl.',245,30,0,'2005-07-13 22:18:27'),(251,1,'Store Lobby','The Store Front Lobby has the logo for the store and contains a list of the categories in that store and the specials taken from throughout the store. It is accessed through a URL something like www.whatchamall.com?store=spacenumber. When a customer clicks on a category, they are taken to the Category Item List.\r\n<P>The variables that are passed to the template are: \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>backgroundimage -- the image for the background as chosen by the tenant\r\n<li>bgcolor -- the background color as chosen by the tenant\r\n<li>spaceno -- the space number of this store\r\n<li>items -- list of active items in this store (item fields plus \"curprice\",\"specialimagetag\", and \"specialstring\")\r\n<li>category -- list of categories with items in them with a count of the number of items (CategoryID,CategoryName,CategoryDesc, Count)\r\n<li>logomaxwidth -- maximum logo width\r\n<li>logoimagetag -- logo image tag\r\n<li>spaceinfo -- information about this space (space fields plus \"style\" which is the directory name of the style)\r\n<li>message -- a message from the program to the user\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<P>The template is contained in either catstorelobby.tpl or galstorelobby.tpl depending  on whether this is a catalog or gallery store. \r\n',245,40,0,'2005-07-13 23:03:46'),(253,1,'Store Item Detail','The item detail has a full size picture and a complete description along with the name, the price and a link to buy the item. It will also have a search engine form and a link back to the category the item belongs to.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>spaceinfo -- all the space info (space fields)\r\n<li>tenantinfo -- all the tenant info (tenant fields)\r\n<li>biglogo -- big logo image\r\n<li>maxitemwidth -- maximum item image witdth\r\n<li>maxlogowidth -- maximum logo width\r\n<li>item -- this item\'s information (all item fields plus imagepath,curprice,specialimage,specialstring)\r\n<li>itemno -- this item number\r\n<li>background -- background image\r\n<li>message --  a message from the program to the user\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<P>The template is contained in either catdetail.tpl or galdetail.tpl depending  on whether this is a catalog or gallery store. ',245,60,0,'2005-07-13 23:24:13'),(254,1,'Tenant Registration','On the main page for the Mall there is a \"register now\" link which takes you to this page. The potential tenant enters his contact information, his username and password, the name and description of the space, the space category and the type of space. Then he clicks on the payment link and goes to PayPal to pay for the first month of service. The space information is saved before we go to PayPal. <P>If PayPal comes back with a positive response, we activate the space; if not then the space information is available to be activated when and if the tenant pays.\r\n<P>\r\nWe take no steps to ensure that any of the contact information is valid; if PayPal gives us the money we know that the tenant is real and can be contacted through PayPal. \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>SpaceCategoryName -- list of possible space category names\r\n<li>SpaceCategoryID -- list of possible space category ids (matches names)\r\n<li>PaymentMethodName -- list of possible payment methods\r\n<li>PaymentMethodID -- list of possible payment method ids (matches names)\r\n<li>SpaceTypeName -- list of possible space type names\r\n<li>SpaceTypeID -- list of possible space type ids (matches names)\r\n<li>message -- a message from the program to the user\r\n</ul>\r\n<P>\r\nThe template is contained in tenantreg.tpl.',245,70,0,'2005-07-13 23:37:17'),(265,1,'Phrase','The phrase module allows for the management of phrases. Phrases can be added and edited. These phrases will eventually form the basis of a multilanguage system. ',247,20,0,'2005-07-14 21:26:23'),(266,1,'Policy','The policy module allows the admin to manage policies. The policies are used by the program anywhere we would have put a \"magic number\" -- they form a sort of web-controlled constants that control how the system works. ',247,30,0,'2005-07-14 21:26:23'),(267,1,'Image Review','This module shows all the images that are in the system along with information about who uploaded them and for what purpose. The admin is allowed to delete any of them but deleted images are kept around. ',247,40,0,'2005-07-14 21:28:59'),(268,1,'Store Category','Every store has a category associated with it. This is the module that allows the admin to edit the categories. The customers have to choose one of the categories on this list to describe their store.',247,50,0,'2005-07-14 21:58:34'),(269,1,'Tenant','<P>On the Tenant Management screen (which is only accessible to admins) every space is listed and the admin can manually add a space, delete a space and edit the information about existing spaces.\r\n<P>\r\nThe main screen shows a list of the sites with the name, rate, paiduntil, status, space category and space type fields displayed in an editable form and a detail link to edit the rest of the tenant information. On the detail page will be listed statistics about sales and other information we have about the tenant including contact information and how many sales he\'s made recently.\r\n<P>\r\nThis has forms for managing (editing, adding, and deleting) space type, shipping methods, payment methods, and space categories and topics. In general, these will require code changes in addition to adding them to this area but we also need a way to edit them.\r\n<P>\r\nThe tenant management screens are protected by the site authentication system. ',247,60,0,'2005-07-13 21:39:50'),(271,1,'Report1','<P>This report show the usage of the web site by listing all the sitelog records. As indicated in the database design, SiteLogID is a unique identifier for the event, the referer is the location that this URL was linked from, the remote_addr is the ip address of the user, the username is the username this user is logged in as (if any), the logTS is the timestamp for this event (year, month, day, 24 hour clock with no spaces) and request_uri is the url that was requested. \r\n<P>No action can be taken on this page.',247,80,0,'2005-07-14 21:58:34'),(224,1,'Item Table','<pre>\r\nItemID INT  -- A globally unique item identifier\r\nCategoryNo INT -- Category this item belongs in\r\nItemName TINYTEXT -- Name of item (on ebay this is called \"title\")\r\nDescription TEXT -- Complete description of item\r\nPrice DECIMAL(10,2), -- price (up to $100,000)\r\nCount INT, -- number of items\r\nSpaceNo INT, -- which space does this item belong to\r\nItemStatus ENUM(ACTIVE,INACTIVE), -- status of item, allows tenant to turn off an item w/o deleting it\r\nSpecialFlag BOOL, -- is this item on special?\r\nSpecialPrice DECIMAL(10,2), -- special price (up to $100,000)\r\nItemID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A globally unique item identifier\r\nCategoryNo INT, -- Category this item belongs in\r\nItemName TINYTEXT, -- Name of item (on ebay this is called \"title\")\r\nDescription TEXT, -- Complete description of item\r\nPrice DECIMAL(10,2), -- price (up to $100,000)\r\nCount INT, -- number of items\r\nSpaceNo INT, -- which space does this item belong to\r\nItemStatus ENUM(ACTIVE,INACTIVE), -- status of item, allows tenant to turn off an item w/o deleting it\r\nSpecialFlag BOOL, -- is this item on special?\r\nSpecialPrice DECIMAL  -- special price (up to $100,000)\r\nFrontPage tinyint  -- does this item belong on the front page?\r\nFrontPageOrder int -- where on the front page does this belong\r\nRFID tinytext -- RFID code\r\nUPC tinytext -- UPC code     \r\nDeleted BOOL, -- nothing is ever really deleted (because of the transaction log)\r\n</pre>',27,10,0,'2005-07-14 03:55:51'),(225,1,'Category  Table','<pre>\r\nCategoryID INT  -- A unique identifier\r\nSpaceNo INT, -- which space this category belong in\r\nCategoryName TINYTEXT, -- name of this category\r\nCategoryDesc TINYTEXT -- description of this category\r\n</pre>',27,20,0,'2005-07-14 03:55:51'),(226,1,'SpaceCategory Table','<pre>\r\nSpaceCategoryID INT , -- A unique identifier\r\nSpaceCategoryName TINYTEXT, -- name of this category\r\nSpaceCategoryDesc TINYTEXT -- description of this category\r\nSpaceTypeNo int -- which type is this category for (gallery or category) \r\n</pre>',27,30,0,'2005-07-14 03:55:51'),(227,1,'Image Table','<pre>\r\nImageID INT  -- A unique identifier\r\nItemNo INT, --which item this image belongs to\r\nImageURL TINYTEXT --URL of the image\r\n ImageData blob -- actual data of image\r\n</pre>',27,40,0,'2005-07-14 03:55:51'),(228,1,'SpaceType Table','<pre>\r\nSpaceTypeID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A unique identifier\r\nSpaceTypeName TINYTEXT, -- the name of the type of space\r\nSpaceTypeDesc TINYTEXT -- the description of the type of space\r\n</pre>',27,50,0,'2005-07-13 23:59:41'),(229,1,'Space Table','<pre>\r\nSpaceID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A unique identifier\r\nSpaceName TINYTEXT, -- the name of the space\r\nSpaceTypeNo INT, -- the space type\r\nSpaceCategoryNo INT, -- the category of the space\r\nStartDate DATE, -- the date this space was created\r\nPaidUntil DATE, -- the space is paid until this date\r\nRentalRate DECIMAL(9,2), -- monthly rental fees (up to $10,000)\r\nSpaceStatus ENUM(ACTIVE,INACTIVE), -- status of space, allows admin to turn off space w/o deleting it\r\n BkColor tinytext -- background color\r\n Style int -- style (aka theme)\r\n BackGround int -- background image\r\n Logo int -- logo for store\r\n PaypalEmail tinytext -- paypal email address of tenant\r\n TenantNo int -- tenant number of owner of this space\r\n</pre>',27,60,0,'2005-07-14 05:07:43'),(230,1,'SpacePaymentMethod Table','<pre>\r\nPaymentID INT -- A unique identifier\r\nPaymentMethodNo INT, -- the method identifier\r\nSpaceNo INT -- the space that has this method\r\n</pre>',27,70,0,'2005-07-14 05:07:43'),(231,1,'SpaceShippingMethod Table','<pre>\r\nShipingID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A unique identifier\r\nShippingMethodNo INT, -- the shipping method identifier\r\nSpaceNo INT); -- the space that has this method\r\n</pre>',27,80,0,'2005-07-13 23:59:42'),(232,1,'PaymentMethod Table','<pre>\r\nPaymentMethodID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A unique identifier\r\nPaymentMethod TINYTEXT);  -- the name of the payment method\r\n</pre>',27,90,0,'2005-07-13 23:59:42'),(233,1,'ShippingMethod Table','<pre>\r\nShipingMethodID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A unique identifier\r\nShippingMethod TINYTEXT); -- the name of the shipping method\r\n</pre>',27,100,0,'2005-07-13 23:59:42'),(234,1,'TenantContact Table','<pre>\r\nTenantID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A unique identifier\r\nContactName TINYTEXT, -- the name of the person who owns the space\r\nAddress1 TINYTEXT, -- the first line of the street address\r\nAddress2 TINYTEXT, -- the second line of the street address\r\nCity TINYTEXT, -- the city\r\nState TINYTEXT, -- the state\r\nZip TINYTEXT, -- the zip\r\nPhone TINYTEXT, -- the phone number\r\nPaymentMethodNo INT, -- the payment method this person uses\r\nUsername TINYTEXT, -- the username for this tenant\r\nPassword TINYTEXT, -- the password for this tenant\r\nTempPW TINYTEXT, -- a temporary password\r\nTempPWExpiry DATE);\r\n</pre>',27,110,0,'2005-07-13 23:59:42'),(235,1,'Languages Table','<pre>\r\nLanguageID INT NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY AUTO-INCREMENT, -- A unique identifier\r\nLanguageName TINYTEXT); -- name of the language\r\n</pre>',27,120,0,'2005-07-13 23:59:42'),(236,1,'Phrases Table','<pre>\r\nPhraseID INT  -- A unique identifier\r\nPhraseName tinytext -- identifying string\r\nPhrase TINYTEXT, -- a phrase in some language\r\nLanguageNo INT); -- language name\r\n</pre>',27,130,0,'2005-07-14 05:07:43'),(237,1,'SiteLog Table','<pre>\r\nSiteLogID INT -- a unique identifier\r\nreferer TINYTEXT -- the url that referered us\r\nremote_addr tinytext -- the ip address of the requestor\r\nhttp_user_agent tinytext -- browser name\r\nusername tinytext -- the username for this request\r\nrequest_uri tinytext -- the url requested\r\n params text \r\n logTS timestamp(14) \r\n</pre>',27,140,0,'2005-07-14 05:07:43'),(238,1,'TransactionLog Table','<pre>\r\nTransactionID INT  -- A unique identifier\r\nSpaceNo INT -- the space associated with this transaction\r\nItemNo INT -- the item number for this transaction\r\nQuantity INT -- the quantity of this transaction\r\nPrice DECIMAL(10,2) -- the price of this transaction\r\nCategoryNo int -- the category number of this transaction\r\nItemName tinytext -- the item name\r\nTransTS TIMESTAMP -- time and date of the transaction\r\n</pre>',27,150,0,'2005-07-14 05:07:43'),(239,1,'Database Design Diagram','<img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/designs/whatchamalldbdesign.jpg\">',0,110,0,'2005-07-13 21:00:29'),(242,1,'Themes Table','<pre>\r\n ThemeID int(11) \r\n ThemeName tinytext \r\n ThemeDescription tinytext \r\n ThemeDirectory tinytext \r\n</pre>',27,180,0,'2005-07-14 05:15:59'),(243,1,'WMImage Table','<pre>\r\n ImageID int(11) \r\n ImageType int(11) \r\n ElementNo int(11) \r\n ImageURL tinytext \r\n ImageData blob \r\n</pre>',27,190,0,'2005-07-14 05:15:59'),(244,1,'DatabaseLog Table','<pre>\r\n</pre>',27,200,0,'2005-07-13 23:56:54'),(245,1,'Customer Modules','<P>The customer modules are all contained in the index.php file. Roughly speaking, each module listed here is a separate screen from the customer\'s point of view. ',0,70,0,'2005-07-13 21:42:08'),(246,1,'Tenant Modules','<P>All the tenant modules are in the tenant.php file. The whole file is authenticated and all the individual routines check to ensure that tenants can only access their own information. ',0,80,0,'2005-07-14 17:46:01'),(247,1,'Administration Modules','<P>Unlike the other modules, the adminstration modules have a single, simple main page. This page has tabs across the top that allow the user to select which admin module she would like. ',0,90,0,'2005-07-13 21:39:50'),(248,1,'Mall Lobby','The Mall Front Lobby is accessed through the WhatchaMall domain name and contains a list of all the spaces in the Mall sorted by their store category, a registration link, a search link (for a global search) and a list of specials taken from throughout the Mall. There will also be a link that allows a user to see all the item categories in all the catalog stores and one that allows a user to see all the topics in the galleries. \r\n<P>The variables that are sent to this module include\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>message - a message from the program to the user\r\n<li>catalogcategory - list of catalog store categories (SpaceCategoryID,SpaceCategoryName, SpaceCategoryDesc, Count)\r\n<li>gallerycategory - list of gallery store categories (SpaceCategoryID,SpaceCategoryName,SpaceCategoryDesc ,Count)\r\n<li>specialitems - list of items that are both active and have either their special flag or their front page flag set (all item fields)\r\n<li>wmlogotag - the whatchamall logo in the form of a tag (<img src=\"\" alt=\"\">)\r\n<li>catspace - list of spaces that are active (all space fields)\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<P>The template is contained in malllobby.tpl.',245,10,0,'2005-07-13 22:18:27'),(255,1,'Edit Tenant Account','Allows users to change everything about their space and contact information. This page also shows whatever data we have about customer activity (sales, browsing, click throughs and so forth). There are links here to the Category and Item management modules. This module is protected by a username/password controlled by the Mall. The login should always check for an unexpired temporary password as part of the authentications determination. The tenant must be able to change their password. ',246,10,0,'2005-07-13 21:35:47'),(256,1,'Category Edit','The category management module allows the tenant to add, edit and delete item categories. At the top is a form for adding a new category and below that is a list of existing categories. The name and description of each category is in the list as a field in a form along with an update button and delete link. This module is protected by a username/password controlled by the Mall.\r\n',246,20,0,'2005-07-13 21:35:47'),(258,1,'Item Summary Edit','The Item management summary page has a form to add new items at the top of the page, along with a link to the category management page. Below that it has a list of every item the tenant has with a thumbnail, the name, the inventory count, the price, the status, the stock number, the special flag and special price and a link to a detail page for that item. All the fields are in a form and can be edited on the summary page.',246,40,0,'2005-07-13 21:35:47'),(259,1,'Item Detail Edit','The detail page has a form to edit all the fields including the description and image (which the tenant can either upload or enter as a link to repository somewhere else). The detail also has all the data we have about customers browsing and sales.\r\n\r\nThis module is protected by a username/password controlled by the Mall. ',246,50,0,'2005-07-13 21:35:47'),(260,1,'Lost Password',' There should be a link for \"forgotten password\" on any login page. The procedure will be to ask for a username. We\'ll send that user an e-mail (based on his e-mail) with a link that has a temporary password encoded in the URL. Add a field for temporary passwords and expiry for them. Always check to see if the temp pw hasn\'t expired and allow them to log in. Recommend that the user reset their password. THIS IMPLIES, that the user can set their password in the first place.',246,100,0,'2005-07-13 21:35:47'),(264,1,'Language','The language module allows for the management of the languages supported by the system. The admin can use this module to add languages. ',247,10,0,'2005-07-14 21:19:18'),(273,31,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-07-14 05:55:49'),(274,31,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-07-14 05:55:49'),(275,31,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-07-14 05:55:49'),(276,31,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-07-14 05:55:49'),(277,31,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-07-14 05:55:49'),(278,31,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-07-14 05:55:49'),(279,32,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-07-17 20:20:11'),(280,32,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-07-17 20:20:11'),(281,32,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-07-17 20:20:11'),(282,32,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-07-17 20:20:11'),(283,32,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-07-17 20:20:11'),(284,32,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-07-17 20:20:11'),(290,33,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-07-23 09:51:58'),(286,23,'Required Pages','<ul>\r\n<li>register to be a moderator\r\n<li>start new game (moderators only)\r\n<li>Sign up for an existing game\r\n<li>check on status (moderators only)\r\n</ul>\r\n',0,45,0,'2005-07-23 08:11:09'),(287,23,'coordinator table','<ul>\r\n<li>coordinator ID\r\n<li>Real name\r\n<li>email address\r\n<li>password\r\n<li>email address\r\n<li>time stamp\r\n</ul>',117,10,0,'2005-07-23 09:00:46'),(288,23,'player table','<ul>\r\n<li>player id\r\n<li>real name\r\n<li>game no\r\n<li>email address\r\n<li>time stamp\r\n</ul>\r\n<i>(note: this is not in 2nf so that when you delete the game you can delete the\r\nplayers)</i>\r\n',117,20,0,'2005-07-23 09:00:53'),(289,23,'Game table','<ul>\r\n<li>gameid\r\n<li>game name\r\n<li>number of players\r\n<li>coordinator no\r\n<li>game city\r\n<li>datestamp\r\n</ul>',117,30,0,'2005-07-23 09:00:46'),(291,33,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-07-23 09:51:58'),(292,33,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-07-23 09:51:58'),(293,33,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-07-23 09:51:58'),(294,33,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-07-23 09:51:58'),(295,33,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-07-23 09:51:58'),(296,34,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-07-28 02:45:01'),(297,34,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-07-28 02:45:01'),(298,34,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-07-28 02:45:01'),(299,34,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-07-28 02:45:01'),(300,34,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-07-28 02:45:01'),(301,34,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-07-28 02:45:01'),(302,35,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-07-28 02:49:42'),(303,35,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-07-28 02:49:42'),(304,35,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-07-28 02:49:42'),(305,35,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-07-28 02:49:42'),(306,35,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-07-28 02:49:42'),(307,35,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-07-28 02:49:42'),(308,36,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-07-28 02:51:51'),(309,36,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-07-28 02:51:51'),(310,36,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-07-28 02:51:51'),(311,36,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-07-28 02:51:51'),(312,36,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-07-28 02:51:51'),(313,36,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-07-28 02:51:51'),(317,37,'Technical Design Notes','',0,50,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(320,38,'Introduction','',0,10,0,'2005-09-21 14:59:46'),(321,38,'Definitions','',0,20,0,'2005-09-21 14:59:46'),(322,38,'Database Design',''