 Maintaining a personal network involves talking to people on a regular basis. Some of us do this naturally but most of us need some mechanism to help us. This application is intended as a mechanical system to assist the maintaining of a network and other networking-related activities. \r\n<P>\r\nThe application does two major things. It maintains a contact list and it provides \"tickles\". That is, it tells you who you should be talking to in any given week. Tickles come in two flavors: new contacts and existing contacts. A new contact is one the user has never talked to before. An existing contact is, basicly, a friend or acquaintence that the user has an existing relationship with. \r\n<P>\r\nThe application provides tickles via email on a regular basis (usually weekly). In each tickle the application sends a list of contacts that should be talked to this week. The user then tells the application what the results of the meetings were (more contacts? just a nice chat? couldn\'t contact the person?) and then the application updates the database and takes that into consideration on the next tickle.\r\n<P>\r\nThe application will also allow the user to enter information about events (interviews, .meetings, etc.) and will generate reports about the activities for the week.\r\n\r\nIt also tracks groups and companies, notes, and todo lists.\r\n<P>\r\nThis is a multiuser application, maintaining user names and passwords and seperate databases for dozens of users.',0,10,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(357,37,'Definitions','<ul>\r\n<li>User -- the person using the application \r\n<li>Person -- an individual that you want to keep track of\r\n<li>Contact -- the act of talking to a person in the database\r\n<li>Tickle -- the message that the application sends to users to tell them which persons they need to contact. \r\n<li>Appointment -- an informational or employment interview\r\n<li>Meeting -- the meeting of a group of people usually involving either a speaker or \"smoozing\" or both\r\n</ul>',0,20,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(358,37,'Database Design','',0,40,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(360,37,'Issues','',0,60,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(361,37,'Future Enhancements','',0,70,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(362,37,'Modules','',0,30,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(383,37,'Manage Persons','<P>Manage our list of persons. These functions would include:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>View a list of persons (may be sorted or filtered)\r\n<li>Add a person to the list\r\n<li>Edit a person entry\r\n</ul>',362,20,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(384,37,'table person','personid int primary index auto\r\nname tinytext\r\nhometel tinytext\r\nrelationship tinytext\r\nprofession tinytext\r\nhomeaddr tinytext\r\ncompany tinytext\r\nofftel tinytext\r\ncelltel tinytext\r\nemail tinytext\r\nwrkaddr tinytext\r\nassistant tinytext\r\nchildren tinytext\r\nlastcall date\r\nrefferedby tinytext\r\nresults mediumtext\r\nfollowup mediumtext\r\nletter mediumtext\r\ncall mediumtext\r\nprefcomm enum (\'email\', \'cell\', \'home\',\'work\', \'mail\')\r\ninterests mediumtext\r\nownerno int\r\ncomments mediumtext\r\npersonno int // person that this contact came from\r\neventno int // event that this contact came from\r\nnextcontact date\r\nlastcontact date\r\neventid int\r\ncategory enum (\'Active\',\'Background\',\'Complementary\',\'Dormant\')\r\nts timestamp',358,10,0,'2005-10-04 06:39:25'),(385,37,'Table Events','EventID\r\norganization\r\nname // name of person this event involves, if any, and if he\'s NOT in our contact list\r\npersonno // person this event involves, if any and if he\'s in our contact list\r\nposition // position this event involves, if known\r\ntype (meeting, phonecontact,  appsched, appatt, sentresume, phonescreen, jobinterview, negotiation)\r\nlocation // where was this this event\r\ndate\r\ntime\r\nduration\r\nsourceno // which person hooked us up with this event\r\nsummary // a text description of the event\r\ninterviewernotes // notes on the interviewer, if any\r\nresponsenotes // notes on the response we received, if any\r\ninformationnotes // notes on information we may have gained/learned\r\nresultsnotes // notes on results\r\n// perhaps these notes should all be in the notes table and these should be refreences\r\nownerno int\r\ntimestamp ',358,20,0,'2005-10-04 06:39:25'),(382,37,'Preferences data','<ul>\r\n<li>Do I get email? (y)\r\n<li>How often?  (1 week)\r\n<li>What times? (Sunday night midnight to 3 pm)\r\n<li>How many existing network contacts do I want to make (existing slots)? (3)\r\n<li>How many new network contacts do I want to make (new slots)? (1) \r\n</ul>\r\n',358,200,0,'2005-10-04 06:31:45'),(369,37,'Events','The basic activities of the user are considered \"events\" and each time one is performed the system must incorporate what was learned from the actvity into the various tables in the database. These events inlclude:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Meeting Attended -- the user went to a meeting, presumably making new contacts\r\n<li>Phone/Email Contact -- the user called someone either as an initial contact or as a followup\r\n<li>Appointment Scheduled -- the user has scheduled an appointment\r\n<li>Appointment Attended -- the user has attended an appointment\r\n<li>Resume Mailed -- the user mailed a resume\r\n<li>Phone Screen -- the user has been interviewed over the phone\r\n<li>Job Interview -- the user has been interviewed in person\r\n<li>Negotiation -- a negotiation for a job has been undertaken\r\n<li>Job Taken -- the user has taken a job \r\n</ul>\r\n<P>For each event there should be a custom form that creates an entry, carefully setting certain fields to a default value based on that type of event and/or simply ignoring certain fields. There must also be a screen that lists events (sorted and perhaps filtered) and a screen that will allow the user to edit events.',362,10,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(393,39,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-10-13 19:55:11'),(394,39,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-10-13 19:55:11'),(395,39,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-10-13 19:55:11'),(396,39,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-10-13 19:55:11'),(373,37,'Tickles','<P>There is a function that creates a list of people who should be contacted based on the current state of the database and the preferences. Essentially, the policies in the preferences will tell you how many existing and new people to contact a week and the person table will tell you which people haven\'t been contacted recently. This function will simply make a list of the N people of each type that haven\'t been contacted.\r\n<P>This module uses that function in two ways. First, it sends an email to the user (based on the user\'s preferences) that contains all the contact information about these people. Second, there is a link to the \"tickle page\" which simply lists the information about these people. ',362,50,0,'2005-10-05 19:16:10'),(398,39,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-10-13 19:55:11'),(397,39,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-10-13 19:55:11'),(374,37,'Administration','',362,60,0,'2005-09-13 06:19:24'),(375,37,'Reports','',362,70,0,'2005-09-13 06:19:24'),(380,38,'Issues','',0,50,0,'2005-09-21 14:59:46'),(381,38,'Future Enhancements','',0,60,0,'2005-09-21 14:59:46'),(392,37,'Todo list','This is a standard todo list except that the project is actually the eventid.\r\nownerno int',358,90,0,'2005-10-04 06:39:25'),(386,37,'table user','Name\r\nemail address\r\npassword\r\nusername\r\nlast login\r\nnewcontacts handled in last month\r\nold contact handled in last month (look at log file, find people he changed the contact date on)\r\nnewcontacts needed in last month (total on list before culling for tickle)\r\nold contacts needed in last month (total on list before culling for tickle)\r\ntemppassword\r\ntpexpiry\r\ncontact time (a number between 1 and 60 which is the minutes beyond the hour that automated things happen for this guy).\r\ntimestamp',358,40,0,'2005-10-04 06:26:10'),(387,37,'table preferences','preferenceid\r\nuserno\r\npreferencename\r\nprferencevalue\r\npreferencedescription',358,50,0,'2005-10-04 06:27:49'),(388,37,'Table hitlog','need to work out the details but it essentially logs each time the program is accessed in any way',358,60,0,'2005-10-04 06:27:49'),(389,37,'table dblog','logs every time an update or insert or delete is executed\r\nincludes\r\nSQL command\r\nuser id\r\nurl\r\ntimestamp',358,70,0,'2005-10-04 06:27:49'),(390,37,'Table Organizations','OrgID\r\nName\r\nDesc\r\nWeb\r\ntype (company, networking org)\r\nsourceno int\r\nownerno int\r\ntimestamp',358,30,0,'2005-10-04 06:39:25'),(391,37,'Notes','noteid\r\nnote\r\ntype (event/org)\r\neventid\r\ndate\r\nownerno int\r\ntimestamp\r\n',358,80,0,'2005-10-04 06:39:25'),(399,40,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-10-13 20:55:45'),(400,40,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-10-13 20:55:45'),(401,40,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-10-13 20:55:45'),(402,40,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-10-13 20:55:45'),(403,40,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-10-13 20:55:45'),(404,40,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-10-13 20:55:45'),(405,41,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-10-17 19:48:03'),(406,41,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-10-17 19:48:03'),(407,41,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-10-17 19:48:03'),(408,41,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-10-17 19:48:03'),(409,41,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-10-17 19:48:03'),(410,41,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-10-17 19:48:03'),(411,42,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2005-10-31 22:25:56'),(412,42,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2005-10-31 22:25:56'),(413,42,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2005-10-31 22:25:56'),(414,42,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2005-10-31 22:25:56'),(415,42,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2005-10-31 22:25:56'),(416,42,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2005-10-31 22:25:56'),(417,43,'Introduction','<P>This is a WIKI project tracking system intended for a software development environmen. The theory behind it is that the traditional project tracking system is limited by the interface between the project maanager and the engineers. This suggests that the easier you can make it to collect data from the engineers, the better the overall system will be. \r\n<P>This system is arranged so that tasks appear to be a simple todo list. Easy to add todo items, easy to check them off when one is done. But behind the scenes the data is being collected and analysed using standard project management practices.\r\n<P>To do any project management system there are some things you obviously need.\r\n<P>Clearly you have to have the tasks assigned to someone and, with that person\'s\r\napproval, you need to assign durations to all those tasks. Then you can\r\ncalculate, for each project, how many man-hours it will take. If you enter in\r\nhow many dollars for time and how much for overtime each person costs you can\r\ncalculate how much the whole thing costs. \r\n<P>So much for planning. The key to this tool is execution. We want to be able to\r\ntrack how far we are on each task. What I\'d like to know is how many hours each\r\nperson spent on each task, how complete each task is (either %complete or #\r\nhours to completion) and what each person spent the rest of their time. I\'d\r\nsettle for simply having each task that is complete checked off. This is risky\r\nbecause the project software can\'t tell if a task is really hard or if it is\r\nbeing ignored but, if the tasks are short this will give you pretty good\r\ntracking. \r\n',0,10,0,'2008-03-21 17:09:26'),(418,43,'Definitions','For the purposes of this system and this document, the following definitions will be used.\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>Project -- a collection of tasks that culminates, at some predictable point int he future with some predictable useful outcome.\r\n<li>Task -- an activity or closely related set of activites that are worked on by one engineer and have a specific end point and a specified duration\r\n<li>Milestone -- an arbitrary collection of tasks; every task much be associated with a milestone and the milestone is said to be met when all the tasks associated with it are complete\r\n',0,20,0,'2006-01-18 18:11:08'),(422,43,'Database Design','Databases\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>PROJECT has pretty much what the design database has in it\r\n<li>TASK has \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>id<li>title <li>duration <li>assigned to <li>start date <li>desc <li>project <li>plus what\'s in the todo list table\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>TASKSTATUS <ul> <li>entryid<li>taskid <li>currentdate<li>hours worked this week<li>OT hours this week <li>hours to completion </ul>\r\n<li>Notes Contains notes about this project\r\n<li>formal design\r\n<li>comments <ul><li>commentid<li>designid<li>userid<li></ul>\r\n<li>Users add<ul><li>efficiency (ratio of projected duration to actual duration) <li>SD (standard deviation)</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n',0,200,0,'2008-03-21 17:00:09'),(423,44,'Introduction','',0,10,0,'2006-02-20 16:02:13'),(424,44,'Overview','',0,20,0,'2006-02-20 16:02:13'),(425,44,'Maintaining A Site','',0,30,0,'2006-02-20 16:02:13'),(426,44,'Creating A New Page','',0,40,0,'2006-02-20 16:02:13'),(427,44,'Creating A Site From The Beginning','',0,50,0,'2006-02-20 16:02:13'),(434,44,'Advanced Features',NULL,0,60,0,'2006-02-20 16:02:43'),(429,43,'Assumptions','<P>I\'m simplifying this system quite a bit when compared to standard project management systems. I thought it might be good to state them explicitely.\r\n\r\n<li> One task, One engineer\r\n<li>Tasks are fairly short (less than 2 weeks)\r\n<li>Tasks are at least one day\r\n<li>Every task belongs to one and only one project\r\n<li> Every task is associated with a milestone\r\n<li> There is only one level of milestones -- this is a very flat work breakdown structure\r\n<li> by default, when a task is checked as done, the actual time taken is the time between the last task that was checked an this moment\r\n<li> every developer is doing one of the tasks in the system at any given moment \r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n',0,30,0,'2006-01-18 18:11:39'),(433,43,'Reports','The program will generate a set of reports that will describe the state of the project in largely numeric ways. These reports are more or less the goal of any good project management system and really aren\'t that hard to produce. \r\n<P>The exact format of the reports is still an open issue. \r\n<ul><\r\nli>Earned Value Management\r\n\r\n<li>Performance Indices\r\n<li>variances\r\n\r\n<li>Estimate At Completion\r\n</ul>\r\n',0,70,0,'2008-03-21 17:06:00'),(435,45,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2006-06-19 13:10:25'),(436,45,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2006-06-19 13:10:25'),(437,45,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2006-06-19 13:10:25'),(438,45,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2006-06-19 13:10:25'),(439,45,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2006-06-19 13:10:25'),(440,45,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2006-06-19 13:10:25'),(441,46,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2006-07-20 04:38:30'),(442,46,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2006-07-20 04:38:30'),(443,46,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2006-07-20 04:38:30'),(444,46,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2006-07-20 04:38:30'),(445,46,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2006-07-20 04:38:30'),(446,46,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2006-07-20 04:38:30'),(447,47,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2006-10-17 19:07:03'),(448,47,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2006-10-17 19:07:03'),(449,47,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2006-10-17 19:07:03'),(450,47,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2006-10-17 19:07:03'),(451,47,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2006-10-17 19:07:03'),(452,47,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2006-10-17 19:07:03'),(453,48,'The Five','This is an \"ugly truth\" kind of place. I\'m sorry but I really believe that we are going to be, literally, in a world of hurt unless we start paying attention to what we\'re doing. There are 5 major areas that I believe can send our civilization into general decline. By \"civilization\" I mean \"global society\" since I don\'t believe any portion of the world can maintain a technological society while a significant portion of the rest descends into war, famine, disease and general chaos. These five potential catastrophes are all related and need to be solved as a group. Solving one or two won\'t save us and I don\'t think it\'s actually possible to solve any of them separately.\r\n<P>\r\nI want to make two things very clear from the outset. First, this is not a doom and gloom, all is lost proposition. I think we can still save ourselves but we have to actually work at it. I see a lot of people ignoring it and I don\'t see anyone taking it really seriously.\r\n<P>Second, I am not an environmentalist per se. That is, I don\'t believe that we should put the earth before ourselves. However, as it turns out, we must rearrange our lifestyle so that the earth can sustain us or we simply won\'t survive. This aligns me with some ideas of environmentalists and sets me against others. For example, I agree that we need to do things sustainably but I would be against not doing things at all. \r\n',0,10,0,'2008-06-01 02:02:01'),(454,48,'Global Warming','More properly called \"global climate change\", this is observed and generally accepted warming of the earth. Most people agree that it\'s caused by the over use of fossil fuels. This means that it is either the potential cause or potential effect of every other one of the five except overpopulation.\r\n<P>\r\nSomething that is not generally appreciated is that the global climate change doesn\'t necessarily mean that the mean temperature goes up everywhere in an orderly and predictable manner. Rather it means that there is a great deal more energy in the weather systems which means that the temperature, winds, rainfall and so forth are more variable and less predicable. This could result in a disruption of food growth if the \"bread basket\" areas of the earth became untenable as growing areas. It could also create a lack of water if rain fall was distributed differently. The main point, however, is that more variable weather will mean more variable crop yields -- it\'s hard to imagine that will be good for growing as much food as we need.\r\n',453,20,0,'2008-06-01 01:01:13'),(455,48,'Energy Shortages','This should come as no surprise to anyone. We\'ve known since the 50\'s that we were using up all the fossil fuels and we\'ve certainly known since the 70\'s that production doesn\'t always meet demand. What\'s becoming clear is that soon it may not be possible for production to meet demand. This has already caused wars and it will cause bigger and bigger wars as the demand becomes more acute.\r\n<P>Some people believe that if we somehow had enough energy -- say, through fusion -- we would be able to hand all the other problems. This simply isn\'t true. \r\n<P>First off, as a practical matter, we really can\'t have \"enough\" energy. The amount of energy to, say, convert sea water to all the drinking water we will ever need is beyond any conceivable amount that can be produced. \r\n<P>But let\'s say we get matter conversion -- cheap, unlimited energy. Even if we only lost 30% of the energy as heat we would be heating up the world at an alarming rate. And most of our energy producing processes lose more like 80% than 30%. \r\n<P>I\'m sorry but there isn\'t even a theoretical answer that will get us out of this. ',453,30,0,'2008-06-01 01:08:09'),(456,48,'Overpopulation','In a sense, this is the root cause of all the others. As the population of the world grows it will need more of everything which will drive global warming, energy consumption, and require ever more food and water.\r\n<P>But this is an oversimplification. The truth is that every North American consumes so much more resources of every kind than any other citizen of the planet that any plan that doesn\'t involve Americans cutting back on their consumption radically is doomed.\r\n<P>Even assuming that North Americans can cut back on their consumption, it still seems unlikely that the world can support the population that it will have very shortly. And that population will keep growing and growing until it becomes unsustainable.\r\n',453,40,0,'2008-06-01 03:06:28'),(457,48,'Starvation','There are several ways that starvation could happen. Climate change might rearrange places were food will grow in a way that prevents us from growing enough food. We could run out of energy and therefore not be able to sustain large scale agriculture and/or the transportation network. Or the population could simply grow beyond our ability to feed it -- there is only so much growth we can sustain, after all.\r\n<P>As we try to avoid starvation we are very likely to use more energy and more water. \r\n',453,50,0,'2008-06-01 02:02:01'),(458,48,'Lack of Water','Currently some parts of America are using more water than they produce. They are borrowing water from other places. The people in those places, however, are growing and need more and more water themselves. Eventually something will have to give and those states that are importing water will find themselves with a shortage.\r\n<P>\r\nPopulation growth has been the main thing that is driving this and there is no sign this will stop. But as the climate changes there will be an unknown effect on the distribution of water and that may cause a shift in where the water is. If it moves to places we can catch it then we\'ll be ok (that is, we\'ll run out later) but if not, we could run out fairly suddenly.',453,60,0,'2008-06-01 03:06:28'),(459,49,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2007-01-23 06:35:30'),(460,49,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2007-01-23 06:35:30'),(461,49,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2007-01-23 06:35:30'),(462,49,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2007-01-23 06:35:30'),(463,49,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2007-01-23 06:35:30'),(464,49,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2007-01-23 06:35:30'),(465,50,'Introduction','<P>The Group Scheduler is a demonstration project to allow a group to schedule a meeting. It will be complete in the sense that there will be SOME way to create a meeting, have all the participants indicate what days they do or don\'t want to meet on and then generate a report that suggests a day or days that would be best. \r\n\r\n<P>But it is imcomplete in that it won\'t necessarily have the best UI. This is because any particular implementation will require that the UI match the site on which the scheduler is implemented. This is the sense in which it is a \"demonstration project\" -- this demonstrates how you might use it.\r\n\r\n',0,10,0,'2007-04-22 16:08:04'),(466,50,'Definitions','<li>Meeting\r\n<li>YesDate\r\n<li>NoDate\r\n<li>Interval\r\n<li>IntervalList\r\n<li>MeetingMaster',0,20,0,'2007-04-22 16:08:04'),(467,50,'Database Design','<P>The design assumes that there exists a user table that defines things like user names and so forth. The demonstration project has such a table but the details aren\'t important. The important thing is that the there be a \"userno\" integer that represents one and only one user. So here is the usertable for the examples:\r\n<pre>\r\nCREATE TABLE gsuser (\r\n  userid int(11) NOT NULL auto_increment primary key,\r\n  username tinytext,\r\n  userpass tinytext,\r\n  email tinytext,\r\n  name tinytext,\r\n  temppw tinytext,\r\n  tpwexpiry date default \'2000-01-01\',\r\n  type enum(\'inactive\',\'active\',\'admin\') default \'inactive\',\r\n  actword tinytext,\r\n  ts timestamp(14) NOT NULL\r\n  );\r\ninsert into gsuser (username) values (\"Alice\"),(\"Bob\"),(\"Charlie\"),(\"Don\"),(\"Ed\");\r\nupdate gsuser set userpass=\"foo\",email=\"fatzero@gmail.com\",name=username,type=\"active\";\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n',0,30,0,'2007-04-22 16:18:31'),(468,50,'Technical Design Notes','<P>Two important notes. \r\n<P>First, no single user can have two dates in the date list. If he does, that will count as 2 votes for or against the date and might screw things up. This can be trivially avoided by having a unique index on the database table. \r\n<P>Second, there needs to be a user table which one can reference with a \"userno\" integer to refer to a specific user. In the examples we\'ll use a pre-built user table and use the email and so forth out of that but it would be unwieldly for this project to include code to create and manage a user list. I mean, don\'t you have that already? ',0,40,0,'2007-04-22 16:08:04'),(469,50,'Issues','',0,50,0,'2007-04-22 16:02:43'),(470,50,'Future Enhancements','',0,60,0,'2007-04-22 16:02:43'),(471,51,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2007-03-12 16:51:24'),(472,51,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2007-03-12 16:51:24'),(473,51,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2007-03-12 16:51:24'),(474,51,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2007-03-12 16:51:24'),(475,51,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2007-03-12 16:51:24'),(476,51,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2007-03-12 16:51:24'),(477,52,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2007-03-14 00:30:55'),(478,52,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2007-03-14 00:30:55'),(479,52,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2007-03-14 00:30:55'),(480,52,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2007-03-14 00:30:55'),(481,52,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2007-03-14 00:30:55'),(482,52,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2007-03-14 00:30:55'),(483,53,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2007-03-25 16:37:51'),(484,53,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2007-03-25 16:37:51'),(485,53,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2007-03-25 16:37:51'),(486,53,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2007-03-25 16:37:51'),(487,53,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2007-03-25 16:37:51'),(488,53,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2007-03-25 16:37:51'),(489,54,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2007-03-27 16:39:20'),(490,54,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2007-03-27 16:39:20'),(491,54,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2007-03-27 16:39:20'),(492,54,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2007-03-27 16:39:20'),(493,54,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2007-03-27 16:39:20'),(494,54,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2007-03-27 16:39:20'),(495,55,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2007-05-08 02:28:32'),(496,55,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2007-05-08 02:28:32'),(497,55,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'20