to a swiss bank account',0,20,0,'2008-04-03 06:43:44'),(531,60,'dave creates corporation','serendipity corp',0,30,0,'2008-04-03 06:43:44'),(532,60,'serendipity buys high rise low income housing project','',0,40,0,'2008-04-03 06:43:44'),(533,60,'serendipity board picks a project','time travel? ftl? teleportation? don\'t know but something that can be researched by physics something that\'s impossible',0,50,0,'2008-04-03 06:43:44'),(534,60,'set up side businesses to employ people,','',0,170,0,'2008-04-03 06:56:14'),(535,61,'Characters','Builder\r\nBuilder\'s #2\r\nBuilder\'s #3',0,10,0,'2008-04-03 05:54:02'),(536,61,'Builder takes over company','',0,20,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(537,61,'builder has a run in with Hamas','',0,30,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(538,61,'builder brings in outside money','Elaborate efforts are made to ensure that hamas isn\'t involved. Outside of that, the investors go into a variety of businesses all of which require new buildings, renovation and so forth. ',0,40,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(539,61,'#2 splits off','#2 wants to start his own company, be his own boss, get out from the shadow of builder. Builder convinces #3 to go with him, help him and report back. Builder explains that it\'s no good having only one company; there needs to be competition and choices',0,50,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(540,61,'#2 gets into trouble; build helps','Builder helps #2 behind the scenes',0,60,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(541,62,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-01-23 03:28:29'),(542,62,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-01-23 03:28:29'),(543,62,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-01-23 03:28:29'),(544,62,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-01-23 03:28:29'),(545,62,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-01-23 03:28:29'),(546,62,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-01-23 03:28:29'),(547,63,'Introduction','1',0,10,0,'2008-04-30 01:38:04'),(548,63,'Definitions','2',0,20,0,'2008-04-29 23:26:33'),(549,63,'Database Design','3',0,30,0,'2008-04-29 23:26:33'),(550,63,'Technical Design Notes','4',0,40,0,'2008-04-29 23:26:33'),(551,63,'Issues','',0,50,0,'2008-04-29 23:02:51'),(552,63,'Future Enhancements','',0,60,0,'2008-04-29 23:02:51'),(553,64,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-03-02 00:10:29'),(554,64,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-03-02 00:10:29'),(555,64,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-03-02 00:10:29'),(556,64,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-03-02 00:10:29'),(557,64,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-03-02 00:10:29'),(558,64,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-03-02 00:10:29'),(605,65,'Game Models','There are two key game models - Strategy and Adventure. Strategy\r\ncovers all games with area movement, where players fight for control of\r\nterritories, raising and deploying leaders, troops, and production\r\nfacilities. Adventure covers all games with area movement, where players\r\nroam between territories, collecting and recruiting leaders, troops, and\r\nequipment. For user interface reasons more than anything else, both\r\nmodels currently assume the fastest rate of strategic movement is one\r\nterritory per turn - so this works very well for armies on the march,\r\nspaceships jumping from system to system, and even short range aircraft\r\nthat are bound to nearby basing facilities, but doesn\'t really for\r\nscenarios where some aircraft or fleets are supposed to have global\r\nreach within a turn.',593,20,0,'2008-03-12 03:57:01'),(606,65,'Shared Data','A core design principal is that both game models will use the same\r\ndata models and unit attributes, such that, in theory, an Adventure game\r\ncould be layered inside a Strategy game with matching data. For\r\ninstance, there could be a Middle Earth Strategy game where players move\r\narmies around fighting over territory, with a Middle Earth Adventure\r\ngame layered inside - parties in the Adventure game would have to worry\r\nabout the titanic battles and shifts in territory happening around them,\r\nand could even participate in those battles should they end up in the\r\nright place at the right time. At some point, we may be able to fuse\r\nboth models entirely, but we aren\'t going to let that possibility divert\r\nus from launching them separately.',593,5,0,'2008-03-12 04:21:02'),(607,65,'Locations','Each Location has a Name, Owner ID, and Terrain ID.',593,40,0,'2008-03-12 03:57:01'),(608,65,'Routes','Locations are connected via Routes. There can be multiple Routes\r\nbetween any two Locations. Each Route has a Name, Length, and Terrain\r\nID. I\'m leaning towards having a Width as well - consider the pass at\r\nThermopylae versus the steppes between Russia and Ukraine, or for that\r\nmatter, all the different types of tunnels in an underground war between\r\norcs and dwarves.',593,50,0,'2008-03-12 04:00:22'),(609,65,'Units','Units have a Name, Owner ID, Attack Rating, Attack Type ID, Defense\r\nRating, Defense Type ID, Range, Mobility Rating, Mobility Type ID,\r\nDetection Rating, Detection Type ID, Stealth Rating, and Stealth Type ID.',593,60,0,'2008-03-12 04:00:22'),(610,65,'Attack & Defense','Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Attack Type IDs to\r\nDefense Type IDs to yield a base fatality rate, which is then multiplied\r\nby the attacker\'s Attack Rating and divided by the Defender\'s Defense\r\nRating to determine the chance of Destroying or Disrupting a target unit\r\nin an attack.',593,70,0,'2008-03-12 04:00:22'),(611,65,'Detection & Stealth','Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Detection Type IDs to\r\nStealth Type IDs, to yield a base detection rate, which is then\r\nmultiplied by the detector\'s Detection Rating and divided by the\r\ntarget\'s Stealth Rating to determine the chance of Detecting the target\r\nunit.',593,80,0,'2008-03-12 04:00:22'),(612,65,'Terrain & Mobility','Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Mobility Type ID with\r\nTerrain Type ID to yield a base speed, which is then multiplied by the\r\nunit\'s Mobility Rating and divided by the Length of a Route to determine\r\nthe chance of that unit crossing that route in one turn. In combat, a\r\nsimilar computation is done to determine what kind of mobility each unit\r\nhas in that combat situation.',593,90,0,'2008-03-12 04:00:22'),(613,65,'Production','The production system consists of 3 parts. \r\n<P>First, there is a collection of units which might be produced by each player.\r\nTo use a card analogy, this might be called a \"deck\".\r\n<P>Second, there is a pool of units which might be produced in the near future. To\r\nuse a card analogy, this might be called a \"hand\".\r\n<P>Third, there is a set of rules which determine, for each card in the deck,\r\nunder which circumstances it might be deployed. \r\n\r\n<P>All three of these elements may be shared among the player and all three may be\r\nknown or hidden to players to whom they do not apply. \r\n\r\n<P>The third element is of the largest interest because it\'s the most complicated\r\nand the difficult to pull off (not only in production but probably in the whole\r\ngame).\r\n\r\n<P>This element requires two sub-elements. First, a way to describe a situation in\r\nthe game and, second, a location where a unit might be deployed.\r\n\r\n<P>The second sub-element is somewhat easier to create but it should still be\r\npossible to define a location in very flexible terms. That is, it\'s not enough\r\nto say \"in Eqypt\" or \"in New York\" or \"in area 2345\". You have to also be able\r\nto say \"within x areas of area 2345\" or within x areas of this unit or this\r\ntype of unit or even \"within x areas of a city which has these attributes\".\r\n\r\n<P>The first sub-element is even more complicated as it defines not just a\r\nlocation but a condition in the game. To be fully open-ended it needs to allow\r\nany condition or combinations of conditions that might exist in the game to be\r\ndefined. \r\n\r\n<P>These requirements suggest nothing less than a scripting language. The\r\nscripting language does not need to DO anything but it does need to be able to\r\nevaluate boolean expressions involving pretty much every variable that makes up\r\na game. \r\n\r\n<P>It\'s possible to write a custom scripting language, to define that scripting\r\nlanguage in terms of it\'s syntax and semantics, to parse that scripting\r\nlanguage (giving appropriate errors anywhere that there is an error), to\r\nconvert that parsed information into the semantic information, to evaluate that\r\ninformation and come up with a list of legal areas on the one hand or a boolean\r\nvalue on the other. \r\n\r\n<P>Of course it\'s possible to write a scripting language -- thousands of people\r\nhave done it. A few of those thousands have actually survived. However, as both\r\nthe victim and author of more than a few of those scripting languages, I am very\r\nmuch in favor of using something that already exists.\r\n\r\n<P>In this case, since the whole thing revolves around defining data that, after\r\nyou parse it and evaluate it, you need to look up in the data, I think using\r\nthe SQL syntax is probably the best thing to do. You limit it to just a few\r\nkeyword and then you basically hand it to the SQL parser and return whatever\r\nerror it returns. \r\n\r\n<P>This implies that we have a well defined and published database schema and that\r\nchanging the schema means breaking existing games. But at some point you have to\r\ndefine the variables that any scripting language can access and changing those\r\nvariables will break games in any case. \r\n\r\n<P>The basic syntax of SQL is variablename=\'constant\' as well as\r\nvariablename=variablename. Wildcarding syntax looks like variablename like\r\n\'%constant%\' where % is the wildcard. Parentheses and the \"AND\" and \"OR\"\r\nkeywords are supported. \r\n\r\n<P>We would have to make sure that all words not on a relatively short list are\r\nremoved (we don\'t want people our game developers hacking our SQL databases).\r\n\r\n<P>We also may want to extend the syntax with keywords like \"exists\" and \"distance\r\nfrom\". \r\n\r\n<P>The key to this system is to construct a framework in which all the things that\r\nwe want to examine are combined (from their various tables in the database) into\r\none view and then allow the developer to ask specific questions about that view.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Mobility Type ID with\r\nTerrain Type ID to yield a base speed, which is then multiplied by the\r\nunit\'s Mobility Rating and divided by the Length of a Route to determine\r\nthe chance of that unit crossing that route in one turn. In combat, a\r\nsimilar computation is done to determine what kind of mobility each unit\r\nhas in that combat situation.',593,100,0,'2008-03-12 05:28:08'),(614,65,'Scenario','<P>Once there is a universe, one may create a scenario in that universe. \r\n<P>You must specify (oy vey):\r\n<li>A \"map\" (that is, a collection of locations and routes plus some kind of\r\ngraphic representation of same)\r\n<li>A unit set (a complete list of all the possible unit, their names, flavor text,\r\nflavor graphics, etc and their attributes)\r\n<li>A unit order of battle (where and under what circumstances these units become\r\navailable during the course of the scenario) This order of battle is used by\r\nthe production system to allow units to come into being. \r\n<li>Number of players\r\n<li>AI players? \r\n<li>End conditions\r\n<li>victory conditions\r\n<li>high score table information (that is, I finished first in the game; what do I get?)\r\n',593,110,0,'2008-03-12 05:28:08'),(615,65,'Universe','One must create a universe first, name it and so forth. Every universe must\r\nhave \r\n<li>attack types\r\n<li>Defense types\r\n<li>terrain types\r\n<li>mobility types\r\n<li>detection types\r\n<li>stealth types\r\n<li>tables that compare each of these types together. \r\n<P>There is also a collection of flavor information associated with a universe.',593,120,0,'2008-03-12 05:28:08'),(621,43,'Estimate At Completion','The EAC gives an idea of the final costs of a project. It takes into account the original budget (BAC), the Earned Value and the Cost Performance Index of the already completed works.\r\nEAC = ACWP + ((BAC - BCWP)/CPI)\r\n',433,30,0,'2008-03-21 17:02:27'),(622,43,'Performance Indices','Schedule Performance Index and Cost Performance Index give indications of the health of the project. Is the project on time, in budget or what?\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schedule Performance Index is a ratio of Earned Value and the planned value of completed works. A SPI < 1 is not good\r\nSPI = BCWP / BCWS\r\n\r\n<li>Cost Performance Index is a ratio of Earned Value and the actual costs of completed works. A CPI < 1 is not good\r\nCPI = BCWP / ACWP \r\n</ul>',433,40,0,'2008-03-21 17:02:52'),(623,43,'Functional Specification ','',0,210,0,'2008-03-21 17:07:41'),(624,43,'Project Data Gatherer','<ol>\r\n<li>  Gathers, for every task, every week, hours spent this week, hours projected to completion (or % complete at the option of the user). To calculate %complete, take the total hours spent plus the hours to completion and divide into total hours spent and then multiply by 100.\r\n<li> Entry has an \"entry Date\" which defaults to today but can be changed to any date past or future\r\n<li> Entry is for the week of the date entered. If multiple entries are made for that week then only the last entrie (based on the time stamp) is counted -- he who writes last, writes best.\r\n<li> Reports\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> Project total hours (projected)\r\n  <li>Percent Project Complete\r\n<li> Project end date (projected with current data)\r\n<li> Original start and end date\r\n<li>BCWS\r\n<li>ACWP\r\n<li>Earned Value (BCWP)\r\n<li> Schedule Variance\r\n<li> Cost Variance\r\n<li> SPI\r\n<li>CPI\r\n<li>EAC\r\n<li> A list of all completed tasks showing how much longer they took than estimated\r\n<li> A list of all developers, showing how far off their estimates were \r\n</ul>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n',623,10,0,'2008-03-26 23:59:42'),(618,43,'Earned Value Management','<ul>\r\n<li>Budgeted Cost for Work Scheduled (BCWS) - the budgets for all activities planned to be completed. Total projected project cost based on work breakdown and resource costs.\r\n    <li>Actual Cost of Work Performed (ACWP) - the real costs of the work charged against the completed activities. ACWP = work completed (by measurement)\r\n    <li>Budgeted Cost of Work Performed (BCWP) or Earned Value (EV) - the planned costs of the work allocated to the completed activities. This is the Earned Value. Earned Value = Percentage project complete X Project Budget\r\n</ul>\r\n',433,10,0,'2008-03-21 17:02:27'),(619,43,'variances','Schedule and cost variances can both be calculated in monetary terms from the data needed to produce the S-curves.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schedule variance is the difference between the Earned Value and the planned budget.\r\nSV = BCWP - BCWS\r\n\r\n<li>Cost Variance is the difference between the Earned Value and the actual costs of the works.\r\nCV = BCWP - ACWP\r\n</ul>',433,20,0,'2008-03-21 17:03:35'),(604,65,'Game Turn Types','Games can be run as turns or rounds. Turns means that each player gets a turn\r\nand then the next player gets a turn. Rounds means that all the players get to\r\nenter orders and, when all the players have done so, the round is \"run\" and a\r\nnew round begins.\r\n\r\n<P>Games can be run daily or weekly -- that should be pretty obvious.\r\n\r\n<P>Game can be \"chained\" or \"unchained\". Unchained games will run at the allotted\r\ntime regardless of who has entered or not entered their orders. Chained games\r\nwill run either when the allotted time is up or earlier if a specific set of\r\nplayers have entered their orders (either a single player for games run as\r\nturns or all the player for games run as rounds). \r\n\r\n<P>So there are 8 possible game styles. Some of them may work better than others.\r\n\r\n<P>1) Daily chained turns -- each player does his turn, with the next player able\r\nto do his turn only when the first finishes or at the end of the day\r\n\r\n<P>2) Daily chained rounds -- all players enter orders when everyone finishes or\r\nat the end of the day, the round runs\r\n\r\n<P>3) Daily unchained turns -- each player does his turn and they are considered\r\ncomplete at the end of day whether or not they have entered a turn\r\n\r\n<P>4) Daily unchained rounds -- all players enter orders and the round is run at\r\nthe end of the day, ready or not\r\n\r\n<P>5) Weekly chained turns -- each player does a turn, with the next player able\r\nto do his turn only when the first finishes or at the end of the week  \r\n\r\n<P>6) Weekly chained rounds -- all the players enter orders with the round run\r\neither when they are all complete or at the end of the week.\r\n\r\n<P>7) Weekly unchained turns -- each player does his turn with the next player\r\nonly able to do his turn at the end of the week.\r\n\r\n<P>8) Weekly unchained rounds -- all players enter orders and the round is run at\r\nthe end of the week\r\n',593,10,0,'2008-03-12 05:28:08'),(569,65,'Database','The basic data types are Player, Universe (like Lord of the Rings\r\nversus Dune), Scenario (like Battle of Minas Tirith versus Battle of\r\nHelm\'s Deep), Game (each individual match of a given Scenario in\r\nprogress), Location (a specific area on the map), Route (a connection\r\nbetween Locations), Unit (like Sauron, the 1st Airborne, ICBM Factory,\r\nor British Parliament), Attack Type (like Particle Beam or Slashing\r\nWeapon), Defense Type (like Force Field or Elvish Armor), Mobility Type\r\n(like Legs or Treads), Terrain Type (like Stargate or Jungle or City).',0,500,0,'2008-03-12 04:06:52'),(570,65,'Introduction','The Ari Game Engine is a system for creating turn based games to be played by multiple players online.  There are aspects of playing multi-player games that are not actually part of the game system but rather in support of the broader agenda of playing such games. This document has two parts; the second deals with the game engine per se while the second deals with the site that supports it (and, presumably, other games). ',0,10,0,'2008-03-29 21:05:57'),(625,43,'Notes','This implies that the todo list should be\r\nsegmentable by both project and user. And we need to think about who can and\r\ncan\'t add tasks or projects to the list! In this method, all tasks are either\r\n0% or 100% complete. ',417,10,0,'2008-03-21 17:10:32'),(626,65,'Definitions','<P>We start with a list of definitions for the words used in this document. \r\n<dl>\r\n<dt>Game</dt><dd>In Ari Game Engine parlance it means an <i>instance</i> of a <i>scenario</i>. It may also mean an <i>instance</i> of a <i>game system</i> but this use is deprecated (replaced by the word <i>instance</i>). In most cases we\'ll use <i>instance</i> unless we\'re talking <em>only</em> about the Ari Game Engine.</dd>\r\n<dt>Game Models</dt><dd>In the <i>Ari Game Engine</i>, there are two <I>game models</i>: Adventure and Strategy. These are dealt with in more detail in the section on the subject. </dd>\r\n<dt>Instance</dt><dd>A specific running <i>game</i>. In Ari Game Engine parlance this is called an <i>game</i>. </dd>\r\n<dt>Location </dt><dd>A particular space on a map within a <i>scenario</i>.</dd>\r\n<dt>Members</dt><dd>People who have an account on our game site. They may or may not be playing one or more games. </dd>\r\n<dt>Non-members</dt><dd>Any <i>visitor</i> who is not a <i>member</I>. </dd>\r\n<dt>Players</dt><dd>People who are participating in a particular game.</dd>\r\n<dt>Scenario</dt><dd>A specific set of <i>locations</i> and terrain types (essentially, a specific map) and units within a universe.</dd>\r\n<dt>Universe </dt><dd>In the <i>Ari Game Engine</i> this is a set of rules that define how units interact with each other and with the world. </dd>\r\n<dt>Visitors</dt><dd>A generic term used to encompass anyone who comes to the site including both <i>members</i> and <i>non-members</i>. </dd>\r\n<dt>Game System</dt><dd>A generic term meaning \"a particular thing we can play on our site\" -- corresponding roughly to the Ari Game Engine term <i>scenario</i> (but without the implication that there is a broader <i>universe</i> into which the the thing fits). </dd>\r\n</dl>',0,12,0,'2008-03-30 16:17:09'),(617,65,'Formal Database Definition','<ul>\r\n<li>Game models Table \r\n<li>player table\r\n<li>universe table\r\n<li>scenario table\r\n<li>game table\r\n<li>location table\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>	name\r\n<li>	owner\r\n<li>	terrain\r\n<li>	?\r\n</ul>	\r\n<li>route table\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>	from location\r\n<li>	to location\r\n<li>	name\r\n<li>	length\r\n<li>	terrain \r\n<li>	width\r\n</ul>	\r\n<li>unit table\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>	name\r\n<li>	description\r\n<li>	image\r\n<li>	owner\r\n<li>	attack rating\r\n<li>	attack type\r\n<li>	defense rating\r\n<li>	defense type\r\n<li>	range\r\n<li>	mobility rating\r\n<li>	mobility type\r\n<li>	detection rating\r\n<li>	detection type\r\n<li>	stealth rating\r\n<li>	stealth type\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>attack type\r\n<li>defense type\r\n<li>mobility type\r\n<li>terrain type\r\n<li>unit type table \r\n<li>AttackDefense\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>	Universe\r\n<li>	AttackType\r\n<li>	DefenseType\r\n<li>	BaseAttrition\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Detection\r\n<li>Stealth\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>	Universe\r\n<li>	DetectionType\r\n<li>	StealthType\r\n<li>	BaseDetection\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>MobilityTerrain\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>	Universe\r\n<li>	MobilityType\r\n<li>	TerrainType\r\n<li>	BaseSpeed\r\n</ul>',569,10,0,'2008-03-12 05:30:17'),(592,65,'Game Site','<P>A distinction is made between the games and the site. The site allows users to register, log in, sign up for games, submit turns, find out their status, maintain high score tables, talk on forums and so forth. The \"site\" will take care of users and \"game systems\".\r\n<P>In all cases, the site formats information it sends to the game system in XML and the game system must send back information in XML format. In both cases there may be big blocks of text or even binary data (text encoded) embedded in the XML. These blocks are game system-specific text or data which the site passes from instance to player or from player to instance without interpretation -- this allows for custom UIs to be built.  The XML schema is pretty basic and simple and has both required fields that every game system must have (game number, turn number, etc) and some optional fields that game systems may ignore if they don\'t use those features. This allows game systems to have optional features which may or may not exist in a particular instance provided the game system has clearly defined defaults (for example, computer players, optional rules, advanced rules, etc).',0,15,0,'2008-03-30 16:24:25'),(593,65,'Game Engine','',0,200,0,'2008-03-12 03:29:28'),(616,65,'Processing','The engine runs in stages. After each stage a plugin runs that may modify virtually any aspect of the stage. \r\n\r\nThe sequence is:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Archive -- saves game state so we can return to this point if necessary\r\n<li>Turn Processing -- make sure all units have at least default orders\r\n<li>Turn Plugin -- modifies or creates orders for any of the units (useful for AI)\r\n<li>Movement Processing -- all units move\r\n<li>Movement Plugin -- modifies movement for any unit\r\n<li>Combat Processing -- all units that meet the combat requirement\r\n<li>Combat Plugin -- modifies combat result for any unit\r\n<li>Production Processing -- Creates new units \r\n<li>Production Plugin -- modifies production \r\n<li>Results Generator -- creates \"turn results\" for each player\r\n<li>Results Plugin -- modifies results\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n',593,130,0,'2008-03-12 05:28:08'),(596,65,'Overview','Visits (that is, a particular transaction between some visitor and the site) to a game site will be made for several reasons. Obviously some visits will be made to play games or to join games. But visitors might also come to get more information or to watch or to discuss the games. Whatever the reason, there needs to be a structure to support (and encourage) those visits. Visitiors',570,10,0,'2008-03-29 21:39:50'),(597,65,'Purpose of Document','The purpose of this document is to describe, in as much detail as necessary, the design, both technical and conceptual, of the Ari Game Website. ',570,20,0,'2008-03-12 03:36:39'),(598,65,'Revision History','<table border=\"1\">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <th>Revision</th><th>Date</th><th>Author</th><th>Description</th>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Initial Revision (0.1)</td><td> 3/11/08</td><td>Dave Menconi</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td>Revision 0.2</td><td> 3/29/08</td><td>Dave Menconi</td><td>First pass edits on the initial revision \r\n  </tr>\r\n\r\n</table>',570,30,0,'2008-03-29 21:39:50'),(599,65,'Other Non Game Elements','<li>Forums\r\n<li>High Score Tables\r\n<li>Rules Sections\r\n<li>Marketing Pages\r\n<li>Faction Pages\r\n',592,210,0,'2008-03-12 03:33:49'),(600,65,'The Rail','The players can look at their private information when they are logged in. But every game should have some public information that everyone can see by going to the \"Rail\" (poker term). This encourages non-players to get involved in the game. Maybe talk about it in the forums or study various strategies. Now players that may not get involved (because they never feel they know enough about the game) can learn enough to eventually play it and new players can actually know enough about the game to bring a reasonable amount of skill to play. \r\n\r\n',592,100,0,'2008-03-30 16:23:20'),(601,65,'Running Games','Games run between Midnight and 3 AM. Weekly games always run on Sunday night;\r\ndaily games run every night. Chained games may run at any time if the\r\nconditions are met. The scheduler may insert a random delay to try to prevent\r\nmultiple games from running at exactly the same minute.\r\n\r\n',592,80,0,'2008-03-30 16:23:20'),(602,65,'Starting A Game','You start a game by specifying a universe and scenario that you want to play. \r\nA unique instance (a copy) of the universe and scenario databases is created. A\r\nrecord for the game is created in the global \"Game\" database. It is in state\r\n\"starting\".\r\nPlayers may join; when the specified number of players are in place, the game\r\nstarts. ',592,60,0,'2008-03-30 16:23:20'),(603,65,'User Management','The site will provide user management including sign up, activation, login, lost password, password change, user preferences (for example, notification methods) and other user account functions.\r\n<P>Authentication is done by means of a cookie with a hased version of the date and time of the cookie, the user name and a secret string plus the username and date and time in clear text. When a page wishes to authenticate it hashes the secret string and the clear text datestamp and user name and compares it to the hash in the cookie; a match means the username is valid. \r\n<P>The data that we will track about a user will include:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>User Table\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>userid\r\n<li>username\r\n<li>password\r\n<li>real name\r\n<li>gender (m,f,unspec)\r\n<li>date of birth\r\n<li>minor (bool) if no data of birth, minor is assumed\r\n<li>activation code \r\n<li>type (inactive, active, banned, developer, admin)\r\n<li>email\r\n<li>textmsgno\r\n<li>phoneno\r\n<li>imaddress\r\n<li>improtocol\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Notification Table\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>userid\r\n<li>method (email,textmsg,phonecall,im)\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n',592,40,0,'2008-03-30 17:07:33'),(640,66,'Main Page','<P> There will be a main page for the whole system. The front page has a logo, then a list of links -- the site navigation stuff --\r\nthen it has a list of games with their logos. Each game has one or more of the\r\nfollowing notations: \"Now Accepting Players\", \"Games Now Running\" and \"Coming\r\nSoon\". The last will always be by itself but the other two are independent of\r\neach other. The logo and each of the notations is a link. The logo and \"Coming\r\nSoon\" go to a description of the game with a link to the rules and the game\r\nsign up. Games Now Running goes to a page that shows the running games and\r\ntheir status and has links to player and non-player game information (i.e.\r\npublic info and private info). Now Accepting Players takes you to the \"sign up\r\nfor this game\" link.\r\n<P>\r\nSite Navigation includes\r\n<li>Home (this main page)\r\n<li>Registration Page\r\n<li>Login Page\r\n<li>Logout Link\r\n<li>Lost Password Page\r\n<li>Links to the most popular Non-game elements (see below)\r\n<P>',0,30,0,'2008-04-29 06:30:29'),(641,66,'Player Management','Everyone who plays a game must be a registered user but it is free to register. Users may pick their own username and password and must give a valid email address. The player may opt to have information sent to his email address or may choose to visit the web site instead. \r\n\r\n<P>In order to play a game the player must both register as a user on the site and use his username to register for a game. The following is a detailed discussion of the components needed to meet these needs.\r\n',0,40,0,'2008-04-29 06:30:29'),(642,66,'Game Management','<P>We will need a system that does game management. This system will keep track of:\r\n    <LI> Which games are accepting new players\r\n    <LI> Which games are currently running\r\n    <LI> How often the running games are accepting input \r\n    <LI> Whether you need pay to play in the games\r\n    <LI> Which games are complete \r\n<P>The game specific page will list all this information for each game type.\r\n<P>The game management system will also need to allow games to start, manage turn input, manage the running of the turns and ending a game. It will also manage score tables customized to each game. \r\n\r\n',0,50,0,'2008-04-29 06:30:29'),(643,66,'Designing A Game','<P>The game designer has to write the instance requests and they need to be registered with the site as part of \"installation\". \r\n\r\n<P>The game must know it\'s own game type and each of it\'s game numbers. These\r\ntogether identify a specific game. \r\n<P>The game must also call the appropriate site functions at the appropriate times. The game also must be able to create and parse XML, although the site developer will probably be able to give the designer libraries that will do that for him/her. ',0,70,0,'2008-04-29 06:30:29'),(698,68,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-03 04:50:21'),(699,68,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-03 04:50:21'),(700,68,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-03 04:50:21'),(644,66,'Definitions','<P>We start with a list of definitions for the words used in this document. \r\n<dl>\r\n<dt>Bounce</dt><dd> An email that did not get to it\'s recipient.</dd>\r\n<dt>Game Models</dt><dd>In the <i>Ari Game Engine</i>, there are two <I>game models</i>: Adventure and Strategy. These are dealt with in more detail in the section on the subject. </dd>\r\n<dt>Game System</dt><dd>A generic term meaning \"a particular thing we can play on our site\" -- corresponding roughly to the Ari Game Engine term <i>scenario</i> (but without the implication that there is a broader <i>universe</i> into which the the thing fits). </dd>\r\n<dt>Game Type</dt><dd> The implementation of a specific game design.</dd>\r\n<dt>Game</dt><dd>In Ari Game Engine parlance it means an <i>instance</i> of a <i>scenario</i>. It may also mean an <i>instance</i> of a <i>game system</i> but this use is deprecated (replaced by the word <i>instance</i>). In most cases we\'ll use <i>instance</i> unless we\'re talking <em>only</em> about the Ari Game Engine.</dd>\r\n<dt>Instance</dt><dd>A specific running <i>game</i>. In Ari Game Engine parlance this is called an <i>game</i>. </dd>\r\n<dt>Location </dt><dd>A particular space on a map within a <i>scenario</i>.</dd>\r\n<dt>Members</dt><dd>People who have an account on our game site. They may or may not be playing one or more games. </dd>\r\n<dt>Non-members</dt><dd>Any <i>visitor</i> who is not a <i>member</I>. </dd>\r\n<dt>Player</dt><dd>People who are participating in a particular game.</dd>\r\n<dt>Scenario</dt><dd>A specific set of <i>locations</i> and terrain types (essentially, a specific map) and units within a universe.</dd>\r\n<dt>Universe </dt><dd>In the <i>Ari Game Engine</i> this is a set of rules that define how units interact with each other and with the world. </dd>\r\n<dt>Visitors</dt><dd>A generic term used to encompass anyone who comes to the site including both <i>members</i> and <i>non-members</i>. </dd>\r\n</dl>',0,20,0,'2008-04-29 06:36:45'),(670,66,'Shared Data','A core design principal is that both game models will use the same\r\ndata models and unit attributes, such that, in theory, an Adventure game\r\ncould be layered inside a Strategy game with matching data. For\r\ninstance, there could be a Middle Earth Strategy game where players move\r\narmies around fighting over territory, with a Middle Earth Adventure\r\ngame layered inside - parties in the Adventure game would have to worry\r\nabout the titanic battles and shifts in territory happening around them,\r\nand could even participate in those battles should they end up in the\r\nright place at the right time. At some point, we may be able to fuse\r\nboth models entirely, but we aren\'t going to let that possibility divert\r\nus from launching them separately.',682,5,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(627,65,'Instance Requests','<P>In the site are \"instances\" by which we mean a \"game\" (an instance of a specific scenario in the Ari game engine) or an instance of a game system. A game can be invoked in one of four ways.\r\n<P>1) Start Game\r\n<br>This invocation is passed an XML file with a list of players: user name, user number, game number, player pseudonym, perhaps some game system-specific parameters which are optional (which means they have perfectly valid defaults).The game system creates it\'s databases and so forth for that game. The game system puts out to standard output an XML file that contains the status of the command (success or failure), the game number, the turn number, perhaps some other game information, and, for each player, a block of text which that player will understand to be his starting position (that is, the first turn). The site then logs the game system specific data into a database, and sends the turn information to each player according to whatever method they have requested. Alternatively, the game system may use it\'s own user interface in which case the game system may send nothing, a simply notification of the turn starting (with appropriate links to, for example, a web based UI) or even a text version of the turn.\r\n<P>2) Parse Orders\r\n<br>A player may email his turn orders in some game systems. When a player sends in orders for a turn, the site invokes the game system and passes in the information for this turn/game/player (in XML) plus the text of the player\'s turn. The game system returns an XML file that has the results of the parsing (success or not), the player/turn/game information and a block of text that has information about problems with the turn. The site will send this to the player according to the player\'s preferences. The game system is responsible for storing the latest turn information for each player in whatever way it uses. The site will not send it again (unless the player sends another turn). Obviously, if the game system uses some other turn entry UI the site will not be involved.\r\n<P>3) Run Turn\r\n<br>The site invokes the run turn command and passes an XML file with the game number (I think that\'s all that is required). The game system runs and spews out an XML file with game system status information, information for each player and, optionally, information for the public.\r\n<P>The site doesn\'t interpret the information but displays the game system specific text in the appropriate ways (showing the public info and sending the player information to the correct players).\r\n<P>If the game is over, this information is noted along with final standings and other information. The game should execute the \"game end\" code and clean up after itself as well as archive any information that should be saved for posterity.\r\n<P>4) End Game\r\n<br>If, for some reason, the site needs to terminate a game, it sends the end game command and the game system kills itself off and terminates, cleaning up all its files, databases, cron tasks and so forth. The game system will spew back the final status of the game system, standings and so forth, if any. It is assumed that the game history is sent back as an XML file to be archived by the site; the game system itself should keep nothing.\r\n',592,15,0,'2008-03-30 16:27:17'),(628,65,'Site Requests','<P>The site can be invoked by a game system -- a \"callback\" if you will -- in  three ways.\r\n<P>1) Authentication Request\r\n<br>The game system may ask the site whether a particular username/password is valid. Inherent in this request is the question \"is this user still allowed\". The game system may use it\'s own authentication system but it <em>must</em> request user authentication from the site before accepting orders from a player or the site has no way to suspend players for bad behavior. \r\n<p>2) Turn Complete\r\n<br>The game system uses this to tell the site that a turn has been completed. This is necessary because some game systems may have very sophisticated turn entry systems that are not directly supported by the site and the site needs to know that it needs to \"start the clock\" on the next turn.\r\n<P>3) Game Over\r\n<br>The game system will use this call to inform the site that the game has ended and to let the site know that it can stop timing turns and accepting email orders. The game system also uses this call to report \"game result\" information.\r\n<br>For example, the first line might have the names of the statistics and the kind of value it is. For example, in the following line, the game system would be asserting that certain values are numbers and should be averaged (\"avg\") or summed (\"sum\") while other fields are text and should simply be counted by instance (i.e. \"Dave was a Warlord x times\").\r\n<br>Score:avg,Cash:avg,Ships:avg,Planets:avg,People:avg,Type:count,Wins:sum\r\n<br>And subsequent lines say\r\n<br>Dave,200000,10000,20,50,2000,Warlord,1\r\n<br>Fred,180000, 9000,25,40,1600,Wizard,0\r\n<br>Ann, 150000,12000,13,25,1000,Senator,0\r\n<br><em>and so forth</em>\r\n<P>Note that this example shows a comma delimited format for readability but the actual format will be sell-defining XML which will be much more cabable.\r\n<P>Using this data the game will keep statistics on things such as how many times a player won each game, average score, average case, average ships and so forth. Note that this information is all Scenario/Game System specific and the site has no idea what any of this stuff means. It just tracks it according to the data given, which is defined by the game system. The site will have a table in which it will create a bunch of key/value pairs for each player based on the \"game result\" information it got from the game. Then it will generate \"high score\" (or more correctly, \"game statistic\") pages based on counts (averages, sums, etc) of the various data it has for that game.',592,30,0,'2008-03-30 16:36:41'),(645,66,'Site Database Design','<P>\r\ncreate table gametype -- this is a list of the types of games that we have<BR>\r\n gametypeid int auto_increment primary key,<BR>\r\n gametypename tinytext,<BR>\r\n gametypeurl tinytext,<BR>\r\n gamets timestamp,<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\ncreate table user -- list of people who are registered on the site<BR>\r\n userid int auto_increment primary key,<BR>\r\n username tinytext,<BR>\r\n realname tinytext,<BR>\r\n emailaddress tinytext,<BR>\r\n password tinytext,<BR>\r\n dateofbirth date,<BR>\r\n minor tinyint,  #if no dateofbirth we assume minor<br>\r\n gender enum(\'m\',\'f\',\'unspec\'),<br>\r\n textmsgno tinytext,<br>\r\n phoneno tinytext,<br>\r\n imaddress tinytext,<br>\r\n improtocol tinytext,<br>\r\n signupdate date,<BR>\r\n usertype enum (inactive, active, banned, developer, tester, admin), <br>\r\n temppassword tinytext,<BR>\r\n temppwexpire datetime,<BR>\r\n userts timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table notification  <br>,\r\n notificationid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n userid int,<br>\r\n method (\'email\',\'textmsg\',\'phonecall\',\'im\'),<br>\r\ncreate table game # actual games, an instance of the game type<BR>\r\n gameid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n gametypeno int,<BR>\r\n status enum (starting,running,paused,finished),<BR>\r\n turninterval int, <br>\r\n gamets timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table player -- link table between users and games<BR>\r\n playerid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n userno int,<BR>\r\n gameno int,<BR>\r\n playerts timestamp,<BR>\r\n gameplayernum int<BR>\r\n playerts timestamp,<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\ncreate table policy -- site policies<BR>\r\n policyid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n policyname tinytext ,<BR>\r\n policydesc tinytext ,<BR>\r\n policyvalue tinytext ,<BR>\r\n adminname tinytext ,<BR>\r\n policyts timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table language -- languages that are supported<BR>\r\n languageid int auto_increment <BR>\r\n languagename tinytext <BR>\r\n<BR>\r\ncreate table phrase -- phrases that are used on the site<BR>\r\n phraseid int auto_increment primary,<BR>\r\n phrasename tinytext,<BR>\r\n phrase tinytext,<BR>\r\n languageno int,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table sitelog -- logs page <BR>\r\n sitelogid int auto_increment primary, <BR>\r\n referer tinytext,<BR>\r\n remote_addr tinytext,<BR>\r\n http_user_agent tinytext,<BR>\r\n username tinytext,<BR>\r\n request_uri tinytext,<BR>\r\n params text,<BR>\r\n logts timestamp,<BR>\r\n <BR>\r\ncreate table dblog -- logs changes to the database itself<BR>\r\n dblogid int auto_increment primary, <BR>\r\n sqlcommand tinytext,<BR>\r\n dblogts timestamp,<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n\r\ncreate table emaillog -- logs emails sent<br>\r\n emaillogid int auto_increment primary, <BR>\r\n userno int,<br>\r\n emailadr tinytext,<br>\r\n status enum (success,failure),<br>\r\n emaillogts timestamp,<br>\r\n<br>\r\n ',0,80,0,'2008-04-29 06:30:29'),(720,60,'move people around and fix portion after portion','',0,90,0,'2008-04-03 06:55:54'),(721,60,'lots of opposition to be over come',' - civil rights groups oppose buying building \r\n - drug addicts \r\n - other local businesses (can\'t get cheap workers), unions (workers in the building are not union)\r\n - teacher\'s association (odd schooling)\r\n - civil rights groups complain that serendipity corp is exploiting people\r\n - enemies ask questions about finance',0,110,0,'2008-04-03 06:55:54'),(722,60,'Train workers to do construction','',0,120,0,'2008-04-03 06:55:54'),(723,60,'vocational training','',0,130,0,'2008-04-03 06:55:54'),(724,60,'set up schools (grade and high)','Schools are weird -- the teachers don\'t teach so much as moderate; kids teach each other; allowed to pick subjects they think are relevant\r\nin the older grades at first there is a greater control of what they are doing; in the younger grades they are indoctrinated into thinking that mathematics are very important. ',0,140,0,'2008-04-03 06:55:54'),(725,60,' set up side businesses to support residents (day care, cleaning, in home care, food delivery, etc)','',0,150,0,'2008-04-03 06:55:54'),(726,60,'gradually things seem to work','',0,180,0,'2008-04-03 06:56:38'),(649,67,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-03-30 19:11:48'),(650,67,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-03-30 19:11:48'),(651,67,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-03-30 19:11:48'),(652,67,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-03-30 19:11:48'),(653,67,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-03-30 19:11:48'),(654,67,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-03-30 19:11:48'),(655,66,'User Database','The user table has the user informaiton in it. Access to this must be restricted. The fields of this table are in the Database Design section.',641,10,0,'2008-03-31 04:12:34'),(718,60,'kick out addicts','',0,80,0,'2008-04-03 06:47:24'),(719,60,' rework condemned portion','',0,100,0,'2008-04-03 06:55:54'),(656,66,'User Module','The user module manages the user database. It allows all other routines unrestricted access to the user information except that it never gives out the user password. Instead, it authenticates the user by taking a username and password and returning true or false. \r\n\r\n    <LI> add user\r\n    <LI> get user info (gets everything except password)\r\n    <LI> does user exist? (returns boolean)\r\n    <LI> is this user/password valid? (returns boolean) ',641,20,0,'2008-03-31 00:14:08'),(657,66,'New User Registration','To register we have a simple form in which the user enters information which is then used to create a new user entry in the database. TIn addition making sure the user name is unique and that the password and validation password match, we validate by sending the user a a validation link via his email address. The following is a list of fields in the form; other fields in the database are initialized algorithmically.\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<LI>username\r\n<LI>real name\r\n<LI>password\r\n<LI>verify password\r\n<LI>email address\r\n<LI>birthdate\r\n<LI>\r\n</ul>\r\n<P>This information is processed & verified and then added to the database. The username must be unique, the password and verify password must match, the email address must be formatted correctly, the birth date must be a valid date. After the user is validated, he is marked active. ',641,40,0,'2008-04-07 01:34:59'),(658,66,'Lost Password','<P>The user enters a username and we generate and send a temporary password to his email address. The temporary password and the expiry are stored in the user table. The login routine must respect both the temp password and the expiry. The temporary password is never actually removed, it just expires. ',641,50,0,'2008-03-31 00:14:08'),(659,66,'Account Management','The Account management page allows the user to examine and change his/her information. The page is protected by a cookie containing the user. Elements should include (italic items can be changed):\r\n\r\n    <LI> <i>Real Name</i>\r\n    <LI> Username\r\n    <LI> <i>Password</i>    \r\n    <LI> <i>Verify Password</i>\r\n    <LI> <i>Email Address</i>\r\n    <LI> <i>Notification Information (various addresses and options)</i>\r\n    <LI> List of Games Registered\r\n    <LI> Report of bounces in the last month \r\n<P>\r\nThe player should not be able to change his/her username here (or, possibly anywhere).   ',641,60,0,'2008-04-07 01:34:59'),(660,66,'User Analysis Utility','We need a program that will examine the user table to determine which, if any,  users should be deleted as well as track the user demographics in general. This is a web page that shows a lists of people that fit the following attributes:\r\n\r\n  <Ul>\r\n<li> New Users (starting date no more than one month in the past) \r\n    <li> Inactive Users (users who are not in any games)\r\n    <li> Long time Inactive users (users who have not sent in a turn for 2 months or more)\r\n    <li> Bad Email users (users who\'s last bounce is more recent than their last received turn)\r\n    <li> Minors\r\n    <li> Users in LOTS of games\r\n    <li> User who have quit a lot of game\r\n</ul>\r\n<P>The administrator(s) can then choose to make the users inactive or banned otherwise change their status. \r\n<P>There should be an other page with <em>all</em> the players (perhaps sorted in some clever way if there are a lot) in which the administrators can make other changes (reset passwords, change users to developers, etc).',641,70,0,'2008-04-07 01:34:59'),(717,60,'recruit people from within the building, ','',0,70,0,'2008-04-03 06:46:46'),(740,71,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:37'),(741,71,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:37'),(742,71,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:37'),(743,71,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:37'),(744,71,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:37'),(745,71,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:37'),(746,72,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:41'),(747,72,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:41'),(748,72,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:41'),(749,72,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:41'),(750,72,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:41'),(751,72,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-10 01:41:41'),(752,73,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-10 02:03:12'),(753,73,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-10 02:03:12'),(754,73,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-10 02:03:12'),(755,73,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-10 02:03:12'),(756,73,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-10 02:03:12'),(757,73,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-10 02:03:12'),(758,74,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-10 02:04:56'),(759,74,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-10 02:04:56'),(760,74,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-10 02:04:56'),(761,74,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-10 02:04:56'),(762,74,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-10 02:04:56'),(763,74,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-10 02:04:56'),(764,75,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-12 02:36:32'),(765,75,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-12 02:36:32'),(766,75,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-12 02:36:32'),(767,75,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-12 02:36:32'),(768,75,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-12 02:36:32'),(769,75,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-12 02:36:32'),(770,66,'Design Goals','There are, with this design as with all designs, some guiding principles or goals. They are:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>To bring as many people to the site as possible as often as possible (the assumption being that traffic -> revenue), especially:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>To enter their turn\r\n<li>To see how the turn is progressing (depending on the game)\r\n<li>To follow other games\r\n<li>To discuss games\r\n<li>To learn about games on the site\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>To have a lot of different games on the site (on the theory that the only way to ensure good games is to have a lot of games -- the basis of the modern games industry). This would be facilitated by:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Facilitating, as much as possible, the development of new games\r\n<li>Allowing guest designers to create games by having a standard interface for game development\r\n<li>Creating a common \"standard\" way that players will find, explore, learn and play a wide variety of games\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Note that the Game Engine is one way to facilitate game development. The other way outlined in this document is to create a wrapper around games that allows the site to control functions such as starting, ending, etc. In this way, the games don\'t have to actually be integral to the site but can be plugged in and removed at will. ',665,30,0,'2008-04-29 22:04:03'),(713,61,'builder asks permission from hamas to help community; hamas honcho has no choice','',0,70,0,'2008-04-03 06:38:53'),(714,61,'builder dies','',0,80,0,'2008-04-03 06:38:53'),(715,61,'#2 findsout that #3 has been helping him','',0,90,0,'2008-04-03 06:38:53'),(716,61,'hamas tries to stop builder','',0,100,0,'2008-04-03 06:38:53'),(665,66,'Introduction','The Ari Game site is a multi-player online game site, primarily for the play of the turn style of games. It is intended to be a \"one stop\" location for multi-player online games. There are aspects of playing multi-player games that are not actually part of the game system but rather in support of the broader agenda of playing such games which are included in the site. \r\n<P>The Ari Game Engine is a system for creating turn based games to be played by multiple players online.  \r\n<P>This document has two parts; the second deals with the game engine per se while the first deals with the site that supports it (and, presumably, other games). ',0,12,0,'2008-04-29 22:33:41'),(669,66,'Game Models','There are two key game models - Strategy and Adventure. Strategy\r\ncovers all games with area movement, where players fight for control of\r\nterritories, raising and deploying leaders, troops, and production\r\nfacilities. Adventure covers all games with area movement, where players\r\nroam between territories, collecting and recruiting leaders, troops, and\r\nequipment. For user interface reasons more than anything else, both\r\nmodels currently assume the fastest rate of strategic movement is one\r\nterritory per turn - so this works very well for armies on the march,\r\nspaceships jumping from system to system, and even short range aircraft\r\nthat are bound to nearby basing facilities, but doesn\'t really for\r\nscenarios where some aircraft or fleets are supposed to have global\r\nreach within a turn.',682,20,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(667,66,'Purpose of Document','The purpose of this document is to describe, in as much detail as necessary, the design, both technical and conceptual, of the Ari Game Website. The goal is to provide enough detail to allow a developer to write the site without creating so much detail that the developer ',665,20,0,'2008-04-29 22:04:03'),(668,66,'Revision History','<table border=\"1\">\r\n<tr><th>Revision</th><th>Date</th><th>Author</th><th>Description</th></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Initial Revision (0.1)</td><td> 3/11/08</td><td>Dave Menconi</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Revision 0.2</td><td> 3/29/08</td><td>Dave Menconi</td><td>First pass edits on the initial revision</tr>\r\n<tr><td>Revision 0.3</td><td> 3/30/08</td><td>Dave Menconi</td><td>Hugely extended site design</tr>\r\n<tr><td>Revision 0.4</td><td> 4/6/08</td><td>Dave Menconi</td><td>Tweaks and Rewrites</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n',665,10,0,'2008-04-29 22:04:03'),(671,66,'Locations','Each Location has a Name, Owner ID, and Terrain ID.',682,40,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(672,66,'Routes','Locations are connected via Routes. There can be multiple Routes\r\nbetween any two Locations. Each Route has a Name, Length, and Terrain\r\nID. I\'m leaning towards having a Width as well - consider the pass at\r\nThermopylae versus the steppes between Russia and Ukraine, or for that\r\nmatter, all the different types of tunnels in an underground war between\r\norcs and dwarves.',682,50,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(673,66,'Units','Units have a Name, Owner ID, Attack Rating, Attack Type ID, Defense\r\nRating, Defense Type ID, Range, Mobility Rating, Mobility Type ID,\r\nDetection Rating, Detection Type ID, Stealth Rating, and Stealth Type ID.',682,60,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(674,66,'Attack & Defense','Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Attack Type IDs to\r\nDefense Type IDs to yield a base fatality rate, which is then multiplied\r\nby the attacker\'s Attack Rating and divided by the Defender\'s Defense\r\nRating to determine the chance of Destroying or Disrupting a target unit\r\nin an attack.',682,70,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(675,66,'Detection & Stealth','Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Detection Type IDs to\r\nStealth Type IDs, to yield a base detection rate, which is then\r\nmultiplied by the detector\'s Detection Rating and divided by the\r\ntarget\'s Stealth Rating to determine the chance of Detecting the target\r\nunit.',682,80,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(676,66,'Terrain & Mobility','Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Mobility Type ID with\r\nTerrain Type ID to yield a base speed, which is then multiplied by the\r\nunit\'s Mobility Rating and divided by the Length of a Route to determine\r\nthe chance of that unit crossing that route in one turn. In combat, a\r\nsimilar computation is done to determine what kind of mobility each unit\r\nhas in that combat situation.',682,90,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(677,66,'Production','The production system consists of 3 parts. \r\n<P>First, there is a collection of units which might be produced by each player.\r\nTo use a card analogy, this might be called a \"deck\".\r\n<P>Second, there is a pool of units which might be produced in the near future. To\r\nuse a card analogy, this might be called a \"hand\".\r\n<P>Third, there is a set of rules which determine, for each card in the deck,\r\nunder which circumstances it might be deployed. \r\n\r\n<P>All three of these elements may be shared among the player and all three may be\r\nknown or hidden to players to whom they do not apply. \r\n\r\n<P>The third element is of the largest interest because it\'s the most complicated\r\nand the difficult to pull off (not only in production but probably in the whole\r\ngame).\r\n\r\n<P>This element requires two sub-elements. First, a way to describe a situation in\r\nthe game and, second, a location where a unit might be deployed.\r\n\r\n<P>The second sub-element is somewhat easier to create but it should still be\r\npossible to define a location in very flexible terms. That is, it\'s not enough\r\nto say \"in Eqypt\" or \"in New York\" or \"in area 2345\". You have to also be able\r\nto say \"within x areas of area 2345\" or within x areas of this unit or this\r\ntype of unit or even \"within x areas of a city which has these attributes\".\r\n\r\n<P>The first sub-element is even more complicated as it defines not just a\r\nlocation but a condition in the game. To be fully open-ended it needs to allow\r\nany condition or combinations of conditions that might exist in the game to be\r\ndefined. \r\n\r\n<P>These requirements suggest nothing less than a scripting language. The\r\nscripting language does not need to DO anything but it does need to be able to\r\nevaluate boolean expressions involving pretty much every variable that makes up\r\na game. \r\n\r\n<P>It\'s possible to write a custom scripting language, to define that scripting\r\nlanguage in terms of it\'s syntax and semantics, to parse that scripting\r\nlanguage (giving appropriate errors anywhere that there is an error), to\r\nconvert that parsed information into the semantic information, to evaluate that\r\ninformation and come up with a list of legal areas on the one hand or a boolean\r\nvalue on the other. \r\n\r\n<P>Of course it\'s possible to write a scripting language -- thousands of people\r\nhave done it. A few of those thousands have actually survived. However, as both\r\nthe victim and author of more than a few of those scripting languages, I am very\r\nmuch in favor of using something that already exists.\r\n\r\n<P>In this case, since the whole thing revolves around defining data that, after\r\nyou parse it and evaluate it, you need to look up in the data, I think using\r\nthe SQL syntax is probably the best thing to do. You limit it to just a few\r\nkeyword and then you basically hand it to the SQL parser and return whatever\r\nerror it returns. \r\n\r\n<P>This implies that we have a well defined and published database schema and that\r\nchanging the schema means breaking existing games. But at some point you have to\r\ndefine the variables that any scripting language can access and changing those\r\nvariables will break games in any case. \r\n\r\n<P>The basic syntax of SQL is variablename=\'constant\' as well as\r\nvariablename=variablename. Wildcarding syntax looks like variablename like\r\n\'%constant%\' where % is the wildcard. Parentheses and the \"AND\" and \"OR\"\r\nkeywords are supported. \r\n\r\n<P>We would have to make sure that all words not on a relatively short list are\r\nremoved (we don\'t want people our game developers hacking our SQL databases).\r\n\r\n<P>We also may want to extend the syntax with keywords like \"exists\" and \"distance\r\nfrom\". \r\n\r\n<P>The key to this system is to construct a framework in which all the things that\r\nwe want to examine are combined (from their various tables in the database) into\r\none view and then allow the developer to ask specific questions about that view.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>Every Universe has a sparse table comparing Mobility Type ID with\r\nTerrain Type ID to yield a base speed, which is then multiplied by the\r\nunit\'s Mobility Rating and divided by the Length of a Route to determine\r\nthe chance of that unit crossing that route in one turn. In combat, a\r\nsimilar computation is done to determine what kind of mobility each unit\r\nhas in that combat situation.',682,100,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(678,66,'Scenario','<P>Once there is a universe, one may create a scenario in that universe. \r\n<P>You must specify (oy vey):\r\n<li>A \"map\" (that is, a collection of locations and routes plus some kind of\r\ngraphic representation of same)\r\n<li>A unit set (a complete list of all the possible unit, their names, flavor text,\r\nflavor graphics, etc and their attributes)\r\n<li>A unit order of battle (where and under what circumstances these units become\r\navailable during the course of the scenario) This order of battle is used by\r\nthe production system to allow units to come into being. \r\n<li>Number of players\r\n<li>AI players? \r\n<li>End conditions\r\n<li>victory conditions\r\n<li>high score table information (that is, I finished first in the game; what do I get?)\r\n',682,110,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(679,66,'Universe','One must create a universe first, name it and so forth. Every universe must\r\nhave \r\n<li>attack types\r\n<li>Defense types\r\n<li>terrain types\r\n<li>mobility types\r\n<li>detection types\r\n<li>stealth types\r\n<li>tables that compare each of these types together. \r\n<P>There is also a collection of flavor information associated with a universe.',682,120,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(680,66,'Game Turn Types','Games can be run as turns or rounds. Turns means that each player gets a turn\r\nand then the next player gets a turn. Rounds means that all the players get to\r\nenter orders and, when all the players have done so, the round is \"run\" and a\r\nnew round begins.\r\n\r\n<P>Games can be run daily or weekly -- that should be pretty obvious.\r\n\r\n<P>Game can be \"chained\" or \"unchained\". Unchained games will run at the allotted\r\ntime regardless of who has entered or not entered their orders. Chained games\r\nwill run either when the allotted time is up or earlier if a specific set of\r\nplayers have entered their orders (either a single player for games run as\r\nturns or all the player for games run as rounds). \r\n\r\n<P>So there are 8 possible game styles. Some of them may work better than others.\r\n\r\n<P>1) Daily chained turns -- each player does his turn, with the next player able\r\nto do his turn only when the first finishes or at the end of the day\r\n\r\n<P>2) Daily chained rounds -- all players enter orders when everyone finishes or\r\nat the end of the day, the round runs\r\n\r\n<P>3) Daily unchained turns -- each player does his turn and they are considered\r\ncomplete at the end of day whether or not they have entered a turn\r\n\r\n<P>4) Daily unchained rounds -- all players enter orders and the round is run at\r\nthe end of the day, ready or not\r\n\r\n<P>5) Weekly chained turns -- each player does a turn, with the next player able\r\nto do his turn only when the first finishes or at the end of the week  \r\n\r\n<P>6) Weekly chained rounds -- all the players enter orders with the round run\r\neither when they are all complete or at the end of the week.\r\n\r\n<P>7) Weekly unchained turns -- each player does his turn with the next player\r\nonly able to do his turn at the end of the week.\r\n\r\n<P>8) Weekly unchained rounds -- all players enter orders and the round is run at\r\nthe end of the week\r\n',682,10,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(681,66,'Processing','The engine runs in stages. After each stage a plugin runs that may modify virtually any aspect of the stage. \r\n\r\nThe sequence is:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Archive -- saves game state so we can return to this point if necessary\r\n<li>Turn Processing -- make sure all units have at least default orders\r\n<li>Turn Plugin -- modifies or creates orders for any of the units (useful for AI)\r\n<li>Movement Processing -- all units move\r\n<li>Movement Plugin -- modifies movement for any unit\r\n<li>Combat Processing -- all units that meet the combat requirement\r\n<li>Combat Plugin -- modifies combat result for any unit\r\n<li>Production Processing -- Creates new units \r\n<li>Production Plugin -- modifies production \r\n<li>Results Generator -- creates \"turn results\" for each player\r\n<li>Results Plugin -- modifies results\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n',682,130,0,'2008-03-31 02:43:31'),(682,66,'The Ari Game Engine','The site is designed to support a variety of game systems. By far the most sophisticated that we have considered is the Ari Game Engine. ',0,90,0,'2008-04-29 06:30:29'),(694,66,'Rules Section','Every game will need to lay out it\'s rules somewhere and this is the place for that. Most likely the \"rules section\" will just be a set of links to the rules, where ever they happen to be. ',690,80,0,'2008-03-31 03:31:30'),(695,66,'Marketing Pages','Every game will have a page or set of pages that will be intended to enhance interest in the game and, hopefully, cause people to play it. ',690,100,0,'2008-03-31 03:31:30'),(696,66,'Faction Pages','Some open ended games develop factions -- that is, the players organize factions which they use to enhance their enjoyment and, presumably, their position in the game. \r\n<P>If we allow people to create sort of private clubhouses for their factions on our site, we can use them to enhance site visits. \r\n<P>Some facility will have to be created to allow users to create spaces and manage who can see them. There are a variety of complexity associated with this but it\'s well worth it because it means that players will both visit and stay on our site more. ',690,120,0,'2008-03-31 03:31:30'),(701,68,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-03 04:50:21'),(702,68,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-03 04:50:21'),(703,68,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-03 04:50:21'),(704,69,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-03 04:51:27'),(705,69,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-03 04:51:27'),(706,69,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-03 04:51:27'),(707,69,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-03 04:51:27'),(708,69,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-03 04:51:27'),(709,69,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-03 04:51:27'),(710,61,'Builder','This is our main character. He\'s a master builder and extremely successful in the US. In addition to building things he has been involved for many years in the financing of properties; lots of connections and considerable good will. Maybe builder should be a woman.',535,10,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(711,61,'Builder\'s #2','This is a Palestinian who was involved in the construction company before builder took over the company. He is the right hand man of the builder.',535,20,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(712,61,'Builder\'s #3','This person has been with builder almost since he started. Loyalty is his middle name and he doesn\'t even mind that #2 superseded him. He has a good relationship with #2',535,30,0,'2008-04-03 06:31:26'),(688,66,'Instance Requests','<P>In the site are \"instances\" by which we mean a \"game\" (an instance of a specific scenario in the Ari game engine) or an instance of a game system. A game can be invoked (that is, the game code is run) in one of four ways by the site.\r\n<P>1) Start Game\r\n<br>This invocation is passed an XML file with a list of players: user name, user number, game number, player pseudonym, perhaps some game system-specific parameters which are optional (which means they have perfectly valid defaults).          The game system creates it\'s databases and so forth for that game. The game system puts out to standard output an XML file that contains the status of the command (success or failure), the game number, the turn number, perhaps some other game information, and, for each player, a block of text which that player will understand to be his starting position (that is, the first turn). The site then logs the game system specific data into a database, and sends the turn information to each player according to whatever method they have requested. Alternatively, the game system may use it\'s own user interface in which case the game system may send nothing, a simply notification of the turn starting (with appropriate links to, for example, a web based UI) or even a text version of the turn.\r\n<P>2) Parse Orders\r\n<br>A player may email his turn orders in some game systems. When a player sends in orders for a turn, the site invokes the game system and passes in the information for this turn/game/player (in XML) plus the text of the player\'s turn. The game system returns an XML file that has the results of the parsing (success or not), the player/turn/game information and a block of text that has information about problems with the turn. The site will send this to the player according to the player\'s preferences. The game system is responsible for storing the latest turn information for each player in whatever way it uses. The site will not send it again (unless the player sends another turn). Obviously, if the game system uses some other turn entry UI the site will not be involved.\r\n<P>3) Run Turn\r\n<br>The site invokes the run turn command and passes an XML file with the game number (I think that\'s all that is required). The game system runs and spews out an XML file with game system status information, information for each player and, optionally, information for the public.\r\n<br>The site doesn\'t interpret the information but displays the game system specific text in the appropriate ways (showing the public info and sending the player information to the correct players).\r\n<br>If the game is over, this information is noted along with final standings and other information. The game should execute the \"game end\" code and clean up after itself as well as archive any information that should be saved for posterity.\r\n<P>4) End Game\r\n<br>If, for some reason, the site needs to terminate a game, it sends the end game command and the game system kills itself off and terminates, cleaning up all its files, databases, cron tasks and so forth. The game system will spew back the final status of the game system, standings and so forth, if any. It is assumed that the game history is sent back as an XML file to be archived by the site; the game system itself should keep nothing.\r\n',642,10,0,'2008-04-29 18:27:18'),(689,66,'Site Requests','<P>The site can be invoked by a game system -- a \"callback\" if you will -- in  three ways.\r\n<P>1) Authentication Request\r\n<br>The game system may ask the site whether a particular username/password is valid. Inherent in this request is the question \"is this user still allowed\". The game system may use it\'s own authentication system but it <em>must</em> request user authentication from the site before accepting orders from a player or the site has no way to suspend players for bad behavior. \r\n<p>2) Turn Complete\r\n<br>The game system uses this to tell the site that a turn has been completed. This is necessary because some game systems may have very sophisticated turn entry systems that are not directly supported by the site and the site needs to know that it needs to \"start the clock\" on the next turn.\r\n<P>3) Game Over\r\n<br>The game system will use this call to inform the site that the game has ended and to let the site know that it can stop timing turns and accepting email orders. The game system also uses this call to report \"game result\" information.\r\n<br>For example, the first line might have the names of the statistics and the kind of value it is. For example, in the following line, the game system would be asserting that certain values are numbers and should be averaged (\"avg\") or summed (\"sum\") while other fields are text and should simply be counted by instance (i.e. \"Dave was a Warlord x times\").\r\n<br>Score:avg,Cash:avg,Ships:avg,Planets:avg,People:avg,Type:count,Wins:sum\r\n<br>And subsequent lines say\r\n<br>Dave,200000,10000,20,50,2000,Warlord,1\r\n<br>Fred,180000, 9000,25,40,1600,Wizard,0\r\n<br>Ann, 150000,12000,13,25,1000,Senator,0\r\n<br><em>and so forth</em>\r\n<P>Note that this example shows a comma delimited format for readability but the actual format will be sell-defining XML which will be much more cabable.\r\n<P>Using this data the game will keep statistics on things such as how many times a player won each game, average score, average case, average ships and so forth. Note that this information is all Scenario/Game System specific and the site has no idea what any of this stuff means. It just tracks it according to the data given, which is defined by the game system. The site will have a table in which it will create a bunch of key/value pairs for each player based on the \"game result\" information it got from the game. Then it will generate \"high score\" (or more correctly, \"game statistic\") pages based on counts (averages, sums, etc) of the various data it has for that game.',642,20,0,'2008-04-29 18:27:18'),(690,66,'Non-Game Elements','There will be various other facilities on the site that are not games but are <em>about</em> games or support games in some way. The goal in all cases is certainly to enhance the fun but more to the point it is to attract more <em>visits</em>.\r\n<P>The non-game elements will also be advertising spaces -- arguably very valuable spaces since the players will only go to the game once per turn but may go to the non-game elements several time plus non players will find these elements fun so it greatly broadens the audience. ',0,60,0,'2008-04-29 06:30:29'),(691,66,'Forums','Player love to talk about games almost as much as they like to play them (perhaps more). The site will contain a threaded message board (of a now familiar sort) that will allow members to post messages and all visitors to read them. \r\n<P>The actual topics will be created as needed but we will create one for the site as a whole and one for each game system and universe as a way of getting things started. ',690,40,0,'2008-03-31 03:31:30'),(692,66,'The Rail','The players can look at their private information when they are logged in. But every game should have some public information that everyone can see by going to the \"Rail\". This encourages non-players to get involved in the game and maybe talk about it in the forums or study various strategies. \r\n<P>Now players that may not get involved (because they never feel they know enough about the game) can learn enough to eventually play it and new players can actually know enough about the game to bring a reasonable amount of skill to play. \r\n<P>And, of course, the Rail will generate \r\n',690,20,0,'2008-03-31 03:31:30'),(693,66,'Game Statistics','Every game system will be encouraged to send statistics about games to the game site. The game site will collect these statistics into pages that are organized in various ways. Added to this, the site will collect and display generic statistics such as \"most games played\", \"most game lost\" and so forth. ',690,60,0,'2008-03-31 03:31:30'),(697,66,'Donation Page','What can it hurt? If you like our games, give us some money. If you give a lot we do something nice for you. \r\n<P>This could be another element in the statistics page: who is a \"Silver Sponsor\" and who is a \"Golden Sponsor\".',690,130,0,'2008-03-31 03:55:03'),(734,70,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-10 01:40:07'),(735,70,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-10 01:40:07'),(736,70,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-10 01:40:07'),(737,70,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-10 01:40:07'),(738,70,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-10 01:40:07'),(739,70,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-10 01:40:07'),(727,60,'set up college','college is also one of the wackiest in the world. It has the best physics department but it allows anyone who is smart enough to join and it does pretty much whatever it takes to bring in people from the building',0,190,0,'2008-04-03 06:58:05'),(728,60,'skip ahead 20 years','now everyone who is graduating from the college has been through the grade and high schools; the graduates begin to take over the schools and they understand the concepts better so a real culture begins to develop',0,200,0,'2008-04-03 06:59:59'),(729,60,'buy a second and third building',NULL,0,210,0,'2008-04-03 07:00:17'),(730,60,'show that serendipity is making money',NULL,0,220,0,'2008-04-03 07:00:35'),(731,60,'Skip ahead 20 MORE years',NULL,0,230,0,'2008-04-03 07:00:56'),(732,60,'explore the physics research -- crazy stuff',NULL,0,240,0,'2008-04-03 07:03:17'),(733,60,'the colege begins to produce viable technology',NULL,0,250,0,'2008-04-03 07:03:47'),(771,76,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-13 23:28:20'),(772,76,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-13 23:28:20'),(773,76,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-13 23:28:20'),(774,76,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-13 23:28:20'),(775,76,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-13 23:28:20'),(776,76,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-13 23:28:20'),(777,77,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:08'),(778,77,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:08'),(779,77,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:08'),(780,77,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:08'),(781,77,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:08'),(782,77,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:08'),(783,78,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:39'),(784,78,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:39'),(785,78,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:39'),(786,78,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:39'),(787,78,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:39'),(788,78,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-14 00:31:39'),(789,79,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-0