<li><a href=\"#Madras\">Madras</a></li>\r\n</ul>',0,20,0,'2008-06-08 22:38:58'),(878,81,'Spectacle Drinks','\"Spectacle\" drinks are drinks that are created and/or served with an unusual amount of pomp and circumstance. An example from last year is the the \"ShotSki\" which is an actual ski with several shot glasses attached to it. \r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Pitcher of Martinis\">Pitcher of Martinis</a>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Bucket of Spit\">Bucket of Spit</a>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Splash of Bourbon\">Splash of Bourbon</a>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Sake Bomb\">Sake Bomb</a>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Thanks Getting\">Thanks Getting</a>\r\n\r\n</ul>',0,210,0,'2008-11-26 05:03:45'),(804,81,'Bourbon','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"#John Collins\">John Collins</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Bourbon & Coke\">Bourbon & Coke</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Bourbon & Seven\">Bourbon & Seven</a></li>\r\n\r\n</ul>',0,30,0,'2008-06-08 22:32:35'),(811,81,'Singapore Sling (Dave\'s)','<UL>\r\n<li>.25 oz <b>*benedictine*</b>\r\n<li>1 dash <b>*bitters*</b>\r\n<li>.5 oz <b>*cherry brandy*</b>\r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>* Gordon London Dry Gin*</b>\r\n<li>2 oz <b>*sour mix*</b>\r\n<li>3 oz  <b>*club soda*</b>\r\n<li>Shake with <b>*ice*</b> and pour into glass. \r\n</ul>\r\n',802,110,1,'2008-11-26 05:05:30'),(813,81,'Dry  Martini','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/martini.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/martini.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>Fill a <b>*Martini glass*</b> with <b>*ice*</b> and set aside\r\n<li>Fill a <b>*Shaker*</b> with <b>*ice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 2 oz <b>*Gordon London Dry Gin*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 oz <b>*dry vermouth*</b>\r\n<li>Shake well\r\n<li>Remove ice from martini glass\r\n<li> strain from shaker into glass. \r\n<LI>Garnish with <b>*olive*</b>.\r\n</ul>\r\n',802,120,0,'2008-07-27 22:33:11'),(814,81,'Cosmopolitan','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/cosmopolitan.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/cosmopolitan.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI>Fill Shaker with <b>*Ice*</B>\r\n<li>Add 1.5 oz <b>*Vodka*</B> \r\n<li>Add 1.5 oz <b>*Triple Sec*</B> \r\n<li>add .5 oz <b>*Rose\'s Lime Juice*</B> \r\n<li>Add  1.5 oz <b>*Cranberry Juice*</B> \r\n<li>Shake\r\n<LI>Pour into <b>*Martini glass *</B>\r\n<li>Place <b>*lime wedge*</B> on the rim.\r\n</ul>\r\n',803,20,0,'2008-08-19 07:21:53'),(818,81,'Gin Gimlet','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/gimlet.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/gimlet.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<b>(provisional)</b>\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>2 Oz <b>*Gordon London Dry Gin*</b>\r\n<li>1/2 oz <b>*Rose\'s Lime Juice*</b>\r\n<li><b>*garnish*</b>\r\n\r\n<li>Shake with <b>*ice*</b>, strain into glass. \r\n<LI>Garnish with <b>*Wedge of Lime *</b>.\r\n</ul>',802,130,1,'2008-11-26 05:05:30'),(821,81,'Tom Collins','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/tomcollins.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/tomcollins.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>Fill <b>*highball glass*</b> with <b>*ice*</b>\r\n<LI>Fill <b>*shaker*</b> with <b>*ice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 2 oz <b>*Gordon\'s London Dry Gin*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 oz <b>*lemon juice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 tsp <b>*superfine sugar*</b>\r\n<LI>Strain shaker into glass\r\n<li>fill glass with <b>*club soda*</b>. \r\n<li>Stir\r\n<li>Garnish with <b>*maraschino cherry*</b> and \r\n<li>Garnish with 1 <b>*orange slice*</b>\r\n</ul>\r\n',802,150,0,'2008-07-27 22:50:26'),(848,84,'The Casting Pickup','A sequence in a book. Maybe this one...\r\n\r\n\r\nYou meet a blond girl in a bar  who is working as a waitress but wants to be an actress and considered herself to be in a class above you. She is certainly a member of a large set in SoCal.\r\n\r\nI thought of a kind of pickup scam that I might have tried on her if 1) she had been alone and 2) I was more of an asshole than I really am\r\n\r\nAfter the initial introductions.\r\nMe: Man, what a fucked day at work it\'s been. You\'d think that actresses who are working as waitresses would be willing to work on something less than an A movie! But we can\'t seem to find anyone!\r\nYou (not in on the scam): What the...\r\nMe (cutting you off): Yeah, you\'re right. I promised I wouldn\'t talk about work tonight. But, dude, it\'s been a week and we haven\'t found ANYBODY! Ok, ok, I\'ll stop.\r\nYou: Odd questioning looks.\r\nNow we just leave it. She either takes the bait or she doesn\'t.\r\n\r\nThe story I would push (revealing as little of it as possible, only if she insists, with sidelong glances at you as if I\'m afraid you\'ll hit me if I talk about work) is that we cast actresses for some fly-by-night movie company. Our boss has a kickback arrangement with some agency and we can only hire people from that agency. But none of them are suitable and we\'re going to lose our jobs (the project will get canceled, our boss will get fired, the company may go out of business) if we can\'t find someone to fill at least some of the roles soon. There is much pointless lamenting about how we have to go through this worthless agency and how we could probably find women on craiglist if we didn\'t have this constraint. They would be willing to get paid good money and get movie credits but not these bitches, etc, etc. Our boss is going to drive the company under just to make a buck but does he care? Etc, etc. Our company is obviously the sleaziest company on the planet. But we are casting agents and we can bestow jobs upon would-be actresses.\r\n\r\nAgain, I stop. We *can* bestow jobs but we don\'t want to! The following can only be revealed if she wheedles, begs, pleads and keeps pushing. If she\'s a workable mark and I\'ve done the stuff up to here correctly, she will.\r\n\r\nI can\'t possibly do an audition for the actress/waitress we\'re talking to. She couldn\'t possibly be interested. She doesn\'t know what she\'s getting into. I don\'t want to talk about it. It\'s just not possible. Etc.\r\n\r\nWell, I suppose Ari has a camera. We could film something and send it to our boss\'s boss, the head of the company and maybe, if he liked it, he would over ride our boss and that might work. Probably not. It would have to be a really GOOD audition tape. But you don\'t even know the genre, you probably couldn\'t handle it.\r\n\r\nAt this stage we reveal, as gradually as possible the kind of films we make. We don\'t actually say  what we do but we say things like, \"They\'re not exactly family films\" and \"they\'re not exactly Warner Brothers\" with many a wry smile at each other. The implication, of course, is that we cast porn films.\r\n\r\nBy now she has convinced herself that, no matter how bad our films are, she would be willing to take a chance on them since it\'s paid acting which is more than she\'s doing. By the time she figures out that it\'s porn, she\'s psychologically committed. We just have to keep saying \"no\" until she insists!\r\n\r\nIf she insists on coming back to your apartment then she can be pretty much talked into whatever we want. She knows it\'s something bad. Even if she\'s naive she\'s got to know it\'s naughty. I just ruthlessly push her into having sex with you.\r\n\r\nAnd of course, *this* is where I\'m a real asshole because you don\'t want to have sex with her and you\'re only going along because you thought I was interested in this slag and you were too polite to stop me. But now I turn the tables on you (dude, I\'m married, I *can\'t* have sex with *anyone*) and you either have to make a scene or have sex with her. In front of a camera. And I can tease you about it FOREVER!\r\n\r\nI suspect it would actually work. At least it would make a good sequence in a book... :)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n',843,10,0,'2008-04-27 22:42:24'),(824,81,'Gin & Tonic','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/ginandtonic.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/ginandtonic.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>Fill a <b>*tumbler*</b> with <b>*ice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1.5 oz <b>*Gin*</b>\r\n<li>Fill glass with <b>*Tonic Water*</b>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n',802,135,0,'2008-07-27 22:37:37'),(842,84,'Characters','<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n</ul>',0,100,0,'2008-04-27 22:42:24'),(843,84,'Events (Stories)','<ul>\r\n<li>The Casting Pickup\r\n</ul>',0,200,0,'2008-04-27 22:42:24'),(844,84,'Situations','<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n</ul>',0,300,0,'2008-04-27 22:42:24'),(825,81,'John Collins','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/johncollins.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/johncollins.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>Mostly fill a <b>*tumbler*</b> with <b>*ice cubes*</b> \r\n<li>Half-fill a <b>*shaker*</b> with <b>*ice cubes*</b> \r\n<li>Add 2 oz <b>*Bourbon*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 oz <b>*lemon juice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 tsp <b>*superfine sugar*</b>\r\n<li>Shake well\r\n<li>Strain into glass\r\n<li>Add 3 oz <b>*club soda*</b>\r\n<li>Stir \r\n<li>garnish with 1 <b>*maraschino cherry*</b>\r\n<li>garnish with 1 <b>*slice orange*</b>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n',804,10,0,'2008-07-27 22:33:11'),(827,81,'Gatorade Drinks','The Simplicity and the American Dream are actually done but the other drinks are not quite finished but I put them in to give you an idea of what I\'m planning. What\'s missing is that each drink needs it\'s own style instead of being just \"booze and Gatorade\". \r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Simplicity\">Simplicity </a>- Fruit Punch & Bourbon\r\n<li><a href=\"#The American Dream\">The American Dream </a>-  Glacier Freeze, Grenadine & Vodka\r\n<li><a href=\"#Limelight \">Limelight</a> - Lemon Lime and Gin\r\n<li><a href=\"#SoCal Rum\">SoCal Rum</a> - Orange and Rum\r\n\r\n\r\n</ul>',0,50,0,'2008-05-29 16:38:18'),(914,81,'Kinds of Alcohol','<P>We need to know what kinds of booze will be the standards (the \"well drink\" liquors) on the Playa. This is what Lucifer told me on this score: \r\n<ul><LI>Vodka: Crown Russe vodka\r\n<LI>Tequila: ??\r\n<LI>Gin: Gordon\'s \r\n<LI>Rum - Bacardi \r\n<li>Bourbon: Ten High Kentucky Straight Sour Mash Bourbon Whiskey\r\n</ul>\r\nIf not otherwise stated, these recipes assume the use of these items.\r\n\r\n',865,20,0,'2008-07-27 21:11:11'),(889,85,'Personality','Before I talk about any experiences I need to discuss personality. \r\n<P>Everyone has experiences and these shape both their perception and their reaction to their perception. Our ability to predict subtle results from subtle trends in our perception is extremely evolved. Our personality is defined by our desire to have certain outcomes. Since we can predict outcomes from perceptions certain combinations of perceptions make us happy while others make us very unhappy. \r\n<P>The key to personality is not that we\'re locked into doing what our personality demands of us but simply that we <b>like</b> to do certain things. Imagine you like vanilla ice cream but you don\'t like chocolate. You certainly can make the choice to eat chocolate if there was some reason to do so but why would you? That\'s what personality is like: you can do anything you want but you want to do the things indicated by your personality.\r\n<P>One of the things that is really surprising about personality is that it\'s possible to categorize them into only a few kinds. One system identifies only 6 that exist in various combinations while another identifies four major classifications each with four minor classifications.  (The four major classifications from this system align well with four of the 6 from the other system and echoes of the other two can be found in the minor classification.) I don\'t know how or why there are so few major personality types when you would expect that there should be an infinite number. \r\n<P>Each person, faced with certain perceptions and desiring certain outcomes will strive for those outcomes. But different people will \r\n<P>Of course, there are many, many variations but an understanding of a person\'s personality coupled with some knowledge of how that person copes with his personality usually makes a person fairly predicable. ',0,10,0,'2008-05-31 19:31:21'),(828,82,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-04-24 21:59:25'),(829,82,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-04-24 21:59:25'),(830,82,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-04-24 21:59:25'),(831,82,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-04-24 21:59:25'),(832,82,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-04-24 21:59:25'),(833,82,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-04-24 21:59:25'),(834,83,'Executive Summary','This is a long letter. The issues, in all their detail, are complicated. But the fundamental issue is not. This first page, then, will outline what this is about in general, saving all the details to subsequent pages. \r\n<P>As you might imagine, on the surface this is a customer service issue. But fundamentally this is an engineering problem of the sort I think of as \"user experience\". \r\n<P>While you make good hardware, the quality of your user experience is very bad. It doesn\'t have to be and you should fix it. ',0,10,0,'2008-05-01 06:00:36'),(835,83,'Having to Pay Twice!',' I bought a memeo backup drive because my hard drive was failing. It hadn\'t crashed but it was getting a lot of errors and there were things on it that weren\'t backed up that I wanted. \r\n\r\n<P>I needed some place to put whatever I could salvage and then I would need a better backup solution so it wouldn\'t happen again. \r\n\r\n<P>I saved what I could but, in a really odd chain of events, the computer crashed and I decided to replace it. I had saved as much as I could; it was the best I could do. \r\n\r\n<P>I connected your product to the new computer and installed the software from the back up disk. That was nice, I liked that. But the license key  wasn\'t backed up. What with having my hard disk fail and then replacing the hard disk and then having the whole computer fail, I had lost the packaging.  \r\n\r\n<P>And the backup system didn\'t save the license key for itself. It\'s like the people who wrote the backup software never expected me to actually need to restore! Do I need to point out that software that is intended to allow one to restore data from a crashed system needs to save it\'s licensing information>? This is a huge hole in your system design! \r\n\r\n<P>That is the first and biggest problem: I paid for  software that\'s intended for use when systems crash. For heaven\'s sake, why do I have to put my key back in!? \r\n\r\n<P>I contacted customer service and explained the situation. \"No problem, just give us your phone number and we\'ll take care of it.\" I sent them my phone number and then sent it again just in case the first message got lost. I never heard from them again. \r\n\r\n<P>Some weeks later the \"trial version\" (that\'s the \"trial version\" on the software I had already paid for, you understand) ran out. So now my choices are 1) pay for the software a second time or 2) not have my system backed up. That is, to have a backup system that I paid hundreds for, become a brick.\r\n\r\n\r\n<P>So I bought the software AGAIN. Ok, I\'m out $30.\r\n\r\n<P>I left a note when I bought it complaining. Someone responded, some more back and forth ensued and the upshot was that they weren\'t going to fix my problem (they never said that, but they aren\'t). \r\n<P>Now they don\'t admit that they ever even talked to me (they probably aren\'t lying -- there are probably multiple groups involved -- buy why should *I* have to worry about that?). I asked to escalate and they ignored me. I could have called, sent more urgent emails and so forth. But again, why should *I* have to worry about your process? I asked, was promised, then ignored, then refused, and denied escalation.\r\n',0,20,0,'2008-05-01 06:04:08'),(836,83,'Upgrading Problems','While I was talking to the customer service rep, he pointed out that the software I had was out of date. He told me where to get the upgrade and suggested I uninstall the old software first. \r\n\r\n<P>First off,you have to uninstall the software before you can install the update. This is wrong because it\'s a horrible thing to do to your customers. The new software should disable and remove the old drivers and fix up the registry and do whatever else it needs to do as part of the new installation. It\'s sloppy and unprofessional to force the customers to do an uninstall. \r\n\r\n<P>Then the uninstall shut down my computer without asking me! I\'m sorry, did your programmers think this was 1990? Totally unacceptable to shut a modern computer down on the user -- whose computer is this, anyway? \r\n\r\n<P>Ok, so the computer comes back up, and I reinstall the software. When it comes back up it doesn\'t have a license (naturally) and is back on the trial period and doesn\'t remember any of the backups. \r\n\r\n<P>I\'m sorry to be so crude but this is all bullshit. The new software should install over the old software and when it\'s done I should have a working system that is licensed and doing backups. Forcing the customer to go through a multi-step install (with a forced reboot!) followed by forcing him to re-configure the software (again) is just wrong. \r\n<P>And  Iâ€™ll bet the version of the software thatâ€™s backed up is the old version, not the upgraded new version, right? So if my hard disk crashes, Iâ€™ll probably install from the backup version (thinking \"how nice that they saved this for me!\") and then go through all these problems again. \r\n<P>At least at this point I\'ve been through it multiple times so I\'ve figured out your crazy user interface...\r\n\r\n',0,30,0,'2008-05-01 06:08:50'),(837,83,'User Interface Problems','And that\'s one more level of issues. The basic user interface is horrible. Granted, it\'s made from standard user interface elements but inappropriately cobbled together. \r\n\r\n<P>First it tells me what the steps are going to be. That\'s a good start. Then I click on the next button. Then I pick the destination. Then I have to click on a link that has me pick the source. But the drive I want to back up is on the \"disallow\" list (why? don\'t people back up their second drive?) and I\'m told to keep going and then click on advanced to fix it. So I go on, click on advanced, take it off the disallow list and then go back and fix the problem. In this lurching, arbitrary and confusing way, I eventually get the thing configured. It\'s not that I can\'t do it but why can\'t you make it easier? Well you can and you should!\r\n\r\n<P>First off, if you are going to give me a list of steps, why not have THAT be the basic interface. At the top of every screen is the list of steps with the steps I\'ve completed greyed out (perhaps next to a \"back\" button) and the current step highlighted. Then in the bottom of the screen a set of controls to handle that step. (It\'s better to put the explanation at the top and the controls at the bottom than the other way around because people usually start at the top of the page or the screen and so they are more likely to find the instructions.)\r\n\r\n<P>If there is some reason why they can\'t do what they are trying to do, have a button that will take them straight to the place they can fix it. Or just have a dialog box that says \"would you like to allow this?\". \r\n\r\n<P>The use of a web-style link in the middle of a page is completely weird in the context of a non-web application. Apart from the dissonance it creates (it\'s important to give users a sense of connection to other applications they have used and not mix and match UI elements from different places), there is seldom a purpose in having a link to another page. If there is something that needs to get done, just put it in the space you had the link. Why make me click again?\r\n\r\n<P>I get the sense that this is a UI written by someone really smart but not used to writing UI (maybe a hardware engineer). It also looks like it went through some pretty good beta testing and that most of the problems found were addressed by the UI designer by adding text (it TELLS me where to fix the problem with the disallow list but it doesn\'t actually TAKE me there). I\'ll bet it has to be rewritten from the ground up.',0,40,0,'2008-05-01 05:42:38'),(838,83,'In Conclusion','It\'s hard to do good customer service. First and foremost because there are so many customers. And then because the issues can be complicated and the users are often not sophisticated. And sometimes we\'re just wrong. \r\n<P>In this case, though, I think I have a legitimate gripe here and I think it needs to be addressed. \r\n<P>Unfortunately customer service isn\'t really set up to address these kinds of problem -- fundamental problems with the software and problems with customer service  themselves. I don\'t know how else to get them addressed than to write you this long letter and send it, scatter shot, to the executives in the company. \r\n<P>I sincerely want to make your product better. I hope that you will respond positively to this approach.\r\n\r\n',0,50,0,'2008-05-01 05:06:21'),(841,81,'Ari\'s Singapore Sling','<b>(provisional)</b>\r\n<UL>\r\n<li>\r\n<li>2oz <b>*Gordon\'s Gin*</b>\\\r\n<li>3/4oz <b>*Lemon Juice*</b>\r\n<li>1 tsp <b>*Powdered Sugar*</b>\r\n<li>Shake with <b>*Ice*</b> and Pour\r\n<li>Top with <b>*Club Soda*</b>\r\n<li>Stir Gently\r\n<li>Layer 1oz <b>*Cherry Brandy*</b>\r\n<li>*Garnish with <b>*Orange Slice* </b>\r\n</ul>',802,12,1,'2008-11-26 05:05:30'),(849,81,'Kamikaze','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/Kamikaze.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/Kamikaze.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<LI>Fill Shaker with <b>*Ice*</B>\r\n<li>Add 1 oz. <b>*Triple Sec*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 oz. <b>*Vodka*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 oz. <b>*Lime Juice*</b>\r\n<li>Shake\r\n<li>Pour into <b>*highball glass*</b>. \r\n<li>Garnish with a <b>*Slice of Lime*</b>.\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n',803,50,0,'2008-08-19 07:22:32'),(850,81,'Gin Fizz','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/ginfizz.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/ginfizz.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<ul>\r\n<LI>Fill <b>*shaker*</b> with <b>*ice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 2 oz <b>*Gordon\'s London Dry Gin*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 oz <b>*fresh limejuice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 2 tsp <b>*fine sugar*</b>\r\n<li>Shake well\r\n<li>Strain into <b>*highball glass*</b>\r\n<li>Fill with <b>*Club Soda*</b>\r\n</ul>\r\n',802,160,0,'2008-07-27 22:50:26'),(852,81,'Bourbon Slow Gin Fizz','<ul>\r\n<li>2 oz <b>*Bourbon Whiskey*</b>\r\n<li>1 oz <b>*sloe gin*</b>\r\n<li>1 tsp <b>*lemon juice*</b>\r\n<li><b>*soda water*</b>\r\n</ul>',804,30,1,'2008-11-26 05:05:30'),(853,81,'Gin Buck','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/ginbuck.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/ginbuck.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fill <b>*tumbler*</b> with <b>*Ice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 2 oz <b>*Gordon\'s London Dry Gin*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1/2 oz <b>*lime juice *</b>\r\n<li>Fill with <b>*Ginger Ale*</b>\r\n</ul>\r\n',802,180,0,'2008-07-27 22:51:02'),(863,63,'Viewable Section','This sections is no hidden',547,20,0,'2008-04-30 05:44:37'),(862,63,'Hidden section','This section is hidden!',547,10,1,'2008-04-30 05:44:37'),(866,78,'',NULL,783,10,0,'2008-04-30 03:53:32'),(864,81,'Pitcher of Martinis','<UL>\r\n<li>Fill 4 martini glasses with <b>*ice*</b>and set them on the bar.\r\n<li>Take a crystal pitcher and fill with <b>*ice*</b>where everyone can see it. \r\n<li>Add 8 oz <b>*Gordon London Dry Gin*</b>\r\n<li>Add 4 oz <b>*dry vermouth*</b>\r\n<li>Stir with flourishes and fanfare <i>exactly</i> 10 times. Have people in bar help count.\r\n<li>Empty martini glasses. \r\n<li>Strain contents of pitcher into 4 martini glasses. \r\n<li>Garnish each glass with <b>*green olive*</b> with a flourish. \r\n<li>Select 4 recipients with great deliberation and ceremony\r\n</ul>\r\n',878,5,0,'2008-05-29 16:44:37'),(865,81,'Introduction','These are the drinks for the <b><i>Golden Cafe</i></b> bar. They are divided it into sections by alcohol (e.g. \"Gin\", \"Vodka\" and so forth) plus a few sections for special things. \r\n',0,10,0,'2008-11-26 05:05:30'),(915,81,'Format Standard','<P>The standard for recipes is to highlight the ingredients in the order they should be added in the midst of the instructions. That way, you can see what you need at a glance and, once you\'ve done that, you can simply work your way down the list without worrying about \"gotcha instructions\". ',865,10,0,'2008-07-27 21:11:11'),(916,81,'Glassware','These recipes use certain terms for glassware, defined as follows: \r\n<dl>\r\n<dt><b>Margarita</b> <DD >  is 8oz. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/margaritaglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Collins</b> <DD >  glass is 10oz tall thin cylinder. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/collinsglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Flute</b> <DD > is 6oz. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/fluteglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Hurricane</b> <DD >16oz+ glass tall & round at the bottom, constricted in the middle, flaring out at the top, with a short stem.. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/hurricaneglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Highball</b> <DD >  is 14oz tall wide cylinder. I think we may lose the highballs in favor of Collins this year. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/highballglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Bowl</b> <DD >  is yet to be measured. </dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Shot</b> <DD >  very short glass (~2 inches) which is roughly cylindrical (wider at top) and holds a little less than 2.5oz. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/shotglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Cocktail</b> <DD >  glass is the inverse 10oz cone on stem. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/cocktailglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Coffee</b> <DD >  glass is 9oz coffee mug. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/coffeeglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n<br><br><dt><b>Rocks </b> <DD > glass is 10oz short squat cylinder. <img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/rocksglass.png\" height=\"60\"></dfn></dt>\r\n\r\n</dl>\r\n',865,30,0,'2008-08-12 19:01:45'),(867,78,'test',NULL,784,10,0,'2008-04-30 03:53:41'),(868,78,'d',NULL,787,10,0,'2008-04-30 03:53:49'),(869,78,'adsf',NULL,783,20,0,'2008-04-30 03:53:58'),(870,83,'Who I am','But who am I to tell you this? Well, I\'ve spent most(but not all) of my 20 year professional career making computer games. And when I wasn\'t doing that I was working for Palm and OmniSky and Network Appliance on their user experiences.  Which is to say, my entire professional career is based on giving my users  an excellent experience. \r\n<P>I therefor knew a great deal about this. And I understand about complicated interactions among hardware. But we always make it easy for the user. \r\n',834,10,1,'2008-05-01 06:08:50'),(871,83,'Why I\'m Writing','In part, I\'m writing because I tried to get a problem corrected through customer service and they promised me they would fix it and then didn\'t. \r\n<P>A deeper issue is that I need a decent backup solution and your hardware and technology seems to be OK. If only the user experience didn\'t suck rocks, it would be a pretty decent product. So maybe if I write you a letter and tell you what I find objectionable, perhaps you\'ll listen and actually fix it. After all, I actually know a lot about software and user interfaces and making things work correctly. Lots of experience. \r\n',834,20,0,'2008-05-01 05:00:29'),(872,83,'What The Problem Is','The main problem is that I had to pay for the software twice because the backup software didn\'t save it\'s own serial number and customer service, after promising they\'d fix it, didn\'t. \r\n<P>A second problem is that I need a good backup solution and I paid for yours and your user experience is very bad. I\'m hoping I can help you improve that. ',834,30,0,'2008-05-01 06:01:56'),(873,83,'Summary of Grievances','To summarize, the backup software should remember it\'s key. Customer service, if they say they\'ll give you a new key should do so. I should get my $30 back. The upgrade is really, really bad (more about that below). And, while we\'re here, the user interface is just crazy. \r\n<P>I think I deserve an acknowledgment that this is really bad. I really deserve my $30 back (frankly, you should give away the software for free as long as it\'s being used with your hardware). And I\'d like to have some reassurance that you\'re at least going to LOOK at my suggestions seriously. Of course, it\'s your business so you can obviously do what you want. ',834,40,0,'2008-05-01 05:00:29'),(874,83,'What I\'m Going To Do Next','If your product doesn\'t improve I\'m going to review it. You can easily imagine what I\'m going to say. Almost every online site has a \"comments\" or \"review this\" or \"rate this\" section. \r\n<P>I\'m hoping that if my lone voice isn\'t persuasive I\'ll seek out fellow users and see if they agree. I\'m also regretting that I took it for granted that Seagate makes good products when I bought this. I can help other people avoid that problem. ',834,50,1,'2008-05-01 06:08:50'),(875,81,'Screw Driver','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/screwdriver.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/screwdriver.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fill <b>*tall glass*</b> with <b>*Ice*</b>\r\n<li>Add 2 oz <b>*Vodka*</b>\r\n<li>Fill with <b>*Orange Juice*</b>\r\n<li>Stir\r\n</ul>',803,60,0,'2008-08-19 07:22:32'),(876,81,'Rongo!','<ul>\r\n<li>Take <b>*Tall glass *</b>\r\n<li>Add 2 oz. <b>*Vodka*</b>\r\n<li>Fill with <b>*Beer*<b>\r\n</ul>',803,70,0,'2008-07-27 21:06:30'),(877,81,'Madras','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/madras.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/madras.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fill a <b>*Highball glass*</b> with <b>*ice*</b></li>.\r\n<li>Add 1.5 oz <b> *vodka*</li>\r\n<li>Add 1.5 oz <b>*orange juice*</li>\r\n<li>Fill (~6 oz) with <b>*cranberry juice*</li>\r\n<li>Stir.\r\n</ul>\r\n',803,80,0,'2008-07-27 21:54:31'),(880,81,'Bucket of Spit','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/bucket.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/bucket.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<P>The Bucket of Spit is a bulk Gatorade drink, mixed in a metal bucket  with a ladle (reference: football practice). Two assistants carry it amidst much grunting, hooting and hollering around the bar. \r\n<P>It should be made clear that, despite the name and the apparent punitive aspect of the process, the drink will be somewhere between good and very good as well as being very good for the drinker. \r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Place <b>*Metal Bucket*</b> on bar.\r\n<LI>Add 2 scoops of <b>*ice *</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 qt of <b>*water*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 <b>*Secret Mix Packet*</b>\r\n<li>Add 10 oz of <b>*Bourbon*</b>\r\n<li>Stir with <b>*Ladle*</b>\r\n<li>Two assistants carry it with much grunting, hooting and hollering around the bar. Anyone who has a empty glass in front of them must drink a ladle offered by the first assistant and then the other assistant busses their glassware. \r\n</ul> ',878,20,0,'2008-07-30 06:20:06'),(885,81,'Simplicity ','<UL>\r\n<li>If you don\'t have any <b>*Fruit Punch Gatorade*</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>In a 1.5 Q pitcher, mix 1 QT of <b>*water*</b> with \r\n<li>1 packet of <b>*Fruit Punch Gatorade Powder*</b>\r\n<li>Stir well\r\n</ul>\r\n<LI>Shake with <b>*Ice*</B>\r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>*Bourbon*</B>\r\n<li>6 oz <b>*Fruit Punch Gatorade*</b> \r\n<li>Strain into tall glass. \r\n</ul>\r\n',827,20,0,'2008-06-01 17:57:23'),(886,81,'The American Dream','<UL>\r\n<li>If you don\'t have any <b>*Glacier Freeze Gatorade*</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>In a 1.5 Q pitcher, mix 1 QT of <b>*water*</b> with \r\n<li>1 packet of <b>*Glacier Freeze Gatorade Powder*</b>\r\n<li>Stir well\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Note the the name comes from the 3 colors of the ingredients so emphasize the ingredients while making.\r\n<li>Fill a tall glass with <b>*Ice*</b> and add\r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>*Vodka*</b> \r\n<li>1 oz <b>*Grenadine*</b>\r\n<li>fill glass (~6 oz.) with <b>*Glacier Freeze Gatorade*</b> .\r\n<li>Stir\r\n<li>Garnish with sparkler\r\n</ul>',827,30,0,'2008-06-01 17:57:23'),(887,81,'Limelight','<UL>\r\n<li>If you don\'t have any <b>*Lemon Lime Gatorade*</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>In a 1.5 Q pitcher, mix 1 QT of <b>*water*</b> with \r\n<li>1 packet of <b>*Lemon Lime Gatorade Powder*</b>\r\n<li>Stir well\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Half fill an 8 oz glass with <b>*Ice*</b>, pour \r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>*Gin*</b> \r\n<li>3 oz <b>*Tonic*</b>\r\n<li>Fill (~6 oz) with  <b>*Lemon Lime Gatorade*</b> .\r\n<li>Stir\r\n</ul>',827,40,0,'2008-06-01 06:47:11'),(888,81,'SoCal Rum','<UL>\r\n<li>If you don\'t have any <b>*Orange Gatorade*</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>In a 1.5 Q pitcher, mix 1 QT of <b>*water*</b> with \r\n<li>1 packet of <b>*Orange  Gatorade Powder*</b>\r\n<li>Stir well\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Fill an 8 oz glass with <b>*Ice*</b>, pour \r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>*Rum*</b> \r\n<li>6 oz <b>*Orange  Gatorade*</b> into the glass .\r\n</ul>',827,50,0,'2008-07-30 06:21:49'),(881,81,'Experiments','<ul>\r\n<li>Fruit Punch Gatorade\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gin - bad, possibly because the gin is poor\r\n<li>Vodka - Pretty good\r\n<li>Rum - Horrible, possibly because it\'s bad rum.\r\n<li>Bourbon - Darn good, actually.\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<li>Glacier Freeze Gatorade\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gin - good, perhaps a bit better than the others\r\n<li>Vodka - good\r\n<li>Bourbon - good, it has a green color (normally blue)\r\n<li>Rum - good\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Lemon Lime Gatorade\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Vodka - good\r\n<li>Bourbon - bad\r\n<li>Rum - bad\r\n<li>Gin - OK\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Orange\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Vodka - good\r\n<li>gin - ok\r\n<li>rum - ok -\r\n<li>Bourbon - ok\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>',827,10,1,'2008-11-26 05:05:30'),(895,81,'Splash of Bourbon','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/bourbon.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/bourbon.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<P>I\'ll be bringing about 6 different kinds of very high end bourbon. This drink is simplicity itself: put 1 oz of a high end bourbon in a glass for a customer. The spectacle is in the authority and ceremony that the bartender brings to the process. \r\nBring out the bottle with reverence. Uncork with a flourish. Pour it out with slow, careful deliberation. In short, make a big deal that we\'re pouring a drink that would cost $20 in any bar in America. This is, truly, the American Dream!\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Get the band to play a fanfare, get the bar to chant, get the attention of everyone.\r\n<li>Bring out a bottle of <b>*High end bourbon*</b> (whatever is left) with ceremony and reverence\r\n<li>Place a <b>*Tumbler*</b> on the bar\r\n<li>add 1 oz <b>*bourbon*</b>\r\n</ul> ',878,30,0,'2008-11-26 05:04:47'),(896,48,'So What?','The world is heading for 15 billion people, apparently. It is not really known if we can support that many or, indeed, how many we can support. Let\'s say it\'s 12 billion. It would be nice to think (although I admit, not very kind -- but I said this was a \"ugly truth\" kind of place) that those 3 billion excess people would simply lay down and die.\r\n<P>\r\nFirst off, those doomed 3 billions will not take it lying down; they are going to try to get more resources to survive. There will be a series of border clashes which will eventually escalate into regional wars. Lots of people will die of famine, war and disease and that will take the pressure off for a time but then the war will flare up again. A war involving 3 billion people on one side is a pretty big war and it will very likely affect the rest of the world.\r\n<P>\r\nThe effect of this extreme chaos will probably be that much resources will be consumed fighting, supplying armies and generally trying to protect oneself. The chaos will inevitably tax our resources so that we can no longer support 12 billion and more people will be threatened with starvation and more will go to war. The world will spiral down from a prosperous, fairly stable state to total chaos. You can\'t maintain a global economy in chaos so the world economy will become fragmented. Some fragments will be unsupportable so the chaos will spread. Some areas will be stable but, inevitably, they will be stable at a much lower level of technology. Whatever this level is, it will be the new \"dark ages\" and it will be the basis for the next civilization on earth many hundreds of years later.\r\n<P>\r\nOf course, this scenario won\'t actually happen. Even if the Earth could support 12 billion people (which is unlikely), we would never get anywhere near 15 billion. Instead the wars would start while we still had plenty of food because of the inequality of distribution. They would get steadily worse until the chaos they caused completely prevented our reaching any kind of stable equilibrium. This dynamic makes it very hard to predict how much the earth can sustain. ',0,70,0,'2008-06-01 03:06:28'),(897,48,'21st Century Dark Ages ','As the world becomes more and more chaotic, the global economy will become less able to sustain the level of technology we have come to expect. We currently get rubber from South America, oil from the Middle East, rare earths from Africa. We manufacture things in China and Korea and Taiwan that we use to maintain our technology in California. As exploitation of raw materials, manufacturing and transportation are disrupted, it can\'t help but ',0,80,0,'2008-06-01 03:06:28'),(898,48,'Why will we lose our technology?','Our technology is based on a global manufacturing economy. If there is suddenly no fossil fuels, the transport web will fail because there won\'t be enough fuel to support it. That means that you can no longer acquire things that aren\'t produced nearby because the is no reasonable way to get them to you.\r\n<P>\r\nIf everything you had access to was produced within, say, 500 miles of you, you\'re technology would be very much constrained. You need to have food production, energy production, manufacturing and so forth all fairly close by.  One could imagine a population heroically reproducing the 19th century with hard work but first they would have to cope with water and food without fossil fuels of any kind. By the time they dealt with those challenges much of the old technology would be lost -- not to memory but to practical use. Keep in mind that all this will happen, not in an orderly predictable fashion, but amidst war, famine, disease and other forms of chaos.\r\n',897,10,0,'2008-06-01 01:11:23'),(899,48,'What level of technology will be sustainable?','If we decided to cut back we could maintain our current technology. We would simply have to give up using too much of everything.\r\nBut if we\'re forced to cut back we\'re likely to lose the electrical grid. Once that goes down for, say, a decade, it will be very hard to bring it back up. Once we lose electricity most of our technology is shot. Of course some places will still have electricity and those places will be little islands of technology but most places will be struggling to farm enough food to feed themselves -- maintaining anything more will be tough.\r\nThink about it: no electricity from a grid and no fossil fuels. Where do you get energy? Burning wood? Horses? ',897,20,0,'2008-06-01 01:11:56'),(900,48,'The Case For The Five','These five things are not just a few of the things we should be concerned about. These five things are the first five things we must deal with before we can address all the other things that will hurt us if we don\'t address them.\r\n<P>It seems obvious that, if any one of these things goes wrong -- we run out of energy without any way to replace it or our population becomes unsustainable -- people will die. If it goes a little wrong -- New York doesn\'t get food for a month, for example -- only thousands will die. If it goes horribly wrong --  say food production is cut in half worldwide for an extended period of time -- millions or even billions could die.\r\n<P>\r\nUnfortunately, there are a <b>lot</b> of things that can go badly wrong and almost anything going wrong makes it more likely that other things would then go wrong. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n',453,70,0,'2008-06-01 03:06:28'),(901,48,'What Can We Do?','to what we\'re doing. There are 5 major areas that I believe can send our civiliation (by which I mean \"global society\" since I don\'t believe any portion of the world can maintain a technological society while a significant portion of the rest decends into war, famine, desease and general chaos). These five potential catastrophes are all related and need to be solved as a group. Solving one or two won\'t save us and I don\'t think it\'s actually possible to solve any of them separately.\r\nI want to make two things very clear from the outset. FIrst, this is not a doom and gloom, all is lost proposition. I think we can still save ourselves but we have to actually work at it. I see a lot of people ignoring it and I don\'t see anyone taking it really seriously.\r\nSecond, I am not an environmentalist per se. That is, I don\'t believe that we should put the earth before ourselves. However, as it turns out, we must rearrange our lifestyle so that the earth can sustain us or we simply won\'t survive. This aligns me with some ideas of environmentalists and sets me against others. For example, I agree that we need to do things sustainably but I would be against (for example) tearing down damns to recreate the natural wild rivers.\r\n\r\n<h3>Global Warming</h3>\r\nMore properly called \"global climate change\", this is observed and generally accepted warming of the earth. Most people agree that it\'s caused by the over use of fossil fuels. This means that it is either the potential cause or potential effect of every other one of the five except overpopulation.\r\nSomething that is not generally appreciated is that the global climate change doesn\'t necessarily mean that the mean temperature goes up everywhere in an orderly and predictable manner. Rather it means that there is a great deal more energy in the weather systems which means that the temperature, winds, rainfall and so forth are more variable and less predicable. This could result in a disruption of food growth if the \"bread basket\" areas of the earth became untenable as growing areas. It could also create a lack of water if rain fall was distributed differently. The main point, however, is that more variable weather will mean more variable crop yields -- it\'s hard to imagine that will be good for growing as much food as we need.\r\n\r\n<h3>Energy Shortages</h3>\r\nThis should come as no surprise to anyone. We\'ve known since the 50\'s that we were using up all the fossil fuels and we\'ve certainly known since the 70\'s that production doesn\'t always meet demand. What\'s becoming clear is that soon it may not be possible for production to meet demand. This has already caused wars and it will cause bigger and bigger wars as the demand becomes more acute.\r\n\r\n<h3>Overpopulation</h3>\r\nIn a sense, this is the root cause of all the others. As the population of the world grows it will need more of everything which will drive global warming, energy consumption, and require ever more food and water.\r\nBut this is an oversimplification. The truth is that every North American consumes so much more resources of every kind than any other citizen of the planet that any plan that doesn\'t involve Americans cutting back on their consumption radically is doomed.\r\n\r\n<h3>Starvation</h3>\r\nThere are several ways that starvation could happen. Climate change might rearrange places were food will grow in a way that prevents us from growing enough food. We could run out of energy and therefore not be able to sustain large scale agriculture and/or the transportation network. Or the population could simply grow beyond our ability to feed it -- there is only so much growth we can sustain, after all.\r\n\r\n<h3>Lack of Water</h3>\r\nCurrently some parts of America are using more water than they produces. They are borrowing water from other places. The people in those places, however, are growing and need more and more water themselves. Eventually something will have to give and those states that are importing water will find themselves with a shortage.\r\nPopulation growth has been the main thing that is driving this and there is no sign this will stop. But as the climate changes there will be an unknown effect on the distribution of water and that may cause a shift in where the water is. If it moves to places we can catch it then we\'ll be ok (that is, we\'ll run out later) but if not, we could run out fairly suddenly.\r\n\r\n<h3>So What?</h3>\r\nThe world is heading for 15 billion people, apparently. It is not really known if we can support that many or, indeed, how many we can support. Let\'s say it\'s 12 billion. It would be nice to think (although I admit, not very kind -- but I said this was a \"ugly truth\" kind of place) that those 3 billion excess people would simply lay down and die.\r\n\r\nFirst off, those doomed 3 billions will not take it lying down; they are going to try to get more resources to survive. There will be a series of border clashes which will eventually escalate into regional wars. Lots of people will die of famine, war and disease and that will take the pressure off for a time but then the war will flare up again. A war involving 3 billion people on one side is a pretty big war and it will very likely affect the rest of the world.\r\nThe effect of this extreme chaos will probably be that much resources will be consumed fighting, supplying armies and generally trying to protect oneself. The chaos will inevitably tax our resources so that we can no longer support 12 billion and more people will be threatened with starvation and more will go to war. The world will spiral down from a prosperous, fairly stable state to total chaos. You can\'t maintain a global economy in chaos so the world economy will become fragmented. Some fragments will be unsupportable so the chaos will spread. Some areas will be stable but, inevitably, they will be stable at a much lower level of technology (why inevitably?). Whatever this level is (what level WILL it be?), it will be the new \"dark ages\" and it will be the basis for the next civilization on earth many hundreds of years later.\r\n\r\nOf course, this scenario won\'t actually happen. Even if the Earth could support 12 billion people (which is unlikely), we would never get anywhere near 15 billion. Instead the wars would start while we still had plenty of food because of the inequality of distribution. They would get steadily worse until the chaos they caused completely prevented our reaching any kind of stable equilibrium. This dynamic makes it very hard to predict how much the earth can sustain. \r\n\r\n<h3>Why will we lose our technology?</h3>\r\nOur technology is based on a global manufacturing economy. If there is suddenly no fossil fuels, the transport web will fail because there won\'t be enough fuel to support it. That means that you can no longer acquire things that aren\'t produced nearby because the is no reasonable way to get them to you.\r\nIf everything you had access to was produced within, say, 500 miles of you, you\'re technology would be very much constrained. You need to have food production, energy production, manufacturing and so forth all fairly close by.  One could imagine a population heroically reproducing the 19th century with hard work but first they would have to cope with water and food without fossil fuels of any kind. By the time they dealt with those challenges much of the old technology would be lost -- not to memory but to practical use. Keep in mind that all this will happen, not in an orderly predictable fashion, but amidst war, famine, disease and other forms of chaos.\r\n\r\n<h3>What level of technology will be sustainable?</h3>\r\nIf we decided to cut back we could maintain our current technology. We would simply have to give up using too much of everything.\r\nBut if we\'re forced to cut back we\'re likely to lose the electrical grid. Once that goes down for, say, a decade, it will be very hard to bring it back up. Once we lose electricity most of our technology is shot. Of course some places will still have electricity and those places will be little islands of technology but most places will be struggling to farm enough food to feed themselves -- maintaining anything more will be tough.\r\nThink about it: no electricity from a grid and no fossil fuels. Where do you get energy? Burning wood? Horses? \r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>But what can we do?</h3>\r\nFor those of us in the US, the problem is really energy.  We could, if we were really committed, cut our energy usage in half in the next 20 years (by \"we\" I mean those of us in the US). I know that sounds outrageous but we could replace all our lights with LEDs, take mass transit whenever possible, drive tiny hybrid cars, and build energy efficient houses. We\'re filthy rich; we could do it all if we wanted to spend the money. We just need to decide that that is what we want to do!\r\nWe would also have to significantly increase our renewable energy sources.\r\n',0,90,0,'2008-06-01 01:14:22'),(902,48,'Sustainability','The environment is a very complicated thing. By \"environment\" what I\'m really talking about is the world in which we try to live. I\'m sure with the discovery of global warming there are probably environmentalists who are congratulating themselves. \"We were right all along! And they didn\'t listen!\"\r\n\r\n<P>But they weren\'t right, not really. Sure, some of what they said we should do we should, in fact do. But other things were just wrong-headed. And all for the wrong reasons. We don\'t need to save the planet, we need to save ourselves. \r\n\r\n<P>For example, I saw an article in which environmentalists demanded that we take apart the great dams to return the rivers to their natural state. This would certainly save the planet but it would certainly harm efforts to prevent global climate change (because the dams would be replaced by some kind of power source that burns carbon). \r\n\r\n<P>Of course, they had good ideas, too. Deforestation is a bad idea and environmentalists have always been against. Until recently, however, the call seemed to be to preserve the forests rather than to harvest them sustainably. The truth is that we\'re going to get wood from SOMEWHERE and if it\'s not sustainably from somewhere close to home than we\'ll destroy some rain forest somewhere -- it\'s inevitable. \r\n\r\n<P>But now we seem to be lining up behind the idea that we want to do thing sustainably. It\'s OK to use power but try to preserve it. It\'s OK to harvest forests but only sustainably. We need to protect the environment but the priority is on making it livable and sustainable, rather than to make it pristine and aesthetic. \r\n\r\n<P>Not that I\'m against aesthetics but I\'m going to ask over an over again this question: how many people will have to die to allow you to preserve that aesthetic? Because the difference between a few less dams (and a few more carbon-emitting power plants) or a few more old-growth forests (and a few more denuded rain forests) could be, ultimately, the difference between a global temperature rise that will kill thousands and one that will kill millions. \r\n\r\n<P>Given this complexity and the effect of unintended consequences (and the extreme stakes), how can we possibly know what to do? We can\'t really. I\'m pretty sure that if the greatest minds in the world tried to design an environment that could sustain billions of people they would not agree on an opening statement for the symposium, much less come up with a plan. There are too many variables and uncertainties. \r\n\r\n<P>But we actually have a much harder problem than to determine what the perfect result ought to be: we have to figure out how to get there. \r\n<P>\r\nOddly, we can say with some confidence what direction we need to go in right now, even if we don\'t know where we\'re going or how to get there. It\'s fairly obvious that we need to use less of pretty much everything, especially petroleum. And how to use less petroleum is fairly obvious: we as consumers should stop driving and we should immediately vote huge \"carbon taxes\" on pretty much everything. Such carbon taxes will make all kinds of alternatives practical  (simply by making petroleum artificially expensive now, instead of waiting until it becomes naturally expensive) while at the same time, funding government backed research and subsidies. The sooner we do this, the more we can mitigate the terrible cost of running out of oil suddenly without anything in place to replace it. \r\n<P>\r\nThis will require tremendous sacrifices here in the developed world and will impose hardships on the developing world, as well. How big the relative hardships depend on the details of implementation but most it depends on whether you live in developed or developing country. Is it worse to have to give up luxuries to which you\'ve become accustomed or to never have those luxuries in the first place? And how many angels CAN dance on the head of a pin? \r\n<P>\r\nMy friend suggests that the most important issues, the overriding thing that, if addressed could address all other problems, is energy. After considering this carefully, I have to disagree. I believe the key to everything is population. If we can\'t stabilize our population we can never get a handle on any other issue because we can continue to increase our population until we run out of something else (probably energy). If we CAN control out population then we can, presumably, gradually bring it to a sustainable level where we WOULD have enough energy (and water, and food, and everything else). \r\n<P>\r\nBut, practically speaking, controlling our population is even harder than increasing our energy production. Who in the developed world would willingly accept a limit on their parenthood? And there are many millions in the world who believe it is there religious duty to have as many children as possible along with many more millions who could not be compelled to limit their progeny simply because there is no government stable enough in their part of the world to impose such a rule. \r\n<P>\r\nThe problem of energy also seems intractable. Unless you believe that the world oil supply is actually infinite and that the problem is therefor one of production, we\'re going to run out of oil. And, because the growth curves are all exponential, we\'ll blow through what\'s left MUCH faster than we used up the same quantity before that. The threat is that we\'ll run out of oil before we have developed replacement energy sources, even though the price of oil will go  through the roof, making all kinds of energy more \"affordable\" (compared to oil). \r\n<P>\r\nThe key issue about energy is investment. If we had an infinite amount of investment, we could build an infinite amount of solar panels (and hydrogen plants to generate power at night) and we\'d all be saved. But the cost of all those solar plants (assuming we could afford to have that much ground shielded from the sun) makes it impractical to do immediately. \r\n<P>\r\nWe need two things: time and money! We can buy time but conservation and we can get money through taxation. It sounds too simple to be true but an immediate carbon tax would both generate a lot of money and force a lot of conservation. And the only reason why we haven\'t done it yet is that various people are still making too much money from the current structure to be willing to change it. And, of course, those of us who drive cars are afraid of what the taxes will do to our budgets.\r\n\r\n',0,100,0,'2008-06-01 01:18:05'),(903,81,'Rum','<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Adam\">Adam</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Rum & Coke\">Rum & Coke</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Cuba Libre\">Cuba Libre</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"#Bermuda Triangle\">Bermuda Triangle</a></li>\r\n</ul>',0,209,0,'2008-06-08 23:50:08'),(904,81,'Adam','<ul>\r\n<li>2 oz <b>*Dark Rum*</b>\r\n<li>1 oz <b>*fresh lemon juice*</b>\r\n<li>1 tsp <b>*grenadine syrup*</b>\r\n<li>Shake with <b>*Ice*</b> and pour\r\n</ul>',903,10,0,'2008-06-08 22:05:53'),(905,81,'Rum & Coke','<ul>\r\n<li>Into a tall glass full of <b>*ice cubes*</b> pour\r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>*Dark Rum*</b>\r\n<li>fill with <b>*Coke*</b> \r\n<li>Stir.\r\n</ul>',903,20,0,'2008-06-08 22:32:35'),(906,81,'Bermuda Triangle','<ul>\r\n<li>Into a tall glass full of <b>*ice cubes*</b> pour\r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>*Dark Rum*</b>\r\n<li>2 oz <b>*Cranberry juice*</b>\r\n<li>2 oz <b>*Orange juice*</b> \r\n\r\n<li>Stir.\r\n</ul>\r\n',903,30,0,'2008-06-08 23:53:03'),(907,81,'Cuba Libre','<ul>\r\n<li>Into a tall glass full of <b>*ice cubes*</b> pour\r\n<li>1.5 oz <b>*Dark Rum*</b>\r\n<li>1 oz <b>*Lime Juice*</b>\r\n<li>fill with <b>*Coke*</b> \r\n<li>Stir.\r\n</ul>',903,40,0,'2008-06-08 23:52:28'),(908,86,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-06-29 16:43:41'),(909,86,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-06-29 16:43:41'),(910,86,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-06-29 16:43:41'),(911,86,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-06-29 16:43:41'),(912,86,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-06-29 16:43:41'),(913,86,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-06-29 16:43:41'),(917,81,'Sake Bomb','<a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/sake.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.menconi.com/bman/drinkpix/sake.jpg\" height=\"100\"></a>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Place <b>*beer stein*</b> on bar in plain sight & within reach of patron\r\n<li>Fill  stein 1/2 full of <b>*Beer*</b>\r\n<li>Ceremoniously place 2 <b>*chopsticks*</b> parallel to each other across the mouth of the stein \r\n<li>Place a <b>*sake cup*</b> on the chopsticks\r\n<li>Fill cup with <b>*sake*</b>\r\n<li>Patron is expected to pull the two chopsticks apart so that the sake drops into the stein and then chug the beer-sake combo\r\n</ul>\r\n',878,40,0,'2008-07-30 05:38:31'),(918,87,'Introduction','The Marching Bar is a group of people who carry a disassembled bar (and drinks and ice and so forth) around Burning Man and, on command, build the bar and start serving drinks. Another command and the bar is packed up and away they go to the next camp. \r\n<P>This manual is to be used by Golden Cafe members who wish to participate in the \"Marching Bar\" project. It provides a description of the actions that must be performed to have the marching bar work as well as tips and pointers for each person in the marching bar. ',0,10,0,'2008-08-14 21:53:51'),(919,87,'Actions','The sergeant will give commands which will cause people to do actions. In all cases the sergeant will start the command with a  \"preparatory command\" or \"ready command\". The command will always take the same form: \"Golden Cafe Ready!\" This gives the members of the bar a few seconds to pay attention. This is followed by a command which always takes 3 beats. The first two beats are the command and the third beat is the beat on which it should be executed. The first beat should always start just as everyone\'s left foot is moving so that the 3rd beat (the execution point) should happen when the left foot is moving again. \r\n<P>For example, for the command \"Right Turn March\", the word \"Right\" should come as the left foot moves, the word \"turn\" should come as the right foot is moving and the word \"March\" -- which is the point at which the command should be executed -- should come just as we move the left foot a second time. \r\n<P> In the following definitions, only the last 3 beats are given; just remember that you have to say the preparatory command first or only some people will follow the order. In many cases the commands are too short to last three beats if spoken naturally; in these cases the first word is stretch out for two beats. In all cases the last word is spoken in one beat (even if it has two syllables).\r\n<dl>\r\n<dt><b>Company Rally</b> <DD > Come out of the bar and get ready. Since this will never be issued while marching it can violate the \"three beat rule\" for well formed orders. </dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>To Arms</b> <DD > Pick up your stuff and strap it on. Once again, this need not be in 3 syllables since it will never be done while marching. </dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Dress Files Dress</b><dd>Line yourself up on the person in front of you. The people in the first rank (first row) should hold their arms out so that their fingers just touch. This command should be given when the company is forming up but may also be given during marching to dress the lines up. In the latter case, it\'s unlikely that people will extend their arms. </dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Dress Ranks Dress</b><dd>Line yourself up on the person to your right. If the company is stationary, the right hand file (everyone on the right side) should turn to their left and extend their arms so that the proper distance can be determined. Then everyone else should face to the left and line themselves up on the person to their right. While marching this would be much less formal but no less important.</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Form Column</b> <DD >form up into a column in front of the sergeant</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Forward March</b> <DD >start marching forward, in column </dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Left Turn March</b> <DD >turn left  </dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Right Turn March</b> <DD >turn right </dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Halt Right Now</b> <DD > Stop</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Double Time</b> <DD > march faster</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Form Bars</b> <DD > Put together the bars</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>break down bars</b> <DD > take bars apart</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Dismissed</b> <DD > Go off and play (but don\'t go far)</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Spin March</b> <DD > turn in place while walking</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Left face</b> <DD >  the command to turn the band 90 degrees to the left while stopped.</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>Right face</b> <DD >  the command to turn the band 90 degrees to the right while stopped.</dfn></dt>\r\n<BR><dt><b>About face</b> <DD >  the command to turn the band 180 degrees to the rear while stopped.</dfn></dt>\r\n<br><dt><b>Make Aisle</b> <dd> when stopped, the middle row steps to the right (between the right file members) so that people can move up or back</dfn></dt>\r\n<br><dt><b>Front To Back</b><dd>Once there is an aisle, the people who belong in the front (sergeant, shield bearers, goldie carriers) move down the aisle to the back. </dfn></dt>\r\n<br><dt><b>Back To Front</b><dd>Once there is an aisle, the people who belong in the back (all the carriers) move to the front. \r\n</dl>\r\n<br><dt><b>Eyes Right</b><dd>Turn your head to the right while walking along</dfn></dt>\r\n<br><dt><b>Eyes Left</b><dd>Turn your head to the left while walking along</dfn></dt>\r\n<br><dt><b>Sal-ute!</b><dd>Give the Gold Cafe Salute (whatever that might be) in the direction your head is facing</dfn></dt>\r\n<br><dt><b>Eyes Front</b><dd>Turn your head to the front </dfn></dt>',0,20,0,'2008-08-21 03:22:03'),(920,87,'Equipment list','<ul>\r\n<li>6 shields\r\n<li>coolers\r\n<li>goldie\r\n<li>bucket of grog\r\n<li>misc. bar tools\r\n<li>Booze carrier (some kind of strap)\r\n<li>glasses carrier\r\n</ul>',0,30,0,'2008-08-12 19:46:32'),(921,87,'Roles','<ul>\r\n<li>sergeant -- leads every aspect\r\n<li>Bartender (2) -- tends the bar\r\n<li>Shield bearer (6) -- carries the bar\r\n<li>Goldie Bearer (2-4)-- Carries Goldie\r\n<li>Cooler Carrier (2-4) -- Carries coolers\r\n<Li>Booze Carrier (?) -- carries booze\r\n<li> Drummer -- keeps beat\r\n<li>Other carrier -- carries something else\r\n<li>Marcher -- everyone is a marcher but some people are nothing else\r\n</ul>',0,40,0,'2008-08-14 22:07:17'),(922,87,'Sequence of Bar Construction','The sequence of construction of the bar is very consistent. The sergeant calls out a series of commands and based on these commands, people run up and add to the bar until it\'s ready. \r\n<ol>\r\n<li> sergeant stops march (halt)\r\n<li>Sergeant calls \"make aisle\" -- the middle file moves to the right\r\n<li>sergeant calls for bar build (Form Bars) -- it will be build right in front of him -- and people get ready\r\n<li>sergeant calls for \"First Base\" and 2 SPECIFIC shield bearers (the first and second rank right most) kneel at his feet\r\n<li>sergeant calls for \"Second Base\" again 2 more add their pieces (the middle two)\r\n<li>sergeant calls \"Top\" and get the tops of the bars -- specific people among the 3 marchers have mallets and do what needs to be done\r\n<li>sergeant calls for \"Coolers\" and the coolers are brought up\r\n<li> sergeant calls for booze and glasses and anything else that\'s needed\r\n<li>sergeant calls for bartenders\r\n<li>sergeant calls \"begin boozing\" to indicate the bar is open and steps out of the way\r\n<li> sergeant calls \"dismissed\" and everyone but the bartenders wanders off\r\n</ol>\r\n',0,50,0,'2008-08-14 22:07:17'),(924,87,'Marching','Here are some important pointers for marchers (and everyone is a marcher in the end). \r\n<ul>\r\n<LI> Always lead with your left foot. Your left foot should hit the ground every time the drummer beats.\r\n<li>If you belong to the marching bar, always be ready for the sergeant or commander to call you up. \r\n<li>Pay attention to the sergeant\'s commands. If everyone stops but you it messes everything up.\r\n<li>Follow the guy in front of you and keep up with the guy to your right. \r\n<LI>During a turn, watch where the person in front of you turns and try to turn at EXACTLY that point.\r\n<li>During a turn, try to maintain spacing. \r\n<li>After a turn, dress the line by lining up on the guy ahead of you and the guy to your right.\r\n</ul>',0,60,0,'2008-08-14 22:07:17'),(925,87,'Sergeant ','The sergeant walks two steps in front of the column. He is responsible for issuing all the commands. He must have a loud voice to carry to the back. \r\n',921,20,0,'2008-08-14 22:07:17'),(926,87,'Shield bearer','The shield bearers form the first two ranks (rows) of the troop. Since there are 6 shield bearers, that would mean that the column is 3 files wide (that is, 3 abreast). \r\n<P>Where the shield bearers are in this little group of 6 determines their specific role. The person on the far right is the person everyone will key on to line up. He should always rally to the right of the sergeant. Furthermore, he is the \"first base\" for the right most bar. The person to his left (middle shield, first rank) is \"second base\" for the right bar. The person to HIS left is the \"Top\" for the right bar. The shield bearers behind them have the same roles for the LEFT bar. \r\n<P>The bar is constructed in front of the sergeant in such a way that he would be it\'s first customer. If he is facing the column then the back of the bar will be to the column. If he turns his back on the column then the shield bearers run around to his front and build the bar there. In this way, he defines where and in what direction the bar is built. The two bars are always build to his left and right as the shield bearer face him. So the \"right bar\" is on his left (but is to the \"right\" of him) and the left bar is on his right (but is to the left of him). Just remember that it\'s YOUR right -- the shield bearer\'s right -- that counts, not the sergeant\'s!\r\nThe left and right bars are constructed simultaneously in this order. \r\n<oL>\r\n<li>First Base -- place his piece down first\r\n<li>Second Base -- place his piece onto the first piece and secure it into position. The first and second base shield bearers now step out of the way\r\n<li>Top -- place his piece on top of the base and secure it into position. \r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nOnce the top is placed the shield bearers should stand in a line while the rest of the work is done on the bar. When they are dismissed, they should go mingle with everyone else, but please don\'t wander off or we may not get our bar home!',921,50,0,'2008-08-14 22:07:17'),(927,87,'Goldie Bearer','There will be two Goldie Bearers who will carry our golden calf on a platform. They will be immediately behind the sergeant and will simply follow him around. They aren\'t really part of troop per se since their main goal is to simply not drop the fucking idol (too many times). \r\n<P>Most commands don\'t affect the goldie bearers since they just follow the sergeant. But when it\'s time to set up the bar they must move smartly out of the way. They should hold the Golden Calf between them until the bar is complete then they should set the calf down next to the bar when they are dismissed. When they are dismissed, they should go mingle with everyone else, but please don\'t wander off or we may not get our bar home!',921,40,0,'2008-08-14 01:47:21'),(928,87,'Carrier','In addition to marching, carriers must (wait for it) carry stuff. Sometimes by themselves and sometimes with someone else. There are three keys to carrying stuff. First, when the sergeant calls for it, you need to rush up to the front with it. Hopefully the guys in front of you have made a space for you to get to the front without walking around. \r\n<P>Second, you really should keep with the Marching Bar until you get back to the Golden Cafe or they may not be ABLE to get to the Golden Cafe. At least find someone to take your place. If you really have to bug out, make sure you tell the sergeant. \r\n<P>Third, if you are carrying something with someone else, you need to keep in step. It\'s best if you can carry it front to back in which case the guy in front leads and the guy behind stays in step with him. If that\'s just too hard then the guy on the right is the lead and the guy on the left has to try to stay in step. \r\n<P>When building the bar, they will be called up after the basic bar is constructed. Place whatever they have on or in the bar and then step to the side and wait until dismissed. ',921,60,0,'2008-08-14 22:07:17'),(929,87,'Bartender ','The bartenders are really just marchers (or carriers) until the bar is built. Then they move up and take their place to tend the bar. When everyone else is dismissed the sergeant will step away from the front of the bar and they can begin serving patrons. ',921,70,0,'2008-08-14 01:47:21'),(930,87,'Marcher ','See marching for pointers on how to march. In addition, if you are not carrying anything, you want to step to the side and wait patiently while the bar is being set up. Stay in formation, just take a step to the right (if you\'re on the right) or the left (if you\'re on the left) so that a space forms running down the middle of the column. \r\n<P>In just a few minutes the sergeant will order the formation dispersed and you should then go and meet the people in this camp, get a drink, and generally hang out. But listen for the call to get back together. \r\n',921,80,0,'2008-08-14 01:47:21'),(932,87,'Drummer','The drummer beats the marching rhythm. He stands to the left of the sergeant so the sergeant can tell him to slow down or speed up or whatever. In all probability he will carry a few pieces of pipe or some wooden dowels rather than a drum. He should beat on every left step. Thus, whatever beats per minute he does it will be exactly half the number of steps per minute. He may also lead the column in a timing call, for example \"left, right, left\" or perhaps something a little more interesting. Consistency is the only requirement -- he must hit the mark with ever single LEFT and keep the same time. \r\n<P>When the column stops to build the bar, the drummer should move over to the side out of the way with the goldie carriers. When dismissed, he can leave his instrument by the bar. ',921,30,0,'2008-08-14 01:58:16'),(945,89,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-11-23 17:12:02'),(937,87,'Spin','In a spin each individual member in the column turns in place without missing a step. People who are carrying stuff together (the goldie carriers and the cooler carriers, for example) do not do this. ',936,10,0,'2008-08-14 21:50:40'),(939,88,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-10-20 06:02:35'),(940,88,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-10-20 06:02:35'),(941,88,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-10-20 06:02:35'),(942,88,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-10-20 06:02:35'),(943,88,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-10-20 06:02:35'),(944,88,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-10-20 06:02:35'),(934,87,'Turning Left or Right','When turning it can get a bit complicated. First off, the sergeant must be careful not to issue the turn command before the front rank has cleared the corner nor after he himself has cleared the middle of the intersection. Furthermore, the people on the outside of the turn have to move farther than the people on the inside of the turn so they have to move faster. \r\n<P>REMEMBER: follow the person in front of you, stop when he stops, go fast when he goes fast and all will be well. \r\n<P>After the command each person will walk slower or faster depending on whether they are on the <i>turn</i> side (the side to which we\'re turning) or not. The person on the turn side turns and then marches in place (called \"marking time\"). The person in the middle takes two steps and turns, marches up to where the person on the turn side has stopped and marches in place. The person on the non-turn side, takes 4 steps and turns and then marches forward. When he gets to where the other two people in this rank are, they all start marching forward together. \r\n<P>In the second and subsequent ranks it\'s pretty much the same story except that people on the turn side have to be careful not to crowd the people in front of them and people on the outside have to be sure to pick up the pace to catch their leaders. \r\n<P> Once the turn has been negotiated the ranks and files should square themselves up with the leaders. Everyone should get behind the person in front and even with the person to the right.  \r\n<P> One final note, in a real marching band (or column of soldiers) everyone trains to have the right stride length and the correct spacing and so a specific number of beats of standing still will always be the right amount. We don\'t have that luxury so we simply have to pay attention and try not to trip over each other. ',0,100,0,'2008-08-14 22:07:17'),(936,87,'Tricks','Assuming we can master turning without dropping anything, there are two tricks we can do: Spin and Salute. ',0,120,0,'2008-08-14 21:46:09'),(935,87,'Turning Arround','You can\'t just do an about face and march on because the column will be in the wrong order. The sequence for turning around is this: \r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Sergeant calls \"halt\" -- everyone stops\r\n<li>Sergeant calls \"make aisle\" -- the middle file moves to the right\r\n<li>Sergeant calls \"front to back\" -- sergeant, drummer, goldie carriers and shield bearers move smartly to the back\r\n<li>Sergeant calls \"back to front\" -- all the carriers in the back move to the front\r\n<li>sergeant calls \"about face\" -- everyone turns around in place\r\n<li>Sergeant calls \"dress rank, dress file\" -- we reform in 3 files\r\n<li>We start marching in the opposite direction\r\n</ol>',0,110,0,'2008-08-14 21:32:05'),(938,87,'Salute','The sergeant calls out \"eyes right\" or \"eyes left\" and everyone turns their head in that direction.\r\n<P>Then the sergeant calls out \"salute\" and everyone does some kind of salute. Everyone does exactly the same kind of salute but it\'s probably not the salute where you hold your hand to the forehead. \r\n<P>Then the sergeant calls out eyes front and everyone faces front. ',936,20,0,'2008-08-14 21:50:40'),(946,89,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-11-23 17:12:02'),(947,89,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-11-23 17:12:02'),(948,89,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-11-23 17:12:02'),(949,89,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-11-23 17:12:02'),(950,89,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-11-23 17:12:02'),(951,81,'Thanks Getting','<ul>\r\n<li>Put 2 cups of <b>*ice*</b> in a <b>*blender*</b>\r\n<li>Crush ice until there are no big chunks\r\n<li>add 1 cup of <b>*Frangelico*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 cup of <b>*Half and Half*</b>\r\n<li>Add 1 cup of <b>*Creme de Cacao*</b>\r\n<li>Liquefy contents until creamy smooth\r\n<li>Serve into 8 glasses \r\n\r\n</ul>',878,50,0,'2008-11-26 05:01:59'),(952,90,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2008-12-31 20:59:12'),(953,90,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2008-12-31 20:59:12'),(954,90,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2008-12-31 20:59:12'),(955,90,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2008-12-31 20:59:12'),(956,90,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2008-12-31 20:59:12'),(957,90,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2008-12-31 20:59:12'),(958,91,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2009-02-27 18:20:04'),(959,91,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2009-02-27 18:20:04'),(960,91,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2009-02-27 18:20:04'),(961,91,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2009-02-27 18:20:04'),(962,91,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2009-02-27 18:20:04'),(963,91,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2009-02-27 18:20:04'),(964,92,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2009-03-14 07:14:12'),(965,92,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2009-03-14 07:14:12'),(966,92,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2009-03-14 07:14:12'),(967,92,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2009-03-14 07:14:12'),(968,92,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2009-03-14 07:14:12'),(969,92,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2009-03-14 07:14:12'),(970,93,'Introduction',NULL,0,10,0,'2009-03-28 16:06:42'),(971,93,'Definitions',NULL,0,20,0,'2009-03-28 16:06:42'),(972,93,'Database Design',NULL,0,30,0,'2009-03-28 16:06:42'),(973,93,'Technical Design Notes',NULL,0,40,0,'2009-03-28 16:06:42'),(974,93,'Issues',NULL,0,50,0,'2009-03-28 16:06:42'),(975,93,'Future Enhancements',NULL,0,60,0,'2009-03-28 16:06:42'),(976,15,'Commdities','<P>Every commodity has a multiplier associated with it. The multipliers will be the first 100 prime numbers (starting with 1).\r\n\r\n<P>Now you roll 2 6 sided dice. For the sell price, subtract 1. For the buy price, add one. That\'s the \"base value\". Now multiply the multiplier to the base value to get the actual price.When you\'ve done that for all 50 cities and all 600 markets (6 buy markets plus 6 sell markets in each city) you\'ve initialized the game.\r\n\r\n<P>Now, to update this you need to have a storage bin called \"number of transactions\". Prices only change at the end of the turn (after everyone has bought or sold) based on the number of transactions. For slots that buy things, the price changes one step down for every 10 transaction. If there is no transaction we decrement the transaction count and if it goes negative then the price goes up. If the \"base value\" drops below 1 then we reinitialize this commodity according to the algorithm above, being careful not to match any of the commodities that are selling.\r\n\r\n<P>For selling the exact same algorithm applies but in reverse: prices step up for every 10 transactions and  the transaction count goes down for no transaction. If the base value goes above some threshhold (12, say) then we reinitialize the commodity.\r\n\r\n',0,60,0,'2009-05-22 20:52:35'),(977,15,'Turn Sequence','<P>As with all multiplayer games, the system collects orders from the players, figures out whether the orders are valid, generates errors, and so forth. At a specific, predetermined deadline (usually every day or every week but it could be several times a day) the turn is run. \r\n\r\n<P>The turn consists of the following steps\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Generate missing orders (for players that didn\'t submit orders or submitted incomplete orders)\r\n<li>Process special orders, if any (moving through gateways, deploying spies, etc)\r\n<li>Buy/sell Commodities\r\n<li>Move\r\n<li>Update quantities, prices and other game mechanic factors, update transaction counts and then reset \"active\" flags\r\n<li>Set up game to accept turn input \r\n<li>Send email notifications (if any)\r\n</ol>\r\n<P>The game never ends. Players join and get their starting money and ship, players quit, players move through the gateway but the game keeps going on and on. ',0,30,0,'2009-05-22 23:25:13'),(978,94,'Introduction','<P>The invoice tracker is a php web-based program to track invoices and bpafs. ',0,10,0,'2009-05-29 23:31:54'),(979,94,'Definitions','',0,20,0,'2009-05-29 23:31:22'),(980,94,'Database Design','<pre>\r\n+------------------------+\r\n| Tables_in_invoicetrack |\r\n+------------------------+\r\n| actions                |\r\n| italarm                |\r\n| itattorney             |\r\n| itbpaf                 |\r\n| itbpafhist             |\r\n| itbudget               |\r\n| itcompany              |\r\n| itinvoice              |\r\n| itlineitem             |\r\n| itmanager              |\r\n| itproject              |\r\n| itprojectauth          |\r\n| itrefnumreserve        |\r\n| itstatus               |\r\n| permission             |\r\n| profile                |\r\n| sysdbupdate            |\r\n| sysinfo                |\r\n| sysversion             |\r\n| user                   |\r\n+------------------------+\r\n+-------------+------------------+------+-----+-------------------+----------------+\r\n| Field       | Type             | Null | Key | Default           | Extra          |\r\n+-------------+------------------+------+-----+-------------------+----------------+\r\n| actionid    | int(10) unsigned | NO   | PRI | NULL              | auto_increment |\r\n| actionURL   | varchar(20)      | NO   | UNI |                   |                |\r\n| description | varchar(45)      | NO   |     |                   |                |\r\n| ts          | timestamp        | NO   |     | CURRENT_TIMESTAMP |                |\r\n+-------------+------------------+------+-----+-------------------+----------------+\r\n4 rows in set (0.00 sec)\r\n\r\nmysql> des