nknown',0,'',49,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(54,'Safari Jack','',57,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',54,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(53,'Carcassonne','Rio Grande / Hans im Gluc',30,'City Building','Tile','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Klaus-Jurgen Wrede',53,269,'<I>Carcassonne</I> is a very nice game visually. Players place tiles that have roads,and bits of wall on them to divide up the space. Players all place their markers in the paces to claim the pasces. At the end, points are counted up and the player with the most wins. <P>I personally do not care for this ame but its a very popular game. ','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=822\">Game Geeks Comments</a>',2,5,5,NULL,1,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(72,'Munchkin Fu','',57,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Keith',0,'',72,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(56,'Janus','',20,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',56,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(57,'6Nimt','',45,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',57,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(58,'Clue','',90,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',NULL,NULL,'<P>The basic idea behind <I>Clue</I> (stop me if you\'ve heard this one) is that a murder has been committed in the mansion and you need to work out who did it, what room it was done in and what weapon was used. There is a set of cards that has a card for each room, one for each person and one for each weapon. At the start the cards are separated into the three sets and one from each set is put in a little envelope -- that\'s the right answer. Now all the remaining cards are shuffled together and dealt out to the players. Every turn a payer in a room can make a guess and anyone who can disprove it (by having a card from the accusation) must do so. Now it\'s a question of who can test all the possibilities most efficiently and come up with the right answer first. When someone think they are right, they check the cards and, if so, they win; otherwise they lose. .<P>If you don\'t know the game you should get a copy. It really is a very famous and popular game. I believe its one of the most interesting games my family played. ','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.menconi.com/games/gm353.html\">Simpson Clue</a><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=1294\">Game Geeks Comments</a>',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(59,'Grave Robbers','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',59,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(60,'Kahuna','',57,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',60,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(61,'Summit','',57,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1961,'',336,383,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(62,'Mafia','',30,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',62,0,'','',8,30,15,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(63,'Uno Stacko','',20,'','','',7,'',5,'Mike',0,'Scott Peterson',63,0,'<P>The basic idea of  <i>Privateer</i> as in it\'s previous version <i>Pirateer</i> is to acquire the purse which is on an island in the middle of the board. You have 3 ships with which to do this. For your turn you roll two dice and move your ships on the grid of the board. You can move two ships using one die for each or you may move one ship and use both dice in which case each die must carry the ship in a straight line. <P>You get the purse by manuevering a ship next to the island and moving the purse (a small metal coin) onto your ship. Now you must get it home by moving to the last square of your harbor. Naturally everyone is going to be after you and the ship with the coin has a movement restriction: it can move toward or parellel to it\'s harbor but it can\'t move backwards. Often the best way to get the purse is to take all the other ships which you do by landing on them by exact count. <P>This is a second edition game with the the original canvas board and three color tokens and the later flatter purse (as distinct from the synthetic white board, the 2 color tokens which came later and the more domed purse which was earlier.<P>The cloth board to this game is signed by the designer, Scott Peterson.','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(71,'RoboRally','Wizards of the Coast',120,'Science Fiction','Programmed Movement','Thinky',4,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',161,41,'','',2,8,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(65,'The WORKS','',30,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'',0,'',65,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(66,'Coloretto','',15,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',66,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(67,'Princes of Florence','',57,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',67,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(68,'Ghettopoly','',60,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',68,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(70,'Constructionary','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',70,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(73,'Cube Farm','',30,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',73,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(74,'Guillotine','Wizards of the Coast',30,'French Revolution','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',1998,'	Paul Peterson',74,0,'As executioners pandering to the masses, the players are trying to behead the least popular nobles. Each day the nobles are lined up and players take turns killing the ones at the front of the line until all the nobles are gone. However, players are given cards which will manipulate the line order right before \'harvesting,\' which is what makes the game interesting.','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/game/116',2,5,4,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(75,'Illuminati','',120,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'Anthony E. Pratt',264,285,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(251,'Guess Who','Milton Bradley',20,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',1987,'Theo Coster,Ora Coster',NULL,NULL,'<P>Each player has a character that the other player is trying to guess. Each player also has a board with each of the possible charaters on a little tile than flips down. Players take turns asking questions like \"does your character have a hat\" and then flipping down the pictures that don\'t match the answer. The first player to guess the other character wins.','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(76,'Snit Smashing','',57,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',76,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(77,'Zombies','',57,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',77,0,'<P>This is a solo game involving clearing the evil zombies from the city. It\'s not the most sophisticated game you\'ve ever played but it\'s a heck of a lot of fun! It\'s sort of like a board game version of Doom!<P>It\'s the year 2032. A warp has opened up in the old Municipal Buildings in the heart of old Manhattan and bizarre creatures are flooding through into our dimension. Goading them on is Darkness, a malevolent entity who intends dragging the city of New York back through the warp -- destroying it utterly!','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(78,'Klunker','',57,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',78,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(79,'Witch Trials','',57,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',293,329,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(80,'Unexploded Cows','',57,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',80,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(81,'Pounce!','',57,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',81,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(82,'Ill Tempered Squires','',57,'','','',7,'',5,'Scott',0,'',82,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(91,'Crown Jewels of India','',45,'','','',7,'',5,'Peterson',0,'',91,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(92,'Aquarius','',20,'Hippyism','Card Matching','Easy',2,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',92,263,'','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/game/814',2,5,5,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(93,'Vampire Hunter','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Mike',0,'Andreas Seyfarth',93,0,'<P><I>Puerto Rico</I> Board game by Rio Grande Games.The basic idea of the game is that you grow/process commodities, sell them to make money so that you can buy building and grow more commodities. But you don\'t make win from the commodities or from the money -- you get victory points for (among other things) shipping your commodities to the old world. <P> NOw comes the interesting part. During your turn you may pick any one of the \"jobs\" that haven\'t been used in this round. These \"jobs\" form the basic activities of the game. You can create commodities, sell commodities, build production facilities and other buildings, sehip things to the new world. settle more acreage or get more colonies. The trick is that all thoe other players get to do the same actvities in the turn as well.  so you want to pick the thing that will benefit you the nost and your opponents the least. <P> This is one of my favorite games at the moment even tho I don\'t think I know how to win at it yet.<P>Dimensions of the game: 13 inches x 9 inches x 3 inches','<h3>Other Interesting Links </h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=3076\">Board Geeks Comments</a>',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(94,'Finster Flur','',60,'','','',7,'',5,'Adony',0,'',94,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(95,'Manhattan','',45,'','','',7,'',2,'Dave',0,'',95,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:40:42'),(96,'Privateer','Mendocino Game Company',15,'Pirates','','Easy',2,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',299,339,'','',2,4,4,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(98,'Power Grid','Rio Grande Games',120,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',2004,' Friedemann Friese',98,0,'The players manage power companies in Europe (or the US or the far east) by building into cities and buying powerplants and fuel to provide power to those cities. ','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/2651',2,6,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(99,'Acquire','Avalon Hill / 3M',90,'Money','Buy & Sell','Moderate',3,'Keep',2,'Dave',1968,'Sid Sackson',99,11,'<P><I>Acquire</I> is a economic game in which you try to make money from buying and selling stock in hotel chains Every turn you get to place one tile and buy 3 shares of stock in any active company. When you place your tile next to an existing tile an hotel chain is formed in which players can now buy shares of stock. The fun starts when the tile you place connects two (or more) existing chains. The top owners in the smaller change get bonuses and all owners get sell their stock or trade it for stock in the big hotel. <P>The trick, then is to be the first or second stock holder in a chain that\'s being acquired during the game (so you don\'t run out of money) AND to be the first or second stock holder in the big chains at the end of the game.<P>This is one of my favorite games and is probably the most famous and popular of the 3M games, being release several times by 3M and then Avalon Hill and finally by, I think, Hasbro. The Avalon Hill version wasn\'t very high quality -- the printing on the tiles of my copy was off center. The newest version has 3 dimensional plastic hotels which looks cool but doesn\'t really add much to the game, IMHO.','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/game/5',2,6,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(100,'Golem','',60,'Other','Card','Brainless',1,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',215,131,'','',2,6,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(101,'Group Photo','',15,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'Klaus-Jurgen Wrede',101,0,'<I>Carcassonne</I> is a very nice game visually. Players place tiles that have roads,and bits of wall on them to divide up the space. Players all place their markers in the paces to claim the pasces. At the end, points are counted up and the player with the most wins. <P>I personally don\'t care for this ame but its a very popular game. ','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=822\">Game Geeks Comments</a>',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(102,'Haunting House, The','',45,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',102,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,5,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(103,'Saboteur','Amigo Spiele',30,'Tunnelling','Card','Moderate',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',2004,'Frederic Moyersoen',103,0,'Each player has a hidden role as either a dwarf or a saboteur. The Dwarves are trying to get the gold; the saboteurs are trying to prevent them. Whichever side wins gets gold the people with the most gold after three rounds wins.','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/game/9220',3,10,8,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(104,'Dork Frag','',60,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',104,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(105,'NeroMundo','',57,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',105,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(106,'Scene It?','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'Urs Hostettler',106,0,'<P>In this 1988 Avalon Hill game the players will secretly note which Soviet politicians they wish to control. During the game these characters are given jobs in the cold war Soviet Politburo. Each job has certain powers and the player who controls the character in that job may exercise those powers. The most important power is the power of the Party Chief to wave at the annual parade. (There\'s a joke here: for years during the cold war we in the west only knew who the Party Chief of the Soviet Union was because he would be the one to wave at the annual parade.) The player who controls the Party Chief through 3 waves (not necessarily the same Party Chief or even consecutively) wins.<P>This is a pretty deep game. Although a lot of the strategy comes in with the choosing of the characters at the start of the game, the timing of revealing your influence -- waiting until your opponents have fought to bring a character you secretly control to a place of power, for example.<P>The game is fairly complicated (the involved sequence of events is explained very well in the rules but it\'s still involved) and the players must commit themselves to a course of action right at the start of the game. This means that first time players are really on the spot and are probably going to lose. Of course, by the second game they are on an even footing with the best of them.','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=196\"> Game Geek Comments </a>',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(107,'Lunch Money','',20,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',107,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(108,'Just Desserts','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',108,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(109,'Chinese Checkers','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',109,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(110,'Dora The Explorer','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'Designer  *',110,0,'description','url * ',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(111,'Condottiere','EuroGames',60,'Wargame','Strategic Sim','Thinky',4,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',193,93,'','',3,6,4,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(347,'Bucaneer','',0,'','','',NULL,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',NULL,NULL,'','',0,0,0,NULL,7,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(113,'Dominoes','',30,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',113,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(114,'Fretters','',90,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',114,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(115,'DB Needs Ham','',30,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',258,274,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(116,'OK Corral','Discovery Games',15,'Western','Card','Brainless',1,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',155,32,'','',2,10,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(117,'Wizard\'s Quest','Avalon Hill',180,'Fantasy','Strategic Sim','Moderate',3,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',135,4,'','',2,6,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 05:25:16'),(118,'Plague & Pestilence','',30,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',118,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(119,'Rummy','',60,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',119,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(120,'Ra','Rio Grande Games',60,'Ancient Egypt','Auction','Moderate',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',1999,'Reiner Knizia',120,0,'Tiles are pulled from the bag until someone starts the bidding on them. Each player may get 3 lots before the round ends but the round can also end early thus setting up tension between drawing lots of tiles and risking having the round end early or grabbing what you can get.','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/game/12',3,5,5,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(121,'Tsuro','Kosmos',15,'Abstract','','Thinky',7,'Keep',0,'Dave',2005,'',121,0,'','',2,8,6,NULL,1,'2010-05-28 05:21:05'),(122,'SW Life','',60,'','','',7,'',5,'Mike',0,'',122,0,'<P>This is a well balanced game. The idea is that you must navigate your river boat down the river, picking up two Southern Belles along the way, and be the first person to dock at the end. The movement rules are fairly simple: you set your speed (movement points) up or down one for free at the beginning of your turn and you can turn one hex side during your move for free. Each additional hex side or movement point change (up or down) costs another coal. You can ram other boats (costs an extra movement point and moves them one square) and you can pick up belles if you pull up to their island going speed 1. <P>The real challenge comes with the way the board is constructed. There are a bunch of large tiles (maybe 6 hexes across) that can fit together straight on, to the left or to the right. The first player to enter a new tile determines the next tile by picking one off the face-down stack and rolling a die to determine the direction.  This means that the leader is always at a huge disadvantage because he is closest to the new river sections -- everyone else can see them from some distance and can adjust their route accordingly -- sometimes saving a lot of time. <P>I can shake the sense that this game is very much like <i>Richtofen\'s War</i> in it\'s movement system. I happen to like RW very much which may be why I like this one. With 6 players we have often had a bit of a puppy pile at the end but, frankly, this just adds to the fun. <P>The game comes with little plastic river boats (pretty cool) and little women in hoop skirts. Some of the boats came missing smoke stacks and some others had them in the bottom of the box. And the designers really didn\'t think it through very well because the women don\'t fit on the boats. They DID add little cardboard placards on which you can set your women but it\'s not idea. Also, each boat has a little hexagonal wheel that has the numbers from 1-6 stuck on it. You adjust these two wheels (one black and one white) to show your movement and coal supply. The problem is that the strips with numbers don\'t stick well so the system is a bit of a nuisance.','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(123,'Loot','',45,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',123,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(124,'Harry Potter Scene It','',90,'','','',7,'',5,'Mike',0,'',124,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(125,'Kill Dr. Lucky','CheapAss Games',90,'Mystery','Other','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',222,138,'','',2,8,6,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(126,'Save Dr. Lucky','',30,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',126,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(127,'Express','Mayfair',20,'Rail Road','Card','Moderate',3,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',164,47,'','',2,6,4,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(129,'Tigris & Euphrates','',90,'','','',7,'',5,'Unknown',0,'',129,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(130,'Star Traders','Steve Jackson Games',120,'Science Fiction','Trading','Moderate',3,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',139,10,'','',2,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(131,'China Moon','',30,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',131,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,6,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(132,'Scrabble','',45,'','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',132,0,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(133,'Ace of Aces','Nova',20,'War Game','Book','Easy',2,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',141,12,', Handy Right Rotary. , Power House ','',2,4,2,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(135,'WizWar','Chessex',60,'Fantasy','Tactical Sim','Easy',2,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',143,14,'','',2,4,4,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(136,'Wings Of War',NULL,45,NULL,NULL,NULL,7,'Keep',2,'Dave',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(137,'My Fish','',20,'','','',7,'',2,'',0,'',NULL,NULL,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,