eal of similarity and it was fairly common for computer games to be designed after board games but I\'ve never talked to him about it. <P>The game has all its pieces and extra copies of the rules and tables. The box shows some wear but the pieces and board look very good.','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://luding.org/Skripte/GameData.py/DEgameid/2120\">Ludwig Game Database (in German)</a><br><a href=\"http://home.comcast.net/~dmitton/18xxover.htm\">The 18xx Overview</a><br>',3,6,3,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(145,'Alibi','Mayfair',60,'Mystery','Card','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',187,81,'<P>Alibi, The Whodunit Card Game, is similar to Clue but more complicated. <P><a href=\"http://www.gamereport.com/tgr5/alibi.html\">Game Report Online Review by Peter Sarrett </a> has a complete description.','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.gamereport.com/tgr5/alibi.html\">Game Report Online Review by Peter Sarrett has a complete description.',3,10,6,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(146,'Amoeba Wars','Avalon Hill',180,'Science Fiction','Grand Strategic Sim','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',156,34,'<P>This is a space conflict game with a very unusual play dynamic.You have cards that are numbered and also have a set of actions that they allow you to do. Every one plays their cards face down and the flips them simultaneously. The lowest numbered card is used first and everyone gets to use that one. Then the next lowest and everyone but the first player uses it. And son on to the last card which is only used by the last player. So why does anyone play a low card? Because the high cards do undesireable things and the low cards do great things. So you usually have a choice of playing a card that won\'t do you much good (and benefiting from everyone else\'s card) or playing a card that\'s great (and sharing it with everyone else).<P>The actual space conflict is also interesting. You have ships which you get from your cards and also from building them based on the number of systems you have. You take system with ships, you get ships from having systems -- it\'s very risk-like. but there are also doomsday machines floating around that have to be beaten. And periodically you have to take on the dreaded space Amoeba which have infested this part of the galaxy.<P>Ultimately you win by controlling the central solar systems and retaking Saestor at the center of the board. <P>All in all it\'s a pretty cool game.','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=982\">Game Geek\'s Notes</a>',2,6,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(147,'Apples To Apples','Pegasus Spiele',30,'Language','Card','Brainless',1,'Keep',2,'Dave',1999,'Mark Alan Osterhaus, Matthew K',236,242,'Apples to Apples consists only of two decks of cards: Things and Descriptions. Each turn, the current referee selects a Description and players try to pick, from the cards in their hands, the Things that best match that Description. The referee then chooses the Thing that appeals most and awards the card to the player who played it. The unusual combinations of Things and Descriptions are humorous to the extreme, and will quickly have the entire room in an uproar. Once a player has won a pre-determined number of cards, that player wins.','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/game/74',3,10,8,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(150,'BattleTech','FASA',180,'War Game','Tactical Sim','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',184,78,'','',2,0,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(253,'Guess Where?','Milton Bradley',15,'Deduction','Children','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',2004,'',NULL,NULL,'','http://www.boardgamegeeks.com/game/13951',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(254,'Mystic Wood','Avalon Hill',60,'Fantasy','','',7,'Keep',2,'Dave',1980,'Terence Peter Donnelly',NULL,NULL,'<P>Players are knights exploring the Mystic Wood. On you turn you move to an adjacent tile and flip it over to reveal what kind of space it is. Then you (usually) draw a card and encounter whatever is on that card. <P>Each knight has a different goal and beating things increases your ability. ','',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(256,'Battleground','Your Move Games',60,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',NULL,NULL,'','',2,4,2,NULL,1,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(257,'PitchCar','',30,'Racing','Physical','',7,'',5,'Adony',0,'',NULL,NULL,'','',2,8,8,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(258,'Through the Desert','',45,'','','',7,'',5,'Adony',0,'',NULL,NULL,'','',2,5,5,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(153,'Blood Royale','Games Workshop',400,'War Game','Grand Strategic Sim','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',179,72,'<P>This is an very high quality game (with a mounted map, plastic tokens and pieces and various cards and markers) that simulates royal families over several generations. You are the head of powerful Dynasty, ruler of one of the great Kingdoms of Europe. Ranged against you are equally powerful monarchs, with the same aims -- conquest, trade and a secure Dynasty. You will arrange marriages for your children, to make alliances and secure deals. You will tax the people of your Kingdom, control their trade and find your financial fortunes ebbing and flowing as events take their toll. And you will fight wars against your enemies to protect your homeland and to take theirs.<P>This is, in part, a role-playing game, a board game, a simulation and a wargame.  It\'s a very detailed game an may take a very long time to play -- which is a good point if you like the game play. ','',3,5,5,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(154,'Boggle','Parker Brothers',10,'Words','Word','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1976,'',342,389,'<P>The idea of this game is that you shake up the 16 letter cubes and then randomly arrange them in a 4x4 tray. Then you flip over the timer and players compete to see who can come up with the most words based on the letters showing. Quick and fun!<P>','<P><a src=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=1293\">Board Game Geek Description</a>',2,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(155,'Broadside','Milton Bradley',45,'War Game','Strategic Sim','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1962,'',163,43,'<P><I>Broadside</I> is an American Heritage game of the War of 1812.The game is relatively simple as wargames go but is more complicated than most family-type board games. We tried this a few times and found it to be pretty good and, of course, the little plastic ship figures are very cool! A good description can be found at <a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=1508\">Game Geek Review</a>. This is a fairly rare and collectible game. They just don\'t make them like this anymore!<P>The box shows some wear but has solid corners and is in much better shape than you would expect for a 40 year old game.','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(156,'Careers','Parker Brothers',60,'Other','Other','Easy',2,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',200,102,'<P>Players determine and write down a secret \"success\" formula career objective, and the first to achieve his/her formula wins. The basic game play is to move around the board (like <i>Monopoly</i>) and when you land on a career space you can pursue that career by entering a track through the middle of the board. Along the way good and bad things will happen. In the end you will have collected some money, some fame and some happiness. Different careers provide different combinations of these things. When you have collected enough to satisfy your formula you win.<P>Game box measures 18 1/4 X 9 1/4 X 1 1/2 inches. Game board measures 17 3/4 X 17 3/4 inches. Box dated 1955; instructions dated 1958.<P>This game has had a rough life. The box has been extensively reinforced by masking tape (not your first choice for this, I can assure you) and is pretty weak even so. The board is in very good condition but it\'s a bit dingy. All the pieces are here but the little tablets were once the nifty sort that you could write on with a stylus and then pull up the cover and that stopped working. We photocopied the form and so there are a bunch of use-once paper pads instead. ','',2,6,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:40:42'),(157,'Chainsaw Warrior','Games Workshop',60,'Science Fiction','Tactical Sim','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',182,75,'','',1,1,1,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(158,'Change','',30,'','','Brainless',1,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',255,270,'','',2,8,8,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(159,'Checkers','',30,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',318,364,'','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(160,'Chess','',60,'','','',7,'Gone',2,'',0,'',316,362,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 05:21:51'),(161,'Circus Maximus','Avalon Hill',300,'Sports','Tactical Sim','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',189,83,'','',1,10,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(162,'City By The Silt Sea','TSR',0,'Fantasy','Role Playing','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',227,145,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(163,'City States of Arklyrell','Task Force Games',120,'Fantasy','Grand Strategic Sim','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',147,18,'<P>This is a fantasy wargame with a hex map board and cardboard squares representing various units. It has a nice little map consisting of both water and land (apparently, much of Arklyrell is islands) it has a 16 page rule book and a small number of counters (on the back of which, someone has thoughtfully written hex numbers to aid in setting up the game).  Players compete for control of the citadels in the course of a 25 turn game. The game comes in a ziplock bag.<P>From the back of the rules book:<P>\"City States of Arklyrell is a game for two to four players. It depicts the wars for control of the world of Arklyrell. Each player takes the part of a leader, and must gather armies, fleets and magical items in order to wage battle. The game revolves around the conquest of the eight great Citadels, the seats of both political and economic power on the world of Arklyrell. Victory is determined by which player\'s leader controls the most Citadels at the end of the game. Or if a players leader can capture a certain number of Citadels, he wins the game immediately. Game components include 54 die cut playing pieces, a colorful map and complete rules of play. \"','<p><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=4248\">Board Game Geek</a>',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(164,'CityTech','FASA',180,'War Game','Tactical Sim','Thinky',4,'Keep',2,'Keith',0,'',185,79,'','',2,0,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(165,'Civilization','Avalon Hill',720,'Empire','Grand Strategic Sim','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',148,20,'','',2,7,7,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(166,'Conquistador','SPI (Simulations Publications',360,'New World Conquest','Military Simulation','Hard',6,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1976,'',243,252,'<P>Play one of three European powers in a bid to make your riches in the New World. This is the original version, published by SPI.<P>Designer: Richard Berg','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P>More information at <a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=1506\">Board Game Geeks</a>',1,3,3,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(167,'Cribbage','',45,'Score board','Card','Moderate',3,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',302,344,'','',0,2,0,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(168,'DarkOver','Eon Products',0,'Science Fiction','Science Fiction','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',228,147,'P>From the box: <BR>\"Based on the best-selling science fiction novels by Marion Zimmer Bradley. <BR>\"On a beautiful alien world, a race of telepathic humans control elemental energies which can destroy the planet. <B>Darkover -- </B><UL><li>where players compete in fierce psychic struggles</li><li>where players seek revenge by hurling deadly forces from the Overworld to destroy their enemies</li><li>where daring strategies and unique psychic gifts lead to quick reversals of fortune</li><li>where players conceal their own feelings while luring their opponents into dangerous emotional outbursts</li><li> where the mysterious Ghost Wind unleashes bizarre human behavior and threatens to reveal players\' secret desires</li><li>where the mounting tensions are suddenly resolved in gut-wrenching laughter</li></UL><B>\"Darkover -- a Future Pastimes Creation\"</b><P>Eon is the same company that made that famous game, Cosmic Encounter!','',2,4,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(169,'Devil Bunny Hates The Earth','',20,'','','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',257,273,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(170,'Dinosaurs of the Lost World','Avalon Hill',120,'Fantasy','Other','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',199,100,'','',1,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(171,'Diplomacy','Games Research Inc',360,'War Game','Grand Strategic Sim','Very Thinky',5,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',165,48,'<P>Diplomacy is a game of strategy and diplomacy for up to 7 players.  Each player takes one country -- Italy, France, Germany, England, Russia, Turkey, Austria-Hungary -- in  pre-Great War Europe. By making deals and exercising strategy, each player takes control of neutral supply centers to grow their armies and navies to take over other countries. Inevitably, someone gets stabbed in the back and, if their other alliances hold, there\'s a war. Gradually the players drop out until only one country is left and that player wins. The game is really quite subtle and elegant -- it\'s simpler than Risk but as hard to master as chess.<P>This is the original version of Diplomacy with wooden blocks for pieces and a very attractive board (it has a map of Europe with a the elevation of the land and the depth of the sea). I have included part of the map with the cover. The game has two sets of rules -- one that dates from 1976 and the other that proclaims itself to be revised in February of 1982. It also has four \"conference maps.<P>Sadly, the top of the box is broken in  every corner and the bottom broken in 3 of four (you can see the tape on the edges of the top of the box in the picture) . The game is still perfectly playable, it\'s just a bit worse for the wear. On the bright side, the board is covered with plastic and in good shape. Overall, I gave it a rating of \"Damaged\" because of the box but the game itself is in good shape. <P>I am also selling the \"Gamer\'s Guide to Diplomacy\" which I highly recomend to both beginning and expert players.','',2,7,7,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(172,'DragonRiders of Pern','Nova',60,'Fantasy','Tactical Sim','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Francis Tresham',154,29,'','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(173,'Dune','Avalon Hill',180,'Science Fiction','Strategic Sim','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1979,'',180,73,'<P>The 1979 version of <I>Dune</I> is a game based on the book, <I>Dune</I>. I has a game play that reminds me of <i>Cosmic Encounter</i>. Players play each of the factions in <I>Dune</I>: Bene Geserit, Atreides, Fremen, Emperor, Harkonnen, Guild. Each has special abilities that fit in with the <I>Dune</I> theme. The goal is to gain control of Dune by managing to get enough troops to take over and hold at least 3 strongholds. When troops fight the players use a special wheel with which they can secretly commit a variable number of troops and then they can play cards which might modify the conflict. Much of the game is about making deals with your opponents to form alliances and generally get what you need while trying not to give up too much.<P>The game is in pretty good shape but the game box looks like it might have been crushed at some point.','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=121\"> Game Geek Comments</a></li></ul>',2,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(174,'Dungeon Quest','',60,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Garrett J. Donner',259,278,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(252,'Guess Who','Milton Bradley',20,'Deduction','Children','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1987,'Theo Coster,Ora Coster',NULL,NULL,'<P>Each player has a character that the other player is trying to guess. Each player also has a board with each of the possible charaters on a little tile than flips down. Players take turns asking questions like \"does your character have a hat\" and then flipping down the pictures that don\'t match the answer. The first player to guess the other character wins.','http://www.boardgamegeeks.com/game/4143',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(175,'Dungeon!','TSR',120,'Fantasy','Tactical Sim','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',172,62,'<P>This is a family board game loosely based on TSR\'s Dungeons & Dragons role-playing game. It is not a role playing game itself, however. The idea is that you pick what kind of character you want to be and then you wander through the dungeon looking for treasure. When you come to a door you open the door, fight the monster and get the treasure.  The first player to return to the start with a certain amount of treasure wins.<P>This is not a fabulously complicated game but it\'s fun for all of that. The monsters and the treasures are randomized (you draw cards) but you can guess how good the treasure will be and how bad the monster by the color of the cards. <P>The board and pieces are in good shap as far as I can tell. The box has tape marks on it (some genius thought it would be a good idea to tape the box closed with masking tape) as you can see from the picture.  On the whole a good game, especially for younger players (I played it a few times but then grew bored but my kids played it for years).','',1,8,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(176,'El Grande','Hans Im Gluck',90,'15th Century Spain','Expansion','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Wolfgang Kramer and Richard Ul',296,336,'<P>A refined strategy game. The setting is Spain in the 15th century, where the players try to extend their influence over Spain by controlling as many regions as possible. Produced by \"Hans Im Gluck\" and created by Wolfgang Kramer and Richard Ulrich.<P>In <i>El Grande </i> \"it is the time of awakening.  The position of the king is secure, but the high aristocrats, the Grandes, look to expand their influence. Thus, intrigue fills the country! Their primary weapons are the attendants to the king: the Cabelleros. Each Grande has his favorites, recruited from the provinces, which he deploys to accumulate the power he so desires. Fencing, not with the sword, but with cunning and deceit, the Grandes struggle for power, sending the Caballeros openly into the regions and secretly to the Castillo.\"','',2,5,5,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(177,'ElfQuest','Mayfair',90,'Fantasy','Strategic Sim','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',183,76,'','',2,5,5,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(178,'Empire Builder','Mayfair Games',180,'Rail Road','Trading','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1982,'',166,50,'','',2,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(179,'Falling','Cheap Ass Games',15,'Other','Card','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',1998,'',213,129,'','',5,10,8,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(180,'Five Crowns','Set Enterprises, Inc.',30,'Rummy','Card','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',306,348,'','',2,7,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(181,'Foreign Exchange','Avalon Hill',180,'Money','Buy & Sell','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',136,5,'','',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(182,'Frank\'s Zoo','Rio Grande Games',60,'Animals','Card','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Alan Turoff',262,283,'','',4,7,7,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(247,'Queen\'s Necklace','Days of Wonder',45,'Jewelry','','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',2003,'',NULL,NULL,'<P>In <i>Queen\'s Necklace</i> each player is a jewler to royalty attempting to outdo the other jewlers both in terms of the Royal Favor and in terms of monetary rewards. ','',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(183,'Freight Train','Mayfair',90,'Rail Road','Card','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'N/A',188,82,'','',2,80,4,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(184,'Get Out','CheapAss Games',240,'Other','Other','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',223,139,'','',2,8,6,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(185,'Gladi