tasy','Tactical Sim','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',322,369,'','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(200,'Mancala','Pressman',10,'Abstract','Traditional','Brainless',1,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',331,378,'Mancala is not one game, but a family of pit-and-pebble games. Play involves scooping up pebbles from a pit and sowing the pebbles, one at a time, into the other pits. These games were probably created in Africa hundreds (if not thousands) of years ago.  One standard board is composed of six pits on each side of the board, and a larger scoring pit on each side. Two players sit across from each other over the board. The large scoring pit to each player\'s right is \"her\" scoring pit.  Online Play      * Yucata (turn-based)     * Ludoteka (real time)     * Kurnik (real time)     * YourturnMyturn (turn-based Oware)     * Vying Games (turn-based Kalah and Oware)     * igGameCenter (real-time Kalah)  ','http://www.boardgamegeek.com/game/2448',2,4,4,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(201,'Masterpiece','',0,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Bill Eberle, Peter Olotka, Jac',271,294,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(202,'Melee','Metagaming',30,'Fantasy','Tactical Sim','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',145,16,'','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(203,'Millebornes','',0,'','','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',317,363,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(204,'Mind Lords Of the Last Sea','TSR',0,'Fantasy','Role Playing','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',229,151,'','',0,0,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(255,'Starfarers of Catan','',120,'','','',7,'',5,'Dennis',0,'',NULL,NULL,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:37:28'),(250,'In a Pickle','Gamewright',20,'Words','Party','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',2004,'Colleen McCarthy-Evans,Joyce J',NULL,NULL,'<P>You play cards based on which cards are \"in\" other cards. A sandwich goes in a lunchbox but the lunchbox is in the house and a pickle is in the sandwich. When you get a chain of 4 than everyone gets a shot at finding something larger. Whoever played the last card gets it.<P>Since there is no actual objective criteria (Paul won the last game by saying \"the skyscraper is in my mind\"), arguments are inevitable. Drunk or stoned (or in any other state where you don\'t care) it might be fun but 2 people quit before we finished the game -- I guess endless arguments aren\'t for everyone. <P> The rules are quite incomplete. We believe that you draw a card after you play but we can\'t prove it. ','http://www.boardgamegeeks.com/game/12205',2,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(205,'Nato','',300,'Wargame','Strategic Sim','Hard',6,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',209,115,'','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(206,'Nuclear War','Flying Buffalo',60,'War Game','Grand Strategic Sim','Brainless',1,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'Darwin Bromley',153,28,'<P>Empire Builder is the original railroad drawing games. The game starts with a map of America with it\'s cities and with black dots set in a grid. Players build their railroads by drawing lines from dot to dot so that they connect cities together. Then the players run the railroads by moving a train to a town that has a commodity to a town that has a demand for that commodity. When such a demand is fulfilled a payment is made which allows the player to build more rail lines and carry more commodities. The winner is the first to reach a predetermined amount of money.<P>More information can be found at <a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=168\">Game Geek Review </a><P>This game is in pretty good shape for being 20 years old. I\'ve taken the unmounted coated map and mounted it on art boards and covered it with clear plastic. We found that dry erase felt pens worked best. You\'ll have to provide your own pens. Some faint lines still remain but this should not affect play. There is an extra set of commodity markers made from normal paper. There is also a set of new rules that are designed to make the game more interactive. ','',2,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(207,'Outreach','SPI',240,'Science Fiction','Tactical Sim','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'James Ernest',201,103,'<P>In <i>Falling</i> one person is the dealer. The dealer continuously deals each player cards. The players can use the cards to get more cards or fewer cards as well as force opponents to get more or fewer cards. The last several cards in the deck are \"ground\" cards; when you are dealt one of these  you have hit the ground and lost. You win by being the last person to hit the ground.<P>I really like this game because it is a unique system. But my friends and family seem to find it vexing.<P>The game is in excellent shape, as if it\'s only been played once or twice.<P>From the box<P>\"Everyone is falling.<P>\"Hit the Ground last.<P>\"It\'s not much of a goal, but it\'s all you could think of on the way down.<P>\"FALLING is a freeform card game in which players are falling, fighting, and struggling to hit the ground last. There are no turns in this game, which means everyone is playing at once. It\'s almost exactly like the real thing!','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=75\">Board Game Geek</a> has more information. ',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(208,'Pachesi','',40,'','Dice','',7,'Keep',2,'dave',0,'M Falco',332,379,'<P>This is basically a very nicely done game of rummy. You\'re work to meld sets of 3 cards in runs or sets. The twist is that the number of cards increase with each hand from 3 to 13 <b>and</b> with every hand a different card is wild (with the wild card equal to the number of cards in your hand, from the 3s to the kings). <P>','<P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=1472\">More information from Board Game Geeks</a>',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(209,'Panzer Leader','Avalon Hill',0,'War Game','Tactical Sim','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',232,216,'<P>This is a simulation of the international money market. There is a beginning game, an intermediate game and an expert game. All of them are designed to teach as well as entertain.<P>This would be a good game for anyone interested in the world of high finance and it would be an excellent game for a class setting. ','',2,2,0,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(210,'Phantoms of the Ice','White Wind',90,'Sports','Card','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Frank Nestel & Doris MatthÃ¤us',298,338,'<P>Sort of like <i>The Great Dalmuti</I> but with a theme of animals. Like <i>Dalmuti</I> your goal is to get rid of all your cards. The suits are different kinds of animals, each of which has a preditor. ','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=340\">Game Geeks</a>',2,10,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(211,'Phantoms of the Ice Expansion','White Wind',90,'Sports','Card','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',292,328,'','',2,10,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(212,'Pictionary','Hasbro / Milton Bradley',90,'Charades','Drawing','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',303,345,'','',3,16,8,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(214,'Pirateer','Mendocino Game Company',30,'Pirates','','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Michael E. Matheny',150,22,'<P><I>Gladiator</I> is essentially a man-to-man combat simulator, in this case a simulation of combat between two Roman gladiators.<P>From the back of the box: <BR>\"<B>The savage splendor and pageantry of ancient Rome lives again in the game of man-to-man gladiatorial combat!</B><BR>\"Each player assumes the role of one of a matched pair of gladiators putted in a contest of arms to the death. Superbly trained and equipped for the sole purpose of entertaining the citizenry with their life and death struggles, each man must fight with all the skill he can muster for his very survival. There is no question of bravery in the arena. It is kill or be killed and each man must muster all the skills and cunning he can summon in this most desperate of battles for survival. There can be only one victor in the arena and no second chance for the loser. For missus can be granted the fallen only at the whim of the emperor, and all too often mercy takes the form of a quick end on an opponent\'s blade. Let the games begin!\"<P>The game is in very good shape. It\'s been played a few times but only two counters have been punched and only a few movement sheets have been used from the pad.http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=1693','<h3>Other Interesting Links</h3><P><a href=\"http://www.boardgamegeek.com/viewitem.php3?gameid=1693\">Game Geeks</a>',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(215,'Pit','Parker Brothers',90,'Commodity Trading','Card','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',314,360,'','',2,8,8,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(216,'Pythagoras','',0,'Shapes','Puzzle','Hard',6,'Keep',2,'Dorita',0,'',305,347,'','',0,0,0,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(217,'Quad-Ominos','Pressman Toy Corp.',20,'Number Matching','Domino','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',334,381,'','',2,8,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(218,'Quinto','3M',60,'Abstract','Other','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',174,65,'','',2,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(219,'Quirks','Eon',120,'Evolution','Card','Moderate',3,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'',138,9,'<P>This is a card game. On the face of it, it\'s pretty straightforward -- the highest card wins the trick. But then there are special cards that change that. ','',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-05-28 05:23:15'),(220,'Racko','Parker Brothers',60,'Abstract','Card','Easy',2,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',133,1,'','',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(221,'Rail Baron','Avalon Hill',240,'Railroad','Trading','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',196,97,'<P>You have a rack and 10 cards. During your turn you pick up a card and use it to replace any card in your rack. The first player to get his whole rack of 10  in order wins. It seems simple but it\'s actually an interesting game.<P>During the game you often have to decide whether to take a card that doesn\'t quite fit or hold out for the perfect cards. And then, of course, there is the issue -- common to many card games -- of holding cards that you don\'t want in your hand so that your opponent won\'t get them. <P>I am very fond of this game but my family doesn\'t like it (maybe because I often win at it) so I\'m selling it.  It is complete and in good shape with all the racks whole and the cards looking good.','',3,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(222,'Readers Digest Q&A','Selchow & Righter',10,'Word Power','Trivia','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',333,380,'<P>This is among the first railroad games and it still stands up well against the many others. Players buy historical US rail lines and then move trains through their system to receive a payoff. Players compete to buy the best network and prevent their opponents from doing the same. ','',1,2,2,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(223,'Renfield','CheapAss Games',90,'Other','Card','Moderate',3,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',217,133,'<P>This is an electronic game based on the <i>Reader\'s Digest</i> feature  \'It Pays to Enrich Your Word Power\'\". It includes a book of  \"Word Power\" questions and answers as well as a \"Brain Power\" book and a \"Quiz Power\" book. You answer questions by typing the letter of your answer into the consol and then it tells you if you got it right and gives you a score based on how many you got right. It has a single player game as well as a two player game. <P>I verified that the game works and so, although it is WAY out of it\'s 90 day warranty (the manual is copyright 1980 :), it is covered by my money back guarantee. It appears to be in excellent condition; it probably has been never or seldom used. You will need a new 9 volt battery -- the one I tested it with was from the smoke detector and I better put that one back before the house burns down!<P>From the box:<P>\"An extraordinary electrionic experience for everyone who loves fun and looks for a challenge. <P>\"<b>GAME 1</b> -- WORD POWER is based on the popular Reader\'s Digest feature \'It Pays to Enrich Your Word Power\'\"<P>\"<b>GAME 2</b> -- BRAIN POWER tests your wits in such subjects as sports, music, entertainment, history and keeps the score. <P>Play it alone or against an opponent. The computer has the answers and keeps the score. <P>Over 3,000 qustions and answers! Q&A is more fun every time it\'s played!\"<P>As I say, it also has a \"Quiz Power\" book which seems to be designed for younger players, with questions like \"\'See red\' means...\". ','',4,7,7,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(224,'Republic Of Rome','Avalon Hill',300,'Historical','Grand Strategic Sim','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',192,91,'','',1,6,6,NULL,0,'2010-04-11 04:36:21'),(225,'Richtofen\'s War','Avalon Hill',45,'Wargame','Tactical Sim','Thinky',4,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Al Leonardi',226,143,'<P><i>Republic of Rome</i> (\"Game of Political Intrigue in the Ancient World 264-43 BC\") is a game of political intrigue in Rome. Sort of like <i>Diplomacy</i> on steroids. In the game each player represents a faction in the Senate with certain senators under his control. The game is played by voting for various offices to be held by the senators you control (or, perhaps, to be controlled by others so that they will support you).<P>Meantime, the barbarians are, metaphorically, at the gates. Various wars and uprisings show up and require the senate to respond. If Rome looses any of these conflicts everyone loses.<P>This is a game about negotiating with your opponents. It\'s a bit complicated but that\'s part of the fun.<P>From the back of the box:<P>\"Republic of Rome is a multiplayer, diplomacy game set in ancient Rome which spans more than 200 years of the republic from the Punic Wars to the assassination of  Julius Caesar and the onset of the Empire. Three to six players vie to control the Senate while also cooperating for the good of the state against Rome\'s enemies. It is this constant balancing act between personal advancement and the welfare of the state that sets REPUBLIC OF ROME apart from ordinary games. If the players allow their personal goals to interfere too heavily with the republic\'s best interests, the peoples may revolt or the state may fall to foreign conquest and all players will be put to the sword. Not since KINGMAKER and CIVILIZATION have so many innovative concepts appeared in a multi-player board game.<P>\"<i>Be forewarned!</i>REPUBLIC OF ROME is not a wargame in the traditional sense. It is a game of political intrigue with the military overtones that literally oozes the rich detail for the period\'s history. A deck of 192 illustrated cards sets the scene for the panoramic spectacle that was the Roman republic. As that history unfolds before them, each player\'s faction of influential Senators vies for political power, military commands, and economic advantages against the backdrop of a turbulent world. Deals and counter-offers abound. Short the necessary votes of Consul? Trade the Armaments Concession for a faction\'s support.\"<P>The game itself is in good shape with only minor wear on the box. The box has some creases. The contents are all here in ziplock bags. 16\"x22\" mounted game board & 24 page rule book. I have a simplified summary.','',2,2,2,NULL,3,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(226,'Risk','Parker Brothers',120,'','','Moderate',3,'Keep',2,'Dave',0,'Al Leonardi',206,110,'','',2,6,6,NULL,1,'2010-04-11 04:50:37'),(227,'Rune Sword (Bith)','Nova Game Designs',10,'Fantasy','Tactical Sim','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'Al Leonardi',324,371,'','',2,4,4,NULL,0,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(228,'Rune Sword (Cal) 1','Nova Game Designs',10,'Fantasy','Tactical Sim','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',326,373,'<P>The full name of this series is <i>Rune Sword Fantasy Combat Book Game</i>.  This particular book is for Bith, Female Cleric. <P>This is a tactical fantasy combat book that uses a system very similar to <i>Ace of Aces</i> to allow interaction between the players. You need at least two books to play this. game. You give your book to your opponent and take their book. They tell you their move and you look that up in their book. Then you look up your move in their book and find the final page. This page will show you what they look like at the end of the turn as well as any damage or other results. Meantime, your opponent will go through a similar process and see the final position of his charater.<P>There is a character sheet that tells you what moves you can make. For example, there are \"Down Swing\", \"Side Swing\", \"Thrust\", \"Fake\", make \"Protected Attacks\", \"Shield Block\", and \"Jump\" plus special moves like \"Kick\", \"Wild Swing\", \"Dislodge Weapon\", and \"Retrieve Weapon\".<P>This is a very workable and fun tactical combat system and can be used by itself or as part of a campaign. I have 8 books representing 7 different characters.','',2,4,4,NULL,10,'2010-06-03 15:16:33'),(229,'Rune Sword (Cal) 2','Nova Game Designs',10,'Fantasy','Tactical Sim','',7,'Gone',1,'Unknown',0,'',327,374,'<P>The full name of this series is <i>Rune Sword Fantasy Combat Book Game - Cal, Warrior with Sword and Shield</i>.<P>This is a tactical fantasy combat book that uses a system very similar to <i>Ace of Aces</i> to allow interaction between the players. You need at least two books to play this. game. You give your book to your opponent and take their book. They tell you their move and you look that up in their book. Then you look up your move in their book and find the final page. This page will show you what they look like at the end of the turn as well as any damage or other results. Meantime, your opponent will go through a similar process and see the final position of his charater.<P>There is a character sheet that tells you what moves you can make. For example, there are \"Down Swing\", \"Side Swing\", \"Thrust\", \"Fake\", make \"Protected Attacks\", \"Shield Block\", and \"Jump\" plus special moves like \"Kick\", \"Wild Swing\", \"Dislodge Weapon\", and \"Retrieve Weapon\".<P>T