na st 19th & minnesota; `6th & 3rd or at ballpark\r\n\r\n',1,26,0,0,'2007-10-08 07:11:47'),(589,10,1,'update work todo database','alter table product add column userno int default 1 after id;\r\nalter table todolist add column userno int default 1 after seq;\r\nalter table todolist add hidden int default 0 after productid;\r\nalter table todolist drop column product;\r\n+-----------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n| Field     | Type          | Null | Key | Default | Extra          |\r\n+-----------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n| id        | int(11)       |      | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment |\r\n| seq       | int(11)       |      |     | 0       |                |\r\n| userno    | int(11)       | YES  |     | 1       |                |\r\n| title     | varchar(100)  |      |     |         |                |\r\n| details   | text          | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n| done      | int(11)       |      |     | 0       |                |\r\n| productid | int(11)       | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n| duration  | int(11)       | YES  |     | 0       |                |\r\n| hidden    | int(11)       | YES  |     | 0       |                |\r\n| todoTS    | timestamp(14) | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n+-----------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n+-------------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n| Field       | Type          | Null | Key | Default | Extra          |\r\n+-------------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n| id          | int(11)       |      | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment |\r\n| userno      | int(11)       | YES  |     | 1       |                |\r\n| product     | varchar(20)   | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n| description | text          | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n| hidden      | int(11)       | YES  |     | 0       |                |\r\n| productts   | timestamp(14) | YES  |     | NULL    |                |\r\n+-------------+---------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+\r\n\r\n',1,6,0,0,'2007-10-10 07:08:17'),(590,5,1,'read Ambur Lowenthal 	writing man in gray','\r\n \r\nIt was 10:07 on a Tuesday morning and little Svetlana Merkle was sitting on the couch in between her mother who was intensely reading a book and her father who was reading the paper. Cooper blond hair up in pigtails, a broad smile on her face, with her feet 17 inches above the floor swinging, she sat there with her parents oblivious to her mysterious joy.\r\n            Outside there was a loud raucous. Svetlana smiled through it.  The Men in Blue were out in force and collecting all children who had aged 7 years. Some blue men had sticks in which to corral the children, others had fire houses to spray the children who spit, and some had long metal telescopes to find children who were far away. Once the children were collected and herded into bright yellow trucks, they were driven away to the Man in Gray so he could decorate his home. \r\n            He lived in a grand estate on top of a burnt orange hill. There were no trees, nor grass, nor shrubbery. Only crispy remnants of foliage that would crunch underneath feet. There were no birds, nor squirrels, nor flying insects. Only tiny red scorpions darting across the property. His home had no windows and was outfitted with only one door wide enough for 7 children to pass through at one time.\r\n            Back on her couch, between her oblivious parents, with her feet at a methodical constant swing 17 inches above the floor, Svetlana continued to smile. She took in a deep breath.  Children are like puppies and other small domesticated animals; they can smell emotions in the air. Svetlana was unlike most children who merely smelled emotions; Svetlana could pick out individual emotions from the air, from any person and understand the intricacies of their pores. She breathed in again. Svetlana smelled many emotions in the air this morning at 10:14 a.m.: the giddiness and sweaty excitement from the Men in Blue as they tore children from their parentâ€™s arms, the sticky fear those same children oozed from their soft pores and snotty noses, the parents heavy grief in the pit of their livers knowing they would never see tiny hands and eyes again, one fatherâ€™s deeply hidden elatement that smelled like rotten oranges at the stealing of his son (this particular boy had very nasty habits: picking his nose and eating it, picking his nose and wiping it on the couch, picking his nose and wiping it on the cat, picking his nose and wiping it on the butterâ€¦), but what Svetlana smelled the most of was the ignorance of her parents.\r\nWhen the Men in Blue stormed into the Merkle home, Svetlana was already prepared that her parents would never leave the world of their words to acknowledge the removal of their only child: a little girl with copper blond pig tails with an eternal smile upon her face.\r\n \r\n            Svetlanaâ€™s legs were dangling to the rhythm of the truck ride up to the Man in Gray. The bench she sat on was hard and wooden. She was thickly surrounded by quiet children, crying children, angry children, and frightened children. Some children even had amazing combinations of these simple emotions. Only one child felt slightly claustrophobic, but since he was only 7 years old, he didnâ€™t know the correct word to describe his feeling, so he just closed his eyes and hugged himself. Coincidently, (or not depending on how your mind works) his hugging caused himself to nuzzle up against Svetlana, who continued to smile. He didnâ€™t move from her side until the bright yellow truck came to a very abrupt halt.\r\n            The doors opened. Each child became quiet; each pair of eyes became wide. The light that shown in through the doors coiled around their faces as the children looked upon the scenery before them. Each held in the bowels of their unknown insides a dread they had only previously associated with nightmares about skeletons with hooks for hands and ghouls chasing them through dark streets only children can imagine. Each child knew internally there would be no waking up, no comforting words from mother, and no kiss on the forehead to chase away terrible images.\r\nThe Men in Blue waved long sticks at the children to herd them from the truck. Forlorn and in lines they piled out of the truck and on to the landscape of the Man in Grayâ€™s estate. The screaming erupted once the scorpions began running over the tiny feet of the children. Svetlana picked one up, looked at with her head cocked, and let it drop to the ground. One of the Men in Blue saw her. He was quickly filled with disquiet.\r\nIn the children went. Into the house, through the large door 7 in a row at a time, and were all told to wait in the main lobby until the Man in Gray came down. In all they numbered 47 (should you be curious, there were 7 more boys than girls.) With the large door now shut, it seemed quiet dark indeed. The floor was gray, the walls were gray, and the ceiling was gray.\r\nâ€œAh, beautiful children! So right of you to join me today!â€ a voice echoed off the barren walls. It was the Man in Gray. His age was hard to tell, as was his height, his weight, whether he was bald or had a head full of hair, whether he was pleased or slightly pissed: his very aura was indefinite.\r\nâ€œNo use standing here in the foyer. Please, join me in the banquet hall.â€ He turned and walked down a gray hallway. The children followed apprehensively with the persuasion by the Men in Blue.  \r\n\r\nIt was not gray in the banquet hall.\r\n\r\nIt was quiet in the banquet hall.\r\n\r\nThe children refused to sit in the chairs at the very long table in the banquet hall.\r\n\r\n            â€œDear children, please do no be afraid. Take a seat, rest your weary legs, you will not be harmed,â€ the man in gray cooed. â€œMy seats are safe, they are sturdy. My table will hold any drink or cake. Please sit.â€\r\n\r\n            Glances were exchanged by the children. Mouths were turn upside down into frowns. Some children were crying.\r\n\r\n            â€œYou are all here today, because I am artist, a decorator, a world creator. I dream to have the most beautiful home, furnished with what I believe is most beautiful in the world- children. Please. Sit.â€ They sat.\r\n\r\n            The wiser children understood what the Man in Gray meant. They looked at the chairs, made from children, bent and shaped. They looked at the table made from children glued and intertwined. One brave soul who would have one day been a philosopher looked up to the chandelier and expelled the tiniest â€œeepâ€ the world has ever known.\r\n\r\n            The furniture was not grotesque (yes it was), there was no blood, there were no fearful faces; just the eerie looks of content children reading or viewing a flower blowing in a warm spring breeze. They were not harmed (they were, depending on how you think), their parts were all there, they wore the clothing they wore in on their backs. Clothing that was washed, dried, folded, and then put into drawers by some caring parent then laid out one morning without the knowledge these would be the final garments their children would wear. The preservation was astounding and not the least bit disturbing (yes it was. It was deeply disturbing).\r\n\r\n            Svetlana continued to smile.\r\n\r\n                                                    \r\n\r\n            â€œDearest children,â€ the Man in Gray began with a smile on his face and determination in his deep blue eyes, â€œI cannot help but thank each and every one of you for being here. What words can my mouth form to express my joy as I peer into each one of your eyes? Can you even begin to ascertain your importance to me? Without you, my life could not even exist!â€ His smile turned slightly somber, and his voice became silken with sincerity. â€œChildren, I know you are all fearful. I can see it in your eyes; I smell in each breath you exhale.  I want each and every one of you to know, that you are part of a grand design, a fantastic pictorial of gargantuan proportions. You my dear ones will line my walls, you will colour the gray of my home. You will brighten my day each and every morning. Questions?\"\r\n\r\n            Silence.\r\n\r\n            Svetlana smiled.\r\n\r\n            \"Little girl, you and only must understand my joy. Tell me what you think.\"\r\n\r\n            Svetlana said nothing. She only stared at the Man in Gray with her tiny little head slightly cocked to the right side. It took the Man in Gray exactly 28 secounds for his face to change from a cool calmness with a creamy joy center, to turn to a cool unease that traveled from the nape of his neck, down his spine, twirling around is heart, slamming into his stomach, and then pummeling itself out through his nicely trimmed toe nails.\r\n\r\n            The Man in Gray took the handkerchief from his gray suite and wiped his hands with a determined wiping motion of a man wiping away something terribly wicked.\r\n\r\n            \"Well little girl, I wish the others shared your same willful excitement. Now, rather then waste my time on silly niceties, why not get on with the decorating? Let us move on to the living room.\"\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n            There are times when a story teller can weave a tale of ugliness with subtle hints of hope. This is one of those times, yet any hope laid out is tragically misleading. The living room had blank walls, ready for children. There were large drums of wallpaper glue and one big brush for the Man in Gray. He floated to the phonograph and placed the needle in the groves of the record. From the copper horn, a sad beautiful song began to tip toe throughout the barren room. The cello and violins wrapping around themselves in a melody of cursed lovers. So bitter and so sweet. The tones climbing down a flight of stairs on their hands and knees begging desire. He stood there with his eyes closed. The Man in Gray spent his life filling it with beauty. Sadly his definition of beauty was pulling off butterfly wings and placing them on graves. He began to sway to the music. The tunes of low noted violin taking him on a journey.\r\n\r\n            It was the music of trapping beauty.  He waltzed around the room with his brush dipping in drums of glue. Sometimes a drop would fall on the ground, more often then not, the brush would fall against the face of a child. As it did their expression would fade to one of silent contentment, never to thaw. The Man in Gray would then lovingly lift the child in their air and place him or her on the wall with the eye of an angelic artist. It was a sight to behold. The atmosphere quiet and strangely calm. A cello moving the bass line with a caring nudge. One lone little smiling girl watching the Man in Gray sustain the only creation he could find on earth to be beautiful. She smelled pure joy and could not bring herself to end it.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n            I wish I could say that Svetlana saved the remaining children. But loves, we all know that is not true. Just as the Man in Gray saw something beautiful in something so grotesque, Svetlana saw something beautiful in the purity of his grotesqueness. I will tell you this loves, this not the last you have heard about the Man in Gray. There are other rooms in his home. There is landscaping to be done. Perhaps Svetlana was passive, but are all children passive? I make you no promises of justice for not even God can grant you that; but I can tell you this tale is not quite over.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nNor is his home complete. \r\n\r\n',0,9,0,0,'2008-03-15 19:11:12'),(591,0,1,'testing','this is a test\r\n',0,15,0,1,'2007-10-07 16:06:53'),(592,0,1,'add code to save things with the right user name','',1,6,0,0,'2007-10-08 22:00:21'),(593,1,1,'get some test usernames','',1